<SLUG> BC-RUN-TRACK-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE REIGNS CONTINUE IN SPAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KIRBY LEE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEVILLE, Spain _ Marion Jones is shooting for an unprecedented
four gold medals at the World Track and Field Championships,
planning to postpone a bid for five titles until the 2000 Olympics.
But don't rule out Jones bringing home five World Championship
golds.
</P>
<P>
   She captured the 100 meters Sunday in a championship-record
10.70 seconds for her first gold of the competition. It was the
second gold of the meet, however, for her family. Jones' husband,
C.J. Hunter, won the shot put title Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming off the emotional victory with C.J. last night and
coming in to get the victory tonight, I am extremely excited,''
Jones said. ``The plan for this whole week is to get a total of
five gold medals for the family and we started out in wonderful
fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Greene also began his bid for multiple gold with a bang,
winning the men's 100 meters in 9.80 seconds, the second-best time
in history and only a hundredth of a second off his world record of
9.79 set in June.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' triumph came against the deepest field in World
Championship history, with six athletes dipping below 11 seconds.
Inger Miller was second in a lifetime-best 10.79 and Ekaterini
Thanou of Greece was third at 10.84. Gail Devers, the 1992 and 1996
Olympic champion, was fifth in 10.95.
</P>
<P>
   Jones dipped under the championship record _ and the fastest
time in the world this season _ for the second time in two days. In
Saturday's quarterfinals she ran 10.76 to break the record of 10.82
seconds set by Devers and Merlene Ottey of Jamaica in the 1993
World Championships at Stuttgart.
</P>
<P>
   Running into a 0.1-meter-per-second headwind, Jones and Thanaou
came out of the blocks first. Jones, running in lane five, felt the
presence of Miller and Thanaou in lanes three and four, then pulled
away at the midpoint to capture her second consecutive world title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I nailed my start today, which is very important for me,''
Jones said. ``I think that is the reason I pulled off the victory.
. . . I knew I had to be extremely ready and on my toes. I think I
executed very well today. I put it all together. Before I stepped
into the blocks, that was going through my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a feeling of exhilaration when Jones, 23, crossed the
finish line, thrusting both arms in triumph and giving the United
States its fourth consecutive World Championship victory in the
women's 100. Two years ago in Athens, Ga., Jones called her win the
most memorable after returning to track from basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``The victory in `97 was to this point the most exciting and
most important race in my life simply because I established myself
as a dominant athlete in the world of track and field,'' Jones
said. ``This is more exciting and more fun than it has ever been.
The fact that I can start off this week feels great.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones will try for her second gold in the nine-day competition
in the long- jump final today. She will also run in the 200 meters
and either the 400- or 1,600-meter relay.
</P>
<P>
   In the men's 100, Greene stumbled out of the blocks but was even
with Canada's Bruny Surin by 60 meters. Greene edged away in the
final 10, pulling Surin to second in a Canadian-national-record
9.84, which equaled Donovan Bailey's former world-record time of
9.84 set at the 1996 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Dwain Chambers of Great Britain was third in 9.97. Americans Tim
Harden and Tim Montgomery were fifth and sixth in 10.02 and 10.04,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beginning was very shaky, but I did not panic,'' Greene
said. ``I stayed in control of myself and I was able to come to my
top-end speed smoothly. . . . When I finally started moving, I was
just thinking `I can come back and get them.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, 27, has been running with a similar attitude throughout
the 100-meter rounds. The 1996 Olympic 400-meter gold medalist from
USC lowered her personal best three times. She ran 10.86 in the
quarterfinals to dip under her best of 10.95 set in 1995. In
Sunday's semis, Miller timed 10.81 before knocking off
two-hundredths more in the final.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point in the final, you have to let everything out,''
said Miller, who trains at UCLA and is the daughter of Jamaican
Olympian Lennox Miller. ``I'm going to critique my race with my
coach (Bruins sprint coach John Smith) and see how I can improve,
but I'm happy. There's nothing to complain about.''
</P>
<P>
   In the women's heptathlon, Shelia Burrell of Reseda was the top
American, placing 11th with 6,162 points. The Cal State Northridge
assistant track coach entered the second day in 13th place, posting
marks of 19-2} in the long jump, 148-9 in the javelin and 2:11.52
in the 800. Burrell, the 1999 national champion, ran the 800 with
her right ankle heavily taped and had to be helped to the medical
area by two volunteers after the event because of arch pain.
</P>
</TEXT>
