</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) SOUTH PADRE ISLAND, Texas -- Aug. 22, 1999 --
GULF-HURRICANE-1, 8-22 -- The causeway leading to South Padre
Island, a resort town north of Brownsville, was closed on Sunday.
As tourists and residents were evacuated, some officials stayed to
ride out the onslaught of Hurricane Bret. Bret is the first
hurricane of the 1999 season and the first major hurricane to
threaten south Texas since Hurricane Allen caused $55 million in
damage in 1980. (Bryce Harper/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) MOSCOW -- Aug. 22, 1999 -- RUSSIA-PROSPERITY-GAP-2, 8-22
-- Lyudmila Kazmina, a 72-year-old pensioner, sells romance novels
and calendars outside of her Moscow apartment house to supplement
her monthly pension of 500 rubles, which was worth nearly $100
before the Russian economic crisis but is now worth only $20. Her
customers are far more careful in parting with their rubles than
they used to be. On one recent balmy day Ms. Kazmina even had
trouble making one simple sale. (Jacqueline Mia Foster/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) MOSCOW -- Aug. 22, 1999 -- RUSSIA-PROSPERITY-GAP, 8-22
-- The Yolki-Palki restaurant in Pushkin Square has made
adjustments and managed to expand during Russia's financial crisis.
For a time, it had looked as if the financial crisis that struck
Russia last August would sound the death knell for restaurants like
Yolki-Palki, a chain of Moscow eateries aimed squarely at the small
but emerging middle class. The plunging ruble was sending costs
through the roof and scaring away customers. ``You really have to
be prepared for anything in this country,'' says the owner Arkady
Novikov. (Jacqueline Mia Foster/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) PICCOTTS END, England -- Aug. 22, 1999 --
FRANKENSTEIN-FOOD, 8-22 -- Bob Fiddaman, who has offered to use
some of his farmland in Piccotts End for testing genetically
altered seed crops, says testing is the only way to determine if
protesters' concern about dangers of such crops is justified.
``Let's face it, there are a lot of considerations in Britain that
don't apply elsewhere,'' says Fiddaman, ``the fact that agriculture
is not spread out across broad spaces but is close to inhabited
areas and the whole tradition here of wanting to keep land pure and
unspoiled even by conventional agriculture.'' (Carlos
Lopez-Barillas/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) ON THE BADME PLAIN, Eritrea -- Aug. 22, 1999 --
ERITREA-ETHIOPIA-2, 8-22 -- An Eritrean sniper and troops in the
trenches at the front in Badme Plain. Rifle fire still rings out
and mortar rounds still drop down, but after 15 months of a
particularly senseless conflict, the killing may in fact stop soon
along the disputed border of Eritrea and its larger neighbor,
Ethiopia. Eritrea has accepted all points of a peace plan. Ethiopia
is asking questions about only a few details. (James Hill/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) ON THE BADME PLAIN, Eritrea -- Aug. 22, 1999 --
ERITREA-ETHIOPIA-1, 8-22 -- Eritrean troops carrying ammunition to
the trenches at the front in Badme Plain as one listens to a radio.
Rifle fire still rings out and mortar rounds still drop down, but
after 15 months of a particularly senseless conflict, the killing
may in fact stop soon along the disputed border of Eritrea and its
larger neighbor, Ethiopia. Eritrea has accepted all points of a
peace plan. Ethiopia is asking questions about only a few details.
(James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Aug. 22, 1999 -- LINCOLN-CENTER, 8-22 --
Bernard Gersten, left, the executive producer at Lincoln Center
Theater since 1985, with Andre Bishop, entering his eighth season
as its artistic director. As Lincoln Center Theater approaches the
35th anniversary of its main stage, it has accumulated an oddly
checkered record, creating unassailable hits and unequivocal flops.
Given it's rocky past, the theater has come a long way; last season
its productions were nominated for 16 Tony Awards and won 2.
Nevertheless, the contradictions in its identity and mission
persist. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Aug. 22, 1999 -- INTERNET-ADDRESS-REGS, 8-22
-- Richard Forman says his company, Register.com, is the
second-largest registrar of Internet names in the world, but many
crucial rules that will govern its competition with rivals have yet
to be worked out. Some of those rules will be decided this month
week when the Internet Corporation for Assigned Names and Numbers,
or Icann, the nonprofit corporation charged with introducing
competition into the business of registering names ending in the
popular domains of .com, .net and .org, holds its fourth board
meeting in Santiago, Chile. (Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) PALM BEACH, Fla. -- Aug. 22, 1999 -- UNIONS-E-MAIL, 8-22
-- Current and former employees of Pratt &AMP; Whitney gather outside
the company's main gate in Palm Beach, Fla. From left: Bob Ahbol,
Kenneth Coolidge, Zachary Waltz, Carol Rinaldi and Brian Waldron.
Last month, more than two years after the suspensions, the union in
Florida, the Florida Professional Association, agreed to withdraw a
complaint accusing Pratt &AMP; Whitney of using unfair labor practices
in return for the company's pledge to allow the limited use of its
e-mail system for organizing drives in the future. (Susan
Greenwood/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Aug. 22, 1999 -- CONDE-NAST-FASHION, 8-22 --
Anna Wintour, the editor in chief of Vogue magazine, left, urged
her boss, Conde Nast's chairman, S.I. Newhouse Jr. to buy Fairchild
Publications, headed by Patrick McCarthy, right. As of Friday, the
fashion, advertising and magazine publishing industries are humming
with the news that Newhouse, whose company publishes Vogue,
Glamour, Mademoiselle, Vanity Fair, The New Yorker and a dozen
other sleek and stylish magazines, had offered $650 million for
Fairchild, the publisher of Women's Wear Daily, W and Jane
magazines. (Rebecca Cooney, left, New York Times Photo; Patrick D.
Pagnano/New York Times Photo, right.)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) SANTA CLARA, Calif. -- Aug. 22, 1999 -- YAHOO-STYLE, 8-22
-- Despite different styles, Jerry Yang, Yahoo's co-founder,
Timothy A. Koogle, chief executive, center, and Jeff Mallett, its
chief operating officer, are said to have developed an easy working
relationship, forging strategy in spirited debates. Still, some
wonder whether Koogle's stubborn independence can survive the
cutthroat market battles that lie ahead, especially redoubled
competition from Microsoft Corp.'s MSN and America Online, both of
which offer Internet access and browser software as well as a broad
range of online services. (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) HOLLYWOOD -- Aug. 22, 1999 -- FILM-NOIR-FEMMES, 8-22 --
Femmes fatales: from left, Jane Greer, Coleen Gray, Marie Windsor
and Audrey Totter in the Formosa Cafe, a restaurant on Santa Monica
Boulevard that dates back to Hollywood's golden age. Fifty years
after playing femmes fatales and hard-boiled dames in classic
examples of film noir, those shadowy mysteries often made by emigre
directors, the actresses who starred in them still receive fan mail
almost daily. (Ted Soqui/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Aug. 22, 1999 -- OBIT-CASTELLI-2-B&AMP;W, 8-22 --
Art dealer Leo Castelli, left, with painter James Rosenquist in the
artist's studio in 1966. Rosenquist's work in the background is
titled ``Growth Material.'' Castelli's identification with Pop Art
made him a lightning rod for criticism. Castelli, who played an
extraordinary role in shaping contemporary American art and
fostering international acceptance of painters like Jasper Johns,
Robert Rauschenberg and Roy Lichtenstein, died on Saturday at his
Manhattan home. He was 91. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Aug. 22, 1999 -- OBIT-CASTELLI-1, 8-22 -- Leo
Castelli, the New York art dealer in his Manhattan gallery in 1997.
Castelli, who played an extraordinary role in shaping contemporary
American art and fostering international acceptance of painters
like Jasper Johns, Robert Rauschenberg and Roy Lichtenstein, died
on Saturday at his Manhattan home. He was 91. Castelli emerged as
one of the most influential American art dealers of the century in
the late 1950s, when Abstract Expressionism began to ebb, and for
decades helped develop and promote the Pop, Minimal, Conceptual and
Neo-Expressionist movements. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Aug. 22, 1999 -- BBN-METS-CARDS-3, 8-22 --
The St. Louis Cardinals Mark McGwire being congratulated by his
teammates after making the history books once again, by becoming
the first player to reach 50 homers in four consecutive seasons.
McGwire hit two home runs against the New York Mets on Sunday in
the first game of a double-header. McGwire has seven multihomer
games this season and 60 in his career. Still, the Mets came from
five runs down to beat the Cardinals 8-7. (Ozier Muhammad/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Aug. 22, 1999 -- BBN-METS-CARDS-2, 8-22 --
The St. Louis Cardinals Mark McGwire hitting his 50th home run the
year against the New York Mets on Sunday at Shea Stadium. McGwire
made history once again by becoming the first player to reach 50
homers in four consecutive seasons. McGwire's 50th homer looked
routine compared to his first-inning blast. He led off the seventh
with a fly ball that just cleared the outstretched glove of Shawon
Dunston in left-center and landed just over the 396-foot sign.
Still, the Mets came from five runs down to beat the Cardinals 8-7.
(Ozier Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Aug. 22, 1999 -- BBN-METS-CARDS-1, 8-22 --
The St. Louis Cardinals Mark McGwire hitting his 49th home run of
the year against the New York Mets on Sunday, in the first game of
a double-header. Big Mac launched the monstrous homer, an estimated
502 feet, in the first-inning, and shattered a light bulb on the
scoreboard. Still, the Mets came from five runs down to beat the
Cardinals 8-7 on Edgardo Alfonzo's RBI single in the ninth inning.
(Ozier Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
