<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Sunday, 08/22/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) SEACREST, N.Y. -- Aug. 22, 1999 --
RUN-TRIATHLON-DISABLED-2, 8-22 -- Maricar Marquez, 27, a veteran
rock climber, spelunker and sky diver, who is deaf and blind,
begins the cycling stage of the12th annual Seacrest-Tobay Triathlon
on Sunday, with her provider, Ed Sullivan. She finished 486th out
of 670. Marquez plans to run the New York City Marathon next year.
``I like to do a lot of different things and get involved. I'm not
the kind of person who stays home. I am fascinated by life.''
(William Lopez/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) SEACREST, N.Y. -- Aug. 22, 1999 --
RUN-TRIATHLON-DISABLED-1, 8-22 -- Anindya Bhattacharyya, 29, left,
a computer technology specialist who is deaf and blind, feeling for
the hand of his support provider, Jim Belanich, after the first
stage of the12th annual Seacrest-Tobay Triathlon on Sunday. ``This
triathlon is just another adventure,'' says Bhattacharyya. He
finished in 2 hours 8 minutes, 670th out of the 900 individual
participants. (William Lopez/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEWFIELD, N.J. -- Aug. 22, 1999 -- GAY-PARENTS-CAMP-2,
8-22 -- Bryan Corley, 10, at Camp Mountain Meadow, created in 1992
to give children whose parents are gay, lesbian or transsexual a
place where they can be themselves without fear. Mountain Meadow
offers daily forums where the children can discuss common problems,
as well as more typical summer camp activities like athletics,
crafts and theater. (Laura Pedrick/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEWFIELD, N.J. -- Aug. 22, 1999 -- GAY-PARENTS-CAMP-1,
8-22 -- Andre Cruz, a counselor at Camp Mountain Meadow, created in
1992 to give children whose parents are gay, lesbian or transsexual
a place where they can be themselves without fear, allows campers
to draw on his face. Mountain Meadow offers daily forums where the
children can discuss common problems, as well as more typical
summer camp activities like athletics, crafts and theater. (Laura
Pedrick/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) HARTFORD, Conn. -- Aug. 22, 1999 -- CT-PROMISE-KEEPERS,
8-22 -- A prayer opens a conference held Friday and Saturday in the
Hartford Civic Center Coliseum by Promise Keepers, an evangelical
Christian ministry. The group is trying to increase attendance at
its rallies. More than 12,000 men had packed into the basketball
arena for the rally. The group has largely faded from public view
since its ``Stand in the Gap'' rally drew hundreds of thousands of
men to the National Mall in Washington in 1997. The group has
shrunk but is still huge, with 180 full-time employees and annual
revenues of $41 million. (George Ruhe/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) WILLIAMSPORT, Pa. -- Aug. 22, 1999 --
BBO-LITTLE-LEAGUE-2, 8-22 -- Eric Campesi, center fielder for Toms
River East flies through the air, as the Little Leaguers from New
Jersey began their defense of their Little League World Series
title on Sunday against Phenix City, Ala. Combining masterly
pitching with a couple of powerful swings, Toms River defeated
Phenix City, 6-0, before a crowd of 12,400 at Howard J. Lamade
Stadium. Toms River is only the third American team to return to
the Little League World Series the year after winning the title.
Toms River plays Boise, Idaho, on Monday night. (Chang W. Lee/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) WILLIAMSPORT, Pa. -- Aug. 22, 1999 --
BBO-LITTLE-LEAGUE-1, 8-22 -- Casey Gaynor of Toms River East
tossing his fifth straight shutout as the Little Leaguers from New
Jersey began their defense of their Little League World Series
title on Sunday against Phenix City, Ala. Combining masterly
pitching with a couple of powerful swings, Toms River defeated
Phenix City, 6-0, before a crowd of 12,400 at Howard J. Lamade
Stadium. Toms River is only the third American team to return to
the Little League World Series the year after winning the title.
Toms River plays Boise, Idaho, on Monday night. (Chang W. Lee/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) SPARKS, Nev. -- Aug. 22, 1999 -- TAILHOOK-CONVENTION,
8-22 -- The Tailhook convention, site of sexual misconduct that
shook the Navy in 1991, is now a much different kind of event, is
now a much calmer event. Pamela Salisbury, left, was one of the few
women this weekend at the aviators' gathering in Sparks this
weekend. Comdr. Chuck Wright, says the gathering convention was ``a
lot more subdued.'' (Don Preisler/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) ALEXANDRIA, Va. -- Aug. 22, 1999 -- DIVALL-PROFILE, 8-22
-- Linda DiVall, Elizabeth Dole's pollster at her office in
Alexandria. After Ms. DiVall was hired to work on Mrs. Dole's bid
for the Republican presidential nomination earlier this year, a few
Republicans contacted the campaign to protest the decision. ``They
didn't think I was conservative enough,'' says Ms. DiVall. The
criticism, Ms. DiVall said, ignored her work in the past for
politicians well to the right of Mrs. Dole -- former House Speaker
Newt Gingrich sprang quickly to mind. (Shana Raab/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) PORT ISABEL, Texas -- Aug. 22, 1999 -- GULF-HURRICANE-3,
8-22 --Powerful winds from Hurricane Bret snapped a treetop in Port
Isabel on Sunday, not far from the causeway leading to South Padre
Island. Bret is the first hurricane of the 1999 season and the
first major hurricane to threaten south Texas since Hurricane Allen
caused $55 million in damage in 1980. (Bryce Harper/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) RAYMONDVILLE, Texas -- Aug. 22, 1999 --
GULF-HURRICANE-2, 8-22 -- Richard Davila and his and sister Marissa
carry a sandbag on Sunday as Raymondville prepares for Hurricane
Bret. Bret is the first hurricane of the 1999 season and the first
major hurricane to threaten south Texas since Hurricane Allen
caused $55 million in damage in 1980. (Bryce Harper/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
