<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BIG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BIG CITY: TOLLS IN THE HAMPTONS WOULD UNCLOG ROADS 
</HEADLINE>
 - CITY-NYT (ms) 
 By JOHN TIERNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The people of the Hamptons have it in their power to help all
Americans, and, in the traditional spirit of the Hamptons, they can
make out quite nicely themselves, too. They can show everyone else
how to end traffic jams.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of relying on failed strategies _ building more
highways, trying to limit sprawl, exhorting people to drive less _
Hamptonites can buy their way out of traffic. They can afford to
adopt economists' favorite method of unclogging traffic: road
pricing.
</P>
<P>
   If slots on highways were priced like airline seats or telephone
calls, traffic would not come to a standstill at rush hour. The
rates could be raised during peak periods to prevent demand from
exceeding supply. The theory has always made wonderful sense, but
until recently it seemed much too complicated to try on a real
highway.
</P>
<P>
   Now road pricing become technically feasible thanks to
electronic toll systems. Some, like EZPass, use radio waves;
others, like one used on a tollway in Toronto, photograph each
license plate. In the newest systems, drivers don't even have to
slow down for the toll to be recorded.
</P>
<P>
   With the technological problem solved, the only remaining
obstacles are political. Once drivers are accustomed to the free
use of a road, they are outraged by the idea of paying for it. In
most places, politicians who supported a new toll would be accused
of gouging the middle class and banishing the poor.
</P>
<P>
   But the Hamptons are a special place. The New Yorkers who brave
the bumper-to-bumper traffic on the Montauk Highway, Route 27,
could not object convincingly to a toll. How could they complain
about price-gouging when they're paying $50,000 a month for a small
beach house that is not even on the beach? How could they pretend
to care about excluding the poor when they are headed for towns
zoned to keep out the middle class?
</P>
<P>
   The logical place for a toll is at the entrance to the Hamptons,
where Route 27 crosses the Shinnecock Canal and narrows from four
lanes to two. You could start with a toll just at peak hours on
weekends. Although some Hamptonites doubt that any toll would make
a difference _ one investment banker told me he would not be
deterred by anything less than $1,000 _ road experts are confident
it would not take much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in a wealthy area like the Hamptons,'' said Peter Samuel,
the editor of Toll Roads Newsletter, ``I suspect that a couple of
bucks would be enough to make a difference. After all, you don't
need to deter many people. Just getting 20 percent of the drivers
to avoid Route 27 at peak times could get traffic flowing much more
smoothly.''
</P>
<P>
   However much of a toll it takes _ $2, $5, $25 _ there could be
protections for the non-rich local residents and workers. There
might be no toll on the alternative route across the Shinnecock
Canal, the Montauk Highway. Or perhaps both routes would be tolled,
but the locals would be exempted, just as they're now exempted from
the fees summer renters pay for parking permits at the beaches.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel B. Klein, an economist at Santa Clara University, points
to a precedent in New York State last century, when private
turnpikes allowed free passage to people living within a mile of a
toll gate. But it would make more sense, he said, to give the
locals some incentive to stay off the road during peak hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might charge locals at a discount rate _ say, 50 percent
of the toll, or maybe just 10 percent,'' Klein said. ``There still
might be complaints from locals who have to cross the canal
frequently. But if they're using the road a lot, they'll appreciate
how much time they've saving. They might be paying only 10 percent
of the toll each trip, but they'll be reaping 100 percent of the
benefits of improved road conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   As a further enticement, the locals could be allowed to pocket
the toll revenues. The money could be divided up equally among all
local drivers, so that EZPass (or whoever operated the system)
would mail out an annual rebate check to drivers living east of the
canal.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the money might also be earmarked for a popular local
cause, like buying up farmland so that it is protected from
developers. That way the locals could enjoy more open space in
their towns without having to pay for it. And the visiting drivers
could finally enjoy some open space in front of their windshields.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
