<SLUG> BC-REAL-LIFE-COMEDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROPOLITAN DIARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ENID NEMY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A weekly column featuring readers' reports on life in the Big
Apple.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   It's Saturday, time for my weekly errands on Broadway. I start
at the Food Emporium between 89th and 90th. On the lower level, the
food demonstrator presents me with an eggplant dip and a Greek
Easter salad; the bakery has samples of French nut cake, the deli
has samples of ham and the fish department offers imitation crab.
Upstairs, the meat department gives chunks of its store-made
sausages.
</P>
<P>
   Two blocks down, I stop at Hot and Crusty, which invites me to
sample their muffins and bread. On to Zabar's, cheese and
raisin-nut bread samples and several varieties of pate on crackers
_ whitefish, smoked salmon, crab, lobster _ distributed throughout
the store.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, on the way, Godiva chocolates, a new addition to the avenue,
which invites passers-by to sample their brewed coffee and
chocolates.
</P>
<P>
   The 76th Street market _ cheese chunks and their hummus on bread
rounds.
</P>
<P>
   One more stop. Citarella on 75th Street. Cheese and samples of
pastry on the upper level and poached salmon on the first floor.
</P>
<P>
   Getting full! Enough _ no dinner tonight.
</P>
<P>
   _ ANNA KATZ BRENNER
</P>
<P>
   Scene: The Bronx Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   Players: Barbara and Aaron Cooper, and their granddaughter
Shauna Gillen, 10, dragging her feet, obviously hot and tired.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Cooper: ``If you're tired, think how I feel. I'm seven times
your age.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Cooper: ``You can figure that out. You're good in math.''
</P>
<P>
   Shauna: ``I don't do math in the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   The recent spell of hot weather reminded David Fishlow of his
return to New York in the 1970s after a stint in Texas. He thought
he would make the sweltering day more bearable by having a
remembered summer treat of his Bronx and Queens childhood. He and
some colleagues from his office took off for lunch at a nearby
delicatessen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have the borscht with sour cream,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Borscht?'' said the waiter in an incredulous voice. ``Who's
got borscht?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it says on the menu ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``Menu, schmenu,'' the waiter said (he really said this, Fishlow
recalls). ``I got no borscht.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So what kind of soup do you have?''
</P>
<P>
   ``What kind of soup? Look at the menu!''
</P>
<P>
   Fishlow's conclusion: ``I knew I was home.''
</P>
<P>
   A man who wishes to remain anonymous was having his
complimentary continental breakfast at a motel in upstate New York.
At a table nearby, a little girl of 7 or 8 had already helped
herself and was starting her breakfast. Soon her mother, carrying
coffee and toast, joined her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mommy, these are the best bagels I ever had!'' the little girl
said. ``Look at the sprinkles on them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, dear,'' her mother replied. ``Those kinds of bagels are
called doughnuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, the man said, he knew they were from New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ON LEAVING THE CITY
</P>
<P>
   Had to move up to the 'burbs
</P>
<P>
   Now no noise my sleep disturbs
</P>
<P>
   All smells sweet like fresh-picked herbs
</P>
<P>
   But, oh, I miss those concrete curbs.
</P>
<P>
   _ PATRICIA HYLAND
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   My 7-year-old granddaughter, Sarah Bressler, was driven to her
piano lesson each week by her mother, Irene. The early burst of
enthusiasm dimmed when she found that some practicing was required.
A few trips later, she sat in the back seat complaining: ``I don't
want to go there. I don't like music. I don't want ...''
</P>
<P>
   Her exasperated mother asked, ``What do you want?'''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what I really want?'' Sarah replied. It starts with a
`C' and ends with a `T.'''
</P>
<P>
   Puzzled, her mother said, ``You want a cat?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You want a carrot?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you want, Sarah?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to cwit.''
</P>
<P>
   _ HELENE R. EMANUEL
</P>
<P>
   Paul Kinney of Westland, Mich., who is in his 40s and has a bit
of gray in his beard, was visiting Manhattan with his parents
recently. They came off the subway train and didn't see any
directional signs. A woman with a bit of gray in her hair was about
to pass them when Kinney's father intercepted her, intending to ask
directions. The woman studiously ignored the older man but turned
to Kinney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are these your parents?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How nice. Are you single?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, so am I. Where do you live?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Detroit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Detroit! Are you Jewish?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to have met you. 'Bye.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kinneys had their chuckle for the day _ and their New York
story to dine out on.
</P>
<P>
   CALL ME!
</P>
<P>
   ``Leave your name and number,''
</P>
<P>
   my phone recording says _
</P>
<P>
   Tomorrow I may wish to remember
</P>
<P>
   Those I rebuff today.
</P>
<P>
   _ EDITH CLARKE
</P>
<P>
   The H &AMP; H bagel truck was in front of Rhea and Martin Basroon as
they drove up to a tollbooth on the New Jersey Turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   They were slightly impatient and curious as the truck remained
at the booth a little longer than expected. Finally, it moved on,
the Basroons moved up for their turn and the reason for the delay
was instantly apparent _ the tollbooth worker was holding a freshly
delivered bag of bagels.
</P>
<P>
   Was it a regular delivery? An unexpected gift? They asked but
they'll never know _ the worker's mouth was full of bagel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
