<SLUG> BC-NYC-REVIEW-BOARD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI'S CONTROL IS CRUX OF DEBATE OVER POLICE REVIEW BOARD
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After Nick Noe graduated magna cum laude from Brown
University last May, he accepted an offer to work as an
investigator for the Civilian Complaint Review Board, the New York
City agency that examines complaints of police misconduct. But the
Giuliani administration overturned his hiring this summer, Noe
said, when it learned of his youthful indiscretion: he had worked
for Democrats as a teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   Noe says officials at the review board, which calls itself an
independent agency, admitted to him that City Hall rejected him
largely because his resume listed too many summers spent
volunteering for Democratic causes.
</P>
<P>
   He says the rejection made him so angry that he signed up last
month as a volunteer for Hillary Rodham Clinton, who is Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani's likely Democratic foe if he runs in next year's
race for the U.S.Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so maddening to me that this would happen for so
explicitly political and seemingly vindictive reasons,'' Noe said.
``Being political and being a Democrat should not be something that
removes you from a job.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials dispute Noe's account, insisting that he was
rejected for nonpolitical reasons that they would not specify. But
the level of control that the mayor's office exerts over the review
board's hiring, over the appointment of its governing panel and
over the size of its budget has become part of the continuing
debate over the board's independence, efficiency and structure, a
debate that is likely to grow louder in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, Police Commissioner Howard Safir has said he
envisions an expanded role for the review board within the police
disciplinary process because the quality of its investigations has
improved.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, that process is being scrutinized by
investigators from the U.S. attorney's office in Brooklyn. The
investigation is focusing on whether the police department has
effectively disciplined officers who use excessive force. As part
of their review, the investigators studied statistics that show
that, for a variety of reasons, the department does not discipline
half of the officers against whom civilian complaints are
substantiated by the review board.
</P>
<P>
   Although police officials have defended their disciplinary
record as strict, federal investigators have already concluded that
the offending officers often escape punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors are now negotiating possible improvements in
police discipline with the Giuliani administration, and the
discussion is likely to consider methods of strengthening the
review board. Though the prosecutors will not discuss their
negotiations, critics of the review board said a major improvement
would be to increase the panel's independence from the executive
branch. Now, the critics note, the mayor has the final say on all
hiring, appoints all of the panel's 13 members and selects its
chairman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-99 0013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990823.0010 </DOCNO>
