<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6059 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-DEATH-PENALTY-NY     08-23 0384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-DEATH-PENALTY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: EXECUTIONS MADE EASIER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, Aug. 23:
</P>
<P>
   Federal judges from the 11th Circuit Court of Appeals and state
judges from the three states of that circuit _ Georgia, Alabama and
Florida _ convened last week at an Atlanta resort to discuss how to
expedite state death-penalty cases.
</P>
<P>
   Though the ostensible goal was to improve the process, there is
little doubt that improvement in this context usually means
speeding up executions by making it harder for death-row inmates to
appeal. Featured speakers included Judge Edward Carnes of the 11th
Circuit, an outspoken death-penalty advocate, and Edith Jones, a
federal appeals judge from Texas who has been a severe critic of
lawyers who file death-penalty appeals.
</P>
<P>
   It is chilling that the judges of the 11th Circuit, which has a
moderate record on executions, should be seeking guidance from
states like Texas. Texas has been ruthlessly effective in executing
184 inmates since 1982, a frenzy made possible in part by courts
willing to deny appeals even in egregiously unjust circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   The judges at the conference may think they are simply
discussing effective caseload management, but the application of
the death penalty in this country is so grossly unfair that any
honest discussion must begin by examining the system's fundamental
defects.
</P>
<P>
   Defendants in capital cases are often represented by
inexperienced or incompetent trial lawyers working for a pittance.
Federal and state statutes and Supreme Court decisions have greatly
limited courts' abilities to consider meritorious constitutional
claims by death-row inmates. Many states pay little or nothing for
post-conviction proceedings, forcing condemned inmates to represent
themselves or seek volunteer lawyers for help.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a system in which some people die because they had
bad lawyers and no real shot at a full and fair review, while
others fortunate enough to get better counsel are spared the death
penalty. A lucky few, helped by pro bono lawyers who take up their
causes, have actually been proved innocent after years on death
row.
</P>
<P>
   Moving this flawed system along more smoothly will only increase
unjust outcomes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-99 0015EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990823.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6061 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-RUN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-H     08-23 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SEVILLE, Spain _ Maurice Greene was shoehorned into a middle seat
on the crowded connecting flight from Madrid, twisting, wriggling
and trying to get comfortable, when the man to his left tapped him
on the shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you traveling to Seville to watch the races?'' the man
asked in a thick German accent.
</P>
<P>
   Greene turned, smiled and pointed to a large color photo on the
front page of a sports section being read by another passenger
across the aisle. It showed a sprinter with his arms raised in
triumph beneath a headline that read, in Spanish, ``Blazing
Glory.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pardon,'' replied the man. ``You don't look to be that fast of
a little bugger.''
</P>
<P>
   Which was probably, about 30 minutes later, the thought going
through the mind of the would-be sneak thief in the airport baggage
claim area as he tried to make off with the wallet of former
University of Texas hurdler Larry Wade, only to be caught from
behind by the fastest man on the planet over 100 meters.
</P>
<P>
   Greene is to world record holders what The Blair Witch Project
is to the film industry _ a frighteningly unlikely success story.
And the scariest thing seems to be that he has still not reached
his limit.
</P>
<P>
   Despite stumbling out of the starting blocks for the first
several steps, Greene engaged Bruny Surin in a dramatic
side-by-side, stride-for-stride duel and eventually ran down the
Canadian in the stretch to claim his second straight gold medal in
the 100 meters Sunday night at the World Track and Field
Championships.
</P>
<P>
   Greene's time of 9.80 was .01 off his world record set in June,
but it was still the second-fastest 100 meters in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess that's pretty amazing to be able to stumble at the
start and still wind up with a 9.80,'' Greene said.
</P>
<P>
   No more amazing than Greene's stunning rise to the top of the
sprint world.
</P>
<P>
   Just two years ago, Greene had given serious thought to quitting
track and field to find a career in the real world. Struggling
mightily to pay his bills, he was eking out an existence on cash
from several part-time jobs and a loan from his training partner,
Ato Boldon.
</P>
<P>
   Then a shocking thing happened. Greene won the 100-meter title
at the U.S. national meet in June 1997, posted the three fastest
times of the year by an American, then stunned the sport two months
later by capturing the gold medal at the World Championships in
Athens.
</P>
<P>
   At precisely the time when Carl Lewis was hanging up his spikes
on a long, glorious career and the talk around the track was the
end of U.S. dominance in men's sprinting, along came this raw,
talkative, fast little bugger to take the baton and carry on the
chase.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beware the phenomenon,'' Greene said before the start of the
competition.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what he is, an entirely different kind of
sprinter than the men who had held the 100-meter record over the
past decade. Canada's Donovan Bailey embraced the role of the angry
outsider from north of the border. Leroy Burrell was quiet and very
unassuming. Lewis was the statesman, the standard-bearer for his
sport, carrying the air of a professor with all of the answers. Ben
Johnson was the bullet-headed pit bull before his reign ended in
steroid-fueled disgrace.
</P>
<P>
   So along comes the tiny 5-9 Greene, who rolls his shoulders like
a boxer before a fight as he approaches the starting block but
makes every trip out seem like a giggle-filled romp to the end of
the block with a playful puppy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have nothing to not be happy about,'' he said. ``It wasn't
long ago when I was worrying about paying my rent, and now I'm
living on top of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Few expected the 100 final to be as compelling or the winning
time so fast. The field was without an injured Boldon, the only man
to beat Greene this year. Also missing were Bailey, the defending
Olympic champ who is recovering from injury, and former U.S. world
medalist Dennis Mitchell, who has been suspended in the ongoing
drug scandals. Then Frank Fredericks, the silver medalist at the
past two Olympics, scratched from the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   There would be nobody to push Greene. Or so it was thought. But
Surin, running to Greene's immediate right, gave him all he could
handle. Until the last 25 meters.
</P>
<P>
   Greene's lean won it at the wire, and Surin, who thought he had
the race won, snarled in anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started out slow, I was thinking, `I can come back and
get them,''' Greene said. ``And in the last 10 meters I knew I had
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Boldon has seen the comebacks up close so many times in their
workouts. Maurice lives to catch people from behind. The would-be
thief at the Seville airport learned that the hard way when he
tried to make off with Wade's wallet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grabbed the guy's arm right away,'' Wade said. ``But the
security guards turned around and grabbed me. Meanwhile, the guy
dropped my wallet and started to run away. That's when Maurice went
after him. The guy had a 10-yard head start, and Maurice caught him
in 25 and turned him in to the police.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad to have the world's fastest man as my best
friend. But I guess it should have been an omen. Maurice ran down a
thief, and then he ran down Surin.''
</P>
<P>
   Quite a quick and persistent little bugger.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
