<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 00:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6078 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-HURRICANE-2NDLD-TEX     08-23 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-2NDLD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HURRICANE POUNDS ASHORE, BUT POPULATED AREAS LARGELY SPARED
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: CORRECTS ``inches'' to ``feet'' in 7th graf) 
(Accompanied by BC-HURRICANE-EVACUATE, BC-HURRICANE-BUSH, others) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER and JOHN MORITZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORPUS CHRISTI, Texas _ Hurricane Bret pummeled a largely
uninhabited region of the Texas coast with 140 mph winds Sunday,
apparently sparing heavily populated areas major damage from the
Category 4 storm.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people from Brownsville to Galveston evacuated
low-lying coastal areas, clogging public shelters and filling
motels as far inland as San Antonio as the first hurricane to
strike Texas in a decade made landfall in sparsely populated Kenedy
County.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush declared seven South Texas counties disaster
areas and called on President Clinton to issue an ``expedited
presidential disaster declaration.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope my fellow Texans say a prayer for those fellow Texans
that are in harm's way,'' Bush said at a news briefing in Austin,
Texas, Sunday afternoon. ``A disaster comes like a thief in the
night sometimes. I hope this storm, as ferocious as it may seem,
will not affect human life.''
</P>
<P>
   Corpus Christi Mayor Loyd Neal said Sunday evening that damage
in the city of 275,000 had been minimal, mainly downed trees and
roof shingles blown off.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could have been a major, major storm hitting Corpus
Christi,'' said Neal, who runs an insurance agency.
</P>
<P>
   Flooding remained a major threat. Forecasters said the storm
could dump 10 to 15 inches of rain as it moved inland. There also
was concern that a storm surge would push water 10 to 15 feet above
normal levels, particularly in bays.
</P>
<P>
   At least 1,600 Texas National Guard troops were put on standby
near San Antonio to provide assistance to hurricane victims, and
all available state troopers were helping evacuate people and
coordinate emergency activities.
</P>
<P>
   The eye of the compact but powerful storm came ashore in late
evening in Kenedy County, aiming the brunt of its force at the
heart of the 825,000-acre King Ranch between Corpus Christi and
Raymondville. The legendary ranch, founded in 1853 by Capt. Richard
King, is bigger than Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   The storm quickly weakened as it moved inland, falling to a
Category 3 hurricane with winds of 125 mph. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ken Graham, meteorologist with the National Weather Ser'' vice
in Fort Worth, said at a Department of Public Safety briefing in
Austin Sunday night that the landfall in Kenedy County minimized
the storm's impact on Corpus Christi. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``But ... it ain't over yet. We've got a long way to go with
this thing,'' Graham said, referring to the potential for
flooding. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Raymondville, a citrus farming community of 8,800 about 30
miles south of where the eye came ashore, wind gusts of up to 75
mph ripped off roofs and blew down trees and power lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, we can just pray the Good Lord spares our
town,'' Mayor Joe Sosa said about 6:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, pastor of the non-denominational Raymondville Christian
Center, urged those in flood-prone areas to seek shelter at a local
funeral home.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane-force winds extended up to 40 miles from the storm's
eye, whipping debris through Raymondville. Streets were deserted
except for a few cars that sought shelter under gas station
awnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting hit pretty hard right now, but there's no way of
telling whether we've seen the worst of it yet,'' said Pete
Fresquez, who was operating Raymondville's emergency hotline.
</P>
<P>
   Lebore Montoya, 45, a resident of Mexico who was trying to get
to Corpus Christi to be with his family, sought shelter at a gas
station in Raymondville when the storm hit. ``At a time like this,
I really want to be with my wife and kids,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The storm's path was similar to that of Hurricane Allen, which
came ashore in the same region with 185 mph winds in 1980, causing
$55 million in property damage and killing two people.
</P>
<P>
   While winds of more than 100 mph were buffeting the scrub brush
and marshes of the coastal ranchland, wind gusts had not exceeded
55 mph in Corpus Christi as of 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Despite nonstop warnings of the approaching storm, people turned
out at Cole Park on the Corpus Christi bayfront in late afternoon
to see the impact of the edge of the hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   Kira Ware, a married college student, took a Suburban-load of
relatives including her 5-year-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to show her what a hurricane is like,'' Ware said.
</P>
<P>
   As choppy waves smacked the rocky shore and sheets of rain began
falling, Ricky Rodriguez showed the view to his 11-year-old
daughter and her 13-year-old cousin. Then they headed home where
Rodriguez said he had a backup electric generator and, to see them
through the storm, ``a bunch of horror videos.''
</P>
<P>
   The landscaped boulevard along the bayfront was littered with
palm fronds shaken loose from trees. Fishing boats and yachts were
beached on traffic islands as a precaution.
</P>
<P>
   In Corpus Christi Sunday night, the major concern was that the
storm surge might push water over the 15-foot seawall and flood
downtown, which is lower than the man-made barrier.
</P>
<P>
   Red Cross and government officials in Corpus Christi decided
against opening shelters in the city, opting instead to wait until
Monday to assess the damage and see if the shelters were needed.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane warnings extended for about 200 miles along the coast
from Brownsville to Port O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   Brownsville residents spent a hurried weekend preparing for the
storm. Moderate rain fell sporadically Sunday, but there was
otherwise no hint of a hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   South Padre Island, the barrier island linked to Brownsville by
a causeway, was evacuated by early Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   At the Builder's Square on Texas 48, which is the road off the
island, manager Charlie Velasco said his store remained open until
2 a.m. as buyers streamed in asking for sheets of plywood and
particle board to protect their windows.
</P>
<P>
   At least 6,000 sheets passed through his checkout counters by
midday, Velasco said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We normally don't sell one-tenth of that in a weekend,'' he
said. ``I got 1,100 sheets in last night at 11. By midnight, they
were gone. They say war is good for the nation's economy. I guess a
hurricane is good for my store's economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of Brownsville residents fled low-lying areas and
filled at least two shelters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were scared our house would be flooded, so we came here,''
said Molly Oyervides, 46, who huddled on the hallway floor of a
school with her 10-year-old daughter. Her husband, who works
nights, was curled up asleep on a blanket.
</P>
<P>
   The school district provided cold-cut meals, bottled water and
soft drinks for those who sought refuge in the shelters, said
Maricela Zarate, the school principal who was doubling as a shelter
operator.
</P>
<P>
   (Star-Telegram writer Bill Hanna contributed to this report.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
