<HEADER>
A6079 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-BULLET-LEAD-FREE-SPI &LR;      08-23 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BULLET-LEAD-FREE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMY HAS QUIETLY BEEN REPLACING LEAD AMMO WITH `GREEN BULLETS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ED OFFLEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   YAKIMA TRAINING CENTER, Wash. _ Crouched over a radio microphone
high atop the turret of his command vehicle, Col. Mark Hertling
watched down range as the treeless terrain bucked and heaved in
response to his every command.
</P>
<P>
   Culminating six months of training at Fort Lewis and a month of
arduous field maneuvers here, Hertling supervised a live-fire
exercise involving a dozen tanks, armor vehicles and artillery
pieces assigned to his unit, the 3rd Brigade, 2nd Infantry
Division. As Hertling barked orders into his radio, the ground
underfoot literally shook with the impact of artillery shells and
tank cannon rounds as hundreds of rounds of rifle and machine-gun
fire crackled.
</P>
<P>
   Both at Fort Lewis near Tacoma and here at this 322,400-acre
desert warfare training center, the Army's need for realistic
combat training and the service's responsibility for careful
management of a fragile environment coexist in a delicate balance,
officials say.
</P>
<P>
   One long-term environmental issue that has attracted the
service's attention in recent years is the potential environmental
threat from lead-based ammunition and a research initiative to come
up with a ``lead-free'' bullet.
</P>
<P>
   With little fanfare, the Army has designed new small-arms
ammunition that replaces lead with the inert heavy metal, tungsten,
and has begun mass production of this so-called ``green bullet,''
said Jim Arnold, chief of the pollution prevention and
environmental technology division of the Army Environmental Center,
in a telephone interview from Aberdeen, Md.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tungsten, lead-free bullet is being put into production as
we speak,'' Arnold said.
</P>
<P>
   Army officials and scientists say the two most likely health
hazards from lead-based ammunition occur at indoor rifle ranges,
where inadequate ventilation may expose soldiers to minute lead
particles in the air, and at outdoor ranges and impact areas that
lie over freshwater aquifers that are the source of drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold said lead from small arms or artillery buried in the soil
of ranges or impact areas poses no threat by itself. ``You need to
look at it on a site specific basis,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason we started taking a harder look at the `green
bullet' was at some installations ... the Army should be taking a
hard look at site-specific conditions,'' Arnold said. He declined
to identify any specific bases that may have a potential pollution
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Lewis officials say there is no known evidence that lead
ammunition is threatening water sources at the Pierce County base
or at Yakima. There are 67 live fire ranges and four artillery
impact areas at Fort Lewis and another 21 live fire ranges and
artillery impact areas at Yakima which are clearly marked and used
for no other purpose, said Fort Lewis spokeswoman Lt. Col. Melanie
Reeder. At Yakima, there are 46,000 acres, constituting 14 percent
of the total center acreage, that are used for live-fire and
artillery impact areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I Corps takes very, very carefully the stewardship we assume
of all areas under our responsibilities,'' Reeder said. ``There are
incredible initiatives in place to preserve water, wildlife and
foliage both here at Fort Lewis and Yakima.''
</P>
<P>
   The lead pollution issue made headlines in Massachusetts two
years ago when the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency banned the
use of live ammunition at a National Guard base on Cape Cod on
grounds the toxic metal was leaching into an aquifer that
constitute's the peninsula's sole source of drinking water. Army
officials later disputed the EPA conclusion, calculating that it
would take several hundred years for the pollution to reach the
water table.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Massachusetts incident prompted the Army to
accelerate production of lead-free ammunition as a result in any
event, Arnold said. The service is already replacing M-16
ammunition with the tungsten round and has a goal of implementing
lead-free ammunition for other small arms including the Squad
Automatic Weapon machine gun, M-60 machine gun and .50 cal. machine
gun within the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   The 3rd Brigade's exercise at Yakima was typical for an Army
unit that size, Hertling said. The 3,900-person brigade will have
shot off about 500,000 rounds of live ammunition when the
two-month-long Yakima maneuver ends next month, he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the Army uses video simulators to train tank and artillery
crews, it is essential for soldiers to ``get out in the dust and
fight with sleep deprivation,'' Hertling said. During the Yakima
exercise, each M1A1 crew has been able to fire 55 tank cannon
rounds apiece, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Armywide, soldiers fire about 400 million rifle rounds a year in
life-fire training, officials say. Since each .223 cal. bullet
fired by the M-16 assault rifle contains about 32 grains of lead
(or .0023 oz.), the Army calculates that each year over 900 tons of
lead metal is fired into rifle range target areas or live-fire
zones armywide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
