<DOCNO> NYT19990823.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 00:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6084 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-SERVERS-INTERNET-SFCH     08-23 1340
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERVERS-INTERNET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
MICROSOFT AND ALLIES SET SIGHTS ON SERVERS &HT;    BY HENRY NORR
 &HT;    c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Squeezed by declining profit margins in the
desktop computer market, Intel, Microsoft and their PC-industry
allies are eager to move up the computing food chain.
</P>
<P>
   They've already taken over a good chunk of the market for
technical workstations and departmental servers, the machines that
store files and run applications for corporate work groups and
small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Now the ``Wintel'' vendors have set their sights on an even more
lucrative business: selling the high-powered machines required for
corporate data centers, Internet service providers and major Web
sites. This month they're rolling out a flurry of new systems
designed for just such uses _ and backing them up with a full-scale
marketing mobilization aimed at information-technology
professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, analysts say, the ``Wintel'' axis almost certainly
will take over a good part of this market. But in the near term _
perhaps a year or more _ the incumbent leaders in the big-server
arena, notably Sun Microsystems, may have less to fear than the
hype suggests.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq, already the largest vendor of small servers, last week
threw down the gauntlet with its first two ``eight-way'' models _
computers that put eight of Intel's most powerful microprocessors
to work in parallel. Code-named ``Thunder'' and ``Lightning,'' the
new machines will ship with Microsoft's Windows NT Server operating
system though they're also capable of running some versions of
Unix.
</P>
<P>
   Today (August 23) Hitachi, which has been offering eight-way,
Intel-based servers since January, will follow with the
announcement of enhanced models. During the next few weeks, Dell,
IBM, Hewlett-Packard, Unisys and nearly 20 others are expected to
join the race.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to top-of-the-line Intel Pentium III Xeon
processors, they'll all use Profusion, a new set of surrounding
chips developed by Intel's Corollary subsidiary, which enable the
Xeon processors to work in parallel.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq, HP and IBM already sell high-powered servers that, like
Sun's, run some flavor of Unix on their own ``RISC'' chips.
Although they'll continue to offer these non-Wintel machines, at
least for now, they're also jumping on the Intel eight-way
bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   The main selling point for the new systems, compared with
current Unix options, is price rather than performance or
reliability.
</P>
<P>
   Not that they're cheap, at least by PC standards: The Compaq
machines, now dubbed the ProLiant 8000 and 8500, will range between
$20,000 and $80,000. Hitachi's new VisionBase 8890R, with a custom
version of the Profusion chip set that Hitachi says increases
performance up to 30 percent, will go for $30,000 to $90,000.
</P>
<P>
   But in comparison to current server options offering similar
levels of performance, those prices look like bargains. An
eight-way RISC system easily can cost three, four or five times as
much or even more.
</P>
<P>
   Why the huge differential? RISC server vendors develop their own
proprietary microprocessors, chip sets and operating system
software. The companies offering the new Intel eight-way servers
are following something much closer to the PC business model: By
relying on Intel for their processors and chips sets and on
Microsoft for the OS, they get the benefits of common standards and
economies of scale.
</P>
<P>
   Similar economics have enabled PC-makers to take over most of
the low-end server market with systems equipped with one, two or
four Intel processors. A recent white paper from International Data
Corp. estimates that in 1999, Intel chips will account for 85
percent of unit shipments in server systems.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, said Dataquest analyst Kimball Brown, ``For a file and
print server, e-mail, groupware, even a basic HTTP (Web) server,
it's crazy not to go to Intel _ it's drastically cheaper.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Wintel camp could face a tougher battle now that it's
trying to sell bigger servers, which are intended to run
``mission-critical'' applications such as order-processing,
reservation and e-commerce systems.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is that the Profusion technology is new and
relatively untested in the field. When Intel acquired Corollary in
1997, it said Profusion would reach the market in 1998, but
technical glitches have forced repeated delays.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of history may be a red flag for many IT
professionals, who tend to be risk-averse when it comes to the
applications from which their organizations earn their bread and
butter.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the OS problem. The newly announced systems will
ship, for now, with Microsoft Windows NT 4.0. That OS isn't
considered particularly efficient in taking advantage of even
four-way Intel-based servers, and Microsoft acknowledges that it
wasn't designed for eight-way hardware.
</P>
<P>
   Even the vendors promoting the new servers admit that NT 4.0
doesn't take full advantage of their hardware. Michael Krieger,
vice president of server marketing at Hitachi Data Systems in Santa
Clara, said that with the current Microsoft OS, going from four to
eight processors improves transaction-processing performance by
only 1.3- or 1.4-fold.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as good as anyone would like,'' he said. ``It's
definitely not as good as Unix.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Krieger and everyone else committed to the Intel
servers, the situation should change this fall, when Microsoft
finally ships Windows 2000, the long-delayed successor to NT.
Windows 2000 Advanced Server, one of the four versions Microsoft
will offer, is designed specifically to take advantage of up to
eight processors. Microsoft said last week that it's on track for
release before the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   In light of the bugs that often have plagued new Microsoft OS
releases, few IT professionals are likely to deploy Windows 2000 in
mission-critical applications immediately, especially because it's
due to arrive on the eve of the Y2K transition. Most customers are
expected to wait at least for Microsoft's first ``Service Pack,''
or bug-fix collection.
</P>
<P>
   As analyst Rob Enderle of Giga Information Group put it, ``It
kind of stretches the limits of credulity to talk about deploying
mission-critical software on a platform that's largely untested.
Probably eight-way doesn't become real until Windows 2000 does.''
</P>
<P>
   But the OS isn't the only software issue. Applications that now
run on RISC Unix machines needed to be ``ported,'' or converted,
then tested and tuned on the Intel chips and Microsoft OS before
they could be moved to the new servers. Even applications that
currently run on smaller Intel-based servers generally will need to
be tuned up to get the full benefit of the new servers' extra
processors.
</P>
<P>
   All of this takes time. ``You don't just say, `The hardware went
from four processors to eight, so I'm going to move all my apps.'
That's absurd,'' said Dataquest's Brown. ``It's a long-term, slow
process.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, said James Gruener, an analyst at the Aberdeen
Group in Boston, the eight-way servers are ``just the first of
several ingredients that are needed to make up the big picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Although many companies might order one or two of the new
machines now for testing, and a few who are particularly
performance-starved might put them to work immediately, the
analysts all agreed that large-scale deployment won't occur until
at least next year, probably not until the second half of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, Giga's Enderle said, the servers will have at best a
modest effect on the financial fortunes of Intel and its partners
in the eight-way initiative.
</P>
<P>
   But in a larger perspective, this month's server introductions
might look more significant. ``Most of all,'' Gruener said, ``it
will change the way Intel servers are perceived by the people who
buy servers. Judging by the benchmarks, it's pretty clear that they
now have the power to handle midrange tasks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And that,'' Gruener said, ``is a real turning point.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
