<HEADLINE>
MACHINISTS TELL BOEING THEY WANT MORE JOBS PROTECTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL NYHAN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The International Association of Machinists told The
Boeing Co. on Sunday that it must take greater steps to preserve
union jobs, including eliminating special promotion rules, if it
wants to avoid a strike.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing and the union are locked in intensive talks to reach a
new contact for 44,000 Machinists by Sept. 1. The union, fueled by
a fear that the company will farm many Boeing jobs out to other
companies and to cheaper labor markets, has made the preservation
of jobs its key issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see what they are planning and it doesn't look good,''
Bill Johnson, head of IAM's District Lodge 751, told hundreds of
workers at a rally Sunday outside a SeaTac, Wash., hotel, the site
of the talks.
</P>
<P>
   The union has called on Boeing to scrap a system that allows
managers to protect a certain number of jobs from layoffs and to
promote a set number of people over others with more seniority.
That debate is only a preview of the larger issues negotiators will
tackle this week over how to preserve jobs at the aerospace giant.
</P>
<P>
   The company has said it's willing to address the union's
concerns, but it's also fighting to retain tools it believes are
vital to managing its work force and workload.
</P>
<P>
   Although Boeing plans to continue to hire some outside firms to
help it build airplanes, it doesn't plan to send the majority of
regional Boeing jobs to other areas, according to a company
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not the Boeing business plan,'' said Peter Conte, a
spokesman for the company.
</P>
<P>
   While the union is fighting to preserve jobs, the company is
fighting to preserve its future as a competitor in the airline
business, Boeing officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The company, currently the world's largest commercial airplane
manufacturer, must hold down its costs to succeed, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The two camps are preparing to enter the critical second week of
negotiations, which will culminate Friday when the company promises
to hand the union a final contract proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The week got off to a bad start Sunday, as union negotiators
complained that Boeing officials abandoned the talks for most of
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to get off the nickel,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing officials have met with the union every day, according to
Conte, and they decided to take Sunday morning off to meet family
obligations and other needs.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, officials from both sides of the bargaining table admit
they are making progress. Despite the disagreement over job
security, the union's lead negotiator said there was a 50-50 chance
that the Machinists would strike.
</P>
<P>
   And even though union leaders said the company wants to avoid
the issue of job security, they believe union members are in an
excellent position to extract concessions because Boeing is
scheduled to deliver a record 620 airplanes this years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to get exactly what we want,'' said Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   But some Machinists were skeptical they would succeed without a
strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's inevitable,'' said Scott Kincaid, who works at
Boeing's Everett plant. ``It's about time to draw the lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Machinists probably will render their judgment Sept. 1, when
they vote to either accept or reject the company's offer. The
current pact will expire Sept. 2.
</P>
<P>
   The final contract will also have influence far beyond the walls
of Boeing's plants.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing is the nation's largest exporter and a massive
manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   Labor leaders and many large U.S. manufacturers are keeping a
close eye on the negotiations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
