A6087 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-RANGERS-BO     08-23 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEEP IN THE HEART OF TEXAS 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-RANGERS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Dan Duquette can do without the kind of
reminder former Sox pitcher Aaron Sele gave him Sunday night while
beating the Sox, 6-0, completing the Texas Rangers' three-game
sweep of the staggering Olde Towne Team.
</P>
<P>
   It'll be even worse come October, if the Red Sox are watching
the playoffs on TV while Sele is pitching for the division-winning
Rangers, who scored two runs before Tim Wakefield retired a batter,
got another home run from Rafael Palmeiro (his fourth of the
weekend and seventh in seven games), and broke it open with two
more runs in the seventh, the last on Rusty Greer's triple off the
top of the wall.
</P>
<P>
   With 38 games left, Sunday night's loss dropped the Sox, losers
of four in a row and five of their last six, a game behind the
Oakland A's in the wild-card race, the first time since Aug. 12 the
Sox have trailed for a playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you can score runs easily, other times it's like
pulling teeth out of a duck,'' Red Sox manager Jimy Williams said
after Sele extended a weekend of misery for the Sox, who failed in
all three games to come up with hits when they needed them.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox were 0 for 3 with runners in scoring position in Friday
night's 4-3 loss, 1 for 11 in Saturday night's 9-2 loss, and after
Jose Offerman lined deep to center fielder Tom Goodwin with two on
and two out in the seventh, their last scoring chance of the game,
0 for 4 Sunday &UR;  &LR; night.
</P>
<P>
   ``They bunched their hits,'' Williams said, ``and we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox were outscored, 19-5, in the sweep after being shut out
for the first time since Aug. 5, when they were beaten, 8-0, by the
Angels in Anaheim. This was only the second time this season
they've been swept in a three-game set; they lost three straight in
Montreal June 6-8.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made good pitches when he had to,'' DH Butch Huskey said of
Sele, who allowed eight hits, seven of them singles, in pitching
his second complete-game shutout of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not an overpowering pitcher, but he threw both breaking
ball and fastball in good spots. When a guy is doing that, he's
going to be tough. (Rangers pitchers) were like that the whole
series. They didn't make too many mistakes out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Sele won 19 games for Texas last season and with 14 wins is on
his way toward matching or exceeding that this season. Meanwhile,
the Sox, so strapped for pitching they rolled Wakefield out of the
bullpen to start for the first time since June 8, have little to
show for the trade in which they sent Sele to the Rangers two years
ago this November.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Leyritz, who was supposed to be the regular catcher, hit
some big home runs a year ago last April, then was gone by June by
mutual discontent. He wasn't happy as a part-timer with the Sox,
and Duquette had little tolerance for the King. Leyritz went to San
Diego, and the players the Sox got in return (pitchers Carlos Reyes
and Dario Veras) are long gone.
</P>
<P>
   All that the Sox have to show for Sele is Damon Buford, a
part-time outfielder who is on the disabled list. And Buford, who
can expect a hefty raise in arbitration this winter, may be gone
after this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially after losing a couple in a row, I think everybody
has been trying to do too much,'' said rookie Brian Daubach, whose
first-inning single was the only time in eight at-bats this weekend
that he got the ball out of the infield.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be OK, especially if we can get a couple of runs early.
We don't have to worry about anybody else, there's still plenty of
time left.''
</P>
<P>
   The Belleville Basher has cooled off since driving in 15 runs in
four games last weekend. He was, of course, not alone in his
futility. Troy O'Leary had a single, but struck out with a runner
on third and is just 2 for his last 32. John Valentin also had a
single, but he's 4 for 32.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox now have scored three runs or fewer in six of their last
eight games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just got to get back in a good groove,'' Daubach said.
``I couldn't keep swinging the way I've been the last couple of
weeks, but I've just got to keep working.
</P>
<P>
   ``They not only made good pitches, they made some real good
defensive plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Sele, who has won seven of his last eight decisions to improve
his record to 14-7, did not retire the Sox in order through the
first seven innings. But it wasn't until the fifth that the Sox
advanced a runner as far as second base, the sixth before they had
a runner on third, and the seventh before they had their first
extra-base hit (Darren Lewis's two-out double) and Sele had issued
his first walk, to Trot Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon, with runners on first and second and no outs after
singles by Jason Varitek and Lewis in the fifth, grounded into a
double play, and Offerman tapped to first to leave Varitek at
third.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin singled to open the sixth, but was erased at second on
a terrific play by shortstop Royce Clayton, who went deep in the
hole to glove Daubach's bid for a single and went airborne to throw
out Valentin. Daubach took second on a grounder to the right side
by Nomar Garciaparra and third on a wild pitch, but was left there
when O'Leary struck out.
</P>
<P>
   Sele, who recorded 17 ground-ball outs, has pitched at least
seven innings in his last five starts and trails only Pedro
Martinez (17) and Baltimore's Mike Mussina (15) in wins, even with
an earned run average that only Sunday night dropped under 5
(4.91). He also has become a strikeout pitcher. He entered the game
with a team-leading 138 whiffs, fourth in the league, and struck
out five Sunday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-99 0059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
