<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 01:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6088 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-TITANS-INTERNET-SFCHR     08-23 1671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TITANS-INTERNET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
MICROSOFT AND AOL'S CYBER WAR &HT;    By TOM STEIN
 &HT;    c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In this corner, weighing in with annual sales of
$19.7 billion, an operating system that controls the vast majority
of the world's personal computers, and a Web browser used by
three-quarters of all Net surfers, the one, the only Microsoft
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In the opposing corner, with $4.8 billion in sales, an
unparalleled subscriber base of 18 million Internet users, and the
fiercest reputation in the online world, the amazing America
Online.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the biggest powerhouses in corporate America are squaring
off in a battle that may determine who will control the next
generation of computing.
</P>
<P>
   For the past month, Microsoft Corp. and America Online have been
engaged in an increasingly bloody slugfest centered around all
things Internet. So far, the battles include instant messaging,
Internet access, online bill paying and e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things represent the future of computing,'' said Rob
Enderle, an analyst with the Giga Information Group. ``Whoever
fails to adapt won't be around in 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   The two titans are duking it out for the hearts and minds of
consumers who are relying more and more on the Internet for
entertainment, communications and shopping.
</P>
<P>
   AOL chief executive Steve Case is playing his cards close to his
vest. Although many observers think the two companies are on a
collision course, &LR;   &LR; he said AOL doesn't want to battle Microsoft's
core business. ``I have a lot of respect for Microsoft,'' Case told
the Washington Post early this year. ``I continue to live in fear
of them.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, AOL clearly has Microsoft worried. After all,
the first time these behemoths went toe-to-toe, it was AOL who came
out on top.
</P>
<P>
   According to the book ``aol.com,'' by Kara Swisher, Microsoft
CEO Bill Gates tried to buy AOL six years ago. Gates invited Case
to Redmond and told him, ``I can buy 20 percent of you, or I can
buy all of you. Or I can go into this business myself and bury
you,'' the book stated.
</P>
<P>
   Case declined the offer. Instead, AOL grew stronger than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft went on to launch the Microsoft Network (MSN), an
online service that closely mimics AOL's mixture of content and
community. In 1995, Microsoft began bundling MSN with its Windows
95 operating system. The logic was that consumers quickly would
turn away from AOL in favor of the preinstalled Microsoft service.
Four years later, Microsoft has only 2 million subscribers, while
AOL has nearly 10 times that amount.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft is not a company that shies away from a good
fight, especially when it thinks someone is encroaching on its
turf. And increasingly, that's what AOL seems to be doing.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, AOL swallowed up Netscape, Microsoft's
biggest rival in the Web browser market. ``That's when AOL really
identified itself as a primary competitor (to Microsoft),'' said
Enderle. ``As soon as that happened, Microsoft changed its focus to
address the AOL threat.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Tarter, publisher of Softletter, a computer industry
newsletter, has an even simpler take on the brewing hostilities.
``Anybody big is Microsoft's enemy,'' he said. ``AOL sits atop a
monster-sized market, and Microsoft's in a position where they have
to go after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Late last month, Microsoft launched its first pre-emptive strike
against AOL with an attack on instant messaging, the Internet
application that alerts Web surfers when their friends are online
and allows them to communicate through text messages in real time,
without the lag of regular e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   AOL currently reigns supreme in instant messaging, with about 65
million users. Microsoft did not even have a messaging product
until last month, when it entered the market with a bang, quickly
signing up 1.3 million users. Unlike other messaging products, MSN
Messenger boasted interoperability features that allowed users to
communicate with friends on AOL's offering.
</P>
<P>
   An outraged AOL claimed that Microsoft was gaining unauthorized
access to its subscriber lists and blocked MSN Messenger customers
from communicating with its user base. Microsoft, for its part,
kept looking for new ways to worm its way into AOL's messaging
service.
</P>
<P>
   In a strange twist of fate, Microsoft now is the one calling for
fairness and open standards in the messaging market and is
recruiting a host of partners to support this mission. Last week,
it even opened up the protocols for its Messenger software so that
any instant messaging product could communicate with MSN Messenger.
</P>
<P>
   AOL, too, is lining up its own allies, such as Apple, Sun
Microsystems and EarthLink, in an apparent attempt to create a
standard around its product.
</P>
<P>
   To the casual observer, this might seem like a childish game of
cat-and-mouse, but instant messaging means big business. The
software represents a powerful platform for sending target
advertisements to the millions of people who remain glued to their
computer screens for large portions of the day. Some observers
predict that some of the billions of dollars now spent on Web site
advertising soon could shift to the instant messaging platform.
</P>
<P>
   Another important battlefront is Internet access. Today, AOL's
18 million members pay $21.95 per month for dial-up access to the
Internet, while the 2 million subscribers to the Microsoft Network
service pay $19.95.
</P>
<P>
   AOL gets more than three-quarters of its revenues from its
subscribers, while MSN subscriptions are a mere drop in the bucket
for Microsoft. That's why Microsoft last month floated a trial
balloon suggesting it soon would begin to offer free _ or greatly
discounted _ Net access through MSN.
</P>
<P>
   ``Free Internet access strikes at the very heart of AOL,'' said
Tarter. ``This is a classic Microsoft strategy. You reduce your
price below what the market leader can afford and watch as they
bleed to death. Then you come in and gradually raise your price
back up.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has declined to elaborate on its intentions. AOL has
resisted the bait and adamantly refuses to lower its prices.
</P>
<P>
   But the tussle over Internet access could be the precursor to a
more critical battle down the road: broadband, or high-speed
connections to the Internet. The so-called broadband future is
supposed to transform the Internet into a vehicle for delivering
video, audio, games, software and even e-commerce directly to the
consumer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Broadband is a channel to deliver products and services, and
whoever owns that channel will control a huge new market,'' said
Enderle.
</P>
<P>
   AOL is attempting to stitch together its own broadband network
by striking high-speed access deals with telecommunications giants
like Bell Atlantic and SBC Communications. Microsoft, meanwhile, is
forging alliances with cable companies, which are expected to be
the most popular providers of high-speed access.
</P>
<P>
   It's worth noting that AOL is in a bitter struggle to get access
to the cable lines controlled by AT&AMP;T. Microsoft recently took a $5
billion stake in AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Though analysts don't expect broadband to become entrenched with
the general public for another five years or so, they said it's
critical for both AOL and Microsoft to start laying the foundation.
``Whoever has the better strategy now will be in the best position
to dominate going forward,'' said Joe Laszlo, an analyst with
Jupiter Communications.
</P>
<P>
   As AOL and Microsoft continue to fight for Web customers, new
battle lines are being drawn. The latest is online bill-paying
services that allow customers to make, say, their car payments
through the electronic transfer of funds via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft began to offer online bill-paying last month on its
MoneyCentral Web site, while AOL has said it was strongly
considering launching a similar service for its members.
</P>
<P>
   This is a lucrative market. The number of households paying
bills online will climb from 2 million this year to 11 million in
2003, according to the Yankee Group research firm.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, online bill-paying can give that all-important
``stickiness'' to a Web site. Analysts believe that Internet users
are likely to give their loyalty to a single site that provides
them with a vast range of compelling services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Online billing is important because it provides AOL, Microsoft
or whoever with the opportunity to become the next Visa,`` said
Barry Parr, an analyst at International Data Corp. ``If you are the
system by which all Internet payments get cleared, then you can
extract a piece of that action.''
</P>
<P>
   Another benefit of online billing is that the more time users
spend on the Web managing their money, the more likely they are to
actually spend online. Both AOL and Microsoft are confident that
users of their financial services will stick around to shop on
their sites.
</P>
<P>
   That's why they're furiously developing virtual shopping malls
where consumers can hunt for cars, make travel arrangements and buy
clothes and other goods.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  So far, the war between Microsoft and AOL has been confined
to Internet. But some industry experts believe that AOL may go
after Microsoft where it really hurts _ namely, the Windows
operating system.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than half of the people who log onto the Net domestically
do so through AOL,'' said Phil Leigh, a financial analyst with
Raymond James &AMP; Associates. ``For them, the real relationship is
with AOL, not Windows. AOL so far hasn't taken steps to wrest
control from the Windows operating system, but it could. What's to
prevent AOL from offering free word processing or free spreadsheet
programs?''
</P>
<P>
   Although most observers feel that the Internet is big enough for
both AOL and Microsoft, others are not so sure. ``If I was running
AOL now, I'd be terrified because Microsoft does not lose,'' said
Tarter. ``It may take Microsoft a while to ramp up, but it's pretty
rare that a competitor walks away alive.''
</P>
<P>
   AOL is betting it will be the exception to the rule.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-99 0100EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
