u s BC-RUN-WORLDCHAMPIONSHIP     08-23 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-WORLD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES CAPTURES 100 METERS 
</HEADLINE>
 CHAMPIONSHIPS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEVILLE, Spain _ Wherever you go through this sultry Andalusian
city, you see the Nike ad touting Marion Jones, the best female
sprinter in the world. In it _ legs outstretched, arms reaching,
jaw set _ the 23-year-old American phenomenon flies toward the
landing of a long jump. Leaving Estadia Olympico, your first
glimpse is along the banks of the Rio Guadalquivir; the next is on
a deserted stretch of the Avenida de la Palmera; soon it looms
again next to a busy sidewalk cafe on Calle Enramadilla.
</P>
<P>
   Jones is everywhere inside the stadium, too, as she tries to do
what no athlete before her ever has done: Win four gold medals at
the World Championships of Track and Field, at 100 and 200 meters,
the long jump and, most likely, the 4 x 400 relay. She has made it
clear she will be disappointed with anything less.
</P>
<P>
   The first step was taken Sunday night when Jones won the 100
meters in 10.70 seconds, the fastest time in the world this year,
to defend her world title. Although American Inger Miller ran a
strong second in 10.79 in her third personal best of the meet
(``It's not a one-woman show,'' Miller said afterward. ``There's
going to be a rivalry going into 2000'') and Jones was quick to
praise both Miller and bronze medalist Ekaterina Thanou of Greece,
who ran a 10.84, all eyes were on Jones Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, as they have
been since she arrived here last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal for this week is to get five total (gold medals) for
the family, and obviously we've started off in fine fashion,'' she
said, referring to her just-completed 100 meters and the shot-put
victory Saturday night of her husband, C.J. Hunter.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, but Seville is just the beginning, a virtual
warmup for next year. The oft-stated goal for 2000 Olympics: Gold
medals in the 100, 200, long jump, and both relays. If she
succeeds, she will be the first track athlete ever to do so,
surpassing the four golds won by Jesse Owens (1936) and Carl Lewis
(1984) and the three by Florence Griffith-Joyner (1988), whose
world records in the 100 and 200 (10:49 and 21:34) Jones is
stalking (10.65 and 21.62 so far, making her the second-fastest
woman ever at both distances).
</P>
<P>
   The schedule here is grueling, with Jones competing seven of the
nine days. Next up is Monday night's long jump final, for which
Jones qualified Saturday with the third-longest jump of the
competition, which she sandwiched between the first and second
rounds of the 100 meters before hanging around the track to watch
Hunter win gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that I can start off the week like this feels
great,'' she said. ``But there's no time for a celebration here.
I've got to get refocused and ready to jump.''
</P>
<P>
   After jumping Monday night, she will arrive early Tuesday for
the first round of the 200 meters at 10:45, try to rest in the
afternoon, then return for the second round at 6:35. If all goes
well, she will compete in the 200 semifinal Wednesday and the final
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Finally come the relays. The master plan is for Jones to run the
4 x 400, but that could change depending on fatigue. After her
three individual events are done (``Hopefully I am happy with three
wins there,'' said Jones) her coach, Trevor Graham, ``will look
into my eyes and tell if I am ready to run the 4 x 400 (relay) and
he said if he does not feel at this point that I am ready he is not
going to put me out there and under the stress of running the 4 x
400. Then I will go out and run the 4 x 100.''
</P>
<P>
   Many see Jones, always articulate and ready with a smile, as the
potential savior of track and field in the United States. (It
doesn't need any help in the rest of the world, where it and she
are already huge.) Others, if one believes the buzz on the
Internet, fear she is raising expectations too high, setting
herself up for failure, by proclaiming her intentions so
forthrightly.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Masback, CEO of USA Track &AMP; Field, insists neither is
true. ``Marion has no responsibility for the sport,'' he said.
``It's no individual's responsibility to save, rescue, build,
whatever other term you want to use. That's my job, and USA Track &AMP;
Field's job.'' Nonetheless, if she succeeds in making Olympic
history, ``she has the opportunity to be the first woman on a
global scale to transcend sport. Pele did it, Muhammad Ali did it,
Michael Jordan did it. No woman has ever done it.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Jones announcing her goals so early, Masback _ a former
world-class miler _ said: ``I assume she didn't do it lightly.''
</P>
<P>
   The journey began in earnest at the US national championships in
1997, where Jones reemerged on the track scene after three years of
playing top-notch basketball at the University of North Carolina,
where she was a freshman point guard on the 1994 team that won the
NCAA title. She gave up her final season of eligibility to return
to what she calls her first love, a sport in which she was fourth
in both the 100 and 200 at the 1992 Olympic Trials (declining a
spot as relay alternate) and still holds the US high school record
at 200 meters.
</P>
<P>
   She promptly won the 100 and long jump, won the 100 at the World
Championships later that summer, and by the end of the year was
ranked No. 1 in the world at both the 100 and 200. Last year, she
was undefeated until Heike Drechsler of Germany beat her in the
long jump in the last competition of the year. As fate would have
it, Drechsler is injured and not competing here.
</P>
<P>
   Although a sprained knee earlier this season has helped mar her
long-jump record _ Jones has lost twice to Drechsler and once to
American Dawn Burrell at US nationals _ her sprint string is
intact, having not lost at 100 meters in 25 races going back to
1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't as relaxed as I could have been,'' Jones said of her
race Sunday &UR;  &LR; night. ``That says a lot, that I was a little bit
tense in the race and still ran 10.70.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed it does.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
