<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS OFFENSE AHEAD OF DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ A year ago at this time the assessment of
the Patriots was that they had a solid defense, but the offense was
suspect because of injury-prone receivers and rookie tailback
Robert Edwards, who still hadn't emerged.
</P>
<P>
   Flip-flop that and you have the proper perspective of the 1999
Patriots after they have split a pair of exhibition games,
thrashing the Dallas Cowboys Saturday night, 34-14, after losing to
the Washington Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   The offense clicked in familiar fashion as quarterback Drew
Bledsoe worked wonderfully with wide receiver Terry Glenn, tight
end Ben Coates, and his running backs. The offensive line protected
Bledsoe well, although it didn't run-block as well as the coaches
would have liked. Still, there should be no worry about this team
scoring points.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, a unit once considered one of the best in the AFC
has some work to do before it regains that status. Certainly the
effort was strong Saturday night, despite missing three injured
starters (Ted Johnson, Henry Thomas, and Chad Eaton).
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots were doing cartwheels over Willie McGinest being
able to go all out for 17 plays and his sack of Dallas backup
quarterback Jason Garrett. It appeared linebacker Andy Katzenmoyer
began to understand his role and his importance in the middle of
the field, while the undermanned interior line got gutsy efforts
from Chris Sullivan, rookie free agent Garrett Johnson, and last
year's fourth-round pick, Leonta Rheams.
</P>
<P>
   The secondary, 25th against the pass a year ago, made some
plays. Chris Carter has intercepted passes in each of the
exhibition games in attempting to fill the void left by the
departed Willie Clay. And despite one poor play, Tebucky Jones
seems more equipped to be a factor in coverage and a viable player
if one of New England's starters at the corners _ Ty Law or Steve
Israel _ goes down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't screw it up. We adjusted better,'' said defensive
coordinator Steve Sidwell. ``Dallas gave us relatively tough
adjustments that we had to make that we did better with than we did
against Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Sidwell isn't ready to promise a championship just yet, but
weeks of intense training have paid off. The players are beginning
to understand and feel comfortable in the basic defense, and when
Sidwell introduced new wrinkles such as the middle linebacker blitz
and the corner blitz, Katzenmoyer and Israel got there in time to
at least disrupt the quarterback's throw.
</P>
<P>
   Weak-side linebacker Tedy Bruschi flew around the field and made
plays, but the most pleasing aspect of the night for the Patriots
was McGinest.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what he has to do for us to be a successful team,''
said Sidwell. ``When we're rushing four guys he has to go in there
and get 'em. I think he's been doing a good job. From what we see,
he's rushing the passer better in practice than he ever has since
we've been here, so we're pleased with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the Patriots must keep McGinest healthy, expand his number
of plays over the next two games, and, according to Sidwell, ``get
him in game shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Sidwell said Katzenmoyer's performance was like night and day
from last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``A big-time improvement,'' said Sidwell. ``He knows what he's
doing. He knows how to take on a block, knowing where his fit is in
the defensive scheme. It's not easy to get all that figured out. He
made marked improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Sidwell said of the steady Sullivan, ``Chris is always going to
give you a great day of work,'' and of Garrett Johnson added,
``he's a great battler.'' He said Jones, ``looked real bad on one
play _ the one where he missed a tackle. He got spun around in the
coverage. Otherwise, I'd have to see the film to see how he did
overall.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no question the Patriots have depth problems. The
interior defensive line is lacking a solid veteran who can take the
load off Thomas and Eaton. But Johnson has a great chance to take
that role. The linebacking corps is still smarting from the losses
of free agent Todd Collins and Johnson (torn biceps tendon), but
here, too, the Patriots are giving Billerica's Dana Cottrell a
chance to shine. Cottrell played well with the second unit. In the
secondary, Kato Serwanga did some good things in the nickel
package, an area in which the Patriots were torched last year.
Again, the presence of one more veteran would be ideal.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots were high on their performance Saturday night, but
it was a preseason high, not a regular-season one. The defense has
yet to be given its full set of marching orders.
</P>
<P>
   It appears McGinest is doing well, and Katzenmoyer has begun
taking steps toward what looks to be a promising career. Say what
you want about Glenn being important to the success of the
Patriots, but the team desperately needs McGinest's pass rush and
Katzenmoyer's toughness. Without them, the Patriots won't be able
to keep up in the toughest division in football, in which the
high-powered offenses of New York, Miami, Buffalo, and Indianapolis
have to be held in check.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
