<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-ONLINE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
WEB SITES FOR WOMEN ARE FLOURISHING &HT;    BY MEKEISHA MADDEN
 &HT;    c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When Mary Foust was planning her wedding, she
needed help on everything from catering to floral arrangements to
seating charts.
</P>
<P>
   But the 44-year-old Sausalito stockbroker didn't want to shell
out thousands to hire a wedding planner. So Foust turned to the
Internet and San Mateo's Women.com Networks Inc. for advice on
planning the event and answers to etiquette questions. There also
was a wedding checklist to keep her on schedule and a gown model to
help her visualize the style of wedding dress that would look best
on her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great resource,'' said Foust, whose wedding is in
November.
</P>
<P>
   Women.com is banking on consumers like Foust, who turn to the
Web for the kind of information they traditionally got from women's
magazines, plus everyday uses like e-mail and the sense of
community that the Web can foster. Women.com has an exclusive deal
to post articles from Hearst Magazines, whose stable includes
Cosmopolitan, Good Housekeeping, Harper's Bazaar and Marie Claire.
But it tries to branch beyond that, with everything from stock
quotes to career advice and book clubs.
</P>
<P>
   The breadth of information on Women.com has made the site the
No.1 online women's network, with 4.4 million unique visitors a
month, according to Media Metrix, a Net ratings service.
</P>
<P>
   As women go online in droves, industry analysts say the
potential for Women.com and other female-oriented sites is
enormous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very competitive space,'' said Lisa Allen, senior
analyst for Forrester Research, a Cambridge, Mass., research firm.
``Women are huge decision-makers when it comes to buying, and
advertisers are all vying for a piece of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The site has some influential backing. The Hearst Corp. owns 50
percent of Women.com. In June, Women.com sold a 2 to 3 percent
slice of the company to Torstar, the Canadian company that
publishes Harlequin romance novels, for $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   Women.com had planned to raise approximately $46 million by
selling 3.75 million shares to the public this month. That would
give it a valuation of as much as $540 million. But the recent
slump in Internet stocks has prompted Women.com to delay its
initial public offering indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a bad season for the stock market, and if you look at
the market last year around the same time, it was bad then, too,''
said Anna Yen, Women.com's head of investor relations.
</P>
<P>
   Women.com's reluctance to go public isn't surprising given
what's happened to its main competitor, iVillage.com of New York.
Launched in 1995, iVillage had a stunning public debut in March,
more than tripling on its first day, from $24 to $80.13. It soared
to $113.75 within a month. But since then, the stock has been on a
precipitous slide. It rose 63 cents to close at $41.50 Friday
(August 20).
</P>
<P>
   But while Wall Street may not be ready for a Women.com debut,
industry watchers say conditions for the site's popularity have
never been better.
</P>
<P>
   Women are surfing the Net in ever-increasing numbers. In less
than two years, the gender gap has narrowed, from 21 percent more
men online to only an 8 percent difference, according to the
Strategis Group, a research and consulting firm in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of 1998, 39 million women (38 percent of the adult
female population) in the United States were on the Internet, the
survey found. And many of those women hold the family's purse
strings.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers have fueled an explosion in sites devoted to all
things female.
</P>
<P>
   Both iVillage.com and Women.com have chat rooms, personalized
e-mail, information ranging from investments to fashion and
creating personalized home pages.
</P>
<P>
   Although Women.com has more eyeballs, iVillage also attracts a
fair number of users _ 3.8 million visitors monthly. iVillage's
revenues for the quarter ended March 31 were $6.5 million, up from
$2.2 million in the same quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
   But iVillage and Women.com can't rest on their laurels. Experts
predict that Women.com and iVillage may find a formidable opponent
in newcomer Oxygen.com from Oxygen Media Inc. Run by Geraldine
Laybourne, who made Nickelodeon a cable giant, the site is backed
by Disney, America Online, Microsoft co-founder Paul Allen and
talk-show host Oprah Winfrey. In addition to its Web site, Oxygen
Media is planning a cable TV channel.
</P>
<P>
   Women.com is trying to differentiate itself by going beyond
articles on beauty and health. The site _ and many of its
competitors _ want to be one-stop Web portals where women can log
on and never leave. Women can create their own home pages and get
investment and financial information.
</P>
<P>
   The site began in 1992 _ before the explosion of the World Wide
Web _ as a dial-up subscriber-based Internet service, called
Women's Wire. Founders Ellen Pack and Nancy Rhine, who hatched the
idea online, envisioned it as a way to get women to plug into the
online opportunities for networking and information. It moved to
the Web in 1995, ahead of many competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The site has grown since its humble beginnings in Pack's guest
room and now has 90,000 pages of content and 220 employees _ 80
percent women, 20 percent men. The Web site has writers, editors
and a number of doctors, consultants and other experts.
</P>
<P>
   But Allen, who analyzes women's Web sites, said the longevity of
Women.com and others like it will depend upon the site narrowing
its focus, making the sites geared toward a specific type of woman.
</P>
<P>
   Women.com and iVillage ``look the same and offer content in
similar areas, and there remains to be some shakeup,'' she said.
``What both sites need to realize is that there is a big difference
between 20-year-old college-aged women and 40-year-old professional
women. Focusing the reach to just one group will help them last in
this market.''
</P>
<P>
   Foust, who uses Women.com's e-mail and gets daily updates on her
wedding checklist, said the site is not without flaws. Like lots of
sites, Foust said, Women.com has too many ads.
</P>
<P>
   But advertising is the lifeblood of Women.com, according to
Women.com Networks CEO and President Marleen McDaniel.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers, who include big names such as Ford Motor Co. and
Clinique, account for the majority of Women.com's revenue. Because
the company is in a pre-IPO quiet period, it would not disclose the
exact amount. Revenue also comes from Web site production. For
instance, Women.com was paid to produce interactive Web sites for
New Woman and Redbook magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Women.com also makes money from e-commerce. It has links to
several online shopping sites: home movie retailer Bigstar.com;
Styleclick.com, a men's and women's fashion retailer; and
PlanetRx.com, a Web drugstore.
</P>
<P>
   Other revenue sources include sales generated by Astronet, an
online astrology site, and a cut of magazine subscriptions for
Hearst's 10 magazines when users subscribe to them on Women.com's
site.
</P>
<P>
   Women.com has a content office in New York and sales offices in
Los Angeles and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Pack hopes that Women.com, which has yet to generate a profit,
someday will be a household name.
</P>
<P>
   Partnerships with Hearst, Disney and other big names are going
to help bring Women.com into the spotlight, Pack said. According to
its prospectus, Women.com may never become profitable and,
according to Reuters, as of June 30 had accumulated $56.5 million
in debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a long time to become profitable,'' said Pack, 34.
``Right now, we're building our market presence and market share.
It (also) takes a long time to build a national consumer brand. If
you could make a profit as soon as you started a company, everybody
would be doing it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
