<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BANKBOSTON </SLUG>
 CLASSIC-BOS  
 McGINNIS HAS SENIORITY  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, Mass. _ Forget the Cohiba cigars and the Dom Perignon.
</P>
<P>
   After a 4-foot birdie on the second playoff hole Sunday gave Tom
McGinnis a $180,000 triumph over Hale Irwin in the BankBoston
Classic, his first victory on the Senior PGA Tour, McGinnis
celebrated without a shred of pretense.
</P>
<P>
   After he arrived at the clubhouse of Nashawtuc Country Club for
his press conference, McGinnis opened a pack of Marlboros, lit one
up, and ordered an ice cold bottle of Budweiser.
</P>
<P>
   When a can of Rolling Rock and a plastic cup were placed in
front of him, McGinnis examined the green aluminum container and
said, ``Rolling Rock? Is that a local brew?'' Then, cracking open
his victory beer, McGinnis smiled broadly and said, ``Well, Rolling
Rock it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Just when it appeared the huge Nashawtuc galleries were set to
hail Irwin as the event's second three-peat champion, McGinnis, a
51-year-old native of Memphis, wound up being the toast of the
Senior Tour's oldest tournament after shooting a final-round
5-under-par 67 for a 54-hole total of 11-under 205.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all such a shock,'' said McGinnis, whose biggest payday
of his tumultuous PGA Tour career was the $4,100 he got for fifth
place in the 1976 Ed McMahon-Jaycees Quad Cities Open. ``I didn't
think that I had a chance to win the tournament. Then I got in a
playoff, and I knew it would be a feather in my cap to beat him. I
mean, I had already beat 76 other guys.''
</P>
<P>
   So what was one more?
</P>
<P>
   McGinnis birdied the 18th hole of regulation after he hit a
marvelous chip out of the left rough, over a greenside bunker,
within 1 foot of the hole to go 5 under for the day and 11 under
for the tournament. Two-time defending champion Irwin, who shot a
final-round 68, reached the 18th in three shots and missed a chance
to win it outright when his 20-foot attempt from beneath the hole
stopped about 6 inches shy of the cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a great putt on (No.) 9 for a birdie and got it close
on 10 and 11, and then never really made another birdie, including
the two playoff holes,'' said Irwin, who has been hampered lately
by tendinitis in his left wrist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't play badly, but I kept misfiring on a lot of little
shots,'' he added. ``I think, subconsciously, the wrist may have
been a little bit of a problem in not getting a lot of shots to the
hole. Over the last week or so, I've been hitting a lot of shots
short of the pin and it's just not enough club in getting them back
there, so I think a couple of days rest will be really nice. My
congratulations to Tom, because he played the 17th hole like it was
easy.''
</P>
<P>
   After both players two-putted for par on the first playoff hole
at the 18th, Irwin went to the par-3, 170-yard 17th and hit it
within 10 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Was it time for Irwin to finally breathe easy?
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody is going to wake up one day and understand that the
Senior Tour is not a bunch of over-the-hill guys,'' said Irwin, the
tour's No. 2 money winner with $1,672,855. ``They can play golf and
Tom McGinnis is one of them. He happens to be a person we haven't
heard a lot of, but he can play, witnessed by the way he played
today. Certainly there was no fold in his game over the two holes
that we played.''
</P>
<P>
   That much was evident when McGinnis followed Irwin by getting a
6-iron to bite the green and stop 4 feet below the pin. When Irwin
just missed his birdie chance, sliding it past about 2 feet,
McGinnis said, ``I was grinning, because I knew I was not going to
miss mine. There was no way I was going to miss.''
</P>
<P>
   True to his word, McGinnis sized up his putt (``Straight
uphill,'' he said) and knocked it home to capture a check that
increased his season earnings to $394,614, leaving him 35th on the
money list.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no quit in him. He's got a lot of intestinal fortitude
and is just a scrambling player who's had to play for his life,''
said Wayne Gilmour, McGinnis's caddie from Liverpool. ``He knows
all the tricks of the trade, and he knows how to deal with
everything. This is not really pressure, because he knew he had 100
grand or 180 grand, so there's not much pressure there (in the
playoff). We were already in the final, and we just had to get rid
of one more guy and Hale was the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how many packs of cigarettes McGinnis, a chain-smoker, had
smoked on the course Sunday, Gilmour said, ``Oh, about 1 1/2. I
went through two packs myself _ and I don't even smoke.''
</P>
<P>
   Said McGinnis, ``I really wasn't that confident out there today.
I knew I was going to stay cool out there, but when I got to 10
under then looked up at the board and saw Hale go to 11 under
(after a 5-iron to 7 feet for a birdie 4), I actually thought, `Oh
well, I'm just playing for the money now.' ''
</P>
<P>
   McGinnis wound up winning more than enough money to keep him
supplied with smokes and suds _ the spoils of his victory _ for at
least the foreseeable future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-99 0105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990823.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 01:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6094 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-BANKBOSTONCLASSIC     08-23 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BANKBOSTON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRWIN HAPPY WITH SECOND 
</HEADLINE>
 CLASSIC-IRWIN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN VELLANTE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, Mass. _ Twenty-four hours before teeing off in Sunday's
final round of the $1.2 million Senior PGA Tour BankBoston Classic
at Nashawtuc Country Club, Hale Irwin predicted the finish was
shaping up as a pretty good horse race.
</P>
<P>
   A betting man would have made Irwin, the two-time defending
champion, a chalk favorite. Jay Sigel and George Archer, with whom
Irwin shared the lead, would have drawn much place and show
support.
</P>
<P>
   Tom McGinnis might have been as much of a long shot as, well,
Mr. Ed.
</P>
<P>
   But it was McGinnis, who has toiled in near obscurity, who
charged down the stretch and caught Irwin in two playoff holes,
winning with a short birdie putt on 17. That put a $180,000 ticket
into his hands and relegated Irwin to also-ran for the first time
since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   That is, if you want to call a check for $105,600 and 11
straight sub-70 rounds over the 6,773-yard Nashawtuc layout
also-ran status. The 11 straight sub-70 rounds equals the mark set
by Lee Trevino in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   A 34-34_68 and 205 total just wasn't good enough for Irwin, who
won BankBoston last year with 201 and in 1997 with 203. Irwin
wanted to join Chi Chi Rodriguez as the only men to win this
tournament three straight times. Rodriguez won in 1986, '87, and
'88 when the tournament was the Digital Seniors Classic.
</P>
<P>
   The end came on the par-3, 170-yard 17th, when Irwin missed a
7-footer for birdie and McGinnis calmly drained a 4-footer for his.
The pair had halved the first playoff hole, the 18th, with pars.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin seemed to be in control and steaming toward another win
with birdies on nine, 10, and 11 to go 11 under. Never did he
think, though, that when he canned the 7-footer on 11, that it
would be his last birdie of the day. He parred the last seven holes
in regulation and the two in the playoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just can't do that and expect to win,'' said Irwin,
``especially here at Nashawtuc where birdies are very obtainable.
You can't win if you don't birdie over the last nine holes. You
can't do that on any golf course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't play badly. I kept misfiring on a lot of little
shots. Subconsciously, the wrist (tendinitis) may have been a
problem in not getting a lot of shots to the hole. Over the last
week or so, I've been hitting a lot of shots short of the pin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't get the ball to the hole the last few holes and it
cost me. My congratulations to Tom. He played the 17th hole like it
was easy. He just had a superb (33-34_67) round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I said yesterday, if I could have a chance playing the
last nine holes, I'd be happy, so theoretically I'm happy.
Three-peats are hard to come by.''
</P>
<P>
   Irwin said it really didn't surprise him that it was McGinnis
that ended his BankBoston reign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone is going to wake up one morning and realize that the
Senior Tour is not a bunch of over-the-hill guys,'' he said. ``They
can play golf and Tom McGinnis is one of them. He happens to be a
person we haven't heard a lot of, but he can play. He's not a
fluke. He's a good player and he'll win again out here.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, as he left the interview room, Irwin turned and thanked
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great ride,'' he said, ``and fun while it lasted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
