<HEADER>
A6095 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MONSTER-JOBS-SFCHRON &LR;      08-23 1200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONSTER-JOBS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
MONSTER.COM MAY HAVE CREATED ONE WITH ONLINE PEOPLE AUCTIONS &HT;    BY DAVID LAZARUS
 &HT;    c.1999 San Francisco   Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Kerry Sheridan O'Leary considers herself a
decent copywriter, well versed in advertising and marketing, and
speaks fluent French to boot. Some employer, she figured, would be
willing to pay at least $45 an hour for her services.
</P>
<P>
   As yet, there haven't been any takers. Rather, there haven't
been any bidders.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary, 25, put herself up for sale at Monster Talent Market,
the Web's first full-time auction of human beings. The site now is
being joined by a handful of imitators, and the big boys of the
online auction world _ eBay, Yahoo and Amazon.com _ are open to
selling free-lancers as well.
</P>
<P>
   But are people auctions really the next big thing to hit the
Net, or just the latest in a long line of fads? And will this
change the way free-lancers operate?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it could be very cutting edge,'' said O'Leary, a
Burlingame free-lancer. ``It could be a marketplace for skills.
Unfortunately, I haven't had any responses yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither has Liz Willner, 33, a Berkeley free-lance Web designer
who auctioned herself off for a minimum $75 an hour. She listed her
services at Monster Talent Market after hearing an ad for the site
on the radio. Now she thinks ``it was a stupid idea.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not for free-lancers,'' Willner said. ``I don't know why
they claim that. When you fill out the questionnaire, you see that
it's really geared toward people looking for regular salaries and
full-time jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a lengthy tour of Talent Market's listings, with dozens
of profiles examined in a variety of categories, confirmed that the
vast majority of job seekers were looking for full-time gigs.
</P>
<P>
   No less significantly, not a single active bid could be found
for anyone. Not one.
</P>
<P>
   ``There hasn't been an overwhelming number of bids,'' conceded
Craig Besant, vice president of marketing for Monster.com in
Maynard, Mass. ``But we think it's going to work and that people
are going to make hires.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea probably looked great on paper. Because eBay and the
rest have demonstrated a ready online market for buying and selling
collectibles and other goods, why not an established venue where
independent contractors can seek top dollar for their services?
</P>
<P>
   Monster.com founder Jeff Taylor saw no reason to doubt the
validity of the concept, and he rolled out Talent Market on July 4
_ Independence Day for free-lancers _ as the company trumpeted its
innovation.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, it's a free service, and that's why about 60,000
people have listed their profiles at the site. Soon, though,
Monster plans to introduce a ``nominal cost'' of about $5 per
listing.
</P>
<P>
   Employers, in turn, will be asked to pony up $5,000 in advance
for five hires. If they sign contracts with fewer than five people,
the remainder would be refunded, Besant said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes down to a thousand dollars a head,'' he said. ``We
feel it's a fair price and substantially less than what they would
pay to headhunters.''
</P>
<P>
   The honor system is a factor. Monster is hoping that employers
will be truthful about making hires and not cut a separate deal
after eventually receiving a person's contact info, thus skirting
that $1,000 commission.
</P>
<P>
   This is just one example of why the effectiveness of online
people auctions remains in question. Another is that even with
60,000 listings, Besant said ``less than 50'' have found jobs via
Talent Market.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he noted that it took Monster.com, the Web's biggest pool
of job openings and resumes, nine months before anyone was hired
through the site.
</P>
<P>
   EBay spokesman Kevin Pursglove said the leading online
auctioneer has no plans at present to introduce sales of human
beings. But he pointed out that there have been listings for
tech-related services from individuals in the site's computer area,
and said the company would comply if users demanded a separate
channel for people auctions.
</P>
<P>
   EBay is where a group of 16 Internet workers put themselves up
for sale this spring for no less than $3.1 million, though the
offer was withdrawn a couple of days later.
</P>
<P>
   Now one of those workers, John Kinsella, has launched his own
online people auction, Bid4geeks.com, with dozens of job-hunting
propeller-heads up for grabs (but receiving only a handful of
bids).
</P>
<P>
   An outfit called eLance, meanwhile, is gearing up to allow
companies to post projects online and allow free-lancers to submit
electronic bids, and a similar service is on tap at Freeagent.com.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever else, there's clearly a market for online recruiting.
Forrester Research in Cambridge, Mass., estimates that U.S.
companies will be spending as much as $1.7 billion by 2003 to track
down new employees via the Internet, compared with $105 million
last year.
</P>
<P>
   There are nearly 3 million resumes now posted online at about
30,000 job-related sites.
</P>
<P>
   But most, if not all, of these resumes are for people seeking
steady work. For free-lancers, the Gypsies of the job market, the
name of the game is still networking and referrals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Free-lancers have to market themselves like crazy,'' said
Betsy Keefer, president of Freelance Online, a directory of about
1,300 free-lancers-for-hire. It's virtually unheard of, she said,
for an employer to compete monetarily for a free-lancer's services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most free-lancers aren't hired because of how much they
cost,'' Keefer observed. ``They're hired because of their
qualifications.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Carles, a senior producer at Yahoo, agreed that
networking, not auctions, is how a free-lancer finds work. For this
reason, she said, her site isn't hurrying to establish an outlet
for buying and selling people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an area for services right now,'' Carles said, ``but
we're not sure that the market's there yet. If it gets there, we'll
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazon spokeswoman Sharon Greenspan said additional auction
categories are added ``as they become popular.'' If people auctions
catch on, she said, Amazon will cut its own slice of the pie.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Nidositko, an analyst with the Yankee Group in Boston,
isn't convinced that auctions, whether of Beanie Babies or
free-lance French speakers, will remain among the hottest
attractions on the Net.
</P>
<P>
   ``The auction format is novel,'' she said. ``It's a way to keep
people coming to a site. But it's not clear how long it will
last.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Monster Talent Market, Nidositko also came up short in
finding any active bids, and said the service ``doesn't seem
particularly successful at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Monster's Besant insisted that Talent Market ``is a work in
progress,'' and said future listings may be expanded to include
writing or design samples.
</P>
<P>
   He also suggested that free-lancers who list themselves with the
site one day may be eligible for some form of health insurance
coverage or discounts on office supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Auctions are a way for you to market yourself on the Web,''
Besant said. ``People respond to the whole concept of auctions.
It's very reinforcing to know that employers are upping the bid on
you.''
</P>
<P>
   When they're actually bidding, that is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
