<HEADLINE>
SIGEL'S BEST SHOT NOT QUITE ENOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
 CLASSIC-SIGEL-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, Mass. _ There must be something in the New England air
that brings out the best in Jay Sigel. He won an emotional US
Amateur championship at The Country Club in 1982, breaking down as
he talked about the magic of the moment. He won the prestigious
Northeastern Amateur at Wannamoisett CC three times, a record.
</P>
<P>
   So didn't it figure that he would become a factor on the PGA
Senior Tour after he became a late convert to the professional game
as age 50 approached? Especially when the venue shifted to
Nashawtuc CC for the BankBoston Classic? When he missed makeable
putts in Sunday's final round to settle for a tie for third, just
one shot out of the playoff between Hale Irwin and Tom McGinnis, it
solidified Sigel's regional presence again.
</P>
<P>
   After struggling during a year in which he has been limited by
nagging shoulder injuries, Sigel followed up his runner-up position
to Irwin a year ago, when he trailed by two, and a tie for second
in 1996 when he and Tom Wargo trailed Jim Dent by one. He has
earned $268,050 without a victory in the six years he has played in
this tournament since he stepped away from a profitable insurance
partnership in the suburbs of Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Uncharacteristically lodged in 45th place on the Senior Tour
money list in a year in which he has had five top 10 finishes
before Sunday's third place matched his two previous lows, in the
Senior Slam and the Legends of Golf, Sigel rekindled the fires in
the home stretch when he hit an 8-iron to 6 feet on the 11th to set
up a run of three straight birdies. He ran in putts from 15 feet
and 18 feet on the next two holes.
</P>
<P>
   That pulled Sigel within one of the lead tenaciously held by
Irwin, who was seeking to join Chi Chi Rodriguez (1986-88) as the
only three-time winner of the Senior Tour's oldest 54-hole event,
which will celebrate its 20th birthday next year at Nashawtuc.
There were solid runs at birdie putts on the final two holes on
this dark, overcast, and chilly afternoon before a robust and
appreciative crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played pretty solid coming in,'' said Sigel, ``and if I can
take anything from this tournament that would be it. The shot I hit
on 17 was a pleaser. I hit the putt just the way I wanted to. It
actually hit something. I don't know what. It just threw it off to
the right. The putt on 18 was exactly what I thought it took. I was
pleased with that when it left the putter. It was a good finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bogey I took on the (par-5) fifth was the killer. I hit it
pretty well off the tee. I was playing safe. I didn't think I could
get it home. I had a funny lie on a mound. I ended up under a tree.
I was on the green about 40 feet away and I three-putted. Instead
of making a 4, I made a 6. I played OK other than that on the front
side.''
</P>
<P>
   The hole that got Sigel untracked and started his climb into
contention was the 11th. ``I must have outhit George (Archer) and
Hale by 25 yards,'' he said. ``They're out there with 5-irons, and
the pin was tucked right over the bunker. Hale hits first and hit
it about 6 feet. George hit second and hits it 6 feet. I hit an
8-iron and hit it about 6 feet. I asked them at that point if they
wanted me to play on through.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately I made it. I got into position to win, so overall
I'm pleased. I felt I was back in the game after 13, but not having
birdied 10 from right in front of the green hurt. I thought I was
in the game. I hit good shots coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to get yourself in position and test yourself,'' said
Sigel, who led the field by two shots after an opening-round 67.
``It's been a heck of a test. It's been a tough year. I just
haven't played that well. I did a lot of good things this week. For
the most part I've played fairly well when my shoulder didn't hurt.
I'm encouraged. I really do like the golf course. It's part of my
good play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
