<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAMES TAPS PARNEVIK, COLTART 
</HEADLINE>
 CUP-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Apparently undaunted by the fact his team already is laden with
Ryder Cup rookies, European captain Mark James Sunday added another
inexperienced player to his 12-man team that will take on the
United States next month at The Country Club in Brookline.
</P>
<P>
   After announcing one captain's pick that was no surprise (Jesper
Parnevik), James shocked many by choosing Scotland's Andrew
Coltart. In so doing, James bypassed Bernhard Langer, a veteran of
nine Ryder Cups, as well as Ian Woosnam (eight) and Nick Faldo
(11). Faldo's selection was considered a long shot at best, though
his candidacy had been trumpeted in recent weeks by Europe's best
player, Colin Montgomerie.
</P>
<P>
   But James gave more emphasis to recent form than experience in
choosing Coltart, 29. ``It doesn't matter who has been there
before,'' said James Sunday after the BMW International Open in
Munich, ``it's the standard of players you have here now.'' It was
an indication that Langer, Faldo, and Woosnam had failed to show
James they were on top of their games in recent weeks. Coltart,
said James, has played very well and finished higher than Langer
and Faldo at the recent PGA Championship at Medinah Country Club
outside of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of Coltart means Europe will field just five
players with Ryder Cup experience _ Montgomerie, Parnevik, Lee
Westwood, Darren Clarke, and Jose Maria Olazabal. Coltart and six
others _ Paul Lawrie, Miguel Angel Jimenez, Sergio Garcia, Jarmo
Sandelin, Jean Van de Velde, and Padraig Harrington _ never have
played in golf's most prestigious team event.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, said James, the decision did not come down to
Coltart or a veteran, but to Coltart or another inexperienced
player, Robert Karlsson.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a tough decision,'' said James of passing over the
Swede, who was 11th in the standings, in favor of Coltart, who was
12th. ``He handled it with real calm, with equanimity. Not much I
can tell him. I can apologize for not picking him, but that's not
going to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Karlsson had entered the BMW International in 10th place in the
European standings but got bumped when Harrington finished second,
behind Montgomerie, earning enough points to jump from 13th to
10th.
</P>
<P>
   ``Padraig was under the most severe pressure again (he had to
finish second to make the team) and he had that bad start (4 over
par through four holes) and coped with that and came through and
delivered the goods,'' said James.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington played the remaining 14 holes at 4 under to finish
one shot ahead of Jarrod Moseley and three behind Montgomerie, who
won for the fifth time this season on the European Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Karlsson's 65 Sunday tied for low round, but it vaulted him to
just a tie for ninth. He needed to finish third.
</P>
<P>
   The choice between Coltart and Karlsson, said James, ``was a
desperate decision.''
</P>
<P>
   One other choice never had to be made, though James confirmed
that had he finished in the top 10 (he finished 13th), ``I would
have played'' and Ken Brown would have captained the team.
</P>
<P>
   James and his team were scheduled to leave Sunday night for the
US, where they will play in this week's NEC Invitational in Akron,
Ohio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-99 0112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
