r a BC-ANTI-HATE-MARCH-LADN     08-23 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTI-HATE-MARCH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. MARCH SEEKS TO SILENCE HATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY HARRISON SHEPPARD  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Some 500 people of different races and religions
used the streets of suburban West Hills to march against hate
Sunday, demonstrating their commitment to resisting bigotry and
intolerance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us agree we will not allow this darkness to put out our
light,'' Universalist Unitarian Community Church representative
Gwynne Guibord told marchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us agree we will not allow fear to grip our hearts and
silence our voices.''
</P>
<P>
   The March Against Hate was one of numerous community events held
in Los Angeles following the shooting of five people at the North
Valley Jewish Community Center and the slaying of a mail carrier in
Chatsworth two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say avowed white supremacist Buford O. Furrow Jr.
targeted Filipino-American postal worker Joseph Ileto because he
was a minority and a federal employee, and he targeted the
community center because its members are Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   Furrow was indicted on a federal murder charge Thursday for
which he could face the death penalty if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   While Furrow allegedly said he intended the shootings to be a
``wake-up call'' for Americans to start killing Jews, in some
respects the opposite has happened since then, marchers said.
</P>
<P>
   Jews, Christians, whites, African-Americans, Latinos and other
groups have come together in the last two weeks in a number of
rallies, forums and public discussions to not only condemn the
shootings, but to work on preventing hate crimes and intolerance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of dividing us, it has united our community as never
before,'' said Assemblyman Tom McClintock, R-Granada Hills, as he
marched down Fallbrook Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Participants braved the near triple-digit heat and walked about
one mile down Fallbrook, from Saticoy to Vanowen streets, then held
the ``Rally in the Valley'' at Shadow Ranch Park, across from a
Jewish community center on Vanowen.
</P>
<P>
   They carried signs against hate and chanted, ``We march for
peace'' and ``No more hate,'' as cars whizzed by, honking their
horns in approval.
</P>
<P>
   Marchers and speakers said that while Americans must resist
intolerance, they should not learn to hate the groups that preach
bigotry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't allow ourselves to become like those who seek to
destroy our lives,'' said Rabbi Aron Kreigel of Temple Ner Maarav
in Encino. ``For if we are, we shall find the haters have destroyed
our souls also.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Brad Sherman, D-Woodland Hills, called for a number of
legislative changes at the state and federal level to prevent and
prosecute hate crimes, including: adding a tagging agent to
explosives which would allow officials to trace their source after
an explosion; instituting stricter gun controls, including
crackdowns on gun shows; teaching tolerance in schools; and
supporting a bill pending in Congress to expand the definition of
hate crimes to include sexual orientation, gender and disability.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all targets of opportunity for those who hate,''
Sherman said, referring to a phrase Furrow allegedly used to
describe why he shot Ileto. ``The question is, What shall we do?''
</P>
<P>
   Among the marchers was a group that had experienced directly
fighting a much larger group of haters _ a local Jewish War
Veterans post whose members battled the Nazis in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Leventhal, a member of the San Fernando Valley-based Post
603, said they mistakenly thought they were defeating bigotry when
they defeated Adolf Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all went into the service a long time ago to end this, and
it certainly hasn't ended,'' said Leventhal, 82, a Studio City
resident. But, he added, society has continued to make gradual
progress since then.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's march, sponsored by the San Fernando Valley Interfaith
Council, also marked the kickoff of the Turn On a Love Light
campaign, which urges residents to turn their porch lights on
through Aug. 29 to demonstrate goodwill toward their neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   The march was aimed at almost every type of hate crime, with
speakers addressing crimes against gays and lesbians, the
handicapped, Latinos, women, Jews and Asians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it sends a message to the hatemongers,'' said Sid
Gold, a Woodland Hills psychiatrist who was among the marchers.
``It shows we're not gonna take it anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
