<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6100 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-LeBRETON-COLUMN-T     08-23 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS ARE AMAZING, BUT CAN THEY MAKE YANKEES DISAPPEAR?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ And now, the New York Yankees. The final
frontier.
</P>
<P>
   The team with the best record in the American League since the
All-Star break kept rolling along Sunday night, defying gravity,
ignoring what used to be tradition, outrunning even those
precocious Oakland Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   The amazing Texas Rangers, behind the amazing Aaron Sele, tidied
the trimmings on an amazing three-game sweep of the wild-card
contending Boston Red Sox on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Amazing.
</P>
<P>
   For three nights, the Rangers brandished timely hitting,
Octoberesque pitching and rally snuffing defense. We saw Esteban
Loaiza, almost cast adrift in the July bulrushes, win on Friday. We
saw Rick Helling and the Yale-lock bullpen win on Saturday. We saw
the Rangers' most reliable magic act, The Great Palmeiro, make four
baseballs disappear into thin air.
</P>
<P>
   And Sunday night, we saw Sele, the human Indiana Jones episode,
darting into and out of trouble. The Rangers' 6-0 victory was his
14th.
</P>
<P>
   With the New York Yankees arriving for three games, beginning
Monday, it opens the door for either (A) a sobering dose of
reality, or (B) hints of a New World Order, as far as the Rangers
are concerned.
</P>
<P>
   If memory serves, the Rangers haven't defeated the Yankees since
the Grover Cleveland administration. (Actually, New York has
mastered the Rangers 21 of 31 times, dating to the beginning of
1997).
</P>
<P>
   But that was then, and this is now, as the sweep of the Red Sox
boldly suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played well,'' left fielder Rusty Greer observed. ``I
think our pitching staff has been overlooked in all this. We've
done a lot of good things _ hit the ball well and played good
defense. But it all begins with pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   Sele proved that by going the distance for his second
complete-game shutout of the season. It wasn't a Renoir, by any
means. But it at least belongs on the family refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Sele surrendered Red Sox hits in each of the game's first seven
innings. Yet each time, he seemed to snuff the threat with a timely
ground-ball out or on a spotlight defensive play.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I was trying to do was to throw strikes,'' Sele said,
after beating his former team for the first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't any more complicated than that. Sele walked only two
and stayed ahead of hitters, relying on his curve ball, when he
most needed to. Sele tossed a large bouquet in the direction of his
defense, which made a half-dozen rally dousing plays behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our starting pitchers should be doing what's going on right
now,'' said shortstop Royce Clayton, whose into-the-hole
sleight-of-hand play in the sixth inning was one of the night's
best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early in the season, they were said to be our Achilles' heel.
Right now, we just have to tip our hats to them. Everybody up and
down the lineup is doing their job.''
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, the Rangers may have enjoyed the best of the
pitching matchups in the weekend series. Conspicuously not taking a
turn for Boston were Pedro Martinez and an injured Bret Saberhagen.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Yankees, meanwhile, the Rangers will face a hot Andy
Pettitte, David Cone and Hideki Irabu.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates will counter with, in order, John Burkett,
Mike Morgan and Loaiza. Clearly, the home team's recent magic will
be tested.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you play good ballclubs, it's how well you pitch,'' Oates
said Sunday night. ``You look at the series against them last year
(the AL divisional series), and I thought we pitched well. We gave
up, what, nine runs in three games?
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played them very close. You go back and look.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates is right. But the feeling persists among Rangers faithful
that the home team is never far from a recurring case of the
Pinstripe Flu. Palms sweat. Knees and bats turn weak.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. But in simple black and white terms, the Rangers hold
baseball's best record since the July break _ 27-11, a mark that
allowed them to put elbow space between themselves and even
Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Amazing.
</P>
<P>
   But now, can they make even the Yankees disappear?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
