<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 01:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6102 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-OUTTAKES-COLUMN-SFCHR     08-23 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTTAKES-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
SOMETIMES OPPORTUNITY DOES KNOCK &HT;    By STAN BUNGER and JAN BOYD
 &HT;    c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE _ It started like so many other product pitches:
Someone knocked at the door of our KRON-TV bureau here, wondering
if it would be possible to talk with someone inside about a
``really interesting new company.''
</P>
<P>
   We try to discourage this sort of sneak attack, else we'd never
get any work done around here.
</P>
<P>
   But it's hard to say ``no'' to a bunch of earnest teenagers, all
decked out in trade-show badges.
</P>
<P>
   The visitors turned out to be students at California High School
in San Ramon, Calif. They'd come to San Jose for the LinuxWorld
Conference. Their badges identified their company as Vector Crew
Development. Apparently, Vector Crew Development isn't big on
corporate structure because the guy in charge, Aaron Wadler, lists
his title as ``The Big Cheese.'' Poised, confident and very
familiar with the world of computers, he'll be entering 11th grade
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   And what exactly is Vector Crew Development's business? A flavor
of the free Linux computer operating system known as Sinux. Wadler
says Sinux is designed to work with home-automation software, which
allows users to control things like lights, sprinkler systems and
air conditioners from their computers. It also supports recording
and playback of MP3 music files. Their first version is now in
public release.
</P>
<P>
   No big investors, no fancy offices, no marketing plan. Just a
bunch of kids hacking away at source code. Enough to want to make
us answer the door more often.
</P>
<P>
   Crash Test.
</P>
<P>
   You can do all the focus group research you want, hire all the
best engineers to tweak and fine-tune things, but what it really
comes down to with any new product is: Does it work?
</P>
<P>
   Craig Lynar, vice president of marketing at Etak of Menlo Park,
Calif., found out the hard way that, yes, Etak's new service does
work. Etak is in the map and navigation business. Its Traffic Touch
service delivers updated traffic information to users of the
wireless Palm VII handheld computer.
</P>
<P>
   A subscriber can customize the service so that information about
accidents and traffic jams on his commute route shows up on the
Palm VII screen.
</P>
<P>
   Lynar's job is to sell the world on the virtues of knowing
what's on the road ahead. But he became a guinea pig when he was
involved in an accident on Interstate 680. ``Someone rear-ended
me,'' Lynar said, ``and I actually timed it. It was two minutes
before the incident popped up on the Traffic Touch screen.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the good news, as far as Lynar was concerned. The bad
news? He says it took the California Highway Patrol more than three
hours to get an officer out to take a report.
</P>
<P>
   Some things, technology can't fix.
</P>
<P>
   Handheld Cash.
</P>
<P>
   And from the ``you gotta be a geek to love it'' category: A Palo
Alto (Calif.) startup called Confinity hopes to persuade you to
carry your cash in your PalmPilot.
</P>
<P>
   Confinity's soon-to-be-released PayPal software lets you
download cash value via the Internet. You can debit a checking
account or charge the cash against a credit card. Either way, you
wind up with digital cash in your handheld computer.
</P>
<P>
   And then what? Confinity believes that there's going to be a
boom in demand for cashless transactions. ``It's not going to be
the e-commerce people do on their desktop,'' argues Confinity CEO
Peter Thiel. ``It's the e-commerce people do in the real world,
away from the desktop.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone carrying a wad of PayPal cash on a PalmPilot could
``beam'' some money to another Palm user via the Palm's infrared
technology. For example, at the end of lunch, when it's time to
split the tab, the old ``but I only have a $50 bill'' stunt could
be avoided.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've received e-cash this way, you have a couple of
choices.
</P>
<P>
   You can go to Confinity's Web site and convert the e-cash back
into real money in the account of your choice (Confinity hopes to
make its profit from the ``float'' while money circulates), or you
can pass it on to someone else at the end of your next lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Tag, you're it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
