<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS KNOCK OFF RED SOX AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ This morning's box score will show that the
bottom third of the Texas Rangers' lineup produced a meager two
hits and one run batted in during their 11 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   It would appear the three provided no significant contribution
during Sunday night's 6-0 victory against the Boston Red Sox at The
Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   What the box score fails to reveal, though, is that there was no
glove lost among the three.
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Lee Stevens, shortstop Royce Clayton and center
fielder Tom Goodwin nurtured right-hander Aaron Sele through his
second shutout this season with their defense.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton handled seven chances cleanly and delivered perhaps the
game's two most pivotal plays from his defensive position. Stevens
started a 3-6-3 double play, made two 3-1 putouts and another three
unassisted putouts appear routine. Goodwin recovered from a poor
jump on a seventh-inning fly ball to snuff Boston's final
legitimate scoring opportunity on the warning track.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is more indicative of what I was expecting out of spring
training,'' manager Johnny Oates said of the Rangers' flawless
defensive execution. ``We're playing really well defensively right
now. We're also getting good pitching and hitting, and we're
playing really well as a result. I think it all goes hand in
hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Sele (14-7) scattered eight hits and issued two walks during his
125-pitch effort and allowed at least one Red Sox runner aboard
every inning except for his 1-2-3 eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I was trying to do was throw strikes,'' Sele said. ``Pudge
did a great job back there calling the game. Royce made a couple of
nice defensive plays, and Lee made several great plays at first
base.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox mounted their best threat with consecutive
fifth-inning singles by catcher Jason Varitek and center fielder
Darren Lewis. That brought right fielder Trot Nixon to the plate
with two aboard and none out, but Sele used his curveball to induce
a ground ball.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Mark McLemore fielded it cleanly and started a
rally-killing 4-6-3 double play that Clayton completed with a
strong-armed throw to Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really impressed with the way he pitched tonight,''
Oates said of Sele. ``He spread (the hits) out, but the key for him
was the defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the lineup supported Sele with six runs.
</P>
<P>
   Designated hitter Rafael Palmeiro drove in two runs and hit his
seventh home run in as many games with his sixth-inning,
bases-empty blast off Boston's Tim Wakefield (4-9). Rusty Greer
collected two hits to improve his batting average to .296 and drove
in another two runs.
</P>
<P>
   The performances by Palmeiro and Greer appear more sexy, but the
Rangers won Sunday night's game with defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's beginning to be that time of year,'' Clayton said,
``where you just have to be solid all the way around.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin joined the act during the seventh inning after Lewis and
Nixon reached with two outs, and Boston second baseman Jose
Offerman sent a 1-0 pitch to the warning track.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a ball I didn't think he hit as well as he did,''
Goodwin said. `` I kind of got a late jump on it, and the ball just
kept carrying. I was like, `Oh, I hope I catch it.' I made the easy
play look hard while they made the hard plays look easy.''
</P>
<P>
   No one would ever know from the box score. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
