<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 01:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6120 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX     08-23 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERE'S A WISH LIST FOR THE COWBOYS AS THE SEASON OPENER APPROACHES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No one would blame coach Chan Gailey and the 0-3 Dallas Cowboys
if they drew up a ``wish list'' after Saturday night's 34-14 loss
at New England.
</P>
<P>
   With two preseason games remaining at Texas Stadium, including
Sunday night against the two-time defending Super Bowl champion
Denver Broncos, Gailey said, ``We have a lot of work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   In three exhibitions, the Cowboys have been outscored 64-34,
outrushed by nearly 70 yards per game and outgained by more than
100 net yards per game. About the only statistical category that
the Cowboys lead week in and week out against their preseason
opponents is the number of inactive players, which hit 19 against
New England.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, here are 10 wishes that the Cowboys might need to
be granted before they open the regular season Sept. 12 at
Washington, and preferably sooner rather than later:
</P>
<P>
   1. Stabilize the offensive line; fix right guard. It's broken.
</P>
<P>
   Converted offensive tackle Solomon Page, a rookie, has started
all three games at right guard in place of the injured Everett
McIver (knee surgery), who will practice with the team today for
the first time since November. Tony Hutson (knee sprain) will make
this his second practice since the first week of camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping to get a combination of those two guys \RMcIver
and Hutson\S playing for a half against Denver,'' Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   2. Resolve cornerback issues.
</P>
<P>
   Bad became worse when starting left cornerback Kevin Mathis was
beaten twice on deep passes from Drew Bledsoe to Terry Glenn
Saturday night. This has become a position of attrition for the
Cowboys, who are without a timetable on Deion Sanders (April toe
surgery), and remain in the dark on Kevin Smith (bulging disc), who
hasn't been in camp for more than a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come Monday, we should have a better feel \Ras to whether or
not Smith can be ready\S for the first part of the season,'' said
Gailey, who awaits a medical report today on Smith.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility exists that the Cowboys will bring in a veteran
cornerback, depending on Smith's prognosis, but not likely before
the NFL roster cutdowns to 60 on Aug. 31 or to 53 on Sept. 5.
</P>
<P>
   3. Put quarterback Troy Aikman in a position to win.
</P>
<P>
   Playing one quarter in each of the Cowboys' three games, Aikman
has completed 62.2 percent of his passes (23 of 37) for 222 yards,
one TD, two interceptions and no sacks. The first two games _
losses to Cleveland and Oakland _ Aikman and the first team moved
the ball but didn't score. Against New England, they finally scored
but struggled (2-for-5) on third down.
</P>
<P>
   4. Beef up the pass rush.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys defense has four sacks in three games, including
none against the Patriots. The first team is looking for its first
sack of the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure you can judge a pass rush against Bledsoe,''
Gailey said. ``The ball is out in a real hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' first-team defense also was sackless against
Cleveland's Ty Detmer and Oakland's Rich Gannon.
</P>
<P>
   5. Launch Rocket.
</P>
<P>
   Idled since Aug. 4 with a slightly separated shoulder, wide
receiver Raghib ``Rocket'' Ismail warmed up prior to Saturday
night's game but was held out for a third consecutive week by
Gailey, this time because of a slick field caused by an incessant
rain at Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rocket came up to me and thought he could play,'' Gailey said.
``But if he would have gotten in a freak fall and landed on that
shoulder, we'd be back to square one ... so I held him \Rout\S.''
</P>
<P>
   With James McKnight out for the season (torn knee ligament) and
Ismail looking for his first preseason game as a Cowboy, rookie
Wane McGarity (10.3 average on six catches) and Jeff Ogden (13.0 on
five) are battling for the No. 4 job. TCU rookie free agent Jason
Tucker (21.2 on five), with three catches for 79 yards and a TD
Saturday night, steps up to battle for the No. 5 job.
</P>
<P>
   6. Script a two-minute drill for the first-team offense.
</P>
<P>
   The shotgun in passing situations seems to be growing on Aikman,
who never used it before last season. But now he needs the
two-minute drill, and he needs to run it with as many starters as
the casualty count will allow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to get Troy in there Saturday night for a two-minute
drive _ forced or unforced almost _ at the end of the first half,''
Gailey said. ``If we have the ball with four minutes left \Rbefore
halftime\S, we might just go to it right there.''
</P>
<P>
   7. Commitment at strongside linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   Free agent Quentin Coryatt has been sidelined most of camp with
a strained hamstring and Achilles' tendon. Darren Hambrick, who has
impressed Gailey with an improved attitude this year, has started
each of the Cowboys' three games.
</P>
<P>
   It is still Coryatt's job to lose. But since the former
first-round pick (second overall in '92) of the Indianapolis Colts
missed all last season with reconstructive shoulder surgery, and
since this is a new defense for him, Gailey has said, ``He
definitely needs reps in our defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Either Coryatt gets sufficient practice/preseason to learn it,
or he doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   8. Get the running game untracked.
</P>
<P>
   Emmitt Smith had his best game of the preseason and has 13
carries for 53 yards (4.1 average). But Chris Warren, with seven
preseason carries for 23 yards (3.3 average), missed the Patriots
game, consequently tabling any chance he had this week to work in
the same backfield with Smith or to develop as the team's
third-down back. Warren spent last week in Colorado, receiving
medical treatment for a groin injury that cut short his '98 season.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the preseason carries for the Cowboys have gone to a
pair of young free agents, Tarik Smith and Devis Manns, who have
combined for 136 yards on 34 carries (4.0). The Cowboys have yet to
score a rushing TD this preseason.
</P>
<P>
   9. Push the fast-forward button on defensive line progress.
</P>
<P>
   Said veteran tackle Chad Hennings: ``We finally really have the
talent that we had on the defensive line when I came to the Cowboys
in '92. We have some young kids who have speed, strength, the whole
package. It's just a matter of getting them developed.''
</P>
<P>
   10. Wish the preseason away.
</P>
<P>
   Or if that doesn't work, learn from mistakes. As Aikman said
after the game, ``Nobody is beating themselves over the head \Rat
being 0-3\S. This is preseason.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-99 0126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
