<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 01:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6121 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-BIOSCOPE-COLUMN-SFCHR     08-23 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOSCOPE-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   GILEAD'S SUCCESS HAS BEEN A BALM FOR BIOTECH INVESTORS &HT;    By TOM ABATE
 &HT;    c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As far as Wall Street is concerned, biotech
resembles a Third World country, with a few rich, elite companies
and hundreds of small, ill-funded ones.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 12 months, Gilead Sciences has risen to the apex of
the triangle. Shares in the Foster City (Calif.) company, which
have skyrocketed 250 percent in the past year, gained $2.50 Friday
(August 20) to close at $81.63. With nearly 38 million shares
outstanding, Gilead enjoys a market capitalization of $3.44
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting into that realm of market cap and liquidity makes it a
stock the mutual and pension funds can buy,'' said analyst Tom
Dietz, with Pacific Growth Equities in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   And buy they have. Institutions now own more than 80 percent of
Gilead's shares, giving it the sort of stable ownership envied by
the majority of biotech firms, whose stock is mostly held by small
investors.
</P>
<P>
   Gilead isn't profitable yet and doesn't expect to make money for
another year. Even so, Wall Street is betting that by the end of
1999, Gilead will win Food and Drug Administration approval to sell
two new drugs _ a flu remedy and a treatment for people with
drug-resistant forms of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   At Gilead headquarters, where a large chunk of the 350-person
staff is focused on the FDA-approval process, Chief Financial
Officer Mark Perry reflected on the company's prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of the hundreds of publicly traded biotech companies, only 10
or 12 have broken through and become profitable,'' he said. ``We
think we have the legs to make it all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   The first critical hurdles come this fall, when the FDA must
give its final yea or nay to Gilead's two drug candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Treanor, an infectious disease expert at the University
of Rochester in New York, was a lead researcher on the clinical
trials that Gilead will present in favor of its anti-flu drug,
Tamiflu.
</P>
<P>
   Treanor said the experimental data show that people given a
single Tamiflu pill each day for five days had shorter, less
violent flu symptoms. Gilead hopes the FDA will approve the drug by
the end of October.
</P>
<P>
   Gilead bases that hope partly on the fact that the FDA recently
OKd a competing anti-flu drug, called Relenza, indicating the
agency is favorably disposed toward new flu treatments. The
disease, a mere annoyance to the young and healthy, kills 20,000 to
40,000 Americans each year, most of them elderly or with weakened
immune systems.
</P>
<P>
   Should Tamiflu win approval, it will be marketed by the Swiss
drug firm, Roche, and probably will sell for $50 to $75 per
treatment. Gilead will collect a royalty of 15 to 20 percent on
Tamiflu sales.
</P>
<P>
   Gilead will undergo even more intense FDA scrutiny of its second
drug candidate, Adefovir dipivoxil, an AIDS treatment. The first
hint of FDA sentiment will come November 1, when a scientific
advisory panel reviews the outcome of 10,000 AIDS patients who were
given experimental doses of Adefovir over the past six years. The
panel will advise the full FDA on whether or not to approve the
drug. An FDA decision is expected before year-end.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Jaffe, Gilead's vice president for drug development,
outlined the company's pitch. Adefovir seems to interrupt the
normal reproductive process of the AIDS virus. Several drugs
already on the market perform similar tasks, but Gilead will argue
that Adefovir is most effective in treating people who have begun
to develop resistance to commonly prescribed AIDS drugs, like AZT
or 3TC.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA advisory panel will have to weigh Adefovir's claimed
benefits against its apparent drawback: Long-term dosing seems to
interfere with the kidney's ability to clean the blood supply.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Hardy, a Los Angeles physician who participated in the
clinical trials of Adefovir, said the kidney problem was minor for
most patients. He would like to see Adefovir approved.
</P>
<P>
   If the FDA agrees, patients could expect an annual treatment to
cost between $2,500 and $3,800. Most important to investors is the
fact that Gilead will market Adefovir itself and therefore keep all
profits.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are impressed by the creative way in which Gilead
built an international sales force to market Adefovir without
having to license the drug to a partner, as it did with Tamiflu.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Gilead acquired NeXstar Pharmaceuticals in March in a
stock swap valued at $550 million. NeXstar, which is based in
Colorado, had already built a European sales force to market an
anti-fungal drug called AmBisome. NeXstar gave Gilead a European
sales force, plus $100 million in annual revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The merger between the two companies closed only a couple of
weeks ago. NeXstar has about 480 people, to Gilead's 350. Dietz,
the San Francisco analyst, said Gilead will tell investors on
September 8 how it plans to ``rationalize'' the staffs and research
programs at the two firms. Wall Street will be looking for
aggressive cost controls.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the factors affecting Gilead's future are unknowable,
like whether the FDA will OK Tamiflu and Adefovir. But Wall Street
is confident enough in the company's management to overlook these
unknowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a company that has had the right mix of panache and
disciplined science,'' said J.P. Morgan Securities analyst Franklin
Berger.
</P>
<P>
   The panache was supplied by Michael Riordan, who founded the
company in 1987 and named it for the ``balm of Gilead,'' a plant
referred to in the Bible as having miraculous healing properties.
Riordan, who took the company public in 1992 at $15 a share, ``had
a bit of the showman in him,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   But Riordan bowed out of the firm in the mid-1990s when Gilead's
original research focus _ it was founded on the ``antisense'' fad,
using bits of good DNA to correct defects caused by bad DNA _
proved as elusive as the Biblical balm.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Riordan had recruited and groomed his successor,
John Martin, who became chief executive in 1996. In the 1970s and
'80s, Martin earned a reputation as one of the world's foremost
antiviral experts. His ascension gave Gilead the scientific focus
that has brought the company to the threshold of profitability,
Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   Is it too late for small investors to get into Gilead? Consider
this. An FDA disappointment on Tamiflu or Adefovir _ or, God
forbid, both! _ could deflate the stock with the rude sound of a
whoopee cushion.
</P>
<P>
   But institutional investors are betting that Gilead has built
something rare in the biotech world _ a company capable of
discovering, developing and marketing a succession of products.
Gilead already has enrolled 198 patients in a Phase II study of
Tenofovir, an ``improved'' version of adefovir that could be more
potent against AIDS, with fewer side effects. Investors are waiting
for Gilead to release data on the Tenofovir tests, which could come
as early as September.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of what we're seeing in the stock price is that people
are beginning to realize the breadth and depth of the portfolio at
Gilead,'' said company CFO Perry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
