<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-CAMP-CHOAS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM BAD TO WORSE  
 `CAMP CATASTROPHE' TAKES TOLL ON CARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - With all that has gone wrong for the Cardinals in
the past three weeks, no one was shocked to see a small cast Sunday
on the left hand of starting left tackle Anthony Clement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, this team is like a dark comedy,'' offensive
lineman Matt Joyce said. ``Just when you think it can't get worse,
it gets worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Clement suffered a small fracture of the ulnar styloid bone near
his wrist in Friday night's 27-17 preseason victory over Tennessee.
He likely will wear a soft cast for about a month but will play
with the injury.
</P>
<P>
   The injury is the latest misfortune to strike the team since
``Camp Catastrophe'' opened July 30. In the past three weeks, three
players were injured in a car accident, three players remain
holdouts, the offensive line has been decimated by injuries and
starting quarterback Jake Plummer suffered a thumb injury to his
throwing hand.
</P>
<P>
   Things have gone so bad that one team official suggested the
coaches lock Plummer in a room and not let him out until the day
before Sept. 12 season opener in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals owner Bill Bidwill has seen worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 1940s, a player sneezed in the hotel lobby and was out
for a week with a bad back,'' Bidwill said.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a recap of the camp's calamities: &QL; 
Ominous beginning &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The night before camp opened, the team's top receiver of a year
ago, Frank Sanders, walked out of the cafeteria at the DuBois
Center on Northern Arizona University's campus and stepped in a
pothole. He suffered an injured left ankle that caused him to miss
the first two workouts.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the eve of camp, the team placed defensive tackle Eric
Swann, their highest-paid defensive lineman, and starting tight end
Johnny McWilliams on the physically unable to perform list. Swann
still hasn't recovered from off-season knee surgery and has been
unable to pass a physical examination to practice. McWilliams was
bothered by a nagging ankle injury but later was cleared to play.
</P>
<P>
   The first day of practice didn't go much better. Veteran tight
end Chris Gedney was released a few weeks after he had his colon
removed. Gedney could have been placed on the non-football
injury/illness list, and although he wouldn't have been paid, he
still would have felt a part of the team. Instead, the Cardinals
came off cruel and heartless, a public relations disaster that was
the hot topic on talk radio in the Valley for several days. &QL; 
Contract hassles &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals began training camp with four holdouts _
first-round draft picks David Boston and L.J. Shelton and veterans
Mark Smith and Rob Moore.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks later, only Boston has signed.
</P>
<P>
   There are eight holdouts in the NFL, and three are with the
Cardinals. So at least they lead in the league in one category.
</P>
<P>
   The Shelton holdout has turned into the theater of the absurd.
His agent, Lamont Smith, has threatened to release a tape that he
claims will show the team hasn't negotiated in good faith.
</P>
<P>
   Smith either doesn't have a tape or has lost his nerve.
</P>
<P>
   During a news conference in Denver nine days ago, Smith claimed
the Cardinals had offered only $2.6 million for a signing bonus,
well below market value.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he didn't ask for the $3.6 million the Cardinals could
offer Shelton, Smith said he didn't want to give the impression he
was signing off on a five-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   The team isn't any closer to signing Mark Smith, a third-year
defensive tackle, to a long-term deal than it was three months ago.
Smith was unhappy with the $325,000 one-year tender offer he
received last spring and also has rejected a one-year deal for
$500,000.
</P>
<P>
   With each week, Mark Smith seems to have more leverage. Swann
still isn't practicing and the team can't stop the run,
particularly up the middle. The Cardinals gave up 4.6 yards per
carry in an embarrassing 38-7 loss at Denver in the preseason
opener and allowed 4.2 yards per carry Friday night against
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Moore is expected to sign within the next week, but he has
missed three weeks of camp and won't have a lot of time to get in
shape. &QL; 
Bruised and battered &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When second-year tight end Terry Hardy (hamstring) joined
McWilliams on the sideline the second day of camp, it was a bad
sign of things to come.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, only two tight ends were healthy, a frequent
occurrence early.
</P>
<P>
   Some days, only seven or eight offensive linemen practiced,
forcing Tobin to alter his schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Starting left guard Chris Dishman injured his elbow the first
week of camp when he got tangled up with defensive lineman Brad
Ottis. Dishman wound up having surgery 10 days ago and likely will
be out until the start of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Early in camp, Ernest Dye (knee), James Dexter (ankle) and Allen
DeGraffenreid (shoulder) were slowed by injuries. Joyce missed a
couple of days of workouts when he had his knee checked out, but
the X-rays proved negative.
</P>
<P>
   The line was nearly depleted after Dye and starting right guard
Lester Holmes were injured in last week's car accident.
</P>
<P>
   Then in Friday night's victory over Tennessee, Jerome Daniels,
who started in Holmes' spot, suffered a dislocated elbow, an injury
that will put him out of action for four to six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The serious injuries weren't limited to the offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   Second-year linebacker Zack Walz hasn't practiced or played
since suffering a neck stinger in an Aug. 7 scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   Pro Bowl cornerback Aeneas Williams has been held out of the
first two preseason games because of recurring neck pain. &QL; 
Silver lining? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals players know last Monday's car crash could have had a
much worse ending. That's why they mobbed the four passers-by, Paul
Wells, Gary Shira and Kendra and Troy Jacobs, who were honored
before Friday night's game for coming to the aid of Dye, Holmes and
defensive end Carl Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   Had they not helped, Dye might have bled to death. His right
arm, which nearly was severed, wouldn't have had a chance to remain
viable.
</P>
<P>
   Dye likely won't play football again. Holmes is healing but
isn't expected to be ready for the Sept. 12 opener in Philadelphia.
Simpson hopes to return to practice this week.
</P>
<P>
   Simpson was the only of the three at Sun Devil Stadium last
Friday night when Plummer suffered a hyperextended right thumb, a
freakish injury that occurred when Titans defensive lineman Mike
Jones grabbed the quarterback's right thumb and twisted it.
</P>
<P>
   With the way the Cardinals' luck has gone, it's surprising no
one stepped on Plummer's injured hand on the bottom of the pile.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer's hand is only bruised. Cardinals players hope that's a
sign the worst is behind them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think good things are ahead of us,'' Simpson said Sunday.
``Sometimes you have to go through this stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how much it hurts. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
