A6135 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-HKN-COYOTES-KHABIBULI     08-23 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-KHABIBULIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLDOUT IN WORKS FOR `NIK'? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Statistically, Nikolai Khabibulin ranks among the top
five goalies in the NHL. Financially, it's doubtful he'll crack the
top 10 _ if and when he ever agrees to a new contract with the
Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   Such is life for Khabibulin, the team's most prominent unsigned
free agent.
</P>
<P>
   General Manager Bobby Smith dropped a bombshell by saying he was
fed up with the high salary demands of another restricted free
agent, No. 2 center Robert Reichel, and will actively seek to trade
him.
</P>
<P>
   The situation regarding Khabibulin, for the moment, is not as
hard line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've given `Nik' and his agent (Jay Grossman) three different
offers with three different terms, but his agent has not
responded,'' Smith said. ``Obviously, we expect him to pretty soon
so we can get this guy signed.''
</P>
<P>
   But with veterans scheduled to report to training camp in less
than three weeks and no word yet from the 25-year-old Russian or
his New York-based agent, Grossman, the Coyotes may have to brace
for a holdout.
</P>
<P>
   After four consecutive seasons in which his numbers have
steadily improved, Khabibulin may want up to $4 million per season
_ a salary at least three other agents agree seems to be the going
rate for a goalie of his caliber.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes, who claim they lost nearly $10 million last season,
will argue they aren't in position to pay that amount. Keith
Tkachuk and Jeremy Roenick each make $4 million a year, and in the
season after, Tkachuk will make $8.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the franchise allotted so much payroll to three
players, it felt forced to trade one away. Teemu Selanne went to
the Anaheim Mighty Ducks, along with his 50-plus goals a season.
The two key players received in return _ Oleg Tverdovsky and Chad
Kilger _ have since been dealt.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he hopes the Coyotes will sign Khabibulin before
training camp opens Sept. 3. But if significant progress isn't made
shortly, Khabibulin could be headed for a long holdout, leaving
fellow Russian Mikhail Shtalenkov as the only experienced goalie on
the roster.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't bode well for a team on its fourth head coach in
five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will Khabibulin be a holdout? I don't know,'' Smith said. ``If
he doesn't have a contract, he won't be in training camp. That's
something we may have to prepare for. If he's not there, I think
more than anything it's going to hurt his ability to get off to a
good start.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I have a responsibility to this organization to make sure
we're in a good position to go places, and I have been fully
prepared to make Nik one of the top-paid goalies in the league _
for a Group II (free agent).''
</P>
<P>
   Therein lies the sticking point. The majority of the NHL's
highest-paid goalies entering this season received their huge
salaries after becoming unrestricted free agents at age 31, or they
were re-signed by their own clubs shortly before reaching
unrestricted status.
</P>
<P>
   Smith contends, and many agents agree, that restricted free
agents don't always carry the same financial leverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Theo Fleury goes from making $3.5 million to $7 million (by
leaving Colorado to sign as an unrestricted free agent with the
Rangers), but does that mean he's three times as good a player
overnight? Of course not,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But a lot of restricted guys have signed lucrative deals,
too,'' countered Grossman, Khabibulin's agent.
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk is one example. Five years ago, he signed an offer sheet
from the Chicago Blackhawks as a restricted free agent that was
worth $6 million the first year alone. The Winnipeg Jets matched
it, and last season the Coyotes restructured the deal and agreed to
give Tkachuk, still a restricted free agent, an extra year worth a
whopping $8.3 million after this upcoming season.
</P>
<P>
   Khabibulin's 32 wins last season tied for fourth-best in the NHL
with Colorado's Patrick Roy and Boston's Byron Dafoe. His 2.13
goals-against average ranked fifth among starters. His .923 save
percentage tied for fourth with Carolina's Arturs Irbe. Only
Buffalo's Dominik Hasek (10) and Dafoe (nine) had more shutouts
than his franchise-record eight.
</P>
<P>
   In his first four full seasons, Khabibulin has averaged 30 wins
a year. Since 1996-97, the Coyotes' first season in the Valley,
only three goalies _ Hasek, Curtis Joseph and New Jersey's Martin
Brodeur _ have faced more shots. Only Hasek and Brodeur have more
shutouts.
</P>
<P>
   On the pay scale, however, Khabibulin's $1.25 million salary
last season was lower than half the league's starting goalies. Even
if he gets a raise of $1 million, at least 13 goalies are scheduled
to earn more than $2.25 million in 1999-2000.
</P>
<P>
   Grossman has declined to publicly discuss the negotiations.
Smith has made offers for two, three and four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've made legitimate offers and I expect Nik to get
signed,'' Smith said. ``(Grossman) hasn't responded, but I don't
think it's a big deal yet. We'll just wait. I'm not worried about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked this week why he hasn't contacted Smith, Grossman said
virtually the same things he has said all summer:
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to negotiate through the media. There's nothing
really to address at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   What about the possibility of a holdout?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not something we're ready to comment on,'' Grossman
said. ``It's a little premature at this point.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
