<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-PIRATES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS PLAY LONG BALL  
 OUTFIELDER TRIGGERS HOME RUN EXPLOSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ When baseball fans think of Luis Gonzalez, they
will remember the 30-game hitting streak he put together this
season.
</P>
<P>
   To the Diamondbacks, he is much more than that. An unassuming
guy who goes out and gives it his best every day and remains on an
even keel. They will look back on this season and say that he was
the glue that helped them stick together during the National League
West pennant race.
</P>
<P>
   The 31-year-old left fielder was at his best Sunday, hitting a
pair of home runs and driving in four runs to spark Arizona to a
7-5 victory against the Pittsburgh Pirates at Three Rivers Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez's first-inning home run was followed in rapid
succession by shots from Matt Williams and Erubiel Durazo, giving
the Diamondbacks three consecutive home runs for the first time in
club history. His second homer gave them a season total of 163,
another team record.
</P>
<P>
   The victory moved Arizona to 20 games above .500 for the first
time in its history, 72-52. By winning their second in a row and
11th in their past 14, the Diamondbacks also were able to maintain
their 7{-game lead over San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks conclude a four-game series against the Pirates
tonight, then move on to Miami to begin a three-game series against
the Marlins on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez had his 50th multihit game of the season (he was second
in the league in that category entering the game) while hitting his
21st and 22nd homers, putting him within one of his career high set
last season with Detroit. He also increased his career-high RBI
total to 84.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, Williams and Durazo hit consecutive homers off
right-hander Jason Schmidt (10-9) and gave the Diamondbacks a 5-0
lead in the first inning. It was the fifth time in club history
that three homers were hit in one inning.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona got another run in the fifth when Steve Finley tripled
and scored on a balk by Schmidt, and scored its last run in the
ninth on a leadoff homer by Gonzalez off right-hander Jose Silva.
</P>
<P>
   All the homers were to left field, which included opposite-field
shots by Gonzalez and Durazo. Williams' homer was his 30th of the
season, the sixth time he has reached that level in his career, to
go with 110 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball carried good out to left today,'' Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   He is pleased with his season but insists he is just a piece of
the veteran Diamondbacks puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got balance in our lineup,'' he said. ``We've got four
guys with the potential to drive in 100 (himself, Williams, Jay
Bell and Steve Finley) and four with the potential to score 100
(himself, Williams, Bell and Tony Womack). That's good, especially
when you're in a pennant race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just feed off each other. If one guy doesn't do it, the
next guy will. We keep pushing each other.''
</P>
<P>
   The cushion generated by the big first inning wasn't comfortable
for long, as the Pirates rallied for four runs in the third off
left-hander Omar Daal. But Daal didn't give up a run during the
remainder of his seven-inning outing and got credit for the victory
(13-6) before turning the eighth and ninth innings over to
right-handers Gregg Olson and Matt Mantei. Mantei picked up his
11th save for Arizona and 21st overall by striking out the side.
</P>
<P>
   Daal walked Schmidt, the leadoff man in the third, then gave up
three hits, including a bloop double to center field by Kevin
Young.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated, Daal kicked some of the dirt from the mound area
onto the artificial turf, creating a small brown cloud.
</P>
<P>
   ``You make good pitches, and they still get base hits,'' he
said. ``Walking the pitcher is not good. It seems that every time
that happens, they come around to score.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first couple of innings, I was a little tight. I didn't
have much control of my slider. But I knew I had to keep the score
the way it was. I said, `My offense has given me some runs, and I
can't lose this game.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Olson, who had given up no runs in his previous six relief
appearances, surrendered a home run to Young, his third of the
series, on the first pitch in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Mantei, who had not pitched since Wednesday night, came in to
strike out pinch-hitters Al Martin and Brant Brown, walk Adrian
Brown and strike out veteran Dale Sveum to end the game. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
