<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-NOTEBOOK-FRAUENHEIM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSSIES FIND HALL FITS RIGHT IN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If television ads for a beer in barrel-size cans provide a
glimpse at the Down Under perspective, Australia likes its offbeat
characters. The bigger, the better.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Gary Hall Jr. qualifies. He's not exactly Crocodile Dundee Jr.,
but he is the kind of personality that captures attention in a
country with a wry, rollicking sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Hall, an Olympic gold and silver medalist from
Phoenix Swim Club, appears to be a welcome relief from Denver
Broncos receiver
 &UR; Shannon Sharpe, who redefined the Ugly American concept a couple of
weeks ago with insults that reverberated from Sydney to Perth
before an NFL preseason game.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe would make a pretty good target for the boomerang that
serves as a remote control on those beer ads.
</P>
<P>
   With Hall, the news reports about his arrival for this week's
Pan Pacific Championships make it sound as if the Aussies would
like to join him in a good laugh, mate.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of samples:
</P>
<P>
   According to the Australian Sports News Service: ``Hall, with
his cowlicked bed-head, cargo pants and love of influential '60s
rock band The Grateful Dead, doesn't seem like the sort of guy
who'd get worked up about things.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the`` Sydney Morning Heral''d: ``This is a bloke
who once suggested that swimmers cover themselves in body paint
similar to wrestlers and race in events on which spectators could
bet.''
</P>
<P>
   The bet in some corners this week is that Hall will break the
world record in the 50-meter freestyle, which he won at the U.S.
nationals in a dramatic comeback since his suspension for a
positive marijuana test and diabetes diagnosis. Hall swam his best
time five days after a bout with the flu and while wearing a baggy
suit that, next to all the microsize Speedos, looked like a pair of
cut-offs.
</P>
<P>
   The only unfortunate aspect about this week's 50 is the absence
of South African sprinter  &UR; Roland  &UR; Schoeman, a University of
Arizona sophomore who recorded the year's fastest time in a
different heat at the same meet that Hall went his best. South
African officials banned him from Australia because he didn't
compete in their national championships after a dispute about
money. &QL; 
Arizona gold &QL; 
Arizona struck gold for the second time in the Pan Pacs early
Sunday, the opening day of competition at the Olympic pool in
Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four hours after 17-year-old  &UR; Klete Keller of Phoenix
Swim Club and Arcadia High won the 5-kilometer swim in Melbourne,
former University of Arizona sprinter  &UR; Liesl Kolbisen of Tucson
swam a leg for the U.S. women's 400-meter freestyle relay, which
beat Australia for the gold.
</P>
<P>
   Another former UA swimmer,  &UR; Chad Carvin, finished fourth in the
men's 400 freestyle, nearly eight seconds behind the world
record-shattering performance by Aussie  &UR; Ian Thorpe.
</P>
<P>
   An Arizona swimmer to watch today:  &UR; Misty Hyman, of the Valley's
Desert Fox Club and Stanford University. She advanced through the
semifinals and qualified fourth for today's final in the 100-meter
butterfly. &QL; 
Briefly . .  &QL; 
Movie star  &UR; Geena Davis is out, but three archers with Arizona
links were still in the hunt this weekend in the U.S. Olympic
trials at Bloomfield, N.J. Former Arizona State archers and Olympic
gold medalists  &UR; Justin Huisch (1996) and  &UR; Jay Barrs (1988) were
among the men's final 16 late Saturday. For the women, the final 16
included &UR; Michelle Ragsdale of Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Yewki  &UR; Tomita of Tucson will compete this week at national
championships in Sacramento for one of five spots on the U.S. men's
gymnastics team at the World Championships, which are scheduled for
China this year. Tomita, America's best on the pommel horse, is
considered a medal possibility at the 2000 Olympics. &QL; 
Information from other media sources included. Norm Frauenheim can
be reached at 602-444-82259 or norm.frauenheim(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
