<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-MOORE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEETING SET WITH AGENT FOR MOORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Negotiations between the Cardinals and unsigned
wide receiver Rob Moore are expected to heat up today when contract
negotiator Rod Graves goes to Los Angeles to meet with Moore's
agent, Gary Wichard.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals have had several informal discussions with Moore's
representative, but they have spent most of training camp
concentrating on getting their rookies signed.
</P>
<P>
   First-round draft pick L.J. Shelton, the offensive tackle from
Eastern Michigan picked 21st overall, and third-year defensive
tackle Mark Smith also are unsigned.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Cardinals and Moore's representatives have not
done a lot of negotiating, there has been friendly dialogue between
the two sides. In fact, Moore picked up his playbook last month, a
few days before the team reported for training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive coordinator Marc Trestman said he has had several
discussions with Moore, the team's designated franchise player,
during camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to him periodically,'' Trestman said. ``Rob knows
this is an important contract for him, but he wants to be here.
He's
</P>
<P>
   excited about trying to get in here.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore, who will be 31 next month, was unable to reach agreement
with the Cardinals on a contract in February, prompting the team to
place the franchise tag on him.
</P>
<P>
   As the franchise player, the Cardinals can match any offer for
Moore and have to pay him at least $3.5 million for this season.
The team wants to sign him to a multiyear deal, which means it
would get the franchise tag back to use on another player next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Moore reportedly would like a four-year package worth about $22
million. The Cardinals seem more interested in a three-year
contract worth about $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Moore's representatives said the team offered $4.5
million a year but only a $2 million signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Moore, a 10-year pro, was the team's second-leading receiver a
year ago with 67 catches for 982 yards and six scores. He was the
club's top receiver in the playoffs with 11 receptions for 132
yards. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-99 0147EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
