<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MESA BLOWS SAVE, THEN PINELLA BLOWS STACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It was one of those old-time Mariners meltdowns, the
kind that haunt the memories of Northwest fans. Ken Griffey Jr.
saves the day ... until the closer blows the save ... and the
manager gets ejected ... and another reliever walks in a run ... in
a nationally televised game.
</P>
<P>
   After Griffey's two-run homer gave the Mariners the lead in the
eighth inning Sunday, Jose Mesa allowed the tying run in the ninth
and the go-ahead runs on a Richie Sexson homer in the 10th. The 7-4
loss to the Cleveland Indians was the Mariners' third in a row in
this series and, to one player, the most bitter of this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight was the low point of the year for us, for a lot of
reasons,'' shortstop Alex Rodriguez said. ``We needed to stop the
bleeding and we didn't. We haven't executed all parts of our game,
and we've been very inconsistent. We're brilliant at times, and
we're (awful) at times. That's what you get _ inconsistent play,
and you're a few games under .500.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners, who were swept by one of the American League's
other elite teams, the New York Yankees, in a four-game series at
Safeco Field earlier this month, face the same outcome if they drop
tonight's finale with the Indians. Seattle is 11-22 against the
four teams leading the American League's playoff races.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've sucked,'' Rodriguez said. ``We've been terrible,
starting with me. It's been frustrating. It starts with me, it
starts with all my teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We suck. We can't beat teams like that the way we played
today. Jamie (Moyer) pitched an outstanding ballgame, and the
offense is dragging. We're just not getting it done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians, who have beaten the Mariners in seven of nine
meetings this year, have three regulars injured and rested two
others Sunday night. When they needed a boost in the ninth, they
used stars Roberto Alomar and David Justice as pinch-hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us to beat good teams, everything almost has to go perfect
for us,'' manager Lou Piniella said. ``We don't have the depth
these teams have.''
</P>
<P>
   With a 4-3 lead, Mesa walked Alomar and allowed a single to
Carlos Baerga, putting runners at the corners with no outs. A
sacrifice fly by Justice scored Alomar, giving Mesa his first blown
save since the Safeco Field opener and fourth on the year.
</P>
<P>
   It took 17 pitches for Mesa to make a Cleveland batter swing and
miss, and when Dave Roberts finally did _ flailing at a high,
outside fastball on a hit-and-run _ chaos followed.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Wilson's throw easily beat Baerga to second base, and
Rodriguez raised his glove after seemingly applying the tag.
Replays showed Baerga, flopping like a fish around second, slid
wide of Rodriguez to avoid the tag, then slapped his hand on the
base as Rodriguez pleaded to umpire Bill Welke.
</P>
<P>
   Welke ruled Baerga safe, Rodriguez turned livid, and Piniella
stormed from the dugout, stumbling his first few steps out as
Indians manager Mike Hargrove laughed. If Piniella was bruised, it
didn't impede one of his most memorable tirades.
</P>
<P>
   He quickly earned his fourth ejection of the year _ all in the
last month _ and proceeded to kick the ground near Welke, appearing
to inadvertently kick the umpire in the shin. After pointing to the
spot Baerga slid, Piniella dropped to the ground, imitating Baerga
to prove his point.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rule says you've got to be able to touch the bag with your
hand,'' Piniella said. ``He was a good six feet from the bag. ...
(Welke) said he could have (touched second), and he could have _ if
he was Wilt Chamberlain.''
</P>
<P>
   As the crowd hooted and ESPN split its screen to show the replay
and Piniella's live tantrum, two fans rushed the field, needing
seven guards to bring them down.
</P>
<P>
   A fine night had turned ugly for a sold-out crowd of 44,941, and
the decisive 10th inning hadn't even begun.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners went quietly off rookie winner David Riske, a Kent
native, in the ninth, then lost in the 10th when Sexson drove a
pitch into the right-field seats. The home run punctuated an inning
that featured four walks, two by Mesa and two (one intentional) by
Steve Sinclair. The last walk, to Justice, gave Cleveland its final
run.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners were trailing 3-2 when Griffey connected off
reliever Paul Assenmacher with one out in the eighth. The blast
gave Griffey sole possession of the American League home run lead
with 38.
</P>
<P>
   But this was not a game in which Griffey, or any of the Mariners
hitters, played the hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you come back, it doesn't matter if it's in the first
inning or the ninth inning, it's still the same,'' Griffey said.
``It's a little more dramatic if it's the ninth inning, but you
still have the same feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Tyler Kepner can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or tylerkepner &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
