<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 03:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6173 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-FORBIDDEN-TEXAS-SFCHR     08-23 1184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORBIDDEN-TEXAS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE EMPERORS' NEW WOES _ MILLIONAIRE'S DREAM SITS LOST IN TEXAS  &HT;     BY MICHAEL TAYLOR
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KATY, Texas _ Out on rural Franz Road, past the CCN Concrete
Materials yard and the Williamsburg Parish housing tract and the
Texaco Food-Mart, Ira P.H. Poon's dream is difficult to spot.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that was the original intention. But it's impossible to
know, since Poon, who spent $20 million on what must be one of the
world's least-known theme parks, isn't talking.
</P>
<P>
   As you get closer, there's a handful of flagpoles with streamers
and, a few inches off the ground, a tiny sign that whispers
Forbidden Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   Down the driveway, the parking lot could handle 300 cars. At 10
a.m., when Forbidden Gardens opens for guided tours _ $10 a ticket
for adults, $5 for children _ only two autos sit ticking under the
101-degree south Texas swelter. By noon, there is one car.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's the summer heat that keeps people away, or the huge
steel roof that looks like the world's largest carport. But
underneath the roof is a 40,000-square-foot, extravagantly precise,
1/20th-scale rendition of the Forbidden City in Beijing, home of Pu
Yi, the last Chinese emperor. Go rent the 1987 Oscar-winning film
``The Last Emperor,'' and imagine the scenery in miniature to get a
feel for the place.
</P>
<P>
   Set on some 80 acres in the bedroom community of Katy, 30 miles
west of Houston, Forbidden Gardens is an outdoor museum whose other
main exhibit, also small-scale, focuses on China's first emperor,
Qin Shi Huang. Poon had all the thousands of miniature buildings,
statues and figurines made in China and installed by Chinese
artisans who were flown in from Asia.
</P>
<P>
   No billboards announce this place along nearby Interstate 10;
there is no hype on radio and television, no travel agent tie-ins.
Disney World it is not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been here 21/2 years, and I went part-time this
January,'' says Connie Williams, the Gardens' director of
marketing, a bit forlornly. ``There's not that much to do. My
agenda is to go full blast, but they're not ready for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbidden Gardens, where the tour guides and the marketing
director and just about everybody else use the term ``low-key'' to
describe their outpost, is the brainchild and lifelong dream of
Poon, an educator and real-estate developer who divides his time
between Hong Kong and Seattle. At least, that is how his staff
describes him. Poon doesn't talk to the press.
</P>
<P>
   A phone call to Maria College, a school he apparently owns in
Hong Kong, is met with a referral to another phone number for Poon.
Calls to Poon are not returned. His Forbidden Gardens employees see
him only once or twice a year, when he flies in to take stock of
his pet project and does not talk about himself or his affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Under the one-acre carport, walking around the Forbidden City
exhibit feels a little like walking around the world's most
expensive and elaborate dollhouse _ doll mansion, maybe. Visitors
can stroll on walkways bordering the various buildings and more
than 900 rooms in the Forbidden City compound, under the watchful
eyes of the hundreds of figurines, each about eight inches high.
</P>
<P>
   When the real Forbidden City was being used as the emperor's
residence, some 5,000 eunuchs, concubines and guards were in
attendance each day. At night, only the 3,000 guards were allowed
to go home, outside the walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wall of the real Forbidden City was 35 feet high,'' says
tour guide Jerry Yeh, ``and it went another 20 feet underground. No
way for the eunuchs and concubines to dig out of the place.''
</P>
<P>
   Poon's compound also contains a replica of the tomb of Qin Shi
Huang, complete with a football-field-size pit containing about
6,000 half-scale, but eerily lifelike terra-cotta soldiers who
guard the first emperor's resting place.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the pit, huge by comparison, is a
more-than-life-size statue of the emperor himself.
</P>
<P>
   Buried in the concrete walls are pieces of terra-cotta, meant to
replicate the bones of actual tomb workers who were killed to keep
them from blabbing about their secret construction project. The
emperor, like his 20th century patron, Mr. Poon, was not a
publicity hound.
</P>
<P>
   All this is a version of the emperor's actual final resting
place near the city of Xian in China. The tomb was built
approximately 2,200 years ago by 700,000 workers who toiled for 36
years. The emperor died at 49, after an 11-year reign. He was on a
tour of his conquered provinces when he took ill from a concoction
of mercury that was supposed to prolong his life but had the
opposite effect.
</P>
<P>
   Since it was discovered in 1974, the tomb has become a
world-famous tourist site that draws 2 million visitors a year.
</P>
<P>
   But the attendance in Katy on a summer morning recently
consisted of one reporter and a group of 16 kids from a local
school. The children seemed pretty impressed, particularly with the
room full of old spears and swords.
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany Loving, 10, looked around, a bit in awe, and wondered,
``If the statues could talk, what would they say?''
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd talk about the emperor and how he acted,'' said
9-year-old Colton Roulston.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Poon, the educator, should have been there. His
second-in-command, D.C. Chan, says via e-mail that Poon ``began his
career as an English teacher in Hong Kong'' and prides himself on
having built a museum to share with ``people who do not have the
chance to see those real wonders.''
</P>
<P>
   Chan says Poon decided to build Forbidden Gardens in south Texas
because ``the weather in Houston is better than Seattle.'' Better
is a relative term, of course, and while Houston doesn't get the
cold rain of Seattle, it gets broiling hot and fiercely humid,
something that brought some unexpected problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past year, we've noticed that the weather has taken a
toll on the buildings,'' says Lisa Gipson, the accounts manager, as
a woman with feather dusters batted at some courtyard railings. ``I
don't think they knew the weather in Texas was harsh. So it's an
ongoing process of maintenance. As soon as you think you're done,
you're not.''
</P>
<P>
   The maintenance crew, in fact, may be the people most aware of
Forbidden Gardens. Over at Katy's City Hall, Missy Bunch, the
assistant city secretary, says, ``We know they're out there, but we
haven't heard a lot of people in town talking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Texaco Food-Mart, the owner, Ann, said, ``I think $10 is
too high to get in there. ... You pay $10, but you don't know what
it is. If it's Disneyland, you know what's in there.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Williamsburg Parish housing development, across the
fields from Poon's project, most residents said they had never been
to Forbidden Gardens and weren't very interested.
</P>
<P>
   And over in Houston, with its Chinese American community of more
than 100,000 people, only a few had even heard of the place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been there,'' said travel agent Thomas Luan. ``It's
interesting, but most people don't know it's there.''
</P>
<P>
   He smiled and added, ``They need a travel agent to promote it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
