<HEADER>
A6175 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     08-23 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 A MAYOR SEEN BUT NOT HEARD  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Remember when Willie Brown stood out in a crowd?
</P>
<P>
   At the opera or symphony, at political gatherings, at the city's
fine restaurants and major social events, the mayor always arrived
with trumpets blaring, figuratively, and took over the room with
his commanding presence, savoir faire and joie de vivre.
</P>
<P>
   But now, the Jolsongate scandal has hit town, and Heeere's
Willie has become ``Where's Waldo?''
</P>
<P>
   An FBI investigation hangs over the head of the city, and from
the glibbest mayor in the history of mayors: Still no comment.
</P>
<P>
   Jolsongate? Al Jolson was a singer in the '20s who performed in
blackface, painting his face in the minstrel-show tradition.
</P>
<P>
   The current FBI investigation appears to be zeroing in on a
local white-owned-and-controlled construction company that,
according to an Examiner story, painted itself in blackface in
order to win millions of dollars in ``minority'' contracts on city
projects.
</P>
<P>
   If this stuff turns out to be true, it means that in the city
that prides itself on its diversity and progressive treatment of
minorities, minorities are being progressively screwed by rich
white guys, with the aid of at least one key black guy.
</P>
<P>
   Ugly stuff, and you'd think the mayor would be interested. Among
the characters involved in the FBI probe are two ex-cons with
histories of violence and/or cheating who have flourished under the
Brown administration.
</P>
<P>
   Brown takes credit for the booming local economy and all the
good projects and programs under way, but doesn't that blame-credit
sword slash both ways?
</P>
<P>
   But you can understand why the mayor doesn't have time to speak
to the people of the city on this matter. He's busy running for
mayor.
</P>
<P>
   IF ONLY San Francisco's high society had been hired to guard the
United States' nuclear weapons secrets, the ones that have steadily
leaked out to the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to keeping a secret, nobody beats our very own
Upper Crust. For several years, Gordon Getty's double life has been
common knowledge among our social elite, but not a word of it
leaked out to the city's lower social strata.
</P>
<P>
   It was the San Jose Mercury News that yanked Getty out of the
closet as a two-family man, with a mistress and three daughters in
L.A. to supplement his wife-and-four-sons family here.
</P>
<P>
   By weird coincidence, notes George Markell, the story ran in The
Chronicle on Saturday, and that same day's New York Times crossword
had this clue for a 19-letter space: ```Jerry Springer' topic?''
</P>
<P>
   The solution: ``I've got a secret family.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean Gordon and his families will be appearing on
``Springer,'' although his mistress might turn up on the new Regis
Philbin quiz show, ``Who Wants to be a Millionaire?''
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Gordon never laid a moral indignation trip on buddy
Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The southern branch of Gordon's family is trying to claim his
name and some of his fortune, but maybe Getty can pick up some
extra cash doing a Doublemint gum commercial.
</P>
<P>
   NO WONDER San Francisco has become the new mecca of country
western music.
</P>
<P>
   Country songs are all about cheatin' and lyin', and who does it
better than we folk by the bay?
</P>
<P>
   Even the local football teams get into the act. The 49ers, of
course, are suffering through their own little Harper Valley
PTA-type scandal /crisis, the good-timin' owner having been forced
out by his cold-hearted sister.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Raiders have a new ad campaign. One billboard shows a
dad and son, their eyes covered with bars like those associated,
I'm told, with old porn pics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never miss a game,'' the kid is saying, ``but Mom thinks
we're at the playground.''
</P>
<P>
   So Dad is teaching Junior to lie to Mom, and they're sneaking
off to an activity that Mom apparently would deem unsavory.
</P>
<P>
   Wonder how they explain to Mom that they spent the rent money on
some of the NFL's most expensive tickets?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe somehow the ballgame trips will help Junior's education,
which is being undermined by the millions of dollars in Oakland tax
money sucked off to subsidize the Raiders and their stadium
improvements. How about some black eyebands for the pols who cut
that deal?
</P>
<P>
   LISTENING TO Thursday night's 49ers-Seahawks game on KGO, Jim
Tubridy heard a commercial for PG&AMP;E _ ``Giving you the power you
need, when you need it.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless you're a major international airport. Earlier that same
day, SFO experienced a three-hour power outage when a high-voltage
underground cable exploded during some construction work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It blew the manhole cover more than 100 feet,'' an airport
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   And that gives me a great idea for adding drama to the 49ers'
pregame coin-flip ceremony.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
