<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 09:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6265 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-VISION-THERAPY-LIFEBE     08-23 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VISION-THERAPY-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VISION THERAPY MAY HELP LEARNING PROBLEMS
</HEADLINE>
  Includes color photo of a pair of glasses 
 By JENNIFER BAKER 
 c.1999 NYT Regional Newspapers 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The office of optometrist Michael Phillips boasts a spacious
eyewear showroom, a finishing lab, a receptionist's office and
several exam rooms _ all up-to-date and professional.
</P>
<P>
   But on most weekdays, the St. Petersburg, Fla., clinic may look
more like an after-school program. A child twists on a trampoline
in a pre-set pattern and then moves on to dribbling a playground
ball a specified number of times with each hand. Another calls out
numbers while traversing a wooden balance beam that stretches
across the back wall. Shelves are jumbled with games, toys,
instruments and homemade apparatuses.
</P>
<P>
   The young patients are receiving vision therapy, a training
program designed to improve visual function. While most of them
have 20/20 vision, or vision that has been corrected to 20/20, they
have trouble with skills such as reading and writing, copying from
the blackboard and eye-hand coordination.
</P>
<P>
   Vision therapy, offered by specially trained optometrists like
Phillips, is aimed at improving near-to-far focusing, tracking,
scanning and using both eyes together. Children who have difficulty
with these vision skills often underperform in school.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been in practice for 25 years, and when these kids come
back and are doctors and attorneys, you see the potential that was
almost wasted,'' Phillips said. ''It's amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   This type of therapy is not new. As far back as 100 years ago,
similar exercises were used to treat lazy eye and crossed eyes. In
the 1930s, the approach expanded to include treatment of focusing,
eye movement and perceptual problems. The College of Optometrists
and Vision Development, based in St. Louis, began certifying vision
therapists in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   As many as one in four children have visual perception problems,
according to the college. Still, vision therapy is not widely
available, with only 600 board certified vision therapists in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Some medical doctors remain skeptical that the treatment is
useful, saying that vision therapy is scientifically unproven.
Michael Redmond, a board member of the American Academy of
Ophthalmology, calls vision therapy a ''wild conglomeration'' of
practices short on scientific proof.
</P>
<P>
   The therapy claims to address a wide range of learning
processing problems that Redmond claims originate in the brain, not
the eye. After long and costly therapy, the learning problems would
still exist, he says. Evidence of improvement, he maintains,
derives from the one-on-one attention children receive during
therapy.
</P>
<P>
   But optometrist Sharon Berger, a board certified vision
therapist in Atlanta, says she has no doubt that vision therapy
works for most patients. ''Yes, we are dealing with the brain,''she
says. ''We're changing the way people visually process information.
We are allowing them to process it more efficiently and faster. The
improvements are ongoing, long after the therapy is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Vision is more than just sight, say vision therapists. It is
also deriving meaning from what is seen, through perception and
integration. Problems in these areas may overlap with learning
disabilities such as dyslexia and attention deficit disorder.
Improvement in eye functioning may alleviate some symptoms,
therapists say.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most children are referred to me by their schools between the
ages of 5 and 10,'' says Berger, who has been practicing with her
husband, Dr. William Moscow, for almost 20 years at the Roswell Eye
Clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Berger begins with a vision screening to make sure there are no
health or pathology problems. Then the child undergoes an initial
assessment and battery of tests that lasts a few hours and costs
about $225. Most children who are diagnosed with vision problems
receive therapy twice a week for six months, although some
treatment can range from three months to more than a year.
Insurance picks up about 80 percent of the cost for patients whose
medical plan includes vision therapy coverage.
</P>
<P>
   If a child needs the therapy, early intervention can make all
the difference, Berger says : ''I've seen lives change, parents cry
because of the changes their children have made. It's the most
rewarding thing we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, several parents report startling improvements in their
child's academic performance after vision therapy. Eight-year-old
Ricky Perry has had vision therapy for about six months at
Phillips' St. Petersburg clinic. His spelling and reading are much
improved, and his aunt, Mignonette Hayden, says Ricky likes school
now for the first time. Amanda Francavilla, 9, saw her reading jump
two grade levels since beginning therapy in St. Petersburg last
September. She now reads two to three books each week, up from a
single chapter a week last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Geimer, 12, was a slow reader in kindergarten and first
grade. Eye screening did not indicate a vision problem. But an
evaluation pointed to a problem with his eye muscles working
together. After a year of vision therapy, said his mother, Diane
Geimer, the change was miraculous. Within the year, he was reading
at grade level; now in the sixth grade, he reads well above grade
level. Along with academic improvements, Geimer saw her son gain
self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   Vision therapists use techniques such as specially designed
computer programs, balance boards, walking rails, mini-trampolines,
chalk boards, parquetry blocks, stereoscopes, colored lenses and 3D
pictures to improve the visual system. ''The visual system has to
develop. Just as we learn to walk and talk, we learn how to see,''
Berger says.
</P>
<P>
   Not all vision therapy takes place in an optometrist's office.
Berger will often suggest informal activities for kids to do at
home, such as mom or dad sitting on one side of the child while
talking or eating, to pull a weak eye over to that side more often;
crafts, such as puzzles, coloring and Play-Doh, and more outdoor
time _ running, jumping and playing ball or Simon Says.
</P>
<P>
   ''So much of vision has to do with movement, where we exist in
space, giving us that orientation,'' she says. ''When a child has
trouble tracking, we have to work with the whole body. When vision
therapy is successful, everything gets better _ from doing homework
to swinging a baseball bat.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Jennifer Baker writes for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla.) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
