<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 09:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6266 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-TWINS-FESTIVAL-LIFEBE     08-23 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWINS-FESTIVAL-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWINS FESTIVAL MORE SIDESHOW THAN CELEBRATION
</HEADLINE>
  Includes color photo of two sets of twins
 By LAURA TAXEL 
 c.1999 Laura Taxel 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since my twin sons were born 13 years ago, my husband and I have
regularly been asked if we're taking them to the Twins Days
Festival, held each August in Twinsburg, Ohio. It is the nation's
largest public celebration of embryonic activity. Each year, since
1976, thousands of people from around the world with the amazing
distinction of having been born at the same time as one of their
siblings converge on the town, along with their families, friends,
and hordes of gawkers to honor this extraordinary confluence of
biochemistry.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays of course, thanks to the wonders of techno-fertility,
multiple births are just as likely to denote the outlay of big
bucks and the availability of a petri dish as they are a burst of
spontaneous ovarian excitement. But on Twins Days in Twinsburg, a
town founded by twin brothers, every look-alike is a VIP, and even
non-identical twins are welcome though they are encouraged to get
in the spirit of things by dressing alike.
</P>
<P>
   We avoided going for years. I didn't quite see the value in
hauling the kids out on a hot a summer day to remind them they
looked alike, a fact they admitted, but found relatively
uninteresting. They also were well aware that they were not the
only twins in the world _ there were five sets in their elementary
school, which makes me wonder if there's something in the water in
our town. Twin-ness, for them, was not an identity, and for us it
was a job not a pastime.
</P>
<P>
   But when the call came for my husband to photograph the event
for the New York Times, our good sense failed us, and we decided to
make it a family outing.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the novelty of twins and even triplets has paled in
comparison to the incidence of quads, quints, or sextuplets. It
takes at least five babies to get you a discount at K-mart, I
learned early on, or a van donation. The most attention being the
mother of twins has ever generated for me is a few sympathetic
words along the line of, ''I don't know how you do it,'' from
mothers who had their babies one at a time. I have always found the
remark irritating _ not only was the statement self-evident, but
what other choice did I have?
</P>
<P>
   I did not know I was pregnant with twins until the first baby
was delivered and the other guy was found. We have had plenty of
time to adjust, and we're pretty much used to it now. I admit it
was a shock initially, and there were a lot of little details to
work out. We had to prepare so many bottles to get through the
night that we called it the baby buffet, and corralling the two of
them once they became mobile was known as boy wrangling. Getting
them from the bath to bed was referred to as the baby rodeo. Get
the picture?
</P>
<P>
   But as they got older and we got smarter, it all became
relatively ordinary...they were our kids, not our twins, and it
seemed obvious that the best way to raise them was to treat them as
two distinctive individuals.
</P>
<P>
   This attitude stands in sharp contrast to the operating
philosophy behind the Twinsburg gala. It is, for all who are part
of a matched set, a time to gather and acknowledge that they belong
to a very special group; PCS, People Conceived Simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   There's a parade of twins, and contests for the most identical
twins _ an event that prompts many to go all out wardrobe-wise,
youngest set of multiples, and oldest. Promoters like to invoke the
fun-for-all carnival atmosphere, but I'd say sideshow is more
accurate. Might be why the National Enquirer shows up with some
regularity. I wish John Waters would focus on the Twin Talent Show
_ he's the only filmmaker I know of who could do it justice.
</P>
<P>
   The festival is a great shopping opportunity. Vendors peddle
useful items rarely found elsewhere: bumper stickers, baseball
hats, T-shirts, and tote-bags, all proclaiming the bearers'
particular affiliation with multiplicity. I myself would have
preferred two-for-one discounts on shoes and college tuition. There
were midway games galore, which of course ended up being twice as
expensive for our family and twice as profitable for the carnies
who ran them. The summer fest ambiance was reinforced by hawkers
offering a variety of food items that melt, stick, and smear, a
special delight, as I recall, for those of us who had to clean two
faces, four hands, and twenty fingers.
</P>
<P>
   The media shows up in droves to document the event, so posing is
a major activity for the multiples in attendance. The Twins Days
Festival Committee is well aware of how rare and compelling are
these images of individuals who share numerous physical
characteristics as well as taste in clothing. So they reserve the
right to charge freelance photographers and other commercial
enterprises a hefty licensing fee. Groups of two or three sets of
unrelated twins seemed especially popular, as were collections of
twin couples: identical brothers who hook up with identical
sisters. Seeing such foursomes standing together, I kept wondering
if they could mix-n-match with impunity, but that's probably just
me.
</P>
<P>
   The Committee urges multiples to register and pay a fee. This
entitles them to the privilege of being counted as an attendee,
thus assuring them a place in the annals of marketing history no
less significant than the number of McBurgers sold. They also
charge an admission fee and offer official souvenirs for sale. As
the mother of twins, I assumed I had a stake in the profits created
by the participation of families like ours, but after making
inquires, it turned out I was mistaken.
</P>
<P>
   The seminal moment for us was when our boys came face to face
with two elderly gentlemen dressed in tails and top hats. They
stared long and hard at these guys who truly were mirror images of
one another, then shrugged and walked away. When we were out of
earshot one said, ''This is really weird,'' and the other added,
''Can we go home now?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Laura Taxel is an Ohio-based free-lance writer.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this ``separate buy'' article, call
New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
(732) 390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LifeBeat
and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
