<HEADER>
A6276 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-R-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBAC     08-23 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV29-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 29)  
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; UNRAVELLING &LR;  By Elizabeth Graver. Harvest/Harcourt Brace, $13.
Aimee Slater is a nave New Hampshire farm girl who leaves home for
a factory job in the 1840s, becomes impregnated by a mechanic and
is exiled by her mother, which forces her to build a new life as an
outcast and struggle to overcome her bitterness. In 1997 in The New
York Times Book Review, Benjamin DeMott called this a ``grave,
winter-wise and absorbing first novel.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TITAN: THE LIFE OF JOHN D. ROCKEFELLER, SR. &LR;  By Ron Chernow.
Vintage, $16. The archcapitalist John D. Rockefeller Sr.
(1839-1937) is portrayed as a complex figure whose lifelong
devotion to making money was balanced by a deep religious
conviction and devotion to his family. Rockefeller's Marxist
analysis of the U.S. economy put him and his fledgling company,
Standard Oil, in ruthless pursuit of monopoly on an unparalleled
scale before he was 30. This evenhanded account, selected as one of
the best books of 1998 by the editors of The New York Times Book
Review, ``is a triumph of the art of biography,'' Jack Beatty
wrote. ``Unflaggingly interesting,'' it brings its subject to life
``through sustained narrative portraiture of the large-scale,
19th-century kind.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUMMER AT GAGLOW &LR;  By Esther Freud. Ecco, $15. Shifting back and
forth between contemporary London and Germany during and after
World War I, this novel explores the fracturing of a Jewish family
and how their notion of ``home'' is altered by their connection to
their former summer estate. The result is ``a near-seamless meshing
of family feeling, history and imagination,'' Deborah Mason wrote
last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE CLIMB: TRAGIC AMBITIONS ON EVEREST &LR;  By Anatoli Boukreev and
G. Weston DeWalt. St. Martin's Griffin, $13.95. This haunting
account of the 1996 storm that killed eight climbers from several
groups focuses on the role played by the driven Russian guide for
one of the teams, who saved three lives (and who died in an
avalanche the following year). In 1997 the reviewer Michael Parfit,
called the book ``raw but powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; I MAY BE SOME TIME: ICE AND THE ENGLISH IMAGINATION &LR; , by
Francis Spufford (Picador USA, $15), is a history of Arctic and
Antarctic exploration centering on the exploits of great British
adventurers like Robert Falcon Scott and James Cook. ``With his
book, just as with the endeavors of the polar pioneers, the journey
might be worth it for its own sake,'' Robert R. Harris wrote last
year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE UNDISCOVERED COUNTRY &LR;  By Samantha Gillison. Owl/Holt, $13.
In this first novel, an American researcher takes his wife and
young daughter to a remote village in Papua New Guinea, where their
fragile family unit is tested after the girl joins the local
culture, escaping more and more often into the rain forest. The
result is an ``exceptional story,'' Elizabeth Gaffney wrote last
year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE SPANISH INQUISITION: A HISTORICAL REVISION &LR;  By Henry Kamen.
Yale University, $15.95. The author argues that the popular image
of the Inquisition as a barbaric, all-powerful scourge is a
19th-century myth, and that the tribunal was actually weak and its
methods more humane than those of most secular courts. Last year
the reviewer Richard L. Kagan called this ``the best general book''
on the subject ``both for its range and its depth of information.''
</P>
<P>
   The same publisher has reissued  &UR; PHILIP OF SPAIN &LR;  ($17.95),
Kamen's biography of Philip II, who reigned during the Inquisition
in the 16th century and who is often portrayed as an intolerant
religious zealot. In presenting the monarch instead as a cultured
Renaissance prince, this nuanced portrait is ``a fine
achievement,'' Hugh Thomas wrote in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MAN WITHOUT A FACE: THE AUTOBIOGRAPHY OF COMMUNISM'S GREATEST
SPYMASTER &LR;  By Markus Wolf with Anne McElvoy. Public Affairs, $14.
The former chief of East German intelligence tells how he spent
more than 30 years planting moles, running agents, orchestrating
betrayals and living the secret life. He ``comes across as a clever
and cultivated man'' who nonetheless ``chose to follow a dark
star,'' David Wise wrote in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IDENTITY &LR;  By Milan Kundera. Harper Perennial, $13. The hero of
this dreamlike novel sends his girlfriend anonymous love letters to
pick up her spirits, with disastrous results. ``Kundera lucidly
discloses the psychological obsessions of the two lovers and how
these obsessions lead to repeated miscommunications,'' Robert
Grudin wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   The same publisher has reissued  &UR; LAUGHABLE LOVES &LR;  ($13), a
collection of the author's tales steeped in anger and fascination
with the communists running the show in Prague in the '60s. In 1974
the reviewer Paul Theroux called Kundera ``a magnificent
short-story writer'' whose ``best humor always seems to be rooted
in authority situations.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE HUNTERS &LR;  By James Salter. Vintage International, $13. The
author's first novel, originally published in 1956, is about a
fighter pilot's harrowing tour of duty in the Korean War and the
jealousies and competition among his fellow squadron members.
Praising the book, George Barrett urged readers to ``curl up for a
flight ... so `clear you can see tomorrow.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-99 0940EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
