about a psychologist counseling a boy who ``sees'' dead people, has
replaced ``Blair Witch'' as No. 1 at the box office. On television,
``Buffy, the Vampire Slayer,'' and ``Sabrina, the Teenage Witch''
reign in teen prime time.
</P>
<P>
   At national bookstore chains and on the Internet, titles about
alchemy, miracles, psychics, tarot, reincarnation and out-of-body
travel fly off the physical and virtual bookshelves.
</P>
<P>
   And most telling, people who call themselves witches get
interviewed by reporters even on days other than Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   Why? A growing number of scholars trace the phenomenon to
feminism, which has made women-led religions like Wicca more open
to public interest and acceptance, and to environmentalism, which
has made regard for Mother Earth a secular, and for some, a sacred
tenet.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, why are a growing number of scholars studying followers
of the occult? Robert S. Ellwood, who wrote ``Religious and
Spiritual Groups in Modern America'' (Prentice-Hall, 1986), a
textbook on alternative religions, said simply, ``Pagans aren't
boring.''
</P>
<P>
   From colonial days, Americans have been fascinated with the
occult, seeing in it both good, evil and the merely utilitarian.
Even at the height of the Salem witch trials in the 1690s, said J.
Gordon Melton, who wrote ``The Encyclopedia of American Religions''
(Gale Research, 1998), few New Englanders thought it odd that the
colonial governor of Connecticut had an alchemy laboratory in his
office.
</P>
<P>
   By the more rational 20th century, however, witches had become
both earthbound and unaccountably sexier, like Veronica Lake in ``I
Married a Witch'' and her later incarnation as Elizabeth Montgomery
on TV's ``Bewitched.'' The picture darkened in the late 1960s, with
films like ``Rosemary's Baby,'' which depicted a young woman
betrayed by a witches' conspiracy. Such films seemed to mirror a
politically chaotic age, especially for the biggest ``minority''
group, women.
</P>
<P>
   Modern feminism, a product of the early 1970s, promised to
empower women, said John K. Simmons, author of the coming ``Beliefs
and Believers,'' which will discuss women-led religions. Before the
women ministers and rabbis of today, the Wiccan movement bestowed
priesthood on both women and men, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And environmentalism, another product of the 1970s, Simmons
said, dovetailed naturally with the occult's emphasis on unseen
forces in the universe that must be brought into harmonious
balance.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a seeming paradox, many people in the Wiccan movement are
computer professionals, according to Ellwood, a retired religion
professor at the University of Southern California. ``But in a
world increasingly dominated by science and technology,'' he said,
``they want one corner left that is closer to nature and the
nonrational.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the occult cannot seem to shake its guilt by association
with the ultimate nonrational, the devil. ``I don't worship Satan,
who I don't think exists, but I do pray to the goddess of
creation,'' said Margot Adler, a New York correspondent for
National Public Radio and a Wiccan practitioner. ``Wicca is not
anti-Christian or pro-Christian, it's pre-Christian.''
</P>
<P>
   As for magic and spells, said Ms. Adler, whose 1979 book,
``Drawing Down the Moon (Penguin U.S.A.), helped popularize
earth-based religions, ``It's not uggah-buggah, it's attempting to
experience a larger physical reality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People say `witch' and think `Rosemary's Baby,''' she said.
``But where does that come from? Who writes the history books? The
victors. And paganism lost.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
