<P>
   1. TV INVADES BHUTAN! The wilfully isolated Himalayan mountain
kingdom of Bhutan has finally let television inside its borders.
Can its ancient Buddhist traditions survive the tube? By Peter de
Jonge. From The New York Times Magazine. Full-length (4,400 words)
+ edited article available.
_____________________________________________________________ 2.
BOYS AND BODY IMAGE There is a kind of timelessness to a teenager's
battle with body image, but in most accounts the teenager is female
and the issue is anorexia or bulimia. Yet as any psychologist
knows, and as any sufficiently evolved adult male could tell you,
boys have body-image problems too. In fact, the cultural messages
about an ideal male body, if not new, have grown more aggressive,
more widespread and more explicit in recent years. By Stephen S.
Hall. From The New York Times Magazine. Full-length (7,500 words) +
edited article available.
_____________________________________________________________ 3.
THE PSYCHE OF THE BULLIED Antrim, N.H., is a long way away from
Littleton, Colorado, as well as Conyers, Ga., where a 15-year-old
boy shot six classmates at his high school in May. But what it
shares with those other places, and with countless others across
the United States, is a brutally enforced teenage social structure.
Most boys live through it, suffer, survive. But the journey may be
especially deadly now, as the avalanche of new ``male identity''
literature attests. By Adrian Nicole LeBlanc. From The New York
Times Magazine. Full-length (4,500 words) + edited article
available.
_____________________________________________________________ 4.
COLONEL QUADDAFI INTERVIEW Four and a half months after the
suspension of UN sanctions against Libya, the 'guide of the
revolution' returns to the international political scene.
Disappointed by the Arab world, Colonel Mouammar Quaddafi is
turning towards Africa. In this rare interview he reveals his new
pan-African dream, ``The United States of Africa,'' gives his
version of the shooting down, in 1989, of the French DC10-UTA
plane, insists on improving relations with France and says that,
today, the gun can be thrown away in favour of peace and
development. By Pierre Prier. From Le Figaro. 4,000 words. (N/A
France, Italy, French-speaking Switzerland, French-speaking Canada,
Spain, Japan.)
