</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-AIR-SAFETY-REVIEW-655&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BACK-DOOR VIEW OF AIRLINE SAFETY 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(lb) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Right after ``What does it cost?'' the question
that almost every traveler planning a trip on a foreign airline
asks is ``Is it safe?'' The average ticket buyer can't get an
answer, and even if the Federal Aviation Administration knows, it
is barred by treaty from saying.
</P>
<P>
   But that's all about to change. An agreement between the
airlines and the Pentagon will take advantage of the industry's
growing use of code-sharing _ agreements enabling carriers to sell
tickets on one another's flights. The airlines will report to the
Defense Department on the operations of their code-share partners.
The result will make commercial interests, not governments, the
driving force behind safety measures.
</P>
<P>
   Code-sharing has given airlines a larger stake in one another's
safety. When a Swissair MD-11 crashed off Halifax, Nova Scotia, on
Sept. 2 last year, killing all 229 people aboard, Delta found that
it, not Swissair, was responsible for about two dozen passengers,
because it had sold them tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Then in April a Korean Air Lines cargo plane crashed in China,
killing five. It was KAL's sixth accident in 48 months, and Delta,
its U.S. code-share partner, ended the 4-year-old relationship. The
Defense Department reacted by putting KAL on its ``non-use'' list a
few days later, and halting the purchase of tickets from that
airline.
</P>
<P>
   This month the Defense Department, which buys 200,000 tickets
yearly on foreign airlines, took the process a giant step forward.
It has been looking for ways to judge the safety of all carriers
since 1985, when a chartered plane, an Arrow DC-8 carrying 248
members of the 101st Airborne Division, crashed at Gander Airport
in Newfoundland, and Congress ordered the department to review its
charter operators.
</P>
<P>
   This month it signed an agreement with the six U.S. airlines
that maintain extensive foreign code shares: The airlines promised
to review their foreign partners using a single set of standards
and report back.
</P>
<P>
   When carried out, the compilation, experts say, will be the
first in-depth, systematic evaluation of the performance of foreign
airlines available to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The six U.S. airlines _ American, Continental, Delta, Northwest,
Trans World and United _ have 160 code-share agreements among them,
representing the great majority of the world's airlines. Some have
already conducted evaluations, though not uniformly or rigorously;
now they will all apply the same yardstick.
</P>
<P>
   ``The set of standards is a book 3 or 4 inches thick,'' said
Mary Lou McHugh, assistant deputy undersecretary of defense for
transportation policy, and uniformly applying those standards,
derived from FAA rules, ``has impact for travelers worldwide.'' The
six carriers will review crew training, cockpit procedures,
maintenance systems, procedures for calculating a plane's weight
and fuel requirements, among dozens of other areas.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Transportation Department, which oversees the
FAA, will decide in the next few weeks whether to order the U.S.
carriers to do rigorous audits on the foreign carriers.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, American supervision of those carriers that fly to
the United States is minimal. After another KAL plane, a Boeing
747, crashed on approach to Guam in August 1997, FAA inspectors
testified at an investigative hearing that they do not check
foreign planes except for occasional visits to those visiting U.S.
airports to see if pilots have their licenses with them and if the
airplanes have U.S.-required gear like aisle lighting.
</P>
<P>
   The Department rule could require the six U.S. carriers to turn
over their audit results, which would make them government property
and subject to disclosure under the Freedom of Information Act.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed system will result in a kind of extraterritoriality
for U.S. flight safety rules, extending the FAA's reach to carriers
over which it has little or no control.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At the International Air Transport Association, David O'Connor,
the trade group's regional director for the United States, said
that the idea of code-share partners auditing one another was long
established, but that public release of such information was not.
O'Connor's group was trying to establish an audit system that
airlines would have to apply to join his organization.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers worldwide will reap the benefits. When the Defense
Department places a foreign carrier in ``non-use,'' it notifies the
State Department, which includes the information in its Consular
Information Sheets. Travelers can get them on the Web at
http://travel.state.gov/travel_warnings.html or by automated fax,
at (202) 647-3000 or by telephone at (202) 647-5225. They can also
get it directly from the Pentagon at (703) 697-2788.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. airlines say they are confident of their ability to
advise and evaluate. Clayton Foushee, vice president of flight
operations at Northwest Airlines, compared his company's
inspections of its code-share partners to large-scale ``white
glove'' inspections that the FAA occasionally conducts on U.S.
carriers. Northwest is a partner with KLM, Alitalia and Air China,
which is a mainland Chinese carrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are things we can do as one commercial entity to another
commercial entity,'' said Capt. Edmond Soliday, vice president for
safety at United. Advice from a fellow airline can be as useful as
a government regulation, he said, because ``You can't punish your
way into safety.'' His airline code-shares with Lufthansa, SAS,
Thai, Varig, Air New Zealand and All Nippon Airways.
</P>
<P>
   But safety improvements, Soliday said, will continue only as
long as the foreign airline wants them to. ``I can audit till I
turn blue, and I can't guarantee there will be no crashes,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-99 1013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
