   &UR; body-piercing &LR;  n. The perforation of body parts for the purpose
of attaching a piece of jewelry
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bose-Einstein Condensate &LR;  n. A state of matter that forms below
a critical temperature in which all bosons that comprise the matter
fall into the same quantum state
</P>
<P>
   &UR; face time &LR;  n. Time spent interacting in the presence of or in
the same location as another or others: putting in face time in the
office instead of working at home
</P>
<P>
   &UR; home-school &LR;  tr. v. To instruct (a pupil, for example) in an
educational program outside of established schools, especially in
the home. intr. vs. To provide educational instruction in a
homeschool
</P>
<P>
   &UR; netiquette &LR;  n. Etiquette practiced or advocated in electronic
communication over a computer network
</P>
<P>
   &UR; nuceloside analogue &LR;  n. Any of a group of antiviral drugs,
including AZT, DDC, and DDI, that interfere with the activity of
the viral enzyme reverse transcriptase and are used in the
treatment of HIV
</P>
<P>
   &UR; soft money &LR;  n. Political donations made in such a way as to
avoid federal regulations or limits, as by donating to a party
organization rather than to a particular candidate or campaign
</P>
<P>
   &UR; xenotransplantation &LR;  n. The surgical transfer of cells,
tissues, or especially whole organs from one species to another
</P>
<P>
   &UR; zine &LR;  n. An inexpensively produced, self-published, underground
publication
</P>
