<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NEW-WORDS-REVIEW-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW WORDS TO SOME, BUT NOT TO OTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(lh) 
 ELIN SCHOEN BROCKMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The people who compile dictionaries always have ``news'' (n. pl.
Oxford English Dictionaries' in-house word for new words). But
neologisms are not always newly minted. Take ``yada yada yada,''
which long before ``Seinfeld'' was used by Lenny Bruce.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Sheidlower, the senior editor in charge of new words at
Random House, became convinced of yada yada yada's staying power
not only by its history, but also by the existence of
well-established parallel expressions (blah blah blah, for
instance). He put it in the 1996 Random House Webster's College
Dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Agnes, editor in chief of Webster's New World College
Dictionary, excluded yada yada yada from his 1996 edition. And
having tracked a decline in its use, he is glad he did. ``This year
we would have had to take it out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   New words help give each dictionary its personality. The
differences among them may not be readily apparent to the average
reader, but when the editors of four dictionaries provided their
unabridged new word lists for comparison, there was no overlap. One
of the editors, on hearing just six words from the list of a
competitor, was able to guess its identity immediately.
</P>
<P>
   What follows is only a brief sampling of the news. The fourth
edition of Webster's New World College Dictionary, the only one
represented here for which a final count is available, because it
has been published, added 7,000 entries. One of them, Nunavut, just
made the deadline, because the editors had to wait until Canada
officially declared the new territory of Nunavut.
</P>
<P>
   There are always late-breaking news, words waiting to be
accepted. Oxford U.S. Dictionaries, for instance, which publishes
several dictionaries including the Oxford American Dictionary and
Language Guide, has this on its waiting list, pending more
evidence: ``Fuggedaboudit.''
</P>
<P>
   WEBSTER'S NEW WORLD COLLEGE DICTIONARY, FOURTH EDITION
(published July 1999)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bubba &LR;  (also b--) (Chiefly South) (Slang)  &UR; 1 &LR;  Brother:
sometimes used as a familiar term of address  &UR; 2 &LR;  close friend  &UR; 3 &LR;  a
man of the Southern U.S., variously characterized as easygoing,
companionable, assertively masculine, uneducated, bigoted, violent,
etc.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 4x4 &LR;  n., pl.  &UR; 4x4s &LR;  or  &UR; 4x4's &LR;  A four-wheel drive vehicle
</P>
<P>
   &UR; gigaflops &LR;  n., pl.  &UR; -flops &LR;  A unit of processing speed in a
computer, equal to one billion flops
</P>
<P>
   &UR; headbanger &LR;  n. A devotee, fan, or performer of heavy metal; see
headbanging
</P>
<P>
   &UR; pedestrianize &LR;  vt.  &UR; -ized &LR; ,  &UR; -izing &LR;  To make (an area, esp. a
street) accessible to pedestrians only by closing to use by
automobiles, buses, etc.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; problematize &LR;  vt.  &UR; -tized &LR; ,  &UR; -tizing &LR;  To demonstrate, to be
unsettled or uncertain, or more complex than originally assumed or
regarded; show to be problematic
</P>
<P>
   &UR; pumped &LR;  adj. (slang) Full of confidence, enthusiasm, etc.:
pumped up
</P>
<P>
   &UR; reality check &LR;  An instance of confronting or acknowledging the
facts about something and thus dispelling unrealistic notions or
expectations
</P>
<P>
   &UR; satisfice &LR;  vi.  &UR; -ficed &LR; ,  &UR; -ficing &LR; , coined by H.A. Simon
(United States social scientist and economist), satis(fy) +
(suf)fice. To be satisfied with a minimum or merely satisfactory
level of performance, profitability, etc. rather than a maximum or
optimum level.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; semi-staged &LR;  adj. Produced with the use of only a limited
number of props, costumes, etc.: said as of an opera staged for an
exhibition performance, in a concert hall, etc.
