<HEADER>
A6355 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-KOREAN-AND-AFRICAN-AM     08-23 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREAN-AND-AFRICAN-AMERICAN-RELATIONS-NU-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER SHARED TRAGEDY: WHERE KOREAN-AND AFRICAN-AMERICAN
COMMUNITIES INTERSECT 
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material is for use only by
arrangement with New York Times Syndicate/Special features. For
purchase information see end of text. 
 By ANGELA E. OH  
 c. 1999 KoreAm Journal 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The July 4 weekend was marred with the news of several gunshot
victims and two deaths: Ricky Byrdsong and Won-Joon Yoon.
</P>
<P>
   Both were the victims of a senseless shooting spree by Benjamin
``August'' Smith _ an avowed white supremacist and disciple of the
World Church of the Creator. There were numerous other injuries
inflicted upon victims of multiple ages, races, religions,
occupations and economic class. Smith's rampage was an ``equal
opportunity'' expression of racial hatred and rage.
</P>
<P>
   Now that deaths and injuries have been inflicted and racial and
religious hatred has been uncovered as the main motivation for the
violence, people want to talk. Sadly, in the face of crisis, there
always emerges a glimmer of understanding that our collective
responsibility begins with engagement in dialogue. These kinds of
conversations are too often postmortem discussions that produce
reactionary political measures that we quickly regret adopting. We
should resist going in that direction now.
</P>
<P>
   For Korean-Americans and African-Americans, this incident
reminds us again of how inextricably tied together we are for
better, for worse. People still ask how relations are between our
communities, as though a simple explanation or answer might be
readily produced.
</P>
<P>
   Korean-Americans and African-Americans alike can recall that the
media made a big deal about ``tensions'' and ``conflicts'' among us
just a few years ago. Indeed, some early, misinformed analyses of
the 1992 Riots suggested that Black/Korean conflicts were the main
cause of the four-day implosion. This was a convenient way to
sidestep more difficult issues: high unemployment, low confidence
in the police, lack of investment in the inner city and rapidly
shifting demographics in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there is no funding for school-based curriculum to teach
kids about what racial and religious intolerance has produced
historically. There are plenty of programs that have been developed
by organizations and school district curriculum development teams,
but the problem has been a lack of funds to implement these
programs. No one is raising the fact that politicians keep saying
they want to do something, and yet, not a single legislative action
has been taken to specifically target implementation.
</P>
<P>
   We are passing legislation to criminalize hate crimes, but the
funds to investigate and prosecute these offenses need to be
increased. Training of law enforcement personnel should be enhanced
and consideration should be given to partnerships with
community-based organizations, which are probably the most likely
places where new immigrants will turn for help if confronted with
hate violence.
</P>
<P>
   The intersection between race and economic status is also a
reality that must be considered in the dialogue that people are
calling for today. There has been no leadership to examine so many
questions.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, how and why does redlining continue to plague
low-income areas? And once again, who do you find there? In Los
Angeles, African-Americans and Korean-Americans continue to meet
one another in places where the economic desperation takes its toll
on everyone.
</P>
<P>
   It is sadly classic: a foreign-born, Ph.D. student of Korean
descent, a native-born African-American who succeeded despite
generations of racial bigotry, brought together in sacrilegious
death. No matter what skin color, language, cultural roots,
immigration status, age or socioeconomic status _ they were lives
lost that remind us that there is much work still left to do for
both communities, inextricably tied together by our common
humanity.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Angela E. Oh is a commissioner with the L.A. City Human
Relations Commission and a former member of the Advisory Board to
President Clinton's Initiative on Race)
</P>
<P>
