<HEADER>
A6372 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT24-COX     08-23 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scooter dream better than reality
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Long before Brando and his ``wild ones''
roared across movie screens, scratching, belching, and terrorizing
small towns, kids growing up in Miami in the late '40s had an
outlaw bunch known as ``The Springs Guys.'' They were too cool for
words.
</P>
<P>
   School mornings, minutes before the last bell, these dashing
young men on wheels would whiz down Flagler Street, whip around the
corner, and single-file their way into the Miami High parking lot.
Kickstands were carelessly heeled into the sand as the drivers,
crooked grins in place, smoothed their crew cuts and checked for
audience appreciation. Girl hearts could be heard cracking wide
open all the way to Florida City.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, The Springs Guys weren't really a bunch _ just Dickie
Stamer, Jim Whitford, and Robert Filer. They didn't look much like
outlaws - no chains or boots - just jeans and penny loafers and as
for the roar - well, they didn't. They putt-putted. That's what
Cushman scooters did.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. Girlish fantasy took over when The Springs Guys made
the scene. We drooled from a distance and tried to imagine
ourselves zipping around town with total abandon on one of those
daredevil machines, arms tightly wrapped around Dickie, Jimmy, or
Bobby.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, it never happened. Nobody ever offered to scooter my
books and me home from school, and even if one of them had, I was
sworn to say no. My
</P>
<P>
   father had laid down the law about his daughter riding around on
the back of one of those ``darn-fool'' contraptions. My social life
was as big a flop as my
</P>
<P>
   curls in the Florida humidity.
</P>
<P>
   And it didn't help when Peggy snagged herself a guy with a
scooter. One day she was catching the bus with the rest of us and
the next - there she was riding sidesaddle on the back of
Clifford's Cushman, books in her lap and one arm around his waist.
My friends and I stood dejected on the sidelines; the sight was
just too romantic for words. But one day the enchantment died.
</P>
<P>
   Clifford wheeled into the parking lot with his lady love in tow,
but instead of her usual carefree pageboy blowing in the wind,
Peggy's hair was in curlers.
</P>
<P>
   Horrors! We were shocked, but secretly delighted to see the
object of our envy looking like Ma Kettle. The romance kind of fell
apart from there. One morning
</P>
<P>
   a few days later, Peggy slumped into the downstairs girls' rest
room looking like she'd been dragged through a knothole backwards.
Her best blue skirt was
</P>
<P>
   torn and her saddle oxfords had skid marks. Seems Clifford lost
her in a tight turn. He swore it was an accident. End of romance.
</P>
<P>
   A few months later, a different cute guy on a Cushman developed
big eyes for my friend Jeanne. Every afternoon after school Tommy
would putt up her
</P>
<P>
   driveway and hang around being cool and saying dumb stuff.
Jeanne didn't particularly like the attention - she already had a
boyfriend - so she shoved me in his
</P>
<P>
   direction. Tommy was less than thrilled but I guess he figured
since he'd already bought the gas he might as well take somebody
for a ride. He asked me.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing full well that lightning was going to strike me dead on
the spot, I accepted. Tommy helped me onto the back of the scooter,
warned me to keep my
</P>
<P>
   leg clear of the exhaust pipe, and putted into the sunset.
Halfway around the block I slid off and wrecked one elbow and a
loafer.
</P>
<P>
   Gentleman that he was, Tommy came back for me. Two houses down,
I fell off again and ripped my dress. Tommy turned around,
valiantly retrieved the
</P>
<P>
   heap in the road that was me, and aimed the Cushman for Jeanne's
drive. That's when I burned my leg on the exhaust.
</P>
<P>
   About dinnertime I came limping home, practicing one big lie
after another in an attempt to explain why I looked like I had just
gone three rounds with King
</P>
<P>
   Kong. Mother said nothing. Daddy asked about school. I kept my
mouth shut and wondered if everybody had gone blind since
breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   So much for life in the fast lane.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or email: eschuett(at)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
