<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 11:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6375 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN25-CO     08-23 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN25-COX-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Illegal immigrants burden school districts
 &HT;    (For release Aug. 25, 1999.)
 &HT;    (Eds: Adds dropped word ``illegal'' in 6th graf.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The torrent of boat people planning the trip to South
Florida's shores now keeps an anxious ear to the weather reports;
it is the time of year when hurricanes are prowling the Atlantic
and Caribbean. It should be presumed that the heavy flow of the
past few months will reduce to less than a trickle until season's
end in December, when it will pick up again.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there will be those who will attempt the journey _ often
engineered by professional smugglers _ and if there's something
more perilous than chancing the Straits of Florida in a small
vessel in decent weather, it's trying it while a hurricane or
tropical storm is bearing down.
</P>
<P>
   Since the rise of Fidel Castro, Florida has been haven for
hundreds of thousands of Cubans and Haitians fleeing awful
existences. Relatively few among them were verifiably enemies of
their states, at least not in a political-activist sense. Most came
for a job, a meal, a roof over their heads and an education for
their children.
</P>
<P>
   In near-border cities all along the southern tier of the U.S.,
Caribbean and Mexican illegal immigrants have impacted most on the
school systems.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, seeking relief from its overcrowded classrooms, the
Anaheim, Calif., School Board approved a resolution to bill the
originating countries of illegal immigrants for the immigrants'
education. The plan is to have the U.S. government pay the school
district, then reclaim the expenditure from the foreign government.
Can you imagine the Mexican government, or Castro, pulling out
checkbooks for this? The resolution has as much chance of advancing
as did Hillary Clinton's health blueprint.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, what that school board did in its frustration was
to reach out, haphazardly, for help. It was a message that illegal
immigration deluges are cutting deeply into the pockets of public
education. The Immigration and Naturalization Service estimates
that of the 3.9 million illegal immigrants in the U.S., 2 million
live in California.
</P>
<P>
   While Florida cannot measure up to those numbers, it
nevertheless has been greatly impacted. Miami has become a Hispanic
city, the schools are teaching bilingually, the classrooms being
stuffed with immigrant children.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Florida Gov. Lawton Chiles filed suit in federal court
for the state to be reimbursed approximately $1.5 billion, which,
the suit claims, was the sum of state and local funds spent on
health care and schooling for illegal immigrants. The suit failed
at every step up the line; in 1996 the U.S. Supreme Court refused
to hear it.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, what we have are two problems that need to be
dealt with. The first is the basic issue of illegal immigrants _
now termed in a political curtsy as ``undocumented aliens.'' Shall
America ever regain its borders? Is there a statute of limitations
on that Statue of Liberty inscription asking for ``your tired
masses''?
</P>
<P>
   That issue lands at the doorstep of the president of the United
States, who, on advice or whim, seemingly can change immigration
policy overnight. It began with Lyndon Johnson's Cuban Immigration
Act in 1965, and has fluctuated back and forth _ depending on what
squeaking wheel was the loudest _ through six presidents.
</P>
<P>
   I read an interesting story the other day in a 1945 issue of The
New York Times in which Greece, besieged by fleeing Jewish illegal
immigrants, subtracted their numbers from the approved quota of
Jews into Greece.
</P>
<P>
   As an example, we allow 20,000 Cubans a year to legally enter
the U.S. That's not a bad amount. But what would be the case if we
began subtracting from that quota, the numbers who came in
illegally? Answer: Castro couldn't care less, the Miami exile
community would go apoplectic and the non-Cubans in the community
would hold a party.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, the borders are closed. In reality, the welcome mat
is out. Just touch U.S. territory _ swim ashore, hop the Rio
Grande, sneak over the fence _ and your kid can be in public school
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   And that's where the second problem arises: funding education
for districts heavily impacted by immigrants; not only illegal
immigrants but by processed immigrants as well. I did not see the
Congress or the president, flush with all that excess money, make
any move to relieve the Anaheim school district voluntarily, or the
Miami district.
</P>
<P>
   The financial impact of immigrants on a school system can be
huge. When the federal government sets the policy by which the
immigrants are accepted into the U.S., it needs to carry its share
of financial responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
