<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 11:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6376 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-LANE-COLUMN-COX     08-23 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lucky guy goes for a spin
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ I exhaled and told myself how lucky I was.
The car had started again with only the slightest flick of the key.
</P>
<P>
   The car was parked in an inch of mud about 5 feet from the edge
of a pine forest, not far from a drainage ditch and about 15 yards
from the road.
</P>
<P>
   The road had turned. I had not. In a sudden, driving rain, the
car was frictionlessly suspended on the road's slick, watery
surface and was not responding either to brakes, the steering wheel
or my adamantly delivered suggestions. It was hydroplaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hydroplaning'' is one of those bland technical terms that
describes the physics of a situation without getting across its
essence. Its essence was that I was moving sideways at about 50
miles an hour before spinning like a tilt-a-whirl. The pine trees
smudged past the windshield while oncoming cars honked their horns
to alert me that driving sideways on a county road is a serious
breach of driver etiquette.
</P>
<P>
   I spun once, then twice, as the car left the road and slid
across the wet grass on the shoulder. It jumped the drainage ditch
with a thump that felt like a punch in the stomach.
</P>
<P>
   There was a spray of mud and I found myself parked. Facing the
right way. No major damage except for torn-up tires.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky me. As a reporter, I had spent many bored hours
translating accident reports from police jargon to English. I wrote
about cars pulled out of drainage ditches in one-car accidents. I
transcribed official non-explanations like: ``the driver lost
control of the vehicle.'' I chatted with highway patrolmen in the
rain who helpfully pointed out tire marks and in flat voices
theorized about ``oversteering'' and shook their head at ``driver
error.'' I sometimes passed copies of these briefs to obit writers.
Very bad things can happen to a car doing the
tilt-a-whirl-maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   My case was also one of driver error. First: The driver let his
tires go bald, something that has been the case for most of my
adult life. Second: When the car started sliding, the driver
reacted quickly and decisively; which is to say I did everything
precisely wrong. You're not supposed to brake hard. You're not
supposed to keep turning the wheel when nothing happens. This is
basic high-school driver's ed.
</P>
<P>
   So, I felt lucky. I hadn't died. The car started again. I was
even able to limp to a nearby tire place.
</P>
<P>
   There are others who have a more exacting definition of luck.
They would see sitting in a car parked in the mud and listing at 15
degrees after spinning across a drainage ditch as something
UNlucky.
</P>
<P>
   It was the same way when lightning struck my house. I felt lucky
my house hadn't caught fire. Others have trouble connecting the
concept of luck with the idea of being hit by lightning.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, when my wallet was lost or stolen _ I still don't
know which _ I felt lucky that the cards were accounted for, that
it held only three dollars and that a person carrying my driver's
license didn't shoot the president. Lucked out again.
</P>
<P>
   When you happen onto a situation rich in disastrous
possibilities and come out unscathed, I consider that luck. A lot
of people think of luck as avoiding all situations rich in
disastrous possibilities. That seems like a boring kind of luck. A
no-hits, no-runs, no-errors kind of luck.
</P>
<P>
   Others are very demanding and only see luck in situations when
good things fall from the sky. Lottery luck. Such connoisseurs of
luck tend to feel unlucky all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shallow men believe in luck,'' wrote Emerson in one of his
more frosty and New Englandy moments. ``Strong men believe in cause
and effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so. But that kind of thinking denies you the exhilaration
of the close call. A thrill that's so life-enriching, that we
sometimes talk ourselves into believing that many near-misses came
closer would seem immediately apparent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have been on that plane,'' we tell ourselves and are
grateful to be alive. I could have run into a tree. I was standing
there only an hour before. ...
</P>
<P>
   Lucky ducks, all of us.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is associate editor at The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. E-mail: marklane(at)n-jcenter.com. Web Site:
http://www2.gdi.net/(tilde)marklane/index.html.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-99 1118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
