<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 11:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6382 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-INTERACTIVE-TV24-COX     08-23 1471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERACTIVE-TV24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PLAY IT AGAIN
 &HT;    Or, maybe, for the first time. A computer called TiVo acts like
a brainy VCR _ even fetching programs it thinks you might like to
watch.
 &HT;    WITH ILLUSTRATION
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Call him TiVo, the television genie. By whatever name,
he makes all of us, the couch potatoes and the no-time-for-TV
crowd, take a brand-new look at the medium and its entertainment
potential.
</P>
<P>
   Calling itself ``the new face of television,'' TiVo Personal
Television Service is a marriage of computers and video. It's a
combination of hardware and software that allows alert viewers to
take charge of TV watching. TiVo may be the first of a new
generation of devices that will change the way you watch
television.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, TiVo is like a VCR. But recording is only a tiny part
of its game. TiVo does the sampling and channel surfing for you.
With a little help from you, it ``studies'' and analyzes your
viewing habits. Then it looks weeks ahead to spot shows and movies
it thinks you will like. It can record and file away up to 14 hours
or more of shows you just ``must'' watch, as soon as you clear some
time.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, however, TiVo lets you watch television in a way
now known only to the handful of households with
</P>
<P>
   digital television, such as TV by satellite, BellSouth's
wireless cable or the promising but seldom seen upgraded service
from MediaOne.
</P>
<P>
   But even if you have digital TV, TiVo offers a few wrinkles that
cutting edge, early adopter households will find valuable.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some samples.
</P>
<P>
   You're watching the Braves in a tight game. The bases are loaded
and Chipper Jones steps to the plate. At that
</P>
<P>
   very moment the phone rings, and it could be the boss who
promised to call and chat about that raise.
</P>
<P>
   No problem. You hit the pause button and settle, unworried, into
the conversation with the boss. When finished, after a minute or
two or even 30 minutes, you hit the pause button again and
televised play resumes _ right where you left it.
</P>
<P>
   You're richer for it.
</P>
<P>
   TiVo feeds the live program signal onto a hard drive, not a
tape, and the viewer's signal comes off the hard drive with a delay
of a second or two.
</P>
<P>
   And so, when you resume watching Chipper bat, you have the
option of staying with the delayed program _ all the way to the end
of the game _ or you can fast-forward and see other highlights you
missed. Or you can hit a catch-up button and instantly go ahead to
the live program.
</P>
<P>
   Because you are watching a stored signal, you can do all sorts
of fun things to the ballgame, or movie, or whatever you watch. You
can pause, you can do a replay, a replay in slow motion, or run the
show backward and watch it over again.
</P>
<P>
   At any moment during the show, you can hit a button and see
background information about the program, such as the cast of
characters, a description of the plot, the running time. (No more
wondering _ is that REALLY Errol Flynn as a young boy?) This
background information is especially helpful in browsing the
channels and getting a quick read on what you see.
</P>
<P>
   Also, at any point you can punch up a full program guide
superimposed lightly on the show being watched, so you can see
what's playing on other channels or what's coming up later in the
day.
</P>
<P>
   For me, one of the most engaging features was the ease in
ordering TiVo to ``record'' programs in the future, without
reference to code numbers. You simply type ``ER'' or ``Law and
Order'' or ``Heat of the Night,'' and the machine automatically
pops up a list of the upcoming showings of the programs, including
new presentations, reruns or whatever. You order the taping or
command TiVo to record every showing of the program in the future.
And TiVo finds the program every day, or every week, even if it
changes time or channels.
</P>
<P>
   TiVo, with viewer input, compiles his ``to-do'' list, which can
be examined, modified or enlarged at any time.
</P>
<P>
   The system obviously allows the couch potato to settle even
deeper into the cushions. But much more importantly, it allows the
busy person to watch the few selected programs she cares about, and
it provides the flexibility to watch them at convenient times.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you forget to watch that edition of ``20/20'' and think
of it only when somebody mentions it around the water cooler, you
simply go home and find that TiVo is on the case and has already
recorded and preserved it.
</P>
<P>
   Even the household with the most sophisticated digital system
can also benefit from having TiVo the computer, the modern-day Hal,
keep an orderly schedule of upcoming viewing.
</P>
<P>
   And here's the way it does that.
</P>
<P>
   TiVo's remote control allows the viewer to vote a thumbs up or a
thumbs down on any program watched, and TiVo keeps a record,
forming a profile of what kinds of programs the viewer likes. As it
``learns,'' it takes the initiative to publish lists likely to be
watched with approval, and it even voluntarily records some of them
so that the viewer can watch at a convenient time later.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of TiVo is hot and getting hotter. First of all, it is
not the only ``personal TV service.'' A competitor called ReplayTV
is coming on strong. Both have received sizable investments from
various businesses in both the television and computer fields.
TiVo, which has plans to go public, has been a source of investment
by America Online, CBS, Walt Disney, Comcast and Cox
Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the prices. You can get the ReplayTV Model 2001, with
10 hours of storage, for $699; the Model 2003, with 14 hours of
storage, for $899; and the Model 2004, with 28 hours of storage,
for $1,499. Orders can be placed from the Web site at
www.replaytv.com/home/index
</P>
<P>
   .shtml. Unlike TiVo, there's no monthly charge.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, TiVo has been valuable already. Thanks to TiVo, I
was introduced to ``The Sopranos,'' the quirky and engaging HBO
series with the fine writing and the absolutely perfect acting. And
I have discovered ``ER'' again.
</P>
<P>
   TiVo keeps an accurate record of what's coming up by dialing up
every night, after the household has retired, and accessing by
toll-free phone call the system's main databases, which are updated
continuously with new program information and program changes.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore TiVo, in a quiet way, is the household's authority on
programming, ready to share it at any time or ready to prepare a
menu of things that are popular.
</P>
<P>
   And so, when you turn on the TV in the morning, TiVo presents a
menu of things it recommends, things it has recorded and filed to
be seen on a moment's notice.
</P>
<P>
   It IS a genie.
</P>
<P>
   It's a fascinating service and an interesting piece of hardware.
But the inventor, Jim Barton, makes no bones about what's closest
to his heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm perfectly willing to license the hardware to anybody who
can help us get this system out there,'' he said in an interview.
``What interests me most is the service, something we can
cultivate, refine and expand over the years and make increasingly
valuable to the viewers.''
</P>
<P>
   TiVo does raise some issues for traditional TV broadcasters. For
instance, the machine allows the viewer watching recorded material
to bypass commercials with startling efficiency. People who sell
expensive advertising time on networks and cable have no reason to
be pleased with that, and there has been grumbling.
</P>
<P>
   But others see the attractiveness of the new system possibly
building TV audiences in general, clearly a boon for an industry
that has been in a funk for years as it tries to compete with other
forms of entertainment and information.
</P>
<P>
   By and large, the industry seems willing to partner with TiVo.
Philips, DirecTV and TiVo are in partnership to develop a new
satellite TV system with TiVo and DirecTV programming in one box.
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts predict many new television sets may be built
with the TiVo system already installed. TiVo is still in the
process of organizing retail distribution networks for sales of the
system, but it can be purchased directly from the Internet at
www.tivo.com.
</P>
<P>
   The machine with capacity to store 14 hours of programming sells
for $499, and another with 30 hours of capacity sells for $999. The
service that keeps updating the television program via toll-free
number costs $9.95 per month or $99 a year. Or you can pay $199
once, with no more payments unless you purchase another TiVo
receiver.
</P>
<P>
   For some experts, TiVo presents the first real system for
television a la carte, allowing each viewer to spoon up the
preferred TV diet for the day, each day.
</P>
<P>
   The smartest operators in television are at work, figuring how
TiVo and similar systems will be sure to put them on that menu.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
