r l BC-CYBERSCENE24-COX     08-23 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERSCENE24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CYBERSCENE COLUMN
 &HT;    A world tour can start anywhere
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is, after all, the World Wide Web _ not the neighborhood Web
or the American Web.
</P>
<P>
   It's still a fast and surprisingly satisfying way to tour the
world _ zapping at the click of a mouse from New Zealand to
Newfoundland. There are, of course, thousands of sites filled with
the kind of information you'd find by reading an atlas and
encyclopedia. But for a really interesting world tour via
cyberspace, try to visit some of the out-of-the-way places ... the
sort of places where the locals hang out.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start, faithful to that theme, at a site you probably have
never visited. It's the official page of the Auckland, New Zealand,
city government at akcity.govt.nz/. Among other things, you'll
learn there's an Andy Warhol exhibit over at the Auckland Art
Gallery, the City Council takes the Year 2000 computer problem
seriously and has worked hard since 1997 to make sure there are no
serious problems, and that _ like every place else _ taxes keep
going up.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe by now, you're getting the idea behind this world tour.
Instead of learning the population, chief industry and history of a
city or country, we'll use the Web today to learn what it is like
to live in a different country and get the feel of traveling in
cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   So let's spend a little time in a very beautiful place, the Cape
Verde islands, off the coast of Africa. Pop on over to users
</P>
<P>
   .erols.com/kauberdi/, and before you read a word click on the
link to see the photographs. Just spend a moment enjoying the view.
This is an archipelago that was populated by the Portuguese, slaves
from the Guinea Coast, Muslims and others beginning shortly after
its discovery by navigator Antonio da Nola in 1457. The language
there is Papiamentu, which is a form of Creole. There's a link
where you can learn enough of the language to sound silly. Bon bini
is welcome, kon ta bai is hello and bon dia is good morning.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to go to out-of-the-way places geographically to
get an insider's view of a country. For instance, a visit to the
site at www.open.gov.uk/ in the United Kingdom can take you deep
into an inquiry about an event that happened Jan. 30, 1972, in
Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   It started as a civil rights march and ended in the deaths of 13
people, with 13 more wounded. Click on the link on this page for
the Bloody Sunday Inquiry, and you will instantly be immersed in a
government inquiry into what went wrong that Sunday, when British
soldiers began firing into the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers, of course, are a good way to learn about the
day-to-day activities in a country or region. The Israeli newspaper
Haaretz is online at www3
</P>
<P>
   .haaretz.co.il/eng/htmls/11
</P>
<P>
   .htm. You will be given the choice of reading the paper in
Hebrew or English.
</P>
<P>
   The real interest here is in the small stories, not the big ones
about the region that you'd see in this newspaper. Part of the
daily fare here is about bombs that were defused, bombs that
weren't defused and terrorist activities. There is even a column
that treats ways to travel the world, using the Net.
</P>
<P>
   SITES IN THIS ARTICLE:
</P>
<P>
   akcity.govt.nz/
</P>
<P>
   users.erols.com/kauberdi/
</P>
<P>
   www.open.gov.uk/
</P>
<P>
   www3.haaretz.co.il/eng/htmls
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
