<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 11:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6393 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NETWATCH24-COX     08-23 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NETWATCHER COLUMN
 &HT;    Marketers want to know all about you
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There he was, the Beastie Boys' rapper Mike D., dressed in the
rocker/rapper/slacker uniform of T-shirt and jeans, slumped before
a microphone in a meeting room at the Marriott Marquis in New York
City, talking about leveraging databases to increase marketing
opportunities on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Rock stars aren't talking about the Web as a medium for artistic
expression, but as a medium for purchasing this outpouring of
artistic expression.
</P>
<P>
   The recording industry is struggling with a variety of money-
and Web-related issues, thanks to the explosion in digital music
download technology. It is desperately searching for ways to bring
loyal fans to the Web with credit cards in hand to purchase music,
concert tickets and other items.
</P>
<P>
   It seems a little surreal to hear the Beastie Boys and other
music stars talk about how to get their fans to buy things from
them on the Web. It's hard to imagine Bob Dylan or Diana Ross
talking about database marketing and optimizing retail
opportunities, but the music business is in a serious turnaround
because of the Web. Stars have become brands as well as artists,
and they want to turn the people who love them offline into a
marketing bonanza online. Even Tom Petty offers digital downloads
on Amazon.com in hopes of selling CDs both on and off the Web.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds cold and calculated, because musicians are supposed to
be above this sort of thing, but personal information is rapidly
becoming the Web's gold standard. Everyone from Amazon.com to The
New York Times knows that information is the Internet's most
valuable currency.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Nisenholtz, the Web guru who oversees online operations
for New York Times Co., has been talking about the value of
databases for years. Anyone who wants to read the Times online has
to register first.
</P>
<P>
   It's not complicated and only takes a few minutes. The Times
doesn't sell the information. It uses it to show advertisers the
market it offers and to develop new products.
</P>
<P>
   Big Brother isn't watching yet, but he would definitely like to
be. Most Web sites realized a long time ago that no one is willing
to pay money to look at Web sites. They are forced to rely on
advertising dollars and electronic commerce to keep the money
coming in and their sites up on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   If all this ``data mining'' _ as they call it in the direct
marketing industry _ works, you'll be getting information you
actually want, about CDs you might buy or vacations you might take.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium still struggling to figure out ways to make money,
gathering personal information seems like the ideal way to charm
both users and advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is, Web sites are totally and completely dependent
on you, the surfer. A researcher for Arbitron, the prominent media
measurement service, says she always lies on online applications.
``There's no reason why anyone on the Web needs to know a single
thing about me,'' she says. This from a woman who gathers data for
a living but won't tell Amazon what books she likes.
</P>
<P>
   In return for providing a Web site with information your spouse,
best friend and mother might not know, you will get frequent notes
from the places at which you have registered.
</P>
<P>
   All it takes is one visit to Amazon.com to see exactly how this
works. Should you decide to buy a second book from Amazon, you'll
be greeted with a cheery personalized ``Welcome Back!'' followed by
a link to a list of recommended titles based on your last purchase.
If the books aren't to your liking, you can tell Amazon what sort
of books you do like, so you can receive recommendations better
suited to your interests.
</P>
<P>
   Give your e-mail address to Salon, the online magazine, and
you'll get a weekly roundup of new articles and essays. The New
York Times on the Web will let you know when it has a special
section, Delta Air Lines will send you a list of cheap flights out
of town this weekend, and Lands' End will offer you a weekly
overstocks newsletter of clearance items.
</P>
<P>
   However, the interesting thing about this is that rappers, rock
stars and media giants can yak all they want to about the value of
databases, but if you don't give them the information, they won't
have any. They are dependent upon your willingness to provide
information about yourself to Web sites you frequent. They need to
know as much information as you are willing to give, from where you
live to how old your kids are. You, the Web surfer, hold all the
cards in this online marketing game.
</P>
<P>
   It's your choice to dispense or withhold personal information.
If filling out online forms makes you nervous, don't do it. It will
just force Web marketers and folks like the Beastie Boys to think
of other ways to get your attention and your money.
</P>
<P>
   PSunday, Aug. 22, 1999 The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
