<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: If the game is monopoly, Intel's an opponent to fear
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you worry that Microsoft dominates the technology world so
completely that other software companies don't have a chance, let
me give you something more important to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   Forget Microsoft. It's a big company. It does have the lion's
share of the operating system market for PCs. But there are
legitimate challengers. There's Unix and its variations coming on
strong enough, and with enough real-world advantages over Windows
to make Microsoft look over its shoulder. Apple _ like a high-tech
Frankenstein _ has arisen from the near dead thanks to that trendy
and multicolored iMac machine.
</P>
<P>
   Worry about Mr. Chips instead. Worry about Intel.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the world and half the Justice Department watch
the Microsoft antitrust action with fear and loathing, something
important is happening in the chip market.
</P>
<P>
   To tell my story, I have to back up a little bit. For several
years, the consumer PC world has been changing from a market where
the sale is closed based on features and power to one where price
closes the sale. Some people will always look for the most powerful
brand-name computer they can find, and price, basically, is no
object. But you don't have to look past the computer newspaper ads
to understand that price is king now.
</P>
<P>
   As that became obvious, manufacturers began to look for ways to
sell a computer at a price beneath the competition. That created a
marketplace for microprocessor chips _ the chips that furnish the
brainpower for PCs _ that cost less than those from Intel.
Companies such as Cyrix and AMD jumped into the market. Nowadays,
to cut to the chase scene, AMD stands alone a legitimate threat to
Intel. It's a real threat. AMD claims to have 51 percent of the
market for PCs that sell for under $1,000. That still leaves Intel
in the driver's seat on more-expensive machines for home and
business.
</P>
<P>
   If the world rocked along like that, with AMD content to hold
its share of the under-$1,000 market and Intel fat and happy with
the power machines, this sort of a divide could continue forever.
</P>
<P>
   But AMD has done a brave _ and perhaps financially necessary _
thing. It has created a chip that challenges high-end Intel chips.
This new AMD chip _ once code-named the K7 and now called the
Athlon _ is available in both 600-megahertz and 650-megahertz
models. When tested against the Intel Pentium III chip, it does
very well. In fact, in most tests, it beats the Intel chip.
</P>
<P>
   Intel may be big and slow to react, but it is also powerful. It
knows what AMD did to it in the low-price market.
</P>
<P>
   Intel is capable _ if it chooses _ of undercutting the Athlon on
price, even if it means losing money. AMD can't afford to get in a
high-stakes poker game with Intel. If money were poker chips, Intel
sits in front of a high-as-the-moon stack of blue chips, and AMD
has just one blue chip. That chip is Athlon.
</P>
<P>
   Technology is a cruel marketplace. The best technology does not
always win.
</P>
<P>
   This may be a battle that AMD must win. AMD executives
acknowledge that the success of Athlon is crucial to the company.
If AMD does lose, and if losing does break the company, Intel
stands alone.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, I prefer the Intel chip for reasons no more
sophisticated than those a bass fisherman might have for selecting
a blue crankbait. I hope this is one time that you don't bank on my
personal preferences.
</P>
<P>
   Without legitimate competition, prices generally rise.
Innovation slows. Competition drives chip companies just as it does
lemonade stands and football players.
</P>
<P>
   I don't fancy a future when the only brand of lemonade comes
from Intel.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
