<SLUG> BC-NFK-CHECKITOUT24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sneak peek at shoe shelves
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Homma Rafi
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Believe it or not, when your parents were your age, having more
than a few pairs of shoes was a bit of a luxury. But times have
changed. Some kids today have closets full of shoes _ especially
sneakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shoes come out all the time and you need to buy new (sneakers)
to keep up with new styles,'' says Demetris White, 11, of Walden
Middle School in Atlanta. ``I own 10 pairs of sneakers, and every
pair helps me look beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Demetris and other kids in the metro area, some of
the hottest sneakers for back to school are Nike's new Jordan XIV
Low ($50-$90) and the Nike Air Max Plus ($60-$85).
</P>
<P>
   Antonio Terrel, 13, of Turner Middle School in Douglas County,
recently bought his 13th pair of sneakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your sneakers should match your clothes so you can look
good,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Nike puts out multiple versions of the Jordans in different
color combinations. The current Jordan is light blue and white. The
Air Max Plus is army green and red.
</P>
<P>
   Reebok has reintroduced its ``pump'' shoes from the early 1990s.
The new Reebok Pump Furious ($50-$60) has an orange pump on top of
the tongue to pump air into the sneaker to improve fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pump is so cool and looks really good on the sneaker,''
says Michael Jamison, 10, of Walnut Grove Elementary in Gwinnett
County.
</P>
<P>
   OK, shoes are cool, but is buying four pairs all at one time
necessary? Some kids say ``yes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' says Eric Reid, 10, of Austin Road Middle School
in Henry County. He owns 14 pairs of sneakers. He likes to pair
high-top and mid-top sneakers with jeans and slacks, and chooses
which to wear based on the color of his shirt.
</P>
<P>
   However, style isn't the issue for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shoes should be cute but comfortable,'' said Melissa Davis, 8,
of Davis Academy in Fulton County. She likes the Reebok Crazy Daisy
($38), a sneaker with inserts to change the color of the flower
pattern along the side of the shoe.
</P>
<P>
   Homma Rafi is a senior at Cross Keys High in DeKalb County in
metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
