u l BC-NFK-FEATURE24-COX     08-23 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-FEATURE24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kosovar kids are excited about being in America and attending
school
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Keith Still
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ten-year-old Besarta Selimi and her 12-year-old sister,
Fatbardha, become fourth- and fifth-graders at Stone Mountain
Elementary today. It's the first time either have been students in
a real school.
</P>
<P>
   The two girls are among about 25 Albanian refugee families from
Yugoslavia's province of Kosovo brought to Stone Mountain this
summer by the International Rescue Committee. Some of the families
came directly from refugee camps in Eastern Europe, while others
made stops at U.S. Army posts like Fort Dix, N.J., before arriving
in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovar Albanians had to leave their homes in Eastern Europe
because they were being attacked by the Serb Army. The Kosovar
Albanians, who are Muslim, wanted to be free from the Serb
government. The Serbians, who are Christian, refused to grant them
independence.
</P>
<P>
   Like many Kosovar refugees, Besarta and Fatbardha didn't attend
public schools in their hometown of Ferizaj.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they've been schooled in the homes of other Kosovar
Albanians all of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like school, and are looking forward very much to starting
in Stone Mountain,'' said Fatbardha with the help of 18-year-old
translator and fellow refugee, Lulzim Shala. ``School here is very
good, and we're excited to go to school with people from other
cultures.''
</P>
<P>
   The Selimis and their new friend, 14-year-old refugee Fixhrie
Buqaj have spent the summer attending an IRC summer camp for
Kosovar children at Stone Mountain's First Baptist Church. There,
children ages 3 to 15 played soccer, participated in new activities
and learned basic English words.
</P>
<P>
   The children are quickly picking up English, but most still
speak mainly Albanian. To overcome the language barrier, IRC
counselors and the kids had to find innovative ways to communicate.
</P>
<P>
   Senior camp counselor Whitney Lacefield said discipline was a
tough subject because the kids didn't know enough English to
understand what was going on. To help keep the kids safe in all of
their activities, the counselors and volunteers adopted the rules
of the refugees' favorite game _ soccer. A yellow card was a
warning, and a red card translated into a three- to five-minute
``time out.''
</P>
<P>
   However, in school the refugees will have to learn other ways to
communicate with their American teachers and classmates. The DeKalb
County school system offers help through its International School.
Students can brush up on their English, learn what an American
school is like and understand what is expected of them as students.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can stay in the International School for as long as they
need, but it's not usually a long-term thing,'' said county
spokesman Spencer Ragsdale, who estimated most return to their own
classrooms within a few weeks. ``Kids really teach each other.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, though, the children seem to be adjusting well to life
in the United States, said Lacefield.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is good here,'' said Fixhrie. ``I like American
people. They're very nice, and American culture is very good.''
</P>
<P>
   But added, Besarta, ``I don't have old friends here like I had
in Kosovo.''acticing English.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
