<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 11:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6401 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-NFK-NEWSFLASH24-COX     08-23 0415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-NEWSFLASH24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Earthquake devastates parts of Turkey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Days after an earthquake struck last week, many people in Turkey
were still sleeping outside, fearing that another quake would cause
their houses to fall on them.
</P>
<P>
   The earthquake caused widespread destruction, killing thousands
of Turks. The final toll won't be known for many days, because lots
of people are still trapped in rubble.
</P>
<P>
   Rescue workers from many countries, including the United States,
are trying desperately to reach anybody who might still be alive.
</P>
<P>
   Among those killed were a man from Marietta and four of his
grandchildren. They were on vacation in the resort town of Yalova
when the five-story building where they were staying collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Falcons make a comeback
</P>
<P>
   Peregrine falcons, which were once nearly extinct, are off the
government's list of endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, there were only 39 breeding pairs in the continental
United States. Today there are more than 1,650.
</P>
<P>
   The falcons made their comeback because the government in 1972
banned DDT, a chemical used to kill bugs, but one that also
decimated populations of several bird species.
</P>
<P>
   Bush leading, but questions linger
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, governor of Texas and son of former President
George Bush, seems well on his way to becoming the Republican
candidate in next year's 2000 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   He's raised more money than other Republican candidates, and he
won an unofficial election in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   But he's got a problem, too. Reporters have been asking whether
he ever used cocaine, and Bush won't say.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bill Clinton and his wife, Hillary, are looking for a
house to move into when the president leaves office in 2001.
They've looked at expensive homes in New York. Mrs. Clinton is
considering running for a U.S. Senate seat from New York.
</P>
<P>
   Can you spare a penny?
</P>
<P>
   There's a shortage of pennies right now, and that's causing
problems in stores. Without pennies they have trouble giving exact
change.
</P>
<P>
   People who save pennies in drawers and jars at home are causing
the shortage. When the economy is as good as it is now _ it's easy
for most workers to find jobs _ people tend to stow their spare
change and forget about it. If times were tougher, people would
spend those coins.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Mint is making more pennies to meet the demand.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
