r a BC-COSUMERQ&AMP;A24-COX     08-23 0492
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSUMERQ&AMP;A24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Death rate is high among male peers
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I just attended my 40th high school reunion class of 1959
(about 250 people). Classmates are now about 57 years old. Of those
250, 23 (9 percent) have died. Of the 23 who died, 20 (87 percent)
were males. Is the number of males who have died unusually high?
All the men in our class have sworn to take better care of
ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   _ Frank C.
</P>
<P>
   A:The mortality rate for this age group is on par for the
population as a whole, says Robert Hummer of the University of
Texas Population Research Center. About 9 percent of a birth
``cohort'' dies by age 55 and 13 percent by age 60. Your group is a
small sample and, having graduated from high school, is expected to
be a healthier group. (Adults with less education tend to die
younger, says the National Center for Health Statistics.)
</P>
<P>
   Hummer notes your class' male mortality rate is higher than
average. Typical fatality figures would be 16 males to 7 females,
not 20 to 3.
</P>
<P>
   Keep me posted on the next reunion stats and, Frank, be careful
out there.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Does the state of Texas recognize ``transfer on death
registration'' for mutual fund and investment stock accounts? If I
transfer my accounts to my children, and my husband and I die while
the children are minors, will the executrix of my will (my sister)
be able to access those accounts to raise my children?
</P>
<P>
   _ Diane S
</P>
<P>
   A:''Yes, Texas does recognize transfer on death registration,''
says PaineWebber's Jan Pickle This is a recent change. But is it a
good idea for transferring money to minor children?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' says Patricia T. Barnes, an attorney certified in estate
planning and probate law, because ``to use the funds, the guardian
must be appointed by the court after incurring attorney's fees and
bonding costs.'' In addition, the guardian can use the money only
for things approved by the judge, which requires more attorney's
fees. I think you get the picture.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, where probating a will is a simple matter, there is
little if any advantage to transfer on death. Neither is there an
estate tax advantage for it, adds Barnes Best advice? Forget
transfer on death and have a will prepared covering all your
assets.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Since my wife died, I have been sorting our worldly
belongings into keep and dispose categories. This difficult task is
compounded by my desire to recycle everything. Does anyone want
rags, or is it into the landfill again?
</P>
<P>
   _ Dave Dobbs
</P>
<P>
   A:The Habitat for Humanity Re-Store, 310 Comal St., would love
donations of rags. They are invaluable when checking donated paint
and other items. Just drop the rags off during business
hours.Contact Jane Greig, author of ``Thanks for Asking,'' at P.O.
Box 670, Austin 78767; (512) 445-3697; e-mail
jgreig(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
