<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 11:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6417 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN24-C     08-23 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ABC's shoddy treatment of ``Once and Again''
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   What can you say about a network that takes one of the most
promising new series of the season and schedules it in such a
suicidal manner that even viewers who fall in love with it won't be
able to find it after the first few weeks?
</P>
<P>
   ABC's bizarre plan for ``Once and Again,'' the romantic
comedy-drama from the creators of ``thirtysomething,'' isn't the
only lame-brain scheduling move, but it's one of the worst.
</P>
<P>
   The broadcast networks are hemorrhaging viewers like crazy, and
yet stupid scheduling tricks continue. You'd think they'd try to
make it easier, not harder, for people to find the few good shows
that are on the air. But noooooo. ...
</P>
<P>
   Remember last fall, when Fox shifted the wildly popular ``King
of the Hill'' from Sunday, where it was happily paired with ``The
Simpsons,'' to Tuesdays? The animated sitcom nose-dived in the
ratings, falling from a healthy Top 20 perch to somewhere near the
bottom of the ratings in a few weeks. Instead of establishing a hit
on Tuesday nights, the network wound up with a little-watched gem.
</P>
<P>
   At least Fox recognized its blunder. When the new season begins
in September, Hank and the gang will return to Sundays. But the
momentum that ``King of the Hill'' had established during its first
season may be hard to rekindle. Stupid scheduling.
</P>
<P>
   ABC's strategy with ``Once and Again'' is considerably more
puzzling. The show, starring Sela Ward and Billy Campbell as
divorced parents starting over in a new romance, has been the buzz
of critics since the tapes were sent out in June. Well-written,
brilliantly acted and warm-hearted, the show is a real bright spot
in an otherwise dull season.
</P>
<P>
   So what does ABC do with its sterling series? The show will
debut in September in the time slot usually occupied by ``NYPD
Blue'' _ Tuesdays at 9 p.m. _ until ``NYPD Blue'' is ready to
return in late October. That's about six weeks. Then ``Once and
Again'' will go off the air until ``Monday Night Football'' departs
in January, leaving a 9 p.m. opening for the new series on Monday
nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a rather unorthodox way to launch a show,'' conceded ABC
entertainment President Jamie Tarses in Los Angeles recently.
``We're profoundly aware there's great risk here.''
</P>
<P>
   No kidding. Great risk that millions of people will fall in love
with ``Once and Again'' and then lose interest during its
three-month layoff. Why not risk a new show that isn't generating
as much buzz, like ``Wasteland,'' the umpteenth take on
twentysomethings trying to find themselves? Or an existing show
with an established audience that might be more likely to remember
it after a three-month absence?
</P>
<P>
   NBC has pulled a stupid scheduling trick, too. Against the
strenuous objections of the show's producer, the network has put
the ``Law &AMP; Order'' spinoff in an 8 p.m. time slot, where it
definitely should not be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Law &AMP; Order: Special Victims Unit'' focuses on sex crimes
cases, usually murders with a sexual twist. In the pilot, a man who
committed multiple rapes is murdered by his victims and has his
penis cut off. This is appropriate material for 8 p.m.?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pushing NBC for a later slot,'' producer Dick Wolf told
critics in Pasadena, Calif., recently. ``Feel free to help me. This
is not designed to be an 8 o'clock show. It's not appropriate for
that hour. It's a very adult drama.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not like NBC doesn't have an easy way out of this quagmire.
``Law &AMP; Order: Special Victims Unit'' is scheduled to air Mondays,
followed by an episode of ``Dateline NBC'' at 9 p.m. So, switch the
two shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it makes a damn bit of difference what time
`Dateline' airs,'' Wolf snarled angrily. ``It's on five times a
week.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Sassa, president of NBC West Coast, said he thought ``Law
&AMP; Order'' will be fine in the earlier time period and will ``carry
an appropriate content rating.'' Big help.
</P>
<P>
   Single and childless adults may be available for an extremely
adult drama at 8 p.m., but people with kids will not want to sit
down to watch this show while the youngsters are wafting through
the room. It's hard to imagine that fans of ``Law &AMP; Order'' will
flock to this spinoff at such an early hour.
</P>
<P>
   Bad scheduling can kill a show before it gets started and drive
viewers away after it's on the air. Last year's annoying habit of
throwing series into reruns after four or five new episodes rankled
more than a few people, especially with shows like ``NYPD Blue''
and ``ER'' that have continuing storylines.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody (hey, I'll be the one!) should tell these network
nitwits to take advantage of good programming when they've got it,
not hammer a stake through its heart.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Holloway writes for the Austin American-Statesman in
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
