<DOCNO> NYT19990823.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 11:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6419 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-DISABLED-SUED24-COX     08-23 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISABLED-SUED24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wheelchair merchants sued for no handicapped parking
 &HT;    By Frank Cerabino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE WORTH, Fla. _ A Lake Worth business that has been selling
and repairing wheelchairs for nearly 20 years is scheduled to offer
a brand new service to its customers Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Handicapped parking.
</P>
<P>
   For Action Mobility's owners, Dave and Donna Batelaan, the
addition of handicapped parking is a bit of an embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I thought it was a joke,'' Donna Batelaan said,
recalling the federal lawsuit that was delivered to the store last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Batelaan and her husband _ both of whom use wheelchairs _ were
surprised to find their business accused of discriminating against
the handicapped because of an absence of handicapped parking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nearly everybody who comes here is handicapped,'' Donna
Batelaan said.
</P>
<P>
   The way she looks at it, the whole lot is handicapped parking.
And when it comes to being sensitive to the access needs of the
handicapped, the Batelaans are local experts.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it's their business. Action Mobility sells, fixes and
designs mobility devices that make life easier for disabled people.
And Dave Batelaan, a former IBM engineer, is a consultant for other
businesses seeking to comply with the Americans with Disabilities
Act _ the act the store is accused of violating.
</P>
<P>
   Action Mobility appears to be about the most disabled-friendly
place you could imagine. The door opens automatically. There are no
steps to navigate, and the counters are at a height for wheelchair
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of this building was designed so that I could get around
it,'' Donna Batelaan said. ``And four of our 17 employees are
handicapped.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Jean Pavlak, 67, of Jupiter, drove to the store with
her daughter to look for a lightweight wheelchair, she was upset to
find no reserved handicapped parking spaces in the store's small
lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want them to give the rights to handicapped people that
they deserve,'' Pavlak said.
</P>
<P>
   Pavlak said she has been in a wheelchair for the past five
years, following a fall. And since then, she has come to appreciate
the hardships disabled people face in public. Action Mobility is
the second local business she has sued over access.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't want the next person to be humiliated or
embarrassed,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Pavlak never spoke to the Batelaans, and had no idea that they
are disabled too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just waited there 20 minutes, and when nobody waited on me,
I left,'' Pavlak said.
</P>
<P>
   She went home and contacted her son's lawyer friend, Anthony
Brady, who filed a federal discrimination suit against the store.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's right is right,'' Donna Batelaan said. ``We'll
certainly comply.''
</P>
<P>
   But a face-to-face request, rather than a federal lawsuit, would
have been all that was needed to address the overlooked issue, said
Joe Fields, the store owners' attorney.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were never given the chance to fix the problem on their
own,'' Fields said.
</P>
<P>
   Once the handicapped spots are installed this weekend, Fields
plans to send photos of them to Pavlak's lawyer to show the store's
compliance.
</P>
<P>
   Will it make life easier for disabled customers?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to mean anything,'' said Barbara Scoville, one
of the store's handicapped employees. ``Just about everybody who
comes in here is handicapped.''
</P>
<P>
   It may end up that the person most affected by the lawsuit will
be the lawyer who filed it.
</P>
<P>
   Disabled people who file discrimination cases like this one
aren't entitled to receive money when they prevail in court. But
their lawyers are.
</P>
<P>
   That means Brady can get the store to pay for his attorney fees
and costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing that this happened in a store that makes
money off the handicapped,'' Brady said.
</P>
<P>
   Brady said he didn't anticipate his fees would be too high for
filing the two-page lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe just a couple thousand,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-99 1147EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990823.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 11:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6420 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-EVERGLADES-MONEY24-CO     08-23 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERGLADES-MONEY24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Floridians face tax bite to restore Everglades
 &HT;    By Robert P. King
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Should we restore the Everglades?
</P>
<P>
   Should we expand South Florida's water supply at the same time?
</P>
<P>
   OK: How about paying a 43 percent rate hike in your water taxes
to pay for it all?
</P>
<P>
   South Florida taxpayers will probably have to unless Gov. Jeb
Bush and the legislature come up with some big bucks.
</P>
<P>
   A federal-state plan being considered by Congress would spend
$7.8 billion on history's grandest environmental restoration _
aimed at re-creating some semblance of natural flow in the
Everglades while providing water to farms and cities.
</P>
<P>
   Half that money, roughly $200 million a year, would come from
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The other half would have to come from someone in Florida. And
without any major help from Tallahassee, the money would come
mostly from the taxpayers of South and Central Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Those taxpayers would shoulder nearly 60 percent of Florida's
burden under one financing scheme devised by the South Florida
Water Management District.
</P>
<P>
   The great bulk of that money would go to the district, the
federal government's partner in the project. But the district would
first have to raise its property tax rate to the maximum allowed
under the state constitution.
</P>
<P>
   If you own a $125,000 home with a $25,000 homestead exemption,
you would pay $100 a year _ $30.30 more than you do now.
</P>
<P>
   And you'd keep on paying, through taxes and fees to your city
and county governments.
</P>
<P>
   You might also have to pay fees that don't even exist now,
district consultants have suggested. Example: The district could
slap a charge on your local utility for pumping water out of the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   None of those numbers accounts for inflation, rising property
values or the interest on money that the district has to borrow for
the project. In March, district economists said they could face a
$2.5 billion deficit by 2020.
</P>
<P>
   The district isn't proposing any tax increase, said Government
Affairs and Communications Director Mike Slayton, who called the
financial outline just a starting point for discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of an infinite number of alternatives,'' Slayton
said.
</P>
<P>
   But another alternative _ major help from Tallahassee _ has yet
to win a commitment from legislators or Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, the legislature spurned environmental groups' pleas
for a guaranteed $100 million a year in Everglades money from the
state's land-preservation program. Bush and lawmakers said last
week they're still studying how to finance the project.
</P>
<P>
   Bush Everglades coordinator Allison DeFoor wouldn't even say
what sources the governor is considering. But he said Bush will
probably decide by January.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody in the world supports the (restoration),''
DeFoor said. ``All this talk about financing is way premature.''
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers oppose any new taxes _ either for the district or
statewide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taxes on the people of South Florida should be the last
alternative,'' said Charles Bronson, R-Indian Harbour Beach,
chairman of the state Senate's Natural Resources Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said he's exploring whether the state could draw
$100 million a year from excess money it already collects from
taxing land sales. Another idea: Getting cities and counties to pay
for parts of the project that would help them.
</P>
<P>
   But at least one local government is saying: Don't look at us.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the Jupiter Town Council formally objected to paying any
``special'' tax toward the restoration without proof that the town
would gain. The council said Jupiter, which filters salt-laden
water from deep wells, doesn't need the Everglades as a water
supply.
</P>
<P>
   Worsening the money quandary is uncertainty about a huge extra
cost: An additional $172 million a year to operate the restoration
project's mammoth network of reservoirs, filter marshes, storage
wells, pumps and floodgates.
</P>
<P>
   Water managers want to split the operating costs 50-50 with the
U.S. Army Corps of Engineers. But the Army's brass in the Pentagon
has proposed making Florida pay the whole thing.
</P>
<P>
   As big as the restoration's price tag seems, Florida Audubon
Society lobbyist Charles Lee argued that it's a small cost for
ensuring the Everglades' survival and water for 12 million people.
Compare it to the billions that routinely go to highway projects,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The important thing is that the state's decision-makers are
talking now about how to raise the money, Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We clearly have this item on the administration's agenda as a
must-do item,'' Lee said. ``I think they're committed all the way
up to Jeb to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff researcher Lynne Palombo contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
