<HEADLINE>
FOR IOWA STATE COACH, THE TIME TO WIN IS NOW
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Progress in the Dan McCarney Era at Iowa State has been measured
in intangibles, not victories. With just nine victories in four
seasons, the intangibles had better be fairly, well ... tangible.
</P>
<P>
   McCarney said that he has rescued a destitute program that had a
winless season before he arrived. New facilities, bigger, faster
players, a stable coaching staff, and a more competitive team are
all positive signs, McCarney said.
</P>
<P>
   But he knows Iowa State fans are eager for all that to translate
into victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like our chances when people outside think you're going to
be 2-9 or 1-10,'' said McCarney, whose .205 winning percentage is
the worst of any Iowa State coach this century. ``That's what I've
seen written and heard said. That's great. We don't lack for any
motivation going into the season, believe me.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more genuine excitement behind our enthusiasm this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   In his first four seasons, the highlights have been few. Running
back Troy Davis had consecutive 2,000-yard rushing seasons. Last
year's team beat cross-state rival Iowa for the first time in 15
years, a triumph that also ended a 31-game winless streak in road
games. And the '98 Cyclones closed the season with a victory for
the first time in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can talk about everything you want to talk about, but
nothing matters more than winning,'' said senior running back
Darren Davis, Troy's brother, who needs 2,004 yards rushing to pass
his sibling as the school's career rushing leader and is trying to
become the first Cyclone to rush for 1,000 yards in three
consecutive seasons. ``I just want to win some games this year.
It's time for us to step up. We can't say we're young anymore. This
has to be the year.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarney's five-year contract expires after this season, but he
was given a two-year extension last fall. That provides a modicum
of job security.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to measure progress for us,'' Iowa State athletic
director Gene Smith said. ``We're a developmental program. We play
in one of the toughest leagues in the country. I think everyone
would agree that Dan has done everything the right way ... creating
the right culture, the right environment for our kids. At some
point, we have to have a winning season and I think this could be
the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a chance to be competitive with all of the schools on
our schedule. Being competitive and winning are two different
things. I think we have more opportunity this fall than we've ever
had in Dan's tenure.''
</P>
<P>
   Iowa State opens with three winnable nonconference games _
Division I-AA Indiana State, cross-state rival Iowa and at
Nevada-Las Vegas. If the Cyclones start 3-0 (the last time they
opened with three victories was 1981), their next six games will be
against Big 12 teams that went to bowls last season _ Kansas State,
Nebraska, Missouri, Colorado, Texas, and Texas Tech.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people told me I was committing professional suicide
taking this job,'' said McCarney, who has won four conference games
during his Ames tenure. ``They said I'd never win at Iowa State,
especially because we were getting ready to go into the Big 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel better about our depth this season, about the players
listed as backups. In the past we virtually put guys out there we
knew couldn't play winning football in the Big 12. But they were
the best we had.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely tough to build a program in the Big 12 North.
We were a unanimous choice to finish last in the North and that's
life. Until we get more competitive and start beating those teams,
that's the way it's going to be. We've got to do something about
that.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
