<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SIDEBAR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BRUSH' LEAGUER COMING INTO HIS OWN WITH CLEVELAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The player with the most family members to please at
Safeco Field Sunday doesn't wear a Mariner uniform and never really
paid much attention to baseball in Seattle, even though he's a
Washington native.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland first baseman/outfielder Richie Sexson, who grew up in
Brush Prairie (pop. 2,650) near Vancouver, Wash., treated 36 people
to the game _ part of a growing entourage for the 24-year-old who
was the Indian's 24th round selection in the 1993 June draft.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't send them home disappointed. Sexson hit his 24th homer
of the season, a two-run shot to right field in the 10th inning off
of a Jose Mesa fastball to break a 4-4 tie in Cleveland's 7-4 win.
</P>
<P>
   ``The home run was nice, but it's always great to do it at home
in front of your family,'' Sexson said.
</P>
<P>
   After six years in the minors, the 6-foot-7, dyed-blond Sexson
got his break last year when All-Star first baseman Jim Thome broke
his hand. Since then, he's become a fan favorite in Cleveland and a
superstar in Brush Prairie, where he still spends part of his
offseason.
</P>
<P>
   Sexson is part of a growing list of major leaguers with ties to
the Vancouver area, including San Diego pitcher Randy Myers and M's
left fielder Brian Hunter. Also, Ty Howington, an 18-year-old
left-handed pitcher from Brush Prairie, was selected 14th overall
by Cincinnati in the June draft.
</P>
<P>
   Those four players have helped put Vancouver on the baseball
map, and Sexson is proud of his roots. In fact, his old Senior Babe
Ruth team, Ryder Construction/3 Kings, recently won the state
championship for the third time in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting better, for raining as much as it does,'' Sexson
said of the quality of baseball in southwest Washington. ``We can't
play baseball year round like a lot of other kids. But baseball is
actually pretty big where I'm from.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Thome's injury last season, Sexson bounced back and forth
between Cleveland and Class AAA Buffalo. When he finally got his
chance to start in August and September, he responded by finishing
the season with 11 home runs, 35 RBIs and a .310 batting average in
174 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that Thome was ahead of him at first base in the
Cleveland organization, Sexson spent his past two seasons in the
minors learning to play the outfield, where he's starting to feel
comfortable. He also added 20 pounds of mostly muscle in the weight
room to boost his lanky frame to 230 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can play both corners in the outfield, but his best
position is first base,'' Cleveland manager Mike Hargrove said.
``And, he's got lots of power.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, he's hitting .258 in 103 games, with 24 homers and 83
RBsI. But he's batting .304 in his last 28 games and . has been a
thorn for Seattle pitchers, going 5-for-11 with two homers and
seven RBIs in the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's important is getting to play for a great team,'' he
said of the chance he's had with the Indians, who own the best
record in baseball and already have the American League Central
Division all but wrapped up.
</P>
<P>
   Sexson's success hasn't changed the way he's treated around
Brush Prairie, although he's in demand for appearances at his
aunt's fourth-grade class.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people there treat me the same,'' he said. ``They realize
where I came from and they know me just the same way. It's not like
I get bothered or anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked who the 36 tickets were going to, Sexson ticked off a list
of his immediate family: ``Aunts and uncles. Grandmother and
grandfather. Mom and Dad. Brother and wife. And a bunch of
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to do well anywhere I go, but obviously to do well here
makes them proud,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Away from baseball, Sexson has taken up the guitar as a way to
relax. Lately he's been a regular in a band with former Mariner
Mark Langston, who's currently on the disabled list for the Indians
and also plays guitar, and Cleveland shortstop Omar Vizquel, who
plays drums. On Saturday night, Sexson, Langston and Vizquel even
toted their instruments to Rocksport, a West Seattle club, to
perform in front of a small audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We play classic rock, AC-DC, some disco tunes,'' he said.
``Neither of us plays lead guitar. It's just a sound, the chords
you hear.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sexson family, of course, was well represented at Rocksport.
His parents, he noted, seemed more surprised by his performance on
stage than on the baseball field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been playing guitar for about two and a half years now,
but I don't really think they knew I took it so seriously,'' he
chuckled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
