   FEATURES BUDGET OFFER:
</P>
<P>
   VOLES: So you probably heard the big news last week about the
prairie vole, a hamster-sized rodent not usually in the headlines. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Turns out, according to scientists at Emory University in
Atlanta, that all it takes to transform an aloof, skirt-chasing
laboratory mouse into a more sensitive, caring mate is the addition
of a single gene. From a prairie vole. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Prairie voles, you see, are famous for being faithful. Not only
that, they're cuddlers _ ``sociable,'' in scientific parlance _ and
males and females share child-rearing duties. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So, with a little help from the prairie vole, scientists have
built a better mouse, but there's still work to be done. Inserting
the vasopressin receptor gene _ vasopressin is a hormone produced
in most mammals' brains, including humans _ made Mickey and the
guys more likely to increase their ``social contact'' with females.
But the gene didn't make the mice monogamous. By Tim Engle. 25
inches.
</P>
