<SLUG> BC-STATES-TODD-PA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        PENNSYLVANIA'S DICKINSON REINVENTS U.S. PATENT OFFICE FOR
INVENTORS
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Lisa Fine  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Aug. 24, -- Who would have thought that a portable
home soccer net dreamed up by a couple of independent inventors
could excite the newly appointed commissioner of the U.S. Patent
and Trademark Office?
</P>
<P>
   But former Pennsylvania patent attorney Q. Todd Dickinson has a
soft spot for inventions by the little guy.
</P>
<P>
   He says he gets stopped on the street by inventors who want to
tell him about their newest household or sports equipment product.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I love most is hearing inventors talk about their
creations,'' said Dickinson, 46, who practiced law in Philadelphia.
``The home soccer practice net that was portable. It was the
greatest.''
</P>
<P>
   It is exactly that kind of enthusiasm for the non-corporate
inventor that is helping Dickinson quietly reinvent the image of
the U.S. patent and trademark office.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his predecessor, Bruce A. Lehman, who offended the
independent inventors by once referring to them as ``weekend
hobbyists,'' Dickinson says he is intrigued most by inventions like
a cardboard shield that protects railings from paint.
</P>
<P>
   Dickinson is trying to make friendlier the agency that sets
patent law policy and issues patents and trademarks to inventors or
corporations responsible for anything from household products to
major corporate technological developments. The PTO will issue its
six millionth patent this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Dickinson said he appreciates the bigger innovations and says he
is thrilled with medical developments he has seen in his lifetime
like ``AIDS cocktail'' drugs and new surgery techniques.
</P>
<P>
   His office is a showcase for his love of inventions complex and
simple. On his desk, there is a new kind of computer chip -- and a
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   With Dickinson at the helm, the PTO created a new division for
independent inventors called the Office of Independent Inventor
Programs that is run by the agency's Technology Group to help small
businesses and inventors.
</P>
<P>
   His two words of advice for independent inventors: be
persistent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inventors can sometimes underestimate the amount of work
needed once the product is created,'' Dickinson said. ``That's just
part of it. You need to also have a solid business plan. Work
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   He has made the Philadelphia intellectual property community
proud.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has never been a better time for small businesses and
inventors to get patents,'' said Jeffrey Spangler, a spokesman for
the Philadelphia Intellectual Property Association. ``It's good for
inventors and it reflects well on the Philadelphia patent
community.''
</P>
<P>
   Spangler said Dickinson's nomination represents the clout of the
city's patent law community.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton officially nominated Dickinson to be Assistant
Secretary of Commerce and Commissioner of Patents and Trademarks in
July, but he worked as acting deputy commissioner since January.
</P>
<P>
   Dickinson said his experiences in Philadelphia as a patent
attorney have prepared him for the new job. He was an attorney with
the Philadelphia law firm of Dechert, Price and Rhoads. From 1990
to 1995, he was chief counsel for intellectual property at Sun
Company Inc.
</P>
<P>
   In his 20-year legal career, he has represented major
corporations, small businesses, and inventors.
</P>
<P>
   Dickinson earned a B.S. in chemistry from Allegheny College in
1974 and a J.D. from the University of Pittsburgh School of Law in
1977.
</P>
<P>
   Intellectual property law experts say Dickinson's tenure comes
at a critical time for the agency. He will oversee growth within
the agency and shepherd through an increasing number of patent and
trademark applications.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two years, patent applications increased 25 percent
and trademark filings are up 16 percent. Last year there were
256,666 patents.
</P>
<P>
   He attributes the increase to a booming economy and a time of
technological advancements in computers and the biotech industry.
</P>
<P>
   Dickinson will oversee the PTO's hiring of nearly 1,300 new
patent examiners this year, bringing the total number of examiners
to 3,300.
</P>
<P>
   He said there have been more and more patents for search methods
and Internet auctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is so exciting to be on the cutting edge of technology and
to see all of the Internet developments,'' Dickinson said. ``We are
really starting to see a lot of that.''
</P>
<P>
   There has also been a recent trend of ``sensory'' patents and
trademarks for sights and sounds, he said. For example, for the
last five years, Harley-Davidson has been trying to trademark the
sound that its motorcycles make.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harley-Davidson. That's been very controversial,'' he said and
laughed. ``But products and innovations are now the way things move
on a screen, or sound, or smell. It's a new world of patents.''
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
