<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 13:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6480 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-INS-DEPORT-ART-HNS &LR;      08-23 1643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INS-DEPORT-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTROVERSIAL LAW BLOCKS MEXICAN TEEN-AGER'S VISIT TO U.S. 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photos available on NYT database) 
 
By EDWARD HEGSTROM 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ It was supposed to be Graciela Meza's dream trip to
the United States. A chance to visit her sister before returning to
Mexico to begin college.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the bewildered 18-year-old Mexican citizen was
interrogated for hours after arriving at Bush Intercontinental
Airport in Houston, thrown in a jail cell overnight and deported
back to Mexico City the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   Meza told airport immigration authorities that she planned to
help care for her infant niece in Houston during the second leg of
a visit in June. Officials said that caring for a baby in the
family amounted to work, something not allowed under the terms of
Meza's tourist visa.
</P>
<P>
   Meza was labeled an illegal immigrant and deported without so
much as a hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The shy teen-ager says she remains traumatized by the memory of
the rough treatment and the sleepless night in a cramped jail cell
with a stinky mattress and a shady cellmate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that even drug dealers get treated as badly as
they treated me,'' Meza said in a telephone interview from her
family's home outside Mexico City. ``What did I do that made them
treat me like a criminal?''
</P>
<P>
   She said she still wonders how immigration officials could
believe she needed a work visa for a family visit in which she
planned to occasionally help change her niece's diapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's a cultural difference,'' Meza said. ``Here (in
Mexico), sisters always help with the baby, and nobody considers it
work.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service denies that Meza
was mistreated.
</P>
<P>
   An internal review of the June 6 incident shows that officials
acted ``professionally and courteously'' during the deportation
proceeding, said an INS letter sent to Meza's in-laws last month.
</P>
<P>
   Meza's attempt to enter the United States was denied because she
had planned to work as an au pair, or an unpaid child-care worker,
the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials also noted that Meza had said she planned to take
English classes and had no return ticket to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Meza's brother-in-law, U.S. citizen William Gehle Jr., continues
to protest the immigration service's handling of the case. He wants
an apology, a reinstatement of Meza's tourist visa and a refund for
her airline ticket.
</P>
<P>
   But the INS says it considers the matter closed after its
internal review.
</P>
<P>
   Meza's swift deportation came under the terms of a controversial
1996 immigration law giving INS inspectors unprecedented powers to
deport foreigners from airports and border checkpoints without a
hearing _ even when the visitors hold what appears to be a valid
visa. Deportations under the new program began in 1997. More than
30,000 foreigners were summarily deported last year under the
program known as ``expedited removal,'' according to the INS.
</P>
<P>
   Congress approved the new regulation to prevent illegal
immigrants from slipping into the country by demanding a hearing
and then disappearing within the United States before their trial
date.
</P>
<P>
   But immigrant-rights activists and foreigners complain that the
new regulation gives far too much power to the INS officers
stationed at airports and border checkpoints.
</P>
<P>
   Those deported usually have no right to appeal. Even the INS
acknowledges that the decision can be somewhat arbitrary, based
partly on the instincts of the agent on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have inspectors at the ports of entry who are very
experienced,'' said Thu Nhi Barrus, an INS spokeswoman. ``This
experience is not all scientific. People who work in this field
have something like a (sixth) sense'' telling them when to allow
entry and when to ship the visitor back home.
</P>
<P>
   Canadians have complained about the new powers of the INS border
officers, whom they have come to label ``cowboys'' because of their
perceived arrogance.
</P>
<P>
   But INS statistics show that 80 percent of those deported under
the new program are Mexican.
</P>
<P>
   Americans married to foreigners say they, too, have suffered
indirectly under the new program. The law has been used to
summarily deport the foreign wives and husbands of U.S. citizens.
Visits from the in-laws also have become more problematic.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Gehle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not one of these liberals who believes we should open up
the border and give a home to anyone who wants it,'' explains
Gehle, an international business consultant whose wife, Laura, is a
Mexican citizen with U.S. residency. ``But to prevent my
sister-in-law from coming for a visit is ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   After the birth of their daughter early this year in Houston,
the Gehles began considering the possibility of visits from Laura
Gehle's family back in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The family decided that Gehle's younger sister, Meza, could come
to Houston for an extended visit before beginning college. It would
be a chance for the teen to see the United States and would also
give the Gehles some help with the baby.
</P>
<P>
   The INS granted Meza a tourist visa after the Gehles signed a
letter promising that the teen-ager would be under their care and
supervision while in the United States. The Gehles promised the INS
that they would pay for all of Meza's expenses, including English
classes. They also signed an affidavit promising to pay for a
return plane ticket when the teen was ready to go home.
</P>
<P>
   Meza first came to Houston early this year. On the first leg of
the visit, she entered the country without a hitch, staying with
the Gehles for a few months.
</P>
<P>
   But then Laura Gehle and Meza decided to have the baby baptized
in Mexico. They decided to go back to their homeland for a one-week
visit in June.
</P>
<P>
   Meza's visa was still current, so the two thought they would
have no trouble going to Mexico for a week and then returning to
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   But when the sisters arrived June 6 at Bush Intercontinental,
they were separated at the immigration checkpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities took Meza into a room for an extended interview.
They opened her handbag, read her letters from friends and rifled
through her photos, Meza said. When they asked what she was
planning to do in the United States, Meza said she was visiting her
sister, helping care for her niece and taking some basic English
courses at a local church.
</P>
<P>
   At first, an immigration official told Meza she could only enter
the United States for one month. Meza accepted this limitation.
</P>
<P>
   But then an INS supervisor entered the room, announcing that
Meza would not be allowed into the country at all.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector ``kept insisting and insisting that I was coming
to the U.S. to work,'' Meza recalled. ``I tried to correct her. I
told her I was only going to help my sister with the baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Meza, barely 18 at the time and accustomed to relying on family
for support, was not allowed to talk to her sister or
brother-in-law during the extended interview. Noncitizens do not
have a right to an attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration officials repeatedly told Meza that she would not be
allowed into the United States, and they tried to persuade her to
sign a statement agreeing that she had attempted to enter the
country illegally.
</P>
<P>
   The statement was written in English and translated verbally
into Spanish for Meza. After hours, Meza said, she relented and
signed.
</P>
<P>
   Meza had left her older sister in charge of the luggage and the
cash. With no change of clothes and no money, she was trucked off
to an INS detention center, where guards put her in a small cell
with a woman who was awaiting a criminal trial, Meza said.
</P>
<P>
   An old mattress was thrown on the floor, but Meza spent the
night sitting on the jail-cell bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't sleep,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the airport, the Gehles frantically tried to make
contact with Meza, hoping to at least give the teen-ager a change
of clothes and some money. Their efforts were to no avail. The INS
refused to allow contact and later instructed the Gehles to go
home.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the terrified Meza was allowed to make one phone
call. She called the Gehles and told them what flight she would be
on in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   An INS guard escorted Meza to the flight to Mexico City the next
morning. William Gehle waited at the gate, and the guard allowed
him to hand his sister-in-law some cash. The guard then escorted
Meza to her seat on the flight.
</P>
<P>
   Gehle said that were it not for his extraordinary effort to make
contact, the INS would have shipped off a penniless 18-year-old to
fend for herself in the largest city in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The INS does not specifically dispute the Gehles' and Meza's
recollection of events, but it argues that the teen-ager's
treatment was routine. INS officials imply that people denied
admission routinely complain about their treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We regret your perception that the inspection was
inappropriate and recognize that the process can seem formidable
and perhaps even intimidating. This is not uncommon when an
admission is denied and the inspection leads to a return instead of
the anticipated continuation of the trip,'' Kenneth J. Elwood,
Deputy Executive Associate Commissioner of the INS Enforcement
Division, wrote in a letter to the Gehles last month.
</P>
<P>
   INS officials say it could have been worse. Foreigners deported
from the United States normally cannot apply for another visa for
five years, Barrus said.
</P>
<P>
   But because Meza cooperated by signing the statement provided by
the INS, she is now eligible to apply for a new visa at any time.
</P>
<P>
   That's small consolation for the teen, now safely back home in
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole experience was very traumatic,'' Meza said. ``It
changed what I think of your country. It took away any desire to go
back.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
