<DOCNO> NYT19990823.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6485 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l BC-SLEEPING-DISORDER-HNS     08-23 1261
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLEEPING-DISORDER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLEEPING SICKNESS: DIVER HELPS PUT THE SPOTLIGHT ON NARCOLEPSY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Ky., Tenn.) 
 
By JANETTE RODRIGUES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Houston diver Tracy Bonner thought she was just tired, a little
drowsy maybe, because of her whirlwind schedule of classes,
studying, practicing and traveling to meets.
</P>
<P>
   That's how the University of Kentucky athlete explained away the
falling asleep in classes after early morning diving practices,
nodding off behind the wheel of her car or dropping off during a
telephone conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would fall asleep at workouts for my diving,'' Bonner, 25,
said from Knoxville, Tenn., where she attends UK and trains.
``Things you take for granted that you wouldn't fall asleep during,
I would fall asleep.
</P>
<P>
   It never occurred to her that she had narcolepsy, a debilitating
neurological condition that causes excessive, daytime drowsiness
and a tendency to fall asleep at inappropriate times.
</P>
<P>
   She's not alone.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 200,000 Americans of all walks of life may suffer,
some silently and unknowingly, from this condition. The sleep
attacks can last a few minutes or more than a half hour.
</P>
<P>
   Bonner takes Dexedrine, a powerful stimulant, to keep awake and
alert. Last week, she received a one-year suspension from competing
from FINA, the international swimming and diving body, because it
is a banned substance. Her Olympic aspirations are in limbo.
</P>
<P>
   Between Bonner's case and the recent discovery of the gene that
researchers in Texas and California believe causes narcolepsy, the
disorder has been in the news recently and is finally starting to
register on the nation's radar screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want people to know about narcolepsy,'' she said.
``Hopefully, this will open some people's eyes and they can go and
get checked out and they can get treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Narcolepsy changes lives. But not for the better.
</P>
<P>
   This is a condition that can ruin lives, say sleep disorder
specialists. It isolates, shames, impairs performance at school,
makes it hard to hold down a job and brings pain _ physical and
emotional.
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Narcolepsy at Stanford University reports that
because sufferers' sleep at night is disrupted, they are usually
not as alert during the day. Because of this they are accident
prone, with about 10 times the rate of auto accidents as the
general population.
</P>
<P>
   The National Institutes of Health reports that about 135,000
Americans suffer from narcolepsy. Some estimates put the number at
200,000, and it could be higher.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Max Hirshkowitz, director of the Sleep Research Center at
Baylor College of Medicine and the Veterans Affairs Medical Center
on Houston, studies sleep disorders, such as narcolepsy.
</P>
<P>
   The center took part in a study of a new drug, modafinil, for
the condition. Modafinil helps people stay awake without the
jolting side effects of amphetamines and other stimulants. The
brand name is Provigil.
</P>
<P>
   Hirshkowitz said narcolepsy isn't difficult to diagnose.
</P>
<P>
   ``But narcolepsy isn't taught much at medical schools,'' he
said. ``If (doctors) haven't been taught about narcolepsy, it
doesn't cross their minds. That's why it takes 10 to 12 years to
diagnose unless you have someone who stumbles across it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the symptoms of narcolepsy can be mistaken for a heart
condition, a thyroid disorder or even epilepsy, Hirshkowitz said.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the sleep attacks, some narcoleptics can suffer from
cataplexy, sudden episodes where they lose muscle function and
experience a weakness in the knees or total body collapse. This is
triggered by emotional responses such as laughter, anger or fear.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Crews, 65, of Houston questioned her sanity before a
doctor told her she had narcolepsy and cataplexy in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   Like Bonner, she takes Dexedrine. Like Bonner, she wishes she
wasn't dependent on the medication to live a normal life. Prolonged
use can lead to addiction and other negative health-related side
affects.
</P>
<P>
   Crews, who is able to drive and exercise with the help of the
medication, has weaned herself off higher dosages, but she still
needs one dose a day. She said she is angry that Bonner has been
banned for using the drug.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand how she has to take the Dexedrine,'' said the
Houston retiree. ``It is a dangerous drug, but what is your
alternative? What kind of life do you have without it? You don't
have a life without it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I was diagnosed, I felt like I was losing my mind,''
Crews said. ``Things were happening to me, and I would do strange
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Falling asleep on a bus was not a problem, she said. Falling
asleep on the assembly line for minutes at a time was, and she
didn't realize she nodded off until a co-worker told her.
</P>
<P>
   But the narcolepsy is not as frightening and embarrassing for
Crews as cataplexy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're laughing, telling a joke or getting angry at someone
and it hits you,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bonner said she used to have laughing fits when someone struck
her as funny and fall down.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Ray Martin does not suffer from cataplexy but he has
narcolepsy. Until he was diagnosed, the condition caused him, as he
understates it, ``a lot of problems.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It most certainly caused me to feel humiliated, but one of the
worst problems in the world was it effected me economically because
I couldn't hold a job,'' said Martin. ``I would work hard, but I
would fall asleep and they would fire me.''
</P>
<P>
   The long-time director of the Progressive Amateur Boxing
Association, or PABA, said he was discharged from the Air Force as
``an unproductive airman'' because he dozed off.
</P>
<P>
   Although the military physician who examined him was aware of
narcolepsy, Martin said the doctor wrote that his nodding off was a
character problem and representative of a lack of ambition.
</P>
<P>
   Martin tried Dexedrine but switched to another narcolepsy
medication because he was boxing competitively at the time and
didn't want it to interfere with his sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kept me awake, but I didn't like the sensation of taking
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin now takes Provigil and is a member of a Houston
narcolepsy support group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tremendous help to know there were other individuals
who had the same problem I had,'' he said. ``For so long, I was
isolated and felt I was the only one with this problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonner wants to start a support group in Knoxville when she has
more time. That will probably be after the Olympics. She and her
synchronized diving partner, Kathy Pesek, also of Houston, hope
FINA will reduce suspension to six months.
</P>
<P>
   They are the national champions in the 3-meter, and their
speciality will be an Olympic event for the first time next year in
Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Bonner argues that even with Dexedrine, she is not at 100
percent alertness. And her sport, an event of precision and
mechanics, is not enhanced by stimulants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be on Dexedrine,'' she said. ``I hate the fact
I have to take a medication every day just to function in normal
life situations. I hate having to rely on this substance to
survive.''
</P>
<P>
   And switching to Provigil is not an option yet. She doesn't know
whether it will work for her or whether it will work enough. Her
hectic pre-Olympic training and competition schedule doesn't have
room for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are climbing up a ladder that's 10 to 15 feet up in
the air, you don't want to worry about falling asleep and falling
onto the concrete,'' Bonner said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
