<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6495 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-NHL-MONEY-2TAKES-     08-23 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-MONEY-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED LINE, BLUE LINE, BOTTOM LINE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Less than 72 hours after the Bruins established an NHL
precedent, rendering Dmitri Khristich a free agent rather than pay
him $2.8 million this year, the Red Wings Friday prevented Nicklas
Lidstrom from returning to play in Sweden, keeping him in Detroit
with a contract that will bring the star defenseman some $22
million over the next three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, the Bruins figure they're exercising fiscal prudence,
working within reasonable budgetary bounds.
</P>
<P>
   In Detroit, owner Mike Ilitch keeps the money tap open wide, his
well-heeled Wings skating in lockstep to the bank with the Rangers.
The Blueshirts this summer committed $62.85 million to recruit five
free agents, hoping to revive a moribund, Wayne Gretzky-less lineup
that hasn't been to the playoffs since the spring of '97.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, as the weeks and months go by, the NHL becomes
increasingly polarized. There are the haves, the have-nots, and in
the Bruins' case, the will-nots.
</P>
<P>
   On one side, the tight-spending Bruins have their allies,
typically smaller-market clubs and, lately, even some bigger-market
clubs. Late last season, even the powerful, high-spending Canadiens
began to downsize their payroll, moving out the likes of Mark
Recchi and underperforming team captain Vincent Damphousse. The
large-market Colorado Avalanche opted not to throw money at Theo
Fleury, after acquiring him from Calgary for a playoff run last
spring, and also chose not to retain forward Valeri Kamensky or
defenseman Sylvain Lefebvre. All three will work on Broadway this
season, earning an average of $4.5 million-plus.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, the free-spending Rangers and Red Wings are
hardly alone. The Flyers have Eric Lindros as their $8.5 million
centerpiece. The Mighty Ducks of Anaheim came to terms in the
offseason with their superstar, Paul Kariya, agreeing to pay the
former Maine Black Bear $30 million over the next three seasons.
Even the bankrupt Pittsburgh Penguins, on the hook to pay Jaromir
Jagr in excess of $10 million this season, continue to be
aggressive in their signings, recently retaining free agents Alexei
Kovalev and Martin Straka for more than $2 millon per year each. As
the dollars flowed inside the Igloo, former superstar Mario Lemieux
frantically continued his attempt to cobble together a deal to buy
the club.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the polarization, however, there may be detectable signs of
a market shift, the most overt of which is Boston's decision to
send Khristich packing. In the four-plus years that the current
Collective Bargaining Agreement has been in place, no team ever
acted like the Bruins Tuesday, setting Khristich free after
learning an arbitrator granted him an $850,000 raise over his
1998-99 salary.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a shift, it could be part of what NHL commissioner
Gary Bettman Saturday depicted as the ``pendulum'' of player
salaries. The CBA, signed in January 1995 after a 100-plus day
lockout, is still evolving, he said. He stressed the CBA is a
toolbox clubs can use to level off or pull back salaries, if they
determine that is necessary. Walkaway arbitration is one of the
tools.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, Boston's move regarding Khristich could be
the harbinger of more walkaways.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll see more,'' said Darcy Regier, general manager
of the small-market Buffalo Sabres. ``It took 4 1/2 years for the
first one, I think, because there was a general optimism that we,
as a league, somehow would be able to control costs. But it hasn't
been effective. In some cases, teams have incurred tremendous
losses. In Buffalo's situation, it's common knowledge that our
losses are mounting up and continue to accrue.''
</P>
<P>
   In Regier's estimation, the Bruins, by signing former Sabre Dave
Andreychuk over the summer, had a strategy in place when they cut
Khristich free. Boston president/general manager Harry Sinden
underscored that fact Tuesday when he said the move to get
Andreychuk was made, in part, anticipating what the club believed
might be an onerous arbitration award for Khristich.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too early to tell exactly what we'll see,'' said Regier.
``But I think for sure we'll see more of that kind of planning in
place. It's one thing to walk, but you've got to have a plan in
place, have alternatives if you decide not to keep a player for
whatever reason. I can tell you, with salaries where they are,
we're definitely planning more here.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston-based agent Mark Witkin, who represents Bruins Don
Sweeney and Hal Gill, among others, said last week he felt NHL
teams ``would like to see a couple of big public floggings'' when
it came to player salaries. The first of those hits could be
Khristich's, if no club comes forward and offers him a deal.
Khristich maintains the right to play in Boston next season for
$1.95 million _ the figure the Bruins offered in arbitration _ but
his agent, Larry Kelly, emphatically stated last week that the
Ukrainian winger won't play again in the Hub.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly also heavily hinted at the possibility of collusion among
owners if he sees his client go without an offer. He chose his
words carefully, referring to the possibility of Khristich's being
cut free being ``orchestrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Goodenow, executive director of the NHL Players'
Association, steered clear of a possible controversy over
collusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``My opinion on it is, the system will work,'' said Goodenow.
</P>
<P>
   Goodenow depicted Boston's decision to cut Khristich free as a
``pricing issue.'' The Bruins didn't want to pay what an arbitrator
set as Khristich's market value and now, exposed to the full
market, Khristich will find out what it will bear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Dmitri Khristich is a solid NHL contributor,'' said
Goodenow. ``Obviously, it didn't work out for Harry (Sinden) and
Pat (Burns). But that seems to be a pricing issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he felt there would be more walkaways in the future,
Goodenow said with a casual air, ``Time will determine that.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of players' agents contacted last week following the
Khristich decision said they detected a change in management's
attitude toward some unrestricted free agents in recent months.
While there have been some significant scores by some high-profile
players this summer (Fleury) and some lesser-profile players (Tim
Taylor), some previously highly compensated players, now getting
long in the tooth, have agreed to continue their careers at
substantial discounts.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-99 1341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990823.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6496 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-NHL-MONEY-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     08-23 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-MONEY-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... substantial discounts.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For instance, Andreychuk, who will be 36 next month, took more
than a 50 percent pay cut when he agreed to a one-year, $1.2
million deal to play in Boston. Former Bruins netminder Bill
Ranford, 32, made more than $3 million last year and recently
signed with the Oilers as a backup at $455,000. Making it easier
for Ranford: He still has $2 million coming his way after having
the final year of his contract bought out.
</P>
<P>
   With training camps ready to open in less than two weeks, some
better-known unrestricted free agents also are still looking for
work. Pat Verbeek made $3.2 million in Dallas last season, the last
year of a three-year $9.3 million free agent deal he signed with
the Stars. Right now, he's 35 and unemployed. It doesn't look like
the Sabres will bring back former Bruin Joe Juneau, who made $2.2
million last year, a deal he originally signed in Washington. Many
figured Ulf Samuelsson, dealt from New York to Detroit at the trade
deadline in March, would end up back on Broadway. Samuelsson, 35,
made $2 million last year, and at the moment remains out on the
range and not a Ranger.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're asking, `Are teams going to be more focused on their
payrolls?' '' said Steve Freyer, longtime agent for Boston captain
Ray Bourque, ``I'd say the resounding answer is yes. But do I think
we'll begin to see more walkaways? No, I don't. You're dealing with
an organization (Boston) that pays close attention to payroll, and
they've made a value judgment about one player. I think that's all
it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Fee, an agent along with former Bruins great Bobby Orr at
Woolf Associates, recently began representing Joe Murphy, who made
$3.8 million with the Sharks last year. Fee acknowledges Murphy
won't make nearly the same money in his next deal and says he
detects a significant slowdown in the signings of unrestricted free
agents overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``In years past, it seems there was an early and consistent
level of activity in these signings,'' said Fee. ``The reverse
might be true now. GMs are taking a more wait-and-see approach.
What changed? Probably some clubs weren't happy with what they got
_ they spent significant money and didn't get the expected
returns.''
</P>
<P>
   Teams are showing more fiscal restraint, said Phoenix GM Bobby
Smith, with a much more critical eye in assessing older talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hit the wall at 35,'' said Smith, once an accomplished
scorer in his days with Minnesota and Montreal. ``I remember I used
to get three or four scoring chances a game. I hit 35 and it was
one chance every four games.''
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver GM Brian Burke, who worked for the league office when
the current CBA was negotiated, said he was surprised it took 4 1/2
years for the first walkaway to be issued.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, there was some conjecture that the Canadiens might
choose not to pay Recchi the $4.5 million he was granted in
arbitration or that St. Louis could opt to let Pierre Turgeon, who
won a $4.65 million award, walk. Recchi eventually was dealt to the
Flyers. The Blues kept Turgeon all season and recently signed him
for two years at about $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Will more walkaways follow?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think so,'' Burke said, emphatically. ``I have hope this
business can return to fiscal sanity for the first time in years. I
think what Boston did was terrific. It used to be that the GM was
in the foxhole all alone, fighting these battles for himself, and
in many cases team owners just said pay. Now, I see team ownership
looking at the bottom line. If you have to make a fearless decision
based on money, you can do it if you've got the owner's blessing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now,'' said Nashville GM David Poile, referring to the
possibility of more walkaways, ``that question doesn't have an
answer. Next year at this time we'll see if there have been more of
these, and what the financial state of the league is as a whole.
Overall, I think what you're seeing is a reality. Each team is
looking at the bottom line, and in a lot of cases they're seeing
losses. It's a costly business. Just to keep the players you have _
never mind go after unrestricted players _ often means offering a
player at least the 10 percent qualifying raise. On a $2 million
salary, that's another $200,000. All of a sudden, your $25 million
payroll is $27.5 million. Where do you add the revenues to pay the
$2.5 million? It's not brain surgery to figure out this is a lot of
money. The bottom line is not good.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodenow said it is still too early to draw conclusions from the
non-signings among the unrestricted free agents. Many, if not most,
could come to terms in the days before the season begins or even
later.
</P>
<P>
   Before the mid-1990s' onset of rocketing salaries, the NHL pay
scale was a vastly different world. Goodenow refers to it as the
time before the ``market being in place.'' Free agency didn't
exist, all but prohibiting player-induced movement. Typically,
players saw modest pay increases throughout their careers. Rarely
did they see their earnings get trimmed. They exited on their
highest paydays. The trend now could be different.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the market in place,'' acknowledged Goodenow, ``the
players fully understand they may have to adjust at the back end of
their careers. That doesn't come as a surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Witkin sees a concerted effort on management's side to change
some of the salary dynamics.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did (Bob) Dylan say?'' he remarked. `` `You don't have to
be a weatherman to know which way the wind is blowing.' What, did
(GMs and owners) all get religion independently? I can't see the
wind, but I think the leaves are moving around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
