<HEADLINE>
UP CLOSE WITH ALBERT BROOKS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A health-care expert from the University of South
Carolina is explaining to Matt Lauer how early cancers are detected
as Albert Brooks watches from the ``Today Show'' greenroom
upstairs. He's here to plug his latest film, ``The Muse,'' which
is, as he is to say more than 50 times on this day, ``opening Aug.
27.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't you just imagine how this is going over in millions of
homes across America?'' asks Brooks. `` `Honey, I found a lump.'
`Be quiet, the guy with the movie's on. He's supposed to be funny.'
`Later on the show, how to take out your own spleen. But, first,
let's talk to funnyman Albert Brooks.' `Our next guest invented
gangrene, but first let's hear from funnyman Albert Brooks.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Albert Brooks is funny. And it's not entirely his fault. Funny
is part of his genetic make-up. His father, Harry Einstein, was an
ethnic comic whose life ended as if it were a Mel Brooks version of
a Greek tragedy. During a roast of Desi Arnaz and Lucille Ball at
the Los Angeles Friar's Club when Brooks was only 11, his father
delivered his stand-up routine, walked back to his place on the
dais, and fell forward into his soup. At first, people thought it
was a joke. It wasn't. After his father's funeral, Brooks remembers
Milton Berle coming over to his house and, in an attempt to cheer
the family up, sticking a cigar up his nose. They lived across the
street from the retired silent-comedy star Harold Lloyd.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks is the youngest of four brothers. The eldest is his
half-brother, Charles Einstein, a noted sportswriter. Then there's
the bullying Bob, more famous as Showtime's satirical stunt man,
Super Dave Osborne; and Cliff, an advertising genius who, among
other things, conceived of the ad campaign that turned Gallo from a
jug wine into ``from the estates of Ernesto and Julio Gallo.''
Albert came last.
</P>
<P>
   The brilliant Brooks has carved out a career playing desperate
peole who strive hard to get what they want, get it, aren't sure
they want it, lose it, and strive hard to get it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's going to be watching this?'' Brooks asks the entourage
in the greenroom. ``I'm at the end, between cancer and the
Globetrotters. And they'll ask me about Einstein.'' Brooks changed
his name from Einstein to Brooks because he didn't really see the
humor in Albert Einstein.
</P>
<P>
   He's spending the day being whisked _ accompanied by a pair of
publicists; his producer-manager, Herb Nanas; and a make-up person
_ from the ``Today'' appearance to a taped interview on ``CBS: This
Morning'' to ABC radio, where he'll do a series of 10-minute
drop-in interviews for radio stations ranging from Boston's WAAF to
Bob, Gene, and Suzy's show in Cleveland. And that's just the
 &UR; morning  &LR; schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really mind it,'' says Brooks. ``It's a marathon.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is also a good way to describe Brooks's career.
</P>
<P>
   It started out great, with regular gigs on ``The Dean Martin
Show'' and ``The Tonight Show'' and Merv and Steve doing his
remarkable stand-up _ a routine that included Albert, the elephant
trainer, who loses his pachyderm on the way to the studio and
substitutes a frog. Johnny Carson practically passed out from
laughter as Albert (pronounced in the French manner) tried to
coerce the frog into doing tricks by offering it peanuts.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1973, while he was touring to support sales of his comedy
album, Brooks's stand-up career ended with a panic attack at Paul's
Mall, a now-defunct Boston club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sitting there watching my friend, my livelihood, have a
nervous breakdown,'' said Nanas, who gave up a prosperous career as
a William Morris agent to tie his life to Brooks's. ``He didn't
really recover for five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks began making short films for ``Saturday Night Live'' in
1975, and was producer Lorne Michaels's choice to be the permanent
host for the show. Brooks balked at moving to New York; even though
he did become a regular contributor, he never set foot in the
studio.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An NBC aide, with a notebook and a headset, enters the greenroom
and asks for Brooks. He follows the aide through the corridors,
walking just the way he did in ``Lost in America'' when he strode
into his boss' office certain of a promotion and discovers it has
been given to somebody named Phil Schibano. Brooks seems confident
but, like David Howard and Wile E. Coyote, he knows that things
could turn in an instant. One tricky question from Katie Couric.
One missed opportunity to snag a viewer.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Brooks does have something going for him. The movie
he's made is a very funny satire of his home town _ a mix of
``Sunset Boulevard'' and ``Sherlock, Jr.'' And Billy Wilder and
Buster Keaton make good company in anybody's book.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks greets Couric and the interview goes well.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Hollywood, cheesy and sleazy go hand-in-hand,'' he tells
Couric. ``In Hollywood, six months out of prison and you could be
running a studio. At least at GM you have to work in parts for a
couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   On the way out of Rockefeller Center, Brooks stops to sign a few
autographs for the two dozen fans who surround him at the exit.
He's polite. Gets his picture taken with a policeman and it's back
in the limousine and over to CBS. He's already called his wife,
Kimberly, for a review. She said the ``Today Show'' appearnce went
well. And Brooks is happy.
</P>
<P>
   Momentarily.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's going well because when we had the premiere party,
people stayed until after midnight,'' he says. ``It was great. And
they were sincere. As sincere as they get. Because I do think that
most people want you to fail.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
