<HEADLINE>
`MONARCH' SOARS WITH FINE WRITING, COLORFUL OBSERVATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
CHASING MONARCHS 
Migrating with the Butterflies of Passage 
By Robert Michael Pyle 
Houghton Mifflin, 307 pp., $24 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In about a month's time, an extraordinary natural event will be
occurring in the skies over New England: the annual migration of
monarch butterflies from their northern breeding grounds to their
wintering grounds in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The extraordinary thing about this migration is not the
fragility of the butterflies or the distance they travel, but the
fact that not a single one of those soon to be heading south had
come north in the spring _ they will be, in fact, the
third-generation offspring of those that had.
</P>
<P>
   Three summers ago, naturalist Robert Michael Pyle set out to
``migrate with the monarchs,'' as he puts it, heading north from
his home in Washington State to meet up with the first wave of
southward-bound butterflies in British Columbia, then to follow
them south toward the Mexican border.
</P>
<P>
   Pyle's stated scientific aim was to settle the question posed by
what he calls (perhaps overstating it a bit) ``a major myth of
American natural history'' _ to determine whether migrating
monarchs cross the high mountain ranges that would appear to funnel
West Coast monarchs up and down the Pacific coast, and New England
monarchs cross-country to and from Mexico. He resolves this to his
satisfaction with the recovery, on the California coast, of a
monarch he had tagged east of the Cascade range.
</P>
<P>
   The crucial test for a book of this kind is whether its
obviously enthusiastic author is able to arouse anything
approaching a similar interest in his readers. Pyle succeeds on the
strength of some very fine nature writing and of some colorful
observations of the non-butterfly world that he encounters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it is early spring,'' he writes, ``and the butterflies'
sex urge has awakened. Their compasses, formerly set for south,
have been recalibrated. Today, after dropping out of the trees,
some will not return to the clusters as the afternoon cools.
Tomorrow, more will depart. The freezes are past, and milkweed is
sprouting in the North. It is time to go.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the ``sex urge,'' there is a description of the monarch
mating ritual that is quite frankly erotic. ``The male simply
attacks the female on the wing, drives her to the ground, and
wrestles with her. He will maneuver the female onto her back, wings
spread, and cover her _ a face-to-face embrace I've never seen
among other butterflies.'' After copulation, ``he will fly straight
up, carrying her in a postnuptial flight, while she remains closed
and inert, into a tree'' where they may remain ``in coitus'' for
the night.
</P>
<P>
   It is writing that owes much _ if sometimes a bit
self-consciously _ to the novelist Vladimir Nabokov, whose writings
on butterflies Pyle is currently editing. And Pyle's ``burnt
cinnamon and orange'' edges out Nabokov's ``amber brown'' as a
description of the monarch's coloration.
</P>
<P>
   And when there were not monarchs to observe, there was the land
over which they migrate.
</P>
<P>
   Pyle passes through Shoshone, Wash., where ``the early optimism
and pretension of the railroad town were obvious in attractive
black-lava mansions and public buildings (and where) the tracks ran
down the middle of the main street.'' And on another day there is
Kanab City, a self-described ``culinary watershed'' on the
Utah-Arizona border, perhaps, Pyle speculates, ``the divide across
which good beer and coffee would again be available. Or the onset
of Tex-Mex food.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the evocative writing and the wealth of clearly
presented information about the monarchs, there is a caveat for the
reader _ reading ``Chasing Monarchs'' really requires having a
basic field guide handy. The only illustration is an oddly scaled
monarch in flight on the jacket (which looks like the result of the
conflicting ideas of two designers), but the reader will probably
also want to see what monarchs look like in their immature stages.
</P>
<P>
   But it may be Pyle himself who most fully captures the reader's
interest. It is not just his obvious enthusiasm for the quest, but
also the respect, even affection, he shows for the objects of the
quest. While tagging a female monarch _ a simpler and less invasive
procedure than it might seem _ Pyle ``felt the powerful flight
muscles pulse against the vascular pads of my fingers, until she
went limp in the possumlike passive resistance some butterflies
affect. Then, stroking her prickly legs to get them moving, I
replaced her on a fresh sunflower.'' Gracefully done, and
gracefully written.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
