<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6509 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-MA-COMMENT-CELLUCCI-B     08-23 1198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-COMMENT-CELLUCCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCANDAL IS REFLECTION OF A GOVERNOR ADRIFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS AND SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- It was the toughest week of Governor Paul Cellucci's 7
1/2 months in office _ and not until the very end of it did the
chief executive return from vacation in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Massport director Peter Blute, point man for the
administration's controversial Logan runway proposal,
self-destructed on a taxpayer-funded cruise Tuesday with
swimsuit-clad young women and free-flowing booze.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal, replete with photos of one young partyer defiantly
flashing her breasts for the cameras, landed like a thunderstorm in
a muggy August, the thunder rolling from newspapers to talk radio
to water-coolers and coffee klatches.
</P>
<P>
   And though Cellucci moved quickly in forcing Blute to resign, on
Friday another story surfaced: Cellucci's economic development
director, Carolyn Boviard, was questioned about whether she was
romantically involved with her top aide, who was forced to resign.
</P>
<P>
   The events, especially the embarrassing details and tabloid
photos of Blute, helped crystallize a growing sense among many
political observers that the Cellucci administration is drifting,
still searching for a vision as State House power shifts elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not exhibit A,'' said Tobe Berkovitz, a Boston
University communications professor. ``This is like exhibit D.''
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit A might be Cellucci's decision to go on vacation in the
midst of a worsening budget impasse, a move that has added to the
sense of an administration without a cause.
</P>
<P>
   Where some governors might have taken to the airwaves to build
public pressure to end the budget stalemate, Cellucci has satisfied
himself with some mild-mannered demands, in effect ceding control
to House Speaker Thomas M. Finneran and Senate President Thomas F.
Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   As weeks have turned to months while the Democratic leaders have
wrestled over the budget, Cellucci's campaign self-portrait as a
bold leader ready and willing to impose fiscal discipline on the
Legislature has faded to a washed-out gray. Indeed, some frustrated
GOP strategists say the governor rebuffs advice to battle the
Democratic leaders in headline-generating spats, preferring cordial
relations even at the cost of results.
</P>
<P>
   The message and the appearance are unmistakable: Cellucci may
hold the title of governor, but he is not seizing control at the
State House. Instead, he comports himself more as legislator in
chief, a man who appears to feel little sense of urgency, who is
willing to go along to get along. When a legislative panel killed
his teacher-testing proposal earlier this summer _ something he had
campaigned long and loud on _ the governor offered hardly an
objection.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say he has not taken tough stands on some issues.
His aides point to his push for a new Logan runway despite fierce
political and community opposition. He also fought for, and nearly
won passage of, a death penalty law. And his threat to take his
$1.2 billion tax-cut proposal to the statewide ballot has forced
the legislative leadership to grudgingly consider reducing taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the prevailing impression is one of relative passivity.
And Cellucci, of all people, is aware that first impressions are
the most important. As lieutenant governor, he watched eight years
ago as Governor William F. Weld strode confidently into the State
House and took on the old boys, slicing up budgets, rolling back
taxes, and quickly forging an image as an outsider determined to
shake up the system.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the dominant images of Cellucci's first seven
months are of patronage, fund-raising, and junketeering, and, now,
Massport misbehavior. Some in Cellucci's inner circle worry that
the administration seems listless, Cellucci himself indecisive and
irresolute.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, his advisers and GOP supporters are concerned the
governor has consigned himself to playing a secondary role on
Beacon Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Finneran has struck a far higher profile with his
aggressive pursuit of policies, while Birmingham has proved almost
as dogged in pursuit of his own agenda.
</P>
<P>
   And with the clock ticking, Cellucci is now running the risk of
casting in concrete his profile as a chief executive enamored of
the trappings of the office and intent on exploiting his patronage
powers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, worried Cellucci advisers did find a silver lining in the
Massport scandal. They hoped that the crisis would jolt the
governor and his administration into setting off on a new and
bolder course.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ultimately could turn out to be a blessing because it's a
wake-up call,'' said one Republican adviser.
</P>
<P>
   But that would mean a sharp correction from the heading he has
steered in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, Cellucci's effort to stack an obscure
environmental board to install a Democrat who broke party ranks to
support him for governor.
</P>
<P>
   Or his jetting off on trade missions sweetened with extravagant
taxpayer-funded extras like a suite at the Beverly Hills Four
Seasons and tickets to the Paris Air Show.
</P>
<P>
   Or his appointing a controversial figure like Steven Tocco to
chair the Board of Education, even though Tocco lacks any expertise
for the post.
</P>
<P>
   Or his penchant for loading up state agencies with political
hacks at mid-level positions, forcing highly respected career
managers out.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's campaign fund-raising is reinforcing his
problems. His operation hits up almost every contractor, regulated
industry, and special interest that comes before his administration
for donations. Cellucci raised about $1 million in the last six
months, far more than any other governor has in the first half-year
in office.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that his aggressive fund-raising for presidential
candidate George Bush, governor of Texas. His organization broke
GOP records by raising about $800,000 for Bush at a Boston
fund-raiser in June.
</P>
<P>
   Intentionally or not, the fund-raising has sent a subtle message
to the state's big donors, lawyers, and business establishment:
access to Cellucci or appointments to his administration may well
depend on contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem, Cellucci's advisers say, is that the
governor is less inclined to listen to his inner circle, Cabinet
officers, or top staff, but rather turns to the advice of the likes
of Michael Connolly, the former secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   Add it all up and these days, instead of talking about changing
the State House culture, Cellucci seems more bent on defending the
local mores.
</P>
<P>
   Take his reaction to a Globe story that detailed the fact that
his appointees at MDC were using political references from
legislators and others to dole out summer jobs, a process that
seemed to freeze out minorities.
</P>
<P>
   That, Cellucci shrugged, is ``just part of life here at the
State House.''
</P>
<P>
   With a political scandal highlighting a long, listless summer,
the danger for Cellucci is that he will come to be seen as a
creature of that culture.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Frank Phillips and Scot Lehigh cover state and federal politics
for the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
