<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAKE-SURVIVAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUAKE'S RUINS LEAVE MANY STRUGGLING FOR DAILY NEEDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALIZA MARCUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ADAPAZARI, Turkey _ Every evening since the earthquake, Nurettin
Cuhadar has locked up his small grocery store, gotten into his red
Volkswagen and curled up in the back seat for another night's
sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a very comfortable place, but I have no choice,
because there are people going around trying to steal whatever they
can and I need to protect my store,'' the shopkeeper said.
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks away, in the parking lot of the Adapazari
governor's office, Onder Varlik waited on line for a free handout
of food, wishing he had something left to protect.
</P>
<P>
   His son and grandson were among the more than 12,000 people
killed last week in the earthquake that ripped through the mainly
middle-class cities of northwestern Turkey. The apartment building
where his family lived was destroyed, one of the tens of thousands
of buildings turned into rubble or made uninhabitable by the quake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God we can get food and water without money, because
otherwise I don't know how I would survive,'' said the 65-year-old
man, slowly shuffling along the line for the packets of macaroni
and crackers being handed out by a Turkish television station.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we have is a place in the park where we go to sleep at
night, praying things will be better in the morning,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As Turkey tries to pull itself together after the quake, which
has left as many as 200,000 people without homes, survivors are
struggling to get through each day in cities where there is no
running water, not much electricity, and the threat of disease.
</P>
<P>
   Many live under sheets and blankets strung up in parks, on
basketball courts and on the sides of roads. With savings often
lost in the rubble, workplaces destroyed and families mourning
losses, most people pass the day trying to get basic necessities.
</P>
<P>
   State authorities have turned sports stadiums into open-air
health clinics and depots where people come and pick through
clothing and other items collected by those lucky enough to live
outside the quake area.
</P>
<P>
   Food and water is handed out by state authorities and
volunteers, who generally load up trucks with food staples and
drive through hard-hit neighborhoods, stopping whenever they are
flagged down.
</P>
<P>
   In downtown Adapazari, where nearly every shop has suffered
serious damage and is shut, the park has been turned into a bazaar
of sorts, where everything from aspirin to telephone calls is
available for free, donated by Turkish individuals and companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see my shirt?'' Ozlem Oner, an 18-year-old girl waiting to
pick up some cough syrup for her little brother, asked as she
lifted the edge of her white T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got it free from a big pile of clothes in the stadium, like
the jeans and the sandals, and it's a good thing because when our
apartment building collapsed, we were left with nothing,'' she
said, sending another brother to look for someone handing out
tents.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, survivors trying to make a life for
themselves without homes or belongings also have had to deal with
people trying to take advantage of the disaster by stealing from
abandoned buildings or profiteering on the backs of those now
weakest.
</P>
<P>
   In the first reported instance of looting, Anatolian news agency
said five people were arrested on charges of theft in the Sakarya
province, where Adapazari is located.
</P>
<P>
   In what was once Adapazari's bustling downtown shopping area,
where the Benetton shop is boarded over, the chandelier shop a mess
of broken glass and the jewelry store empty, Turkish soldiers
patrol the streets, letting through only those who can prove they
own a shop there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to stop people to make sure that nobody comes here and
tries to steal things,'' said a Turkish soldier standing guard next
to a clothing store where mannequins had collapsed on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Nese Iscan knows all this first-hand. Someone broke into her
furniture store sometime after the quake, stealing a couple of
chairs and the curtains that were covering the windows.
</P>
<P>
   Now every night she and her brother sit on a worn-out couch
outside the furniture store _ the ceiling has almost collapsed,
making it impossible to remove the items _ watching a small
television they plug into the car and waiting to make sure they do
not lose anything else.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are combing through the rubble of buildings, looking
for gold. This city is finished and we have to do what we can to
protect the little we have left,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
