<SLUG> BC-CHINA-VILLAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOUNTAIN VILLAGE CLINGS TO HOPE OF BETTER LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HESHIJIA VILLAGE, China _ Hailstorms, landslides, and soil so
dry that even a cactus has trouble growing. Those are just three
reasons that Ma Zhende, the local Communist Party secretary in this
dusty, remote community high in the mountains of eastern Qinghai
province, wants to move his entire village to a place 400 miles
away.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, Ma has sent annual appeals to authorities for help
resettling the 296 Muslims who live here in mud houses on a dry
mountainside to a better location. But his pleas went unanswered
until last year, when China hatched a plan to resettle 58,000
farmers from high, barren outposts in eastern Qinghai to land in
the west.
</P>
<P>
   Ma is unaware of the flap over the $40 million World Bank
funding that was voted for the plan but put on hold while
inspectors determine if the loan meets the Bank's guidelines. Ma
believes he and his neighbors will finally be able to leave, and
they are thrilled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our kids can't go to school because the nearest one is'' 3
miles ``uphill and we worry about hailstorms and flash floods,''
said Ma, 58, whose broad straw hat shields him from a scorching
sun.
</P>
<P>
   Ma's family of eight lives on just $43 a year _ the salary his
son earns as a construction worker building roads to Qinghai's
western frontier. In winter, residents borrow grain from other,
better-off villages.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem is erosion. Land here is so dry that
threshing grounds and farming plots that were precariously terraced
into the mountainside have crumbled away.
</P>
<P>
   Ma Yinusi, 50, the elected village chief, urgently motions to
where part of the village has been carried down the mountain in
landslides. Ma's 7-year-old son died here six years ago when the
ground fell out from under him.
</P>
<P>
   Some 500 miles away, authorities point to Xinlong village, a
settlement that dates from 1987, as proof that the best way to help
peasants with poor farmland is to move them.
</P>
<P>
   Xinlong is adjacent to the proposed World Bank project site, and
residents report that with the help of government-funded
irrigation, they enjoy crop yields three to four times higher than
before _ and incomes more than 30 times higher.
</P>
<P>
   In Xinlong, majority Han Chinese live peacefully alongside
minorities _ Tibetan Buddhists and Hui Muslims. They have running
water and a school, and a mosque for the Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more people who come, the more prosperous this region will
become,'' said Ye Youfu, 32, the deputy village chief, who is Han
Chinese. ``Before we moved, we lived in the east where there was a
lot of hail and we didn't even have subsistence living. Now we have
spare cash.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
