<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6513 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-CHINA-QINGHAI-BOS &LR;      08-23 1746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-QINGHAI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESETTLEMENT OF POOR CHINESE FARMERS HOTLY DEBATED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANG KAZANG, China _ A five-hour drive across treacherous
mountain passes from the nearest city, this desolate village of 253
people clings to the side of a barren peak. Here, farmers earn as
little as $35 a year, walk a mile to fetch water, and till land so
infertile that they they go hungry half the year.
</P>
<P>
   Shang Kazang is among thousands of destitute villages in China
that house an estimated 80 million rural poor. But in this village
and others in Qinghai province, bordering Tibet in China's remote
northwest, farmers have become pawns in the debate over a massive
resettlement project.
</P>
<P>
   Daja Meston, a gentle 29-year-old US researcher and former
Buddhist monk, became a casualty of the debate last week. Detained
last Sunday with an Australian scholar for ``illegally''
investigating the project, the Massachusetts man suffered grave
injuries while in Chinese custody.
</P>
<P>
   The government proposes to resettle 58,000 farmers from the dry,
overpopulated eastern region of Qinghai to a mostly empty expanse
in the west. There, China would divert a seasonal river, the
Xiangride, and build a dam to irrigate former wasteland for crops.
</P>
<P>
   However, eastern Qinghai is the birthplace of the Dalai Lama,
the exiled Tibetan Buddhist leader. And thousands of miles away, in
Washington, D.C., and London, a Tibetan lobby including movie stars
and members of the US Congress has allied with environmentalists to
try to block the project.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Chinese government's plan has received initial
approval from the World Bank, whose financial support is required,
millions of dollars in low-interest loans are being withheld while
the bank investigates social concerns raised by critics.
</P>
<P>
   Activists see a Chinese plot to obliterate the minority Tibetan
culture by transplanting farmers, most of whom are ethnic Chinese
or Muslims of varying heritage, onto the western pastureland used
by Tibetan and Mongolian herdsmen. Cynics say Chinese authorities
are less interested in alleviating poverty than in moving thousands
of potential laborers into a region rich in natural gas, oil, zinc,
and lead _ and that they have duped the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of the debate are the people of Shang Kazang, who
must hike three hours to reach a hospital or a school, and whose
only meal, three times a day, is bread. All but three of the
villagers are illiterate.
</P>
<P>
   The debate evokes do-good rhetoric on both sides. China insists
its Western Poverty Alleviation Project is an honest attempt to
help the poor. Opponents counter that the plan fits into China's
unattractive history of forced migrations, environmental
degradation, and oppression of minorities.
</P>
<P>
   US Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers and more than 60 US
senators opposed the World Bank loan, but the bank board voted
narrowly on June 24 to approve the project _ for the first time
overruling a dissenting vote from the United States, the bank's
largest stakeholder. The bank did agree, however, to withhold $40
million earmarked for Qinghai until a bank team and independent
monitors could inspect the area to assess any danger to indigenous
people or the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Some bank officials complained they were rushed. The vote was
taken in late June because on July 1 China would be disqualified by
its wealth from receiving a loan on the most favorable terms. The
$160 million, largely interest-free loan is not due for 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   Already, some are questioning whether China intends to live up
to the promises it made in seeking the loan. A public pledge that
officials, reporters, nongovernmental groups and ``legitimate''
individuals would be allowed unfettered access to the project area
was violated by Meston's detention. Only under strict supervision
was a small group of journalists permitted to visit the area this
month.
</P>
<P>
   The journalists' 1,800-mile escorted trip across the province
turned up widespread support for the resettlement among prospective
migrants and their future neighbors _ at least among those to whom
journalists had access. The trip also exposed some misconceptions
held by overseas opponents.
</P>
<P>
   But interviews with provincial and county authorities also
raised doubts about the government's commitment to preserving
minority religions and culture, and the sensitivity of Chinese
officials to the people they propose to help.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the 60 monks at Jide monastery, a 300-year-old
Tibetan shrine near Shang Kazang village, believe that they and
their temple will be moved along with their worshippers. Asked
about this, surprised authorities sputtered that the villagers
would have to pay for the move themselves _ a ludicrous suggestion,
since they have no money.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, after orating about the lack of food in remote, arid
villages, several officials helped themselves to bags of peas
plucked from a hapless farmer's land.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is no denying that the people tapped for relocation
are barely surviving, and that the few peasants already resettled
in the west have gained a better life. Three times as many people
have applied to move as will be able to do so if China receives its
funding.
</P>
<P>
   Qinghai was closed to foreigners until 1983, and even after 20
years of nationwide economic reform, there is scant foreign
investment here. The province is China's least developed. Its gross
domestic product accounts for less than 0.3 percent of China's
national output, and nearly 40 percent of Qinghai's population,
mostly farmers and herders, live in poverty, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents ask why the government couldn't first try to improve
conditions in the east, instead of moving people hundreds of miles
from their homes and opening the door to conflicts over land and
water between locals and the settlers.
</P>
<P>
   Officials reply that that there was no alternative _ eastern
Qinghai is too barren, mountainous, and overcrowded to sustain its
population.
</P>
<P>
   Critics note that the county where the new villages would be
located is in a historically Tibetan and Mongolian area with an
autonomous regional government. Activists express concern that the
influx of Chinese and Muslim ethnic groups, which will reduce
Tibetans from 23 percent to 15 percent of the population, could
force the assimilation of minorities in Dulan County _ a charge
officials deny.
</P>
<P>
   China has a history of subjugating minorities, especially
Tibetans. Qinghai, where 1 million Tibetans live, was absorbed into
the Chinese empire in the early 18th century. Neighboring
modern-day Tibet was annexed in 1950. Nine years later, China
crushed a rebellion in Tibet, and the Dalai Lama and his loyalists
fled to India. Over the years, China has destroyed thousands of
monasteries and jailed many clerics for remaining loyal to the
Dalai Lama or supporting independence.
</P>
<P>
   However, not a single Tibetan actually lives in the immediate
area of the proposed 126 new villages _ and nearly 3,500 Tibetans
will be moved in under the plan. The people most directly affected
by the project will be Mongol herdsmen, not Tibetans. China has
promised to compensate herders who will lose their pastureland with
$100 each and access to irrigated forage lands.
</P>
<P>
   Qinghai, an expanse 33 times the size of Massachusetts, has been
called the Siberia of China, a sparsely populated, harsh
environment perfect for prison camps, secret arms installations
and, some allege, atomic research facilities, all built after the
Communist Revolution. In the 1950s and '60s, thousands of Chinese
were resettled here to work in weapons factories that had been
moved inland to avoid a feared Soviet attack. ``Rightists'' and
former student radicals were forcibly shipped here, and Dulan
County is believed to have the highest concentration of forced
labor camps in China.
</P>
<P>
   China promises prison labor will not be used in the
resettlement.
</P>
<P>
   Politics and prisoners are far from the minds of most people in
the villages, which lie at an altitude of 12,000 feet or more on a
vast plateau dubbed ``the roof of the world.'' In eastern Qinghai,
the talk was all about survival.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists say that diverting the Xiangride River to
irrigate 47,000 acres may deprive herders of water, kill wildlife,
and damage wetlands. They also fear the environmental damage caused
by exposing the soil to chemical fertilizers and leveling hills to
create farmland that may be subject to wind erosion.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities counter that the project will check erosion and
improve the environment through irrigation, reforestation, and
depopulation of the east, where the population density is at least
70 times that of the west.
</P>
<P>
   The vice governor of Qinghai, Liu Guanghe, is indignant that a
plan to help the poor has been delayed by controversy, and he pins
the blame on ``Dalai Lama cliques.'' Liu said: ``Relations between
us and Dalai are relations between enemies. The issue is heated . .
. while our people are still living in poverty and starvation.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Western critics fear that indigenous herders in Dulan
County will be encouraged to give up their nomadic lives to farm or
labor in mines.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates counter that it is patronizing for Westerners to
glorify a primitive lifestyle instead of celebrating China's
progress. It is also questionable how ``traditional'' the herding
lifestyle is today. Reporters encountered herders shooting pool on
a hillside and others charging tourists for yak rides and
photographs.
</P>
<P>
   Daxicairen, a Mongol chief who supports the resettlement into
Dulan County, said most herders welcome the newcomers, because with
them will come electricity, water, and roads.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, we really thought this nomadic life was good,''
said Daxicairen, 45, whose group rode a full day on horseback from
the Kunlun Mountains to meet with journalists. ``But now that the
country is developing and we visit cities, I myself don't think
this is as good as settling down, growing some crops, and having a
more stable and better life.''
</P>
<P>
   And those who would be resettled are even more enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no land, no water, no doctor . . . no one to take care
of us,'' said La Tai, 37, a Tibetan farmer whose threadbare T-shirt
and face were caked with layers of dirt accumulated in the month
since he was last able to bathe. ``We want to move.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
