<HEADLINE>
A SOUND FUND FOR A 75-YEAR-OLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am writing on behalf of my mother, who is a 75-year-old
widow. Her expenses are currently about $1,100 a month. She
receives about $700 a month in Social Security. She has $34,000
invested in Vanguard LifeStrategy Income fund, and is looking for
an appropriate investment for an additional $30,000 that is now in
a money market account. She also anticipates receiving about
$100,000 later this year from the sale of a house jointly owned
with her brother, and she wants to invest this money wisely.
</P>
<P>
   K.O., Ipswich, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. She could do a lot worse than simply add to her holding in
Vanguard's LifeStrategy Income fund.
</P>
<P>
   Such a move wouldn't really mean that she is placing all her
eggs in one basket, since the LifeStrategy series of funds are
offerings that simply place the assets in a mixture of other
Vanguard funds. In the case of LifeStrategy Income, the current mix
shows nearly half the assets in the Total Bond Market Index fund,
with about a quarter in Vanguard Asset Allocation fund, 19 percent
in its Short-Term Corporate Bond fund, and the rest in its Total
Stock Market Index fund.
</P>
<P>
   When you add the stock holdings in the Asset Allocation fund to
the position in the Total Stock Market fund, it works out to about
a 15 percent reliance on the stock markets. Overall portfolio yield
is 5.1 percent. If she combined the cash now in the money market
account to her LifeStrategy Income position, she could expect a
monthly income stream of $293 _ not enough to meet her anticipated
expenses, but close enough so she shouldn't worry, given the
anticipated proceeds from the real estate sale later this year.
</P>
<P>
   But I think when that lump sum arrives, I'd take a different
course, roughly following the example of the LifeStrategy fund but
without the stock market exposure. With this money, I'd put 50
percent in Vanguard GNMA and 25 percent each in its Short-Term
Corporate Bond and its High-Yield Corporate Bond funds. The latter
two funds represent opposite ends of the risk spectrum, with the
GNMA more or less in the middle. Once such a portfolio was
established, its yield should be more than enough to supply the
needed income stream, and she could simply allow the LifeStrategy
Income account to grow. But before you make up your mind to follow
this suggestion, read the next letter _ and make sure your mother
reads it, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I wish I had waited a while before I invested my money in a
GNMA fund. Shortly after I did, I remember reading a letter in the
paper in which you mentioned that GNMA funds were for a long-term
investor. And, I might add, they're not for real old people of my
age _ which is 87. I invested $64,000 in April of this year, and in
three months it became $61,546. I had no idea how it operated.
There was a man on the radio over the weekend constantly
recommending GNMAs and he never mentioned how it can fluctuate. I
was afraid to stay in as I watched it go down, because of my age. I
think it is a darn shame to keep talking about this fund.
</P>
<P>
   A.K., La Jolla, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I'm sorry you had such a bad experience, but as you can see
from the letter above, I'm still at it, still recommending Ginnie
Maes.
</P>
<P>
   I think these funds are attractive for people who seek an income
stream and who won't have to draw upon their principal for many
years. As you have seen, the current value of these funds can
fluctuate quite significantly when interest rates are unsettled _
losing money as yours did when interest rates increase or when the
markets anticipate rate increases. The opposite happens when
interest rates fall.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, if you look at results over many years, the losses
and the gains tend to cross each other out, leaving the fund owner
with the income stream he presumably sought in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   An example: As this is written, shares of Vanguard GNMA (which
is probably the fund I wrote about in the column you read) stand at
a $9.99 net asset value. The shares ended 1989 at a $9.79 net asset
value.
</P>
<P>
   That's not a lot of change over most of a decade, and although
the returns through the 10 years varied from a loss of 0.95 percent
in 1994 to a gain of 17.04 percent the next year, the 10-year
average annual total return of 7.87 percent is in line with what
people might have expected a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   So the important point that your experience underlines is that
people shouldn't buy such a fund unless they understand that there
will be bad seasons _ typically about two bad years in every decade
_ and that the owners will have to ignore the bad times and ride
them out. It's equally important to take the attitude: the market
gives, and it will most likely take it away later on during the
good seasons for bond funds.
</P>
<P>
   Your experience also underscores another appropriate warning:
GNMA funds are no good for people who can't accept the fluctuations
with ease. There are people who will be upset by a 5 percent
negative swing in principal that the overall experience will be
devastating.
</P>
<P>
   But what a long-term investor can expect from a good GNMA fund
is a return that runs about 1 1/2 percentage points ahead of what
they might have gotten with a money market fund. However, if the
fluctuations make them miserable, forget about that 1 1/2 percent;
a good night's sleep is worth more.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say that owners of GNMA funds shouldn't take
notice when their fund is doing poorly. When results are poor,
investors should check to make sure their fund's returns are in
line with other similar funds; if a fund is consistently
underperforming its peers, that is a cause for a change, whether it
comes at a time when GNMAs are doing well or poorly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am a 46-year-old woman with a chronic illness. I work part
time. I also receive some alimony and I own a two-family home and
receive income from an apartment. I would eventually like to move
to a town house or a smaller single-family home, but cannot afford
to do so without the income I receive from the apartment. I don't
know much about investment, but if I were to sell my home and
invest a portion of the money I receive _ say $40,000 to $50,000 _
would I be able to earn at least $600 a month through investments?
If not, how much would I need to invest, and in what type of
investments?
</P>
<P>
   R.A., Revere, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You would need a 16 percent investment yield to realize a
$600 monthly income stream from a $45,000 investment. Needless to
say, such returns are extremely unlikely, and when they can be
found they are very risky.
</P>
<P>
   Generally speaking, you can expect a prudent fixed-income
portfolio to yield only about 6.5 percent in the current market.
You would need $110,243 invested at that rate to replace that $600
monthly income stream from the leased apartment.
</P>
<P>
   My guess is that the amount you'd have to invest is so far from
what you estimated you could provide that the investment question
becomes academic. But if you can somehow make the arithmetic work,
I'd suggest a portfolio divided among three mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   This would consist of 25 percent positions at the opposite end
of the risk spectrum: a money market fund and a high-yield (or
junk) bond fund, and the rest in a GNMA fund, which holds a
portfolio of government-backed mortgage securities. (Make sure,
also, that you read the two preceding letters, to get a perspective
on how GNMA funds work.)
</P>
<P>
   Most mutual fund companies have offerings in these categories,
and solid examples can be found through Fidelity and Vanguard,
among others. But you should know from the outset that such a
portfolio should be viewed only with a long-term approach, and
money that you might need suddenly should not be put into it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
