<HEADLINE>
WHY DOES ICE CREAM GIVE YOU A HEADACHE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Why does eating ice cream too fast give you a headache?
</P>
<P>
   E.B., Concord, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. ``Nobody knows, really,'' says Dr. Keith Campbell, editor of
the journal Headache and Professor Emeritus of Neurology at the
Mayo Clinic. ``Some people have written about it, but it's really
completely unknown.''
</P>
<P>
   Cold stimulus headache, or ``brain freeze,'' is officially
classified as a distinct form of head pain. Some people get it by
being outside in cold weather without a hat. More commonly people
get that throbbing in either their forehead or the temples while
they're eating something cold, or several seconds after they've
swallowed something cold. Some studies suggest it is more common in
people who suffer migraines. Not everybody gets them.
</P>
<P>
   But why does it happen? There are only theories. One suggests
that cold on the palate or tongue upsets a key nerve that carries
sensation from the mouth to the brain in a way that causes referred
pain. Another theory supposes that the rapid cooling of blood
vessels in the mouth and upper throat makes blood vessels in the
brain momentarily expand and contract, which is commonly thought to
be a cause of headache.
</P>
<P>
   Strictly in the name of science, your How and Why correspondent
conducted an unscientific but fatteningly delicious experiment. A
heaping teaspoon of Hagen Daaz Lemon Swirl was applied to the
palate for 30 seconds, inducing palate pain, but no headache.
Another similar portion was placed on the tongue for 30 seconds.
Tongue freeze, but no brain freeze. A similar portion was then
quickly swallowed, and 30 seconds later, the ice cream headache
pounded for a few seconds.
</P>
<P>
   So why would swallowing something cold cause an ice cream
headache? Dr. Campbell, who gets his when the ice cream is still in
his mouth, says ``We don't know. It hasn't really been studied.''
</P>
<P>
   Pass the vanilla.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why does eating ice cream make you thirsty?
</P>
<P>
   E.B., Concord, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Here's a quiz. Which will make you thirstier: table salt _
sodium chloride _ or table sugar _ sucrose? Barbara Rolls,
Professor of Nutrition at Penn State University, says ``They're
about the same.''
</P>
<P>
   She explains that particles of sodium chloride and sucrose both
act like water magnets drawing water out of our cells. If the cells
shrink too much, they'll die. We have evolved osmo receptors,
special intracellular fluid detectors, to keep levels just right.
If we eat too many salty french fries, or polish off a sugar-rich
banana split, the osmo receptors sense that water is being drawn
out of the cells. They tell the brain to secrete a hormone that
directs the kidneys to hold onto fluid rather than send it out of
the body as urine. Several related body responses trigger the
sensation we describe as thirst.
</P>
<P>
   Ever wonder why drinking soda leaves you thirsty? Blame it on
the fructose, the most common sugar in sweetened foods like candy
and soft drinks. It breaks down faster in the body than sucrose so
it doesn't act as powerfully to draw water out of cells.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write to
How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
