<DOCNO> NYT19990823.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6529 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-COMMENT-CONGRESS-BOS &LR;      08-23 1495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMENT-CONGRESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET'S MAKE USE OF THE LULL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Finally, it is quiet in the nation's capital. Unusually quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is off on its August recess. The war in Kosovo has run
its course. The year of Monica mania that preceded it is well
behind us. Elections are still more than 14 months away, and the
first presidential caucuses are still five months away.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in more than a year, there is little on the
nation's political agenda _ except, perhaps, for the disquiet over
continued episodes of random violence (whose causes Washington may
be peculiarly unsuited to address).
</P>
<P>
   But what about the issues that were eclipsed by the impeachment
effort and the unexpected war that has thus far dominated 1999? We
have let them fade, maybe at our own civic peril.
</P>
<P>
   So here, in our summer interlude, is a list of topics that can
help shape our resumed national conversation.
</P>
<P>
   A national debate about the use of prosperity. Ordinarily
prosperity can be defined as the period between recessions, but the
prosperity that Americans have enjoyed in recent years is
unprecedented. The economy keeps producing jobs; the stock market
keeps inching skyward; welfare rolls keep shrinking; American
expectations keep growing. This prosperity may be a
once-in-a-lifetime phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is fond of saying that the country should fix
the roof while the sun is shining, and now is that time. Big
challenges are easier to confront in peacetime and prosperity than
in war and recession. Among the questions to be debated:
</P>
<P>
   Should a wealthy national government undertake a comprehensive
program to eradicate domestic poverty? What is the responsibility
of a rich nation in a world of the poor, the struggling, and the
striving? How much money should Americans save? Does national
prosperity endanger the nation's spiritual life? What is the
relationship between freedom of markets and freedom of expression?
</P>
<P>
   Some of these questions may have been addressed in graduate
seminars or from church pulpits, but they were seldom confronted in
Washington or on television.
</P>
<P>
   Once bad times return, and they always do, we may regret not
having lingered on such questions in leisure.
</P>
<P>
   A conversation about the role of a superpower in a world without
a single, threatening adversary.
</P>
<P>
   Only in the last decade has a single nation, in this case the
United States, stood completely alone, its power dominant, its
ideology in triumph. The century opened with big-power tensions
between Britain and Germany, with Russia and France playing major
supporting roles. At the end of World War II, the United States,
Britain, and France stood triumphant as Germany rebuilt its armed
forces and its threat to Europe. After World War II, the United
States and Russia began a Cold War that held the world in its
thrall.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the United States has become the lone superpower, the last
threats to American superiority, economic as well as geopolitical,
all but vanished.
</P>
<P>
   That makes now a good time to have a sober discussion about the
role the United States wants to, and should, play in this new
world, a question that is even more urgent in the wake of the
unsettling but successful war in the Balkans. How should we respond
to the kinds of dangers _ terrorism, drug warfare, cyberconflict,
weapons of mass destruction _ that a superpower faces at a time
when there isn't one obvious threat, like Nazism or Soviet
communism?
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily incidents such as the bombings of American embassies
in Kenya and Sudan might have put such a discussion at the top of
our national agenda, but they didn't. Nor did the brief war in
Yugoslavia. Nor has Saddam Hussein's stubborn refusal to honor
United Nations inspections. The death of King Hussein in Jordan,
which underlined the fragility of peace in the Middle East, didn't
prompt it either.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we were discussing the meaning of obstruction of
justice, there was another debate going on _ on the role of America
in the modern world,'' says former White House press secretary
Michael D. McCurry. ``Yet that was back on page A56, and we didn't
pay much attention to it.''
</P>
<P>
   A national seminar on questions of aging. This is a country that
is growing older in a world where issues affecting the elderly _
housing, pensions, health care, changing lifestyles _ are fast
crowding out conventional political issues. These issues are
particularly acute in Europe and Russia, but they are no less
urgent here.
</P>
<P>
   Here, after all, are the elements of a crisis: Social Security
trust funds will probably remain adequately financed until 2032,
but after that the annual income to the program will only cover
about three-quarters of the benefits. Costs are rising far more
swiftly than income. By 2013, the cost of benefits paid by the
old-age and survivors' trust fund will exceed the income of the
trust fund. In 1960, there were more than five workers for each
Social Secuity beneficiary. Right now there are more than three
workers for each beneficiary. By 2030, there will be only two
workers for each beneficiary.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to the advice of the Social Security trustees:
``Extensive public discussions and analysis of the practical
implications of alternatives (to the current Social Security
financing structure) is essential to developing the broad support
needed to enact any Social Security reform legislation. . . . We
must use the coming months to find changes that effectively
guarantee a basic level of income for the aged, disabled, and
survivors of deceased workers.''
</P>
<P>
   That call went out almost a year ago. The discussion is overdue.
</P>
<P>
   A searching examination of the role that regulation _
particularly Washington regulation _ plays in American life.
</P>
<P>
   Washington is full of the clash of two passionate armies, one
contending that there is too much regulation, the other maintaining
that there is not enough. Together they represent the most critical
question of political philosophy facing Washington today.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the 20th anniversary of airline deregulation, began
with growing recognition that the nation's air-transport system
needed fundamental changes, and with the promise that there might
be a serious debate about the commercialization of the air-traffic
control system, deregulating airports themselves, and perhaps
allocation of takeoff and landing slots by a bidding process. But
debate on the topics has yet to resume full flight.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican initiative signed into law by Clinton provided an
expedited mechanism for lawmakers to challenge new regulations, as
a way to rein in out-of-control bureaucrats. But distracted
lawmakers did not use this new tool once in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Congress passed landmark legislation in both 1996 and 1997 to
regulate the use of pesticides and to streamline the Food and Drug
Administration's decisions on labels describing health claims for
various food products. The Environmental Protection Agency and the
FDA were expected to finalize the scientific policies that would
form the basis for their decisions. The public is still waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Experts and lobbyists from banking and securities interests and
from consumer groups agree that an overhaul of financial services
is at least a decade overdue, mostly as a result of enormous
changes in technology and a dramatic restructuring of the banking
world. Indeed, bankers and consumers are operating under rules
developed after the Great Depression. But again, legislation that
was expected to address the problem got lost in the impeachment
shuffle. It's time to revive it.
</P>
<P>
   A broad colloquium on integrity and ethics in American civic
life. For all the times that the words ``truth'' and ``honesty''
were tossed around during the presidential sex scandal, the country
never had a serious conversation about ethics in government.
</P>
<P>
   ``A democracy is built on the foundations of public trust and
public participation,'' Common Cause, the citizens' lobby, said in
a publication released last winter. ``The current campaign-finance
system _ in Washington and in many states and localities across the
country _ has eroded both.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, is the view of would-be reformers, although
certainly not of the elected officials who have been beneficiaries
of the current system. The point isn't that one side or the other
is right. The point is that this debate never pierced the din of
the capital.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Congress returns in just over two weeks, it has a chance to
resume serious lawmaking for the first time in a year. Voters, too,
have a chance to turn their attention to matters that will shape
our nation as we enter a new century. Let's hope the national
conversation that follows provides a richer discourse than that of
the last year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David M. Shribman is the chief of the Globe's Washington Bureau.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-99 1406EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
