<DOCNO> NYT19990823.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 14:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6533 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-PUERTO-RICO-ART-BOS &LR;      08-23 1651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUERTO-RICO-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAILED PUERTO RICO ACTIVIST WON'T RENOUNCE CAUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DANBURY, Conn. _ Leaning against the cinderblock walls of her
jail cell, Alejandrina Torres reaches into one of the envelopes her
husband has mailed every week for the past 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, she always finds a love letter _ ``We'll be together
again one day,'' he reminds her _ along with writings from Puerto
Rican independence groups updating her on the campaign to free her.
</P>
<P>
   The romantic notes and the political manifestos reflect Torres's
odd mix of roles: wife, grandmother, revolutionary.
</P>
<P>
   Torres, 60, is serving a 35-year sentence in a federal
penitentiary here for her involvement in an underground guerrilla
organization that bombed US political and military sites between
1973 and 1983 in an attempt to free Puerto Rico from US control.
</P>
<P>
   After 16 years of living inside a sterile cell under the eyes of
armed guards, Torres could walk out of prison soon if she accepts
an offer from President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Under mounting pressure, Clinton on Aug. 11 offered to commute
the sentences of Torres and 10 others in prisons across the
country. But the Puerto Rican nationalists reject the strings
attached: notifying probation officers when they travel to other
cities, and avoiding contact with each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they are proposing is to gag us,'' Torres said in an
interview with the Globe. ``Anything that has to do with exercising
our right to self-determination would be a thing of the past. They
think if we keep our mouths shut their burden of colonialization
will go away.''
</P>
<P>
   Torres, a bright-eyed woman with deep frown lines, is a world
removed from the chaotic demonstrations of the 1970s and 1980s,
when she chanted ``End US Imperialism! Free Puerto Rico!'' and
lived by Malcolm X's provocative mantra _ ``By any means
necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI contends she was a member of the Armed Forces of
National Liberation, known by its Spanish acronym FALN, which took
responsibility for dozens of bombings, including planting pipe
bombs at the New York City headquarters of several major
corporations as well as the New York Public Library.
</P>
<P>
   Although the 11 who have been offered clemency were not involved
in attacks that resulted in injuries, prosecutors branded them as
terrorists. Authorities say FALN violence was responsible for six
deaths and more than 100 injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Torres says she no longer believes in violence as a political
tool: ``There was a time when that was necessary. I guess each
generation has its own method.''
</P>
<P>
   But the fire that has fueled her revolutionary spirit still
burns. If anything, her time in prison has only hardened her views.
</P>
<P>
   She said that whenever she is released, she will continue to
demonstrate against the US government for oppressing her people _
even if it takes another five years when she is eligible for
parole.
</P>
<P>
   The 14 conditions of release set by the Clinton administration
include monthly meetings with probation officers, restrictions on
travel, and a prohibition against associating with people who have
criminal records. Because many ``independentistas'' have criminal
records, that stipulation would essentially bar Torres from meeting
or demonstrating with her compatriots.
</P>
<P>
   To agree to the conditions of release, she said, would be to
revoke her First Amendment right to free speech. Supporters of
civil liberties agree and have taken on that fight.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston and other cities with large Puerto Rican populations,
a new campaign is under way: A call for the unconditional release
of all 15 independentistas _ the 11 offered clemency plus four
others _ who they call ``political prisoners.'' Among those
pressuring Clinton to free them are Bishop Desmond Tutu, the Rev.
Jesse Jackson, and Coretta Scott King.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are Puerto Rican patriots,'' said Marcos Vilar, national
coordinator of the Committee to Free Puerto Rican Prisoners-of-War
and Political Prisoners. ``The prisoners are to Puerto Rico what
George Washington, Thomas Jefferson, and all the founding fathers
are to the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gene ``Tito'' Roman, the former director of the
Massachusetts regional office of Puerto Rican Federal Affairs, says
people want to remake them as heroes, but they are not.
</P>
<P>
   ``The romantic vision of the terrorist group FALN as patriots
obscures the violence and destruction they have wrought since the
1970s,'' Roman said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Poor beginnings
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Torres grew up in San Lorenzo, a pueblo in rural Puerto Rico,
where lush vegetation and towering palm trees sweep over the land.
Her father died of stomach cancer when she was an infant, leaving
her mother to support 10 children.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother rolled cigars, her hands stained greenish-brown from
the tobacco. When Torres was 11, the family moved to New York
City's Hell's Kitchen neighborhood, where her older sister, who was
a young adult, helped care for the family.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Torres became convinced that Puerto Ricans would
never benefit from US Commonwealth status. She said America holds
on to the territory because it is a strategic military site. She
said most Puerto Ricans are against becoming independent because
they fear they won't survive economically without the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   But many Puerto Ricans living in the United States are just as
poor as the ones living on the island _ proof, she says, that
institutional racism in America will continue to keep Puerto Ricans
impoverished.
</P>
<P>
   As she grew older, working as a secretary for Broadway
Congregational Church, a congregation active in the civil rights
movement, she got swept up in the struggle. Her future husband, the
Rev. Jos Alberto Torres, marched in Selma and Montgomery, Ala.,
with the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when they moved to Chicago in the mid-1960s and married,
Torres and her husband took up the cause of Puerto Ricans, saying
they were voiceless. Through her advocacy work at a Chicago church,
she said she learned that Latino children were humiliated by
teachers in school and their parents could not find jobs _
especially if they spoke with accents.
</P>
<P>
   She saw a link between their impoverished lives on the mainland
and what she calls the legacy of colonialism: the brainwashing of
children in Puerto Rican schools and the US control of Puerto Rican
trade and economy.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, when a small group of Puerto Rican high school students
fought what they called a Eurocentric curriculum, Torres and
several others founded Puerto Rican High School in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was always full of love and singing songs,'' said Marvin
Garca, who grew up in Torres's neighborhood and is now director of
the school. ``She always had a smile, was always full of
laughter.''
</P>
<P>
   During the day, Torres worked as a caseworker at the Cook County
Department of Public Aid, helping Cuban refugees. She counseled
teens at the school after work. And during her free time, she went
to every Puerto Rican independence demonstration she could. But she
adamantly denies she ever helped make bombs, or conspired to blow
up military sites.
</P>
<P>
   She said the FBI tracked her family because her stepson, Carlos
Alberto Torres, was a fugitive. Authorities, she said, found
explosives in his apartment. He is now serving time in a federal
prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were always under surveillance,'' Torres said. ``You
couldn't miss them.''
</P>
<P>
   As a pro-independence activist, she said she offered assistance
to anyone involved in her political struggle who asked for help.
She admitted helping a wanted man escape the country in the late
1970s, but never asked his name.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors told another story during the 1983 trial of the 15
alleged Puerto Rican nationalists. They said Torres and the others
possessed explosives and were plotting to bomb a US military
installation near Chicago. The Puerto Rican 15, as they were
called, did not contest the charges, saying they did not recognize
US authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``In no way did I expect justice in the court of my oppressor,''
Torres said. The 15 hoped in vain that the trial would be played
out in an international court.
</P>
<P>
   During her years in prison, including the last five years at the
Federal Correctional Institute in Danbury, Torres has built a life
similar to the one she led outside: She teaches inmates how to
read, and found work at the prison chapel. She makes 40 cents an
hour putting together the church calendar, service programs, and
writing the church bulletin in English and Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, who still lives in Chicago, calls weekly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't talk about the struggle. When I talk to her, I blow
her kisses and tell her I love her,'' said Torres, who is 75. ``But
I continue to be an independentista. She continues to be an
independentista.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Puerto Rican 15
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Puerto Rican 15 have each served 16 years of sentences that
ranged from 35 to 90 years in prison _ time that many, including
Clinton, agree does not fit the crime.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, four ``independentistas'' who had done worse _ stormed
the US House of Representatives in 1954, unfurled the Puerto Rican
flag, then fired gunshots, wounding five congressmen _ were
pardoned by President Jimmy Carter in 1979. Carter also pardoned
Oscar Collazo, a Puerto Rican who was convicted in 1950 of trying
to kill President Harry S. Truman.
</P>
<P>
   Though she wants to see her mother free, Catalina Torres, a
chiropractor in Syracuse, said that if her mother signed the
agreement, it would be the same as admitting she committed a crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother is not a criminal. What she did was not wrong,''
Torres said. ``There is nothing wrong with fighting against
colonialism.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-99 1407EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990823.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6534 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-ARTS-WEB-2TAKES-BOS &LR;      08-23 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-WEB-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DEN INTRODUCES INTERACTIVE ENTERTAINMENT VIA THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA MONICA, Calif. _ It's twilight on a warm Friday evening,
too early to prowl the subterranean Los Angeles night life, yet too
late to be click-clacking away at the office. But at a funky,
two-story converted warehouse here, workers show no signs of
slowing down for the weekend. Some are gathered for an impromptu
cake-and-beer celebration, where a dressed-down executive
introduces 40 new employees. Others remain cheerfully glued to
their workstations, staring at monitors as if they contain the
great secrets of the universe.
</P>
<P>
   The intense young computer heads and self-conscious creative
types, most in their early 20s, eagerly pop out of their cubicles
to explain the place to a visitor. The Concept is Big, these
staffers say. It's the biggest thing to hit Hollywood since D. W.
Griffith invented the epic. It's bigger than the talkies. It's
bigger than television. It's bigger than _ gasp _ MTV. It's a brand
new media for a brave new world, they claim.
</P>
<P>
   Who are these self-promoters and what is this place? What's the
Big Idea? The company is called Digital Entertainment Network, or
simply the Den. ``We're trying to build something, and it's going
to change the world,'' says the Den's director of marketing, Adam
Solomon, a kind of combination cruise director and spin doctor. The
concept is this: The Den aims to develop Internet-specific
programming geared for Generation Y, today's high school and
college students, ages 14 to 24. This generation, estimated at 60
million and also known as Echo Boomers, grew up with computers and
faxes and cell phones and beepers: They're used to
``multitasking,'' and they're at home getting their information
through one wire or another, often through more than one at once.
</P>
<P>
   Den's low-budget programs, aimed at such narrowly defined groups
as gay teens, Christian young adults, and punk rockers, will be
delivered via streaming video on the Internet; all shows will be
interactive, with built-in e-commerce mechanisms and plenty of
click-on features that provide as much or as little information as
an individual viewer wants. These shows will be available on
demand, 24-7 (Netspeak for every hour, every day). Each segment
(which costs anywhere from $10,000 to $50,000 to produce, less
expensive than network television and with a shorter turnaround
time) lasts a mere six or seven minutes, the ideal length for the
generation that is growing up with a mouse in one hand and a remote
in the other.
</P>
<P>
   That's the basic idea, and Solomon discusses it with the zeal of
a scientist pondering the cure for cancer. Solomon leads a
high-energy tour of the warehouse, racing by the conference room
(``Ikea meets money''), the recording studio (``Austin Powers meets
the Jetsons''), and then bounding up to the second floor for a demo
of the site (which is at http://www.den.net). It begins with a
promotional video, in which the familiar NBC peacock logo morphs
into a stuffed holiday turkey. Next up is a preview of ``Frat
Ratz,'' a soap-opera series featuring testosterone-driven students
and their long-suffering yet lovely girlfriends.
</P>
<P>
   Shallow plot aside, the series does experiment with
interactivity. In one segment, an actor who is shaving delivers a
plug for the razor, just as actors did in the early television of
the '50s and '60s (and in ``The Truman Show''). Viewers can click
on a logo and purchase the razor or surf over to the razor
company's home page. Likewise, when music plays during any Den
show, viewers can stop the program, click to get more information
about the artist, read articles, or buy the album. They can also
stop the show at any point to get more information about their
favorite characters.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of interactive programming _ also known as TV Plus,
telefusion, or convergence _ is suddenly all the rage in Hollywood,
and investors and sponsors are viewing it as the Next Big Thing in
entertainment. And the Den is growing exponentially. Launched in
1998 by three entrepreneurs, it began 1999 with 10 employees.
Today, it has 220 staffers spread out in six buildings, including
the original warehouse. It has raised $26 million so far, with
funds from prominent venture capitalists as well as Dell Computer
Corp. and Microsoft Corp. And Den has signed up Pepsi and Ford
Motor Co. as charter sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking for a fresh approach to reaching the Echo
Boomers,'' says Dave Ropes, Ford's director of corporate
advertising and integrated marketing. ``It's no question that this
generation has a short attention span; they want to be entertained
in shorter lengths and shorter soundbites.''
</P>
<P>
   Interactive entertainment could be the next gold mine in
cyberspace, but so far, mainstream networks have offered only
regular television programming complemented with a chat rooom or a
fan site on line. ``Convergence usually means a separated
experience,'' says Jim Ritts, the Den's chief executive officer,
pointing out that running between the television and the computer
is hardly an integrated experience. ``It's like saying, `I have a
potato, and I put plastic eyes and a nose and a mouth on it, and
now I have an animated character.' No. It's not an animated
character. It's Mr. Potatohead.''
</P>
<P>
   The Den isn't toying around, though, and neither are several
other companies racing to enter the market before the networks and
film studios offer their own made-for-the-Net entertainment. These
media companies seem to be popping up every day and include
ventures like WireBreak.com, Brilliant Digital Entertainment, and
Honkworm Interactive. Den's primary competitor is the New
York-based Pseudo.com, which has launched a network of Internet
talk shows and bills itself as ``TV you can't get on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Pseudo.com founder Joshua Harris considers Den a formidable and
respectable competitor. ``If I had to say anything about their
programming, it's a little too much like regular broadcast TV,''
Harris says. ``Den and Pseudo, not in that order, I hope, are
dogfighting it out to get a toehold in a market that I know will
clobber regular old television in the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   But even Harris admits that the technology isn't quite there yet
to satisfy most viewers. Den targets its programs for machines with
Internet connection speeds of 56K or higher _ the faster the
connection, the better the quality. But the New York-based Jupiter
Communications predicts that only 20 percent of all computers will
have broadband Internet access by 2002, creating an accessibility
problem. And some analysts are skeptical in general about the
quality of streaming-video technology, which features grainy images
on matchbox-sized screens.
</P>
<P>
   But others are impressed with the Den model. ``They are creating
unique content and not just reproducing something else on line,''
says Mark Hardie, senior analyst at the Cambridge-based Forrester
Research. ``What normally happens is producers add a chat room to a
situation comedy and think they're doing programming for the Net.
That's nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-99 1408EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990823.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6535 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-ARTS-WEB-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-BO     08-23 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-WEB-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 SANTA MONICA, Calif.: ... That's nonsense.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some folks in Hollywood, however initially slow to respond to
the Internet, are beginning to get it. Most film studios and
television networks are currently exploring ways to offer
Net-specific entertainment; Warner Bros. Interactive, for one, will
launch a Net entertainment portal, called Entertaindom, later this
year. David Wertheimer, former president of Paramount Digital
Entertainment, launched WireBreak.com, a Web operation that is
developing short interactive shows; when he left Paramount last
fall, he says, colleagues told him he was crazy, but the same
people are now asking for jobs. ``It's suddenly hip and trendy to
be in entertainment on the Internet,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Hip and trendy is what La-La Land is all about, and so far, the
buzz about the Den has been mostly positive _ with one major
concern. ``They are to be saluted for being one of the leaders
moving the Internet into the entertainment field,'' says Jim
Moloshok, president of Warner Bros. Online. ``But from what I've
seen to date, all they're doing is creating poorly written
television shows and streaming them on the Web. Bad scripts and bad
acting aren't going to appeal to the public just because you're
streaming them on line.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, most of Den's programs follow the linear-story format of
traditional television, be it talk show, sitcom, or sci-fi drama
(see accompanying story). ``That's a fair note at this time,'' says
Den president David Neuman. ``Most of the shows are very linear and
true to the Aristotelian storytelling method. But over time, you'll
see more innovative programming. You're literally watching the
previews.
</P>
<P>
   ``But name one network show done with Asian teenagers,'' he
continues. ``Name one show about punk rockers. Name one show about
Hispanic teenagers. This is the most diverse generation in history,
and we think it would be bad business and bad karma to leave
anybody out.''
</P>
<P>
   Den was producing its diverse programming before the NAACP
criticized the television industry this summer for its
overwhelmingly white fall lineup; that backlash might pay off for
the Den. ``I'm disappointed with the lack of commitment television
makes to show the texture of America,'' says Jack Johnson, producer
of a Den show about hip-hop music. ``The beauty of the Internet is
that we're able to take that risk.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Den prides itself on being a multicultural,
youth-oriented company, its top executive suites are occupied by
middle-aged white men. And one of its premiere shows, a digital
sci-fi thriller called ``Royal Standard,'' is directed by
53-year-old Randall Kleiser, best known for such Boomer teen movies
as ``The Blue Lagoon'' and ``Grease.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, the network is striving to develop a show for every
possible subculture of Generation Y, from punk rockers and
hip-hoppers to skateboarders, surfers, and computer geeks. This
approach is called ``narrowcasting,'' and it's what the Internet
does best. ``A lot of us are really sick of MTV because it doesn't
cater to different subculture preferences,'' says Leo Zhao, a
24-year-old Den designer. ``Me, I'm into post-dance electronic
music, and I'm bored with 99.9 percent of the stuff out there on
television.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhao is not just an employee: He's a member of the Den's target
audience. The top brass want today's youth to describe themselves
as the ``Den Generation,'' the same way the Gen-Xers identify with
MTV. But will it work? Will Den capture the attention of a
generation or will it just slip away, like so many other Internet
startups?
</P>
<P>
   The denizens, no doubt, are banking on the company's mix of
industry connections and youthful enthusiasm. The top executives
have ties to Disney Television and Channel One (the controversial
in-school network), while the programming and producing staffers
reflect the pop culture that blooms on the streets of Los Angeles,
with 20-somethings sporting tattoos and piercings and various
unnatural shades of hair. ``I feel very much at home in this
environment,'' says Zhao.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone who sets foot in the place learns to talk the talk _
and they might as well, since they all have stock options.
Music-industry veteran Gary Gersh signed on in June to head the new
Den Music Group; he picked up the company line instantly. ``We
think of ourselves as NATO for the music industry; we're here for
everyone to use and interact with,'' he says, explaining that bands
signed by Den Music Group can be featured on other Den programs,
including the dramas and the talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   Comparisons to international peacekeeping forces, of course,
mean nothing if the kids don't come to the site. Den debuted its
preview site in May (in what Internet folks call a ``soft''
launch), featuring a few segments of 10 video shows and limited
interactive features. The revamped site (the ``hard'' launch) will
be unveiled in mid-October, with 30 shows, chat rooms, and other
popular Web features. The company is mounting a marketing campaign
on college campuses and in funky hangouts and youthful meccas,
trying to pull off the kind of buzz that turned the low-budget
horror flick ``The Blair Witch Project'' into a phenomenon. The
campaign, with posters designed by Zhao, will hit Boston next week.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stated mission is to provide today's youth with
``a revolutionary replacement for the passive, brain-killing
experience of watching network and cable television.'' Is its
programming really that revolutionary? Industry critics say no, but
Den staffers are convinced they are on the cusp of a radical media
realignment. ``A lot of what we're doing is still rhetoric, but
we're in the process of turning it into a reality,'' says Solomon.
</P>
<P>
   And Ritts adds, ``It will be just as different in 90 days as it
was 90 days ago. This is a network of, by, and for the Y
Generation. So we better be nimble. We better adjust. And we better
be fluid.''
</P>
<P>
   And they better stick around on a Friday night. Solomon, for
one, knows he ought to be home with his toddler, 17-month-old
Theodore. ``You have to understand; we're defining a brand new
medium,'' he says. And as for Zhao, he works all night, every
night, not necessarily at the office. ``It's part of my job to
scope out the underground of LA night life so I can be in touch
with the newest trends,'' he says. It's unclear whether those fads
will play in Peoria, but for the young programmers in Santa Monica,
if one trend loses its luster, the next Big Thing is just a few
clicks away.
</P>
</TEXT>
