   &UR; INTERNATONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ORAHOVAC (Orahovac) _ Albanians at a roadblock turn back
Russian peaceekeepers headed to this flashpoint town where
Albanians want Serbs to be held for war crimes and don't want
Russian troops (seen as pro-Serb) to come in. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-QUAKE (Dateline to kum) _ Developments in the aftermath
of the earthquake: The government admits mistakes in its rescue
efforts; a three-year-old boy is pulled alive from rubble after
being trapped six days. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   (See also SCI-QUAKE-LESSONS, on the Science Times budget.
</P>
<P>
   LOCKERBIE-VICTIMS (Washington) _ Relatives of the Lockerbie
victims meet with U.S. officials because they're afraid the Libyan
suspects in the bombing will get off the hook. By David Stout.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIANS-LAUNDER (New York) _ Developments in the investigation
of money laundering by Russian organized crime through the Bank of
New York. By Raymond Bonner and Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.N. (Undated) _ A report expected from the
secretary-general on the status of the Iraqi oil-for-food program.
By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-CRASH (Hong Kong) _ As investigators pored over the
smoldering wreckage of a China Airlines plane that crash-landed
here Sunday night, aviation experts began asking some hard
questions about Taiwan's flagship carrier. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RESEARCH-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Universities teamed up with
lobbyists to obtain nearly $800 million from Congress last year in
obscurely written ``earmarks'' for multimillion-dollar studies in
wood research, papaya fungus, bridge-building, agribusiness and
other academic oddities. Almost all the earmarks were inserted,
without public debate, in closed-door conferences. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-STORM (Corpus Christi) _ Developments after Hurricane Bret
skirted populated areas to land on top of the tiny border town of
Sarita, where the 1,000 town residents are huddled in shelters.
Bret has been downgraded to tropical storm, but flood threat
remains. By Jim Yardley.
</P>
