<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6539 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIES-BROOKS-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     08-23 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-BROOKS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 NEW YORK: ... to fail.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's as if Albert Brooks goes through life skinless. He has no
defense against that one person in 10,000 who doesn't think he's
funny, or that one review that isn't thumbs up, four stars, instant
classic.
</P>
<P>
   As his pal Nanas puts it, ``In this business they don't pay you
for being a great comic artist, they pay you for putting asses in
the seats.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Muse,'' there's a sequence where Brooks, a recently
demoted screenwriter, is denied a parking pass to the studio and
trudges endlessly from one end of the lot to the other for a
meeting. It seems he'll never get there. In that scene it's easy to
see the Keaton-Brooks connection. Both know that the end of the
painful journey will even be more painful. But they keep it up
anyway. Trudging along. Sweating. Hoping against hope.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The limousine swings up to CBS. The guard tells Brooks how funny
he is and asks the publicist to take a picture of them. He's got
the camera ready. Brooks agrees and smiles and goes upstairs.
</P>
<P>
   His interview is delayed. While he stands off to the side
watching another guest assemble a wall of the latest handbags, a
producer apologizes for the brief delay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to go to a bulletin,'' he said. Over at the anchor
desk, the newscaster is doing a few facial warm-ups as an aide
advises her to keep her chin up, avoiding the deadly hints of a
double chin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just like `Broadcast News,' '' whispers Brooks, referring
to the James L. Brooks (no relation) film that garnered Brooks an
Oscar nomination as best supporting actor for playing the sharp,
but perpetully perspiring, newsman Aaron Altman. This time, Brooks
isn't sweating.
</P>
<P>
   The newscaster updates the disaster in Turkey, where the death
toll from the earthquake now stands in the thousands. Brooks leans
over and asks with a straight face, ``You think people dying in
Turkey is more important than my movie?'' Then he smiles. He smiles
that wonderfully ironic smile we saw on his face when Holly Hunter
dumped him for William Hurt in ``Broadcast News.'' It's a smile
that says he recognizes full well that the entertainment business
is inconsequential when compared to disease and disaster but,
dammit, if you're in it you might as well do the best job you can.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brooks thought his difficulties getting financing for his
pictures was over after the success of ``Mother,'' the hilarious
story of a middle-aged man moving back home with his mother, with
Brooks and Debbie Reynolds as the stars. But when he showed the
executives the best script he and co-writer Monica Johnson had ever
written, they turned him down. Too ``inside.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Too inside? What does that mean?,'' asks Brooks. ``Funny's
funny. Dramatic's dramatic. It's a good movie.''
</P>
<P>
   So Brooks moved his office over to Universal. But he shot some
scenes near his old Paramount office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to pay a location fee to go back to Paramount,'' says
Brooks, givig no clue whether this is a joke or not. ``I signed up
under an assumed name. Jackie Chan.''
</P>
<P>
   While Brooks jokes about it, it drives him crazy that he gets
all these critical accolades and still has to beg a studio to make
his movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe not after this one,'' he sighs. ``But that's what I said
after the last one.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Within a few moments, Brooks is back in the car heading to the
West End for the series of satellite interviews with radio stations
from coast to coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``They like to fool listeners at these radio stations into
thinking I'm not in New York but in Salt Lake City, say,'' says
Brooks. Then he adopts a perfectly pitched DJ's voice. `` `So, Mr.
Brooks, how are you spending your time here in Salt Lake City?'
`Well, this mormning I went downtown and drank coffee in front of a
Mormon.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks is doing his own warm-up.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks settles into his seat at a radio console, like a pilot
ready for take-off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if they see my movie as long as they buy a
ticket. . . . Buy a ticket,'' he says to John Gambling of New
York's WOR. ``Aug. 27.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Bernard of KQRS asks about the cameos played by various
stars and directors _ including Cybill Shepherd, Wolfgang Puck,
Jennifer Tilly, Lorenzo Lamas, Martin Scorsese, Rob Reiner, and
James Cameron. ``I told Cameron the movie was funnier than
`Titanic,' '' says Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   He's on a roll. ``Aug. 27.''
</P>
<P>
   The first thing Kevin Matthews of Chicago's WXCD wants to know
is about Sharon Stone's nude scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know where you're coming from,'' says Brooks, ``and it's a
pretty pitiful place. It was all her idea, to take her clothes off.
It was appropriate. Sharon's great in the picture. She's got a
great comic touch. She really does. Go see it. Aug. 27.''
</P>
<P>
   But there's a bit of a problem. For virtually every interview,
Brooks must explain what the title means.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zeus had nine daughters,'' he says into the microphone for the
seventh time in an hour. ``One of them ends up living in Hollywood.
. . . You see all the crap coming out of that place _ you wonder
how that could be true. But it is. Trust me on this.''
</P>
<P>
   As the DJ comes on from Planet 96.3 somewhere in the Midwest, a
news bulletin pops up on the CNN television monitor in the radio
studio, saying there's an iceberg off the southern coast of South
America. It must be headed straight for Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been laughing at you a long time,'' says the guy from
Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks pauses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God, I'm a comedian.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
