<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990823.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6541 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIES-HORROR-BOS &LR;      08-23 1203
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-HORROR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW HORROR THRILLERS SCARING UP BIG PROFITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By IAN SHAPIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scary movies are roaring, moaning, and screeching their way into
America's cineplexes _ and they're swathed in greenbacks.
</P>
<P>
   This summer's horror movies involving some element of the
supernatural have grossed about $360 million, led by ``The Sixth
Sense'' and ``The Blair Witch Project.'' The scare tactics began in
May with ``The Mummy'' and ``The 13th Floor'' and continued with
``The Haunting,'' ``Lake Placid,'' and ``Deep Blue Sea.'' The
onslaught of fright will continue with the release of at least a
half-dozen paranormal thrillers in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Sixth Sense,'' a psychological ghost thriller starring
Bruce Willis, eclipsed the super-popular ``The Blair Witch
Project'' when it opened Aug. 6 and has been No. 1 at the box
office for three weekends in a row _ earning $107.7 million in
three weeks. The only other summer movie to hold consecutive weeks
at No. 1 was ``Star Wars: Phantom Menace.'' ``Blair Witch'' has
earned $120.5 million to date.
</P>
<P>
   The success of these movies is defining a new horror genre
tinged with a classic style that harkens back to Alfred Hitchcock's
technique of maintaining a taut tension between the characters and
unseen terror.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond McNally, a professor at Boston College who teaches ``The
History of Horror'' film course, believes it's the little things
making the big effects _ and big dollars for the horror industry.
He said audiences are more sophisticated now and perhaps jaded
about the Freddie Krueger-style effects of 1984's ``Nightmare on
Elm Street.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Slasher movies went repetitive. I am bored with the slasher.
He's some freak. He's insane. Most of the time, they're just
funny,'' he said. ``You have to be able to suspend disbelief _ if I
don't believe it, it's ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Crispin Miller, a media studies professor at New York
University, says the success of these movies is rooted in
contemporary lifestyles. ``It takes more artfulness to frighten
audiences. (In `Blair Witch), the prospect of that solitude is so
scary because we're not used to it. How many of us can live without
our e-mail, beepers, or TV?''
</P>
<P>
   It's not just a summer fondness for these movies. The fall
season promises a new batch of witches, ghosts, and spirit
elements. Slated for release in mid-September is ``Stir of
Echoes,'' a paranormal thriller about a suburban father plagued by
clairvoyant visions. Then October and November will bring ``The
Astronaut's Wife,'' in which Johnny Depp is taken over by a
mysterious outerspace element; ``Lost Souls'' starring Winona Ryder
as a conspiracy theorist out to stop Satan from wreaking havoc on
Manhattan; ``Stigmata,'' a Boston-based story about a woman
possessed by an evil, violent, and invisible phenomenon; and ``The
End of Days,'' starring Arnold Schwarzenegger fends off the devil
(surprise!) in a doomsday battle. The year wraps up with a Roman
Polanski film called ``The Ninth Gate,'' opening in December.
</P>
<P>
   To outsiders, this may seem like the calculated work of industry
machinations and grand plans. But to insiders, the phenomenon is
simply Hollywood happenstance.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a zeitgeist _ people get hold of the same idea,''
said Kirk Honeycutt, chief film critic for Hollywood Reporter, a
daily trade magazine based in Los Angeles. ``When a producer has an
idea, he hires a bunch of writers. Everybody comes back with their
own pitches and screenplays, but only one is used _ and then
suddenly there are all these scripts floating around.''
</P>
<P>
   However, directors of such movies like to chalk up the recent
horror fix to a combination of serendipity and a response to last
summer's self-referential and witty movies _ ``Scream 2'' and ``I
Still Know What You Did Last Summer'' _ that relied on comedic
tactics more than scare tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``People wanted to make scary movies because there really
weren't any more of them,'' said David Koepp, director of ``Stir of
Echoes.'' ``You don't know you're part of a trend when it starts _
it just sort of happens _ otherwise, it's implied that there is
some logic to Hollywood, which is not the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kind of movies fill two needs,'' Koepp added. ``One is
the audience needs to be scared, which goes back to peek-a-boo,
when you spring out and scare a kid out of his wits. The second is
that everyone wants to believe in an afterlife _ and ghost stories
are just intensely comfortable notions.''
</P>
<P>
   M. Night Shyamalan, writer and director of ``The Sixth Sense,''
believes in the less-is-more theory of filmmking. ``People want to
savor things . . . (I) do not throw eye candy at them but attempt
to assimiliate them (the audience) into the lives of the
characters,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shyamalan, whose influences include Hitchcock and Polanski,
cited as his model Polanski's ``Repulsion,'' a psychological
shocker depicting the mental demise of a sexually repressed woman.
``In that film, you were so into this woman's psychosis, that when
she opens a glass cabinet, you see a reflection of a man _ just for
a second _ and you literally scream,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For ``The Sixth Sense,'' Shyamalan skillfully applies that
strategy to his child-star Haley Joel Osment, 11, who plays Cole
Sear, a hyper-compassionate and sensitive boy who sees ghosts. In
one scene, the audience catches a glimpse of a woman walking behind
Cole. She's onscreen for only a split second, but the moment is
frightening.
</P>
<P>
   Osment, who played Gump's son in 1994's ``Forrest Gump,''
admitted he had nightmares after reading Shyalaman's script.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real scary part is that there really could be kids like
this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the human side of the story, the filmmakers want to make
the ghosts frightening _ yet believable. In ``Sixth Sense'' and
``Stir of Echoes,'' the ghosts appear as pale, sometimes bloodied
humans _ not invisible creatures who yell ``Boo!''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Stir of Echoes,'' Koepp tried something new with his
teenage ghost Samantha, a camera technique that combines both a
realistic and supernatural feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally you shoot somebody at 24 frames a second, but we shot
Samantha (played by ballet dancer Jenny Morrison) at 6 frames and
had her move a quarter of normal speed,'' he said. ``So on screen,
there's a weird quiver to her _ it's subtle and you know that
something ain't right.''
</P>
<P>
   But the appeal of scary movies isn't restricted to current
films. Hitchcock, master of the psychological thriller, still
attracts filmgoers. The Brattle Theatre in Harvard Square,
Cambridge, drew 20,000 people to this summer's seven-week Hitchcock
revival in honor of his 100th birthday, said Connie White of the
Beacon Cinema Group.
</P>
<P>
   But the question still remains. Why on earth does one want to be
scared out of their skinnies?
</P>
<P>
   ``You're attracted to dangerous situations, to the repetition of
it, if it's consistent with what you're feeling inside,'' said
clinical psychologist Lynn Margolies. ``There's a push for these
fears and feelings to come out. But even better than that, it's
safe and it has nothing to do with you in the end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
