<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Tuesday, Aug. 24,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   RETIRED _ WASHINGTON _ Working when you don't have to seems to
be the best way to go. Retired men who return to work have lower
levels of depression than just about anybody, employed or
unemployed, according to a study by Cornell University
psychologists. This is especially true, the psychologists report
Monday, when the retired working man has a wife who remains at
home. On the other hand, the lowest morale and the highest
depression settle on those men who make retirement permanent.
(Nesmith, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BRET _ AUSTIN, Texas _ A blustery shadow of its former self,
Hurricane Bret plodded across a sparsely populated swath of
southern Texas today after riding ashore with less might than
forecasters had feared. The storm, the biggest hurricane to strike
Texas in nearly 20 years, continued to drench the region with
thunderous squalls, but no injuries were reported since Bret made
landfall about 6 p.m. Sunday in sparsely populated Kenedy County.
(Austin American-Statesman). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   QUAKE-FAMILY _ ATLANTA _ A 76-year-old woman and her
daughter-in-law, both injured in the earthquake in Turkey that
killed more than 12,000, returned home to Georgia early today. The
bodies of five family members, four of them children, killed in the
earthquake were also returned. Turkan Kilic, 76, was in critical
condition in the intensive care unit at a metro Atlanta hospital
with injuries to her lungs. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   STAROFDAVID _ GULFPORT, Miss. _ Feeling heat from the casino
tourism industry, the Harrison County school board is having second
thoughts about its crackdown on gang symbols that led to a Jewish
junior being ordered not to wear his Star of David. The board and
tourism officials met with members of the Jewish community, and the
board is throwing the issue open to debate at a Monday meeting.
(Konigsmark, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NC-SCHOOLDESEG _ CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ Public officials gather
Monday hoping to end divisivenss and present a unified public front
on the eve of a judge's ruling on whether the Charlotte-Mecklenburg
public schools qualify as integrated, allowing decades of busing to
end. Members of the school board have disagreed on what remedies
are still needed, even as the board defended itself in court this
summer against suits calling for busing to end, and for it to
continue. Nationally, a recent NAACP survey found about half of
young adults believe that separation of the races is acceptable as
long as there are equal opportunties for everyone _ an attitude
reflected in the Charlotte school debate. (Burritt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EVERGLADES-FUNDING _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A federal-state
plan being considered by Congress would spend $7.8 billion on
history's grandest environmental restoration _ aimed at re-creating
some semblance of natural flow in the Everglades while providing
water to farms and cities. Half that money, roughly $200 million a
year, would come from Washington. The other half would have to come
from someone in Florida. And without any major help from
Tallahassee, the money would come mostly from the taxpayers of
South and Central Florida. (King, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-CRICKET _ LONDON _ A short on the failure of the English
cricket team, which has the entire country despressed _ well, maybe
just the Englanders. After a match Sunday in which they were
summarily trounced by New Zealand, the English team rates as the
world's worst. It would be as if the United States suddenly found
itself with the worst national basketball or baseball team on
Earth. (Roughton, Cox News Service). 10.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in the (i) International and (l) Lifestyle
categories.
</P>
