<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (BS)(BS)(BS)(BS) ``Cabaret Balkan'' If life is a cabaret, old
chum, it's a pretty grim one on a night in Belgrade in 1995. With
heightened realism and black humor, Goran Paskaljevic directs his
ensemble cast through a series of vignettes suggesting nihilistic
life on the edge of apocalypse; politics is only in the background,
while the foreground is filled _ fascinatingly _ with ordinary
people under a state of siege. (R) (Jim Sullivan) &QL; 
 &QL; 
(BS)(BS) ``Illuminata'' An affectionate but inescapably clumsy
farce about life backstage at a repertory company in
turn-of-the-century Manhattan. Writer-director John Turturro
sometimes falters, but he's right on target in his obvious
genuflection to the company's leading lady, Katherine Borowitz (his
real-life wife). Her depth and delicacy justify the title. Susan
Sarandon is a big help, too, as a stylish and oh-so-worldly rival
diva. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
(BS)(BS)(BS) ``Mickey Blue Eyes'' Hugh Grant, of all people, mixes
it up with the mob and makes it work. He plays a proper Brit art
auctioneer naive enough to believe he'll be able to handle marrying
a mob princess (Jeanne Tripplehorn). The fun lies in seeing how he
can't, from the moment he meets his prospective father-in-law
(James Caan), who leads him into a deeper, not to say
bullet-riddled, understanding of the word trouble. (PG-13) &QL; 
 &QL; 
(BS) 1/2 ``Teaching Mrs. Tingle'' Kevin Williamson finally gives us
the kind of shlocky scare movie he previously has had such success
mocking. It's an utter waste of the magnificent Helen Mirren, who
plays a spiteful teacher tied to her bed by students she
maliciously intends to derail just
</P>
<P>
   before graduation. They take a lot longer than we do to realize
that they don't know what they're doing in this sluggish exercise.
(PG-13)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-99 1416EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
