<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 14:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6550 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-PAULUS-BOS &LR;      08-23 1640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-PAULUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING EDITH WHARTON TO THE OPERA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Edith Wharton wrote ``Summer'' in 1916 when she was 54 and
living in Paris. A novel about sexual awakening and coming of age,
``Summer'' presents one of the most memorable heroines of American
literature, Charity Royall; the setting is a small town in the
Berkshires, where Wharton lived in a great house in Lenox called
``The Mount'' that still flourishes as a museum.
</P>
<P>
   Wharton had sold The Mount five years before she came to write
``Summer,'' but her story and her heroine come home to Western
Massachusetts this week when Berkshire Opera presents the world
premiere performances of Stephen Paulus's opera ``Summer.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, when he was 30, Paulus claimed a space on the operatic
map when he wrote a one-act piece for the Opera Theater of Saint
Louis, ``The Village Singer.'' During the rehearsal period, it was
clear the company had a hit on its hands, and even before opening
night, the company asked Paulus to write a full-length opera. His
own suggestion was an opera based on ``Summer,'' but Richard Gaddes
and Colin Graham, who were running the company, advised against a
second period New England piece. (``The Village Singer'' is based
on a short story by Mary E. Wilkins Freeman.) Paulus is a
professional, prolific, and industrious composer with more than 200
works to his credit at age 49; he may be the only American composer
since Gian-Carlo Menotti who has made his living writing operas _
``Summer'' is his seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``By design, I've never taken a teaching post,'' Paulus said
over the phone during a rehearsal break last week. ``At the
begining, when I was young, a composer's salary seemd just fine,
and since then, it's improved greatly _ at any one time, I have
about 20 commissions lying before me, ranging from operas to
chamber music to a new piano concerto for Anton Nel to play. When
St. Louis turned down my suggestion of `Summer,' they were in a way
taking charge of my career. They were afraid I'd be typecast as a
composer, and wanted me to do something completely different. One
day Colin came up with `The Postman Always Rings Twice,' and that
was completely different.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Postman'' has proved Paulus's most popular opera to date; the
Boston Lyric Opera produced it five seasons ago. ``I still thought
`Summer' would be perfect for an opera, and its atmosphere
resonates with my temperament _ the characters, the irony, the
melancholy. I thought, `Well, someday I may get the chance to write
it.' '' &QL; 
 &QL; 
A talk with an old friend &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That chance came about because of a conversation with his old
friend, conductor Joel Revzen, who is the artistic director of
Berkshire Opera. Coming onto the line, Revzen said, ``I had known
Steve in Minneapolis-St. Paul and had conducted several of his
works. I have always felt that his music is both accessible and
honest. We were just having a friendly conversation one day, when
he told me he'd been wanting to write this opera for years. I
didn't know the novel, but I loved the other books by Edith Wharton
I'd read, and when I did look at `Summer,' I thought this was too
wonderful an opportunity to pass up, so I just told him, `We'll do
it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Revzen admires Paulus ``because I know how he writes for the
voice; his music fits into the voice so beautifully _ there's no
screeching. It's the exact opposite to Peter Maxwell Davies's
`Eight Songs for a Mad King,' which has its own wonderful
qualities. When I read the book, I saw immediately how it could
work as an opera. It captures the essence of what I feel about this
place _ I've lived and worked here only in the summers, until now.
It has all the atmosphere _ the smell of wildflowers, the soft
mountains, the feelings of nature _ everything but the tourists! I
convinced our board to take the risk, and we commissioned it.''
</P>
<P>
   When Paulus was in Boston for ``Postman,'' he said he hoped his
next opera would be a comedy. He has composed two operas since
then, and neither was a comedy. ``The Three Hermits'' is a church
opera, on the model established by Benjamin Britten, and ``The
Woman at Otawi Crossing'' is a full-length piece based on a book by
Frank Waters about Edith Warner, who lived in Santa Fe and
befriended both the atomic scientists at Los Alamos and the Native
Americans of the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it hasn't worked out that I've written a comedy yet,''
Paulus said, wryly. ``But after his second opera, Verdi waited
until he was 80 _ the smart money preceding me waited to write
comedy! My next opera, based on the story of Abelard and Heloise,
is for the Juilliard Opera Center _ this was another subject I
proposed at St. Louis after they turned down `Summer.' Joel and I
started talking about this project in 1993. By the time he had sold
the board on the idea, raised the money, and got people behind it,
it was 1997. I started real work on it about a year ago. I scored
it for a `do-able' orchestra, about 32 players, which should fill
the house and complement the singers without eradicating them,
which some other composers seem to enjoy doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Revzen had a cast in mind almost from the beginning, and served
as a kind of informal adviser throughout the project. ``Steve was
wonderful, letting me sit in a little on the process. We talked
about the vocal types and characters, and I described what I
thought were the particular strengths and colors of the individual
voices. I thought Charity Royall should be a mezzo, someone with
real substance in the voice to convey Charity's strength, and yet a
singer who is able to float the top notes, like Margaret Lattimore
can. I thought of John Cheek for her guardian and the elder
statesman of the community; I wanted a real voice and presence for
the role. Michael Chioldi, like John, was in our production and
recording of Menotti's `The Consul,' and he has weight in his voice
and a real theatrical presence _ like Maggie (Lattimore), he has a
lot of experience in other kinds of musical theater as well as in
opera. And every member of the cast was hand picked; I think we
have major artists for even the smallest roles.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Turning to an old associate &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Paulus chose his librettist for ``The Woman at Otawi Crossing,''
Joan Vail Thorne, to prepare the text. ``I think it is a wonderful
libretto,'' he said. ``It's very lean, and concentrates on the very
unusual and sad love story. The relationship between Charity Royall
and Lucius Harney grows and develops _ she's trapped in this small
town, a prisoner in a place where nothing ever happens, and then
here comes this good-looking stranger, and then they're off. But it
also becomes inevitable that this is not going to work out.''
Wharton wrote only one other novel set in the Berkshires, ``Ethan
Frome,'' which has always been more famous than ``Summer''; Wharton
called the later book her ``hot Ethan.''
</P>
<P>
   Paulus said the text and music have been structured very
carefully to bring a rising tension to the relationship between
Charity and Lucius as it develops. ``In the first act, there is one
duet where they sing of their gorgeous surroundings here in the
Berkshires, and it becomes a metaphor for their budding
relationship. There are two big duets in Act 2, which grow
progressively stronger and more passionate; at a fireworks display
they get down to brass tacks. That's the one place where there may
be something specifically New Englandish in the music _ `Yankee
Doodle' makes an appearance in the texture.''
</P>
<P>
   Revzen is very enthusiastic about the score. ``The work is
beyond anything I expected. It has beauty, honesty, passion, and
lyricism. I don't say this lightly, but I believe this work will go
into the repertory like Carlisle Floyd's `Susannah' and Douglas
Moore's `The Ballad of Baby Doe.' It has that same kind of feeling,
that temperature, the same honest human emotions. And the subject
matter is still relevant _ Carol Gilligan from Harvard is doing
work with young pregnant teenage girls in this very community.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Backdrops do double duty &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The production has been designed by David Gordon. Revzen said,
``Because so much of it is set outdoors in nature, we have 20
projectors putting photographs from the Berkshires onto a dozen
different clapboard panels that slide back and forth. A fabulous
side effect is that the panels are all actually made of wood, so
there are hard surfaces behind the singers, which will add some
sonic ambience to the voices in the hall.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's better than trying to put trees and hills onto the
stage,'' Paulus said. Like Revzen, he speaks with quiet conviction
of the piece. ``My own appraisal is that this is my best stage work
so far. It's my seventh opera, and if you pay attention to what
you're doing, you tend to learn a little bit about the art form _
it's an ongoing task!''
</P>
<P>
   Paulus said that from the beginning people have commented on how
the music keeps the opera moving. ``Nobody is being stabbed or
drawn and quartered, but there is plenty of dramatic tension,
psychological and emotional interplay. There are some angular
little dissonant things, but many lyrical moments too. This is a
love story, after all. To me, the human voice is a special,
wonderful thing; I love the voice and all that it can do. And I
love drama _ people tell me that even my orchestral pieces have
dramatic impact. I also think that over the years, I have learned
to use the orchestra in an opera _ in one aria, for example, the
singer is singing a naive, old, sweet song, but the orchestra
represents the tempest going on around her as she sings and
suggests that things are not at all well; the orchestra puts the
aria into a different frame. I created a piece I thought I would
enjoy hearing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-99 1419EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
