<HEADER>
A6555 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-SHADOW-BOS &LR;      08-23 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SHADOW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LURKING IN `THE EMPEROR'S SHADOW' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stories of ancient Chinese emperors are favorites of modern
Chinese directors, and no wonder. In a country where direct public
commentary on contemporary leaders and social conditions always
risks ruining the commentator, using distant mirrors to make veiled
observations is as close as many Chinese ever come to free public
expression.
</P>
<P>
   Qin Shi Huangdi, the first ruler to unify China, lived 22
centuries ago _ sometimes on one side of the diaphanous curtain
dividing fable from fact, sometimes on the other. Builder of the
Great Wall and the Grand Canal, master of the fabulous terra-cotta
armies of Xian, tyrant, visionary, his life is, literally, carved
in stone, and his legacy _ the imperative for China to maintain its
unity at all costs _ is possibly the strongest single strand in the
country's political culture.
</P>
<P>
   Blessedly for the contemporary storyteller, the stone carvings
are mostly paeans of praise to the great man, providing no main
story line or narrative. The emperor's friends, enemies, and
nemeses are recorded only sketchily, almost as props providing a
backdrop for the great man's life. Directors and writers can't tell
his story without using large doses of imagination. And that opens
the door to a most Chinese practice _ using historical semi-fiction
to comment on contemporary leaders and conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Emperor's Shadow'' opens with scenes of military pomp and
pageantry, a bow to the film's billing as the first made-in-China
epic.
</P>
<P>
   But while there is ample marching around and bloodletting to
maintain the appearances of a nation-building saga, this is not
what the story is about.
</P>
<P>
   From armies in the field, the film cuts sharply to a woman
nursing two infants: one her own son, Gao Jianli, who will become
the greatest musician of his time, the other Ying Zheng, who will
become the first emperor. As she nurses them, she sings of ``two
little doggies, dreaming of a bone . . . biting all night, mouths
full of fur.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the true subject of ``The Emperor's Shadow'' _ the
culture war between ruthlessly authoritarian rulers on one side and
doomed but indomitable artists and intellectuals on the other that
persists in Chinese society, discomfiting its leaders, to this day.
</P>
<P>
   A record of 100 Chinese characters establishes Gao Jianli as a
historical character. It states only that he was a master of music
whom the emperor wanted to keep close because they were countrymen
_ an important tie in the era of warring states in which the boys
grew up and faced hair-raising dangers together.
</P>
<P>
   Later histories state that Gao hated the emperor, and refused to
bend to his will. The emperor had him blinded so he would
concentrate on his music; the musician filled his instrument with
lead to strike back at the emperor.
</P>
<P>
   The proposition that a latter-day historian could add such
detail accurately is at best improbable, says Zhou Xiaowen,
director of ``The Emperor's Shadow,'' whose previous films focused
on contemporary social conditions. ``History, as soon as you start
writing it, it becomes fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter. Zhou seizes on the real or imagined tensions between
the men to illuminate the conflict between politics and free
expression that has repeatedly led to spasms of repression in the
20th century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Artists in China have no position, no place in society,'' Zhou
said in an interview at Wellesley College last winter, when it
seemed his film was finally about to be released in the United
States. ``It is easy for the powerful to control them. But to
control their creativity is impossible. Their spirit and creativity
can never be controlled.''
</P>
<P>
   As Zhou tells the story, Gao's and Ying's paths diverge in early
manhood as one pursues music and the other power, but as the goal
of empire comes within his grasp, Ying draws Gao into the imperial
inner circle, and becomes obsessed with the idea that his musician
friend can write an anthem that will win the hearts and minds of
the people in a way that military prowess and grandiose
construction cannot.
</P>
<P>
   Gao stubbornly refuses to do the composition, despite torture
and the enticements of the emperor's favorite daughter, who falls
for the musician and winds up in her own futile, ultimately fatal,
struggle for control of her life.
</P>
<P>
   Rulers for two millennia have shown ``this impulse for control
of people's minds,'' Zhou says. ``Telling people what to do and
having them obey is not enough. The ruler feels `you have to think
as I think.' This first emperor has the supreme power, but he
cannot control the soul or mind of a single friend of his.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhou steadfastly refuses to confirm what seem obvious parallels
between his fictionalized history and Chinese society today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Irrespective of who they are _ workers, officials, film
critics _ after they watch the film people come to their own
conclusions based on their own experience,'' he says blandly,
laying down a defense a modern thought commissar would have trouble
breaching. ``An artist does not have the right to try to shape
people's minds. I'm not trying to hide anything in the movie. It is
transparent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Emperor's Shadow'' was completed in 1996, but has had a
rough time getting shown in China and America. The director and
producers made a US tour last December, when they felt a commercial
release was imminent; the film is just now being screened _ on the
festival circuit.
</P>
<P>
   In China, the film initially passed censorship. Then, two weeks
after it opened, the filmmakers were told it could not be screened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still don't know why,'' Zhou says. ``It was stopped, banned.
After seven months, I heard it was OK to show again. There was just
a sentence in an `internal' document.''
</P>
<P>
   With a budget of $5 million, ``Shadow'' is one of the most
costly films made in China, and its billing as an epic could be
what made it palatable, initially, to Beijing's current autocrats.
Tired of seeing the megabucks of the moviegoing masses flow to Hong
Kong and Hollywood while cutting-edge Chinese directors, in the
words of a New China News Agency critique, ``produce elitist works
that focus on the oppressed,'' the leadership is trying to
encourage homemade epic production that serves ``as an
entertainment as well as a means of refuge from reality.''
</P>
<P>
   In this context, the irony of the current emperors winding up
with a film they cannot fully stomach is delicious. Like Qin Shi
Huangdi, they were smart enough to know they could not send a
flunky to do an artist's work. And also like the first emperor,
they overreached themselves: In trying for one of the best
directors, they wound up with someone who would not bend to their
will. He made an epic about ancient history that is all about
today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-99 1420EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990823.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6558 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-ARTS-WEB-SITES-BOS &LR;      08-23 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-WEB-SITES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S ON THE 'NET TONIGHT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They call it ``narrowcasting'' _ that is,
something-different-for-everyone programming. Say you're into
extreme sports: There's a show for you. The rave scene? Click right
in. This philosophy of programming lies at the heart of Digital
Entertainment Network (or Den), an Internet startup targeting
14-to-24-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our sole mission is the self-actualization of Generation Y,''
says Den president David Neuman. ``And we would not be embracing
that unless we embrace everybody _ every ethnic group, every
interest, psychographic, and subculture.''
</P>
<P>
   So how narrow is narrowcasting? Here are a few examples:
</P>
<P>
   ``Tales from the Eastside'': Described by Den staffers as a
Latino ``Beverly Hills 90210,'' this made-for-the-Net soap opera
presents the barrio of East Los Angeles as a mix of gangs, love
affairs, and the occasional boxing match. The characters border on
stereotypes _ hardly a cultural breakthrough. But the show is
presented in both Spanish and English, and interactive links
connect viewers to information about prominent Latino artists and
activists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Direct Drive'': Host Veronica De La Cruz, a 23-year-old
promoter of dance parties in Los Angeles, spotlights the DJ
culture, introducing viewers to the styles and the spinners. The
show offers an inside look at a phenomenon that has been all but
ignored by the mainstream media. ``The kids don't have a place to
go,'' says De La Cruz. ``It's a very underground community, and Den
is giving kids the programming they want.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Chang Gang'': Den executives describe this show as a ``Hardy
Boys mystery with Asian-American kids,'' with a supernatural twist
similar to ``The X-Files.'' Den designer Leo Zhao, who was born in
China, says of the series, ``It represents a segment of Asian kids,
the sort who wear designer labels and drive custom-made cars. It
represents a part of us, not all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Frat Ratz'': ``Animal House'' for the '90s _ only the clothes
are different. In the Den's own description, the heroes are
``feebleminded stalwarts'' who ``stumble and bumble through
calamity after calamity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Redemption High'': The pilot hasn't been shown yet, but the
show is about a group of Christian teenagers faced with issues of
faith and fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Help Den'': A self-help show for teens that explores such
issues as AIDS and eating disorders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aggronation'': Extreme sports on demand. Watch for
opportunites to click and buy the equipment when the network
launches officially in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fear of a Punk Planet'': Rival punk rockers band together to
save their favorite nightclub. Not your usual dramatic series
subject, but the script is your basic fill-in-the-blanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exoticom'': Two wild and crazy guys travel the globe and offer
their ``insights.'' In Thailand, they ride elephants, commune with
monkeys, and visit ancient temples. Here's the show's take on
Buddhism: ``I'm not real familiar with the religion, but the monks
lead these really incredible lives'':
</P>
<P>
   ``Rated DG'': The show claims to feature film critics and
reviews, but it offers little more than glorified press releases
for feature films, complete with promotional footage. Here's a
recent ``review'': ``If you like smart scripts, cute chicks, and
pot-eating presidents, check out `Dick.' '' Not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
