<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEATTY REHARSES WINDBAGGERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the op-ed page of Sunday's New York Times, Warren Beatty gave
readers fresh hope that maybe he will run for president after all.
He didn't come straight out and say as much, but he's famous for
being elliptical, another indication he'd make a good candidate.
You had to read between the lines of Beatty's column, which wasn't
easy:
</P>
<P>
   ``But when a Roosevelt-Truman-Stevenson-Kennedy Democrat,
comfortably continuing a career of writing and directing movies,
accepts the megaphone tossed to him, it will be to challenge the
present party to admit its timidity in protecting those who need
help most and to acknowledge the undeniable: To achieve universal
health care, to tend adequately to the 100 million Americans left
behind in the prosperity of the global economy, to lift 35 million
of our people out of poverty, a segment of our population that has
remained virtually constant for 20 years, to give the 20 to 25
percent of our children who live in poverty a decent start in life,
to protect our environment and improve our schools, to arouse the
nonvoting half of our population to participate in public life, WE
MUST HAVE COMPLETE PUBLIC FINANCING OF ALL FEDERAL CAMPAIGNS.''
</P>
<P>
   That's one sentence. Amazing. Obviously the man has mastered
political rhetoric. You can almost hear him intoning those lines,
his voice rising on the capital letters. He's running all right,
whether he admits it or not.
</P>
<P>
   Beatty has windbaggery down pat. He's also capable of inducing
what I think of as the Clinton effect. It's a perverse reaction
that occurs when you hear a politician articulating an opinion you
hold strongly and you find yourself thinking: Gee, maybe I'm wrong
about that.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to disagree with his point, that too much money is
ruining politics. And yet there's something about the way he says
it that's so . . . political. Not that I doubt his sincerity. As a
struggling actor/writer/director/producer in Hollywood, his
sympathies would naturally lie with the disadvantaged.
</P>
<P>
   Reading Beatty's column, I remembered that he's famous for
wanting to control even the smallest details of his film projects.
He's reputed to be so in love with his own work that he finds
editing his films painful. The column in question may be the
journalistic equivalent of ``Reds,'' Beatty's interminable
``masterpiece.''
</P>
<P>
   I would guess it came to the Times with instructions not to
change a word. I would also guess that if a lesser figure had
expressed the same thoughts in the same way the paper would never
have run the piece. But he's Beatty, and there is a mystique that
hovers about him, a mystique that arises not from his acting,
producing, or directing _ and definitely not from his writing _ but
from his sex life. His reputation as a lover of uncountable numbers
of women has made him a national icon. If someone were to poll
American women and ask, a) Have you had sex with Warren Beatty? or
b) Can you pick Bill Bradley out of a crowd? there would be many
more of the former than the latter.
</P>
<P>
   It makes sense that after eight years of sexual shenanigans in
the White House, the American public would be ready for Beatty, a
real pro, one of the few men in the public eye whose sexual track
record makes Bill Clinton look positively monklike by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   There's no comparsion, really. Beatty spent four decades on the
prowl in Hollwood and made love to many of the the most beautiful,
famous women in the world. Then he got married.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton got married first and then, well, we know too much about
that already.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
