<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-99 1501EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990823.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6592 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-COKE-MUSEUM-COKE     08-23 1339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-MUSEUM-COKE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Archive shows soft drink's changing images
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Here's the real Coke formula: Team up with Santa and
conquer the world.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 70 years ago, Coca-Cola Co. decided to do just that after
getting tired of seeing sales fizzle following the hot summer
months.
</P>
<P>
   But the Atlanta-based company needed an unusually effective
marketing campaign if it was going to change entrenched consumer
drinking habits that had been built over decades. Selling cold Coke
during the winters of the late 1920s and early 1930s was almost as
fruitless as selling ice.
</P>
<P>
   Enter artist Haddon Sundblom with his depictions of the jolly
old man from the North Pole in need of a drink as he slid down
chimneys and flew around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Santa Claus needs refreshment along the way, so why not
Coke?'' Philip Mooney, the company's archivist, asked rhetorically.
``It struck an emotional chord with the consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest, as they say, is history.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that rich marketing history is stored in the
subterranean bowels of the company's headquarters on North Avenue.
Coca-Cola's archive, one of the most extensive in the corporate
world, is located below the parking garage and requires a special
elevator and security code to enter.
</P>
<P>
   While it is not open to the public, the company recently
provided The Atlanta Journal-Constitution a rare look at its
collection.
</P>
<P>
   The well-organized, 8,000-square-foot basement houses
decades-old Coke bottles and cans, and examples of the company's
marketing and advertising campaigns over the past 113 years. They
are kept on 10-foot library shelves in three rooms, where the
temperature is a constant 68 degrees to protect the documents from
deteriorating.
</P>
<P>
   The $20 million-plus collection helps explain how Coke became
one of the world's most famous brands.
</P>
<P>
   19th century junk mail?
</P>
<P>
   If you think direct marketing is some relatively new concept,
think again. In the 1890s, the company mailed redeemable Coke
coupons to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Said an 1898 pitch:
</P>
<P>
   ``We herewith enclose a complimentary card entitling you to one
glass of Coca-Cola free at any soda fountain dispensing it.'' At
the time, Coke was almost exclusively dispensed at drugstore
counters for 5 cents a glass.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, these early marketing campaigns focused on Coke's
alleged health benefits. An 1890 ad described the soft drink this
way:
</P>
<P>
   ``The wonderful nerve and brain tonic and remarkable therapeutic
agent.''
</P>
<P>
   Another ad in May of that year insists:
</P>
<P>
   ``Coca-Cola is needed to overcome depression and languor in the
warm May days.''
</P>
<P>
   Back then, of course, the druggists didn't know about Prozac.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, the archive material shows how the company switched
from its medicinal marketing approach to one centered on fun and
refreshment. Nearly everyone in a Coke ad started wearing a smile
that any dentist would be proud of.
</P>
<P>
   As the company attempted to expand its reach, it put its name
and distinctive script logo on as many promotions as possible _
from carrying trays, calendars and soda jerk hats, to counter
stools, toys, puzzles, checkers and school kits.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, executives knew that getting kids to start drinking
Coke early on was key to the company's long-term success.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1930s, local bottlers distributed Coke's school kit
around the country. It included a bookmark, ruler, pencil, eraser,
fountain pen and blotter _ all with the company's logo on it.
</P>
<P>
   Then in the 1950s and 1960s, the company began sponsoring
instructional films for both schools and athletic programs. Titles
included ``Catching a Football'' and ``How to Invite a Girl to the
Prom and What to do There.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can teach a course on American social history and just use
material from Coca-Cola,'' said Mooney, the 54-year-old archivist
who's been at the company for more than two decades.
</P>
<P>
   The archive also holds a lesson about how investors' appetite
for corporate information has changed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1926, the company's 40th anniversary annual report was just
10 pages, and only two of them contained financial data. By
contrast, the 1998 annual report is 65 pages, and full of
statistical and strategic information.
</P>
<P>
   Sports is key
</P>
<P>
   By looking at Coke's marketing and advertising campaigns through
the years, it's easy to see how important sports has become, both
in society and to the company.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola has spent billions of dollars associating itself with
famous athletes and sporting events around the globe. The archive
not only contains past Olympic and World Cup campaigns, but the
in-depth strategies that generated them. That way, executives can
look at what the company did in previous years when they develop
future promotions.
</P>
<P>
   For example, there are eight loose-leaf books, each containing
hundreds of pages, about Coke's marketing strategy during the 1996
Summer Games in Atlanta, with stats on how effective the programs
were. In fact, the archive has marketing information on what Coke
did during every Olympics since 1928.
</P>
<P>
   The company's reliance on sports began in the early 1900s, when
it used baseball players, including ``Georgia Peach'' Ty Cobb, to
endorse its soft drink.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time Coca-Cola used such timeless baseball themes,
it also took advantage of topical events. During the height of
World War II, for example, the company depicted men and women in
military uniforms drinking Coke. Patriotism sells, especially
during a war.
</P>
<P>
   The company also has employed imaginary figures to plug its soft
drink, such as the ``Sprite Boy'' of the 1940s and 1950s. This
smiling, young elflike spirit with white hair hawked Coke nearly as
hard as Santa did. (The Sprite brand was not introduced until
1961.)
</P>
<P>
   Archive lives today
</P>
<P>
   When brand managers are looking for fresh approaches to
marketing, they often consult with Mooney about the archive
material. There's usually a lesson there about why some campaigns
worked and others didn't.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa campaign, for example, originally flopped for Coke. In
1930, artist Fred Mizen depicted Santa in a department store as
just a regular guy dressed in a red and white costume. But research
told Coke that consumers didn't relate to that concept. They wanted
``the real thing'' instead.
</P>
<P>
   So the next year, the company commissioned artist Sundblom to
depict St. Nicholas rushing around delivering toys on Christmas
Eve. Sundblom painted Santa as a jovial figure with a hearty laugh
and twinkling eyes. Santa was capable of raiding the icebox or
rewarding you if you left him a Coke.
</P>
<P>
   To this very day, Sundblom's artwork is used in Coke marketing
campaigns in diverse parts of the globe. In fact, as the company
expanded overseas, many of the images Coke initially created for
the U.S. market turned out to have universal appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The trademark script, bright red color, patented contour bottle
and much of the marketing material frequently could be transported
from nation to nation without a hitch.
</P>
<P>
   That also applies to Coca-Cola material used by restaurant
chains in the United States and abroad. Many restaurants want to
have a certain historical motif or atmosphere in their facilities,
so they contact Mooney to see what the archive might be able to
provide. Images can then be reproduced and hung in restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   The archive has even put about 6,500 historical images on the
company's internal database so employees can see some of the
possibilities. They can then pass the information on to interested
clients.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the company licenses many of the images to other firms
that sell everything from Coke playing cards to decorative
glassware.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at the archives as another resource our managers can
use to increase the business and to connect with consumers in ways
that have been relevant to their lives,'' Mooney said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a museum.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-99 1506EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990823.0206 </DOCNO>
