<HEADER>
A6595 &Cx1f; sci-z
u v BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-     08-23 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following  &UR; Science
Times &LR;  stories for papers of Tuesday, Aug. 24.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-QUAKE-LESSONS (Undated) _ Teams of American scientists and
engineers have joined Turkish colleagues in seeking ``take home''
lessons from last week's devastating earthquake. For Americans the
question is: Can this faraway earthquake help predict the next big
one in California? By Sandra Blakeslee. (1650 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-RABBITS (Undated) _ A new rabbit species has been discovered
in the mountains between Laos and Vietnam. By Henry Fountain. (200
words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-OCEAN-CABLES (Undated) _ Making use of thousands of miles of
discarded telephone cables, scientists have begun to wire remote
regions of deep ocean floor to create an undersea network of
geological observatories. The old cables will serve as deep-sea
extension chords running thousands of miles from land-based power
stations to sensors, some of which are already sending back
continuous flows of data from the ocean floor. By Malcolm W.
Browne. (1500 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NEPTUNE-RINGS (Undated) _ New observations of Neptune's
rings with space telescopes obliterate the leading theory on why
the rings are there. By Henry Fountain. (700 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ Shorts on science: Items on planet-eating
stars, erosion, good news in the air. By Henry Fountain. (700
words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-JOURNALS-ECON (Undated) _ A generation ago, leading medical
journals measured their profits in the tens of thousands of
dollars. They were scholarly publications meant to help doctors
keep abreast of scientific advances and share information on new
remedies. That mission has not changed. But increasingly, the
journals have become cash cows for the medical societies and
companies that own them, with annual profits in the tens of
millions of dollars, largely from drug company advertising. By
Lawrence K. Altman Jr. (1800 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ The Personal Health column: If bad
medical news is delivered badly, it can permanently damage the
doctor-patient relationship, leading to a loss of confidence in a
doctor's recommendations and treatment plan. Some news is
particularly devastating to families, and few doctors are prepared
to break it. By Jane E. Brody. (1300 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-TEENS-FASHION (Undated) _ Most teen-age girls retain their
