<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6612 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT     08-23 1287
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF WE WANT A DEATH PENALTY, WE MUST ALLOW EXTENSIVE APPEALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds, in 6thgraf, use brackets for double parens.)  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.)  
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c. 1999 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seventy-two years ago, on Aug. 23, 1927, Nicola Sacco and
Bartolomeo Vanzetti were executed in Massachusetts for a crime they
probably did not commit. The two Italian immigrants were hard
working men _ Sacco worked in a shoe factory, Vanzetti sold fish on
the docks. Neither men had a criminal record, nor were they
Communists. They were, however, pacifists and anarchists and had
avoided the draft during World War I.
</P>
<P>
   Those three elements convicted them of the murder of a paymaster
and a payroll guard in South Braintree, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Despite contradictory evidence, the two were found guilty in
July, 1921 and sentenced to death. An appeal was denied, even
though new evidence implicated other men. In his book ``An Almanac
of Liberty,'' former U.S. Supreme Court Justice William O. Douglas
wrote: ``They were convicted on the flimsiest evidence ... a
reading of the record years later leaves the impression that Sacco
and Vanzetti, charged with murder, were convicted because they were
pacifists, draft dodgers and radicals.''
</P>
<P>
   During the 1920s, the nation was convulsed with a fear of
Communist infiltrators. The federal government arrested and
deported thousands of immigrants who had come to our shores from
Europe because they were suspected of being in sympathy with
communism and Russia. The hysteria swept through communities and
states where newly arrived immigrants had taken jobs.
</P>
<P>
   By any standard in this nation, Sacco and Vanzetti did not get a
fair trial. Unfortunately at that time, the Supreme Judicial Court
of Massachusetts had very limited powers of review. The court could
only review questions of law, not the weight of the evidence. It
could not consider the whole record of the case in order to weigh
whether an appeal was necessary. The court could not order a new
trial even when it felt that an injustice had been done.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the Sacco-Vanzetti case, that changed 12 years
later, after the hysteria against ``foreigners'' had abated. The
power of the Supreme Judicial Court of Massachusetts was greatly
expanded in capital cases. According to Douglas, ``By an Act passed
in ((Aug. 25,)) 1939 it was granted review of the whole case _ of
the law and the evidence; and it was given the power to order a new
trial, if satisfied that justice required it. No longer was the
trial judge absolute master; no longer could his prejudice or
partisanship determine the fate of men.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a lesson here to consider. In the past decade, the U.S.
Supreme Court has consistently narrowed the right of a death row
inmate to appeal in federal courts _ whether or not new evidence
points to someone else as the murderer. This stricter limit on
appeals must inevitably lead to the execution of those who are
innocent of the crimes for which they were convicted and sentenced
to death.
</P>
<P>
   Limiting appeals in capital punishment cases speeds up the
process from conviction to execution _ but often it is the very
length of time an inmate spends on death row that raises the odds
of a successful appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1976 when the high court reinstated the death penalty, 82
death row inmates have been freed, but 566 were executed. How many
more were innocent?
</P>
<P>
   There are currently more than 3,500 men and women on death row
in this nation. How many are innocent?
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals Judge Stephen Reinhardt,
dissenting in the decision to allow Thomas Thompson to be executed
in California, wrote: ``In closing, I would observe that the
miscarriage of justice that is about to occur is the product of the
federal judiciary's elevation of procedure over justice, of speed
and efficiency over fairness and due process. I regret that we have
chosen that course in recent years, and believe that in doing so,
we have severely tarnished our nation's justice system.'' Thompson
was executed on July 14.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Dworkin, professor of law and philosophy at New York
University wrote in the Los Angeles Times, July 11 edition: ``The
Supreme Court has become impatient, and `super due process' has
turned into `due process-lite.' Its impatience is understandable,
but it is also unacceptable. If Americans insist on the death
penalty, they must accept the moral consequences of their choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judges must listen, with painstaking and patient attention, to
every argument for life that is not plainly frivolous. If they find
any actual mistake in the process that has condemned a human being
to death, they must repeat that process and give him another chance
for life. These are inescapable moral demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``What if we cannot meet these demands? What if we cannot
tolerate all the stays and appeals and retrials that a decent
respect for human life requires without making the law seem foolish
and without subverting the point of a death sentence?
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we must abandon capital punishment, even if we think it
right in principle, because then we cannot have it, even if it is
right, without cheating.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past 12 years in Illinois, 12 men have been executed
while 12 others on death row were exonerated. Illinois could take
pride in its judicial system regarding capital punishment, if those
12 inmates were freed by an appeals system that was working well.
However, that wasn't the situation in most of the successful
appeals; it was pure luck that saved the inmates.
</P>
<P>
   Darby Tillis and Perry Cobb were convicted of robbing and
murdering two people at a hot dog stand in 1977. Years later, a
young lawyer who read a news story about their case, realized he
had worked with the state's star witness against Tillis and Cobb.
He remembered, too, that she had told him she and her boyfriend had
planned to rob the restaurant but the plan went awry and someone
was shot. In a new trial in 1987, Tillis and Cobb were found not
guilty.
</P>
<P>
   David Protess, professor of journalism at Northwestern
University, and a few of his students helped free four men
convicted of gang rape and a double murder. Two of the men were on
death row; two were given life sentences. They had already spent 18
years behind bars. Protess and his students unearthed new evidence
and caused the witnesses to change their stories. Later three other
men confessed to the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Protess and his students also helped free a man who was only two
days away from execution after 17 years behind bars. Anthony Porter
had been convicted of a double murder. Protess and his team of
students gathered evidence that proved that Porter was innocent.
Key witnesses changed their testimony. And a Milwaukee man
confessed to the murders.
</P>
<P>
   Journalism professors aren't part of the judicial system. We
cannot count on the help of those outside the system to exonerate
those wrongfully convicted. Without Protess and his students, there
is little doubt that Anthony Porter would have been executed.
</P>
<P>
   After the shock of realizing innocent people might have been
executed, Illinois _ with 156 inmates on death row _ has
temporarily put a moratorium on executions.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson of the Sacco-Vanzetti case is pivotal _ appeals
cannot and should not be arbitrarily limited. Streamling the
judicial process for capital punishment irrevocably streamlines
death for the innocent. And that price is too high, morally.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
