<DOCNO> NYT19990823.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 15:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6614 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-YSLETA-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      08-23 1225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YSLETA-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE WRONG ANSWER MARRED TEXAS DISTRICT'S HIGH EDUCATION MARKS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By THADDEUS HERRICK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was praised by one newspaper for its ``standards,
accountability and a demonstrated belief that school systems are
run for the benefit of the children, not the people who work for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Former House Speaker Newt Gingrich called its previous
superintendent ``the wisest education reformer I have met in 55
years.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ysleta school district on El Paso's heavily Hispanic east
side was above all something most poor, urban districts are not: a
success. It was a model that educators came from around the nation
to study.
</P>
<P>
   But last week the state's highest-performing inner-city school
district suffered a serious blow. The Texas Education Agency, which
last year praised Ysleta for its accomplishments, labeled the
district with a new, low rating because of errors in its dropout
reporting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hallmark of an organization is not the absence of problems
but how it deals with them once they arise,'' said Manny Soto,
Ysleta's associate superintendent. ``Even though you get knocked
down, you pick yourself up.''
</P>
<P>
   State ratings are based on the percentage of students passing
the state basic skills test and its dropout and attendance rates.
With 80 percent passing the skills test, Ysleta last year became
the state's first ``recognized'' urban district, second only to the
TEA's ``exemplary'' distinction.
</P>
<P>
   Now Ysleta finds itself with an altogether more troubling
rating: ``unacceptable'' because of erroneous data. Austin was the
only other district to receive such a rating, though the state is
investigating dropout data at 14 other school systems, six of them
in the Houston area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically Ysleta underreported its dropouts,'' said DeEtta
Culbertson, a TEA spokewoman. ``Adding them back in drove their
rates up.''
</P>
<P>
   Dropout rates are believed to be widely underreported in the
majority of the state's heavily Hispanic urban districts, where in
most cases more than half the students who begin ninth grade do not
graduate. Nationwide, one in four Hispanics are high school
dropouts, double the rate of other groups.
</P>
<P>
   But critics said the TEA glossed over the problem, a point
underscored by a 1996 state audit that showed weak agency oversight
had resulted in a dropout rate that was less than half the actual
rate. Also at issue was the way the TEA calculated the dropout
rates.
</P>
<P>
   In part to respond to that criticism, the TEA this year unveiled
its new data-quality ranking. But its reprimands of Ysleta and
Austin have triggered a backlash, with critics arguing that these
districts may have misled the state, but probably not any worse
than other major urban Texas districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first reaction was why only them?'' said Jay Greene, a
professor of government at the University of Texas and an education
expert. ``One would think the conduct in these districts can't be
that different from Houston, Dallas and San Antonio.''
</P>
<P>
   The TEA responds that Ysleta and Austin are the only two Texas
school districts with ``confirmed'' dropout data problems, thanks
in part to local media reports, and ``we are not picking on them or
singling them out,'' according to spokeswoman Debbie Graves
Ratcliffe.
</P>
<P>
   In Ysleta's case, the district brought the data problem to the
attention of the TEA, but not before the El Paso Times raised the
issue first. The state says Ysleta systematically misreported data,
either anticipating the accountability consequences or through
carelessness.
</P>
<P>
   Ysleta's Soto portrays the situation as one of carelessness. But
the associate superintendent also argues that the state unfairly
penalized Ysleta because of pressure from the Legislature to
address the state's dropout situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The TEA has to wrestle with its own credibility,'' said Soto.
``We don't have any problem with ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ysleta's gathering of dropout data raises some troubling
questions. In all, the district reported to the state 378 dropouts
out of a student population of nearly 50,000. But after a closer
look, the number was nearly three times that.
</P>
<P>
   Students who Ysleta reported had moved to another Texas district
had in fact dropped out. The same was true for students who were
reported to the state as having moved out of state or even to
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   After the El Paso newspaper reported such irregularities, Ysleta
ordered an audit and concluded that there was, in Soto's words, a
``documentation weakness.'' At that point the district ordered a
more comprehensive audit and advised state officials of the
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the high road,'' said Soto. ``That was the road
fraught with consequences, but it was the road of integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the dropout flap threatens to erode the reputation made
by the district, which under former Superintendent Anthony Trujillo
sought to graduate every student fully bilingual and prepared for a
four-year college.
</P>
<P>
   His challenge was daunting. Prior to Trujillo's hiring the TEA
had assigned a monitor to Ysleta. Many believed a state takeover of
the district was imminent.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Trujillo gave the district's principals considerable
freedom. He also gave them competition, instituting a modified
school-choice plan where students can enroll at any of the
district's campuses.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, test scores were up and Ysleta was all the rage with
reformers, winning praise from Washington, D.C., to California,
where the Sacramento Bee lauded the school system for its
standards, accountability and benefits to the kids rather than
those who work for the district.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps the pendulum swung too far in Trujillo's favor,'' said
UT's Greene. ``He probably made real, substantive gains, but he
also probably benefited from the appearance of gains.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Trujillo ultimately was forced out by an opposition
school board, his changes were lauded by education reformers around
the country. Ysleta, meanwhile, developed an attitude that heavily
minority urban districts can achieve _ despite the world of poverty
that so often works against them.
</P>
<P>
   Now that spirit is shaken. At Ysleta High School, where some of
the dropout misreporting apparently occurred, principal Ralph
Ornelas says the momentum that seemed to carry the school is
lagging.
</P>
<P>
   ``My community is not happy,'' Ornelas said. ``The teachers are
not happy. The students are not happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ornelas says the dropout data problems occurred when a satellite
school for at-risk students was folded into the high school. Though
the campus accommodated some of the students, others simply
disappeared, leaving administrators to try to establish their
whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got hurt for something we had no control over,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the details of Ysleta travails may only obscure the larger
issue, which is that the state's Hispanic kids are dropping out at
alarming rates.
</P>
<P>
   Greene says Texas must address the dropout problem by
acknowledging it. That may mean coming up with a new way to
calculate the dropout rate, or giving the accountability
enforcement role to an organization other than the TEA.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we need above all is honesty,'' said Greene.
``Unfortunately I don't see any general trend for that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
