   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BRET-STORM (Corpus Christi, Texas) _ Hurricane Bret turned into
a weak tropical storm that claimed no lives, apparently injured no
one and left just $100,000 in damage to Corpus Christi. By POLLY
ROSS HUGHES and ED HEGSTROM.
</P>
<P>
   BRET-TRAGEDY (Houston) _ A South Texas man who was afraid his
mobile home would not survive Hurricane Bret's force drove his
family to Houston. Late Sunday night, he was struck and killed as
he tried to cross a Houston freeway on foot to get food for his
family. Now, his widow and six children remain in Houston, with no
clear idea of what to do next. By S.K. BARDWELL.
</P>
<P>
   INS-DEPORT (Houston) _ It was supposed to be Graciela Meza's
dream trip to the United States, a chance to visit her sister in
Houston before returning to her native Mexico to begin college.
Instead, the bewildered 18-year-old was interrogated for hours at
Bush Intercontinental Airport, put in a jail cell overnight, and
deported back to Mexico the morning after her arrival on the second
leg of a trip earlier this summer. Meza's deportation came under
the terms of a controversial 1996 immigration law giving INS
inspectors unprecedented powers to deport foreigners from airports
and border checkpoints without a hearing. By ED HEGSTROM. (Photos
available on NYT database.) (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   PLACEBO-SURGERY (Houston) _ Four out of five patients at the
Veterans Affairs hospital thought that arthroscopic surgery for
their painful knees was so worthwhile, they said they would
recommend it to their friends. The twist is, none of them actually
had the surgery _ they underwent placebo, or sham surgery. After
being sedated, they woke up with three little incisions on their
knee, but unknown to them, no instruments had been inserted.
Houston doctors are conducting a groundbreaking study to find out,
literally, whether this type of surgery works as well as people
think it does. By LEIGH HOPPER. (Photos available on NYT database.)
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   YSLETA-TEXAS (Undated) _ Once held up as a shining example of a
poor border school district that has worked wonders, the Ysleta
district's reputation was tarnished with a recent district rating
of ``unacceptable.'' The district in El Paso misled state education
officials with its dropout statistics. Dropout rates are believed
to be widely underreported in the majority of the state's heavily
Hispanic urban districts. By THADDEUS HERRICK. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush's problem
is that he is finally being judged by the harsh standards for
personal behavior long applied to President Clinton. The way Bush
has bumbled the cocaine controversy raises questions about whether
he is hypocritical, evasive and arrogant. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ Although nagging questions
about funerals and illegal drugs _ a not-unheard-of combination _
haven't buried Gov. George W. Bush's presidential aspirations, they
certainly have ripped some of the magic from his high-flying
campaign. The outspoken advocate of ``personal responsibility'' is
being painfully reminded what it means to be personally
responsible. By CLAY ROBISON (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLES/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SLEEPING-DISORDER (Undated) _ University of Kentucky diver Tracy
Bonner just thought she was tired because she slept a lot. As an
elite athlete, she's always on the go between classes, studying,
intense practices and nail-biting competitions. But she wasn't just
tired. Three years ago, she was diagnosed with narcolepsy, a
debilitating, neurological condition that causes excessive, daytime
sleepiness. Bonner's one of some 200,000 Americans who suffer from
the condition. By JANETTE RODRIGUES. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-BROOKS (Undated) _ Albert Brooks' humor is often considered
too sophisticated for cinema audiences. He disagrees. He thinks the
crowds need a little sophistication to go along with what Adam
Sandler is offering. Brooks' new movie. ``The Muse'' opens Friday
nationwide. By LOUIS B. PARKS (Already filed.)
</P>
