<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6678 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-WOMEN-IRONMAN-ART     08-23 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WOMEN-IRONMAN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 U.S. WOMEN TO ENTER DOUBLE IRONMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By LIZ NEPORENT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Ironman triathlon consists of 2.4 miles of swimming, 112
miles of cycling and 26.2 miles of running. That might seem to be
about the upper limit of human endurance, but not for Patricia
Buttenheim and Ann Snoeyenbos.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Buttenheim, a 38-year-old registered nurse from Brooklyn,
and Ms. Snoeyenbos (pronounced snow-yen-BOSS), a 35-year-old
reference librarian from Manhattan, are training to become the
first American women in five years to complete a Double Ironman.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Double Ironman. That's 4.8 miles of swimming, 224 miles of
biking and 52.4 miles of running. And as Ms. Buttenheim is quick to
point out, those events are consecutive. (The women's record, set
by Tina Bishoff in 1994, is 22 hours, 7 minutes.)
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the two women, who are friends, will be among the
two dozen or so entrants in the 12th annual Odyssey Double-Iron
Triathlon in Colonial Beach, Va., organized by Odyssey Adventure
Racing of Virginia Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Buttenheim and Ms. Snoeyenbos are members of the New York
University Triathlon Club in Manhattan. They began training for the
competition about six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Each weekday they awaken at 4 a.m. to cycle 40-plus miles around
Central Park, then do an hour and a half of yoga and strength
training before heading off to work; in the evenings, they run or
swim for one to two hours.
</P>
<P>
   On the weekends they travel all over the country to participate
in a 50-mile races, 100-mile bike rides, or four-mile swim
contests. Ms. Buttenheim said, ``We just completed a single Ironman
as our last long training day before the big race.''
</P>
<P>
   While it might seem a foregone conclusion that the women are
pounding their bodies to a pulp with this grueling training
schedule, neither has had any serious physical setbacks.
</P>
<P>
   To Benjamin Gelfand, a physical therapist, who is the author of
``A Return to Glory Days'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, 1997), a primer on
prevention of athletic injuries, this is not surprising.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultra athletes learn to adapt their form and body mechanics so
that they become very efficient,'' he said. ``This economy of
movement probably protects their joints and muscles from excessive
overuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Because long-distance athletes move at relatively low speeds and
intensities, he added, their injuries may be slower to develop and
thus easier to head off.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ms. Buttenheim acknowledges that with all the running, it
is hard to keep her feet from turning to hamburger.
</P>
<P>
   She spends about $11 a day on foot-care products like moleskin,
blister pads and Epsom salts. Chafing and chapping around the
thighs and along the bra line are sometimes a problem as well, Ms.
Snoeyenbos says.
</P>
<P>
   Both women say that a big reason for undertaking this endeavor
is to prove that ordinary people are capable of performing
extraordinary feats.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, both are average athletes with the stats to prove it.
Last year they underwent extensive physiological testing as part of
a study at Teachers College, Columbia University, on the
nutritional needs of female endurance athletes. Their scores for
parameters like body fat percentage, lung power and cardiovascular
capacity were unremarkable.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, and even though only 33 percent of Double Ironman
competitors make it across the finish line, both Ms. Buttenheim and
Ms. Snoeyenbos say they are confident they can go the distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps that we've trained safely and sanely and that we have
total support from friends and family,'' says Ms. Snoeyenbos.
Still, neither expects to finish in less than 30 hours.
</P>
<P>
   The goal in the Double Ironman is to keep moving for the entire
30-plus hours, if at all possible. And some people do stop to
sleep. But for those who are serious competitors, stopping is not
an option.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Ms. Buttenheim and Ms. Snoeyenbos were ``handlers''
for a participant in the race. All participants have a handler or
team of handlers to supply water and food and to keep them from
wandering off the course should they become disoriented.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Buttenheim and Ms. Snoeyenbos say this race is just the
beginning of their ultradistance careers. They have their eyes on
the Eco Challenge, a multiday ``adventure'' race held in a
different place each year.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the Fifteenfold Triathlon, a race 15 times the
distance of a single Ironman. The women's record, which stands at
403:01:54, has gone unchallenged since 1992.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
