<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By C. CLAIBORNE RAY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hard-Headed Birds
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why don't woodpeckers damage their brains?
</P>
<P>
   A. For at least one species of woodpecker, the naturalist Dr.
E.O. Wilson provided a classic answer in his book ``The Diversity
of Life'' (Belknap Press of Harvard University Press, 1992).
</P>
<P>
   The acorn woodpecker of California, Wilson explained, keeps its
wits despite hitting the wood with its bill at speeds of 12 to 15
miles an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The woodpecker survives, he said, because its brain is held
firmly in a case, which acts as a shock absorber, and because its
body moves in a single plane like a metronome, avoiding the
rotational forces that would twist and tear its brain loose from
its moorings.
</P>
<P>
   The human brain does not enjoy this protection.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it is encased in a sac of fluid.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when a cyclist hits the pavement, for example, the impact
can make the brain bounce around in its sack, hitting first one
side of the skull and then the other.
</P>
<P>
   That motion can tear nerve fibers and cause permanent damage.
</P>
<P>
   Readers are invited to submit questions by mail to Question,
Science Times, The New York Times, 229 West 43d St., New York, N.Y.
10036-3959, or by e-mail to:question(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   Questions of general interest will be answered in this column,
but requests for medical advice cannot be honored and unpublished
letters cannot be answered individually.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
