<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6690 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-BORGES-ANNIVERSARY-AU     08-23 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORGES-ANNIVERSARY-AUG24-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO READ BORGES, 100 YEARS AFTER HIS BIRTH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By TOMAS ELOY MARTINEZ  
 c.1999 New York Times Special Features  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a revealing interview in 1979, Jorge Luis Borges said that
``every writer leaves behind him two works: one, the written; the
other, the image that is left of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, in the long run, the man's image erases the work.
</P>
<P>
   For today's readers, it is hard to read Borges without thinking
of the image of the man: the wise and blind old scholar who had an
answer for all the world's questions and who wandered through the
maze of his favorite library shelves, even though the books were
closed to his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   When I started to read Borges, in my adolescence, what really
impressed me were the stories he told, the boundless variations of
his characters' identities and the infinite recreations of his
repertoire of facts.
</P>
<P>
   I felt that, for the first time since the Golden Century, the
Castilian tongue had found, in Borges' austere texts, the greatness
which had been dissipated by the minor regional writers. I felt
that, through Borges, the Argentinean language had acquired a
solidity and an intensity capable of expressing all the Universe.
</P>
<P>
   Once, during a Greek class, the professor found me reading ``The
Death and the Compass,'' and he reprimanded me in front of
everybody: ``Why do you spend your time reading an Argentinean
writer instead of Thucydides?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It just happens that this one is better,'' I replied, fully
convinced my words were true.
</P>
<P>
   For adolescents of the '50s, Borges was, besides, a little-known
writer, a cult writer. We believed that even one of his short
stories or poems _ ``The Poem of the Gifts,'' for example, or the
moving ``Limits'' _ were worth all of the literature yet created.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, a professor at Rutgers University, who had
read only one of Borges' short stories _ ``The Search of
Averroes,'' translated into English _ told me that those few pages
were enough to make him worthy of the Nobel Prize.
</P>
<P>
   To read Borges, I thought, and not have the pleasure of his
masterpieces colored in any way by knowledge of the man, is an
enviable achievement now all but impossible for us Argentineans.
</P>
<P>
   In 1961, soon after he received the Formentor Award, Borges was
asked to select those texts which, in his opinion, best represented
him. The resulting slim volume, of less than 200 pages, was
published that same year by Editorial Sur, ``Personal Anthology.''
</P>
<P>
   In the prologue, Borges says, with a certain emphasis: ``My
preferences have dictated this book. I want to be judged by it,
justified or reproved by it.'' The order he chose was not
chronological, but based _ as Borges defined it _ on
``congenialities and differences.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost all of the obvious short stories are there: ``The Death
and the Compass,'' ``The South,'' ``Funes the Mindful,'' ``The
Aleph,'' ``The Search of Averroes,'' ``The Circular Ruins'' and
``The End,'' even though at least three, equally worthy, are
missing: ``Pierre Menard, Author of the Quixote,'' ``Tloen, Uqbar,
Orbis Tertius'' and ``The Garden of the Paths that Bifurcate.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the poems, one wonders at the absence of ``Mythological
Foundation of Buenos Aires'' whose ``apocryphal local color''
Borges once said he ``couldn't remember without blushing.''
</P>
<P>
   A second personal anthology, entrusted by him to Emece press,
did cover those voluntary omissions.
</P>
<P>
   I saw Borges many times in the '60s _ sometimes accompanying him
a couple of blocks and helping him cross the street _ and over the
next 20 years or so, I added a few texts to his ``Personal
Anthology'' of 1961 _ stories I deemed invaluable: ``The
Intruder,'' ``The Gospel, According to Mark,'' ``The Book of
Sand,'' ``Juan Lopez and John Ward,'' and his seminars about
blindness and the Kabbala, which are included in the ``Seven
Nights.''
</P>
<P>
   Once, for four months, the only book I had with me was his ``The
Book of Sand,'' and those seven short stories were my only teacher.
I think in those few pages, and in his personal anthologies of 1961
and 1968, it's possible to find everything Borges was and always
will be.
</P>
<P>
   The last two times I saw Borges before he died in 1986, he no
longer was Borges, but his glory. The first time was in Venezuela.
He arrived silently, modestly, at the Ateneo of Caracas, and when
the lights were on him, overwhelming him, the public crowned him
with a 10-minute ovation.
</P>
<P>
   A Venezuelan writer standing by my side touched me with his
elbow and said: ``Look hard. He is Homer, he is Dante, he is all of
literature.''
</P>
<P>
   Five years later I found him again at George Mason University,
in Virginia, where thousands of silent, devoted students heard him
speak. I heard him say then that he dictated prologues and poems
when he was flying on airplanes, and that the applause of men is an
undeserved form of happiness.
</P>
<P>
   On those two occasions I was worried by the fact, which I later
confirmed, that many of those who applauded Borges had never read
Borges. Some guessed he had written ``Ulysses'' and had learned his
elegant English at Trinity College, in Dublin. Others, closer to
the mark, thought he was Cervantes.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the best homage to Borges in this centenary of his birth
is to forget the articles he wrote for newspaper deadlines and the
books he wrote in his youth _ which he later excluded from his
complete works _ and to read again the texts he asked to be
remembered by.
</P>
<P>
   Out of the works of every writer only a few pages remain: some
images, an indispensable stanza, an argument that is often repeated
by others who don't know they didn't create it. Borges exists
forever in his own immortal lines and not in the all-too-mortal
character which has been built by the years.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Tomas Eloy Martinez is the distinguished author of ``The Peron
Novel'' and ``Santa Evita.'' He is chairman of the Latin American
studies department at Rutgers University and travels widely as an
editor and journalist.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ----------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
