<SLUG> BC-BORGES-ANNIVERSARY-AUG24-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO READ BORGES, 100 YEARS AFTER HIS BIRTH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By TOMAS ELOY MARTINEZ  
 c.1999 New York Times Special Features  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a revealing interview in 1979, Jorge Luis Borges said that
``every writer leaves behind him two works: one, the written; the
other, the image that is left of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, in the long run, the man's image erases the work.
</P>
<P>
   For today's readers, it is hard to read Borges without thinking
of the image of the man: the wise and blind old scholar who had an
answer for all the world's questions and who wandered through the
maze of his favorite library shelves, even though the books were
closed to his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   When I started to read Borges, in my adolescence, what really
impressed me were the stories he told, the boundless variations of
his characters' identities and the infinite recreations of his
repertoire of facts.
</P>
<P>
   I felt that, for the first time since the Golden Century, the
Castilian tongue had found, in Borges' austere texts, the greatness
which had been dissipated by the minor regional writers. I felt
that, through Borges, the Argentinean language had acquired a
solidity and an intensity capable of expressing all the Universe.
</P>
<P>
   Once, during a Greek class, the professor found me reading ``The
Death and the Compass,'' and he reprimanded me in front of
everybody: ``Why do you spend your time reading an Argentinean
writer instead of Thucydides?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It just happens that this one is better,'' I replied, fully
convinced my words were true.
</P>
<P>
   For adolescents of the '50s, Borges was, besides, a little-known
writer, a cult writer. We believed that even one of his short
stories or poems _ ``The Poem of the Gifts,'' for example, or the
moving ``Limits'' _ were worth all of the literature yet created.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, a professor at Rutgers University, who had
read only one of Borges' short stories _ ``The Search of
Averroes,'' translated into English _ told me that those few pages
were enough to make him worthy of the Nobel Prize.
</P>
<P>
   To read Borges, I thought, and not have the pleasure of his
masterpieces colored in any way by knowledge of the man, is an
enviable achievement now all but impossible for us Argentineans.
</P>
<P>
   In 1961, soon after he received the Formentor Award, Borges was
asked to select those texts which, in his opinion, best represented
