published that same year by Editorial Sur, ``Personal Anthology.''
</P>
<P>
   In the prologue, Borges says, with a certain emphasis: ``My
preferences have dictated this book. I want to be judged by it,
justified or reproved by it.'' The order he chose was not
chronological, but based _ as Borges defined it _ on
``congenialities and differences.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost all of the obvious short stories are there: ``The Death
and the Compass,'' ``The South,'' ``Funes the Mindful,'' ``The
Aleph,'' ``The Search of Averroes,'' ``The Circular Ruins'' and
``The End,'' even though at least three, equally worthy, are
missing: ``Pierre Menard, Author of the Quixote,'' ``Tloen, Uqbar,
Orbis Tertius'' and ``The Garden of the Paths that Bifurcate.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the poems, one wonders at the absence of ``Mythological
Foundation of Buenos Aires'' whose ``apocryphal local color''
Borges once said he ``couldn't remember without blushing.''
</P>
<P>
   A second personal anthology, entrusted by him to Emece press,
did cover those voluntary omissions.
</P>
<P>
   I saw Borges many times in the '60s _ sometimes accompanying him
a couple of blocks and helping him cross the street _ and over the
next 20 years or so, I added a few texts to his ``Personal
Anthology'' of 1961 _ stories I deemed invaluable: ``The
Intruder,'' ``The Gospel, According to Mark,'' ``The Book of
Sand,'' ``Juan Lopez and John Ward,'' and his seminars about
blindness and the Kabbala, which are included in the ``Seven
Nights.''
</P>
<P>
   Once, for four months, the only book I had with me was his ``The
Book of Sand,'' and those seven short stories were my only teacher.
I think in those few pages, and in his personal anthologies of 1961
and 1968, it's possible to find everything Borges was and always
will be.
</P>
<P>
   The last two times I saw Borges before he died in 1986, he no
longer was Borges, but his glory. The first time was in Venezuela.
He arrived silently, modestly, at the Ateneo of Caracas, and when
the lights were on him, overwhelming him, the public crowned him
with a 10-minute ovation.
</P>
<P>
   A Venezuelan writer standing by my side touched me with his
elbow and said: ``Look hard. He is Homer, he is Dante, he is all of
literature.''
</P>
<P>
   Five years later I found him again at George Mason University,
in Virginia, where thousands of silent, devoted students heard him
speak. I heard him say then that he dictated prologues and poems
when he was flying on airplanes, and that the applause of men is an
undeserved form of happiness.
</P>
<P>
   On those two occasions I was worried by the fact, which I later
