   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-GAMBLING (Los Angeles) _ The California Supreme Court on
Monday overturned a state ballot measure passed last year to allow
expansion of legalized gambling on Indian lands in California,
ruling that the measure violated the state constitution's ban on
Nevada-style casino gambling and raising the prospect that federal
prosecutors might soon move to shut down some of the lucrative
Indian casinos that have sprung up around the state in recent
years. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-DICTIONARY (Undated) _ The breathless promotions for
Microsoft's first foray into the rarefied dictionary market promise
a mighty international reference guide for the English-speaking
world _ the ``first dictionary born in the information age.'' But
the Encarta World English Dictionary, has also ignited a tart war
of words in the elite universe of dictionary publishing, a
high-volume, low-margin business that suddenly finds itself warily
facing the threat of Microsoft's financial resources, marketing
muscle and global reach. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``e'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   GRAYING-AUDIENCES (Lennox, Mass.) _ At all the locales that have
made the Berkshires an unrivaled summer paradise for culture
seekers _ at Tanglewood's classical concerts, the Jacob's Pillow
Dance Festival, the Berkshire Theater Festival, the museums _ young
visitors seem to have become an endangered species. These serene
hills are increasingly populated by lifelong followers of music and
theater who started traveling here from New York or Boston a
generation ago but are now gray-haired second-home owners and
Florida snowbirds who summer in the condominiums that sprouted in
the Berkshires in the 1980s. By Joseph Berger.
</P>
