<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETIRED24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A LITTLE WORK KEEPS RETIREMENT HAPPY, STUDY FINDS
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Regardless of their age, income or health, retired
men who return to work in second careers tend to have high morale
and relatively little depression, psychologists reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
   That is especially true if the men's wives are in the home,
Cornell University's Jungmeen Kim and Phyllis Moen told the annual
convention of the American Psychological Association.
</P>
<P>
   Among retirees, the highest levels of depression and the lowest
morale are experienced by men who make retirement permanent, the
researchers found.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men who are free from the demands of their career jobs but are
re-employed are happiest,'' probably because they are working part
time, they reported.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, recently retired women have more trouble
adjusting to depression if they remain at home and their husbands
aren't also at home, Kim and Moen said.
</P>
<P>
   The overall meaning of retirement has changed rapidly in the
past decade, and an even greater wave of changes is just ahead as
baby boomers start leaving the traditional work force, Moen said in
a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to start thinking of retirement as a couple
transition, rather than an individual change,'' she said. ``Now
couples are having to coordinate two retirements, and it matters
how they do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The researchers' study was based on two surveys among a group of
late-middle-age men and women, many of whom were still working
during the initial survey.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers studied 534 married men and women between ages
50 and 74 in New York. They defined retirement as being eligible
for or receiving an employee pension or Social Security, or both.
</P>
<P>
   Information from a third survey of the same group is still being
analyzed, Moen said.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, retirement is more difficult for women these days,
Moen said. Many entered the job market late and have fewer
benefits, such as buyouts or early retirement privileges, and find
retirement less rewarding.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, for many men retirement has come to mean
leaving one career for a second.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had an engineer in our sample who retired from a large
Fortune 500 company,'' she said. ``Now he has a hot dog stand at
the ballpark. He is very happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Many said they had wished they could have remained in their
career jobs, but with fewer hours and less stress, she said, but
the choice was not available.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the researchers found that a man's employment status
is more predictive of his self-perceived psychological well-being,
while a woman is more apt to be affected by the quality of a
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   As baby boomers start retiring, many in their mid-50s or even
early 50s, they will redefine retirement, she predicted. They will
be the youngest population of retirees in history, the best
educated, the healthiest and the most likely to be married to a
retiree.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to start thinking differently about the transitions
involved in retirement,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
