a digital VCR, it monitors your viewing habits and suggests other
programs that you might want to watch, based on those habits.
(Holsendolph, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH ILLUSTRATION.
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY_ Popular column about personal computing written for
the average user. This week: If you worry about a large company
dominating the technology market, chances are you probably worry
about Microsoft. You should worry about Intel, ``Mr. Chips,'
instead. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-TOOLS _ Software reviews. This week: Let us now, with a nod
to James Agee, praise famous programs. I submit to you the
proposition that within the bowels of Windows, under the
Accessories button, there lies the very heart of computing, a small
gem of programming, a glass through which all other such endeavors
may be viewed and judged. Oh, yes, my friends, I speak of
Solitaire. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH _ What's new on the Web. This week: There he was, the
Beastie Boys' rapper Mike D. dressed in the rocker/rapper/slacker
uniform of T-shirt and jeans, slumped before a microphone in a
meeting room at the Marriott Marquis hotel in New York City,
talking about leveraging databases to increase sales and marketing
opportunities on the Web. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE _ What's new on the Web. This week: It is, after all,
the World Wide Web _ not the neighborhood Web, or the American Web.
And it's still a fast and surprisingly satisfying way to tour the
world _ zapping at the click of a mouse from New Zealand to
Newfoundland. There are, of course, thousands of sites filled with
the kind of information you'd find by reading an atlas and
encyclopedia. But for a really interesting world tour via
cyberspace, try to visit some of the out-of-the-way places ... the
sort of places where the locals hang out. (Husted, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-MEDIA _ What the tech magazines are writing about. This
week: In these fading days of summer there's still time yet to
squeeze in playing a few more new computer games. You can find some
likely choices in the August issue of PC Gamer. The issue features
a list of a host of new reviews. And there's a look at the 10 best
games scheduled for release next year. The new games include
Freelancer, Throne of Darkness, Alone in the Dark 4 and Planet of
the Apes. (Haddad, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MAC-REPORT _ This column, which features news about Apple and
its products, is not available this week. (Haddad , Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   TECH-REPORT _ Tech briefs on new products and developments. This
week: Years ago, when science fiction novels _ not video games _
were an obsession with most boys and some girls, the robot was
king. The robots of science fiction were wonderful (and sometimes
awful) creatures that could think for themselves and that seemed
like mechanical versions of a real person. For a time, it seemed
almost certain that _ as technology moved to the stage where such
things were possible _ robot housekeepers and waiters would be
common by the end of the century. (Husted, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   POWERUSER-COLUMN _ The advanced computer users column is not
available this week. (Yandel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
