<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6713 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT &LR;      08-23 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AND FASHION NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; LONGEVITY: Aging Advice: Stay Busy to Stay Healthy &LR;
</P>
<P>
   It is well established that exercise helps elderly people live
longer.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, new evidence suggests that nonstrenuous activities
_ playing cards, gardening, cooking, going to the movies, attending
church or visiting friends _ may be just as helpful.
</P>
<P>
   The findings, just published in The British Medical Journal,
were based on a study of 2,761 men and women age 65 and over in the
New Haven area from 1982 through 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers measured survival rates for people who engaged in
three types of activity: physical, social and ``productive''
(cooking, shopping, gardening, volunteering).
</P>
<P>
   After taking age, sex, race, income, body type and medical
history into account, the researchers found that all three kinds of
activity produced similar benefits in terms of longevity.
</P>
<P>
   While staying involved to stay alive may seem like common sense,
it has been less researched than physical activity, said Dr. Thomas
A. Glass, an assistant professor at Harvard's School of Public
Health, who led the study with three colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is it that a sense of purpose in life is demonstrably
related to the risk of death?'' Glass asked. The research, he said,
suggests that there are psychosocial benefits that directly affect
the brain in a life-prolonging way.
</P>
<P>
   This does not mean it is safe to skip the outdoor walks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would under no circumstances say that social activity or
social engagement is a replacement for exercise,'' Glass cautioned.
</P>
<P>
   But he added that in helping the elderly, society should rethink
what it means to be active. ``We've tended to ignore the fact that
activity is social in nature,'' Glass said.
</P>
<P>
   _MICHAEL POLLAK
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONSEQUENCES: Inner Peace, on the Bright Side of Trauma &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Surviving a plane crash is clearly better than the alternative.
But it may actually have positive long-term effects.
</P>
<P>
   A study presented last week at the 107th annual convention of
the American Psychological Association in Boston suggests that
crash survivors may enjoy better mental health than those who have
never been in a crash.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, Gary Capobianco of Old Dominion University and
Dr. Thanos Patelis of the College Board in New York, selected 15
crash survivors _ 11 men and 4 women _ as the experimental group
and chose 8 frequent travelers who had never experienced a plane
crash as the control group.
</P>
<P>
   All were asked to fill out questionnaires about their
backgrounds and their levels of anxiety, depression and emotional
distress.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers were surprised at how well the survivors seemed
to be doing, Dr. Patelis said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, they were less likely to display rash behavior like
anger or aggression than the control group. And the survivors who
did not seek counseling after the crash exhibited even lower levels
of distress than those who did.
</P>
<P>
   While the numbers were small and the findings were tentative,
Patelis said he hoped the study would lead to more research on the
long-term benefits of overcoming a traumatic event.
</P>
<P>
   _DENISE DE LAS NUECAS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PERFORMANCE: A Matter of Keeping the Men Amused &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Humor has long been known to relieve stress and elevate the
mood. What's not to like?
</P>
<P>
   The benefits, however, may not be distributed equally between
the sexes, according to a new study.
</P>
<P>
   Allan Filipowicz, the researcher, who is also a doctoral student
at Harvard University, set out to investigate whether humor affects
the productivity of workers.
</P>
<P>
   It can, he suggested in a paper presented this month to the
Academy of Management in Chicago, but only if the worker is male.
</P>
<P>
   Filipowicz chose 50 test subjects, 25 men and 25 women.
</P>
<P>
   Half were shown a humorous 20-minute movie clip; half saw a clip
that was not funny.
</P>
<P>
   Then everyone had to complete two tasks, one individually and
the other with a partner of the opposite sex, building a structure
using materials like straws and sticks.
</P>
<P>
   The construction projects were judged on creativity, efficient
use of the materials and other measures.
</P>
<P>
   Although both sexes rated the movies as equally funny (or
unfunny), the men reacted to the humor on both the thinking and
feeling levels, while the women responded only on the thinking
level.
</P>
<P>
   The humor seemed to stimulate the men to better individual
performances than those of the women and the control group. And in
groups consisting of a man and a woman, the increased stimulus for
men was offset by the women's lack of stimulus.
</P>
<P>
   _DENISE DE LAS NUECES
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHILDBIRTH: Long-Lasting Scars of Unwanted Births &LR;
</P>
<P>
   An unwanted birth can have harmful emotional effects not only on
the mother and her child but on other children in the family as
well, researchers at the University of Michigan have found. And
their study says the damage can last well into adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   The study, published in the September issue of the Journal of
Health and Social Behavior, analyzed two sets of data.
</P>
<P>
   The first, a survey of more than 13,000 respondents in 1987-88,
showed that mothers whose births were all intended were less likely
than other mothers to spank or slap their children. And, they were
more likely to take their children on activities and other trips
outside the home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The data showed that mothers with intended births engaged in
fun stuff like going to the movies or the zoo with their children
3.7 times a week,'' said the lead researcher, Dr. Jennifer Barber.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mothers with unintended births reported only doing activities
3.5 times a week. Over the lifetime of a child,'' she added,
``that's a huge difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Using another set of data, on mother-child pairs from 1962 to
1993, the researchers found that adults who had been raised in
families where there was an unintended pregnancy were still having
lower-quality relationships with their mothers than children in
families where all pregnancies were wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our 20s and 30s we get a lot of help from our parents,''
Dr. Barber said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These children are missing out on this big piece of social
support we all need and expect. The mothers with unintended
pregnancies aren't helping them as much as other mothers _ with
child care or moves or just talking.''
</P>
<P>
   _ALISHA BERGER
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
