<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6714 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-CRICKET-0824-     08-23 0437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-CRICKET-0824-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ENGLAND'S CRICKET DREAM TEAM BECOMING A NIGHTMARE
 &HT;    Moving in both International and Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ First the empire, and now this.
</P>
<P>
   Cricket, the sport that symbolizes England, has come to denote a
special sort of misery for the English.
</P>
<P>
   On the grass at London's hallowed Oval stadium, England's
national cricket team on Sunday lost to New Zealand. It was bad
enough to lose to what had been regarded a weak sister team, but it
soon penetrated the nation's collective consciousness that England
now officially and for the first time has the distinction of
fielding the worst national cricket team on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   The loss so stung the 10,000 usually stoic fans at the Oval that
they booed the team's captain and repeated often insulting and
sometimes obscene chants.
</P>
<P>
   Frustration has been building throughout the miserable summer
season during which England has recorded three wins in 14 matches.
</P>
<P>
   The lamentable story was on the front page of virtually every
newspaper here Monday. The Sun dedicated its front page to the
somber pronouncement: ``Official: The death of our national game.
English Cricket. 1744 _ 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   While few Americans pay much attention to cricket _ much less
understand it _ the image of players in dazzling white uniforms
whacking a small hard ball and then trotting around inexplicably,
is as English as Big Ben or bangers and mash. For the English to
find themselves so inept at their defining sport would be
comparable to Americans finding themselves unable to field a decent
baseball or basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The days have long gone when beating England represented the
taking of a scalp,'' wrote the Daily Telegraph. ``Nowadays, it's
the equivalent of stealing a blind man's wig.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, cricket has been played here in one form or another for
hundreds of years. The English spread the sport across the British
Empire. That was their first mistake. The former commonwealth
players share a love of cricket with and an unbridled joy of
beating the English at their own game. The five best national teams
are Australia, West Indies, South Africa, Pakistan and India.
</P>
<P>
   To end the cricket malaise, The Sun offered a modest proposal:
</P>
<P>
   ``Increase defense spending 1000 percent and re-occupy (the
colonies). Ban cricket everywhere and invent another ludicrous
bat-and-ball game which will take the colonies the best part of
another century to master.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-99 1658EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
