<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Aug. 24, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heavy thunderstorms will drench portions of the eastern
Tennessee Valley and southern Appalachians on Tuesday as humid air
pushes northward from the Gulf of Mexico. A large disturbance will
develop over the Middle West and this will induce low pressure to
form in Indiana. Showers will spread across the Ohio Valley into
the Appalachians. Cool, moist winds from the northeast will cause
clouds and light rain to linger over the central Great Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure east of New England will keep dry and warm weather
in much of the Northeast. Clouds will increase from the west and
onshore breezes will refresh the coast. Showers will progress into
the Carolinas and Virginia as a warm front moves slowly north along
the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Sultry air over the South will be marked by a few patches of
thunder-storms, mainly inland. The remnants of Hurricane Bret, now
a tropical depression, will creep westward into northern Mexico's
Coahuila state, but torrential rain will still fall in the lower
Rio Grande Valley. Flooding will persist south of the Big Bend.
Less humid, but rather warm air will occupy the northern and
central Plains as high pressure builds south from Manitoba. It will
stay hot over the Rockies with moisture circulating through the
central and northern mountains. Afternoon storms will be most
common from western Montana to eastern Nevada, but a few storms
will form around the Four Corners region.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds will return to the Northwest Coast as winds become
lighter. Sunshine should burn off patches of fog in California.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Unseen Fury
</P>
<P>
   Although Hurricane Bret was a powerful tropical cyclone when it
made landfall, few people saw the essence of its fury. The
hurricane crossed into the least populated coastal county in the
United States. While the circulation of a strong hurricane
typically covers tens of thousands of square miles, its most
devastating effects are concentrated within 50 miles of the center
of the storm. Sustained hurricane force winds are usually found in
that narrow corridor along the storms path. It is also within that
small zone that the wall of water called the storm surge can crush
coastal structures.
</P>
</TEXT>
