<HEADLINE>
NEW SPECIES OF STRIPED RABBIT FOUND IN SOUTHEAST ASIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Indonesia, Laos, Vietnam)   (The Science Times)  
(DW) 
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Annamite Mountains of Laos and Vietnam, where more new
species of mammals have been found this century than anywhere else
on the planet, have revealed another new animal, this time a
striped rabbit.
</P>
<P>
   The rabbit, discovered by a researcher with the Wildlife
Conservation Society in 1998 and announced in the journal Nature,
has been shown through DNA analysis to be a distant cousin of the
only other known striped rabbit species, found 900 miles to the
south on Sumatra.
</P>
<P>
   The new rabbit, which began to diverge from the Sumatran species
millions of years ago, when Sumatra was joined to mainland Asia,
has yet to be named.
</P>
<P>
   The researcher, Robert J. Timmins, first saw specimens of the
animal for sale in a food market in Ban Lak, Laos, in the foothills
of the Annamites. Teams from the society would often come down from
the mountains to replenish supplies in the market, according to
Alan Rabinowitz, the society's director of science for Asia, who
has led surveys in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had already made discoveries or rediscoveries of four new
species,'' Rabinowitz said. ``So we were kind of clued in to
anything that looked weird.''
</P>
<P>
   The Annamites, a remote, rugged region inhabited by the Hmong
tribe, have been a major source for new mammals. Of the roughly
dozen large mammal species discovered in the world since 1900,
Rabinowitz said, nearly half have been found since 1992 in the
Annamites.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for all the discoveries is that, until this decade,
the region was largely off limits to Westerners. But another may
have to do with an accident of geography.
</P>
<P>
   During the Pleistocene Epoch, a time of alternating glaciation
and warming beginning less than two million years ago, the
Annamites remained glacier-free. Scientists have speculated that
during the warmer periods, animals that had become acclimated to
lower temperatures sought refuge in the colder elevations of the
Annamites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually, with the fragmentation of their habitat, they were
stuck up there,'' Rabinowitz said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
