<HEADER>
A6777 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-QUAKE-LESSONS-ART     08-23 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUAKE-LESSONS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURKISH QUAKE HAS LESSONS FOR CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (The Science Times) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By SANDRA BLAKESLEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Teams of American scientists and engineers have joined Turkish
colleagues in seeking lessons from last week's devastating
earthquake in Anatolia.
</P>
<P>
   For Americans the question is: Does this faraway earthquake help
scientists foretell where the next big one will be in California?
The San Andreas fault in California is almost an identical twin to
the North Anatolian fault that produced the magnitude 7.4
earthquake centered near Izmit, Turkey. The two faults are the same
size and length, move at the same rate and are caused by same
confluence of geological factors, chiefly the movement of tectonic
plates.
</P>
<P>
   The American researchers hope measurements of ground motion in
Turkey will help them pinpoint where the next California quakes are
most likely to occur.
</P>
<P>
   Also, quake-related building codes in Turkey and California are
equally strict. While many structures collapsed last week,
apparently because of shoddy materials or workmanship, it will be
important to learn if those properly built to code withstood the
shaking.
</P>
<P>
   For the Turkish scientists, the big question is: Does this
earthquake increase the risk that another big one will occur closer
to Istanbul and its 12 million people?
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Aykut Barka, a geology professor at Istanbul Technical
University and a leading authority on Anatolian tectonics, said
that earthquakes in Turkey seem to be moving toward Istanbul. While
there is no way to predict earthquakes in the short term, he said,
researchers hope that this quake will provide clues about where the
next one will occur in coming decades.
</P>
<P>
   In mapping the area affected by last week's quake, Barka said
that the fault ruptured for at least 60 miles east of Izmit. In
some places, one side of the fault zone shifted more than 12 feet
relative to the other side. It appears that two fault segments may
have broken 30 seconds apart, producing the very large shocks.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James Dolan, an American geologist from the University of
Southern California who is in Turkey this week, said that
earthquakes as big as this are rare and provide valuable
information on the physics of how and why they occur. ``The more we
know about this quake,'' he said in a telephone interview, ``the
more we'll know about quakes back home.''
</P>
<P>
   The San Andreas and North Anatolian faults are textbook examples
of right lateral strike slip faults.
</P>
<P>
   The San Andreas is a gigantic fracture formed at the boundary of
the Pacific and North American plates _ enormous slabs of the
earth's crust tightly pressed against each other and sitting atop a
deep layer of hot, taffylike rocks. Moving northward, the Pacific
plate is positioned to slide past the North American plate.
</P>
<P>
   The North Anatolian plate is a small slab of crust trapped
between the larger Arabian plate and Eurasian plate. It can be
pictured as a watermelon seed between one's index finger and thumb.
The thumb is Arabia, the index finger is Eurasia and the seed is
Turkey. When the two fingers are squeezed, the ``seed'' slides. The
resulting movement produces earthquakes in much the same fashion as
those seen in California.
</P>
<P>
   Both the San Andreas and the North Anatolian faults are more
than 600 miles long and 10 miles deep and move about an eighth of
an inch each year. In regions of weak rock, small earthquakes occur
frequently. Where rocks are rigid and unforgiving, strain builds
up. Earthquakes occur when the rocks finally give way, releasing
accumulated stress.
</P>
<P>
   The process then repeats itself as the plates continue their
journey. Large fault systems like these tend to be made of segments
that produce earthquakes of varying magnitudes. Moreover, when a
fault segment breaks, neighboring segments can become more loaded
with strain or relieved of strain depending on many factors _ local
fault geometry, the direction of slip, amounts of friction,
relative motions at depth and so on.
</P>
<P>
   Most earthquakes tend to transfer strain to both ends of the
fault, altering stress patterns over tens or hundreds of miles,
depending on the size of the quake. The effects are long lasting.
Thus fault motion in one earthquake affects the probability of
future earthquakes nearby.
</P>
<P>
   In Turkey, for example, one earthquake can set off stress
patterns that set the stage for future temblors. In fact, it has
``the most spectacular example of progressive earthquake failure
anywhere in the world,'' said Dr. Ross Stein, a geophysicist at the
U.S. Geological Survey in Menlo Park, Calif., who has studied the
sequence of events.
</P>
<P>
   In three earlier eras, Stein said, earthquakes migrated in
stepwise fashion from east to west. One began in 967 and ended in
1050. Another sequence took place from 1509 to 1754, and a third
occurred from 1650 to 1668. Many other large, devastating
earthquakes hit Turkey in other centuries.
</P>
<P>
   But most interesting to scientists is the current dominolike
sequence of quakes that began in eastern Turkey in 1939 (killing
30,000 people) and has been progressing westward ever since. Twelve
large earthquakes have occurred along the fault from east to west,
marching toward Istanbul. A few others have struck to the east of
the 1939 temblor but not in the same pattern.
</P>
<P>
   Stein, working with Barka and Dr. James Dieterich of the
Geological Survey, found that all but one of the progressive
earthquakes increased stress in the next fault segment down the
east-to-west line of earthquake activity. No one knows why the
North Anatolian fault behaves in this linear fashion, he said. It
may have a simpler geometry. ``It's something you can't help but
want to study,'' Stein said.
</P>
<P>
   Given the sequence of modern earthquakes, Barka, Stein and
Dieterich used computer models of stress accumulation to report in
a scientific article two years ago that the area around Izmit had
an increased probability of a large earthquake occurring in the
near future. It was not an earthquake prediction, Dieterich said,
``but we were certainly not surprised when it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   If the earthquakes continue to progress toward the west, the
next big one could strike very close to Istanbul and the Sea of
Marmara, Barka said. But he added: ``Istanbul has two advantages
relative to Izmit. It sits on hard rock, and it is six to 10 miles
away from the fault. If buildings are built according to code, I
don't think it would result in the kind of damage we see in this
1999 earthquake.''
</P>
<P>
   The Izmit earthquake has many lessons for California, Stein
said. The San Andreas fault is more irregular and complex but
earthquakes there also tend to increase strain on the ends of fault
segments and reduce strain on collateral or regional faults
elsewhere.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The good news, he said, is that the 1906 San Francisco quake was
so huge that it relieved stress over all of northern California.
Strain increased in the north, around Mendocino, where the San
Andreas meets other plates. It also increased in the south but that
is in central California where the San Andreas fault encounters
weak rock and tends to ``creep'' aseismically _ without quakes. The
1989 Loma Prieta earthquake added stress to both its ends but the
system has been relaxing since then.
</P>
<P>
   The picture in Southern California is more complicated, Stein
said. Relative plate motions are driving the Los Angeles basin _
home to millions of people _ into a mountain range, producing
accordionlike faults all over the region.
</P>
<P>
   The last large quake on the straight southern end of the San
Andreas, in 1857, increased strain to the south but no records
exist to evaluate much more, he said. The 1991 Landers earthquake
raised stress along the San Bernardino segment of the southern San
Andreas, hastening the next great earthquake there by about a
decade. The 1994 Northridge earthquake probably lessened strain
directly north of the town but increased the probability of another
event toward the northeast.
</P>
<P>
   American structural and civil engineers are also in Turkey this
week studying buildings that survived or failed. For them, every
earthquake is a natural experiment for testing theories of how to
safely construct buildings, bridges, hospitals and freeways.
</P>
<P>
   The scene is chilling, said Dr. Thomas Heaton, a professor of
engineering seismology at the California Institute of Technology in
Pasadena. Turkey has an advanced earthquake engineering community.
The same building philosophies are used in Turkey and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The lessons from Izmit will be learned from the buildings that
collapsed, Heaton said. If they met code and were well built, it is
time for California to worry. If the structures are substandard,
Americans can feel more confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in any earthquake,'' Heaton said, ``you can expect
nonductile concrete buildings to collapse. If a quake the size of
the one in Izmit were to strike L.A. or San Francisco, you can
almost guarantee that many older buildings will end up in a similar
situation,'' Heaton said. ``Also changes in architectural style can
make buildings more or less dangerous by where you put windows or
shear walls. Two buildings that meet strict code may not have the
same performance in an earthquake. Until we know what happened in
Turkey, we should be humble.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Poor Turks mostly believe in the fortunes of God, who decides
everything, including whether their houses will collapse or not,''
Barka said. ``They need to be taught that if their houses are
reasonably well built, their lives will not be in danger.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
