<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIMBELL-EXHIBIT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIMBELL MUSEUM WILL HOST TWO MAJOR EXHIBITS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JANET TYSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The Kimbell Art Museum has announced two
important new exhibitions for 2000 _ including an exclusive U.S.
presentation of a blockbuster show featuring works by Renoir,
Cezanne, Matisse, Picasso and others.
</P>
<P>
   The Kimbell will be the only U.S. venue for an international
exhibition of 81 paintings from the Musee de l'Orangerie in Paris,
which is closed for renovation. ``From Renoir to Picasso:
Masterpieces from the Musee de l'Orangerie,'' opens Nov. 12, 2000,
and will feature 16 works by Pierre-Auguste Renoir and seven by
Pablo Picasso, among other late-19th and early-20th-century
artists.
</P>
<P>
   The Kimbell also announced that it will unveil a redesigned,
temporary installation of its permanent collection in November. In
addition, the museum will host ``Stroganoff: The Palace and
Collections of a Russian Noble Family,'' an exhibition of 230
masterworks by Botticelli, Poussin, Van Dyck, Watteau and others,
opening in July 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The announcements are the first major moves made by Timothy
Potts, who became the museum's director in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very pleased we've been able to put in place two
exhibitions as complementary as the Orangerie and the Stroganoff,''
Potts said. ``These are the backbone of next year's visiting
exhibition program.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kimbell, which opened in 1972, has become known as one of
the most important small museums in the United States, recognized
for the quality of its permanent collection, its Louis Kahn
building, and for organizing and presenting major shows. Previous
blockbuster shows include the Impressionist masterpieces loaned
from The Barnes Collection in 1994; ``Monet and the Mediterranean''
in 1997; and a Matisse and Picasso exhibit earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Orangerie collection was put together by two Frenchmen, art
dealer Paul Guillaume and, after Guillaume's death, Jean Walter. It
equals or exceeds in quality the collection assembled by
Guillaume's most celebrated customer, Albert C. Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal is the only other North American venue for the
exhibition, which will also travel to Japan and Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt (the Orangerie) show will be very popular,'' Potts
said, conceding the inevitability of comparison between it and the
Kimbell's record-setting presentation of works from the Barnes
Collection. ``But it will be more than another collection of
important works from this period. It also is a story about how a
great collection was built at a time when this work was not so
greatly appreciated.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Stroganoff: The Palace and Collections of a Russian Noble
Family,'' which will be on view from July 2 through Oct. 1, will
feature a recreation of the Paintings Gallery of the Stroganoff
Palace on St. Petersburg's Nevsky Prospekt, and present more than
200 master works, lent by the State Hermitage and State Russian
museums. The Stroganoffs collected, sponsored and commissioned
artworks over the course of five centuries and had an indelible
impact on Russian cultural life.
</P>
<P>
   Potts is also curating a small, tightly focused show that will
open earlier in 2000 but said that he could not describe it until
loans of art have been finalized.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Kimbell visitors will have a fresh opportunity
to view works from the permanent collection in settings evoking
centuries-old tradition. Instead of the neutral linen and
travertine so closely associated with its galleries, the Kimbell's
Old Master paintings and Asian, pre-Columbian and African works
will temporarily be shown against panels covered with fabrics in
muted colors.
</P>
<P>
   The installation is the work of Milanese architect Mario
Bellini, who has designed a number of important historical
exhibitions and worked with Potts on redesigning and adding to the
National Gallery of Victoria in Melbourne, where Potts was deputy
director and director from 1993 to late 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Occasional changes in either the grouping of artworks or in
their surroundings help reanimate familiar artworks, Potts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a way of telling a different story, one that is commonly
used in museums around the world. And I'd like people to be
thinking more about installation as an aspect of their museum
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Other changes in store include new gallery seating, new cases
and pedestals for three-dimensional works and new furnishings for
the Buffet restaurant. The vertical blinds that for many years
covered the windows around the museum's Maillol courtyard will be
replaced with the finely perforated roll-down scrim seen in many
museums.
</P>
<P>
   The temporary installation ``will be the first time since
(Kimbell founding director) Ric Brown that the permanent collection
has been treated to an art-historical presentation,'' said Patricia
Loud, the Kimbell's curator of architecture.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
