<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6791 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     08-23 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERE'S THE REAL QUESTION ABOUT THE QUESTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's put aside the issue of whether George W. Bush will or will
not answer The Question: Did he ever use illegal drugs,
specifically cocaine?
</P>
<P>
   Bush seems inclined to stick to his guns, refusing to answer
``yes'' or ``no'' beyond suggesting that if he ever did use illegal
drugs, it was more than 25 years ago. But this is subject matter
that is not totally within his control. At some point, Bush might
decide that he has no choice but to answer because The Question is
overshadowing everything else he says or does.
</P>
<P>
   The inevitable public backlash against the media's preoccupation
with The Question could eventually make it unnecessary for Bush to
provide The Answer. But it won't be easy for him to keep resisting
until the backlash sets in.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there is a question that needs to be considered in
addition to the purely speculative proposition of WILL he or WON'T
he? This other question is: SHOULD he?
</P>
<P>
   We've heard a lot of sanctimonious rhetoric about exactly what a
candidate for president of the United States does or does not owe
the voters in the way of information about his private life. And it
should not surprise us in the least that some of the most
vociferous demands for full disclosure from Bush are coming from
people who only a few months ago were adamant in their insistence
that a president's private foibles are none of the public's
business.
</P>
<P>
   Can we say ``hypocrisy,'' boys and girls?
</P>
<P>
   My position on Bush's situation is that he shouldn't confess to
anything that he doesn't want to confess to _ and that voters can
decide whether his candor or lack of same should be a factor in
their electoral decision-making.
</P>
<P>
   That is Bush's position as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to tell people I made mistakes and that I have
learned from my mistakes,'' Bush said the other day. ``And if they
like it, I hope they give me a chance. And if they don't like it,
they can go find somebody else to vote for.''
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, plenty of people _ including some who
support Bush for president _ who believe that the Texas governor
should answer The Question.
</P>
<P>
   But I have a question of my own: Why should he?
</P>
<P>
   Does a candidate have to answer every question that's asked just
because someone has the audacity to ask it?
</P>
<P>
   If that's the standard, then we can force any candidate to
respond to any unfounded allegation we can conjure up _ no matter
how unfair, no matter how outrageous. It's the standard that Bush
says he's challenging when he refuses to answer the drug question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody floats a rumor and it causes you to ask a question,''
Bush said last week.
</P>
<P>
   If he answers the question, the answer prompts another question.
Which prompts more rumors, more questions, more answers, more
rumors.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's the game in American politics and I refuse to play
it,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   I don't mean to suggest that there could never be some aspect of
a politician's private life that might be relevant to his
suitability to hold office. The problem is, no one exercises any
judgment about which aspects are relevant and which aren't.
</P>
<P>
   The media and the character assassins go after everything _ and
they often go after it without bothering to find out if an
allegation is true or false.
</P>
<P>
   Bush obviously hasn't closed the door to the possibility that he
used cocaine in the distant past. But do any of the people who are
asking him about it have proof that he did? If they had proof,
wouldn't we have seen it or heard it by now?
</P>
<P>
   Why should a candidate have to answer personal questions based
on mere presumptions _ with no evidence of any kind to give them
legitimacy?
</P>
<P>
   Are we headed toward a day when every candidate for public
office is forced to provide a public inventory of everything he
ever did that some voter might consider unacceptable?
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Bush may feel that he has no choice but to answer
The Question. Which is too bad, because it's a question that he
should not have to answer.
</P>
<P>
   It's a question that should not have been asked.
(Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
