<HEADER>
A6792 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX     08-23 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPECT NO THANKS OR APOLOGIES _ IT'S A MONOPOLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JIM WRIGHT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This century began with Theodore Roosevelt and others urgently
warning of the rapid growth of monopolies and insisting on controls
to keep a few big corporations from poisoning the roots of free
enterprise by squeezing out smaller competitors. Ironically, the
century ends with the most rapid, rampant spread of monopoly in the
world's history.
</P>
<P>
   Duing the first half of our century, America's statesmen
crafted a careful matrix of measures to restrict the always eager
tentacles of the biggest from gaining control of whole industries
by strangling or gobbling up all significant competition.
</P>
<P>
   There were antitrust laws; the graduated income tax; controls on
banks, stock and bond promotions, and interstate telephone,
pipeline and transportation companies; and other legal measures to
protect the public from price gouging by monopolistic greed.
</P>
<P>
   Free enterprise thrived from a million roots, and most
businesses were home-grown, locally owned. Some grew big, but not
so big as to dominate whole industries. America became a beacon to
the world, the symbol of opportunity for all. Franklin Roosevelt's
second vice president, Henry A. Wallace, proclaimed this ``the
century of the common man.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, somewhere along the way, we seem to have lost our zeal for
small, local, competitive free enterprise where businesses knew and
cherished their workers and their individual customers, and where
the well-being of laborers and consumers was the business of us
all. We strayed from that path.
</P>
<P>
   It may have begun changing in the 1970s with the overlobbied
mania for ``decontrol.'' We deregulated the airlines, savings and
loan companies, banking, telephones. Now cable television. This was
supposed to promote competition. It hasn't. Today there are fewer,
not more serious competitors. The biggest keep getting bigger. The
middle-sized are all being squeezed out.
</P>
<P>
   How does this affect the consumer? In lots of ways. Mainly, it
reduces him or her to a number, a tiny faceless, voiceless figure
on a ream of computer printouts whose convenience is not important
and whose business is dispensable, buried in a bottom-line
calculation of averages.
</P>
<P>
   Let's consider something as familiar as the family TV set. Until
recently, cable TV service was supplied here in Fort Worth by
Marcus Cable. It was locally owned. If you had a problem, you could
call someone locally. For 10 years, my family had no problems.
Everything went smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, Marcus was taken over by Charter
Communications, a national chain with a million customers. Maybe
Mrs. Wright and I are atypical. We moved our residence in May.
Perhaps our moving angered the computer. Since Charter took over,
we've had nothing but headaches _ and nobody to talk to.
Immediately we began getting impersonal printed duns for $158 that
we didn't actually owe, threatening to disconnect our service if it
weren't paid immediately.
</P>
<P>
   When the first of these arrived, I wrote a personal check for
the stipulated amount, accompanied by a handwritten letter, and
posted it that afternoon from our home. I got no acknowledgement,
then or ever. A week or so later, we got another dun. Then, on a
Saturday evening, just as Betty was settling in for a pleasant
evening at home, our sets went blank except for a message that said
we owed $158. There was a telephone number.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't only the cable channels that were out. The computer
had shut down our free stations as well. I called the number
displayed on our set. After listening to several options, I pressed
the number for discussing our bill and then waited. And waited. All
Charter's ``service representatives'' were busy, I was repeatedly
told via recording.
</P>
<P>
   I explained to the lady who finally came on line that there was
an error, as we owed nothing and had actually sent in a voluntary
overpayment. She said she could not help, as the computer showed
that we owed $158. She didn't say she was sorry.
</P>
<P>
   So we waited, televisionless, until Monday morning when a young
man called, stating that he would be out soon to ``disconnect'' our
cable. I explained again. He said he didn't work for Charter and
was only a freelance contractor, but he quoted a figure for which,
in addition to the $158, he'd reconnect us. I waited for him most
of the day.
</P>
<P>
   When he arrived, I pointed out that this would be the second
time I'd have paid the unowed bill. ``Too bad,'' he said, but there
was nothing that he _ or anyone else, for that matter _ could do
about it. ``They're a monopoly,'' was his only explanation.
</P>
<P>
   That week, my office assistant got someone on the telephone at
Charter. After considerable discussion, an error was acknowledged.
A ``computer glitch,'' I think they call it.
</P>
<P>
   Charter's computer had been carrying two accounts, one in my
name and one in Betty's. Mine carried a healthy credit. We asked
that the two be consolidated. This done, Charter's spokesperson
said, we had a credit balance.
</P>
<P>
   Fine, I thought. We'll stay ahead and avoid further harassment.
</P>
<P>
   The next week I got another printout threat. The computer hasn't
forgiven me. We owe $158, and if we wanted to avoid a disruption in
service, we'd better pay up immediately!
</P>
<P>
   Now, I don't really think that big corporation is deliberately
trying to cheat me. It's just that it's ... well, sort of ...
distant, you know, and ... well, computer-dependent and
personality-deprived, and ... do I dare say ``indifferent''? It
hasn't said it's sorry yet, or thanks, or ... not that I expect it
to.
</P>
<P>
   It's a monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Wright of Fort Worth is a former speaker of the U.S. House
of Representatives. You can write him at P.O. Box 1413, Fort Worth,
TX 76101, or at j.wright(AT)tcu.edu. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
