<SLUG> BC-TV-MOB-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FAMILY VALUES:' SO IT'S ONLY MAKE-BELIEVE. GOTTA PROBLEM WITH
THAT? 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes appear at end of review. Time, channel are
for New York area. Check local listings.) 
(DW) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   From time to time in the course of ``Family Values: The Mob and
the Movies,'' it is stipulated that most Italian-Americans are
honest, hard-working and as averse to violence as other citizens.
But this documentary is not a production of some Italian-American
Anti-Defamation League. No sooner is ethnic etiquette out of the
way than the program settles into tales of larceny and mayhem among
gangs led by New Yorkers with names like Gotti, Gambino and
Columbo.
</P>
<P>
   What gives these two hours a fresh spin is the real-life cast,
most of them members of what they drolly call the Gangsters Actors
Guild (that's right, GAG). Few viewers may recognize their names or
stage names, but their non-matinee-idol faces, pavement accents and
often abrupt on-screen demises sustain an industry of mob movies.
</P>
<P>
   Their monikers include Adonis, Pastore, Salerno, Serra, Sirico
and Squicciarini, and their professional personas blend with their
mostly fond accounts of growing up in Bensonhurst in Brooklyn, on
Belmont Avenue in the Bronx and in other enclaves of ethnic
identity.
</P>
<P>
   If you have trouble sorting out what are offered as authentic
sidewalks-of-New York memories from the scenes from ``Goodfellas,''
``A Bronx Tale,'' ``Gotti,'' ``Donnie Brasco'' and other mob epics
treated here, the confusion is built into a program that never
quite figures out what it wants to be: a lesson in how
Italian-American youths are either lured into the criminal life by
the wise guys or narrowly escape that fate, or just another
exercise in screen-wise battery and slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Joining the actors around a convivial table, the viewer can
easily imagine them playing gin rummy in the back room of a Little
Italy social club. Their memories of family life are appropriately
sentimental, their descriptions of mob life admonitory. The right
clothes (pinky rings and Piaget watches) and an appreciation of
southern Italian cooking (very thin slices of garlic) get their
due.
</P>
<P>
   Whether these chatty gents are delivering firsthand information
or the leavings from years of scripts, flavored with cliches about
respect and honor, you decide. Either way the program is likely to
elicit complaints that once again television is subjecting
Italian-Americans to stereotypes that other minorities are now
spared.
</P>
<P>
   Several nonactors purport to tell of real, unscripted
experiences. There is Dominick, who having testified against some
colleagues is now in the Federal Witness Protection Program; Jerry
Capeci, a no-nonsense journalist who calls the mobs ``killing
machines'' and Frank Pontillo, who is serving a term for declining
to rat on his pals.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Vincent, whom we can see being blown away in one of his
roles, is the evening's host. This gang agrees that being an actor
is wiser than being a wise guy.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `FAMILY VALUES
</P>
<P>
   The Mob and the Movies'
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. ET Tuesday on TNT
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Cosentino, producer/director; Sandra Consentino,
editor/director. Frank Vincent, host. Telescript by Allen Rucker.
Carl H. Lindahl, executive producer, TNT. A production of Big Bear
Films.
</P>
<P>
   With: Frank Adonis, Tony Darrow, Vincent Pastore, Dave Salerno,
Ray Serra, Tony Sirico, Michael Squicciarini. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
