<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-MARYLAND-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Maryland's Vanderlinden looks to buck losing trendBy Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE PARK, Md. _ Since Bobby Ross left in 1986 after winning
three ACC titles in his last four years, Maryland has been a place
for coaches to end their careers.
</P>
<P>
   The Terrapins have compiled an inglorious 45-86-2 mark since
Ross, have been through Joe Krivak and Mark Duffner, and now are
working on Ron Vanderlinden.
</P>
<P>
   Vanderlinden came to College Park two seasons ago from Gary
Barnett's staff at Northwestern with great expectations, but the
Terps have gone 5-17 under him. This year looks to be more of the
same. Maryland has been picked last in the conference in most
preseason publications, and some of the Terp following are losing
patience. Vanderlinden recited the obstacles he has had to overcome
but conceded, ``I really didn't know what I was walking into. I
knew the records were 6-5 and 5-6. I was hopeful. But for one
reason or another, (a turnaround) hasn't happened. Really, what
happened for us was that the cupboard was bare.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, the 43-year-old coach said, ``We had to convert
from the run-and-shoot, we didn't have a tight end or a fullback on
campus, and the linemen were only used to pass blocking.''
</P>
<P>
   The Terps have two things going for them that could make this
season interesting.
</P>
<P>
   One is tailback Lamont Jordan, one of the top runners in the
ACC. Jordan had 906 yards last season despite missing most of two
games and running behind a poor offensive line. He averaged 5.4
yards per carry and visited Vanderlinden in the off-season to
suggest that he should carry the ball more.
</P>
<P>
   The other is a freshman named Latrez Harrison, a 6-foot-3,
215-pound quarterback from Atlanta. Harrison, rated as one of the
nation's top schoolboy quarterbacks last season, turned down
scholarship offers from Auburn, Syracuse, Georgia, Alabama and
Georgia Tech to come to Maryland. Harrison is in a battle for the
starting job with last year's starter, Randall Jones, and redshirt
freshman Calvin McCall.
</P>
<P>
   Fall practice observers say Harrison might not start the first
game but he is too good to keep out of the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Latrez is everything we thought he would be and everything we
hoped he would be,'' Vanderlinden said. ``Latrez is as talented a
recruit as I've had since I've been here.'' Right now, Jordan is
the best player. Is he the best running back in the ACC? ``Yes and
no,'' Jordan said. ``Yes, because that's the kind of mentality I
have to have. No, because my statistics don't show it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was fun on game day, but it wasn't any fun watching
the film the week after. It was always the same thing. If this guy
had made a block or that guy had made a block, we might have won.''
</P>
<P>
   The offensive line is better this year, Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we had trouble sustaining drives, and that's why I
wasn't getting more carries, '' he said. ``But we're improved
there, and (defenses) can't put eight or nine people up at the line
of scrimmage. We've got a passing game, too. We're not just a
running team.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the proof will be at season's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the thing,'' Jordan said. ``Last year we were talking
about what we had to do, and then we'd go out and not do it. This
year we've got to show we can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   MARYLAND FACT BOX
</P>
<P>
   _ Location: College Park, Md.
</P>
<P>
   _ Enrollment: 33,006.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Ron Vanderlinden is 5-17 in two years at Maryland and
overall.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nickname: Terrapins.
</P>
<P>
   _ Stadium: Byrd Stadium (48,055).
</P>
<P>
   _ Record: 526-473-43.
</P>
<P>
   _ ACC titles: 8 (1953, '55, '74, '75, '76, '83, '84, '85).
</P>
<P>
   _ 1998 record: 3-8 overall, 1-7 ACC.
</P>
<P>
   _ Schedule: Sept. 2, at Temple; Sept. 11, Western Carolina;
Sept. 18, West Virginia;
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 30, at Georgia Tech; Oct. 9, at Wake Forest; Oct. 16,
Clemson; Oct. 23, North Carolina; Oct. 30, Duke; Nov. 6, at N.C.
State; Nov. 13, at Florida State; Nov. 20, Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Arey writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
