<SLUG> BC-NOTBRITNEY-1000(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THANKS, BUT JESSICA SIMPSON DOESN'T WANT TO BE NEXT BRITNEY SPEARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The buzz has already started: She recently finished a
tour with teen heartthrobs 98 Degrees, and she has been featured in
several teen magazines, from ``Teen'' to ``Teen People,'' even
though her Columbia debut, ``Sweet Kisses,'' doesn't come out until
November.
</P>
<P>
   And here's the clincher: She's being compared with Britney
Spears _ and she's not too thrilled about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're both young and we both dance, so I hear a lot of, `Oh,
she's trying to be Britney,' '' she said. ``I wouldn't mind selling
as many records as her, but I'm not trying to be her.''
</P>
<P>
   Meet Jessica Simpson, a young, gorgeous Texan and budding pop
singer who could very well become pop music's next teen sensation.
</P>
<P>
   She has the looks, the music (a pop/R&AMP;B-flavored disc due in
November), the power (she's on major label Columbia) and, yes, the
talent. She really can sing.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Morales, assistant program/music director for Fort
Worth-Dallas pop station KISS/106.1 FM, was sold on her the day she
performed at the station's recent KISS Party in Dallas. ``The
response from the crowd was very positive,'' he said. ``I told her
record company that with the right material, this girl is gonna be
very, very big. I hate to compare her to Britney, but ...''
</P>
<P>
   Simpson and her label are getting an early start on muting the
here-comes-the-next-Britney scuttlebutt. In an effort to quash
Britney comparisons, Columbia has taken a different approach to
establishing Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   First, the label, or rather label president and Mariah Carey-ex
Tommy Mottola, has chosen a Celine Dion-type ballad called ``I
Wanna Love You Forever'' as Simpson's first single, which comes out
next month. Traditionally, labels release catchy pop-radio tracks
as launch singles, then later, the big ballads.
</P>
<P>
   Simpson said Mottola wanted to go the reverse route, to
introduce her voice, not necessarily to introduce her.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first single was gonna be `The Final Heartbreak' (an
upbeat track) until Tommy got involved,'' Simpson said. ``He wants
me to be totally respected and have it be about my voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Second, Sony has sent Simpson on a promotional tour. Instead of
playing public full-length concerts, she sings in small clubs,
performing to rooms of music journalists, radio station folks and
other industry decision-makers.
</P>
<P>
   Simpson did this last week at Dallas' Gypsy Tea Room, performing
two songs to a crowd of local writers and radio-station bigwigs, as
well as members of her family and her label's family.
</P>
<P>
   The pre-show presentation was cheese _ images of her flashed
across a video screen, along with phrases such as ``She is bright,
beautiful and blessed.''
</P>
<P>
   Things didn't necessarily get better when Simpson came out.
Accompanied by four backup dancers (one of whom was her 14-year-old
sister, Ashlee), Simpson proceeded to take her place along
pop-music's conveyor belt of Backstreets and Britneys, dancing and
singing along to pre-recorded music and vocals. It takes talent to
do this?
</P>
<P>
   Everything changed when the dancers left, the lights dimmed and
the canned-music intro to ``I Wanna Love You Forever'' purred
through the club's speakers. Leaning her head back, she began to
sing. Glasses filled with free drinks stopped clinking. Chatter
silenced. Everyone stared. And Simpson wailed, holding onto notes
like she was holding onto her last breath. When the song was over,
the tough-to-sell crowd cheered.
</P>
<P>
   Sony's strategy just might work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think ballads are timeless,'' Simpson said. ``It's hard to
think of an uptempo song that has made a big impact on my life. One
year, it's techno, rap another year, but it's the ballads that have
been the same. That's what so many people like about Mariah and
Celine. I'll have to change my music to change with the times, but
I'll always do ballads. I'm never gonna rap or anything, yo, yo,
yo.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Simpson has a professional air that belies her
age, no doubt due to working on ``Kisses'' for the past two years
and touring with 98 Degrees.
</P>
<P>
   But in other ways, she is still very much a 19-year-old _
giggly, giddy, cracking jokes about rap, fame and even Britney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mine are definitely real,'' she said, comparing a particular
region of her anatomy to Spears'. (Spears has been subjected to
criticism for undergoing breast-enhancement surgery, emphasizing
body over talent for her female teen-age fans).
</P>
<P>
   Simpson even has a lighthearted attitude toward a recent surgery
that was not a laughing matter.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a week before her Dallas appearance, she had a cyst
removed from one of her fallopian tubes. She canceled her Boston
show, went home to rest for a few days, then was back onstage in
Dallas, despite continued pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really, really sick in Dallas, that's why I wasn't
dancing a whole lot. I was still in a lot of pain,'' she said on
the phone from San Francisco. ``I thought my stitches were gonna
pop open.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Raised in Richardson, Texas, Simpson got an early start on her
music career, singing at Richardson Heights Baptist Church, where
her father was a minister. At 14, she cut a gospel record. But by
the time the CD was finished, the label had folded, leaving Simpson
out in the cold.
</P>
<P>
   Releasing the disc became a family effort. ``My grandmother paid
for it to be mixed and when my dad would speak at different church
conferences, I'd be the special guest and sing. We'd sell CDs that
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Simpson quickly established herself on the local Christian-music
circuit, often appearing on bills with Kirk Franklin and CeCe
Winans. Realizing their daughter's potential, the Simpsons hired an
entertainment lawyer in hopes of breaking her nationally. Word got
around. Labels started calling. It got frantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I showcased to nine record labels in two days when I was 17,''
said Simpson, a graduate of J.J. Pierce High School in Richardson.
``I got a couple offers, but then Tommy Mottola wanted to hear me.
I was so nervous, you know, because he listens to Mariah all the
time. But I sang for him and he signed me on the spot.''
</P>
<P>
   During the past two years, Simpson has been working on her debut
with a variety of producers, including Sam Waters of Color Me Badd
and Carey's producer, Louis Biancanella. The toughest part, Simpson
said, was choosing songs for it. She said she didn't want the
material to contradict her personal or religious beliefs. That's
also why she passed on appearing in a risque scene in ``Top Gun''
producer Jerry Bruckheimer's new movie, ``Coyote Ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted me to do a sex scene. It was more of an implied
thing, but I still didn't feel right doing it,'' she said. ``I felt
like it was contradicting everything I stand for. Some people think
I'm crazy. There was definitely a lot of money involved, and my
album and the movie would come out around the same time. But my
morals are worth more to me than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Simpson said she's taking the same approach to music.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to get caught up in the whole image thing, like
what outfit I'm wearing or how big my boobs are,'' she said. ``I
don't know if that's the case with all artists, but for me, I
really do love to sing. This is something I want to do for the rest
of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
