u i BC-CHINA-TIBET-0824-COX     08-23 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TIBET-0824-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. SEEKS RETURN OF AMERICAN INJURED TRYING TO ESCAPE IN CHINA
 &HT;    400&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ The American Embassy said Monday it is seeking Chinese
permission to airlift out a badly injured American of Tibetan
ancestry who reportedly tumbled out of a hotel window last week
while trying to escape Chinese police interrogation in a remote
region near Tibet.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. embassy spokeswoman said Daja Meston, a 29-year-old
Tibetan linguist from Newton, Mass., is in ``serious but stable
condition'' in a Chinese hospital 900 miles west of Beijing. He is
suffering from a broken spine and other broken bones as well as
internal injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The scene of this strange episode was Qinghai Province, one of
China's emptiest and least-visited borderlands near the mountain
passes into Tibet. Qinghai is a land where ethnic Tibetans and
Muslims have been in a centuries-long struggle for domination
against ethnic Chinese settlers, and where the ruling Chinese have
established prison factories for several hundred thousand convicts
from across China.
</P>
<P>
   Meston, along with an Australian human rights activist and a
local Tibetan-speaking guide, were seized by Chinese police in a
Tibetan-populated rural area of the Qinghai Province on August 15.
The two foreigners were charged with conducting ``illegal
interviews'' and entering a forbidden area while visiting China on
tourist visas.
</P>
<P>
   The trio had been looking into a controversial aid project in
which China has tentatively obtained a $40 million World Bank loan
to resettle 58,000 poor Chinese farmers into an area that Tibetan
activists claim as their ancestral land. The loan had been frozen
in June pending further evaluation following protests from the
Clinton Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The three were transported for interrogation to a hotel in the
provincial capital Xining, the only part of the province with a
solid ethnic Chinese majority. Following Meston's reported fall
from the window, he was being held under police guard in an
undisclosed hospital in Xining.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. embassy spokeswoman, who declined to be identified,
said an embassy doctor who flew to visit Meston over the weekend
found that his injuries ``consistent'' with a report from China's
official Xinhua news agency that Meston ``jumped or fell from the
window while trying to escape.''
</P>
<P>
   She said Chinese authorities have assured the U.S. Embassy that
``his investigation has been suspended while he is hospitalized.''
She said that Chinese and American authorities are discussing a
possible Medivac flight but ``no date has been set.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Meston's Australian colleague, academic researcher Gabriel
Lafitte, was deported to Australia over the weekend after he agreed
to Chinese demands that he confess to conducting illegal research
and entering an off-limits area _ a state farm near the
resettlement project that employs prison labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Mr. Meston's fall) was not an accident,'' Lafitte said after
an emotional reunion with his wife in Australia. ``That is
inconceivable. There were police in the rooms the whole time. I
think he was driven to it by the calculated cruelty of the
interrogation process.''
</P>
<P>
   Lafitte said that as he was being interrogated, he could
sometimes hear through the walls while Meston was defiantly
refusing to sign any confession demanded by the police. Lafitte
said he was intensely questioned from 1 a.m. to 5 a.m. each day for
a week, but not beaten.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
