<SLUG> BC-ETOUR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former Coke whiz Zyman hired by start-up firms
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ To help build brand recognition and grab the attention
of Web surfers and entrepreneurs everywhere, a trio of
Atlanta-based Internet start-up firms have retained the services of
former Coca-Cola Co. marketing whiz Sergio Zyman and his marketing
firm Z Group.
</P>
<P>
   Zyman, author of the best-selling business book ``The End of
Marketing as We Know It,'' has signed on to work with eTour.com,
which delivers Web sites targeted to user interests.
</P>
<P>
   Zyman, famous for launching the disastrous New Coke and the
phenomenally successful Diet Coke, will also be a senior marketing
advisor to local e-commerce enabler Nexchange, along with
eHatchery, the new Atlanta-based next-generation incubator founded
by Relevant Knowledge founder Jeff Levy.
</P>
<P>
   Zyman will serve as senior marketing advisor to Levy's new
company which launched Monday. The new company will provide Web
start-ups with equity investment capital, Internet-ready office
space, complete administrative and financial infrastructure, and
hands-on strategic and tactical assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was introduced to Sergio through Roger Barnette of eTour and
Boland Jones of Premiere Technologies,'' Levy says. ``Of all
places, we connected on a golf course in Vail (Colo.). He
understood our vision and the importance of a strong marketing
program for Internet start-ups.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnette is also enthusiastic about employing Zyman's marketing
wizardry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wealth of marketing experience Sergio Zyman and his team
bring to eTour is essential for us to realize the full potential of
our business,'' Barnette says. ``We feel the Z Group will help
eTour become a household name.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnette's eTour.com will also employ Zyman's Z Group to help
design and develop the eTour brand and assist in helping the two
year old company develop a communications and marketing strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Nexchange Corporation, which helps companies create
co-branded online stores that sell products relevant to their
Website's content, will also be utilizing Zyman's services. The
company said Monday it received a $9 million second round equity
round equity financing commitment and will use the proceeds from
the investment to expand its sales and marketing operations. That's
where Zyman comes in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sergio is known worldwide as one of the best marketing minds
in the business,'' said Joe Michaels, Nexchange's President and
Chief Marketing Officer. ``To have him join our team is an
invaluable endorsement of the Nexchange business model.''
</P>
<P>
   Zyman, who spends much of his time in Colorado, said he's been
spending a lot of time online and is enthusiastic about his new
clients.
</P>
<P>
   Zyman believes the clients' Internet savvy combined with his
experience creating brand leadership ``should give each company the
resources it needs to thrive.''
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
