u e BC-HEADLONG-BOOK-REVIEW-     08-23 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEADLONG-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOST MASTERPIECE? MAYBE. HUMAN FOLLY? INDEED. 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: production notes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In one brightly colored canvas after another, Pieter Bruegel
chronicled the varieties of human folly _ from individual hubris
(``The Fall of Icarus'') to public brutality (``The Massacre of the
Innocents''), from private lunacy (``The Blue Cloak'') to
apocalyptic carnage (``Dulle Griet''). Some of his biographers
suggest that he belonged to an Antwerp circle of humanists who
believed that man is driven to sin by his own foolishness.
</P>
<P>
   In his antic new novel, ``Headlong,'' the British playwright
Michael Frayn has constructed an ingenious plot around a missing
Bruegel painting, and in doing so, created his own resonant
portrait of human folly. In this case, it is the folly of one
impulsive Englishman who allows greed, snobbery and intellectual
hubris to lead him astray and to risk his marriage, his family's
savings and his good name _ all for the sake of a painting that may
or may not be a long-lost Bruegel. It is a story that enables Frayn
to showcase his own gift for satiric farce while re-examining one
of his favorite themes: namely, people's tendency to impose their
own ideas and preoccupations on the world at large.
</P>
<P>
   Reliving the events that changed his life, Frayn's narrator _ a
philosophy professor named Martin Clay who bears more than a
passing resemblance to the self-aggrandizing scholar in the
author's 1990 novel, ``The Trick of It'' _ recounts his story in
the present tense, allowing events to unfurl as they occurred, and
``explaining exactly what I thought as I thought it'' without ``the
distortions of hindsight.''
</P>
<P>
   This technique, combined with Martin's confession that he is
afraid of emerging from the story as ``an object of outrage and
horror,'' lends the story a powerful undertow of suspense, even as
it teases the reader into sharing Martin's blindered point of view.
</P>
<P>
   Martin and his wife, Kate, we learn, have left London for an
extended sojourn at their country house with their infant daughter,
Tilda. Kate has taken some time off from her job as an art
historian, while Martin is supposed to be finishing a book about
``the impact of nominalism on Netherlandish art of the 15th
century.'' Their pastoral idyll is abruptly interrupted, however,
when one of their neighbors, a blustering local named Tony Churt,
invites them over for dinner and asks their opinion of several
paintings he wants to sell.
</P>
<P>
   The first painting _ and the one Tony is most eager to get
appraised _ is a gigantic rendering of the abduction of Helen of
Troy, by an Italian artist named Giordano. The second and third are
17th-century Dutch pictorials. The fourth is _ or appears to
Martin, to be _ a genuine Bruegel. Not just any Bruegel, but the
long-missing sixth panel from the Flemish painter's famous 1565
``Seasons'' series _ a painting that would not only make its owner
a wealthy man, but also bring accolades from the art world for
uncovering one of history's most elusive treasures.
</P>
<P>
   The canvas Martin glimpses in Tony's breakfast room is titled
``Pretmakers in een Berglandschap'' (that is, ``Merrymakers in a
Mountain Landscape'') and depicts a springtime landscape: a group
of Bruegelesque peasants perform a heavy, clumping dance in one
corner while a thickset man courts his beloved in another. Martin
is stunned by what he sees, but instead of telling Tony of his
suspicions, he invents a byzantine plot for taking possession of
the painting himself. He rationalizes his unscrupulous plan by
telling himself that the boorish Tony could never appreciate the
magnitude of his find, and he vows to give Tony ``a lesson in the
gentlemanly attributes of ruthlessness and style.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin's plot for gaining ownership of ``Pretmakers'' involves
finding a phony buyer for the Giordano canvas and then casually
telling Tony that this buyer would like to purchase the other three
paintings as well. It will mean raising some 100,000 pounds,
finding a genuine buyer for the Giordano and then concocting a
diplomatic mechanism for revealing the Bruegel to the world. When
Martin tells Kate about his discovery, she is duly skeptical, and
he promises her that he will find some way to verify the painting's
authenticity before putting the family's finances on the line.
</P>
<P>
   So Martin immerses himself in Bruegel research, reading
everything he can find about the painter's life and work. Frayn
artfully orchestrates this research, giving the reader a
fascinating tour through the intellectual thickets of Bruegel
scholarship while persuading us to share Martin's growing
conviction that he has found the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, Frayn also shows us how easily the eager Martin _
who, like so many of the author's earlier characters, is intent on
finding a way to order the messy world around him _ allows his
speculative fantasies to run away with him, and how he uses all his
intellectual resources to make his research fit ``his'' painting.
At the same time, Frayn draws subtle parallels between Martin and
his world, and the lives depicted in Bruegel's paintings: Martin,
he suggests, may be headed, like Icarus, for a fatal fall, while
Tony Churt recalls all those Bruegel peasants who seem oblivious to
the calamities around them.
</P>
<P>
   While one of the pleasures of this book certainly lies in
Frayn's deft sendup of pompous academics, the novel also delivers
humor of a less cerebral kind. Frayn cleverly builds the clockwork
mechanism of farce _ showcased so brilliantly in his 1983 Broadway
hit, ``Noises Off'' _ into the story of ``Headlong,'' piling one
misunderstanding and complication upon the next to plunge Martin
into a snowballing comedy of errors.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's discovery that Tony is trying to get him to sell his
paintings as a tax dodge; his realization that Tony's wife, Laura,
has mistaken his interest in the paintings for a romantic interest
in her, and his growing antipathy toward Kate for involving one of
her art historian colleagues in his scheme _ each of these
developments will contribute to the explosive conclusion of this
novel, a novel that turns out to be as entertaining as it is
intelligent, as stimulating as it is funny.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATON NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `HEADLONG'
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Frayn
</P>
<P>
   342 pages. Metropolitan Books/Henry Holt &AMP; Co. $26.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
