<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HDEPOT-MUSEUM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Museum holds nuts and bolts of Home Depot history
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With two decades of home improvement under its belt,
Home Depot lately has been drilling its history into the minds of
anyone who will listen.
</P>
<P>
   The nostalgia rolled out this spring with ``Built from
Scratch,'' a tell-(almost)-all by co-founders Bernie Marcus and
Arthur Blank.
</P>
<P>
   And now there's the Legend, a new company museum at Home Depot's
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The museum opens Wednesday, in time for the home improvement
retailer's 20th anniversary celebration. About 4,000 managers are
expected in Atlanta for the four-day meeting, which is to be equal
parts shop talk, pep rally and party.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the executives will tour the museum, which will be open
to employees and shareholders on an appointment-only basis. The $2
million museum was built as a training tool, not an attraction,
said Rob Hallam, director of internal communication and one of the
original designers of the museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to create the World of Coca-Cola here,''
Hallam said. ``The idea for an ongoing historical effort began 10
years ago as a way to preserve Home Depot's values.''
</P>
<P>
   Employees won't find ancient hacksaws or primitive hand tools in
the museum. The Legend is more like fancy Cliff Notes of the
company's biography, laid out in the framework of an unfinished
house. Displays are mounted on particle board with nuts and bolts.
In one room, a shower head serves as a speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Packrat customers helped stock the artifact section. Thanks to a
shopper who recently brought in a 16-year-old can of paint to match
the color, Home Depot can show off its original ``Atlanta's
Finest'' brand. (The can still had wet paint in it, company
historian Nancy Beliveau proudly noted.)
</P>
<P>
   Only 20 percent of the 2,700-square-foot museum is of Home
Depot's history. The rest is an overview of the company operations
in sectors, including marketing and community affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies start spinning their corporate lore after 50
years or so in the business. While Home Depot's scrapbook is
relatively young, it's packed with milestones already, said Dick
Hammill, senior vice president of marketing and communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the dynamic growth of the company, the headlines we've
made and our financial success gave us license to open a museum,''
Hammill said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most companies wouldn't have that much to talk about after 20
years.
</P>
<P>
   Patti Bond writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
