<HEADER>
A6844 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-FRANCE-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      08-23 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE'S GREEN PARTY PUSHES JOSPIN ON NUCLEAR POWER POLICY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MARLISE SIMONS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ France's Green Party, emboldened by a good showing in
the European parliamentary elections, has threatened to pull out of
the government coalition if Prime Minister Lionel Jospin approves a
new generation of nuclear power stations to replace old ones.
</P>
<P>
   The Greens, who joined Jospin's minority government in 1997,
have always insisted that the nuclear energy issue is at the center
of their policy concerns. But even though the Green leader,
Dominique Voynet, serves as environment minister, the party says it
is being ignored on vital questions inside the government
coalition.
</P>
<P>
   The issue at hand is the coming debate on the future of France's
energy policy. Its central question is whether France will reduce
its dependence on nuclear energy and turn to other sources.
France's 57 nuclear reactors provide the country with 78 percent of
its energy, one of the highest rates in the world.
</P>
<P>
   But as those plants become obsolete in the coming years, France
will face the choice of phasing them out or replacing them with a
new type, the so-called European Pressurized Reactors. These
reactors, developed in a Franco-German project, are expected to be
ready to go into operation around 2010.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-nuclear campaign planned in France may cause some
turbulence, but even if the Greens walk out this is not likely to
threaten the fate of the government coalition, which includes the
Communists and would still retain its majority in Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   As Greens have elsewhere in Europe, those in France have
strongly campaigned against nuclear energy, and they say a straight
replacement plan is not acceptable. They insist they cannot
compromise on this point, which they see as a cornerstone of their
agreement with the Socialists before joining the coalition
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very fundamental question for us,'' said Denis Baupin,
the Green Party spokesman. ``Do we replace the decommissioned
plants with new ones or do we start to opt out of nuclear energy,
like Belgium and Germany? If the decision is for new plants, we
will pull out of the government.''
</P>
<P>
   To make sure they will be heard, the Greens say they are
planning a series of protests against nuclear power _ matching the
campaign of Germany's Greens, who have been pressuring the
government of Gerhard Schroeder to phase out nuclear energy use
more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The French environmentalists see the experience of their German
counterparts as a warning sign. German Greens have become angry and
frustrated as Schroeder's promised effort to shut down nuclear
power stations has stalled after pressure from business leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say privately that an informal consensus is forming
that France will reduce, though not abolish, its nuclear power
stations. They say that if the matter heats up, the government can
afford to postpone any key decisions until after the presidential
elections of 2002 _ for which the Socialists want to keep the
Greens as allies.
</P>
<P>
   But the tension over the issue underscores the rising influence
of the Green movement here. After long seeming indifferent to
environmental questions, France is now among the European countries
where Greens have gained support and moved from the political
fringes closer to the center of power.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists currently hold Cabinet posts in half a dozen
European governments, including France's. As their neighbors fared
better, France's Greens had remained marginal in political life
because of in-fighting and splits over ideology. But their position
improved after Mrs. Voynet took charge in 1993. Among other
changes, she allied the Greens with the Socialists.
</P>
<P>
   But unexpected success came in the June European Parliamentary
elections, when the Greens vote surged to close to 10 percent from
less than 3 percent in the last European election, in 1994. In the
Paris area alone, the Greens scored almost 20 percent. This has
prompted them to fight for greater influence in future local
elections.
</P>
<P>
   They have been taken aback to discover that their new popularity
does not translate automatically into more political clout. Mrs.
Voynet and other party members have said that their 10 percent vote
should have earned them more seats in the Cabinet than the single
one they now have. Party leaders also sound clearly frustrated that
they apparently have not gained greater say over key policy
decisions. Rather they feel rebuffed by Jospin.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, they appear more determined than before to stand
their ground, and fight, if the nuclear energy debate gets under
way in the coming months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-99 1821EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990823.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6848 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-23 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DID HE OR DIDN'T HE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Tsk, tsk. Such howls of outrage. The sedate
coronation may be off. We seem to be in an untidy Republican
presidential campaign brawl after all.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush is _ horrors _ being picked on by the
nasty, inconsiderate press. We have discovered he's not perfect!
</P>
<P>
   He got into trouble for sounding oddly evasive about possible
youthful experimentation with cocaine. Bush's weaseling triggered
all sorts of bad memories of President Clinton's habit of
half-truths, obfuscations and glib distortions when confronted with
allegations of embarrassing conduct that often turned out to be
true.
</P>
<P>
   And the treatment of Clinton has set the standard by which all
subsequent presidential candidates will be judged. It is a ruthless
measure, applied unmercifully.
</P>
<P>
   After years of unprecedented scrutiny, Clinton has been stripped
of virtually all privacy, his most tawdry secrets exposed for the
world to see. It is not a pretty sight. He has been accused of
everything from rape to obstruction of justice. He admitted lying
about illicit affairs and was fined for contempt of court and
mocked for claiming not to have inhaled when he tried marijuana as
a student.
</P>
<P>
   All presidents fib when it suits them, but Clinton's fibs seemed
swollen with evil portent for the future. Every small misstep, past
and present, became grist for suspicions about a permanent, deep
character flaw making him unsuitable for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he has survived. A majority of voters still approve of the
job he is doing although they don't approve of his personal
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Insofar as we know, Bush has led a more exemplary private life
than Clinton over the last two decades. (They are both 53, baby
boomers who are products of the tumultuous '60s.)
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's peculiar performance when confronted with
increasingly specific questions about using cocaine, a felony in
many states, has made him suddenly vulnerable to suspicions that he
is hiding something. The character issue comes in many forms.
</P>
<P>
   Bush admits to being ``reckless'' in his youth, drinking and
partying too much, but says that he has grown up and now minds his
manners. He has also admitted to premarital sex, although as
governor he promotes a campaign urging Texas youth to remain
virginal until they are in a ``Biblical marriage relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush, declaring that he has been constantly faithful to his
wife, contrasts his marital fidelity to Clinton's promiscuity.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's straightforward talk is unlikely to interfere
with his presidential ambitions. But it makes his bungling of the
drug issue all the more puzzling. Every other presidential
candidate has flatly denied ever taking cocaine or crack.
</P>
<P>
   Bush at first refused to answer but then last week allowed as
how he had been clean since the age of 28. Naturally, people wonder
what he was doing when he was 27 and younger. In this country, we
are regarded as adults at the age of 18, responsible for our own
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Bush supporters claim that youthful indiscretions, whatever they
may be, are not relevant to his ability to lead the nation as
president. It was all too long ago. Oh? Clinton's marijuana episode
and maneuvers to duck the Vietnam draft at a similar age were
constantly cited as profoundly indicative of a permanently warped
moral code.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, if Bush snorted cocaine _ and there is no proof so
far that he did _ it was not just a sin, the word preferred by his
spin masters, but a crime. Bush says that what is important is
``who you are today, not who you were yesterday.'' But who he is
today is a vengeful governor unforgiving toward drug users,
insisting on harsh sentences and sending them to jail. He shows no
compassionate understanding for the mistakes of today's
``reckless'' youth. Into the slammer with them!
</P>
<P>
   So here we have once again the issue of hypocrisy. It's not just
Clinton and Democrats who love the old double standard. Republicans
too are happy to believe that others should do what they say, not
what they do. Former House Speaker Newt Gingrich, that philandering
champion of family values, is merely the latest example.
</P>
<P>
   The next we know, Laura Bush will tell TV interviewers it's all
a vast left-wing conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the public doesn't seem to care. In a recent CNN-Time
magazine poll, 84 percent of those surveyed said that cocaine use
should not disqualify Bush from the presidency. This too may be a
legacy from Clinton. We are ashamed to confess how fascinated we
are by political dirty laundry and no longer shocked by misconduct
in high places.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's real problem comes from his GOP presidential rivals.
They sense their first opportunity to jostle him away from the
throne.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Orrin Hatch, a presidential
longshot, set the tone by sternly lecturing Bush on the importance
of honesty just as he used to lecture Clinton. ``Questions that
involve a person's leadership potential, attitude toward
leadership, candidness, forthrightness, honesty, these questions
are legitimate and need to be answered,'' Hatch said. ``The problem
is the way it's been handled ... If there was (anything there), he
should answer it _ get it behind him.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch is on the right track. Voters may forgive all kinds of
wrongdoing by public figures, but what they really resent is being
deliberately deceived. It's patronizing. It's maddening. It's
dishonest.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has created a credibility crisis that can be resolved only
by telling us more about that misspent youth of his. Rumors are
already racing ahead of him, inventing purported new scandals that
point to a pattern of hypocrisy on many public and private issues.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton didn't listen to Hatch, but Bush ought to. Speak up,
Governor.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means may be reached by e-mail at
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
