<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASUAL-COOKING-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COOK FOR COMPANY  _ AND ENJOY YOURSELF, TOO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Has art 
By NATALIE HAUGHTON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ You can cook for company and enjoy the guests and
festivities, too, says cooking teacher Phillis Carey. Her modus
operandi favors relying on fast and fabulous casual recipes, many
with make-ahead attributes that fit into busy schedules _ including
her own _ and yield attractive and colorful results.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like things that have vibrant flavors and are filled with
lots of herbs and spices but are not necessarily hot and spicy,''
said Carey.
</P>
<P>
   Carey recently demonstrated three main dishes and one dessert
for summertime lunch, brunch or dinner entertaining during a recent
class at a local market. Although some of the recipes may seem
overwhelming because they have several parts, once you break them
down and make them, they're not difficult for home cooks to master.
</P>
<P>
   The Roasted Red Pepper Caesar Salad, great for a casual summer
party, involves preparing an easy, creamy Caesar dressing and a
salad and grilling marinated chicken breasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a real stickler about boneless chicken breasts. You should
always pound them (except if you're slitting and filling them) in
between plastic wrap (on the underside, not the shiny side) with a
flat, round, stainless-steel meat pounder (with no teeth) to even
up the thick and thin edges.''
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to end up with an even 1/2-inch-thick breast that
requires three to four minutes of cooking time per side, she
emphasized.
</P>
<P>
   Once marinated in a mixture of oil (which keeps the chicken from
sticking to the grill), lemon juice, garlic and red pepper flakes,
the breasts are grilled or broiled over medium-high heat, then cut
across the grain into thin strips and served atop the salad.
</P>
<P>
   For the class, Carey grilled the chicken on the stove top over
medium heat on a grill that stretched across two burners. It's also
feasible to use a grill pan atop the cook-top.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marinate the chicken breasts no longer than four hours in the
fridge, otherwise the acid in the marinade may cause the chicken to
fall apart,'' she advised.
</P>
<P>
   The salad mixture goes together quickly with roasted red bell
pepper strips, small nonpareil capers (rinsed to remove excess
salt), romaine lettuce, garlic croutons and dressing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you like your croutons soggy, toss them with the salad and
dressing. If you prefer them crunchy, sprinkle them on top of the
salad just before serving.''
</P>
<P>
   The fastest way to roast peppers is to cut open the red or green
bell peppers, remove the seeds and broil, skin side up, on a
foil-lined baking sheet under a preheated broiler eight minutes
until black and bubbly. Remove from the broiler, fold up the sides
of the foil and steam the peppers 10 minutes. The skin should slip
off easily.
</P>
<P>
   The upscale Caesar dressing, which also contains a roasted red
pepper, is a delicious doctored-up mayonnaise-based mixture with
Parmesan cheese, lemon juice, Worcestershire sauce, garlic and
Dijon mustard. Use nonfat mayonnaise, if desired, because the other
ingredients will help disguise it, suggested Carey.
</P>
<P>
   Present the salad mixture topped with warm or cold chicken
strips and sprinkled with coarsely grated fresh Parmesan cheese _
not the already grated type, which does not have the same flavor.
</P>
<P>
   The Caesar dressing by itself also makes a delicious veggie dip
_ and the more you process it, the thinner it gets. Carey noted
that it's also terrific drizzled over fresh cooked vegetables for a
vegetable side dish.
</P>
<P>
   You can skip the chicken and just serve the salad with whatever
else you like _ such as grilled steaks. Another time, if you don't
want to make the entire salad, just whip up the chicken. Add an
herb such as rosemary to the chicken marinade, marinate the
breasts, then grill and serve with a salad and side dishes of your
choice. This recipe, like some of Carey's others, is versatile and
lends itself to different interpretations.
</P>
<P>
   Next Carey turned her attention to a Grilled Salmon Salad With
Corn Relish and Basil Vinaigrette _ a mixture of warm and cold
foods. ``It's really three recipes in one,'' she noted.
</P>
<P>
   You can prepare the Basil Vinaigrette _ which is used to dress
the Corn Relish and salad greens and to marinate the salmon _ by
hand or in a food processor or blender. It's best used within 24
hours of preparation. A combination of both balsamic vinegar (which
is smooth) and red wine vinegar (which has more zing) is used along
with basil, garlic, tarragon, chili paste with garlic and olive
oil. When using basil, chop or mince just prior to using; otherwise
it turns black. Remember that fresh herbs are usually measured
lightly packed, Carey reminded.
</P>
<P>
   The colorful Corn Relish with green and red peppers, black
olives and red onion can be made a day in advance of serving and
kept refrigerated. Use fresh or frozen yellow _ not white _ corn
for best color. If using fresh, the best way to remove the corn
from the cob _ and to avoid having it fly all over the kitchen _ is
to stand an ear in a bowl and cut the corn off with downward
strokes of a knife. Figure each ear of corn will yield half to one
cup corn kernels.
</P>
<P>
   When using red or white onions in a salad, Carey suggests
getting rid of the acid or onion taste by covering with water, a
splash of vinegar (any kind except rice or balsamic) and a pinch of
sugar and letting stand for 10 minutes or longer before draining.
</P>
<P>
   After marinating the serving-sized pieces of skinless salmon
fillets in some of the Basil Vinaigrette (in the fridge) and
grilling them stove-top (about five to seven minutes per side),
serve atop mixed delicate greens with sliced tomatoes and a scoop
(use an ice-cream scoop to mold) of Corn Relish on the side. For
convenience and ease, use prepared, cleaned lettuces purchased in
bags in the produce section. To complete this main-dish selection,
Carey suggests serving with strips of herbed focaccia on the side.
</P>
<P>
   The versatile salad is also good with grilled shrimp or chicken
breasts, added Carey. Try the Corn Relish as an accompaniment with
grilled meats or other fish or as a side dish served in
hollowed-out fresh whole tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Another interesting entree choice is Spicy Pork Tenderloin With
Orange Chipotle BBQ Sauce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pork tenderloins have hardly any fat and are hardly any
work,'' noted Carey, who loves them and often finds them at Costco
and supermarkets. The sauce that bastes the pork tenderloins while
they cook and goes over the top before serving is flavorful with
chipotle chiles in adobo sauce, ketchup, liquid smoke, orange juice
and Worcestershire sauce. Adjust the amount of chipotles (chiles
that have been smoked) depending on how hot you want the sauce.
</P>
<P>
   For extra flavor, coat the pork tenderloins with a rub made with
paprika, chili powder, pepper and garlic before grilling, broiling
or oven roasting (on a tray lined with heavy-duty foil). If you end
up with any rub leftover, keep refrigerated and use within a week
or two.
</P>
<P>
   Carey suggests investing in an instant-read thermometer to test
all meats for doneness. For pork, cook to 160 degrees F; higher
than that, the pork will dry out.
</P>
<P>
   Carey serves the pork tenderloins sliced diagonally across the
grain, accompanied by Blue Cheese Potato Salad. One of her favorite
potato salad renditions, it can be prepared with either russet or
red potatoes. Substitute feta cheese or garlic and herb cheese
(Boursin) for the blue, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   For dessert, offer a square of warm or cold Chocolate Fudge Cake
slathered with a large dollop of White Chocolate Orange Cream.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never cut back on dessert,'' noted Carey, who offers no
ingredient substitutes for butter, sour cream, heavy cream, etc.
``Either eat it or don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Use heavy whipping cream, not regular whipping cream, she
advised, as it whips up fast and once whipped, holds up longer.
Fold in grated orange peel, orange liqueur and cut-up white
chocolate pieces, then refrigerate until serving time.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to entertaining, Carey suggests planning ahead and
cooking as much of the food as possible a day or several hours in
advance. Freeze things like filo appetizers, lasagna, shortbread
crackers and cheesecakes if you feel so inclined.
</P>
<P>
   As for garnishing, gussy up plates with food items that are
already used in the dish. For instance, if rosemary or basil is
used in a recipe, garnish the plate with either of those herbs.
``Don't put chiles on something that doesn't have chiles in it, as
it sends the wrong message to diners.''
</P>
<P>
   Next time you are looking for casual and easy company fare, pull
out these recipes shared by Carey in her class and from her
cookbook, ``The Casual Gourmet.'' You and your guests are in for
some wonderful dining. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GRILLED SALMON SALAD WITH CORN RELISH AND BASIL VINAIGRETTE
</P>
<P>
   BASIL VINAIGRETTE:
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped fresh basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced fresh tarragon
</P>
<P>
   2 to 4 teaspoons chili paste with garlic
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   SALMON SALAD:
</P>
<P>
   4 (6- to 7-ounce) salmon fillets
</P>
<P>
   Basil Vinaigrette
</P>
<P>
   8 to 10 cups mixed salad greens
</P>
<P>
   2 large tomatoes, sliced
</P>
<P>
   CORN RELISH:
</P>
<P>
   3 cups raw corn kernels, cut from about 4 ears corn OR use
frozen
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup diced green bell peppers
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup diced red bell peppers
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup diced OR sliced black olives
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup diced red onion
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup Basil Vinaigrette
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   For Basil Vinaigrette, combine vinegars, basil, garlic, tarragon
and chili paste in a food processor or blender until blended. With
machine running, slowly add olive oil. Chill until ready to use, or
up to overnight.
</P>
<P>
   For Salmon Salad, rinse salmon and pat dry. Place in a 9x13-inch
baking dish. Pour 3/4 cup Basil Vinaigrette over fillets. Chill
about 1 hour, turning every 15 minutes or up until next day.
</P>
<P>
   For Corn Relish, combine all relish ingredients in a bowl. Cover
and chill until ready to serve, or up to 4 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Grill or broil salmon fillets until moist looking but opaque in
thickest part, 8 to 10 minutes, turning fillets after 4 minutes.
Remove from grill; cover loosely with foil to keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Mix salad greens with remaining vinaigrette and evenly divide
among 4 dinner plates. Spoon Corn Relish and tomato slices on top
of greens. Lay warm fillets over greens. Makes 4 servings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ROASTED RED PEPPER CAESAR SALAD
</P>
<P>
   DRESSING:
</P>
<P>
   3 garlic cloves
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   1 large red bell pepper, roasted and peeled
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons freshly grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   SALAD:
</P>
<P>
   2 large red bell peppers, roasted and peeled
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons rinsed capers
</P>
<P>
   1 large head romaine lettuce, in bite-size pieces
</P>
<P>
   2 cups garlic croutons
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup coarsely grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Grilled Garlicky Lemon Chicken
</P>
<P>
   For Dressing, drop garlic into running food processor and
process until minced. Add mayonnaise, roasted red pepper, 2
tablespoons Parmesan cheese, lemon juice, Worcestershire sauce and
mustard; process to blend. Transfer to a medium bowl. Season with
salt and pepper. Refrigerate up to 3 days.
</P>
<P>
   For Salad, just before serving, cut red pepper into thin strips
and toss with capers, lettuce and croutons. Add enough dressing and
toss to coat. Serve sprinkled with Parmesan cheese and topped with
warm or cold strips of Grilled Garlicky Lemon Chicken. Makes 4
servings.
</P>
<P>
   GRILLED GARLICKY LEMON CHICKEN: Pound 4 chicken breasts to a
1/4- to 1/2-inch thickness. Marinate chicken in a flat baking dish,
20 minutes at room temperature or up to 4 hours in refrigerator, in
a mixture of 1/4 cup olive oil, 1 tablespoon fresh lemon juice, 4
cloves minced garlic, 1/2 teaspoon red pepper flakes and salt and
pepper to taste. On preheated grill or broiler, cook chicken 3 to 5
minutes per side or until cooked through. Cut across grain into
thin strips. Makes 4 chicken breast halves. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SPICY RUBBED PORK TENDERLOIN WITH CHIPOTLE BBQ SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   SAUCE:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 chipotle chiles in adobo sauce, minced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 small onion, diced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup ketchup
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons honey
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon liquid smoke seasoning
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup fresh orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon white wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   RUB:
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup paprika
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chili powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped garlic OR garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   PORK:
</P>
<P>
   4 pork tenderloins, about 2 1/2 to 3 pounds total
</P>
<P>
   For Sauce, heat oil in a large skillet over medium heat. Add
chipotle and onion and saute until onion is translucent, about 5
minutes. Reduce heat and add ketchup, honey, liquid smoke, orange
juice, vinegar and Worcestershire sauce. Simmer 10 minutes. Remove
1/2 cup of sauce and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   For Rub, combine all rub ingredients in a pie plate or plastic
food bag; mix well.
</P>
<P>
   Coat each piece of pork with spice rub. Place pork on preheated
grill or under broiler and cook about 3 minutes; turn and cook
another 3 minutes to sear. Continue cooking 15 to 20 minutes,
brushing with sauce and turning every few minutes. Cook until meat
reaches an internal temperature of 155 to 160 degrees F. (Pork may
also be roasted in preheated 400-degree oven 25 minutes.)
</P>
<P>
   Remove pork from grill and brush or drizzle with reserved sauce.
Slice meat on an angle and serve. Makes 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: If desired, double sauce for extra to serve with cooked
pork. Serve pork slices with Blue Cheese Potato Salad. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BLUE CHEESE POTATO SALAD
</P>
<P>
   5 pounds russet potatoes, peeled OR red potatoes, unpeeled
</P>
<P>
   Water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups dairy sour cream
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 tablespoons Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 tablespoons cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound blue cheese, crumbled
</P>
<P>
   5 green onions, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups chopped celery
</P>
<P>
   Cut potatoes into quarters and cover with cold water. Bring to a
boil, then simmer until potatoes are tender. Drain, cool and cut
into 1-inch cubes.
</P>
<P>
   Toss with wine, salt and pepper. Cool completely. Potatoes may
be prepared 1 day ahead to this point.
</P>
<P>
   Combine all remaining ingredients and mix with potatoes. Adjust
seasonings. Cover and refrigerate. Can keep 1 day. Makes 12
servings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHOCOLATE FUDGE CAKE WITH WHITE CHOCOLATE ORANGE CREAM FROSTING
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup unsweetened cocoa powder
</P>
<P>
   1 cup plus 2 tablespoons boiling water
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup unsalted butter, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   2 1/4 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons vanilla
</P>
<P>
   2 1/4 cups all purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons baking soda
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups dairy sour cream
</P>
<P>
   White Chocolate Orange Cream (recipe follows)
</P>
<P>
   Grease a 9x13-inch baking pan. Place cocoa in a metal bowl.
Gradually add boiling water, stirring constantly. Cool.
</P>
<P>
   Using an electric mixer, cream butter with sugar in a large
bowl. Add eggs, one at at time, beating well after each addition.
Beat in vanilla. Mix flour, baking soda and salt in a bowl. Stir
into butter mixture alternately with sour cream. Stir in cocoa
mixture. Pour batter into prepared pan.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 350-degree oven about 50 minutes, until a
toothpick inserted into center of cake comes out clean. Cool cake
slightly on a rack.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, cut warm cake into squares. Top squares with White
Chocolate Orange Cream. Makes 12 servings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WHITE CHOCOLATE ORANGE CREAM
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chilled heavy whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon grated orange peel
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Grand Marnier
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces imported white chocolate, cut up into 1/4-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   Combine cream, sugar and orange peel in a medium bowl and beat
until stiff peaks form. Mix in Grand Marnier and fold in white
chocolate. Cover and refrigerate up to 4 hours. Makes 2 cups. &QL; 
?kPhoto: (1--4--Color) Grilled Salmon Salad With Corn Relish and
Basil Vinaigrette, left, is really three recipes in one and fills
the bill for casual summer entertaining. Make and serve together or
whip up the Corn Relish any time to serve with grilled chicken,
beef or fish. The Basil Vinaigrette makes a terrific dressing over
fresh sliced tomatoes, vegetable salads or any tossed greens.
Cooking instructor Phillis Carey, left, teaches a class in
preparing her Fast and Fabulous Summer Main Dishes, including
Roasted Red Pepper Caesar Salad, middle. For something a little
different for guests, choose Spicy Rubbed Pork Tenderloin, above,
and accompany with Blue Cheese Potato Salad.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
</TEXT>
