<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV29-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Aug. 29) 
(jt) 
 By PAUL FREIREICH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Prague, Vienna, Budapest
</P>
<P>
   Q. My husband and I will be in Prague in the fall and would like
to take a river cruise to Vienna and/or Budapest. Through what
companies can we make reservations? _ Elaine D. Trehub, Amherst,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Any traveling between Prague and Vienna won't be on a major
river. The Vltava, which passes through Prague, doesn't go that
way; it links up with the Elbe, which continues into Germany.
</P>
<P>
   To get to Vienna from Prague, you can fly or take a train.
Providing a more intimate view is the Prague-Vienna Greenways, a
250-mile network of six trails each of which covers part of the way
between the two cities. En route, there are historic villages and
monuments, walled towns, castles and quiet countryside.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the trail, you can get around on foot and horseback
or by bike and canoe. In many instances, you can also drive on
roads that essentially parallel the trails. Transporting luggage
and arranging accommodations and the like are handled by Palava
Tours. Its U.S. representative is Summit International Travel, 789
Springfield Ave., Summit, N.J. 07901; (800) 527-8664, fax (908)
522-0657; www.summittours.com.
</P>
<P>
   Peter V. Dytrych, co-owner of Summit, said that under the
flexible tour option, breakfast was included and that the charges,
per person per day, were $80 a day for hiking, $90 for cycling,
$100 for car or canoe and $120 for horseback riding. For a minibus,
which carries 16 to 18 passengers, the charge is $1,049 a person,
based on double occupancy, for 11 days. That includes a night in
Vienna and two nights in Prague. The bicycle tour is 10 days and
costs $859 a person; like the minibus tour, it includes breakfast
and dinner daily. None of the rates include air fare. Tours usually
go from Vienna to Prague, but travel in the opposite direction can
be arranged.
</P>
<P>
   By train, the trip takes about five hours, as does the most
direct route by car: heading southeast from Prague to Brno on the
E50 and then taking the E461 south to Vienna.
</P>
<P>
   The train schedule starting late next month calls for a
departure from the Hlavni Station in Prague at 9:40 a.m. and
departures from the Holesevice Station at 1:43 and 5:43 p.m. All
three trains run daily and arrive at the Sudbahnhof in Vienna.
</P>
<P>
   The one-way fare is $65 first class, $45 second class.
Reservations are recommended and cost $11 a seat if made with Rail
Europe at (800) 438-7245 or at www.raileurope.com. They can also be
made by a travel agent.
</P>
<P>
   Although you cannot cruise from Prague to Vienna, you can take a
cruise from Budapest to Vienna, on the Danube. Hydrofoils link
Vienna and Budapest, as do more expensive cruise vessels. The
journey by hydrofoil takes about five and a half hours; through
Nov. 1, vessels leave from Vienna and Budapest at 9 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Danube Cruises Austria/European Cruises in Fort Lauderdale, Fla.
(800) 327-8223 or (954) 491-0333, charges $95 one way, $155 round
trip. Tickets bought abroad cost less _ about $62.40 one way, $88
round trip at current rates of exchange _ but availability could be
a problem.
</P>
<P>
   For information about the Czech Republic: the Czech Tourist
Authority, 1109 Madison Ave. (83d Street), New York, N.Y. 10028;
(212) 288-0830, fax (212) 288-0971; www.czechcenter.com. Closed
Monday. Information about the Greenways:
www.pragueviennagreenways.org.
</P>
<P>
   A package combining Prague, Vienna and Budapest can be arranged
by Summit International and by such tour operators as European
Connection, (800) 345-4679 or (516) 625-1805; Isram World of
Travel, (800) 223-7460, and Rivers of Eu-rope/N&AMP;S Connections,
(800) 999-0226.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Bennett for 2000
</P>
<P>
   Q. My wife is an unabashed fan of Tony Bennett's and wants to
greet the millennium at his show on Dec. 31. Can you tell us where
he'll be performing that night? _ Marvin E. Mazie, Des Moines
</P>
<P>
   A. He will be at the Desert Inn in Las Vegas on New Year's Eve,
but the odds of your getting in to that show are not on your side
since his performance is a ``private casino party.'' That means it
is open only to those who frequent the Desert Inn casino regularly
and play often enough and bet enough to be awarded a bonus.
</P>
<P>
   It may not be quite the same, but you can hear Bennett on Jan. 1
and 2 for $125 a night. No free champagne on those nights. On the
31st, Don Rickles will also be performing at the Desert Inn.
Admission, including a bottle of champagne and party favors, is
$150; on Dec. 29 and 30, it's $75. A 10 percent tax applies to all
tickets. Reservations: (800) 634-6909. If you're thinking of
staying at the Desert Inn over New Year's, the rate is $2,000 a
night plus 9 percent tax, with a three-night minimum. That's
$6,540, based on double occupancy. (No credit cards accepted for
this period.)
</P>
<P>
   What else is going on in Las Vegas for the millennium? See
www.vegas.com or www.lasvegas24hours.com.
</P>
<P>
   Gatwick and Pooh
</P>
<P>
   Q. My family and I will be arriving at Gatwick Airport outside
London at 7 a.m. in the fall on the way to Bath. One of our group
will arrive four hours later. Any suggestions to pass the time? We
will be renting a car. _ Betsy Kirkgard, Houston.
</P>
<P>
   A. Not only is time a constraint but so is time of day: not many
places are open at 9 a.m. or before.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a fan of Winnie-the-Pooh, you're in luck. Ashdown
Forest, a 6,480-acre preserve celebrated in the writings of A.A.
Milne, is about a half hour's drive and offers walks through
heathland and woodland.
</P>
<P>
   To get there from the airport, take the M23 south. At the first
exit, take the A264 to East Grinstead and then the A22 south.
Beyond the village of Forest Row, take a left turn at the traffic
light at Wych Cross. The Ashdown Forest Center office, where you
can pick up a map, is a mile away. The office opens at 9 on
weekdays. On weekends, maps are available at the exhibition barn,
which is open 11 to 5. Telephone: (44-1342) 823583;
www.eastsussexcc.gov.uk/ashdown/icentre.htm. The forest is open all
the time; admission is free. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two miles from the office you can see the Enchanted Place,
Gill's Lap, the Sandy Pit where Roo played, Lone Pine and the
Hefalump Trap. About a mile plus 15-minute walk away is Poohsticks
Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   If you just want to relax on arrival at Gatwick, the 211-room
Europa Gatwick has day rooms as early as 9 a.m. and possibly
earlier. The hotel is in Crawley, six miles from the airport, off
the M23 at Junction 10A; it has an indoor pool and health club. The
room rate is $80 a day. Telephone (44-1293) 886 666, fax (44-1293)
886 680.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
