</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-PANAMA-CANAL-ZONE-$ADV29-745&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANAMA CONVERTING CANAL ZONE FOR TOURISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 29)  
(lb) 
 By MIREYA NAVARRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA CITY, Panama _ On Dec. 31, the United States is scheduled
to complete the transfer of the Panama Canal to Panama. The 50-mile
passageway _ a wondrous feat of U.S. engineering _ transports more
than 13,000 ships, including cruise vessels, and 190 million tons
of cargo a year between the Pacific and the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   But the transfer, which is being carried out in steps according
to treaties signed in 1977 by President Carter and Brig. Gen. Omar
Torrijos Herrera of Panama, who died in a plane crash in 1981, also
includes about $4 billion worth of property in what was known as
the American Canal Zone.
</P>
<P>
   If Panama's ambitious plans are realized, 232,278 acres occupied
by U.S. military installations to defend the canal will be
transformed into an international hub of commerce closer to a
mini-Singapore, with the potential of increasing tourism and
exports and adding millions to the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to take advantage of the infrastructure we already
have and use interesting concepts, looking for new markets,'' said
Ricardo Icaza, marketing manager of the Interoceanic Region
Authority, created in 1993 to manage the property relinquished
under the canal treaties.
</P>
<P>
   Buildings on the military bases _ barracks, hospitals, schools,
houses and offices _ are already being turned into private housing,
hotels, industrial parks, ports, universities and sports
facilities. A new 310-room hotel, the Sol Melia, is scheduled to
open in December in what used to be the School of the Americas,
where Latin American military officers trained.
</P>
<P>
   The former military base of Amador is being turned into a
tourism complex, set to open in 2001, that is meant to attract the
passengers of more than 300 cruise ships that transit the canal
annually but do not stop. The complex will offer hotels with views
of Panama City and passing ships, casinos, golf courses, shopping
centers and marinas.
</P>
<P>
   Near the small town of Gamboa, at the canal's midpoint, a $25
million ecotourism project over 91 acres, the Gamboa Tropical
Rainforest Resort, is expected to open next year. The development
on the banks of the Chagres River, about 45 minutes from Panama
City by car, will include a 100-room hotel and marina in a natural
setting that offers rain-forest trails, bird watching and fishing.
</P>
<P>
   As the Canal Zone, which occupied close to 10 percent of the
national territory after the waterway was completed in 1914, has
gradually reverted to Panama under steps mandated by the treaties,
some tourism projects have already been completed.
</P>
<P>
   Within the Soberania National Park not far from Gamboa, the
privately run Canopy Tower hotel opened in January in a former
military radar tower. In an ingenious conversion, the circular,
galvanized-steel tower building topped by a 30-foot-high yellow
dome is now a five-story, six-room ``eco-lodge'' with a 360-degree
view of treetops. There are plans to add four guest rooms nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``The potential is enormous for the adaptive reuse of
facilities,'' said Pierre Cowart, a visitor from Chicago on his
honeymoon, who with his wife was spotting birds through a telescope
from the tower's observatory. A construction manager by profession,
he commented, ``It's an architectural challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Panama and countries like Spain and Taiwan have already
invested $1 billion, mostly in tourism and maritime projects due to
be finished over the next five years, Panamanian officials say.
More than 100 such projects are under way.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is also great uncertainty. Many Panamanians I
talked to noted that some of the properties that have reverted to
Panama since 1995 are already deteriorating. Most of the nine
military bases that make up the most valuable property are being
transferred this year. The property's fate hinges on the ability of
Panama to attract more investors, Panamanian officials say.
</P>
<P>
   It is a tall order for Panama, which has greeted the Americans'
departure with a mixture of national pride and anxiety. Besides
disposing of the valuable real estate the United States is leaving,
Panama must replace the jobs and income earned from the U.S. bases
_ up to $350 million a year at one time _ and operate the canal,
which brings in about $545 million a year in tolls.
</P>
<P>
   The government must also oversee an expansion of the canal
already under way and prevent deforestation of the watershed, under
the scrutiny of both Panamanians and much of the world.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Historically, most of the canal's revenue has been invested in
maintenance and modernization, but there are worries among
Panamanians and Americans that governments here could be tempted to
divert canal money for their own use or politicize its operation,
lowering the canal's standards and safety.
</P>
<P>
   But the newly elected president, Mireya Moscoso, who will take
office on Wednesday, has promised to keep the canal free of
corruption and nepotism and use it to reduce high unemployment and
poverty among the population of 2.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of Panama is monitoring very closely what will happen to
the canal,'' a U.S. official here said. ``They all feel it's an
asset that belongs to the whole country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
