<HEADER>
A6886 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$A     08-23 1569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$ADV29-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRAUD SEEKS OUT OLD AND YOUNG 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Aug. 29) 
(jt) 
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sale of travel climbed into the top 10 categories of complaints
made to the Federal Trade Commission in the last year. Sales on the
Internet and over the telephone helped to push travel operators
into the No. 6 spot, in the unlovely company of organizations that
promise to fix bad credit ratings, say you have won the
sweepstakes, sell telephone access cards that provide no access,
and operate Internet auctions without sending merchandise, among
other classic frauds.
</P>
<P>
   These confidence artists do not prey equally. The old and the
young are their preferred targets, the government discovered.
Around spring break time this year, the Federal agency reports, it
began to hear a crescendo of complaints about tour packages sold to
students. And senior citizens were found to be frequent victims of
companies that did not deliver the trips they promised, to say the
least.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This month the agency announced a wide attack on these deceptive
practices. It, in cooperation with the Department of
Transportation, state attorneys general and other agencies in 19
states, accused 25 travel companies of varied offenses, seeking
injunctions and penalties to provide restitution to defrauded
customers.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Forty-odd legal actions have been lodged against companies that
operate under many names. One example is Cerkvenik-Anderson Travel
of Phoenix, which sells under the names Student Tours, College
Tours, Mexico Tours and Andy Anderson.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The FTC is seeking a permanent injunction against this company
in federal court in Arizona. Thayer Lindauer of Westlake Village,
Calif., who is defending the company in court, said: ``The claims
are excessively overblown and not typical and I expect the company
to win.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Such companies' habit of going out of business under one name
and starting up under another is an additional reason the
government is moving now. Back in March 1997, according to Jodie Z.
Bernstein, director of consumer protection for the FTC, the agency
took action against a number of travel companies, and after two
years some operators might have decided that the coast was clear
for re-entering the field. ``We don't want them back,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The form in which most adults encounter fraudulent travel offers
is a pseudo-embossed certificate starting with the recipient's name
and saying: ``Pack your bags! You have been chosen for a World
Class Florida Caribbean package including all accommodations and a
round-trip cruise.'' A prompt telephone reply is demanded, and this
usually evokes a high-pressure sales talk for what may be a day
trip on a ferry, an enforced tour of a time-share property or a
stay at a substandard motel far from the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Some version of this fraud is what is usually attempted against
senior citizens, and the government said that frequently older
people find themselves hearing long sales pitches when they claim
their ``prize vacation.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Students are approached by fellow students, some of whom may be
getting trips free for selling a certain amount. This creates a
more difficult situation because the student agents may not know
they are window dressing for bad merchandise, and a group mentality
may take over.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Sara Walker, a high school senior in Eugene, Ore., came
home from school with a flier for a Cerkvenik-Anderson ``graduation
blowout'' in Mazatlan, Mexico. Her mother, Vicki L. Walker, said
her son had gone on a similar trip ``and everything was on the up
and up.'' But this one, she said, ``turned out to be a nightmare
that my daughter still has trouble talking about.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The plane, flown by a charter operator, sat at the Portland
airport for an hour and arrived in Mexico quite late. No food and
no water were aboard. Ms. Walker, who has since taken her seat as
an Oregon state representative, said she got a hysterical telephone
call from her daughter at the hotel at 11:30 p.m. that night, June
11, saying that the flight had involved wet T-shirt contests among
five female students incited by the flight attendants and judged by
the flight crew. On the bus to the hotel, Ms. Walker continued, her
daughter said beer at $1 each was offered to all 153 students, some
of whom were only 17 and none of whom had eaten since Portland. The
hotel quarters were not as advertised, and although she had paid
for a double room, she was told that she would have to pay $120
additional for a double. The tour operator's staff, which was
supposed to be in charge, was drinking with the kids, she said.
``There was constant sexual innuendo,'' Ms. Walker said, and the
activities all focused on alcohol and sex.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many things paid for in advance had to be paid for again,
including a bracelet to provide identification and entry into
various clubs. Sara Walker told her mother that unpleasant threats
were made to students who refused to buy the new bracelets.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the flight returned seven days later, Ms. Walker, a court
reporter, interviewed 40 of the students and got the transcripts
notarized. Since almost all the students were from Oregon, this
material provided grist when the Oregon legislature approved a law
regulating sellers of travel and requiring that school districts
develop policies that could prevent trips like the graduation
blowout. Ms. Walker said that the American Society of Travel Agents
had helped with the bill's language.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a market that has seen little scrutiny,'' Ms. Walker
said. ``Kids take a bad trip and then come back and they want to
move on. My goal is to be sure everyone knows what can happen.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She said she was discouraged to hear from some parents who were
letting their children go on such trips this year ``because all of
their friends were going.'' She said that parents had to take a
stand with their children that nothing should be allowed to
threaten the safety and health of family members.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ronna Brown, president of the Better Business Bureau of
Metropolitan New York, and Ms. Bernstein of the FTC both emphasize
the importance of doing research about travel offers, particularly
if the seller approaches the customer, rather than the other way
around. ``Do business with somebody you know,'' Ms. Brown says.
``If not that, somebody a friend knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales information on the Internet, like that given by telephone
sales-people describing free or discounted trips, does not tell the
consumer what company is offering the trip. Just because a company
is on the Internet, Ms. Bernstein said, does not make a proposition
real or assure the honesty of the operator. For confidence artists,
the Internet provides still another cover for identity, whereabouts
and past history.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The experts say that once you find out what company is actually
chartering the plane, making the hotel reservations and providing
the transfers, there are ways to check up on it _ although, as
several notable cases prove, the ownership can change quickly.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Better Business Bureau in New York compiles complaints about
companies in the city, Long Island and most of the 914 area code.
It seeks responses from them. If a company fails to respond to
multiple complaints, the bureau gives it an unsatisfactory rating.
The potential customer needs to know the company's name and
address. There are two ways to call for information: (212)
533-6200, which will involve a charge of $3.80 on the caller's
credit card in addition to any long-distance tolls, or (900)
555-4222, which costs 95 cents a minute. The Web site is
www.newyork.bbb.org. Written inquiries, with a stamped
self-addressed envelope, should be directed to 257 Park Avenue So.,
New York, N.Y. 10010. If a company is not in its area, the bureau
can provide a reference to a bureau in the right area.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission wrote two new leaflets as part of
its drive against travel fraud. They are available free on request
to the address below, or through the Internet. ``Avoid a School
Break Bust'' gives the number at the Department of Transportation,
(202) 366-2396, to call to verify that an air-charter operator has
filed for permission to operate the flight. ``Telemarketing Travel
Fraud'' describes all the ways the truth can be shaded and depicts
the pressure tactics often used.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If it is too late for leaflets, complaints can be filed with the
agency at (877) 382-4357. The number for TDD is (202) 326-2502. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The agency cannot help individual consumers resolve their
problems, but their complaints may help an investigation, or create
a probable reason for the agency to act. Written complaints should
go to the Consumer Response Center, Federal Trade Commission, 600
Pennsylvania Ave., N.W., Washington, D.C. 20580.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All the experts counsel people in situations they consider
ticklish to pay with credit cards. In New York, it is illegal to
charge extra for the use of a credit card, but Ms. Brown concedes
that nothing can be done about companies that provide discounts for
those paying cash. ``It is worthwhile to pay the extra to provide
yourself with the added margin of safety,'' Ms. Brown said.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This advice certainly applies to parents whose children are wild
to take a trip a friend is selling: legitimate operators will
accept at least one type of credit card.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-99 1854EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
