<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6889 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV29-     08-23 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV29-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Aug. 29) 
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   2 Airlines Offer Deals on New York Fares
</P>
<P>
   Air fares within New York state have caused politicians and
business leaders to complain that it can cost more to fly halfway
across the state than all the way across the Atlantic. But now
prices have come down in two more markets.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shuttle America, a regional airline based in Windsor Locks,
Conn., began flying from MacArthur Airport in Islip, N.Y., about 45
minutes from Manhattan, to Albany and Buffalo on July 13 at steeply
discounted fares. Round-trip fares between Islip and Albany or
Buffalo are $98 if purchased at least 21 days in advance. With a
14-day advance purchase, fares are $158 to Albany and $178 to
Buffalo. Walk-up fares are $198 to Albany and $298 to Buffalo. No
Saturday-night stay is required, so even the lowest fares allow a
round trip on the same day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Until recently only US Airways offered service between Islip and
Albany.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Flights from Islip to Buffalo are also available via Albany,
Boston or Philadelphia on US Airways, via Cleveland on Continental
and via Cincinnati on Delta. But US Airways, Delta and Continental
charge walk-up coach fares of $495 to $1,538, far above the
comparable Shuttle America fare. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before Shuttle America began flying between Islip and Buffalo,
the lowest round-trip fare was $318, but the US Airways schedule
shows that after Shuttle America began service, its cheapest fell
to $118.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shuttle America has three daily nonstop flights between Islip
and Albany (the same as US Airways), each with connecting Buffalo
service. It flies 50-passenger Dash-8 turboprops.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Next year a new low-fare airline backed by the financier George
Soros is to begin flying eight Airbus A-320 jets (seating 150 to
180 passengers) from Kennedy Airport to several cities, one of
which will be either Buffalo, Rochester or Syracuse. David
Neeleman, the company's chief executive, said recently that the
airline will operate as Jetblue Airways. Each passenger will have a
personal television screen showing programs broadcast by satellite,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Edinburgh Puts Planet in Dramatic Light
</P>
<P>
   Earthquakes, erupting volcanos and torrential rains are a few of
the simulated catastrophes awaiting visitors to Dynamic Earth, a
new attraction in Edinburgh's Old Town. Housed in the William
Younger Center, a new building with a translucent roof, Dynamic
Earth tells the planet's story through interactive exhibits, videos
and state-of-the-art special effects.
</P>
<P>
   After boarding a ``time machine'' elevator, visitors may explore
11 environmental zones, ranging from a tropical rain forest with
computer-controlled daylight cycles to a Restless Earth zone,
replete with sulfurous emissions and a vibrating floor that lights
up. An indoor iceberg can be found in the chilly Polar Zone, and
the Showdome offers a planetariumlike display of earthquakes,
lightning storms and tidal waves. Human evolution, extinction of
the dinosaurs and the sustainability of the planet are among the
themes explored elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Dynamic Earth, at 112 Holyrood Road in Holyrood Park, is open
Wednesday to Sunday. Admission is $9.50; $5.60 for children.
Information: (44-131) 550 7800.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak Is Rolling Out Satisfaction Express
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak plans to put a customer-satisfaction guarantee into
effect by the end of the year. Passengers dissatisfied with the
service, food or other aspects of their trip will be able to get a
voucher with a value equal to the trip's cost.
</P>
<P>
   The guarantee will take effect after the company completes a
training program for its 24,000 employees, establishes standards
for its service and creates employee incentives. It is similar to
programs at many hotel chains, and its announcement last month came
at the peak of a dispute in Congress over airline passengers'
rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to guarantee passenger rights while others in the
transportation industry are fighting them in Congress,'' said
George Warrington, Amtrak's president. The Air Transport
Association, representing major U.S. lines, has agreed on a
``customer service commitment'' to improve airline performance.
Amtrak said its new hiring would focus on people with traits that
met customer-service needs.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the program will involve checking each train before
departure for adequate food supplies and properly functioning
plumbing, among other things. Trains that don't pass muster won't
be permitted to leave, said John Wolf, an Amtrak spokesman. The
first phase has begun on four trains: the California Zephyr; the
Crescent, between New York and New Orleans; the San Diegans, and
the Washington-New York corridor service.
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver Exhibit Shows Rich Tribal Past
</P>
<P>
   Since ancient times, the Nuu-chah-nulth people of the west coast
of Vancouver Island, British Columbia, have preserved their
cultural heritage, which celebrates their reverence for the sea,
land and wildlife. In ``Out of the Mist: HuupuKwanum/Tupaat,
Treasures of the Nuu-chah-nulth Chiefs,'' a new exhibition at the
Royal British Columbia Museum in Victoria, that heritage is
explored.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Nuu-chah-nulth tribal council of chiefs, elders and
contemporary artists worked closely with museum officials on the
exhibition. Among the 241 artifacts and 75 images on display are
18th-century ceremonial bowls, a serpent headdress and a cedar
mask. One of the key pieces is the Frank Family curtain, a
24-foot-long ceremonial cotton curtain, circa 1900, that was a part
of the Andy Warhol Collection and is now owned by the museum. The
curtain is normally kept in storage, and the exhibit offers a rare
opportunity to view the spectacular hand-crafted piece.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The museum expects the exhibition to travel to at least 10 other
museums in North America after it closes in Victoria on April 30.
The Royal British Columbia Museum, 675 Belleville St. in Victoria,
(250) 387-3701, is open daily. Admission is $6.40; ages 6 to 18,
$2.60, at $1.50 Canadian to the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
