<HEADLINE>
THE PLEASURES OF GOP COOKING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thanks to  &UR; Patti &LR;  and  &UR; Glenn Itano &LR; , we are in possession of the
National Federation of Republican Women's 1970 Republican Woman's
Dessert cookbook, which leads off with  &UR; Pat Nixon &LR; 's Blueberry
Dessert,  &UR; Mamie Eisenhower &LR; 's Frosted Mint Delight and Federation
President  &UR; Gladys O'Donnell &LR; 's Mocha Delight. (The number of
Delights and Surprises among the recipes indicates just how much
fun those Republican wW &LR; omen were having.)
</P>
<P>
   Among the other highlights is the Raspberry Surprise of
 &UR; George P. &LR;   &UR; Shultz &LR; , who was secretary of labor at the time and not
exactly a Republican woman. His equally imprecise recipe called for
``frozen raspberries, partially thawed'' and ``ricotta cheese.''
The directions: ``Ladle several spoonfuls of raspberries over one
scoop of cheese. Yield: One serving.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SIGNIFICANT OTHERS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ British-born  &UR; Neil Travis &LR;  of the New York Post reports that
pals in England are whispering that  &UR; Prince Harry &LR; , 14, is growing
up to look a lot more like  &UR; James Hewitt &LR; , his mother's lover, than
 &UR; Prince Charles &LR; , his mother's husband. This would mean that the
affair between Di and her riding instructor began long before they
admitted it had.
</P>
<P>
   _ Another musician, another countermelody: Conductor  &UR; Zubin &LR; 
 &UR; Mehta &LR;  told the Telegraph of London that he has an illegitimate
8-year-old son in Israel. ``I am getting to be close,'' he said.
``I couldn't communicate with him because I don't speak Hebrew, but
he's starting to speak English.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ O.J. Simpson &LR;  was asked to leave the Pacific Palisades home
he was renting and is living with his children at a hotel in
Brentwood, reports the New York Daily News. Simpson's former
landlord said that neighbors were not pleased with Simpson's
presence, and furthermore, his dog tore up the backyard.
</P>
<P>
   _ Unauthorized by its namesake, the Motel Lewinsky is open for
business in Cardel, Mexico, reports the New York Daily News.
Furthermore,  &UR; Peter Sussman &LR;  cites Sunday's paper describing the
meeting of  &UR; Bill Clinton &LR;  and  &UR; Hillary Rodham &LR;  in 1971. What he
first noticed, Clinton recalled, was ``this woman has initiative'';
his second finding: She was ``nothing but trouble.'' Both
characteristics, says Sussman, would qualify
 &UR; Monica Lewinsky &LR;  to run for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Sharon Stone &LR;  and  &UR; Michael Douglas &LR;  are celebrity investors
in Maui Tacos, a fast-food restaurant with a surfing theme. The
restaurant will open in Manhattan in a few months.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ever since her husband was caught cheating on her,  &UR; Kathie &LR; 
 &UR; Lee Gifford &LR;  has been ``dressing increasingly provocatively,''
reports MSNBC, and viewers are starting to complain about her
bralessness, for example. ``I just don't want to look at that while
I'm drinking my morning coffee,'' said one.
</P>
<P>
   _ Interviewed by Radio Times on the occasion of the opening of
``Mickey Blue Eyes,''  &UR; James Caan &LR;  was asked about the acting
abilities of his co-star,  &UR; Hugh Grant &LR; . ``It's not fair to ask me
if he's a good actor,'' said Caan. ``He's very good at what he
does. I haven't seen him do much else.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GLAAD COMPLAINS ABOUT SITCOM GAYS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Out of 540 lead or supporting characters on this fall's TV
shows, ``only 2 percent of the characters on TV shows are gay, and
those are white men who are gay in name only,'' says the Gay &AMP;
Lesbian Alliance Against Defamation.
</P>
<P>
   GLAAD entertainment director  &UR; Scott Seomin &LR;  notes that lesbians
have only tiny roles, and ``gay people of color are almost
nonexistent.'' What's more, the group charges that most gays,
identified with a punch line usually, are one-dimensional.
``Wearing a gay name tag should not be confused with identity.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not an oddball or weirdo. I'm a collector of the
McDonald's dining experience.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Peter Holden, a Maryland high-tech executive who has eaten at
10,893 McDonald's restaurants in North America, quoted in the Wall
Street Journal.
</P>
</TEXT>
