<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6897 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-PAN-AM-103-FAMILIES-H     08-23 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAN-AM-103-FAMILIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTIMS OF PAN AM FLIGHT 103 BRIEFED ON UPCOMING TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Relatives of those killed in the bombing of Pan Am
Flight 103 over Scotland said Monday Attorney General Janet Reno
assured them that prosecutors would pursue any foreign official,
including Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi, implicated by the evidence
in the 11-year-old case.
</P>
<P>
   Two Libyan men are accused of the Dec. 21, 1988, bombing that
killed all 259 people on board the plane, including 189 Americans.
Eleven people in the southern Scottish town of Lockerbie were
killed by falling debris.
</P>
<P>
   ``After speaking with Ms. Reno, I have no doubt in my mind that
prosecutors will not shy away from going after the people
responsible for this attack,'' said Stan Maslowski of Haddonfield,
N.J., whose 30-year-old daughter Diane died in the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Dater, of Pittstown, N.Y., who lost her 20-year-old
daughter Gretchen in the attack, also said Reno and the case's
prosecutors were committed to following the evidence ``wherever it
may lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno declined to comment on the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   In closed-door meetings at a Washington hotel, the families were
briefed on the upcoming trial by Scottish prosecutors and Justice
Department officials.
</P>
<P>
   Abdel Basset Ali al-Megrahi and Lamen Khalifa Fhimah, both
presumed intelligence agents, are scheduled to be tried under
Scottish law in the Netherlands on charges of planting a suitcase
bomb that blew up the jumbo jet. The trial is to begin in early
February.
</P>
<P>
   For families of the victims, the upcoming trial has brought a
mix of reactions. Dater sees it as positive step in a crusade for
justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly never thought this day would come,'' Dater said
after meeting with Reno and the prosecutors from Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   But for others, like Stephanie Bernstein from Bethesda, Md.,
whose 36-year-old husband Michael died in the bombing, the trial is
merely a way for the U.S. and British governments to put the
tragedy behind them and to renew relations with Gadhafi.
</P>
<P>
   She said the two government were ``trying to put the best face
on what I feel was a very politically motivated compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   In April, the United Nations lifted stiff sanctions against
Libya after Gadhafi handed over the two Libyan suspects to U.N.
officials.
</P>
<P>
   The end of those sanctions, in place since 1992, allowed
international air travel and the sale of vital industrial equipment
to Libya to resume. The step also released Libyan assets that had
been frozen in a number of countries.
</P>
<P>
   But separate sanctions imposed by the United States before the
bombing over Lockerbie will not end until other conditions are
fulfilled, according to the U.S. State Department.
</P>
<P>
   Although fractured in their feelings about the upcoming trial,
the victims' families are united in their belief that the bombing
was likely ordered by Gadhafi and that if evidence in the trial
implicates him and other foreign officials, they should be
punished.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all hoping and believe that the Scottish prosecutors
will not stop pushing if evidence begins to emerge showing just who
ordered the bombing,'' Dater said.
</P>
<P>
   Using funds derived from fines paid by U.S. criminals, the
Justice Department's Office for Victims of Crime is helping pay to
fly some relatives to the Netherlands to watch the trial, arranging
a satellite telecast of the trial or its highlights for families
here, and providing a daily report of trial activity on a toll-free
telephone line.
</P>
<P>
   It also is establishing a secure Internet Web site with trial
reports and an electronic bulletin board through which families of
those killed can communicate with one another.
</P>
<P>
   The extradition of the two suspects and the upcoming trial have
marked a turning point in the efforts of the victims' relatives.
Through quarterly meetings, monthly conference calls, newsletters
and trips around the world, they have fought tirelessly to see
those responsible brought to trial. They have also lobbied to make
skies and airports safer for travelers.
</P>
<P>
   The two Libyans suspects were taken to the Netherlands under a
complex arrangement that treats a former military base near the
college town of Utrecht as Scottish territory so the suspects can
be tried under Scottish law.
</P>
<P>
   It was this formula _ promoted by Britain _ of holding the trial
in a third country that finally broke the deadlock and ended
Libya's long refusal to cooperate with American and British
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   The Scottish judges will have to weigh the still-secret evidence
provided by the United States and Britain and decide whether the
two Libyans are guilty of planting the suitcase bomb. The judges
will then face the fundamental questions of who gave the orders to
blow up the plane and why.
</P>
<P>
   British and American investigators concluded that a bomb was put
aboard the Pan Am flight on its way from Frankfurt to New York
during its stopover at Heathrow Airport in London. Less than an
hour after takeoff, the Pan Am Boeing 747 exploded into flames,
killing its passengers and crew members. In 1991, Britain and the
United States indicted al-Megrahi and Fhimah in connection with the
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
