<HEADER>
A6909 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-RETIREMENT-COUPLES-BO     08-23 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETIREMENT-COUPLES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY OF RETIRED COUPLES POINTS UP CONFLICTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Retirement is supposed to represent the golden years, when
husband and wife finally get to enjoy their time together,
unbothered by worries about children or work.
</P>
<P>
   But a study presented Monday at the American Psychological
Association meeting in Boston finds that for some couples,
depression and marital conflict develop, especially when one spouse
is newly retired and the other continues to work.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the first psychological studies to look at
couples during retirement, not just middle-aged men, or men and
women separately.
</P>
<P>
   With more women now in the work force and companies offering
early buyouts, the possibility of spouses having different
retirement timetables is greater than ever, prompting an increasing
number of researchers to call for studies of retirement as a
couples phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   Lou Pare, 66, knows first-hand what tensions can develop, saying
the study's findings made sense to him. He took an early buyout in
December 1993 from Raytheon Co., while his wife, Claudette,
continues to work as an administrative manager for the curriculum
department at a technical high school.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the popular notions of retirement as idyllic, of
``two people holding hands, walking the beach, both very slim, both
looking 20 years younger than the age they're trying to portray. .
. ,'' Pare said, ``It's not true.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, it's been five years that I've been retired. I've
been a house husband. The first year, I almost went nuts,'' said
Pare. He and his wife have since worked things out, but Pare said
he's still looking forward to his wife's retirement in October of
next year.
</P>
<P>
   In the study, based on interviews with 534 married men and women
in upstate New York, Cornell University researchers found some
interesting differences based on gender, and on who's retired and
who's still working.
</P>
<P>
   Newly retired men whose wives still work experienced more
marital conflict than those whose wives have also retired or have
never worked outside the home at all, while newly retired women
whose husbands still work tended to be more depressed than women
who have long been retired or have never worked outside of the
home, especially if they are dissatisfied with their marriage.
</P>
<P>
   For men, the solution seems to be to find some other kind of
paid work after retirement, even if it's part-time. Those who did
had the highest morale and lowest depression, while those who did
not know what to do with themselves had the lowest morale and most
depression, according to the study.
</P>
<P>
   ``For men, post-retirement employment appears to be beneficial
for their psychological well-being,'' according to the study by
Jungmeen E. Kim and Phyllis Moen.
</P>
<P>
   That seems to describe the situation for Pare. While working on
house repairs helped to fill the time that first year of
retirement, Pare says he didn't feel satisfied until he started
working with the American Association of Retired Persons.
</P>
<P>
   He is now state coordinator for AARP/VOTE in Massachusetts,
setting up forums for congressional and gubernatorial candidates to
share their views with voters, among other activities. While the
work is unpaid, it entails as much commitment as a paid job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find the volunteering rewarding in a lot of ways,'' Pare
said, especially when he helps low-income elderly hook up with
programs to assist with prescription drugs and other services. ``I
get something out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   For women who are newly retired, the answer doesn't appear to
come from finding other work, but from having a happy marriage,
according to the study presented Monday. In fact, women who found
post-retirement employment did not feel significantly less
depressed than those who stayed in retirement.
</P>
<P>
   This apparent gender difference seems to support earlier
researchers' findings that men tend to identify more with their
work, and women with their relationships, say Kim and Moen.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that men who came out retirement and whose wives stayed
at home were the happiest of all, suggests that men ``appear to be
more satisfied with their lives when their spouses are following
traditional gender role expectations,'' said researcher Kim.
</P>
<P>
   The research is part of an ongoing Cornell Retirement and
Well-Being study.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
