<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-20-YEARS-AT-NICKELODEON-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GREEN SLIME NETWORK: 20 YEARS AT NICKELODEON 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide from Nickelodeon's 20th anniversary party)
 By LAUREL GRAEBER  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Scientists believe that all life may have originated in some
great prehistoric molecular stew. The same could be said of
Nickelodeon, except that the medium wasn't primordial ooze: It was
more like green slime.
 &HT;    That gloppy goo has become a trademark of Nickelodeon, the first
network for children and the No. 1 cable network.
 &HT;    Now 20 years old, it has been celebrating its birthday this
summer with special programming, contests, retrospectives,
giveaways and, of course, some green slime.
 &HT;    But while Nickelodeon's signature is the messy and the
irreverent, it wasn't always been the case.
 &HT;    In 1979 it was known to more kids as the ``green vegetable
network'' than the ``green slime network.''
 &HT;    ``The joke was that our early research showed that kids thought
Nickelodeon was like a green vegetable,'' said Cyma Zarghami, the
network's executive vice president and general manager. ``Just
because it's good for kids doesn't mean it tastes good.''
 &HT;    A typical program, she says, was ``Going Great,'' which
showcased the talents of Wunderkinder, a concert pianist.
 &HT;    ``Kids said it didn't do anything to build their self-esteem,''
she says. ``So we decided to create everyday heroes out of everyday
kids.''
 &HT;    The network found its new direction in 1982, when it began to
create programs such as ``You Can't Do That on Television,'' which
Zarghami described as ``one of the earliest versions of `Laugh-In'
for kids.''
 &HT;    A running routine was that anytime anyone said ``I don't know,''
green slime was dumped on his or her head.
 &HT;    (The slime was so successful that it has resurfaced on other
Nickelodeon programs and in its annual Kids' Choice Awards.)
 &HT;    The network also reinvented other adult concepts, like the talk
show and the game show, and came up with a ``Twilight Zone'' for
pre-teens, the still-running ``Are You Afraid of the Dark?''
 &HT;    The series ``makes kids hide behind the couch and bite their
nails, but (it's) never bloody or gory,'' Zarghami says.
 &HT;    In all this programming, there was one constant: ``We looked for
talent that looked like someone you might know from school,''
Zarghami says. ``Not exceptionally beautiful people, but ones who
had ordinary kid personas.''
 &HT;    Funny how things turn out.
 &HT;    During its anniversary bash, the network is showing ``Nick Knew
Them When,'' a series of Nickelodeon programs whose stars are far
from ordinary today. But back then, in the early days of slime and
silliness, they were pretty green and unformed themselves.
 &HT;    Just imagine, for instance, rock singer Alanis Morissette,
poster girl for the jilted and vengeful, as a winsome 12-year-old
getting slime poured on her head in ``You Can't Do That on
Television.''
 &HT;    A series regular, Morissette ``was sort of happy and peppy and
had bigger hair,'' Zarghami says.
 &HT;    ``She doesn't appear to be happy and peppy now,'' she added.
 &HT;    Or James Van Der Beek, the heartthrob in the hit series
``Dawson's Creek,'' playing a musician in an early 1990s episode of
``Clarissa Explains It All.''
 &HT;    Clarissa, played by Melissa Joan Hart, meets him when she's
disguised herself as a punk teen-ager. He's an aspiring rock
drummer who falls under her spell so much that he dons a
skull-shaped earring. Not exactly Dawsonesque behavior.
 &HT;    Some old roles are not such stretches, though.
 &HT;    Neve Campbell, the television star who went on to Hollywood fame
in ``Scream'' (1996) and ``Scream 2'' (1997), can be seen in a 1994
episode of ``Are You Afraid of the Dark?''
 &HT;    She plays the hostess of a restaurant that serves fare that's,
well, unusual _ not a bad training ground, given all the screaming.
 &HT;    Other Nickelodeon graduates include actress Michelle
Trachtenberg (star of the movie ``Harriet the Spy,'' 1996), actor
Will Fredell, who has appeared in the television series ``Zoe,
Duncan, Jack and Jane,'' and singer A.J. McLean, now a member of
the immensely popular Backstreet Boys.
 &HT;    At age 12, McLean starred in the pilot for ``Hi, Honey, I'm
Home,'' the network's comedy series about a 1950s sitcom family
facing life in the 1990s.
 &HT;    As these stars have grown up, so has the network.
 &HT;    ``The way it looks now is different,'' Zarghami says. ``And the
way it looks five years from now will be different. Kids are always
changing, the world is always changing, we are always changing.''
 &HT;    Just don't expect them to abandon the green slime.
 c.1999 The New York Times Company.
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Laurel Graeber is a staff editor at the New York Times.) &LR; 
