<HEADER>
A6911 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-AMY-SMART-IN-OUTSIDE-     08-23 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMY-SMART-IN-OUTSIDE-PROVIDENCE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LONG AND WINDING ROAD FOR `VARSITY BLUES' STAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Amy Smart and Sean Hatosy in a scene
from ``Outside Providence.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    She never saw it coming.
 &HT;    Amy Smart had been in several movies that either closed quietly,
failed to capture the collective imagination of moviegoers, or
featured gigantic man-eating space insects.
 &HT;    Her credits included ``Dee Snider's StrangeLand'' (1998), ``The
Last Time I Committed Suicide'' (1997) and ``Starship Troopers''
(1997), a film which confirmed the showbiz adage that actors should
never work with babies, small dogs or monstrous flesh-eaters.
 &HT;    Then, last year, Smart played the sensible girlfriend opposite
``Dawson's Creek'' star James Van Der Beek in ``Varsity Blues,'' a
high school football movie that opened at the top of the box-office
charts despite lukewarm reviews and went on to score as a solid
hit.
 &HT;    Go figure.
 &HT;    ``We had no idea it would do what it did,'' Smart says. ``It
surprised everyone.''
 &HT;    The weekend the movie opened, people on the street began to
recognize the pretty blonde with the pale blue eyes and low-key
demeanor.
 &HT;    It wasn't exactly Beatlemania, but it was a welcome change.
 &HT;    ``It was very random and it happened when I least expected it,''
says Smart, who sits bundled up in her chair and laughs easily
during a conversation in a New York hotel suite.
 &HT;    ``Middle-aged mothers recognized me and I didn't expect them to
notice. I still don't know how or why they did,'' Smart shrugs.
 &HT;    ``It was an exciting weekend, but I didn't think my life
changed. `Varsity Blues' was an ensemble film, and there wasn't a
lot of hype before it came out, so it really didn't change
everything for me.
 &HT;    ``I do think `Varsity Blues' gave me more credibility going into
auditions _ it could have been my worst performance, but because it
was a hit people took notice of me. That can be distracting. They
see you in that role and think that's as far as you can go as an
actress.''
 &HT;    Smart has gone the distance in her 23 years. Born and reared in
Los Angeles, she steadily worked her way up the Hollywood ladder
after catching the bug at a drama class run by the noted teacher
Howard Fine.
 &HT;    ``I fell in love with the art of it,'' she says. ``I knew after
taking these classes _ and I was the youngest person in a group of
adults _ that I wanted to continue acting.
 &HT;    ``Then, with every job I got, it just kept getting better and
better. I still feel new at it and I've been doing this for almost
six years. There's still so much to learn and to grow from, but
each time I do something I know it feels right.''
 &HT;    Smart recently filmed a television pilot that didn't get picked
up and says she is ``this close'' to landing a role in a film she
won't mention by name.
 &HT;    Why jinx it, she figures, or embarrass herself if she doesn't
get the part? If she loses out it will likely go to one of the many
other well-regarded young actresses Smart so often finds herself
competing against: Claire Danes, Rachael Leigh Cook or her friend
and ``Varsity Blues'' co-star Ali Larter.
 &HT;    ``There have always been a lot of young actors, but now we're
all getting the roles because there are so many teen films,'' she
says. ``Personally, I don't want be this kind of overnight success
that's hyped up for a couple of years and then disappears.
 &HT;    ``I'm young and I'm still learning so much. I don't expect to
win an Academy Award in the next five or 10 years,'' Smart says
with a cheeky smile. ``Well, maybe in 10. Who knows?''
 &HT;    At first glance, her latest project may not be typical Oscar
material, but Smart shows her range in ``Outside Providence,'' a
comedy written by the Farrelly brothers, who were responsible for
1998's bad-taste sensation ``There's Something About Mary.''
 &HT;    Set in Pawtucket, R.I. in the 1970s, the new film tracks the
exploits of Timothy Dunphy (Shawn Hatosy), a poor but decent kid
who lives with his widower father (Alec Baldwin), her
wheelchair-bound brother and a three-legged dog, and hangs out with
a group of grungy, rudderless pals.
 &HT;    When Dunphy crashes into a parked police car, his father trades
in some favors and ships him off to a fancy prep school. There, he
meets Jane (Smart), a well-off, well-adjusted girl, and the two
begin an unlikely romance.
 &HT;    ``Jane gives him motivation and inspiration, and she shows him a
whole different side of life ...'' Smart says enthusiastically.
``She has something to say and she has an impact on this guy's
life.
 &HT;    ``Through their relationship, they both experience new things.
She's inspired by his wild side, his rough edges and his endearing,
tender qualities ... She has a heart and she wants to learn,'' she
adds.
 &HT;    ``Providence,'' Smart says, also has heart. ``... And depth and
a lot of comedy that comes of out natural situations, which is
always the best kind of comedy.''
 &HT;    Wait a second. A movie with heart and depth? From the brothers
Farrelly, who not only unleashed ``Mary,'' but also made ``Dumber
and Dumber,'' as well as the taste-impaired ``Kingpin?''
 &HT;    Smart laughs.
 &HT;    ``I think people will be pleasantly surprised that it's a
Farrelly brothers movie, and that it's not over the top or
outrageously funny,'' says the actress, who filmed ``Outside
Providence'' well before ``Mary'' gave hair gel a whole new
meaning.
 &HT;    ``I think they'll reach an even wider audience with this.''
 &HT;    And so, too, might Smart.
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
