<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEX-AND-THE-CITY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SEX AND THE CITY' _ GOTHAM HEATS UP FOR CABLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Cynthia Nixon, Kristin Davis, Sarah
Jessica Parker and Kim Cattrall in ``Sex and the City.'') 
 By ANITA GATES  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    There will be no more dating.
 &HT;    There are several reasons for this, among them Neil LaBute
films, my advanced age, my last blind date (a man who pronounced
``theater'' to rhyme with ``free gator'' _ and he rejected me) and
HBO's ``Sex and the City.''
 &HT;    Especially ``Sex and the City.''
 &HT;    Have you seen this show? Sarah Jessica Parker and three other
good-looking actresses play single New Yorkers in their 30s who
repeatedly suffer horrible humiliations at the hands of men.
 &HT;    In one painful episode, Charlotte (Kristin Davis), an art
dealer, decides not to have sex on her first date with a handsome
man because she wants to get the relationship off to a better
start.
 &HT;    He says, sure, he understands and he respects her for it, and
he'll get her a taxi home. Then he jumps into the cab with her, so
he can go back to the party and pick up someone else.
 &HT;    ``I really want to have sex tonight,'' he explains politely.
 &HT;    During this half-hour tragicomedy's first season, Carrie, the
sex columnist (Parker) woke up after a tryst with a French
architect to find that he'd left her $1,000 in cash.
 &HT;    Samantha (Kim Cattrall), who's in public relations and is the
most gleefully promiscuous of the four women, dated a man who was
such a ``modelizer'' that he videotaped all his sexual encounters
with models. But when Samantha went to bed with him, he didn't
bother to turn on the camera.
 &HT;    Miranda (Cynthia Nixon), a levelheaded lawyer, had a better time
of it (although she was upset when everyone started talking about
sexual threesomes, and no one wanted to have one with her).
 &HT;    In one episode Miranda called an old boyfriend, Skipper, who
heard her voice on the answering machine and picked up the
telephone, even though he was in the middle of sex with the new
woman in his life.
 &HT;    In a short conversation he agreed to go back to Miranda and
explained that to the other woman, still in flagrante.
 &HT;    Yes, it's funny. The show, which recently began its 18-episode
second season (Wednesday nights at 8:30), is a hit for good reason.
 &HT;    But those of us who aren't out at Moomba (or wherever hip young
people go now) every night cannot watch without asking a couple of
crucial questions:
 &HT;    Are things really that bad for single women in New York these
days?
 &HT;    Does this show represent the sort of things that really happen?
 &HT;    That guy jumping into Charlotte's taxi, for instance. ``True
story,'' said Darren Star, the show's creator and executive
producer, in a telephone interview from Silvercup Studios in Long
Island City, Queens, N.Y., where the series is filmed.
 &HT;    ``There is nothing on the show that has not been, in one way or
the other, verified,'' he says. ``The stories I hear are endless
and horrifying and horrifyingly funny.''
 &HT;    Cattrall sees the situations in ``Sex and the City'' as
heightened versions of real life but not grossly exaggerated.
 &HT;    ``It's awful for the men and for the women'' in real 1990s life,
she said. ``I think our empowerment has put men in some ways on the
defensive.''
 &HT;    Not that Cattrall has to worry about dating problems anymore.
Last September she married a man that she met at a Greenwich
Village jazz club. (She went there alone, and he came over to talk
to her.)
 &HT;    Parker has been married to Matthew Broderick since 1997, and the
two have been a couple since 1992.
 &HT;    Nixon has been in a committed relationship for 11 years, but
they never really dated, she said. She and her boyfriend, who now
have a 2 1/2-year-old daughter, had been friends since junior high
school. Then one day ``we kissed, and he moved in,'' she said.
 &HT;    Only Davis is unattached. Her most humiliating experience has
been finding her date's roommate's written comment about her beside
the phone: ``Kristin. Not funny or clever but single.'' It could
have been worse.
 &HT;    A visit to the ``Sex and the City'' set made it all look so
harmless. On a perfect spring afternoon, with the park's daffodils
in bloom, Parker and Cattrall stood at a pretzel cart at Central
Park West and 90th Street doing dialogue about the masculine habit
of looking at other women.
 &HT;    ``It's like I'm the amazing disappearing girlfriend,'' said
Parker, wearing a floral spaghetti-strap dress.
 &HT;    Cattrall, in a fabulous white coat, replied, ``Looking doesn't
mean he's buying the merchandise, sweetie.''
 &HT;    It could have been an exchange from a Neil Simon comedy.
 &HT;    Later, in her trailer between scenes, Parker said: ``I'd rather
be single in New York City than anywhere else in the world. There
are so many distractions. It's thrilling and sexy and combative,
and we live on top of each other, so at least we're not that
isolated.''
 &HT;    Nixon is sympathetic, too.
 &HT;    ``It's like running for the presidency: the dating obstacle
course,'' she said. ``You know, getting through it and succeeding
in it is not a very good judge of what you would be in a long-term
relationship. To succeed in the dating world you've got to be very
facile, you've got to blow your own horn, be confident, almost numb
to rejection. Which is exactly the opposite of what you want to be
in a relationship.''
 &HT;    ``It's sort of the problem with America in general,'' she added.
``We've become so obsessed with selling. Everything is advertising
now, even dating.''
 &HT;    Chris Noth, who plays Mr. Big, Carrie's on-again, off-again
grand passion, doesn't think very highly of contemporary dating
behavior either.
 &HT;    ``We're living in an adolescent age right now,'' he said, then
headed off to a scene in which his character panics when Carrie
asks for a key to his apartment.
 &HT;    In all fairness, ``Sex and the City'' sometimes makes dating
look just as hideous for men as for women. In one episode Carrie's
gay friend Stanford (Willie Garson) stands on Fifth Avenue waiting
for a man who has answered his personal ad.
 &HT;    When the man arrives, he takes one look at Stanford, says,
``Sorry, it's not going to happen,'' and walks away. As Stanford
later tells Carrie, ``It's so brutal out there.''
 &HT;    Whatever the case in the real world, ``Sex and the City'' itself
seems less romantically bleak this year, albeit much more risque.
 &HT;    So far this season Carrie has captured Mr. Big's attention
again, Samantha has discarded a boyfriend because of his anatomical
shortcomings, and Miranda has risen above it all and bought a huge
new apartment.
 &HT;    But she is now convinced that she will die alone, and that her
cat will eat half her face before anyone finds her.
 &HT;    Charlotte has had an unfortunate experience. After meeting a
great man in a cemetery, at his wife's grave, she comforts him,
beds him, gets all starry-eyed and then discovers that she's one of
four women he is stringing along during his time of need. The
secret is out when all four girlfriends turn up at the wife's grave
with armfuls of white lilies.
 &HT;    Mr. Star, whose first big television success was ``Melrose
Place,'' sees the show as equal-opportunity abuse. ``I think men
are slammed so badly,'' he said. ``It shows some of their worst
characteristics. My guy friends look at the show and say, `How can
you be doing that to men?' ''
 &HT;    Things are tough all over.
 c.1999 The New York Times Company  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Sex and the City,'' consult
HBO's Website at www.hbo.com. And don't forget to visit The New
York Times Syndicate Website at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate
for information on StarBeat and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
