<HEADER>
A6915 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-KOSOVO-ORAHOVAC-ART-2     08-23 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ORAHOVAC-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBANIANS BLOCK RUSSIAN PEACEKEEPERS FROM KOSOVO VILLAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORAHOVAC, Yugoslavia _ Hundreds of Albanians with tractors, cars
and trucks spread out across a hillside and for a mile along a
winding road Monday, blocking an advance column of Russian
peacekeepers from moving in to take charge of the city.
</P>
<P>
   The Albanians, mostly young men, but also families with young
children, bore placards in Albanian and English that read
``Russians killed us,'' and ``We don't trust Russians.''
</P>
<P>
   After a long day on the isolated road, where cars and trucks
wound up into the hills beyond their blockade, they showed no signs
of backing down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want them here because they fought here on the side
of the Serbs,'' said Vesel Vehapi, a farmer from a nearby village.
``We are scared of them from what happened before, and there is no
trust.''
</P>
<P>
   The Albanians have said Russian mercenaries fought beside the
Serbian militias in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Orahovac is one of the most tortured areas in Kosovo and as
such, a microcosm of the province's agony and continuing
insecurity. The area has the greatest concentration of mass graves
_ 75 in an area of 4 square miles _ and was where more than 1,000
people were massacred during the war.
</P>
<P>
   Peacekeeping officials say it also has the largest concentration
of war-crimes suspects still living in Kosovo, local Serbs who have
been named by witnesses and survivors.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of these Serbs, and others like them, is at the heart
of a tension that has been simmering in Kosovo since the end of the
war. The International War Crimes Tribunal in the Hague has handed
down indictments against major Serbian figures, like President
Slobodan Milosevic, and sent scores of investigators to the
province to gather those cases.
</P>
<P>
   But many Albanians are interested in more personal, and pressing
questions, suspecting their former neighbors of burning their homes
and killing their relatives and eager for the kind of detailed
accounting the tribunal has no intention of providing them.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Col. Tony van Loon, who commands the Dutch task force here,
said there are dozens of suspected war criminals in the Serbian
quarter and in a nearby Serbian village, Velika Hoca.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a frenzy of killing,'' said Lt. Col. Tony van Loon, who
commands the Dutch task force here, referring to March and April
when violence by Serbs was frequent. ``People were shot in the legs
and then burned when their house was set on fire. A baby was found
with its head chopped off. There is tremendous rage among the
Albanians when they find their family members dead when they
return.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, Monday, inside the Albanian blockade, within an even
tighter blockade of Dutch troops, the city's 2,500 Serbs live in a
small cluster of narrow steep streets, clustered around the Serbian
Orthodox Church.
</P>
<P>
   They are the source of much of the tension, and the main reason
behind the Albanians' aversion to letting Russian troops deploy in
the area.
</P>
<P>
   Dutch troops guard the ends of the streets with huge
self-propelled guns pointing outwards. They are guarding the Serbs
from attacks by vengeful Albanians, but they are also preventing
the Serbs from leaving, to make sure the war-crimes suspects living
there do not escape. Only a few Serbs are allowed to leave each
day, taken out under the protection of the office of the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the quarter, which the residents themselves liken to a
ghetto, there is a dead, dispirited air, but also a lingering trace
of menace. People hang around the streets buying or selling a few
vegetables or sweets. Young men in tracksuits swagger along with
nowhere to go. Older men sit on street corners and question
strangers as to who they are and what they want.
</P>
<P>
   According to van Loon, there are dozens of suspected war
criminals in the Serbian quarter and in a nearby Serbian village,
Velika Hoca.
</P>
<P>
   The tension soared on Friday when Dutch troops received orders
to hand over the sector to Russian peacekeepers and move east to
another area in central Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time they got the go ahead to arrest three local
Serbian leaders, which they did without incident, with the help of
German military police. They had been investigating the three men
in connection with war-crimes accusations for some time and had
been watching their movements.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the wives and relatives of the three arrested men were
cloistered in the walled garden of a house in the Serbian quarter,
looking scared and trapped. They said they had not been informed of
what, if anything, the men had been charged with.
</P>
<P>
   Vesna Kolasinac said she had no idea why her husband, Andjelko
Kolasinac, the mayor of Orahovac, had been arrested.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had no responsibility for mobilization during the war. He
was only involved in things like the water supply, and the
electricity supply. The reason he stayed behind was because he did
not do anything bad, and that can be confirmed by 90 percent of
Albanians, if they are honest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever committed the crimes, they have run away. Only the
innocent are left behind,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Simic said the same about her husband, Vekoslav Simic, 37,
the former chief of the town hospital and for the last two months
the only working doctor in the Serbian quarter. ``He was involved
in humanitarian things, not politics,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The third man arrested was Stanislav Levic, who worked at a
flour mill.
</P>
<P>
   The order to arrest the men came from the U.N. mission in
Kosovo, said Capt. Mike Bos, spokesman for the Dutch task force
here. U.N. police and a representative of the international war
crimes tribunal from the Hague were present during the arrest, a
German policeman confirmed, and Bos said the arrests were made
based on evidence collected by tribunal investigators. But no
charges or indictments have been made public.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were the leaders,'' the policeman said of the three men.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The men appear to have aided and even orchestrated the campaign
of ethnic cleansing in and around the town of Orahovac. As
community leaders they are expected to be charged with organizing
the campaign, rather than doing the killing themselves, said Fehmi
Cena, chief pediatrician at the town hospital and acting president
of the Albanian-run Council for Human Rights in Orahovac.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Both Kolasinac and Simic worked with the military and were seen
in uniform during the war, he said. Kolasinac, the mayor, was a
more reasonable type, Cena said. ``At least you could talk to
him.''
</P>
<P>
   But Simic, the doctor, was a known extremist, he said. ``The
people think that he is one of the Serb chauvinists who created
ethnic cleansing of Orahovac,'' Cena said. ``He examined many of
the bodies of those killed during this time.''
</P>
<P>
   The three men were taken to the southern town of Prizren and are
thought to be still there, where the families understand they will
be detained pending further investigation.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear if the men have or will be removed to the Hague
for trial. Their arrest brings the number of people detained on
suspicion of having committed war crimes in Kosovo to about 15.
There are more Serbian suspects in both Orahovac and Velika Hoca
under investigation, Dutch and German officers confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs will remain blockaded in their own ghetto, trapped
with their own horrors. A woman called to reporters from her
upstairs room that her son was kidnapped two months ago. ``I want
to tell you, it is all the fault of the evil, nationalist politics
of Slobodan Milosevic,'' she said, weeping into a handkerchief.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of the Serbs say they want to leave for Serbia, but
for now they are stuck. The Russians, when they come, are unlikely
to help them, they said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Russians are stuck too. An advance unit drove
several times up toward the protesters Monday and then turned back.
Their commanders were negotiating with Dutch and German troops and
local community leaders, they said.
</P>
<P>
   When they do arrive in Orahovac, they will inherit a cauldron of
tension. ``The situation is very difficult,'' said a German
military policeman on duty in the Serb quarter. ``The Albanians are
scared, the Serbs are scared, and the two communities hate each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Loon, in an interview last week, said, ``Anyone who expects
the enmity to end between the Serbs and the Albanians is a wild
optimist.'' And the political decision to send Russian troops here
will complicate things further. ``It will set us a whole lot of
steps back,'' he warned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
