<SLUG> BC-MALCOLM-MCDOWELL-REMEMBERS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CLOCKWORK'S' MCDOWELL REMEMBERS KUBRICK, `CALIGULA' 
</HEADLINE>
 
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)  (Includes a color slide of Malcolm McDowell with Irene Jacob and
Colin Firth in ``My Life So Far.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Malcolm McDowell, the actor who became a role-model for young
sociopaths when he played the ``ultra-violent'' Alex in Stanley
Kubrick's classic ``A Clockwork Orange'' (1971), is reading a fax
from Hugh Hefner.
 &HT;    It's only a few months after Kubrick's death, and the Playboy
publisher has just screened ``Clockwork'' for a handful of friends.
 &HT;    Hefner has sent McDowell a couple of questions about the movie.
 &HT;    One is about the brutal water torture scene. The other is about
sex.
 &HT;    ``Hef is a very bright observer of film, but he always wants to
know more,'' McDowell says.
 &HT;    ``He wants to know about the underwater scene in `Clockwork.' He
wants to know if I had an air hose in the water to sustain myself
... And somebody else wants to know why I didn't get an erection
during the orgy scene.''
 &HT;    McDowell laughs uproariously.
 &HT;    ``I told him there were a few other actors around and I was
feeling quite shy that day,'' he adds.
 &HT;    McDowell, 56, has never been known as a shy one.
 &HT;    It's been nearly three decades since he played the ruthless punk
with a penchant for Beethoven in the Kubrick film, which is still
considered so violent it is banned in Britain. McDowell has worked
steadily ever since, but ``Clockwork'' is the film he is best
remembered for and the performance against which all of his work
has been measured.
 &HT;    ``Critics said it was the `performance of a lifetime,'''
McDowell shrugs. ``The only problem is that it came very early in
my career. And you can't keep that level of art up. That type of
movie is so wonderful and special, it only comes along maybe once
in an actor's life.''
 &HT;    ``Clockwork'' became McDowell's calling card after Kubrick saw
him play an insolent schoolboy in Lindsay Anderson's
anti-establishment ``If...'' (1968) and sent him Anthony Burgess'
novel.
 &HT;    ``Stanley sent me the book and said simply, `Read it. Call me.'
Well, I read it three times and I said, `This is marvelous, but how
the hell will you do this as a movie?'
 &HT;    ``Stanley said, `Oh, I don't think that will be a problem.'
 &HT;    When McDowell paused to consider the offer, the irascible
Kubrick asked him: ``Look do you want to do this part or not?''
 &HT;    ``It was a magical shoot,'' McDowell recalls. ``Just to be on
the set with Stanley Kubrick and see him laughing was spectacular.
I remember Stanley putting an actual hanky in his mouth during
certain scenes just so he would stop laughing.''
 &HT;    McDowell also remembers painful moments playing the snarling
delinquent Alex, including the filming of one sequence in which his
character's eyes are propped open and he is forced to watch a
series of violent and terrifying film clips.
 &HT;    ``I actually scratched my cornea and had to walk around putting
antiseptic in my eyes.'' McDowell says. ``Of course, I can't really
complain. I got to work with a great man.''
 &HT;    In the end, McDowell says, he had a somewhat turbulent
relationship with the late director.
 &HT;    ``I would have liked to have settled things with Stanley,''
McDowell says. ``We had a few issues: First of all, I was upset
with his withdrawal from my life after the film shoot was over. I
found that very difficult to understand at my young age.
 &HT;    ``I didn't grasp the fact that you move on after a film. I
thought we had become best friends.''
 &HT;    There were also financial disagreements.
 &HT;    ``He used me,'' McDowell says without much malice. ``Stanley
cheated me out of a percent of the grosses ... I wasn't paid what I
should have been paid in the end.''
 &HT;    ``I guess it's all water under the bridge,'' McDowell sighs.
Today, McDowell is looking back at his career in more ways than
one.
 &HT;    His 1980 film ``Caligula,'' co-starring Peter O'Toole, Helen
Mirren and John Gielgud, will be re-released in America in
September.
 &HT;    Produced by Bob Guccione and Penthouse magazine, it was the
called the first $15 porno movie. In excruciating detail, it told
the story of the Roman emperor's life and included scenes of
decapitation and disemboweling in addition to six minutes of
hardcore sex footage that made it a cult classic.
 &HT;    ``The movie has made more money than any other film I've ever
done,'' McDowell says, laughing. ``I credit the porn.''
 &HT;    The actor says the ``Caligula'' shoot was a heated one for other
reasons.
 &HT;    ``All I remember about that one is trying to make it through the
week and wracking my brain to find ways to keep going,'' McDowell
says. ``It was a tough shoot. We didn't have a script. Our original
director Gore Vidal walked off. And I was Gore's man. I was
devastated when he left.''
 &HT;    Enter new director Tinto Brass. McDowell was not a happy Roman.
 &HT;    ``I was left all alone on this movie where no one could write or
speak English,'' he says, citing further headaches he says were
caused by Penthouse founder Guccione.
 &HT;    ``He owned the film. He owns everything,'' McDowell gripes. ``I
made it clear where I stood. I said, `Mr. Guccione, you have hired
me for 10 weeks. You don't own me.'''
 &HT;    Ownership is also the theme of McDowell's latest film.
 &HT;    ``My Life So Far'' is a pre-World War II period piece which
stars McDowell as a wealthy, self-made Scottish landowner with a
beautiful young fiancee (Irene Jacob).
 &HT;    McDowell says that, in marked contrast to his stint on
``Caligula,'' making the new film was one of the best experiences
of his career.
 &HT;    ``It takes place over a beautiful summer and wants to tell a
story about what family is and what family isn't,'' he says, adding
that he liked playing a vulnerable man, not the kind of part he is
usually offered. He is currently in London playing a more typical
role in the mob film ``Gangster 1.''
 &HT;    ``It's a very violent, profane and brilliant piece in the same
vein as `Reservoir Dogs,''' he says. ``It's about the rise and fall
of the very first gangster ... It's also about a man's descent into
madness.''
 &HT;    McDowell, whose films include ``Voyage of the Damned'' (1976),
``Cat People'' (1982) and ``The Player''(1992), grew up in Leeds,
England as the son of a pub owner and says he always planned to
become an actor.
 &HT;    ``The first time I stepped on stage, I felt all the tension
leave my body,'' he recalls. ``Of course, I was nervous before the
play started. But as soon as the lights went up, I was totally
relaxed.''
 &HT;    After brief stints working at his father's bar, in a coffee
factory and as a regional salesman, he began taking acting lessons.
He gave up his odd jobs when was hired at a repertory theater
company on the Isle of Wight. A year later, he was accepted into
the Royal Shakespeare Company.
 &HT;    He has never looked back, and remains one of the hardest working
actors in the business.
 &HT;    Last season, he took on the Ricardo Montalban role as the
mysterious, white-suited host in an ill-fated re-creation of the
hit television series ``Fantasy Island.''
 &HT;    And this year, in addition to the British gangster role, he is
playing a wizard in a re-make of the French time-travel comedy
``The Visitors.''
 &HT;    ``I know I should take a bit of time off, but they keep asking
me to play these wonderful parts, '' McDowell says.
 &HT;    ``And it's funny because even now I still feel like every role
could be my last.''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``My Life So Far,'' consult
