<HEADLINE>
QUAKE SHAKES ATTITUDES TOWARD `FATHER STATE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN GORVETT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL _ Handing out everything from water to blankets to
diapers from the backs of trucks, pickups, and cars, thousands of
ordinary Turks have been rallying to help out since the very first
day of the country's worst earthquake this century.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, they also may have ushered in political and social
changes that could have far-reaching consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are learning civic solidarity again,'' says columnist Oral
Calisor of the daily newspaper Cumhuriyet. ``We are learning what
we can do for ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   A team of a dozen line workers from the Ford Otosan car factory
south of the stricken town of Yalova got to the scene well in
advance of army and municipal authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of our colleagues were from here,'' said Omer Selcuk, as
his workmates shifted rubble from the collapsed roof of what had
once been a five-story apartment block. ``So we got together, asked
the boss for some tools, a generator, and a winch and headed down
here. When we arrived, there was nobody official at all here.''
</P>
<P>
   In the quake-ravaged Istanbul district of Avcilar, Asena Erdem
and friends from her street in an unaffected part of the city moved
in last Wednesday with an impromptu field kitchen, assembled from
anything they had on hand in their apartments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been hard,'' she said. ``We have done all this completely
by ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So many people have volunteered to help,'' said Turkish Red
Crescent worker Oznur Onen at a tent city set up outside Izmit to
house 5,000 of the devastated city's homeless. ``I've never seen
anything like this in Turkey before.''
</P>
<P>
   Columnist Haluk Sahin of the daily Radikal sees in this
outpouring of public self-organization a radical shift in
attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lack of coordination and paralysis of the government in
the first 48 hours of the crisis was a very dramatic demonstration
that it was not capable of dealing with an emergency,'' he said.
``In Turkey, people tend to expect everything from the state. It's
very different from the US. People here have a phrase _ ``father
state'' _ and an idea that everything will come from there. But
this time, the state's sons and daughters took their own
initiative.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With this, things must change,'' said Calisor. ``This state is
organized for killing, not living. We have the sixth-biggest army
in the world, the largest in Europe, but no civil organizations
because the state always puts so much pressure on them that they
don't have a chance. The vacuum got filled though by the ordinary
people themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   One government minister agreed Monday that the quake, which
killed more than 12,000 people, had exposed an administrative
system that was unprepared and irresponsible.
</P>
<P>
   ``This earthquake is a declaration of bankruptcy for the Turkish
political and administrative system that lacks a city planning
policy,'' said Tourism Minister Erkan Mumcu.
</P>
<P>
   Political and military leaders met Monday in Ankara to discuss
the earthquake crisis, but there was little expectation that any
heads would roll, except perhaps that of Health Minister Osman
Durmus, who told reporters on Sunday that Turkey did not need any
help from foreigners and said on Turkish TV that the nation did not
want any ``Greek blood'' in particular.
</P>
<P>
   The widespread public anger at the ineffectiveness of the
government is unlikely to benefit any one faction.
</P>
<P>
   ``No party can say that they are completely clean in this,''
said Sahin, ``so none of them can really move against the other in
parliament.''
</P>
<P>
   The Islamists, the main opposition party, have been widely
accused of turning a blind eye to shoddy construction practices,
held to be a major cause of the huge death toll. Many of the
buildings that collapsed were built in Islamist-governed
municipalities.
</P>
<P>
   For now, one week after the quake first hit, burying the dead
and dealing with the immediate humanitarian disaster is uppermost
in most people's minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we should not forget how it was,'' said Selcuk in the
ruins of Yalova. ``We won't forget it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
