<HEADLINE>
2,000 US MARINES ARRIVE FOR QUAKE RELIEF DUTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALIZA MARCUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABOARD THE USS KEARSARGE _ US Marines in Izmit Bay readied
themselves Monday to join the relief effort to help Turkey recover
from the earthquake that killed more than 12,000 people last week.
</P>
<P>
   More than 2,000 Marines, who were last in Kosovo providing
security and ferrying aid after the NATO bombing operation against
Serbian forces, arrived on ships of the Sixth Fleet, which patrols
in the Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
   Aboard the USS Kearsarge, the largest of the three ships that
make up the quick response force sent here, Marines prepared
transport helicopters, operating rooms, and water purification
systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we go out it's a different type of situation, but
we are trained for humanitarian assistance and for security
operations and basically, whatever it is, we will do it well,''
said Marine Corporal Irving Barney, a 25-year-old from Watertown,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Their mission now is to help the hundreds of thousands of people
made homeless by the quake.
</P>
<P>
   Specialists from the 26th Marine Expeditionary Unit were already
in the hard-hit Izmit region _ a mainly middle-class region where
tens of thousands of apartment buildings either collapsed or were
heavily damaged _ trying to assess needs.
</P>
<P>
   With electricity still out in many areas, water lines cut and
many roads blocked by rubble, the Marines expect that much of their
job will be to provide clean drinking water and get aid where it is
most needed.
</P>
<P>
   International organizations have sent planeloads of medical
supplies, blankets, and plastic sheeting to protect people living
outside, but part of the problem has been getting the materials
from the Istanbul airport to survivors a few hours' drive away.
</P>
<P>
   Roads are blocked in some towns and cities, and the airport is
overcrowded because of the large numbers of planes bringing donated
supplies from all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   The 40,532-ton USS Kearsarge carries 26 helicopters, some of
which can transport heavy machinery that can clear roads, extract
bodies from the rubble, or tear down heavily damaged buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of people are living in tents in parks and
empty lots, without running water, few toilets, and almost no
showers.
</P>
<P>
   Turkish authorities and volunteers are handing out bottled water
in areas where water mains are broken, but there are fears it may
not be enough to prevent the spread of water-borne diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Three US ships _ the USS Kearsarge arrived with the smaller USS
Gunston Hall and USS Ponce _ have brought in mobile water
purification systems and can produce clean water that can be
shipped by barge along the coast.
</P>
<P>
   With hospitals damaged by the quake, the ships are ready to step
in with medical assistance. Together they have six operating rooms,
five X-ray suites, 47 beds for intensive care, and 588 extra beds.
</P>
<P>
   In the medical care unit of the USS Kearsarge, Navy personnel
stacked supplies in rooms once used for office space.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are preparing for the expected and the unexpected, we've
broken out additional supplies, and we're ready,'' said First Class
Navy Corpsman Brent Davis, a 29-year-old Virginia native.
</P>
<P>
   The operation is part of a large US relief effort that was
mobilized after the quake shook northwestern Turkey, leaving some
30,000 people believed still buried under the rubble.
</P>
<P>
   Two US search and rescue teams have been among those combing the
rubble for survivors, a Navy field hospital was set up to help with
emergency operations, planeloads of supplies have been coming in,
and disease experts were sent to help Turkey evaluate potential
threats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our initial response focused on saving lives,'' said US
Ambassador Mark Parris at a news conference on the ship. ``In
recent days the focus has shifted to meeting long-term health and
medical needs of the population, and the Kearsarge can make a
direct contribution.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
