<HEADLINE>
NEW AIRPORT'S LOCATION EYED IN HONG KONG CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN AND JOYCE HORCHUNG LAU AND  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Sunday's fiery crash of a Taiwanese passenger jet
trying to land in typhoon winds has left some wondering whether
this city's year-old, ultra-modern $20.2 billion airport was built
in the wrong place.
</P>
<P>
   The crash fueled speculation that the location of new Hong Kong
airport, on landfill astride a mountainous island, may make its two
runways more vulnerable to dangerous wind shear and crosswinds,
especially during storms.
</P>
<P>
   It was also the 12th reported fatal crash involving planes
operated by Taiwan-based China Airlines, leading some aviation
analysts to worry about the effect on the reputation of the Asian
aviation industry in general.
</P>
<P>
   Seven China Airlines crashes since the 1980s have claimed 542
lives _ one of the worst safety records in Asia, alongside Korean
Air and Garuda Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   Two people, a Portuguese woman and a Taiwanese man, were killed
as the right wing of the McDonnell Douglas MD-11 scraped the runway
on landing, leaving a trail of fire and flipping over onto its
back. More than 200 passengers were injured, and 60 people remained
in hospitals Monday.
</P>
<P>
   It has also been a bad year for the MD-11 aircraft. At least 240
people have perished in MD-11 accidents in the last year, including
a Swissair crash over Nova Scotia and a Korean Air crash in
Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's crash came as Hong Kong was lashed by Typhoon Sam,
which brought gale force winds and rains that halted bus and ferry
services and shuttered shops. The airport remained open, as it does
except in the most severe typhoon warning.
</P>
<P>
   Airport officials defended its location, calling it
``appropriate'' for safety. ``The meteorological phenomena there is
not the cause of the accident,'' said Albert Lam, director of the
Civil Aviation Department. He also said typhoon warnings that shut
down businesses and public transport have ``no direct relation on
whether or not the airplanes can land.''
</P>
<P>
   But aviation analysts questioned who should have final say on
whether it is safe to land in poor weather. The Hong Kong
Observatory says its system of giving weather updates to
air-traffic controllers, who pass alerts on to pilots, is the best
in the world. As at most airports, the pilots decide whether to
land.
</P>
<P>
   But Jim Eckes, managing director of Hong Kong-based Indoswiss
Aviation consultants, suggested Hong Kong should be considered an
exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is decided that Hong Kong has a propensity for heavy
crosswinds or wind shear, the authorities may decide to
preventively close the airport during bad weather. But the
government may be embarassed politically to make that decision,''
he said, because it could imply the airport's design was flawed.
</P>
<P>
   Wind shear occurs when a strong wind changes directions
suddenly, sometimes in a matter of seconds, often forcing the
airplane's nose down. Two months ago, 11 flights diverted from Hong
Kong to other airports during Typhoon Maggie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wind shear is a problem of terrain. Winds do all sorts of
funny things with mountains,'' said Stephen Miller, managing
director of Hong Kong-based Trinity Aviation.
</P>
<P>
   The location of the new airport, with runways abutting Lantau
Island's 3,300-foot-high peaks, was questioned by industry insiders
from the start.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's Chek Lap Kok Airport project _ at $20.2 billion the
most expensive in the world counting related infrastructure _ has
been fraught with controversy since work on it began under the
former British colonial government in 1989. After many delays, it
opened July 6 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately, the airport encountered mishaps, from chaotic cargo
operations that left tons of goods stranded at warehouses, to lost
luggage, delays, and errant flight displays. Even the brand-new
toilets were stopped up at first.
</P>
<P>
   After early bugs were ironed out, however, the airport became
popular with travellers for its efficiency, spaciousness, speedy
public transport system, and architectural beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Asian airlines accounted for one-third of all crashes worldwide
over the last five years _ three of the seven fatal crashes last
year _ though they represent just 20 percent of all air traffic,
according to Airclaims, Ltd., a British insurer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
