<HEADLINE>
TREASURY YIELDS ARE LOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Yields on Treasury securities hovered at their lowest
levels in a month again Monday, supported by investor optimism that
the Federal Reserve, which was expected to raise interest rates
Tuesday, would not do so again this year.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the 30-year bond rose a scant 1/32, to 102 1/32,
leaving the yield unchanged from Friday at 5.98 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Buying Monday was also influenced briefly by the dollar's early
weakness against the yen, even though it later recovered. Foreign
investors are always a little wary of snapping up Treasuries when
the dollar is down against other currencies because that situation
raises the possibility of a loss when investors convert dollar
proceeds into their own currencies.
</P>
<P>
   Many investors and economists expect the Fed to raise the
federal funds rate, the overnight lending rate among banks, by a
quarter percentage point, to 5.25 percent, when the policy-setting
Federal Open Market Committee meets Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, there's more uncertainty about other related
issues,'' said Maury Harris, chief economist at Paine Webber Inc.,
``such as the nature of the operating policy directive adopted at
the FOMC, when the Fed might raise its current 4.5 percent discount
rate, and the Fed's future actions at the following FOMC meeting on
Oct. 5.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris said he did not expect the Fed to announce a tightening
bias, even though such a directive initially sent a misleading
signal to the markets after the previous FOMC session on June 29
and 30, when the Fed also tightened. At that time, the financial
markets initially rallied on the hope the Fed was finished
tightening.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Blankman, a Treasury market analyst with Standard &AMP; Poor's
MMS, a market research and analysis firm in San Francisco, said:
``The focus will be on reading smoke signals from the wording of
the announcement, the policy directive and the discount rate. We
believe the Fed is apt to tread cautiously, in order to leave all
the options open.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Blankman predicted that the rate increase expected
Tuesday might be the lone policy move for the remainder of 1999.
``As for the text of the announcement, we doubt the FOMC will back
itself into a corner by issuing an overtly friendly message about
the future course of policy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At most, the Fed could note that inflation is still tame and
that GDP growth was appreciably slower in the second quarter,''
Blankman added, referring to the gross domestic product. ``The Fed
may prefer the short and sweet approach in order to keep the market
from making any unwarranted assumptions.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the international environment remained a wild card for
Treasuries. ``Weakness in the dollar is still a source of concern,
and the market will continue to eye prospects for intervention by
the Bank of Japan,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury will auction two-year notes on Wednesday. ``The day
after the presumed Fed rate hike,'' Blankman said, ``so a dismal
auction would not be a surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the weekly bill auction was weak _ especially in the
shorter bill, which was awarded at 4.85 percent, while the
six-month bill came in at 4.95 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
