<HEADER>
A6933 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-HONGKONG-CRASH-NYT &LR;      08-23 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-CRASH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOST QUESTIONS ABOUT HONG KONG AIR CRASH BEGIN WITH THE AIRLINE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ As investigators pored over the wreckage of a China
Airlines plane that crash-landed here Sunday night, aviation
experts began asking questions about the company, Taiwan's flagship
carrier.
</P>
<P>
   Why did the jet, with 315 passengers and crew members, try to
land during a howling typhoon that had driven other airlines to
cancel or divert flights? Why has China Airlines had four major
accidents in the past six years, the worst safety record in Asia?
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been trying to improve, but how can you defend it when
you've lost four airplanes since 1993?'' asked Nicholas Ionides,
the Singapore-based editor of Air Transport Intelligence, a news
agency that covers the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Hong Kong and Taiwan would not speculate on the
cause of the crash, which killed 2 people and injured 212. But the
chairman of China Airlines, Chiang Hung-i expressed deep apologies
for the accident, which he said was ``possibly caused by the
typhoon.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the airline declined to comment on the crash or
on the airline's safety record.
</P>
<P>
   The plane, Flight CI-642 from Bangkok, was landing in heavy wind
and rain at Hong Kong's new $9-billion international airport when
its right wing touched the runway. Witnesses said the plane, a
McDonnell Douglas MD-11, flipped over and skidded to a stop before
being engulfed by flames that apparently began when its right
engine scraped the tarmac.
</P>
<P>
   The Hong Kong government said that of the 212 injured
passengers, 152 had been treated and released. Sixty remain in
several local hospitals, two in critical and six in serious
condition.
</P>
<P>
   The crash bore eerie similarities to two other recent China
Airlines crashes.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a China Airlines Airbus A300 crashed while trying to
land in rain and fog at the Chiang Kai-shek International Airport
in Taipei, Taiwan, killing 196 passengers and crew and 7 people on
the ground.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, a China Airlines 747 overshot the runway while landing
in a typhoon at Hong Kong's old airport, Kai Tak. That accident
injured 23 people; the plane had to be fished out of Victoria
Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   China Airlines suffered its deadliest crash in 1994 when an
Airbus A300 crashed while landing in Nagoya, Japan, killing all 264
aboard. The weather that day was fine; an investigation found that
the pilots had tried to override the plane's autopilot, which was
aborting the landing.
</P>
<P>
   Several aviation experts lay the blame for the safety problems
at China Airlines on its senior pilots, most of whom are drawn from
the Taiwan Air Force. The experts said these pilots tend to be
authoritarian figures who are not open to dissenting opinions from
their co-pilots.
</P>
<P>
   But the plane that crashed here Sunday was piloted by an
Italian, Gerardo Lettich, 58, who joined China Airlines in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Chang Kuo-cheng, the deputy director of the Civil Aeronautics
Administration in Taiwan, said the co-pilot had noticed the plane
was tilting 15 degrees as it came in to land.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the co-pilot found something wrong in the angle of the
plane in approaching the airport, he asked the pilot to `go
around,''' Chang said at a news conference, citing a report filed
by the co-pilot. ``But the pilot did not act, and then a wing of
the plane hit the ground.'' Industry experts said China Airlines
was taking steps to improve safety, such as recertifying its pilots
and recruiting more foreigners. It has hired the German airline,
Lufthansa, to help tighten its operations.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the plane should have landed in such tempestuous
conditions is another question. The weather observatory had hoisted
a No. 8 cyclone warning signal, indicating winds of 39 miles to 73
miles an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Aviation officials in Hong Kong said that it is routine to
operate the airport during typhoons, but that it is up to the
airlines to decide whether to land. By the time Flight CI-642
arrived in Hong Kong, 3 incoming and 3 outgoing flights had been
canceled, 10 incoming flights had been diverted and 14 outbound
flights had been delayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hong Kong's new airport is not an easy place to land a
plane,'' said David A. Sherman, who specializes in transportation
at A.T. Kearney, a global consulting firm. ``When there are strong
winds, it creates a lot of challenging turbulence.''
</P>
<P>
   While pilots are trained and planes are designed to land in such
conditions, Sherman said, there is a higher risk. ``The question is
whether it is a reasonable risk to take,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
