<SLUG> BC-STEM-CELLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP RECOMMENDS USE OF PRIVATE FUNDS TO PRODUCE STEM CELLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal funds should be used to speed research and development
of human embryonic stem cells for a variety of potential treatments
and cures, says a preliminary report from the nation's largest
scientific group on the controversial issue.
</P>
<P>
   The versatile cells, which are formed soon after conception, can
change into any type of cell in the body. Many scientists believe
the cells will eventually be harnessed in unprecedented ways to
repair damaged and diseased tissue throughout the body.
</P>
<P>
   ``We share the enthusiasm of others that (stem cell research)
will offer the real possibility for cures and treatments for many
diseases for which adequate therapies do not exist,'' says the
report.
</P>
<P>
   But the working group of the American Association for the
Advancement of Science recommends against allowing public funds to
be spent in destroying embryos to obtain the stem cells. The cells
could be extracted from human embryos in the private sector; once
transferred to laboratory dishes, the cells could be used in
publicly funded research, says the AAAS report.
</P>
<P>
   The source of the cells remains a controversial issue because
human embryos are destroyed in the process of isolating the stem
cells from them.
</P>
<P>
   One logical source of embryonic cells would be the surplus
embryos created through in vitro fertilization that infertile
couples no longer planned to use.
</P>
<P>
   The AAAS report also said there was no need to create new
regulatory mechanisms for stem cell research. The research itself
raises no new ethical or policy issues, and oversight by the
government's existing Recombinant DNA Advisory Committee would be
adequate, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The preliminary report of the AAAS working group is to be
released publicly Wednesday at a Washington hearing on the issue.
The final version is to be completed within a few weeks, said
Audrey Chapman, an AAAS official who co-directed the study.
</P>
<P>
   She said the timing was aimed at providing ``an informed set of
recommendations'' in advance of expected congressional debate on
the issue of funding stem cell research. The working group included
scientists, physicians, religious scholars, ethicists, and
representatives of patients' groups.
</P>
<P>
   Some conservative lawmakers have vowed to prevent public funding
because the embryonic cells can only be obtained from human embryos
or aborted fetuses.
</P>
<P>
   Actually there are three types of human stem cells: embryonic
stem cells, which are found in the days-old embryo; embryonic germ
cells, which are similar but are obtained from a fetus; and adult
stem cells, which exist in adult tissues and can develop into some,
but not all, types of human cells.
</P>
<P>
   Evan Snyder, a researcher at Children's Hospital in Boston and
Harvard Medical School, who is investigating the potential use of
adult stem cells in the brain to treat neurological diseases,
agreed with the AAAS report that public funding of the work is
crucial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only does the government have more money than private
sources, if (support) comes from the federal government the public
will hopefully find that the work has been done in a scientifically
rigorous way, and not just to have a product at the end,'' said
Snyder.
</P>
<P>
   Although the first isolation of the embryonic cells was reported
only last year, their scientific and medical potential has
attracted great interest among scientists, said Snyder. ``Everyone
in every discipline is beginning to wonder, what can stem cells
offer to my field, or my interest?''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the AAAS working group, the stem cell issue is
being reviewed by the National Bioethics Advisory Committee (NBAC)
and the National Institutes of Health, which contends that public
funding is legal but is in the process of setting up guidelines for
stem cell research.
</P>
<P>
   In a preliminary report in July, NBAC agreed that it would be
proper to spend federal funds on stem cell research, but, unlike
the AAAS working group, NBAC recommended setting up a new oversight
and review panel specifically to review stem cell research.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
