<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6940 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-ELDER-BEERMAN-COX     08-23 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELDER-BEERMAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Elder-Beerman to repurchase its own stock
 &HT;    By Tim Tresslar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Elder-Beerman Stores Corp. said Monday it will
buy back $24 million of its stock over two years and take other
steps to strengthen itself financially and bolster its share price.
</P>
<P>
   Word of the Moraine-based retailer's initiatives comes a week
after a Washington state investment group notified the federal
government that it has purchased 845,000 common shares, or 5.3
percent of Elder-Beerman's 16 million shares outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Elder-Beerman executives say the share repurchase program and
other steps outlined Monday are not a response to calls from the
group, D3 Family Fund L.P., to either fire top management or sell
the company.
</P>
<P>
   At current prices, Elder-Beerman could buy back about 23 percent
of its stock through the open market and privately negotiated
transactions, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Currently Elder-Beerman's biggest shareholder is Snyder Capital
Management Inc., a San Francisco money manager, which holds 10.8
percent or 1.7 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   D3 Family Fund L.P. says the holders of more than 50 percent of
Elder-Beerman's stock have expressed support for the group's
efforts to raise the share price.
</P>
<P>
   Elder-Beerman's stock jumped 15 percent Monday, closing at 7
7/8, up 1 1/16 for the day.
</P>
<P>
   The retailer's management has been considering a stock
repurchase program for several months, but pursued it heavily over
the last month, said Scott Davido, executive vice president and
chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   The company sought approval from its board and banks for a
repurchase program because its shares are undervalued and buying
back stock seemed like a good use of capital, Davido said.
</P>
<P>
   David Nierenberg, D3 Family Fund L.P.'s fund manager and general
partner, said he supports the idea of a stock buy back, but he
still wants Chairman Fred Mershad and President John ``Jay''
Muskovich fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``A share repurchase by itself does nothing to address those
concerns,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other steps outlined by the company include:
</P>
<P>
   _Restructure the merchandising organization. The company also
announced Monday the hiring of Charles P. Shaffer as executive vice
president of merchandising and marketing. Shaffer has been with the
company since 1985 in various executive positions.
</P>
<P>
   _ Open more concept stores similar to those scheduled to open in
Warsaw, Ind., and Frankfort, Ky., over the next couple of months.
The company also will open stores in Sandusky and Winfield, W. Va.,
this year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Implement a four-point program to increase the usage and
profitability of the company's credit card division. The program
includes more aggressive recruitment of cardholders in new markets
and creation of a card-holder affinity program, Davido said. In
fiscal 1998, about 43 percent of Elder-Beerman's sales were made on
its private label credit card, according to the company's annual
report.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pursuit of more acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   _ Increased emphasis on moderate price zones in the core
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's announcement is of things we think will drive
shareholder value,'' Davido said.
</P>
<P>
   Nierenberg said he supports most of the ideas offered by the
company. But he doesn't want the retailer to make more acquisitions
under its current management, he said. Growth is not a cure-all for
a struggling company, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally speaking, I don't think a company grows its way out
of problems,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company's announcement did not mention Nierenberg or his
investment group, which includes about 80 investors and $30
million. But the board said it believes the current management team
can carry out the plan, according to a written statement.
</P>
<P>
   The retailer today is expected to release its fiscal second
quarter financial report that includes a substantial loss. Earlier
this month Elder-Beerman cautioned investors to expect a loss of up
to $1.6 million or 7 to 10 cents a share in the fiscal second
quarter ended July 31.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Tresslar writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
