<HEADER>
A6945 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-WNBA-COX     08-23 0319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WNBA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Growing pains linger for league
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The WNBA continues to expand, averages five-figure crowds in
most cities and has begun attracting some top coaches. By the time
play gets under way next summer, the league will have doubled in
size, from the original eight to 16 teams. The season will serve as
the perfect lead-in to the Sydney Olympics, with virtually the
entire U.S. team and many international stars culled from WNBA
rosters.
</P>
<P>
   But the growing pains aren't completely over. The league might
stress greater ``parity,'' brought about primarily by an influx of
talent from the defunct American Basketball League, but it's a
euphemism for mediocrity.
</P>
<P>
   Television ratings declined, especially during the Women's World
Cup soccer tournament. But the playoffs should generate greater
interest, with the dramatic story line of the Houston Comets' drive
for a third consecutive title as they mourn the death of point
guard Kim Perrot.
</P>
<P>
   The WNBA set another cumulative attendance record, topping the
1.8 million mark and maintaining a league-wide average of around
10,000. The Atlanta Hawks want to be part of the next round of
expansion, but WNBA commissioner Val Ackerman said a decision won't
be made for at least another year.
</P>
<P>
   In June, the WNBA starts in four more cities, with coaches
already hired in three. Lin Dunn and Linda Hargrove, who coached in
the ABL, are in place in Seattle and Portland, respectively.
Indiana will get U.S. Olympic coach Nell Fortner for the 2001
season and Miami is still looking.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the expansion Orlando Miracle nearly made the
playoffs under coach Carolyn Peck, who led Purdue to the 1999
women's NCAA title.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Parker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
