<HEADER>
A6947 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-WNBA-PLAYOFFS-COX     08-23 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WNBA-PLAYOFFS-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Comets playing with a purpose
</P>
<P>
   By Wendy Parker
</P>
<P>
   C. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   The moment was a brief one, and the words certainly had to be
chosen carefully. After his Los Angeles team had beaten the Houston
Comets on Friday near the end of the WNBA regular season, coach
Orlando Woolridge quietly consoled his sideline counterpart, Van
Chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets were subdued by the death the day before of Kim
Perrot, starting point guard on their league championship teams the
last two years. But as they await the winner of tonight's one-game
Western Conference playoff, the woman who was the focus of their
dominating 26-6 campaign figures to take on even greater
motivational significance in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `Your team really scares me now,''' Woolridge
said. ``After back-to-back championships, sometimes the hunger
isn't there. But when you have something to rally around, you have
something to focus on, and with the emotional stress and trauma
that they've been through, that sometimes can be a rallying cry.''
</P>
<P>
   Perrot, 32, the crowd-pleasing floor general who played in the
shadows of the ``Big Three'' of Cynthia Cooper, Sheryl Swoopes and
Tina Thompson, succumbed Thursday after a nine-month bout with lung
cancer. She will be buried today in her hometown of Lafayette, La.
</P>
<P>
   As she recovered from surgery to remove a brain tumor and then
sought non-chemotherapy treatment in Mexico, the Comets charged
ahead. Swoopes posted the WNBA's first triple-double and might be
the league MVP, succeeding Cooper, 36, just named to the U.S.
Olympic roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're always going to be the favorites until somebody beats
them,'' said former University of Georgia standout guard Kedra
Holland-Corn of the Sacramento Monarchs.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento, which plays Los Angeles for the right to take on
Houston, will be without forward Yolanda Griffith, the WNBA's
second-leading scorer and leading rebounder, out with a knee
injury. Los Angeles rallied late, partly because Woolridge inserted
La'Keisha Frett, Holland-Corn's Georgia teammate, into the starting
lineup. And up front, ex-Bradwell Institute star DeLisha Milton, an
All-American at Florida, has helped Lisa Leslie, who is enjoying
her best professional season.
</P>
<P>
   In its third season, the WNBA has improved its overall talent
considerably. Aside from Houston and the New York Liberty, the
playoff teams are built largely around players from the defunct
American Basketball League. But only four of the 12 WNBA teams
posted winning records. New York won the Eastern Conference, but
its 18-14 record would have been fourth best in the West.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty's opponent in the conference finals will have a
losing record. Detroit hosts Charlotte, also tonight, in a one-game
matchup of 15-17 teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty much like the NCAA format,'' said coach Nancy
Lieberman-Cline of Detroit, whose team won its last three games to
make the playoffs. ``You have to win to stay alive. For us, it's
been good, because we've been in a one-game playoff for about two
weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest name missing from the playoffs is former Tennessee
All-American Chamique Holdsclaw. She helped the Washington Mystics
go from 3-27 a year ago to 12-20. But even by WNBA standards, it
wasn't close to being good enough.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Parker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
