   MARKET (New York) _ Investors swagger back into stocks, surer
than ever that the Federal Reserve Board, at its meeting Tuesday,
will raise rates only once more and then be done, at least for this
year. The turnabout in investor mood comes after weeks of
directionless stock trading. Having peaked in mid-July, most of the
market indexes fell as investors grew concerned that rising
commodity prices and labor costs as well as strong economic growth
around the world would push the Fed to take a more aggressive
stance on rates. But over the last week or so, a consensus started
to build that a quarter-point increase might be enough. By Gretchen
Morgenson. (We plan to move the story by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``f'' news
