<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-PORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIFTEEN RESIDENTS RIDE OUT STORM IN COASTAL TOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (Accompanies HURRICANE-TEX) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JOHN MORITZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT MANSFIELD, Texas _ Tamara Hecker and Cindy Rutledge were
not about to be bullied by Bret.
</P>
<P>
   Hecker, 36 and the daughter of missionaries, and Rutledge, 50, a
watercolor artist who is battling breast cancer, were among 15
residents of this bayside community about 100 miles south of Corpus
Christi who shrugged off evacuation warnings as the fierce winds
and rain of Hurricane Bret crashed into the Texas Gulf coast Sunday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us just decided to stay for the adventure of it,''
said Hecker, who withstood a South American earthquake as a child
and faced down a Southeast Texas tornado as a young adult. ``Our
homes are here, our lives are here. So we figured we'd stay here.''
</P>
<P>
   Hecker and Rutledge spent part of Monday afternoon sipping
coffee in the unlighted office of the Fisherman's Inn motel
reliving their overnight adventure for awe-struck visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those who chose to ride out the storm in Port Mansfield
toyed with the idea of heading for higher ground, just as the other
1,000 or so residents of the community had.
</P>
<P>
   But by the time officials ordered the closing of Texas 186, the
main road inland, the self-proclaimed bitter-enders thought they'd
be safer in their homes than on the wind- and rain-swept highway.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I felt rather stupid by staying once those
100-mph winds came crashing in,'' said Rutledge. ``It seemed like
trifling with fate. So I just grabbed my Bible and hunkered down,
but I don't think I had time to pray.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Bret, which came ashore as a Category 4 storm with 140
mph winds, missed such population centers as Corpus Christi and
Brownsville, saving the bulk of its fury for largely rural Kenedy
County and the sprawling King Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   But the unincorporated community of Port Mansfield was not
spared.
</P>
<P>
   Winds tore sections of rooftops from homes and small businesses
along Laguna Madre, which separates the town from the barrier
islands off the Texas Coast. Several trailer homes were toppled and
boats stored on a dry lot were tossed around like toys in a
sandbox.
</P>
<P>
   Many residents, assisted by an army of work crews from the local
utility company, spent Monday cleaning up and trying to restore
electric and water service, which had been out for more than 24
hours.
</P>
<P>
   The 900-square-foot bungalow belonging to Margaret and Gerald
Raleigh lost the front side of its roof, exposing the bathroom and
living room to the driving rain. But the 50-year-old home, which
also weathered Hurricanes Allen and Beulah, remained on its
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is nothing we can't fix,'' said Margaret Raleigh, who has
a fishing boat charter business with her husband. ``This is the
most enjoyable and relaxing place there is. We're not going to give
this place up.''
</P>
<P>
   Across from the Raleighs, the home of John and Patsy Turney
escaped unscathed. The once-sturdy gnarled mesquite on the corner
of their property was not so fortunate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were lucky in the sense that the winds came in from the
northwest and not straight in from the bay,'' said John Turney,
also a charter fishing guide who has lived in Port Mansfield since
1984. ``Basically, it kept the water from coming up onto the
land.''
</P>
<P>
   Hecker and Rutledge said they felt fortunate to survive the
storm, and for just having the experience, even though two
Department of Public Safety troopers patrolling the town on Monday
said they were foolish not to have evacuated before the storm hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little freaky seeing parts of roofs and hunks of tin
flying through the air,'' Hecker said. ``But this building (the
Fisherman's Inn) is made of concrete and steel. I really felt
safe.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
