<HEADLINE>
NEED A USED SPACESUIT? HERE'S YOUR CHANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(The Science Times) 
(mk) 
 By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As they go through the rites of passage into the
history books, the old-timers of the early days of space flight
have had their reunions for John Glenn's nostalgia trip back into
orbit and moments of reflection on the 30th anniversary of their
greatest triumph, the first moon landing, in 1969. So the next step
was perhaps inevitable: Some of their stuff of history is headed
for the auction block.
</P>
<P>
   Christie's East, the New York City auction house, will test the
market for space memorabilia on Sept. 18. It is putting on sale
more than 300 items of space apparel and equipment, mission manuals
and notebooks, astronaut-autographed flight plans and commemorative
postal covers and coins. The auction house described this as the
first large public sale of materials from the American space
program, with a few important items included from the Soviet
Union's rival program.
</P>
<P>
   Price estimates range from $400 for some mission emblems to
$80,000 for a Neil Armstrong spacesuit and possibly $250,000 for a
vintage Soviet spacesuit complete with a Vostok spacecraft ejection
seat.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Austin, who organized the sale for Christie's East,
conceded that it was unusual for historical materials to be the
subject of a major auction so soon after the events they are
associated with had occurred. Often the importance of a historic
event as an area of serious collecting is recognized only in
retrospect.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sale gives collectors a chance to preserve significant
pieces from a historic event that took place in our lifetime,''
Austin said.
</P>
<P>
   Christie's East began planning the auction eight months ago
after a private collector made inquiries about selling some of his
space materials. Several former astronauts who were then approached
agreed to consign items from their attics and basements.
</P>
<P>
   Among those contributing material were Buzz Aldrin, Gordon
Cooper, R. Walter Cunningham, Edgar Mitchell, Walter Schirra and
Thomas Stafford, as well as the estates of Charles Conrad Jr., Gus
Grissom, James Irwin and Donald Slayton. One of the prized items,
estimated to be worth up to $100,000, is the NASA emblem and name
tag from the spacesuit worn by Irwin on the moon and still coated
with lunar dust.
</P>
<P>
   Austin, head of the auction house's books and manuscripts
department, said the manuals and notebooks for the Apollo missions
should have growing value as primary documents of the historic
lunar flights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
