<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SOUP-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUP IS REASONABLY GOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's easy to think Pax TV isn't for cynics. What could those who
disparage the motives of others, who disdain accepted standards of
morality, ever gain from a ``family values'' network?
</P>
<P>
   But after one serving of ``Chicken Soup for the Soul,'' it's
easy to think Pax TV is expressly for cynics.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the astoundingly successful series of books by
self-esteem gurus Jack Canfield and Mark Victor Hansen, ``Chicken
Soup'' becomes a weekly series this year after airing as a Pax
special last season. Simplistic and moralistic, the collection of
stories contained in ``Chicken Soup'' is a sort of uplifting
</P>
<P>
   Reader's Digest cavalcade. Even sad endings aren't really sad,
because there's always a silver lining, a hidden message, intended
to give the principal character _ and the viewer _ a life-changing
ray of hope.
</P>
<P>
   Is that inherently bad TV?
</P>
<P>
   Nope.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, ``Chicken Soup,'' premiering tonight at 8 on KWPX/33,
is reasonably good TV: well-produced, well-written, well-acted. And
the kitchens of Vin Di Bona Productions, where ``Chicken Soup'' is
prepared, have managed to attract some medium-profile stars to
participate in the vignettes _ average length: about six minutes _
that make up an evening's bill of fare. Tonight's debut program has
stories featuring Roxanne Hart, Teri Garr and Shirley Knight.
Future episodes will include Carl Weathers, Gordon Clapp, Ray
Walston and the show's host, Michael Tucker, appearing with his
wife, Jill Eikenberry.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of tonight's program, Tucker says the universal
appeal of good storytelling is no mystery: The best stories, no
matter how fabulous, how mythical, are ultimately about us. As a
steady diet, however, the high-sugar content of the ``Chicken
Soup'' tales may cause intellectual constipation. Each vignette,
whether it's about having the moral courage to do the right thing
or simply the good sense to open all of one's wedding gifts, is
uniformly sappy.
</P>
<P>
   Charming performances, most notably Hart's as a depressed
divorcee, help rescue most of the stories, but even good acting can
get tiresome when a theater company stages plays that have an
unremitting sameness about them. All stories _ parables, fables,
whatever _ have more impact when parceled out judiciously, not
lumped together in a mind-numbing anthology.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, a little ``Chicken Soup'' can go a long way. And too
much of a goody-goody thing will make you queasy.
</P>
<P>
   Chicken Soup for the Soul. A weekly collection of stories about
hope, inspiration and triumph of the human spirit, hosted by
Michael Tucker. Season premiere Tuesday night at 8, KWPX/33.
Parental guideline rating: TV-G.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
