<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6961 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-LOMBARDI-COX     08-23 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOMBARDI-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    University of Florida's president expected to resign amid
controversy
 &HT;    By Shirish Date
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ The University of Florida's popular but
often controversial John Lombardi is, after several close calls
over the years, finally stepping down from the flagship school's
top spot.
</P>
<P>
   Probably.
</P>
<P>
   As with so many Lombardi incidents since his arrival in 1990,
the announcement of his departure Monday itself became high drama.
After scheduling a news conference for 3 p.m., Lombardi left it to
UF spokeswoman Linda Gray to relay the message at 2:56 p.m. that he
wouldn't be talking to reporters Monday after all. No reason was
given.
</P>
<P>
   Lombardi, 57, did not respond to a reporter's e-mailed query on
the matter. Earlier in the day, Gray told the Associated Press that
Lombardi would resign as president but would probably remain at the
school.
</P>
<P>
   Universities Chancellor Adam Herbert, who has had a strained
relationship with Lombardi ever since Lombardi called him an
``Oreo,'' did not return phone calls Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to the matter, who spoke on the condition they not
be named, said Herbert lost patience with Lombardi and has been
insisting he step down by the end of next month but that Lombardi
has repeatedly put it off.
</P>
<P>
   In past battles with the governing Board of Regents, Lombardi
was rescued by influential alumni and legislators. But on Monday,
state Sen. George Kirkpatrick said he thought now was an opportune
time for Lombardi to leave, adding that he didn't really try to
talk him out of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really wants to retire and pursue other things, from
working on his truck to writing a couple of books,'' said
Kirkpatrick, a Gainesville Republican and a perennial Lombardi
booster. ``For his sake and his family, it's a good decision.''
</P>
<P>
   In the world of somber academicians speaking in careful, heavy
prose, Lombardi has been the glib rogue. At regents meetings or in
testimony before various legislative committees, Lombardi was
always off-the-cuff, lively and sarcastic, sometimes openly
disrespectful of the group he was addressing.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, legislators, most regents and particularly his
students found his unpretentious style and appearance irresistible.
His Latin America history classes were among the most popular on
campus, and students frequently chatted with him as he got in or
out of the beat-up, red pickup he drove.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State University President Sandy D'Alemberte on Monday
called Lombardi the smartest man he knows, but added that he had no
real knowledge of what happened or why.
</P>
<P>
   Regent Jim Heekin, possibly Lombardi's strongest critic on the
board, also said the apparent sudden departure came as a surprise.
``He's his own worst enemy, in many ways,'' Heekin said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, it was Heekin's letter criticizing Lombardi for going
around the board and taking UF's case directly to lawmakers that
prompted the first major Lombardi crisis, with the president
threatening to return to Johns Hopkins University, where he'd been
provost before coming to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Another row came two years later, when Lombardi called new
Chancellor Herbert an ``Oreo'' _ black on the outside but white on
the inside. Regents responded by putting Lombardi on a sort of
probation for six months.
</P>
<P>
   The final crisis came this summer, when regents learned of a
letter written by two prominent law school deans complaining of
Lombardi's abusive treatment during a campus visit the previous
autumn.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Sharlot of the University of Texas and Judith Welch
Wegner of the University of North Carolina wrote that Lombardi
behaved ``with gross discourtesy and as an immature bully'' when
they tried to discuss their findings regarding UF's law school
program.
</P>
<P>
   The two had been hired by the regents as outside consultants for
the law school's periodic evaluation by the board. Sharlot and
Wegner suggested that any future consultants be ``given notice that
the president may vent his penchant for abusive behavior upon them.
They should be told that they may have their intelligence, ethics,
and good faith questioned to their faces and expect to have their
professional reputations impugned behind their backs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They just caught John on a bad day, is the kindest way I could
put it,'' Heekin said of the consultants' complaints, adding that
influential law school alumni who in the past had lobbied state
officials to keep Lombardi this time had suggested he leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether this was the straw that broke the camel's back, I
don't know,'' Heekin said.
</P>
<P>
   Herbert told the regents in July that he planned to deal with
the problem himself, in Lombardi's performance review scheduled for
September. It was not clear Monday whether the timing of the review
affected the timing of this latest episode.
</P>
<P>
   Shirish Date writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
