<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6962 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-NEWSSTAND24-COX     08-23 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTAND24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Exploring options for aging parents
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Time's ($3.50) cover story about caring for aging parents is a
topic that weighs heavily on baby boomers. What happens when mom
and dad can no longer cope? Nursing homes are one choice, but there
are new alternatives, such as the Gardens of Towne Lake in
Woodstock. Time correspondent John Greenwald talks with 82-year-old
Marjorie Bryan, who decided against living with her grown son and
moved into her own apartment in the Woodstock complex. Staffers are
available 24 hours a day to help with daily tasks, but the
residents maintain their independence.
</P>
<P>
   In other news, the search for Person of the Century continues.
Asked for their choices, author Tom Wolfe nominated Alexander
Solzhenitsyn, while historian John Keegan cited Vladimir Lenin.
When Solzhenitsyn's ``The Gulag Archipelago'' was smuggled out of
the Soviet Union, Wolfe says, ``it was as if a stake had been
driven through the heart of Marxism.'' On the other hand, Keegan
insists that the spread of Lenin's Bolshevism exerted a malign
influence that included creating nationalist reactionaries such as
Adolf Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where there's smoke: Cigar Aficionado ($4.95), the slick
entertainment magazine for stogie lovers, is not famous for its
investigative reporting. But the October issue has a surprisingly
in-depth article detailing efforts by the Kennedy administration
and Fidel Castro to end the conflict between the United States and
Cuba. Peter Kornbluh, an analyst at the National Security Archive,
sifted through declassified files to reveal the secret U.S.-Cuban
dialogue that began in March 1963.
</P>
<P>
   According to a secret memo, President Kennedy overruled the
State Department's position that Cuba had to break its relations
with the Soviet Union as a precondition for normalizing relations.
A pivotal role in the negotiations was played by ABC News reporter
Lisa Howard, who carried messages between Havana and Washington and
provided her New York apartment for meetings between U.S. and Cuban
officials. The talks ended in December 1964.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Grading parents: Many harried parents feel guilty because they
don't spend enough time with their children, but children don't
necessarily feel the same way, says Ellen Galinsky, whose book
``Ask the Children'' is excerpted in Newsweek ($3.50). According to
Galinsky's research, while 56 percent of parents think their
children want to spend more time with them, only 10 percent of kids
want more time with their mother and 15.5 percent with father.
Children also resent it when they feel that the time parents spend
with them is rushed.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Manly things: Males who may be in doubt about their
masculinity are invited to take Esquire's ($3.50) Hugh Grant
Manhood Test. If you talk like Prince Charles, stammer a lot,
refuse to go to a gym and live in fear of your lady friend, then
you probably are Hugh Grant. In a lively interview, the British
actor talks about his macho shortcomings and his role in the
gangster movie ``Mickey Blue Eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  More about men: Susan Faludi, whose 1992 book ``Backlash: The
Undeclared War Against American Women'' made her a feminist icon,
speaks out on the oppression of men in the September/October issue
of Mother Jones ($3.95). The author of the forthcoming book
``Stiffed: The Betrayal of the American Man'' says that ``being a
feminist opens your eyes to the ways men, like women, are
imprisoned in cultural stereotypes.'' Even with the economy
booming, Faludi writes, men feel betrayed by their communities, by
their companies, and by their sports teams which abandon one city
for another. But the greatest sense of betrayal, she says, has to
do with the loyalty between fathers and sons. Instead of handing
off positions of leadership to their sons, the fathers of the World
War II generation gave them ``a consumer culture that focused on
winning, and on dominating everything and everyone. ... We are now
living in a culture that runs on image.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The music scene: When Rolling Stone ($3) covered Woodstock in
1969, managing editor Robert Love says the prose was idealistic to
the point of being almost dewy-eyed. ``Out of mud and hunger and
thirst,'' one reporter wrote, ``a new nation had emerged.'' Thirty
years later, the mood of the country has changed. In a report from
the trenches of Woodstock '99, correspondent Joe Rosenthal says
that a more fitting name for the gathering might have been
``Fratstock.'' It was simply one big party, with no thoughts of
peace or politics.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
