<HEADER>
A6963 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TV-MOB24-COX     08-23 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MOB24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Real informant the star of `Family Values'
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Analyze this: Watching mob movies are a left brain, right brain
experience.
</P>
<P>
   On some level, we're instinctively drawn to the colorful swagger
of characters who follow a strict code of respect and loyalty. But
we're also repulsed by men wearing pinky rings who kill for a
living.
</P>
<P>
   So it's not too surprising that TNT's documentary ``Family
Values: The Mob &AMP; the Movies'' can't decide if it's a lighthearted
look at the history of Hollywood gangsters, or a fascinating,
frightening meditation on a real-life mobster turned informant. Too
bad it tries to be both.
</P>
<P>
   Banking on the recent spate of movies such as ``Analyze This''
and ``Mickey Blue Eyes,'' this two-hour tour through the show
business underworld is guided by Tony Sirico and Vincent Pastore, a
pair of wiseguys from the hit cable series ``The Sopranos.''
</P>
<P>
   They are members of GAG _ the Gangster Actors Guild _ a crew of
Brooklyn-based regulars who have spent their careers playing
mobsters. The narrator is fellow GAG member Frank Vincent, a
white-haired, craggy-faced actor most moviegoers could easily pick
out of a lineup.
</P>
<P>
   GAG's small fraternity spends time busting each other's chops at
Bensonhurst social clubs, making spaghetti sauce and hanging out at
off-track betting parlors like any self-respecting gangster might.
But they make it clear that none of them ever becomes a ``made
guy'' _ a full-fledged Mafia solider.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes Dominick, a sad-faced, real ex-hood in a cartoonish
fake beard who steals the show from the make-believe mobsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I ever knew was backstabbing, lying and best friends
killing best friends,'' says Dominick, who doesn't give his last
name. ``I gave up the best wife and the best kids in the world to
be a creep.''
</P>
<P>
   We learn that Dominick has spent the last five years ``in the
wind,'' lingo for a soldier who
</P>
<P>
   ratted out his family and eventually left the federal witness
protection program to fend for himself.
</P>
<P>
   His life _ recorded in family snapshots and chilling homemade
movies _ sounds like the plot of every great modern mob film we've
ever seen or memorized.
</P>
<P>
   Raised by an uncle who was a vicious mob captain in the Gambino
crime family, Dominick remembers cousins who suddenly disappeared,
missing school because of a gangland war and being ordered to kill
an old classmate.
</P>
<P>
   Even when Dominick tried to get out of the family ``business''
(he was a Green Beret in Vietnam commended for combat bravery and
later formed a rock band), they kept pulling him back in.
</P>
<P>
   Dominick's narrative is so engrossing that midway through the
documentary the GAG-fellas' muddled moralizing about their onscreen
characters becomes an annoying, silly distraction. Who cares about
the wannabes when you have the real thing?
</P>
<P>
   There are other voices in ``Family Values'' worth hearing,
including character actor Paul Sorvino, former John Gotti attorney
Bruce Cutler and Katherine Narducci, an actor on ``The Sopranos''
whose father was killed in a mob-related shooting when she was 10.
</P>
<P>
   But it's Dominick's story that slices through the nonsense of
our collective Mafia-mania and offers a sobering dose of reality
that's very hard to refuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Family Values:
</P>
<P>
   The Mob &AMP; the Movies''
</P>
<P>
   8 tonight on TNT
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Lyle V. Harris writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
