<HEADLINE>
LITTLE CHANGED (SO FAR) IN PATRIOTS ROSTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ If the Patriots roster were set today, the
midpoint of the preseason, there would be few changes from last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Chris Carter plugs in for Willie Clay, Andy
Katzenmoyer for Ted Johnson, Tedy Bruschi for Todd Collins, and
Damien Woody for Dave Wohlabaugh.
</P>
<P>
   Other than center, the much-maligned offensive line of a year
ago is currently unchanged, which is good news for Todd Rucci, Max
Lane, Zefross Moss, and Bruce Armstrong, bad news for Damon Denson,
Ed Ellis, and Heath Irwin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we have no major shifts in what we're doing,'' said
coach Pete Carroll. ``We are shifting a little bit of playing time,
but nothing dramatic has happened. Nobody has made a move to take a
spot on the offensive line. Woody has a chance to start this week
and we'll see if he can make it through the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll go with the best guys we got. The starters are holding
their spots. We're making progress. I don't see anything happening.
We've got two more weeks for these guys to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   As things stand, Kevin Faulk will be starting at running back
over Lamont Warren, and Steve Israel is beating out Tebucky Jones
at right corner. The fullback spot could change, with Chris Floyd
edging Tony Carter, but indications are the two will share time.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll also spoke of one or two young guys making the roster
because of their special teams prowess. Sean Morey and Bernard Russ
are the front-runners, but Florida State defensive end Willie
Cohens is a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   If the Patriots follow their pattern of recent years, all of
this year's draft picks will make the team. This also could be the
year when some picks of three years ago _ fellows such as Denson
and Ellis _ are fighting to keep a spot.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots must reduce their current roster of 86 to 65 by
next Tuesday, then get down to 53 by 4 p.m. on Sept. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at what the final roster may look like:
</P>
<P>
   --QUARTERBACK (3): Drew Bledsoe, John Friesz, and Michael
Bishop.
</P>
<P>
   There is no debate that these three will make it. Jim Murphy or
Scott Mutryn could stick on the practice squad.
</P>
<P>
   --RUNNING BACK (4): Kevin Faulk, Lamont Warren, Derrick Cullors,
and Harold Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots could tweak this if they pick up a veteran running
back. It doesn't appear that Marques Brigham, the rookie from
Wyoming, will have a spot, though he is a practice squad candidate.
Though Cullors and Warren do the same things, Cullors is valuable
as a kick returner; for the moment, nobody is better.
</P>
<P>
   --FULLBACK (2): Chris Floyd and Tony Carter.
</P>
<P>
   The only debate here is, who starts? The Patriots prefer Floyd
as a blocker and a tough runner at the goal line, but Carter has
the experience and catches the ball very well.
</P>
<P>
   --RECEIVERS (6): Terry Glenn, Shawn Jefferson, Vincent Brisby,
Tony Simmons, Troy Brown, and Sean Morey.
</P>
<P>
   This is where things may get interesting. Will all five veterans
be on the roster Opening Day or will either Jefferson or Brisby be
dealt, for draft picks or to fill another need? And whither Morey?
All indications are that the Brown grad has made it, based on his
special teams play and his fourth-quarter receiving. He shows grit
and fight.
</P>
<P>
   --TIGHT END (4): Ben Coates, Rod Rutledge, Henry Lusk, Mike
Bartrum.
</P>
<P>
   The first two are no-brainers, and Bartrum is the long snapper,
so he makes it. The question is, Lusk or rookie free agent Jamie
Bowers from Wabash, who is also a fullback? The Patriots cleared
salary cap space by reworking Lane's contract to fit Lusk in, so
they must believe he'll be on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   --OFFENSIVE LINE (8): Zefross Moss, Bruce Armstrong, Damien
Woody, Todd Rucci, Max Lane, Heath Irwin, Damon Denson, Jason
Andersen.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll reiterated at his press conference Monday that the
backup guys haven't pushed any of the starters out of a job. It'll
be interesting to watch how they handle fifth-round pick Derrick
Fletcher. Though enamored with his size, quickness, and strength,
they believe he needs time to learn the system. The decision may
come down to whether they should keep Fletcher on the roster or
risk placing him on the practice squad, which means he has to go
through waivers. If the Patriots want to keep an extra defensive
lineman, Ellis could be in danger.
</P>
<P>
   --DEFENSIVE LINE (8): Willie McGinest, Chad Eaton, Henry Thomas,
Chris Sullivan, Brandon Mitchell, Greg Spires, Garrett Johnson,
Leonta Rheams.
</P>
<P>
   They are fragile here and must be careful about whom they keep.
Johnson is a tough kid who has made an impression inside, which is
where they're most vulnerable to injuries (Thomas and Eaton are
already hurt). Rheams also has looked good inside. Veteran free
agent Sterling Palmer and rookie free agent Willie Cohens could
break in. Carroll mentioned that Cohens could make the special
teams.
</P>
<P>
   --LINEBACKERS (7): Chris Slade, Tedy Bruschi, Andy Katzenmoyer,
Ted Johnson, Marty Moore, Bernard Russ, Dana Cottrell.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have to decide whether to keep Johnson on the
active roster or place him on injured reserve. Despite the recent
surge by Katzenmoyer and Bruschi, the Patriots will likely tinker
with this group before deciding on the final six or seven. Cottrell
has been getting a shot lately and has pushed third-year vet Vernon
Crawford out of the picture, but Crawford still has a shot to get
back into it. Newly acquired Aaron Adams, who flunked his Packer
physical before being signed here, needs to show something in a
hurry. Ron Merkerson, who was on IR last year, needs to rebound
from his latest injury before the rosters are set.
</P>
<P>
   --CORNERBACKS (4): Ty Law, Steve Israel, Tebucky Jones, Kato
Serwanga.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots will likely go with five corners, but the fifth man
may not be on the team yet. These four are sure bets, and there's
always the possibility they go with an extra safety, such as
sixth-rounder Marcus Washington, who can play both positions.
</P>
<P>
   --SAFETIES (4): Lawyer Milloy, Chris Carter, Larry Whigham, Tony
George.
</P>
<P>
   Washington is the bubble guy. He'll have to have a strong final
two games or he'll wind up on the practice squad, especially if the
Patriots acquire another defensive back. The Patriots like Cory
Gilliard of Ball State, who had a good NFL Europe season, but he
hasn't played yet because of knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   --KICKERS (2): Adam Vinatieri, Lee Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The only debate is over which of the two will kick off. Johnson
appears to be in the lead based on the past two games. Young kicker
Marcus Williams looks like a practice squad guy, as Phil Dawson was
a year ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
