<HEADLINE>
BRET SPARES SOUTH TEXAS COAST; INLAND BRACES FOR RAIN, TWISTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARLINGEN, Texas _ Communities along the south coast of Texas
breathed a sigh of relief at narrowly escaping heavy damage from
their first major hurricane in two decades, while inland residents
Monday braced for Bret's potent remnants in the form of tornadoes
and flash floods.
</P>
<P>
   Even as families began returning to the homes they fled when
Hurricane Bret was approaching the mainland on Sunday, officials
issued warnings for the second consecutive day that people in the
Rio Grande Valley take cover and clear the roads because of
torrential rains and the threat of deadly twisters.
</P>
<P>
   As much as 25 inches of rain pelted portions of this cattle and
farming region, turning streets and highways into rivers and
flooding low-lying areas, officials said. Several funnel clouds and
at least two tornadoes were spotted in different inland areas as
the storm continued to march west toward Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may be the worst of the storm for us,'' said Eleazar
Garcia, city manager of Raymondville, a small town where at least
two funnel clouds were spotted Monday afternoon. ``The hurricane
was not as bad as we thought, but the rest of the danger is the
flooding.''
</P>
<P>
   As with the hurricane, residents and officials reported no
casualties or heavy damage from the sweeping winds and driving rain
that moved unpredictably across the region throughout the day. But
authorities warned that flash floods and tornadoes could hit at any
time.
</P>
<P>
   The anxieties prompted by the afternoon storms were in contrast
to the relief felt earlier in the day that this area near the
Mexican border had escaped the muscle of Bret's punch.
</P>
<P>
   Many families who had taken shelter in schools and community
centers on Sunday, when the hurricane hit, returned to their homes
in the morning only to go back to the shelters when threat of
tornadoes and floods became apparent.
</P>
<P>
   One state emergency official, who requested anonymity, wondered
whether local workers had been premature in allowing residents to
return to their neighborhoods before it was clear that Bret had
passed.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the day, winds inland were reported between 40 and
55 mph and up to 25 inches of rain fell in Kenedy County, where the
eye of the hurricane passed on Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy rains and flash floods were also expected further north in
the city of Laredo, where forecasters predicted up to 20 inches of
rain. At least 3,800 residents were evacuated and moved to higher
ground.
</P>
<P>
   But for most of the region's residents, the formula for dealing
with Bret seemed to be a mixture of early preparation, careful
monitoring and a heaping of good luck.
</P>
<P>
   With winds as strong as 140 mph and waves up to 25-feet high on
Sunday morning before it made landfall, the hurricane seem poised
to be one of the deadliest to hit the Texas coast in more than 20
years.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of hitting directly on any of the heavily-populated
cities that dot the coast, Bret's eye passed between Brownsville
and Corpus Christi, over rural towns which had been largely
evacuated by the time the hurricane arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Some damage was reported in the towns of Falfurrias, about 60
miles west of Corpus Christi, where residents said roofs were
ripped from homes and most of the town had no electrical power.
Several mobile homes and other insecure structures were heavily
damaged in Port Mansfield, about 50 miles north of Brownsville.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane was downgraded to a tropical storm Monday morning,
once the minimum sustained winds fell below 74 mph. Meterologists
expected the heavy rains to continue, although weaker, as the storm
pushed ahead over land with diminished winds.
</P>
<P>
   Bret was the first storm to hit directly on this area since
Hurricane Allen blew through in 1980, causing serious damage and
killing three people.
</P>
<P>
   For all of its bluster, though, Bret may have brought some
much-needed moisture to the area. Officials said that several areas
of the state have registered less than average rainfall this year,
including Brownsville, Corpus Christi, Dallas, San Antonio and
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were lucky this time, but we always have to be prepared,''
said Irma Cantu, 39, a waitress in Brownsville who spent most of
the storm's worst moments in a dark house with boarded windows. ``I
hope we don't have to go through something like this again for
another 20 years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
