<HEADER>
A6978 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BO     08-23 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ILIE ALL TORN UP _ ABOUT WINNING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Before Brandi Chastain, the shirt-shedder,
there was Andrew Ilie.
</P>
<P>
   But he doesn't feel she's a copycat or that she infringed on his
act when the US women won the world kickball championship and she
ripped her jersey off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just something that came naturally to me _ to celebrate a
great occasion, a great win,'' Ilie said Monday at Longwood Cricket
Club after a leadoff victory over Andrei Pavel. ``I understand how
she felt.''
</P>
<P>
   The US Pro was on again, marking the 35th anniversary of its
long run here, but so was Ilie's shirt.
</P>
<P>
   This may have disappointed the growing cult of Ilie-watchers,
but Monday wasn't a day for a topless triumph, he said. The score
was 6-3, 1-0, before Pavel surrendered with a gimpy right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt bad for Andrei to have to quit; he was hurting,'' said
Ilie. ``It was no time to celebrate.''
</P>
<P>
   Did the match rate a subtitle: ``championship of Romania on a
patch of Boston pavement''?
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever,'' Ilie said while smiling, something he does often.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Ilie, Romanian-born Australian, had gotten the better of
a Romanian who lives in Germany. Unlike Pavel, who plays Davis Cup
for the homeland, Ilie turned down a lucrative opportunity to do so
four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was eligible because of my Romanian birth,'' he said. ``But
I'm Australian first, and my goal is to play for Australia. I feel
very grateful that the country took me and my parents in 13 years
ago. Those were bad times in Romania under the Ceausescu
dictatorship.''
</P>
<P>
   But 10-year-old Andrew didn't joyfully tear his shirt to tatters
when the Ilies (father Dan, mother Katherine) scored a familial
victory by landing in the sunshine of Melbourne. They arrived from
a refugee camp in Austria with one bag apiece, and a few hundred
dollars. Shirts were precious. He wasn't on a clothier's free list
then, although in a few years he would be Australia's best
14-year-old tennis player, then 16 and 18, a pro at 17.
</P>
<P>
   Sartorial demolition began ``spontaneously'' last May in Paris
when he beat Swede Jonas Bjorkman in five tough sets as the French
Open commenced. You could hear the rrrrippp! on top of the Eiffel
Tower as Ilie danced gleefully and made the chemise suitable for
dust rags.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that was my best win,'' said Ilie, currently No. 53.
``Jonas had been in the top 10. I had to play five sets again in
the next round, beating Martin Rodriguez _ and there went another
shirt.''
</P>
<P>
   He might have had a hat trick of shirts, but, going five once
more, Ilie fell to Dominik Hrbaty. Still, it was a $27,337
three-day stretch of turning riches and rags. His wardrobe stayed
intact until Los Angeles three weeks ago, a double-dicer. The names
of his victims were big in his mind: Byron Black had spearheaded
Zimbabwe's huge upset of Australia during the 1998 Davis Cup; Goran
Ivanisevic was, well, the Croat Croaker, the guy who'd nearly
beaten Pete Sampras in the 1998 Wimbledon final.
</P>
<P>
   But there was nothing of the usual frenzy in his post-Ivanisevic
garment dismembering. It was artistic, according to a witness.
Surgical. He went at it very slowly, savoring every
cotton-picking-apart tug.
</P>
<P>
   Longwood accommodated his largest and perhaps most appreciative
audience, 5,300, last month as Ilie, a squad member, ripped and
raved. He was leading the Aussies' celebration of their Davis Cup
victory over the US after Patrick Rafter clinched against Todd
Martin. ``It seemed like the thing to do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Five shirts have been sacrificed by the blocky, good-natured
23-year-old, a 5-foot-11-inch 160 pounder. Nevertheless, he has an
ample supply, saying he's ready to go on a tear in our town. Next
to test his rending tendencies Wednesday will be the survivor of an
intramural matinee matching Frenchman Guillaume Raoux and Sebastian
Grosjean.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to have fun playing tennis,'' said Ilie, and he wants
the people watching to have fun, too. Maybe it comes with the name,
Ilie. Certainly Romania's foremost product was the picaresque Hall
of Famer Ilie Nastase. But this Ilie, Andrew, seldom boils over.
</P>
<P>
   He wraps a ``lucky'' red bandanna around his white cap and goes
about his work bullishly as though seeing red, mashing heavy
groundies.
</P>
<P>
   He enjoys talking to umpires, like the other Ilie, but is more
playful. If he thinks an umpire has failed to hear a let, he will
crack his racket hard against the tape, inquiring, ``Could you hear
that?''
</P>
<P>
   Like most parents, Dan and Katherine Ilie would give the shirts
off their backs for their boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to leave Bucharest, get out of Romania then,'' said his
father, a metallurgical engineer (mom is a mechanical engineer).
``There was no future for Andrew. We were doing all right by the
standard of the time, but we wanted more for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took six years of applying for exit visas before they let
us go. Then we were a year in the refugee camp before Australia
would take us. Andrew is the only jock in the family, but I could
see that he could be a very good player. I'd taken him to the
Progresul Club when he was 5, and when he saw kids playing tennis
he said, `I want to play that game.' He had the gift, but Romania
was no place to develop it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now my engineering,'' papa said with a laugh, ``is devoted to
keeping Andrew in working order.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
