<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILENE-BANKRUPTCY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILENE'S BASEMENT SEEKS BANKRUPTCY PROTECTION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)   By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In another sign that the competitive discount apparel sector may
be ripe for a shakeout, the Filene's Basement Corp., which
pioneered the business of offering designer clothing at cut-rate
prices, filed for bankruptcy protection on Monday in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which is no longer related to Filene's, said it had
assets of $200 million and liabilities of $148 million. It has
4,000 employees and operates 55 stores, including 12 in the New
York metropolitan area, and said all of its stores would continue
to operate until a reorganization plan is completed.
</P>
<P>
   Filene's Basement also said it had secured $135 million in
financing from the General Electric Capital Corp. and Paragon
Capital LLC, subject to bankruptcy court approval.
</P>
<P>
   Top creditors include companies like Sak's Fifth Avenue and
Nike.
</P>
<P>
   The concept behind Filene's Basement started in 1908 when Edward
Filene decided to offer the previous season's fashions at low price
in the basement of his elegant Boston Department store. The company
was bought by Federated Department stores in 1929, which split
Filene's and Filene's Basement into two companies in 1984. Filene's
is now owned by the May Department Stores Co.
</P>
<P>
   Filene's Basement, based in Wellesley, Mass., was taken private
in 1988 by top managers and then went public by in 1991. It is
probably best known for the quarterly wedding dress sales at its
flagship Boston store, where brides-to-be have been known to fight
for $8,000 Christian Dior gowns that can be had for as little as
$280.
</P>
<P>
   The bankruptcy filing surprised few in the industry because the
chain, has had sales troubles since the mid-1990s. Its stock had
been sinking since January. A week ago, the company said it lost
about $15 million in the quarter ended July 31 on sales of $144
million.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate cause of Filene's Basement's troubles was that
suppliers had stopped delivering merchandise because they feared
the chain would not meet it financial obligations. For bargain
chains that rely on customers returning frequently to sniff out a
new jewel, the lack of fresh offerings can prove deadly.
</P>
<P>
   ``With our stores' inventory below optimal levels, we determined
it was in the best interest of all of our stakeholders to file for
Chapter 11 in order to insure strong inventory positions prior to
the holiday selling season,'' Sam Gerson, the chairman and chief
executive of Filene's Basement, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The larger issue is that the discount and off-price apparel
sector, which has been highly competitive in recent years, is
increasingly dominated by a few big companies, putting pressure on
smaller players. Loehmann's Inc., another venerable name in the
off-price apparel world, filed for bankruptcy protection in May. In
particular, the TJX Co., the owner of both T.J. Maxx and Marshall's
stores, which had $8 billion in sales last year, has been
aggressively scooping up the best offerings from houses like Ralph
Lauren and Donna Karan, leaving Filene's to pick over clothes in
colors like burnt orange and chartreuse and offer lesser status
brands.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Filene's competitors have also been raising their
profiles through aggressive advertising, a move Filene's could not
or would not counter. ``The others have been very sharp with both
pricing and promotional vehicles, but Filene's still operates as if
low price only is enough to get people through the doors,'' said
Wendy Liebmann, president of W.S.L. Strategic Retail.
</P>
<P>
   Before the filing, Filene's Basement said it had been working on
a strategy to streamline the business. The headquarters staff was
recently pared 15 percent, to 200 people. The company is focusing
on a concept known as Aisle 3 stores. The company now operates four
of these stores, which are open only on the weekends and offer
moderate brands, as opposed to designers, at discounted prices. It
plans to open four more by the end of the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
