A6981 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-BRET-TRAGEDY-HNS &LR;      08-23 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRET-TRAGEDY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAGEDY STRIKES SOUTH TEXAS FAMILY FLEEING HURRICANE BRET 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By S.K. BARDWELL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Sabas Quiroga feared for his family's safety. As
Hurricane Bret approached Sunday, he loaded up his wife and
children and left their mobile home in Seadrift, heading up the
coast to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Within an hour of the family's arrival at a southeast Houston
motel, Quiroga, 32, was dead.
</P>
<P>
   Melinda Quiroga said their children were hungry after the
150-mile drive, and after they were settled into a room at the Red
Carpet Inn about 9:30 p.m. CDT, her husband decided to walk to a
fast-food restaurant on the other side of the freeway.
</P>
<P>
   As he reached the inside northbound lane of the freeway, Sgt.
Mark Newcomb of the Houston Police Department said the wind blew
off Sabas Quiroga's hat. He stopped and stepped back to retrieve
it.
</P>
<P>
   Melinda Quiroga saw a vehicle strike her husband. It tossed him
up in the air and into the windshield of another vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Newcomb said the driver who struck Quiroga stopped. The sergeant
said he doesn't believe the driver was at fault, and he doesn't
expect any charges will be filed.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the room at the Red Carpet Inn, the children heard the
commotion and ran outside before their mother could stop them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were all at the scene,'' said Newcomb, who helped
investigate the accident. ``They kept asking, `Is that my dad? Is
that my dad?'''
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said the children and their mother were crying, as
were some of the officers and many of the passers-by who stopped to
help.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew it was (their father), but we didn't want to tell them
there in front of everybody,'' Newcomb said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, police called Ben Taub Hospital, where a room was set
up for the family and the bad news related in privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a heartbreaking, very sad situation, to see all those
children,'' Newcomb said. ``They didn't have any money.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to myself, `I can't go to bed tonight, until I do
something.''' Newcomb began making telephone calls to anyone who
might help.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Santana Funeral Home had offered its services to the
family at no charge, and the Sabas Quiroga Memorial Fund had been
set up for contributions to help the family.
</P>
<P>
   Those wishing to donate to the fund may mail money to the Sabas
Quiroga Memorial Fund at Seaport Bank, P.O. Box 670, Seadrift,
Texas 77983.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Melinda and the five children, ages 3 to 12, spent the night on
the floor in the family room at Ben Taub Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Sabas' brother, Jose Quiroga, drove in from Tyler, Texas, as
soon as he heard about the accident, and he and Sabas' older sister
were trying to care for the family Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The widow had no idea of what she would do. ``We'll go home, I
guess, because that's the only home we have,'' she said. ``I just
don't know what to do when we get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Jose Quiroga said his brother worked in construction and made
just enough to keep his family going. Melinda, Jose said, is
disabled and cannot work.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Jose said it appeared the family's trailer in
Seadrift, just south of Port Lavaca, was untouched by the storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were fleeing the hurricane, but he caught up with death
anyway,'' Jose said of his brother. ``Just a different way.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
