<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-RATES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FED EXPECTED TO BOOST INTEREST RATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Call it done.
</P>
<P>
   Financial-market analysts and economists are confident that
Federal Reserve Board members will vote Tuesday to raise interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
   Although prices at both the retail and wholesale level were
remarkably tame in July, and no one can be certain the Fed will
raise rates, the widely held belief is that the Fed must act to
rein in an economy that is simply growing too fast.
</P>
<P>
   If Fed members, at their scheduled meeting, boost the federal
funds rates, as expected, by another quarter of a percentage point,
to 5.25 percent, it would mark a second preemptive strike against
inflationary steam that may be building in an economy forecast to
pick up momentum as the year rolls on.
</P>
<P>
   The funds rate, which commercial banks charge each other for
overnight loans, was first raised a quarter-point, to 5 percent, on
June 30.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average surged to a record high Monday
of 11,299.76, despite investors' expectations of a rate hike _ an
event that would normally send markets tumbling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nonevent,'' said Ned Riley, chief investment officer
for BankBoston Corp. Now, Riley added, ``The markets are working on
the proposition that's the last increase we'll see for quite a
while.''
</P>
<P>
   The market's certainty stems from recent testimony by Fed
chairman Alan Greenspan, including a July 22 speech to Congress in
which he warned that he would not hesitate to raise rates if data
suggest ``the pace of cost and price increases will be picking
up.'' As if on cue a week later, the employment cost index for the
second quarter leaped 1.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't do anything that would be absolutely
mind-boggling,'' said Nicholas Perna, chief economist for Fleet
Financial Group Inc., ``The reaction would probably be a big rally
on Wall Street.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors and economists said they believe a rate hike is
required to undo the three rate reductions, in rapid succession,
the Fed announced last fall to soothe world currency markets and to
avert a near-crisis on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   But, the data watched closely by the Fed to gauge inflation
continue to send mixed signals.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two weeks, government reports showed consumer and
wholesale prices in July have been calm. The consumer price index
rose just 0.3 percent in July, an increase spurred largely by a
spike in gasoline prices. The producer price index rose a modest
0.2 percent last month, following a 0.1 percent drop in June.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Angell, a former Fed governor during the Reagan and early
Clinton administrations, noted that the core inflation rate _ the
CPI minus volatile food and energy prices _ has risen only 1.7
percent, annualized, this year. In 1998, the core CPI rose 2.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Given such data, ``What is there that requires us to act today?
Why not wait for more data?'' asked Angell, a senior vice president
of Bear Stearns Co. Such a sentiment, he said, ``may be overlooked
by such a strong consensus as to what the the Fed will do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's next meeting to set monetary policy is scheduled for
Oct. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Economic growth slowed to an annual rate of 2.3 percent in the
second quarter after growing 4.3 percent in the first, but is
expected to accelerate this fall.
</P>
<P>
   While the stock market typically falls when rates rise, the
market, oddly, soared in anticipation of the outcome of the Fed
meeting. That's because investors long ago factored in the Fed's
action and are now looking beyond it to whether a third rate hike
would follow, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average surged 199.15 points to a new
record close of 11,299.76. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index, a
broader measure of the market, gained 23.61 points and closed at
1360.22.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market, said Doug Cliggott, equity strategist for J.P.
Morgan &AMP; Co. in New York, ``is like a beach ball. Try to hold it
under water. It wants to go up.''
</P>
<P>
   One force pushing the market higher, Cliggott said, has no
direct link to interest rates: an ``astonishing'' influx of foreign
capital, in the form of overseas, mainly European, acquisitions of
US companies. Through July, overseas companies announced mergers or
acquisitions of US companies valued at $242 billion. That's on a
pace to far oustrip the $232 billion in similar deals for all of
1998 and $64 billion in 1997, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for the market rally, economists said, is that
investors may also be hoping that two positive inflation reports
indicate that while the Fed would raise rates, it may continue to
hold a neutral bias toward further increases in rates in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet's Perna said the Dow's rise in the wake of the last
tightening by the Fed may be in response to a drop in yields on
30-year Treasury bonds.
</P>
<P>
   The long-term government bond has fallen from recent highs of
about 6.20 percent to below 6 percent. Thirty-year yields Monday
fell 1 basis point to 5.98 percent, the lowest level since July 22.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed also sent the stock market soaring on June 30 when it
last boosted interest rates. Although its announcement of a rate
increase was expected, investors were ebullient at the Fed's
remarks that no future rate increases were planned.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the Dow has gained more than 325 points, while the
S&AMP;P has lost 32 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's cut and dried that they're going to hike funds another
quarter point'' at the Fed meeting, said David Jones, a veteran Fed
watcher for Aubrey Lanston &AMP; Co., a New York securities firm. ``The
markets are pretty comfortable with that idea, and they could
conclude that would be the last one for a while.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-99 2017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990823.0352 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6986 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-PROVENCE-$ADV2     08-23 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-PROVENCE-$ADV29-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING DO IN PROVENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Aug. 29) 
(jt) 
 By ANITA GATES    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jennifer and Rand are my Sara and Gerald Murphy. (Or _ a more
disturbing thought _ I am their Zelda Fitzgerald.) Like the
Murphys, the Americans who almost singlehandedly made the Riviera
fashionable in the '20s, these are friends who know how to enjoy
life and how to entertain.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, I've visited them in New York, Philadelphia,
Jamaica, Switzerland and the Berkshires, and I've never had less
than a wonderful time. Whether we're having Negronis before a city
dinner or plantains at a Caribbean breakfast, food and drinks
always taste better and the conversation seems more sparkling when
they're the hosts.
</P>
<P>
   So, when Rand, facing the trauma of his 50th birthday, announced
that they planned to spend it in Provence at a house he and
Jennifer had rented several times before, I immediately invited
myself. ``Next year in Fayence!'' we said, waving goodbye last
summer at their rented house in Rhode Island. I didn't know where
Fayence was exactly, but that seemed incidental. Fly to Nice. Hitch
a ride.
</P>
<P>
   Which I did. But as is so often the case, the adventure began at
the airport, in this case Charles de Gaulle, near Paris.
</P>
<P>
   There are nonstop flights from New York to Nice, but I
sacrificed that for a lower air fare ($444 round trip on Air
France, reserved six weeks ahead, but available only on flights
through Paris). Two other guests landed air fares of $262, thanks
to an Alitalia sale announced the day after I booked my flights.
Those are the breaks.
</P>
<P>
   When I arrived at de Gaulle, after a stress-free overnight
flight from New York, I couldn't find my connecting flight to Nice
on any of the airport's information screens. In pathetic French, I
asked, and was told to walk to Terminal F. This was an invigorating
stroll (comparable to walking from Times Square to Columbus Circle
indoors), but unfortunately none of the information screens there
listed a flight to Nice either.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I spotted my flight number on the screen, but the
destination was listed as Toulon. I decided that Nice must be an
intermediate stop or something. Only when I opened my copy of The
International Herald Tribune did I learn what was happening: ``Nice
Airport Stoppage in 4th Day'' read a headline near the bottom of
page 2. The first French word I ever learned outside the classroom
was greve (strike), and it has come in handy all too often.
</P>
<P>
   And so after some delays, I arrived in Toulon (on the coast,
east of Marseilles) at 3:25 p.m., about the time I had planned to
be checking into my hotel. The free Air France bus left at 4:10;
almost two hours later, we arrived at the Nice airport, where taxis
were waiting as if the airport were actually in use. After another
hour and a $37 taxi ride, I checked into the Le Metropole in
Beaulieu-sur-Mer.
</P>
<P>
   Provence may be paradise, but it doesn't have a beach. So my
plan was to spend the first two days of the trip on the Cote
d'Azur, feeding my insatiable need for a water view. I had stayed
at the Carlton Hotel in Cannes once and loved it, but Cannes seemed
almost urban and, anyway, the beach was all the way across the
street.
</P>
<P>
   None of the alleged world travelers I knew had a good hotel
recommendation in the area, so I chose Le Metropole from a
guidebook, based on a combination of factors. It was between Nice
and Monaco, a ``huge white villa'' with ``opulent gardens,'' a
pool, a beach and room service, the service was described as
peerless, the clientele as wealthy but ``anything but flashy,'' and
the clincher: it was a Relais et Chateaux property. What worried me
was the room rate: about $145. Since when do you get luxury on the
Riviera for this price?
</P>
<P>
   But I did. Considering the rates, I would have splurged and
reserved an oceanview room but a garden view was the only thing
available on the dates I needed. And the garden view was such that
by turning my head slightly to the right, I was facing the pool and
the Mediterranean beyond it. From where I stood, the two bodies of
blue water seemed to merge. The pool is heated, so even though it
was only late April it was being put to use.
</P>
<P>
   The room was smallish but very pleasant with black-and-tan
carpet, white-on-white latticework wallpaper, a small television on
top of a minibar, and a walk-in closet. The bath was small but
elegant, white and chrome, with a forceful shower, double basins
and a real medicine cabinet with triple mirrors. Its only flaw was
a weak hair dryer.
</P>
<P>
   Beaulieu turned out to be a charming town, and I spent my two
days strolling, shopping a little and just reading and staring at
the sea from the hotel lobby or its small outdoor tables
overlooking the water. On the second day, it was warm enough to
take advantage of the pool but I had to meet George and Mary,
friends from San Francisco, at the airport and move on.
</P>
<P>
   When I checked out, my bill _ including meals (except one goat
cheese salad I'd had in town), considerable wine and careless
expenditures like small $6 bottles of Evian from the minibar to
carry around with me _ came to about $485. The food, incidentally,
was excellent; completely out of control, I ate a basketful of
bread at every meal.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, in the middle of the airport strike, George and Mary's
plane managed to land in Nice. The flight was late, though, so I
had a little airport food while I waited. Only in France can you do
that and find yourself savoring a large piece of crisp, very
lightly breaded whitefish (the plat du jour), a large serving of
haricots verts accented with red peppers, mushrooms and eggplant, a
bottle of Pellegrino and a half bottle of very decent local red
wine (Chateau Virant 1997, Coteaux d'Aix-en-Provence). The bill was
just under $20.
</P>
<P>
   We soon piled into a rented Citroen, got out our hand-drawn maps
and headed out on Autoroute A8. Less than an hour later, we were in
Fayence (which turned out to be west of Grasse). Jennifer and Rand
seemed dressed for New England, including hip boots, a sign that
the weather might not be as glorious as we'd hoped, and Jennifer
was worried that the house might be ``a little too rustique.''
</P>
<P>
   It was definitely not a palace. The kitchen looked like a
particularly dreary ``before'' picture in a decorating magazine.
The living room was the size of a breakfast nook. To get to my
bedroom, I had to walk through George and Mary's, and there was one
bathroom for five people.
</P>
<P>
   But there was an olive grove and a set of stone steps leading up
a hill to the ``pool'' (actually an ancient sheep dip). Something
was at work _ the transforming power of great hosts, some
exclusively Provencal magic, I don't know _ but a couple of hours
later, we were happy as clams.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
