<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6987 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-NC-SCHOOLDESEG-COX     08-23 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NC-SCHOOLDESEG-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Possible busing halt has NAACP, parents waiting for judge's
decision
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ In the city that pioneered busing as a tool
for school desegregation, some of Charlotte-Mecklenburg's public
schools could again become segregated if a federal judge allows the
district to end busing, officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But while an end to forced busing would mean that some schools
would be either all-white or all-black, Mecklenburg County
Commission Chairman Parks Helms said, it would not mean ``that we
are going back to separate but equal.''
</P>
<P>
   That possibility, however, alarms the NAACP and others who
oppose any retreat in the integration of the county's 101,000
school students, whose fate is in the hands of U.S. District Judge
Robert Potter. The outcome in the case, brought by white parents,
could have broad ramifications on race in public education,
especially if an appeal reaches the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   It comes as school officials in DeKalb County, Ga., and in
Boston are stopping busing as a means to achieve integration. In
cities such as Buffalo, Cleveland and Seattle, school districts are
phasing out desegregation plans.
</P>
<P>
   The trend seems bolstered by the findings of a recent study
sponsored by the National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People. In a random survey of 1,001 people, aged 18 to 29,
about 50 percent of whites said separation of the races is
acceptable, as long as everybody has equal opportunities. About 40
percent of blacks responded the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Griffin, chairman of Charlotte-Mecklenburg's Board of
Education, said the findings do not suggest to him that public
acceptance of segregation in schools and other institutions is
growing.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte has too much invested in integration to reverse
course, said Griffin, 50, who attended all-black public schools in
Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get back to rigidly separate schools, you lose the
public will to make these schools a positive educational
experience,'' Griffin said Monday in an interview, after appearing
at a public gathering in downtown Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   Local school, political, business and church leaders issued a
call for unity in what has has been a wrenching debate over schools
in this fast-growing city of 500,000 people. The discord comes 30
years after another federal judge ordered busing in Charlotte, then
a relatively unheralded Southern city where the peaceful
desegregation of schools served as a model for other cities.
</P>
<P>
   The 1969 ruling, Swann v. Charlotte-Mecklenburg Board of
Education, set a national precedent, ushering in busing in many
cities seeking to desegregate schools.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Charlotte, a 1997 lawsuit challenging the Swann ruling
led to a three-month trial that ended in June. A group of white
parents sued, arguing that forced busing and race-based student
placement violated their constitutional guarantee of equal
protection.
</P>
<P>
   The original plaintiff, Bill Capacchione, complained that his
daughter waited two years trying to enroll in one of the county's
magnet schools. At the time of the lottery for seats, spots
reserved for black children had gone unfilled. Blacks eventually
took the seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``My children are bused because of their race,'' said Scott
Willard, 34, another plaintiff. He said he believes it is unlawful
that his two daughters are forced to travel 10 miles to a
predominantly black school, even though six other elementary
schools are closer to their northeastern Charlotte home.
</P>
<P>
   Like many others who attended Monday's meeting, Willard believes
that Potter's ruling will bring an end to Charlotte-Mecklenburg's
forced busing, at least the way it has been practiced over three
decades.
</P>
<P>
   This year, 12,000 students in Charlotte-Mecklenburg are forcibly
bused. Historically, black inner-city children have been bused to
predominantly white suburban schools. Since 1992, a growing number
of white students have voluntarily been bused to inner-city magnet
schools, raising concern among black parents.
</P>
<P>
   If the school board decides to turn magnet schools into
neighborhood schools_a likely scenario if forced busing ends_black
parents fear their children will not have adequate access. The
Board of Education has endorsed a plan to eliminate busing for
integration over five years by dividing schools into three to five
geographic areas that would reflect the county's racial and
socio-economic diversity. In that way, students would be able to
attend schools in the areas where they live.
</P>
<P>
   While school officials generally believe that the judge will
decide that Charlotte's schools have reached an acceptable level of
desegregation, and thus busing can end, nobody is sure of the
outcome. The NAACP has threatened to appeal if it believes that
desegregation is threatened.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot stop busing now,'' said Reginald Hawkins, 75, a
Presbyterian minister and dentist who was a plaintiff in the
original lawsuit in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Burritt writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-99 2019EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
