<DOCNO> NYT19990823.0354 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6988 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-PROVENCE-$ADV2     08-23 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-PROVENCE-$ADV29-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: as clams.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a visit to the local olive oil factory and the supermarket
(I love French supermarkets: they look just like American ones
until you notice that there's a creme fraiche section and those
things on ice next to the shrimp are giant eels), the five of us
were in the kitchen having a little foie gras on brioche toast and
drinking a white Cote du Rhone, Domaine de Durban
Beaumes-de-Venise, that Rand said went perfectly with foie gras _
and it did. Mary snapped the haricots verts while Jennifer cooked.
We might as well have been at Villa America.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Friday, was Rand's birthday, and our hosts had
made reservations at Le Castellaras, a nearby restaurant in the
hills. We were meeting the other two guests, John and Corby, who
were staying at a hotel in the village. It rained, but the
restaurant's nighttime view was still beautiful. The main dining
room is formal with a massive fireplace, but it feels open because
the outside wall is floor-to-ceiling glass. Beyond that is a
gorgeous patio that must be heaven on summer days.
</P>
<P>
   The food was largely wonderful, particularly the foie gras and
langoustine terrine, the cheese course and the wine. One guest had
brought along a bottle as a gift, and the sommelier graciously
opened it for us. Although he announced, only half-joking, ``There
is no wine in California,'' after decanting the gift bottle, he
pronounced it ``not bad.'' Gifts were opened, toasts were made, and
Rand survived his cinquantenaire.
</P>
<P>
   Fayence itself is one of those hilltop conglomerations of red
roofs and narrow medieval streets where every shopfront exudes
effortless charm and you could swear that nothing has been changed
in a century at the very least. It has a nice Saturday morning
market, with everything from wonderfully smelly cheeses to
clothing.
</P>
<P>
   During our three days in Fayence, we did some shopping in the
village, but mostly for food. My only nonedible purchase was at
Fayence-Tissu, a great fabric store where everything looks like
Pierre Deux but costs less. I picked up matching Provencal-print
oven mitts and toiletries bag, which will come in really handy if I
ever want to bake my shampoo, moisturizer and toothpaste.
</P>
<P>
   One day, we made a group excursion to St.-Tropez. I had been
there before and warned the others that they were going to be
disappointed (they were) but no one listened. One day, we drove
back to Beaulieu. But mostly we ate: simple lunches on the patio of
lettuce, tomatoes, tuna, olives, cornichons, delicious bread and
cold white wine; one breakfast of amazing croissants from the
patisserie in the village, strawberry jam from the farmers' market,
strong coffee and some candy that Corby had brought from Nice.
</P>
<P>
   On our last night, we had dinner at Patin Couffin, which I
translated as the Skating Basket or Skate in a Basket, neither of
which made any sense (it turns out that in the Nicois dialect, it
really means something like ``this and that''). It was a rustic
place in the village that the others had discovered on a morning
walk. Our table was in a cavelike alcove with plaster walls and low
ceiling, which matched the hearty, inexpensive food. We paid about
$35 each for appetizers, main courses, desserts and voluminous
amounts of wine. (I had the sole and a pork terrine; both were very
good.)
</P>
<P>
   But the highlight of the evening was meeting the owner,
Virginie, a transsexual who likes to play Marilyn Monroe albums as
background music. The last thing I remember is Virginie sitting in
somebody's lap and all of us singing along to ``Diamonds Are a
Girl's Best Friend.'' Feeling very old, we gave special emphasis to
the line ``and we all lose our charms in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're going to have to turn 50 (or 40 or 60 or any of those
round numbers), I am now sure that doing it in the right place can
substantially reduce the pain. Especially if foie gras is involved.
</P>
<P>
   French charm
</P>
<P>
   Where to Stay  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before driving to Fayence, I stayed at Le Metropole, 15
Boulevard du Marechal Leclerc, 06310 Beaulieu-sur-Mer, a 47-room
seaside hotel, with bar, restaurant and heated outdoor pool.
Doubles with bath, $145 to $450; telephone (33-4) 93.01.00.08, fax
(33-4) 93.01.18.51.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Eat
</P>
<P>
   Le Castellaras, Fayence, (33-4) 94.76.13.80, fax (33-4)
94.84.17.50, has a Michelin star. The lamb and the frogs' legs are
specialties. Dinner with wine is about $50 a person.
</P>
<P>
   Patin Couffin, Placette Olivier, Fayence, (33-4) 94.76.29.96,
serves hearty, casual Provencal cuisine. Dinner with wine: $25 to
$35 a person.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Where to Shop
</P>
<P>
   Fayence-Tissu, 24 Place Leon Roux, 83440 Fayence, (33-4)
94.76.10.61, sells tablecloths, napkins, potholders, sheets, towels
and other items in a wide variety of Provencal prints. A zippered
makeup bag is about $25, a pair of oven mitts $17.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
