<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6990 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES24-CO     08-23 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BRAVES NOTEBOOK: Maddux not in as much pain
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Greg Maddux said Monday afternoon his right wrist was
feeling much better, which means a start for him Friday may at
least be possible, a start the next time through the rotation
likely and talk of his missing the rest of the season is beginning
to fade out.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux had an MRI on Monday which confirmed the earlier
diagnosis of a chipped bone and a sprained right wrist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm real encouraged by how much better I feel than
yesterday,'' Maddux said Monday afternoon. ``I'm pleasantly
surprised. Yesterday was no fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux even asked manager Bobby Cox if he could play a little
long toss on Monday, though Cox recommended he didn't. Maddux was
just happy to return to some normalcy in his everyday life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can brush my teeth, tie my shoes,'' Maddux said.
</P>
<P>
   As courtesy to his fellow starters, Maddux plans to get together
with Cox and make a decision about his Friday start on Wednesday.
That would allow Terry Mulholland the off day Thursday to get ready
for the start on Friday in St. Louis if Maddux can't go. Maddux
could very well skip his next start and pitch Aug. 31 in Cincinnati
when his turn comes around again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have three more days to get treatment, let it heal up and
see if I can pitch Friday,'' Maddux said. ``If not, I'll try to get
ready to pitch the next time around.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux hasn't missed a start since April of 1997 when he missed
one with a hamstring strain.
</P>
<P>
   ``In his mind, I think he wants to make his next start, but
we'll see,'' Cox said. ``We'll wait a couple days and play it by
ear.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cox is sounding and feeling much more positive on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have been a disaster,'' Cox said. ``He could have
been out all season.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan to get shot
</P>
<P>
   Brian Jordan paid a second visit to a hand specialist on Monday
and was reassured his right hand was getting no worse physically,
though the pain undoubtedly was. To combat that, Jordan is planning
to get a third cortisone shot on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Two cortisone shots have been ineffective probably because the
affected area is so small. Jordan will have to miss three to five
games following the shot, but is hoping if he gets it after
Wednesday's afternoon game he can miss only Friday's game following
the off day Thursday and try to return on Saturday in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has been bothered by a sore right hand ever since he was
hit by a Mike Thurman pitch on June 22. Sunday afternoon was one of
his toughest days yet but he still finished with two hits and drove
in the game-winning run.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind it felt like it was getting worse, but it really
wasn't,'' Jordan said. ``The doctor said `You're playing every day,
you're swinging and using it, you're going to generate a lot of
pain...All I've got to do is suck up the pain. It's hard to do. It
just frustrates me. I'm so angry on the bench. I'm growling at
people on the bench.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's game-winning hit Sunday brought him his 99th RBI of the
season. He's topped 100 in RBI only one other season - in 1996 with
the Cardinals when he drove in a career-high 104. Through Sunday's
game, Jordan was hitting .300 and was on pace to drive in 127 RBI
this season and score 108 runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``One hundred (RBI) is still a big deal,'' Jordan said. ``My
goal every year is to score 100 runs, drive in 100 runs and hit
.300.''
</P>
<P>
   All in the family
</P>
<P>
   If Reds third baseman Aaron Boone has been looking for some
fun-loving trash talk from his older brother Bret, he's apparently
been disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He tries to talk trash, but I don't,'' Bret Boone said.
``He'll call me up and say `We're for real.'... This is not a big
series. What's bigger than losing two out of three to San Diego?
Every series is big.''
</P>
<P>
   This is only the second time in their lives the two Boones, the
sons of former major leaguer Bob Boone and grandson of former major
league Ray Boone, have played against each other at any level. The
first was May 2 in Atlanta when the Braves beat the Reds 5-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he's happy for us,'' Aaron Boone recently told the
Cincinnati Post of his brother and former Reds teammate. ``But deep
down I can tell he thinks we're playing a little over our heads.
That's OK because I understand that Braves mentality. They're
thinking `There's the Braves and then there's everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Monday the Braves named fired Detroit Tigers pitching coach Rick
Adair their minor league pitching coordinator. Adair worked as the
Tigers pitching coach from September of 1996 until he was released
on July 9. Adair was also the pitching coach for the Cleveland
Indians in 1992 and 1993. Adair will take over on Sept. 15. He'll
replace Jerry Nyman, who will be reassigned.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
