<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-770&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS FED PREPARES TO MEET ON RATES, THE MARKETS JUMP 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Investors swaggered back into stocks Monday, surer
than ever that the Federal Reserve Board, at its meeting Tuesday,
will raise rates only once more and then be done, at least for this
year.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average closed at a record high of
11,299.76, up 199.15 points, or 1.79 percent. The average has risen
23 percent so far this year, well above its 16 percent gain during
all of 1998. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index also rose 1.77 percent
Monday, but remains 4.1 percent below its high reached on July 16.
</P>
<P>
   The turnabout in investor mood comes after weeks of
directionless and confused stock trading. Having peaked in
mid-July, most of the market indexes fell as investors grew
concerned that rising commodity prices and labor costs as well as
strong economic growth around the world would push the Fed to take
a more aggressive stance on rates.
</P>
<P>
   A slight weakening in the dollar, which could push up prices of
imported goods and make U.S. stocks less attractive abroad, was
also a worry.
</P>
<P>
   Traders feared that the Fed's quarter-point increase in rates on
June 30 would be followed by similar increases at its meetings in
August and October, increases aimed at cooling an economy in danger
of overheating. But over the last week or so, a consensus started
to build that a quarter-point increase on Tuesday might be enough.
</P>
<P>
   Helping investors to regain optimism was a trickle of economic
data indicating that inflation was still under control and that
growth in output was slowing. Bond traders, hypervigilant for
inflation harbingers, have liked what they have seen in the numbers
as well. The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond was unchanged
Monday at 5.985 percent, down from 6.277 percent Aug. 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interest rates have stopped going up,'' said Alan Kral, vice
president at Trevor, Stewart, Burton &AMP; Jacobsen Inc., a money
management firm in New York, ``so people can focus on earnings
growth. If we don't have to worry about interest rates, the market
ought to do well, and people are getting a jump on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kral noted that by all accounts, third-quarter earnings at U.S.
companies will be robust, thanks mostly to rebounding global
economies in Europe, the Pacific Rim and Latin America. The results
will look especially good against the third quarter of 1998, when
economic crises in Latin America, Russia and the Far East dragged
down corporate profits. A slight weakening in the dollar will also
contribute to better sales of U.S. goods abroad.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, most economists believe that corporate earnings
will rise about 15 percent in the second half of 1999 from the
second half of 1998. If fulfilled, those predictions could become
fuel for even more stock-market gains.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the recent view among investors could quickly turn to
ash if economic data in coming weeks showed an economy that was a
bit too heated.
</P>
<P>
   Traders will pore over this week's news releases _ particularly
the growth rate of orders for refrigerators, washing machines and
other durable goods, out on Wednesday, and the revised gross
domestic product growth for June, out on Thursday. If either number
comes far afield of investors' expectations, inflation fears could
be reignited.
</P>
<P>
   And it is a fact of life on Wall Street that investors always
believe immediately before a Fed meeting at which rates are
expected to be increased that the increase will be the last.
Indeed, in June, after Greenspan and some of his colleagues had
warned investors that rates were likely to rise, most analysts said
that increase would be the last for a while.
</P>
<P>
   But stock investors seem now to believe that the Fed is simply
trying to slow the economy, and betting that it will not go too far
and bring it to a halt. As they grow more comfortable in their view
of the Fed's abilities to fine-tune the economy, they may be happy
to buy stocks even if they cannot rule out a third rate increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that we're going to have a U.S. economy that stays
stronger for longer and that we will be in a longer tightening
cycle,'' said Stefan Abrams, chief investment officer, asset
allocation, at Trust Company of the West in New York. ``But people
should not confuse a longer tightening cycle with a draconian body
slam by the Fed. They're not trying to break the back of inflation;
all they're trying to do is keep us on a path to a soft landing.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's move in the Dow came as many on Wall Street were on
vacation. Some 683 million shares traded hands on the New York
Stock Exchange, a respectable if not torrid day. The Nasdaq
Composite rose 71 points, or 2.69 percent on the day.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One reason investors have become more confident about guessing
the Fed's behavior is that the bond market has become a leading
indicator in recent years. In the 1970s and early '80s, the Fed
would move, and bond traders would follow.
</P>
<P>
   No longer. In the spring of 1997, just before the global
economic crisis began and well after bond yields had begun to rise,
the Fed raised rates. By the fall of 1998, bond yields had plunged
when the Fed finally eased to help stem the growing panic in world
markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``My answer to what do you think the Fed is going to do is look
at what the bond market has already done,'' said James Paulsen,
chief investment officer at Wells Capital Management in
Minneapolis. ``The real interest-rate setter in this country is the
bond market. They speak daily and they speak clearly. If there was
an inflation problem, they have addressed it.''
</P>
<P>
   With inflation fears on the shelf, at least momentarily,
investors' focus will shift to identifying which industry sectors
or stock-market groups will be the top performers going forward.
</P>
<P>
   The move on Monday in the Dow average, which has twice the
percentage gain of the S&AMP;P 500 so far this year, continues a broad
shift in market leadership away from the kind of high-powered
growth stocks that investors have favored for the last five years
and into more mundane manufacturing companies that have been much
less popular. Drug companies, for example, are down over 5 percent
this year, while the chemical sector is up more than 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Even as investors celebrated on Monday, market strategists
warned that a weak dollar remained a concern. ``The dollar is the
one thing that keeps me awake at night,'' Abrams said. ``It has
been the linchpin of the stock market for the past five years. If
the weakness is contained, we're OK. If it gets out of hand, it's a
huge negative for interest rates and stock prices.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
