<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT ACTS TO REMOVE CLIP ART IMAGE OFFENSIVE TO BLACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAMES BANDLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Students headed back to school will get a nasty surprise when
they search for ``monkey'' on one of Microsoft's key educational
software programs.
</P>
<P>
   A search function of the Clip Art tool in the Teaching and
Learning with Microsoft CD-ROM returns several images of monkeys.
But it also returns an image of a black couple posed on monkey
bars.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft calls the incident unfortunate and unintended,
explaining that the image of the couple comes up because the
program reads ``monkey bars'' as a match for monkey.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter of apology sent this summer to educators, Microsoft
called the juxtaposition ``inappropriate and offensive,'' and said
the company was taking swift action to deal with the matter.
</P>
<P>
   The same racially charged match was discovered this spring on
the company's Publisher 1998 software, which is sold separately or
included in Microsoft Office 97 and other applications.
</P>
<P>
   A Microsoft spokesman said the company learned four weeks ago
that its ``Teaching and Learning'' CD contained the offending
clips. The program, which debuted this spring, is distributed to
schools with a $4.95 shipping and handling fee around the nation. A
Microsoft spokeswoman said 75,000 copies were affected.
</P>
<P>
   A San Diego man has already filed a lawsuit againt Microsoft
over the Publisher 1998 software. John Elijah, 32, is seeking
$75,000 in damages, saying he was humiliated after co-workers
showed him the images.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's troubles offer a lesson in the perils of computer
search functions. Microsoft's Clip Art Gallery allows users to
search for images that can be pasted onto newsletters, posters, and
other documents.
</P>
<P>
   The program searches for partial matches as well as complete
matches of search words.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the word ``dog'' returns images of dogs and
hotdogs. The search word ``monkey'' returns seven images of
monkeys, and an image of the black couple posing on ``monkey
bars.'' The software linked the photo of the couple with several
keywords including ``playground,'' ``couples,'' ``recreation,'' and
``monkey bars.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to note that the Clip Art Gallery includes
several other photos of this same African-American couple as part
of Microsoft's commitment to diversity in our clip art images,''
the apology letter said. None of these other photos, Microsoft
said, show the monkey-bar equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft says it discovered the problem through its own
testing, and found no evidence of malicious intent by the vendor
who worked on the Clip Art feature or anyone at Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, they were concerned,'' said Lisa Wolfe, a
public-relations specialist with Grant-Jacboy in Chicago that
represents Microsoft. ``They wanted to take steps to resolve the
problem as quickly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe said only a handful of educators had called Microsoft. She
said all of the calls were in response to the company's letter.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft will send a free replacement CD to customers who
request one. The company's Web site offers information on how to
remove the offending clips. In its letter, Microsoft announced it
was instituting a new process for reviewing its Clip Art gallery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal with these images and others was to ensure that the
images in our Clip Art Gallery are multi-cultural, and contribute
to greater ease of use for our customers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
