<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6995 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SMITHSONIAN-FOIE-GRAS     08-23 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMITHSONIAN-FOIE-GRAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANIMAL RIGHTS PROTESTS LEAD SMITHSONIAN TO CANCEL FOIE GRAS
TASTING  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Yielding to protests from animal rights
organizations and celebrities like Sir John Gielgud and Bea Arthur,
the Smithsonian Institution on Monday canceled a panel discussion
and tasting of foie gras, the fattened liver of a duck or goose,
that had been scheduled for next month.
</P>
<P>
   The animal rights advocates celebrated. The producer of the foie
gras at issue called himself a victim of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   David Umansky, the spokesman for the Smithsonian, said the 133
people who had bought tickets, at $25 or $30 apiece, would get
refunds. He said the Smithsonian had canvassed them before deciding
on the cancellation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We received messages of protest,'' Umansky said. ``Some of
them were of a tenor that led to the decision that we should talk
to the ticket holders and get their opinions.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether the protests had taken the form of threats,
Umansky declined to answer. But he did say, ``Some were way over
the top.''
</P>
<P>
   The foie gras program, one of a long-running series that raises
money for the Smithsonian and provides a setting for authors to
sell their books, was the first ever canceled by the Smithsonian,
Umansky said.
</P>
<P>
   The decision led Michael Ginor, owner of Hudson Valley Foie Gras
in the Catskill community of Ferndale, N.Y., and author of ``Foie
Gras ... A Passion,'' to complain of the protesters: ``What these
people are doing are terrorist acts. They intimidate. They use
means that are close to terrorists but without the blood.''
</P>
<P>
   When it became known that the program would be an occasion for
Ginor to promote his book, which will be published next month by
Wylie, organizations including People for the Ethical Treatment of
Animals and the Humane Society of the United States complained that
a scientific organization like the Smithsonian should not allow
itself to be identified with the production of foie gras, which
involves the force-feeding of ducks and geese to make their livers
swell.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Arthur said in a letter to the Smithsonian that she was not
a vegetarian but that the treatment of ducks and geese in the
production of foie gras ``would be shocking to any meat eater.''
</P>
<P>
   Gielgud wrote to the Smithsonian that he was ``extremely
distressed'' that it was planning the foie gras event. He
complained that foie gras production involved thrusting long metal
pipes down the birds' throats and forcing ``two to three pounds of
corn mixture into their stomachs'' three times a day for four
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Reached at his office in Great Neck, N.Y., Ginor (pronounced
ghee-NOR) maintained that much of what Gielgud had said was
incorrect. The pipes that are used, Ginor said, are not metal but
plastic, and are not long; the largest are six inches, he said, and
are held in the bird for one and a half seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not painful, and it is not distressing,'' Ginor said,
offering as proof that ``when a person comes to feed them, they
come to the feeders.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael McGraw, the spokesman for People for the Ethical
Treatment of Animals, denied that his organization had ever engaged
in terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made no threats whatsoever,'' McGraw said. ``We would
most likely dress up as ducks or geese and hold up signs.''
</P>
<P>
   Ginor disputed that, saying, ``It's a great shame to succumb to
stuff like this, like succumbing to a terrorist hijacking of a
plane.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
