A7000 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-CALIF-GAMBLING-800&AMP;AD     08-23 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-GAMBLING-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA COURT BLOCKS EXPANSION OF INDIAN GAMBLING INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Nev.)  (mk) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Throwing up a major roadblock to California Indian
tribes' efforts to build a gambling empire to rival Las Vegas, the
state Supreme Court on Monday overturned a ballot measure that
would have allowed expansion of legalized gambling on Indian lands
here.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, known as Proposition 5, passed last November with
63 percent of the vote after a $100 million spending campaign _ a
national record. The campaign pitted the state's $1.4 billion
tribal gambling industry against Nevada casino operators, who
feared the measure had the potential to clear the way for new
casinos that could draw thousands of customers away from Las Vegas.
The new law had been on hold pending the outcome of the court case.
</P>
<P>
   In its 6-1 ruling, the state Supreme Court held that by seeking
to legalize card games like ``21'' and slot-machine-style
videogames, Proposition 5 had improperly skirted the state
constitution's prohibitions against such games. Because Proposition
5 was a statute ``and because in a conflict between statutory and
constitutional law, the constitution must prevail, we conclude
Proposition 5's authorization of casino gambling is invalid and
inoperative,'' the majority wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling raised the prospect that some of the lucrative tribal
casinos that have sprouted around the state in recent years might
soon risk being shut down.
</P>
<P>
   Indian tribes, anticipating Monday's decision and determined to
protect their network of cavernous casinos around the state, have
already begun collecting signatures to place a new measure on the
ballot in the state's presidential primary election in March; the
measure would amend the state constitution to allow casino
gambling. But the casinos' legal status in the meantime is in
doubt, since a federal appeals court ruled last January that if
Proposition 5 was invalidated, some 10 tribes that have been the
subject of a federal case would have just two weeks to cease casino
operations. Monday's ruling does not take effect for at least 30
days, so the tribes and state officials have about six weeks to
reach a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We anticipate that the Indians will follow the law,'' said
Thom Mrozek, a spokesman for the U. S. attorney's office here,
which has been trying to shut down about 10 tribal casinos, most of
them in the Palm Springs area. The U.S. attorney contends that the
tribes have been operating thousands of slot machines and other
games illegally, without a valid compact with the state as required
by federal law.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gray Davis, who remained neutral on the ballot measure last
year, has been trying to negotiate compacts with tribes running
casinos since he took office this year. In a statement Monday
afternoon, he said he was determined to find ``a constitutionally
acceptable means'' of allowing Indian gambling, in light of last
year's popular vote in favor of Proposition 5. He said he would
work with the state Legislature and the tribes to that end.
</P>
<P>
   ``In addition to the benefits to the tribes themselves,'' the
governor said, ``I am mindful of the fact that some 16,000
Californians, currently employed by Indian gaming, may lose their
source of employment if we cannot respond to this challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Penny Le Doux, a spokeswoman for a group of California residents
who had sued to overturn Proposition 5, backed by Nevada casinos
and joined by the Hotel Employees &AMP; Restaurant Employees
International Union, said she was ``delighted'' by Monday's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it does is ratify everything that we have said for so
long, that it's unconstitutional,'' Ms. LeDoux said in a telephone
interview from her home in Shingle Springs, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   But Richard Milanovich, a spokesman for the gambling tribes and
chairman of the Agua Caliente Indians, who operate a spa and casino
in Palm Springs, said the tribes would press ahead with their
efforts to pass a constitutional amendment, and perhaps appeal some
aspects of Monday's ruling to the U. S. Supreme Court. The
California Supreme Court is the final arbiter of issues relating to
the state constitution, but Indian gambling is also regulated by
federal law, and lawyers said that some aspects of the ruling might
be subject to federal judicial review.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have a close look at that,'' said Mark Epstein,
a lawyer for the tribes.
</P>
<P>
   Indian gambling has been a subject of controversy in California
for most of the decade, as long-impoverished tribes sought new
revenues by moving beyond traditional bingo parlors to operate card
games and video slot machines.
</P>
<P>
   But under the federal Indian Gaming Regulatory Act of 1988,
tribes are allowed to offer games like ``21'' or slot machines only
after negotiating compacts with states, and former Gov. Pete Wilson
refused to open negotiations with any tribe that was already
offering such games, which he contended were illegal.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The tribes sponsored Proposition 5 last year and spent heavily
to pass it. From the beginning, there were doubts about the
measure's constitutionality, but fewer voter signatures were needed
to qualify a statute for the ballot than to qualify a proposed
constitutional amendment, and the tribes were eager to resolve the
matter.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 5 essentially required the state to enter into a
compact allowing gambling with any tribe that wanted one. The
tribes have long contended that their slot machines and card games
did not constitute Nevada-style casino gambling as defined by the
1984 state constitutional amendment, because players do not bet
against the house but against a pool of other players, with no
chance for the house to win.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday's ruling held for the first time that the tribal
casinos' card games and slot machines do not operate as lotteries,
in which casinos distribute fixed winnings without any interest in
the outcome, but in fact more like a traditional casino bank,
because the amount of money the players' pool pays out depends on
whether individual bets are won or lost.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
