<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT HITS THE GOLF COURSE, AND THE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDGARTOWN, Mass. _ Under a cloudless azure sky, President
Clinton took to the golf course Monday, attended a fund-raiser for
a local hospital on Monday night and dined again with friends. But
the real news from his vacation compound was the release of the
list of books that the president is delving into.
</P>
<P>
   A voracious and eclectic reader, Clinton has made the release of
his summer reading list something of an annual rite. It provides a
glimpse into what the first reader is thinking about, and it is one
of the few nuggets of news that reporters covering him can count
on, since most of his vacation activities are screened from public
view.
</P>
<P>
   The president has no fewer than 12 titles on this year's list
for his 10 days on Martha's Vineyard. They include a book on the
right-wing media, an exploration of risk, and a novel about two
bright young couples who form a lifelong friendship.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear how many of the books the president will read
from cover to cover, but the presidential endorsement is becoming a
coveted status symbol among authors, who can see their book sales
soar, particularly among those who might encounter the president
during vacation and want to share his interests.
</P>
<P>
   Giving out the list was the main point of Monday's 21-minute
briefing held here by Joe Lockhart, the president's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Other topics included a question on whether Clinton's fund
raising for his wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton, and her expected
Senate campaign, might interfere with his fund-raising obligations
to Vice President Gore, who is seeking to succeed him. Some in
Gore's camp have expressed concern that Clinton's time and energy
will be funneled into Mrs. Clinton's campaign, leaving less for
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he sees these things as mutually exclusive, and
he looks forward to helping all Democrats,'' Lockhart said. But he
also said that after Labor Day, the president's fund raising for
Mrs. Clinton would probably subside.
</P>
<P>
   As Lockhart spoke, Clinton was out on the links at the Farm Neck
Golf Club. He took a mulligan on his first shot, which veered off
course. ``Oh, I killed it,'' he shouted.
</P>
<P>
   He was playing with Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., whose pending
retirement has fueled concern in the party that he could be
replaced by a Republican, Gov. Christie Whitman of New Jersey. This
could seriously weaken the Democratic ranks in the Senate. But
Lockhart said Monday that he thought any pleas to Lautenberg to
reconsider had ceased.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, meanwhile, was at home. Clinton said Monday night
at the hospital fund-raiser, which was held conveniently at the
golf course, that his wife was ``a little under the weather,'' but
he did not elaborate. ``I want her to get well because she has a
rigorous schedule ahead of her,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Between his golf and his many social soirees _ he has dined out
every night since he arrived and has attended two fund-raisers for
his wife _ Clinton appears to be devoting much of his time to
reading.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the usual briefing books and assorted mysteries are three
eye-catching titles. Perhaps the most controversial is ``Waves of
Rancor: Tuning in the Radical Right,'' by Robert Hillard and
Michael Keith (M.E. Sharpe, 1999). The book has a giant swastika on
the cover. Studs Terkel, reviewing the book, said it revealed the
``hate-mongering'' of the extreme right wing, which has disguised
itself in the form of talk-show hosts.
</P>
<P>
   Another on the list is ``Against the Gods: The Remarkable Story
of Risk,'' by Peter L. Bernstein (John Wiley &AMP; Sons, 1998). A
synopsis by the publisher says the author ``explains the origin of
risk management _ the basics of probability, sampling, regression
to the mean, game theory, and rational versus irrational
decision-making.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on the list is a 1991 novel by Wallace Stegner called
``Crossing to Safety,'' about two couples who meet during the
Depression and remain friends for life. A synopsis on Amazon.com
calls it ``the poignant story of two couples who form a lifelong
friendship, and the loyalties, celebrations, tragedies, and
conflicts that afflict them as individuals and as families.''
</P>
<P>
   The other books on Clinton's list are ``A Clearing in the
Distance: Frederick Law Olmsted and America in the Nineteenth
Century,'' by Witold Rybczynski (1999); ``Cold Hit,'' a thriller by
Linda A. Fairstein (1999); ``Dark Lady,'' a suspense novel by
Richard North Patterson (1999); ``The Diving Bell and the
Butterfly: A Memoir of Life and Death,'' by Jean-Dominique Bauby
(1998); ``Guns, Germs and Steel: The Fate of Human Societies,'' by
Jared Diamond (1999); ``Just Revenge,'' by Alan Dershowitz (1999);
``The Last Patrician: Bobby Kennedy and the End of American
Aristocracy,'' by Michael Knox Beran (1998); ``Memoirs of
Hadrian,'' by Marguerite Yourcenar (1951); and ``Prayers for
Rain,'' by Dennis Lehane (1999).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
