<SLUG> BC-LOCKERBIE-VICTIMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTOR TELLS LOCKERBIE RELATIVES HE'LL KEEP TRIAL NONPOLITICAL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Scotland, the Netherlands, Md., N.J., Va.)  (rk) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ About 200 relatives of people killed in the bombing
of Pan Am Flight 103 over Scotland nearly 11 years ago were assured
Monday by Scottish officials that the two suspects would be
prosecuted vigorously and without regard to political
considerations.
</P>
<P>
   The assurances, by Scotland's senior law officer, Lord Hardie,
came at a meeting arranged by the Justice Department to brief the
relatives on the case. The two suspects, both Libyan intelligence
officers, are to go on trial in February in the Netherlands. The
bombing, on Dec. 21, 1988, killed 270 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've assured the family members that there have been no
deals,'' Lord Hardie said. But several relatives of victims were
skeptical. ``I'll be convinced of that when I see it in court,''
said Rosemary Wolfe of Alexandria, Va., whose stepdaughter, Miriam
Wolfe, died on the plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm praying that the prosecutors are totally independent,''
said Kathleen Flynn of Montville, N.J. She and her husband, John,
lost a son when the Boeing 747 blew up over Scotland, killing the
259 people on board and 11 others in Lockerbie village.
</P>
<P>
   No relatives questioned the seriousness or integrity of Lord
Hardie or the prosecutors. But some said their feelings had been
hardened by more than a decade of grief, followed by what they see
as official foot-dragging. They also suspect that there is a desire
by some countries to let the atrocity fade into the past so
business as usual can resume with Libya, which is rich in oil.
</P>
<P>
   The suspects, Abdel Basset Ali al-Megrahi and Lamen Khalifa
Fhimah, are to be tried under Scottish law at Camp Zeist, 30 miles
southeast of Amsterdam. The pair were accused in an indictment
returned in U.S. Federal Court in November 1991. The dead included
189 Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators concluded that the two men had arranged to have a
bomb, concealed in a portable cassette player, put aboard a plane
in Malta and eventually transferred to the 747 in London just
before takeoff.
</P>
<P>
   Britain and the United States agreed to a trial in the
Netherlands, under Scottish law, in part to get the Libyan leader,
Col. Moammar Gadhafi, to turn over the suspects.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has continued to impose sanctions on Libya and
regards it as an outlaw country. The United Nations recently
suspended its sanctions and is weighing whether to lift them
permanently. And Britain announced recently that it was resuming
normal relations with Libya now that the two suspects are to face
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Bernstein of Bethesda, Md., whose husband, Michael,
died on Flight 103, said she was ``somewhat reassured'' by Lord
Hardie. But Susan Cohen of Cape May Court House, N.J., whose
daughter, Theodora, was killed, said Monday's session ``has done
nothing to sweep away my concerns.'' She said she still wonders
what prosecutors will do if the evidence points much higher than
the two suspects.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Gadhafi is thriving at the end of this, I don't consider it
justice,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
