<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRET-STORM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRET CAUSES LITTLE DAMAGE AS STORM BREEZES INTO TEXAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trim) 
 
By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
and ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hurricane Bret proved more bluster than bite Monday as the
largest hurricane to hit Texas in 20 years weakened into a tropical
storm that so far has caused no reported deaths, major injuries or
extensive damage.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its early designation Sunday as a ``major disaster''
area, the seven-county region sustained relatively minor damage,
with costs expected mostly from clearing debris and organizing
widespread evacuations, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   By late afternoon, emergency preparedness officials had agreed
to reduce the number of Texas National Guardsmen on alert from
1,600 to 450.
</P>
<P>
   In Laredo, local officials took the unusual step of declaring a
state of emergency in anticipation of imminent danger, requiring
businesses to shut their doors by 6 p.m. CDT and closing roads and
three international bridges, said Jack Colley, assistant director
of the emergency management division of the Texas Department of
Public Safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to do the reasonable and smart thing and that's
prepare for it,'' said Colley, noting that heavy rains remained
likely for the town on the banks of the Rio Grande. ``It's the
right thing to do. Laredo's flood-prone because it's very, very
flat.''
</P>
<P>
   Fears of devastating flooding in South Texas, however, had
already begun to subside as the eye of the storm headed northwest
between Laredo and Eagle Pass en route to Mexico, according to the
National Weather Service regional office in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday or Thursday, the service predicted, the system
could wind its way into the Big Bend area.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that prevented the storm from causing
significant damage was it moved onshore over the least populated
county along the coast, Kenedy County, '' said meteorologist
Constantine Pashos.
</P>
<P>
   Had Sunday's storm struck just 40 miles north in Corpus Christi
or at the Brownsville-Harlingen area 50 to 60 miles south,
consequences could have been considerably more severe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a little bit of heavy rain and gusty winds, but as
of now, no serious flooding,'' Pashos said of the storm's progress
as it pushed northwestward Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll get some showers and bands of rain and thunderstorms
tonight and tomorrow,'' Pashos said of the Laredo area. ``Nothing
out of the ordinary in respect to tropical systems.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, against predictions of destruction Sunday when the
powerful hurricane appeared heading for Corpus Christi, President
Clinton declared the seven-county South Texas area a ``major
disaster'' after Texas Gov. George W. Bush appealed for federal
help.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very fortunate in Texas that Hurricane Bret did not
directly hit a major population area, and that so far, no deaths or
serious injuries have been reported,'' Bush said. ``The damage
could have been much worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the storm still posed a threat as night fell, however,
Bush warned ``all Texans in the affected areas to take the threat
of flooding seriously, to continue to pay close attention to this
storm, and to follow the advice and directions of local
officials.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Health Commissioner William ``Reyn'' Archer III warned
that an outbreak of mosquito-carry dengue fever, causing severe
flulike symptoms that has struck 16 in South Texas so far, posed a
major health threat. He urged cleanup crews to watch for containers
with standing water, perfect breeding grounds for the
disease-carrying insects.
</P>
<P>
   Corpus Christi emerged virtually unscathed, but before leaving
the Coastal Bend, as if in a last gasp, Hurricane Bret backhanded
the city with a band of heavy rain and gusting winds early Monday
morning, snapping branches, uprooting trees and flooding city
streets.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of low-lying neighborhoods who chose to wait out the
storm may have gone to sleep believing the worst had passed, but
awoke to find streets flooded with several inches of water.
</P>
<P>
   But in all, the floodwaters were little more than an
inconvenience. By 9 a.m., evacuees, primarily those with beachfront
homes on north Padre Island, were urged to return home. By noon
Monday, the city had closed its emergency operations center and
little remained to remind residents that a Category 4 hurricane,
packing 140 mph winds, had threatened their homes and community 24
hours earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Officials estimated damages at only $100,000, and the storm
caused no major structural damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were fortunate that the eye passed 50 miles south of here,
but it was also fortunate that we trained and prepared as much as
we do,'' said Corpus Christi City Manager David Garcia. ``It's easy
to be lucky when you're prepared and trained.''
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 25,000 to 30,000 people, including most of the
island's 15,000 residents, evacuated the city Saturday and early
Sunday, clogging Interstate 37 as they headed for high ground
elsewhere. An estimated 7,000 residents went to Red Cross shelters
in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Some, like Rebekah Smith, 18, and her family, opted to stay in
Corpus Christi. On Monday, Smith and her cousins were sweeping and
bagging leaves off the sidewalk and street in front of their
grandmother's home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kinda worried, but it took a turn and there was nothing
to worry about any more,'' Smith said, adding that she was thankful
she was sweeping leaves rather than splintered pieces of her
grandmother's home.
</P>
<P>
   By early afternoon, most floodwaters had receded and sporadic
power outages had been restored. Central, Power and Light, which
provides the city electrical power, received 3,900 calls by 8 p.m.
Sunday from customers who had lost power.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of power lines down, we had power interrupted to
our waste water treatment plant, we had some emergency back up
generators damaged, but we were able to repair all that and as of
noon today everything is up and operating,'' Garcia said.
</P>
<P>
   Nueces County, where Corpus Christi is located, is one of the
counties Bush asked to be declared a disaster area for federal
relief. Though the city incurred little damage, Garcia said he
hopes some relief is offered to offset the cost of responding to
the emergency.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a major emergency, we mobilized a lot of resources to
deal with it, and the storm was clearly a threat and a hazard to
the community and the public safety,'' Garcia said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On gulf shores, it was hard to find any sign a major storm had
passed near by.
</P>
<P>
   The string of hotels along North Padre Island were untouched,
with the exception of a few overturned trash cans and patio
furniture blown across parking lots. There was no visible beach
erosion along the North Padre sea wall, with wooden steps leading
down to the beach still firmly in place and even metal trash cans
still standing on the beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were fortunate,'' said Jim Urban, a 43-year-old civil
engineer and developer who arrived early Monday to begin removing
boards from his harbor-front home in Port Aransas. ``I drove around
town and I saw a few signs down. We're real lucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother-in-law stayed here all last night and the tides
never got as high as the winter tides that cover our pier,'' Urban
said.
</P>
<P>
   He quickly hauled a ``Jolly Rogers'' pirate flag up the mast of
his ``Cajun Queen,'' a 38-foot Louisiana oyster boat converted into
a party skiff that floated unscathed behind his home. In the
adjacent slip, Urban's 34-foot offshore power boat sat securely on
hoists, untouched as was virtually every other boat in Port
Aransas' large harbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was my biggest concern, the storm surge bringing the boat
up on the docks and through the house,'' Urban said, gesturing to
his three-story home behind the pier. ``They kept saying a 15-foot
storm surge and we got a 15-inch tide, which is good.''
</P>
<P>
   Urban weathered the storm in Corpus Christi, a decision he made
due to his previous hurricane experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in school in Corpus Christi during hurricane Celia and
stayed there and watched the house crumble around us, and I vowed
never to stay again.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of streets, intersections and yards were flooded in
Port Aransas early Monday, but City Manager Tom Brooks said there
was no damage to the town of 3,000 full-time residents. Police were
stationed at the entrance to the town, allowing only residents to
enter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had a single report of anything, and positively no
flooding of businesses or residences. The only damage I'm aware of
is the roof over the cafeteria portion of the high school collapsed
at 2:30 yesterday (Sunday),'' due to heavy rains, Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say overall we came out better than expected.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
