<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-CORPSES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BODIES POSE NO DANGER OF DISEASE, DOCTORS SAY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The thousands of unburied corpses in Turkey's earthquake zone
may be traumatic for the survivors but they do not pose any danger
of an epidemic of infectious diseases, public health experts said
Monday. Nor is there any evidence of increased disease in the past
week, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dead bodies do not create diseases among survivors,'' Dr.
Michel Thieren, a medical officer in the World Health
Organization's department of emergency and humanitarian action,
said in a telephone interview. ``Natural disasters do not import
diseases that are not already present in the affected area.''
</P>
<P>
   WHO, a unit of the United Nations, is speaking out to correct
misinformation about the health hazards of disasters ``because
myths are about to create panic in the field and divert the
resources and the assistance to those who really need them,''
Thieren said.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit said, ``Perhaps the
greatest problem now facing us is that of epidemics.''
</P>
<P>
   But Thieren's comments disputing this were echoed by other
health officials, who said Turkey's greatest public health needs
were to monitor the incidence of infectious diseases and restore
basic water and sanitation services.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Stephen M. Ostroff, the acting deputy director of the
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, a federal agency in
Atlanta, said, ``There are a lot of good reasons for not leaving
bodies sitting there, but the highest priority is try to keep the
living as healthy as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Serge Manoncourt, a medical adviser to Doctors Without
Borders, said that the threat of epidemics ``was in people's
imagination'' and that epidemics ``almost never occurred unless
there was massive water and food contamination.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Haroutune Armenian, an epidemiologist at Johns Hopkins
School of Public Health who has dealt with disasters in Lebanon,
said, ``There is no evidence that bodies in an environment like
this would cause any disease on their own.''
</P>
<P>
   The experts said they knew of no published articles documenting
the hazards of dead bodies. ``It is information that is passed from
one generation to another, just as the misconceptions about health
hazards from disasters are passed from disaster to disaster,''
Armenian said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Eric Noji, an expert for the United Nations who has been
reporting to WHO from Turkey for the last four days, told the
agency that sporadic cases of illness are occurring now as they did
before the earthquake, Thieren said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should not correlate occurrence of sporadic cases to the
natural disaster which has occurred,'' Thieren said. ``But it seems
that if you have a case of dysentery now, it will be immediately
reported as being an epidemic, which is not true.''
</P>
<P>
   Turkey also needs to resume standard immunization programs for
children, but vaccine programs against diseases like cholera are
not necessary because no cholera has been reported in Turkey in the
past two years, Thieren said.
</P>
<P>
   If there had been many cases of cholera in the quake area, or
many bodies floating in water, then a potential epidemic of cholera
would be a concern. ``Those are exceptional situations that are
definitely not present in the earthquake in Turkey,'' Thieren said.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``If you overimmunize, people develop a false sense of
security and believe they are totally protected when they are not.
To organize a massive immunization campaign against cholera and
things like that would be public health malpractice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
