<SLUG> BC-U.S.-CHINA-TIBET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA URGED TO FREE AMERICAN HURT FLEEING POLICE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (lb) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration is pressing China for
the immediate release of an American who was reported to have
suffered serious spinal injuries after he jumped or fell from a
third-floor window in a confrontation with the Chinese police.
</P>
<P>
   China has said that the 29-year-old American, Daja Mizu Meston,
a Tibetan linguist from Newton, Mass., was injured while trying to
escape police officers in a region of western China where the
government is carrying out a population resettlement project
opposed by human rights groups and environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department said Monday that it had no evidence to
contradict the Chinese account that Meston, who is now in a
hospital under police guard, jumped or fell in his escape attempt
on Aug. 15.
</P>
<P>
   But a department spokesman, James Foley, said, ``We're not
drawing any definitive conclusions about the circumstances of his
injury until we've had an opportunity really to explore the matter
with him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our view is that as soon as his medical condition permits, the
Chinese authorities conclude their actions against him and indeed
release him and allow him to leave the country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Foley said that although Meston was apparently not paralyzed, he
had suffered ``serious back injuries'' and was in urgent need of
specialized spinal treatment outside China.
</P>
<P>
   China has said that the police were seeking to question Meston
and an Australian colleague about their activities in a remote area
of Qinghai province, which is geographically part of the Tibetan
Plateau.
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank is considering a proposal to offer $40 million in
loans to what the Chinese government describes as an anti-poverty
project in the province. The project involves the construction of a
dam and irrigation works, and calls for the relocation of 58,000
impoverished farmers from eastern Qinghai, mostly Han Chinese and
Hui Muslims, to an area farther west in the province populated
largely by ethnic Tibetans.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights activists and environmental groups have charged
that the project is an effort by Beijing to dilute the Tibetan
population in the region and undermine Tibetan culture, and the
World Bank has held off on final approval of the loans in the face
of criticism from the United States and other nations.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian, Gabriel Lafitte, was allowed to leave China last
weekend after the intervention of the Australian government. In
interviews since returning home to Australia, he has expressed fear
for the lives of Meston and a local translator who worked with
them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
