<HEADER>
A7025 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-COLUMN24-C     08-23 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pennant race a novelty among Braves players
 &HT;    By Mark Bradley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Chipper Jones has been a world champion but has never
been part of a real pennant race. Andruw Jones has never known a
big-league season that didn't carry past the 162nd game. Ryan
Klesko was a September call-up when last September mattered around
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear people say that we've never been in a pennant race,''
Tom Glavine said, and those people are correct. Most of these
Braves haven't, at least not as Braves. Not since 1993 has this
franchise played a truly significant regular-season game after
school re-opens. Not since 1993 have the cold fingers of pressure
been felt before October.
</P>
<P>
   A strike halted the 1994 season on Aug. 12. Over the next four
seasons the Braves were as dominant as a latter-day baseball team
can be. From 1995 through 1998, their average lead on Aug. 23 was
11 games. Not once in four Augusts or Septembers has this team come
to work knowing that tomorrow could find it in second place.
</P>
<P>
   But Aug. 23, 1999, was different. The Braves began the day
leading the Mets by a half-game in the NL East, two games ahead of
Cincinnati in the wild-card standings. The Reds were in town for
the first of three games. The Mets were playing Houston, which
stood a half-game ahead of Cincy in the Central. In the course of
three days a flurry of shuffling could be done. Or everything could
stay status quo. In a pennant race you never know, which is why
pennant races are both hated and loved by those involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're fun as long as they end good,'' said Glavine, who
hasn't been through one that didn't. In 1991 the Braves chased the
Dodgers for two months and pulled ahead to stay on the final
weekend, clinching the West on the season's penultimate day. In
1993 it took longer still, the Braves having to beat Colorado in
the 162nd game _ Glavine was the winning pitcher _ and wait to see
if the Giants would lose to L.A. They did.
</P>
<P>
   Even now it's hard to say which chase was sweeter. ``Ninety-one
was totally unexpected, an electrifying year,'' Glavine said. ``But
'93, coming from 14 games behind'' _ actually only 10; see how
races blur into legend? _ ``was gratifying, too.'' And those
pursuits, lest we forget, came without a safety net. There were no
wild cards then, another indication of how long ago it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to win our division those years,'' Glavine said. In '93
the Braves and Giants finished with the two best records in
baseball, yet only Atlanta qualified for postseason. This time
there are four teams tracking three spots. This time one runner-up
will advance. This time the scoreboard-watching will be
three-pronged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at the Mets first,'' Glavine said. ``Our primary focus
is still to win the division. But then you look at Houston and
Cincinnati, and you're constantly trying to figure out what we
want: Is it better if Houston wins and Cincinnati loses? It gets
kind of confusing.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the uncertainty comes this bit of clarity: Pennant races
are never boring. No Brave will be pushing the snooze button on
this September. ``You'd like to win by a comfortable margin,''
Glavine said, ``but this has added some excitement. And that's not
a bad thing around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Bradley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
