<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-STORM-1STLD-WRITETHRU-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREES HARDEST HIT BY HURRICANE BRET IN RURAL TEXAS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (subs to correct spelling of `Cafe' in 7th graf)   By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARITA, Texas _ If there is such a thing as a perfect spot for a
hurricane to come ashore, Kenedy County might be it. The flat,
green pastures are filled with wild oaks and mesquite instead of
shopping centers and subdivisions. There is not a store, restaurant
or gas station in this county called home by only 460 people.
</P>
<P>
   But if you are one of those 460, perfect is not the right word
at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all make jokes about it,'' J.A. Garcia, a county judge,
said inside the darkened county courthouse as a thunderstorm
crackled overhead Monday afternoon. ``There are people who are
living here.''
</P>
<P>
   On the day after Hurricane Bret slowly pushed ashore onto the
South Texas coastline, people awoke to find most buildings still
standing and lives spared; not a single fatality or serious injury
was reported. Initially compared in its potential for destruction
to Hurricane Andrew, this storm picked a path as if it were trying
to avoid people, grinding steadily through the vast ranch lands
halfway between Brownsville and Corpus Christi as it was downgraded
to a tropical storm.
</P>
<P>
   But federal officials were still cautioning Monday that flooding
was possible as the storm moved inland and stalled near Laredo,
dumping heavy amounts of rain. Federal officials closed the three
bridges over the Rio Grande as a precautionary measure, blocking
traffic on both sides of the border. Sporadic flooding was reported
in some Laredo neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   With the storm moving well inland from the South Texas coast,
city officials in Corpus Christi began allowing evacuated residents
to return home late Monday. About 30 miles to the south, more than
16,000 people remained without power, many of them in Kingsville,
as utility workers struggled to restore electricity. Yet for a
region that has not endured a major hurricane in more than 20
years, the fears that prompted thousands of people to evacuate the
coast were replaced by relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were lucky, man,'' said Sam Delarosa, the kitchen manager
of Snoopy's Cafe, located on Padre Island, the barrier island
stretching down the coast. ``Very, very lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials had warned that a tidal surge of 12 feet could cause
flooding inland as well as tremendous damage to the low-lying
barrier islands. But the tidal surge apparently never happened.
From Port Aransas as far south as Malaquite Beach on the Padre
Island National Seashore, the damage was light. ``That tide hasn't
gone up more than a foot or two, and the wind must have just blown
all that water back out into the Gulf,'' Delarosa said.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting behind his desk inside the Kenedy County Courthouse,
Sheriff Rafael M. Cuellar Jr. offered his own theory of why the
storm weakened as it came inland: trees. With nearly 1 million
acres of pasture land, much of it divided between the Kenedy Ranch
and the King Ranch, the two largest ranches in Texas, Kenedy County
is covered in oaks and mesquite and cactus. The terrain is so
desolate, and so stultifying in the summer, that illegal immigrants
walking through the pastures north toward Houston often succumb to
the elements in Kenedy County. Last month, Cuellar said the bodies
of four illegal immigrants were found in the brush dead from the
heat.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The isolation infuses every aspect of life in Kenedy County.
With the closest convenience store a 5-mile drive from Sarita, the
county seat, the sheriff said people become accustomed to living
apart from the modern world. ``Anybody who wants a Coke has to come
up here and get it from the courthouse,'' the sheriff said, noting
toward the drink machine.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But when people learned of the approaching storm, many of them
sought shelter. Most of Sarita's 200 residents gathered in the
local Catholic church or schoolhouse. In the early hours Monday
morning, the storm's worst winds tore through Sarita and
Falfurrias, about 25 miles to the west, uprooting trees and downing
power lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was bad,'' said Cuellar, who keeps a package of chewing
tobacco and three bottles of hot pepper sauce on his desk. He said
everyone in the shelters got along. ``They all knew each other,''
he said. ``More than half of them are related. You don't have
problems like in big cities where they don't want to be close to
one another.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Genho, vice president for livestock for the King Ranch,
said the 825,000-acre ranch lost about 25,000 acres of cotton and
suffered extensive damage to trees and various buildings and
windmills. He said the Norias division in the Ranch, which is
Kenedy County, absorbed the full brunt of the southern eye of the
storm. ``We were extremely blessed,'' Genho said. ``I have been in
a lot of hurricanes having lived in Florida most of my life. When
you get a Class 4 hurricane, that's scary anywhere. There's a lot
of potential for damage.''
</P>
<P>
   At the courthouse in the afternoon, sheriff's deputies returned
after canvassing the county for damages. They had seen many downed
trees, but everyone agreed it could have been far worse.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CAN END HERE.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   All of that was good news for Cuellar.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I need most is to go to sleep because I haven't slept in
two nights,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
