<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7047 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-GEORGE-COLUMN-NYT     08-23 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GEORGE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S ALL EGO: IN BACK SEAT, OR UP FRONT 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Follow this trek.
</P>
<P>
   You grow up a budding star, a gleam in your sport. Little League
coaches insure you are at practices and games and, if necessary,
they transport you daily. Later, while you're still young, fans are
stumbling over one another for your autograph. You are always news
in the local papers and sometimes in national ones.
</P>
<P>
   And you have yet to graduate from high school.
</P>
<P>
   Similar patterns continue throughout college. You are the big
star on campus. The spotlight glares. Your ego is fed full. Back
home, by now, you may even have a street in your name. You are hot
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   And then, one day, you make the pros. The biggest of times.
</P>
<P>
   And guess what? You suddenly become just a player. Only a piece
of the puzzle, because now you are in a stratosphere where a star
of all stars reigns on your team.
</P>
<P>
   Take a back seat. Swallow that ego. Know your place. Contribute,
but do it quietly.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the most difficult transitions in sports: taking
``superstars'' and developing them into, basically, role players.
Getting an athlete who is used to being pampered to accept and then
to flourish under the hammer of a teammate who is the ultimate
superstar, whose light is blinding.
</P>
<P>
   This comes to mind with Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   Who cares anything about the rest of the Cardinals and the Cubs,
respectively? For the last two seasons now, McGwire and Sosa have
been the show, and everyone else on their teams has taken a back
seat. Swallowed his ego. This can be very tiring. Imagine everyone
always asking about the other guy's performances and not yours.
Does this have anything to do with both teams' being total flops
this year?
</P>
<P>
   Some players accept the quieter role.
</P>
<P>
   Others do grudgingly.
</P>
<P>
   Some never do.
</P>
<P>
   I remember talking with players under Bo Schembechler, then the
Michigan football coach, about how he did not want a team of stars.
Players said he would check their numbers on offense, and if
something was ``getting out of hand'' then the ball would begin to
be spread around. Schembechler believed that a star player treated
as bigger than the team would ruin the team. Thus, his chant, his
foundation was always: ``The team! The team! The team!''
</P>
<P>
   Norman Braman, the former Philadelphia Eagles owner, once told
me that he left pro football in part because he could not see
success in wide-sweeping free agency, paying one player $200,000
and then expecting from him effort, work and production equal to
that of a guy standing next to him earning $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Ball, now a defensive lineman for the Cleveland Browns,
said that when he played for Detroit, Barry Sanders ``then and now
was bigger than the Detroit Lions tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   Ball continued: ``He is one of the few athletes who around the
world you can say `Barry' and people would respond with his last
name. I don't know if the Lions ever understood that.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, the Lions players did.
</P>
<P>
   And some of them, privately, are not sad that Sanders left. They
want some of the spotlight that he, without demanding, totally
consumed.
</P>
<P>
   Some Philadelphia 76ers feel that way about Allen Iverson. Some
San Francisco 49ers in past years felt that way about Jerry Rice.
Wonder if any of the Washington Mystics players are a touch bemused
at the mountain of attention awarded the rookie Chamique Holdsclaw?
</P>
<P>
   An essence of pro coaching today is selecting players who are
confident enough in their own stature to take a back seat to
superstars who engulf them. A compelling trait of the best coaches
in the next century will be those who can milk and massage the egos
and confidence of the ``minor players,'' while creating room for
the superstar to be a superstar.
</P>
<P>
   No small task in an industry where egos rule.
</P>
<P>
   Pro athletes today think of themselves as entertainers, and love
aligning themselves with the music and movie industries. Glamour
people all. For some, the brighter the lights, the better. Players
now compete with one another for the best contracts and for the
biggest stature as much as they do for championships.
</P>
<P>
   Where is that fine line where it ruins the team?
</P>
<P>
   Coaches and their organizations have to look under the surface
and find it. It is each player's job, too.
</P>
<P>
   And for many marginal athletes, the origin is not hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   What they envy, they once were.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-99 2131EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
