group called ``AIDS Drugs for Africa'' during a demonstration
outside the Old Executive Office Building in Washington on Monday.
The building houses the offices of aides to Vice President Al Gore.
The demonstration was the latest protest aimed at Gore for his role
in a trade dispute, which centers on a South African law designed
to bring cheaper medicines to the country's millions of poor AIDS
victims. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) BOSTON -- Aug. 23, 1999 -- RESEARCH-CONGRESS, 08-23 --
For years, members of Congress have slipped millions of dollars
into spending bills to build dams and highways back home.
Increasingly, the money is going to academic studies. Defenders of
earmarking, like John Silber, chancellor of Boston University, one
of the largest beneficiaries of such money, say it merely allows
academics to appeal directly to the source of financing. Silber
(Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) UNDATED -- Aug. 23, 1999 -- SUB-BLASS-FASHION-2, 08-23
-- From left, quintessential Bill Blass for a fall evening shown in
1998; Blass often uses fabrics inspired by men's wear for his
women's suits, this one in a gutsy Houndstooth for spring 1996. A
Blass design for fall 1998, a plain cashmere sweater and a fancy
skirt, typical of his dressy sportswear for evening. (Marilynn K.
Yee/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Aug. 23, 1999 -- SCI-HURRICANES-BOS,
08-23 -- Moshe Alamaro, of the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology, with research assistants Amir Mesarwi, rear, and Hilary
Carter in their laboratory. They are standing around a device that
allows them to study what happens in the crucial boundary zone
between air and water, where a hurricane's devastating power
originates. Alamaro and his team are attempting to begin to unlock
the mystery of exactly how hurricanes derive their energy. (Pat
Greenhouse/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) DANBURY, Conn. -- Aug. 23, 1999 -- PUERTO-RICO-BOS,
08-23 -- Alejandrina Torres during an interview earlier this week.
Torres, 60, is serving a 35-year sentence in a federal penitentiary
here for her involvement in an underground guerrilla organization
that bombed US political and military sites between 1973 and 1983
in an attempt to free Puerto Rico from US control. After 16 years
of prison, Torres could walk out soon if she accepts an offer of
from President Clinton. (Tom Herde/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- Aug. 23, 1999 -- GLOBAL-HOLIDAYS, 08-23 --
Paul Spraos, founder of Swaps Monitor Publications Inc. in New
York, which publishes a newsletter covering the exotic world of
interest-rate swaps and other financial derivatives. Since 1992,
Spraos has also produced an international holiday calendar, which
heroically tries to identify all the holidays -- ``bad business
days,'' he calls them, that will occur in more than 100 countries
over the next 100 years. (Don Hogan Charles/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- Aug. 23, 1999 -- BLASS-FASHION, 08-23 --
Fashion designer Bill Blass in his office in Manhattan earlier this
month. Sometime fairly soon, Blass, who turned 77 in June, expects
to sell his $700 million company with its constellation of 40
licenses. More than Ralph Lauren, more than Calvin Klein or anyone
else who came along later, Blass has been the one to more
profoundly influenced American fashion. ``Basically, you've got to
thank Bill Blass for making American fashion respectable,'' said
John Fairchild, the former chairman of Women's Wear Daily.
(Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) COLOMBO, Sri Lanka -- Aug. 23, 1999 --
SRILANKA-TIRUCHELVAM, 08-23 -- Dr. Neelan Thiruchelvam, left, and
his friend Dr. Jayadeva Uyangoda, a political science professor,
during a meeting at the University of Colombo in February. In a
country where there is no vocation more perilous than being a voice
for peace, Tiruchelvam had worked to bring an end to the savage
ethnic conflict that has tormented this lush island nation. Last
month, a suicide bomber blew him up. (Nihal Mahawaduge/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) FALFURRIAS, Texas -- Aug. 23, 1999 -- TEXAS-STORM, 08-23
-- People walk past a service station whose roof was blown off by
Hurricane Bret on Monday. Bret skirted populated areas on Monday
hitting border towns where town residents evacuated or huddled in
shelters. Bret has been downgraded to tropical storm, but the
threat of flood remains. (Bryce Harper/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) UNDATED -- Aug. 23, 1999 -- SCI-SPACE-AUCTION-2, 08-23
-- Christie's East, the New York City auction house, will test the
market for space memorabilia on Sept. 18. One item to be auctioned:
The world's first orbital spacesuit and helmet, developed by the
Soviet space program, along with a full-scale mock-up of the pilot
ejection pilot seat for the Vostok spacecraft. Price estimate:
$200,000-$250,000. (Christie's/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) UNDATED -- Aug. 23, 1999 -- SCI-SPACE-AUCTION-1, 08-23
-- Christie's East, the New York City auction house, will test the
market for space memorabilia on Sept. 18. One item to be auctioned:
Gemini era space suit gloves, made with aluminized nylon, feature
mounting rings at the base that snap into the arms of the suit.
Price estimate: $5,000 to $7,000. (Christie's/New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) IZMIT, Turkey-- Aug. 23, 1999 -- TURKEY-QUAKE, 08-23 --
An aerial view of damage to a residential area taken on Monday from
a U.S. Navy helicopter. With hope of finding survivors of Turkey's
devastating earthquake now all but gone, the Turkish authorities
are turning their attention to caring for those who have survived
and recovering the remains of victims before the outbreak of
disease. (Chief Warrant Officer 2 Seth Rossman/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Aug. 23, 1999 -- SCI-WOMEN-IRONMAN, 08-23 --
Patricia Buttenheim and Ann Snoeyenbos training in New York City
for the Double Ironman - biking 224 miles, swimming 4.8 miles and
running 52 miles. To prepare, each weekday they awaken at 4 a.m. to
cycle 40-plus miles around Central Park, then do an hour and a half
of yoga and strength training before heading off to work; in the
evenings, they run or swim for one to two hours. (Angel Franco/New
York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 23, 1999 -- SCI-JOURNALS-ECON, 08-23
-- In January, the American Medical Association dismissed the top
editor of its journal, Dr. George Lundberg, over a survey about
sex. Although Lundberg's dismissal was ostensibly over an issue of
speeding up publication of old research to fit a political context,
it also reflected the need to satisfy the demands of medical
society's growing publishing empire and an attendant $54.7 million
of advertising a year. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) HOUSTON -- Aug. 23, 1999 -- PLACEBO-SURGERY-2-HNS, 08-23
-- Marvin Gilbert, 67-year-old water-well drill contractor, shows
off his knees. Gilbert, who had a hand grenade in the Korean War
paralyze his left knee, and osteoarthritis in his right knee,
signed up to participate in the placebo study funded by research
unit financed by Baylor College of Medicine and Veterans Affairs.
Only a few days after surgery, Gilbert was walking. ``It didn't
matter. It stopped the pain,'' he said. ``I didn't wonder what it
was.'' (Carlos Antonio Rios/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) HOUSTON -- Aug. 23, 1999 -- PLACEBO-SURGERY-1-HNS, 08-23
-- Orthopedic surgeon Bruce Moseley with a model of the knee.
Moseley, a clinical associate professor at Baylor College of
Medicine, was skeptical about a commonplace operation performed on
the painful knees of older patients. In an unusual, groundbreaking
study, Moseley and other Houston researchers are comparing actual
surgery to phony, or placebo, surgery to see whether the operation
really helps - or if people simply believe it relieves their pain.
(Betty Tichich/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) HOUSTON -- Aug. 23, 1999 -- INS-DEPORT-HNS, 08-23 --
Chip and Laura Gehle with their 7-month-old daughter, Elena. The
Gehle's invited Laura's sister, Graciela Meza, from her home in
Mexico. When Ms. Meza told immigration officials that she would be
caring for niece, the authorities denied her visit. Ms. Meza's
swift deportation came under the terms of a controversial 1996
immigration law giving INS inspectors the power to deport
foreigners from airports and border checkpoints without a hearing.
(Steve Campbell/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) ATLANTA -- Aug. 23, 1999 -- COKE-MUSEUM-COX-2, 08-23 -- A
collection of Coca-Cola marketing memorabilia from the archives of
Coca Cola. Coke's well-organized, 8,000-square-foot basement, which
requires a special elevator and security code to enter, houses
decades-old bottles and cans, and examples of the company's
marketing and advertising campaigns over the past 113 years. (Phil
Skinner/Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) ATLANTA -- Aug. 23, 1999 -- COKE-MUSEUM-COX-1, 08-23 --
Philip Mooney, the archivist for Coca Cola, with some of the
bottles which form part of the company's collection in the
subterranean levels of the company's headquarters. The
well-organized, 8,000-square-foot basement, which requires a
special elevator and security code to enter, houses decades-old
Coke bottles and cans, and examples of the company's marketing and
advertising campaigns over the past 113 years. (Phil
Skinner/Atlanta Journal-Constitution) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) SEATTLE -- Aug. 23, 1999 -- ARTS-CAMP-SPI, 08-20 -- Louis
Husted, 14, uses a stapler as a slide for an electric guitar while
recording a song he has written for a music technology workshop at
The Experience Arts Camp. The program is part community outreach,
part educational extension of Paul Allen's Experience Music
Project, the $100 million-plus interactive multimedia and learning
museum that will open next spring at the Seattle Center. (Dan
DeLong/Seattle Post-Intelligencer Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) POMEROY, Wash. -- Aug. 23, 1999 --
WASHINGTON-DROUGHT-2-SPI, 08-20 -- Garfield County farmer Bill Cox
and his nephew, Ben, examine this year's wheat crop. Cox's wheat
harvest is less than half of his average crop. Unfavorable weather
throughout the growing season, most recently this summer's drought,
has reduced his yield and the quality of the grain. (Paul Joseph
Brown/Seattle Post-Intelligencer Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) POMEROY, Wash. -- Aug. 23, 1999 --
WASHINGTON-DROUGHT-1-SPI, 08-20 -- Walt Neff, who dryland farms in
Franklin County near Pasco, should be getting ready to harvest
wheat. Instead all he has is sun-scorched brown earth. The dryland
farmers, those who farm without benefit of irrigation, are
suffering from a bad winter, spring and now a drought in summer.
(Paul Joseph Brown/Seattle Post-Intelligencer Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BOTLIKH, Russia -- Aug. 23, 1999 --
RUSSIA-DAGESTAN-BOS-4, 08-19 -- A woman calls for the heads of
local Islamic rebels to be cut off last week in the town in
Dagestan, near the Chechen border, controlled by Russian forces.
Russia last week acknowledged that its campaign to suppress an
Islamic rebellion in Dagestan, a province on the Caspian Sea, was
not working, a stark reversal of almost daily assurances that it
would crush the rebels within a week. (Dmitry Shalgonov/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BOTLIKH, Russia -- Aug. 23, 1999 --
RUSSIA-DAGESTAN-BOS-3, 08-19 -- A Russian soldier suffering from
shrapnel wounds in his eyes is helped by a colleage at the airport
prior to his evacuation last week from the region in Russia's
Dagestan province. Russia last week acknowledged that its campaign
to suppress an Islamic rebellion in Dagestan, a province on the
Caspian Sea next to Chechnya, was not working, a stark reversal of
almost daily assurances that it would crush the rebels within a
week. (Dmitry Shalgonov/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BOTLIKH, Russia -- Aug. 23, 1999 --
RUSSIA-DAGESTAN-BOS-2, 08-19 -- A Russian soldier on a hill
overlooking Botlikh last week. Russia last week acknowledged that
its campaign to suppress an Islamic rebellion in Dagestan, a
province on the Caspian Sea next to Chechnya, was not working, a
stark reversal of almost daily assurances that it would crush the
rebels within a week. (Dmitry Shalgonov/Boston Globe Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BOTLIKH, Russia -- Aug. 23, 1999 --
RUSSIA-DAGESTAN-BOS-1, 08-19 -- A pro-Moscow Dagestan volunteer
tries to prevent photographs from being taken of Russian troops at
a checkpoint last week. Russia last week acknowledged that its
campaign to suppress an Islamic rebellion in Dagestan, a province
on the Caspian Sea next to Chechnya, was not working, a stark
reversal of almost daily assurances that it would crush the rebels
within a week. (Dmitry Shalgonov/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
