<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7060 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-MASSACRE-SURVIVOR-COX     08-23 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASSACRE-SURVIVOR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Massacre survivors adapt to new family
 &HT;    By Lyda Longa
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ He sits in the living room of his grandmother's
apartment watching a celebrity game show on TV with his father, his
younger sister and a family friend. Occasionally, the boy, with the
cast and metal pins in his right arm, turns to hisfather and they
share a smile or tease each other about the score.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in new blue jeans, a dark red T-shirt and new sneakers,
he is the picture of the average 12-year-old boy sharing a light
moment with his family after the first day of middle school.
</P>
<P>
   In the kitchen of the northeast Atlanta home, his grandmother
sits before a huge bowl, mixing and mashing giant sweet potatoes
and sugar for a pie. Ribs, collard greens and potato salad are also
on the menu in celebration of the first day of classes for the boy
and his 10-year-old sister.
</P>
<P>
   But at night, when the TV is turned off and the dishes are
washed and put away and the little apartment is dark and quiet,
Santonio Lucas cries.
</P>
<P>
   For his mother. His aunt. His brothers and sisters. The family
he lost in a mass murder-suicide on a sweltering July day.
</P>
<P>
   On this afternoon, Santonio, his sister Jalisa and their father
David Lucas, sit together talking about their lives and how they
came together.
</P>
<P>
   The boy places his chin on a table and gazes impassively at a
smaller TV set up in his grandmother's bedroom. Jalisa, a dynamo
who loves math and science, talks non-stop with a visitor about her
first day at elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   Jalisa did not witness the horrible event that unfolded at her
home in southwest Atlanta earlier this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Santonio did.
</P>
<P>
   On July 12 just before sunup, Santonio was forced to watch as
Cyrano Marks, his mother's live-in boyfriend, shot and killed
Santonio's mother, his aunt and four of his siblings.
</P>
<P>
   Santonio survived only after he faked his death when Marks
cornered him in a hallway closet and shot him in the arm. Though
Marks put a bullet through his own head minutes later, the
terrified youngster crouched in the closet for eight hours before
running to a neighbor's house to call police.
</P>
<P>
   Jalisa, little-girl innocent with a plethora of braids and an
infectious smile, was saved from the horror because she stayed over
at an aunt's house to play with cousins the night before her family
was executed.
</P>
<P>
   In the days following the murders, Santonio lived at Hughes
Spalding Children Hospital. He celebrated his 12th birthday there
on July 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``He cried like a baby all that day. It was the toughest day,''
Lucas said Monday. ``It was his birthday and he wanted his mother.
They were close.''
</P>
<P>
   Nightmares about the shootings also haunted Santonio's time at
the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The bad dreams are gone now, his father said, but the tears
remain.
</P>
<P>
   ``He cries almost every night,'' Lucas said gazing fondly at his
son. ``He and his sister have gotten very close. They're even
closer to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas divorced Santonio's mother Delean Briskey years ago. But
the couple had four children and Lucas often visited his kids on
weekends at Briskey's house.
</P>
<P>
   Though united by tragedy, Lucas is happy his two youngest
children are with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they want to go everywhere I go,'' Lucas said. ``I'm the
only parent they have left and they want to be with me all the
time. I feel good about it. We talk. We cry. We laugh. We watch TV
and we go to the movies whenever we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Life also has changed for Santonio's grandmother Cynthia Lucas
Waller. She used to live comfortably in the apartment with her
second husband.
</P>
<P>
   Now, two children and a 37-year-old son later, Waller has no
regrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason why these children are here is sad,'' Waller said
Monday. ``I've opened my heart and given them my understanding and
my love. As I see it, they lost one family and gained another.''
</P>
<P>
   Administrators at both Santonio's and Jalisa's schools also made
sure the children were given emotional support.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been preparing for Jalisa's arrival for the last month,
talking to her new teacher and a school counsleor about the
situation,'' said Gwendolyn Mayfield, principal at Miles Elementary
in southwest Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``The children in her fifth-grade class were encouraged to talk
about what happened to her family so that she'll feel it's alright
to talk about it. Her new teacher is looking forward to spending
time with her.''
</P>
<P>
   Santonio's seventh-grade classmates at Usher Middle School
welcomed him back with pats on the back and boyish conversation,
said principal Geraldine Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to keep it as ordinary as possible for Santonio the
first few days he's here,'' Williams said. ``Later on we're
planning to have an assembly just to welcome him back to school.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently unemployed because of a back injury, Lucas spends his
days ferrying Santonio and Jalisa to their counselling sessions and
Santonio's doctor. The boy's cast will be removed in about two
months and he looks forward to playing football and baseball again.
</P>
<P>
   But the child's arm is the least of his father's worries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Santonio and his sister talk about their mama all the time you
know,'' Lucas, 37, said. ``They'll say, 'You know this is how mama
did this or this is how mama did that.' And I'll look at them and
smile.
</P>
<P>
   `` I know my son will never get over this. It will be with him
forever. But every night I pray he'll make it alright.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyda Longa writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
