<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-BERLIN-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHROEDER _ AND GERMANY'S CENTER OF GRAVITY _ MOVES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Almost a decade after the fall of the wall that divided
Germany and Europe, Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder took up residence
here on Monday, inaugurating the first Berlin-based government to
rule the country since Hitler's collapsed at the end of World War
II.
</P>
<P>
   Because the enormous new chancellery opposite the Reichstag is
not yet ready, Schroeder was obliged to move into the refurbished
former office of Erich Honecker, the East German leader, a curious
twist on which he chose not to dwell Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The chancellor's arrival was a low-key occasion. There was no
ceremony at the Brandenburg Gate, no political rally, no pomp and
circumstance _ as befits a shift of which most Germans are proud
but whose historical symbolism remains too charged for broad public
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   As Schroeder began governing from Honecker's former office,
Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer moved into a remodeled building
next door that once housed Hitler's Reichsbank. After protracted
discussions over the last decade, Germany has decided that some
former Nazi buildings will be used as ministries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democracy has won and therefore these memories are not
threatening,'' said Franz Muentefering, the transport minister, who
has organized much of the 375-mile move eastward from Bonn. ``On
the contrary, it is useful to be aware of them and not to try to
run from history by destroying the buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   Eberhard Diepgen, the Christian Democratic mayor of Berlin,
welcomed the Social Democratic chancellor in a small ceremony
during which Schroeder cut a cake decorated with bears _ the symbol
of Berlin. He said the city would become ``one of the great world
metropolises _ if it is not one already.''
</P>
<P>
   The chancellor appeared to be indulging in a little diplomatic
hyperbole, for much of Berlin remains a building site, the hum of
economic activity is not yet widely discernible, chic streets
number one or two at most, and the city does not yet offer direct
flights to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But Berlin has something else _ a sense of being wide open, of
beginning life again _ that perhaps no other European city offers
to the same degree. Few would argue with its potential.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder added that the arrival of the government was a
``historic moment'' _ the completion of a decade-long transition
during which Germany had undergone ``a peaceful and successful
revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Peace has indeed prevailed since the Berlin wall fell in
November 1989, but the integration of east and west has not been as
smooth or as successful as Helmut Kohl, the former chancellor,
predicted at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Schroeder's failure since taking office last year to
make any dent in high unemployment, particularly in the eastern
part of the country, has been a major reason for a sharp plunge in
his popularity. Recent opinion polls have shown that only 23
percent of the electorate approves of the way he has governed.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly he has had trouble stamping his authority on Germany.
One television station, RTL, is now preparing a soap opera based on
the chancellor and his life called ``Wie war ich, Doris?'' or ``How
was I, Doris?'' after the reported propensity of Schroeder to ask
his wife, a former journalist, how he has fared in public
appearances.
</P>
<P>
   The plans for the soap opera have outraged Schroeder, who
canceled an interview with RTL this week, but it appeared to
reflect some of his difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   In the new capital, the chancellor is clearly hoping to turn the
corner. He has never concealed his mild contempt for Bonn and his
strong desire to be in Berlin, and he has suggested repeatedly that
the new ``Berlin Republic'' should provide a catalyst for the
reconciliation of east and west that has proved so elusive up to
now.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But whatever the symbolism of Berlin, the economic and political
reality facing Schroeder is harsh. As five important state
elections loom in the next two months, he is trying to move his
Social Democratic Party sharply toward fiscal conservatism against
resistance from many party members and from labor unions.
</P>
<P>
   His finance minister, Hans Eichel, has proposed budget cuts of
over $15 billion, including a two-year freeze on pensions, and
Schroeder has resisted repeated calls for a tax on large fortunes
that was promised during his election campaign. Those policies,
welcomed by big business, have drawn fire from the chancellor's
party.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, during a quick visit to the western town of
Saarbruecken, where political resistance to his ideas has been
particularly intense, Schroeder made it clear that he would not
waver and said he planned to revise his party's 40-year-old
manifesto before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to look afresh at how the basic values of this party _
which in themselves are not in doubt _ can be achieved,'' Schroeder
said.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder is expected to govern from his temporary offices for
at least a year. The new chancellery was enlarged after Kohl
insisted that it should be as tall as the Reichstag to symbolize a
balance between the executive and Parliament. As a result, the
project was delayed and the cost has increased by 15 percent, to
about $250 million.
</P>
<P>
   The chancellor has recently expressed a personal view that the
building is rather large. It is in fact about three times the size
of the former chancellery in Bonn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
