<DOCNO> NYT19990823.0393 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7062 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-BASEMENT-CHAP11-BOS &LR;      08-23 1333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASEMENT-CHAP11-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AILING FILENE'S BASEMENT FILES FOR PROTECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- In what may be the beginning of the end for a Boston
institution _ or the chance for a fresh start _ beleaguered
Filene's Basement filed for bankruptcy protection Monday amid
mounting losses and fierce competition from rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Filene's Basement has been an enduring city attraction. ``It's
one of our landmarks, something everyone who comes to our city
wants to visit,'' said Mayor Thomas M. Menino, reacting to the
bankrupcty filing, which came a week after the company announced
another quarter of anemic earnings.
</P>
<P>
   But if Filene's Basement is a favorite tourist stop, it is also
a business in trouble, a retail throwback hurt by larger companies,
outlet chains, and a change in the way that time-harried consumers
shop in the Internet era.
</P>
<P>
   It may be premature to write off the Basement just yet. For the
91-year-old company, bankruptcy isn't necessarily a final chapter
but perhaps the first chapter of a comeback story.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a knockdown to one knee, but it's not a knockout,'' said
Basement chairman Sam Gerson, citing an inventory shortage brought
on by credit problems as the immediate reason for the decision to
seek so-called Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection. ``The Basement is
still one damn terrific company.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a gray day,'' Gerson added. ``But it's also a new
beginning.'' Gerson gave no timetable for when the chain might
emerge from bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   The chain's flagship Boston store and 54 stores spread across
the Northeast and Midwest will continue to be open for business,
and customers should see no changes, at least in the short term,
according to company officials. By filing for bankruptcy, the
company will be able to obtain additional credit from its lenders
to pay for new shipments of fall merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it recently eliminated nearly 40 of about 230
jobs at its Wellesley headquarters, with some of the cuts coming
through attrition. The chain employs about 3,800 workers.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers often use Chapter 11 to close unprofitable stores.
Some analysts believe that Filene's Basement, which has faced
criticism that it expanded too rapidly and strayed too far from its
base, will follow that strategy. Gerson declined to say how many
stores might be closed.
</P>
<P>
   In simple terms, a retailer in bankruptcy is similar to a
hospital patient with a serious illness. The illness can be fatal,
but a full recovery is also possible. So is survival in some
diminished form, perhaps the likeliest outcome for Filene's
Basement.
</P>
<P>
   For Caldor Corp., bankruptcy presaged doom. Unable to fix its
problems, the chain went out of business this year. But for
Bradlees Inc., Chapter 11 was part of a long, painful healing that
saw the Braintree, Mass. company emerge from bankruptcy six months
ago. During its 3 1/2 years in Chapter 11, Bradlees closed roughly
33 of 136 stores and shed about 6,000 jobs, including the job of a
former chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   But there has been some upside to all that pain. Last week
Bradlees reported a modest quarterly profit.
</P>
<P>
   Filing for bankruptcy can give a troubled retailer some
``breathing space as it attempts to reorganize,'' said Christopher
J. Panos, a Boston lawyer who heads up the Boston Bar Association's
bankruptcy law section.
</P>
<P>
   The Basement's most pressing problem was that it had lost the
faith of its vendors. Afraid they wouldn't be paid, some stopped
shipping goods, and the Basement's sales were hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody was shipping because their credit was bad,'' said Gary
Wassner, president of Hilldun Corp., a New York firm that provides
financing to vendors.
</P>
<P>
   In Chapter 11, a retailer can usually obtain more flexible
financing to ease short-term cash-flow problems. Bankruptcy
protection can also make it easier to close underperforming stores
because a retailer is shielded from many of the economic
consequences of breaking a store lease at unprofitable sites.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Filene's Basement said it had received a commitment from
its lenders, General Electric Capital Corp. and Paragon Capital
LLC, for a $135 million in special financing. That financing could
be approved Tuesday when the US District Court in Boston is set to
hear Filene's Basement's request to seek Chapter 11 protection, the
company said.
</P>
<P>
   In its filing, Filene's Basement listed assets of more than $200
million and debts of nearly $149 million, according to the
company's public relation's firm.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the Basement's greatest challenge has been to
import the magic of its downtown store to other locations.
</P>
<P>
   As the Basement struggled to replicate itself, TJX Cos. of
Framingham, Mass. came up with its T.J. Maxx retail format. T.J.
Maxx never had the cachet of the Basement's flagship, but it has
been able to clone its T.J. Maxx model hundreds of times.
</P>
<P>
   Today TJX is a phenomenal success. With nearly $8 billion in
sales last year, it has far eclipsed Filene's Basement in the world
of off-price retail, and it has emerged as a formidable competitor.
By comparison, Filene's Basement had about $588.5 million in sales
last year.
</P>
<P>
   While a legend in the Boston area, Filene's Basement has never
been as big a draw outside of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Loehmann's Inc., a New York off-price retail chain that filed
for bankruptcy protection in May, faces a similar problem.
</P>
<P>
   The farther the Basement and Loehmann's strayed from their
hometowns, the more they struggled to give faraway consumers a
compelling reason to shop at unfamiliar stores, said John Macht of
the Macht Group, a Boston retail consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   In 1908 when Filene's Basement first opened its doors, nobody
had seen anything quite like it. For tonier department stores, the
Basement solved a problem; it was a place where they could unload
merchandise they couldn't sell at full price.
</P>
<P>
   For consumers who didn't mind shopping in a no-frills bargain
basement, the payoff was the chance of finding a great deal.
</P>
<P>
   The concept was a smash, and generations of Bostonians and
tourists thronged the Basement's Downtown Crossing store. In the
late 1970s, the Basement began opening suburban stores, later
expanding to other cities.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last decade, the retail landscape has changed. After
a period of consolidation, many department stores began offering
more and more promotional sales.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of selling slow-moving goods to off-price retailers such
as Filene's Basement, department stores decided either to discount
and sell the goods themselves or to open their own outlet stores
that would be stocked with excess merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Such changes made it harder for the Basement to find the quality
merchandise that had made it famous.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, consumers were changing their shopping habits.
Landing a bargain at Filene's Basement can be labor intensive, and
today's busy lifestyles leave consumers less time and energy to
rummage through bins in search of the elusive bargain.
</P>
<P>
   The Basement recently launched a new chain called Aisle 3,
designed to serve consumers the way they shop now. These warehouse
stores are open for business only on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   The chain's first four stores are ``showing strong signs of
success,'' Gerson said, and four other stores are about to open.
</P>
<P>
   If other retail bankruptcies are any guide, the company may
expand Aisle 3 and close many outlying Filene's Basement stores.
Also expect the Basement to offer a bonus retention package to
discourage top executives from leaving.
</P>
<P>
   Following the announcement of its intention to file for
bankruptcy, trading in shares of Basement stock was halted Monday
at 29/32. Shareholders usually lose out when a company files for
bankruptcy. According to Bloomberg News, Fidelity Investments was
the largest investor in Filene's Basement at the end of June. At
the time, Fidelity owned just over 1.9 million shares.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
