<SLUG> BC-BBN-CONTENDERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL COLUMN: NATIONAL LEAGUE PLAYOFF CONTENDERS FACE OFF 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two months ago, the Cincinnati Reds were in the midst of
establishing a major league record by winning 10 consecutive games
against first-place teams, Arizona and Houston. Monday night the
Mets began a 10-day stretch against those same teams, but they will
not match the streak that catapulted the Reds into the National
League Central and wild-card races.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets can't tie the Reds' record because they play the
first-place Astros and Diamondbacks only nine times, but the games
will nevertheless have an impact on their position in the NL East
and wild-card races.
</P>
<P>
   Division championship, wild card; wild card, division
championship. What's a team to do? Focus on one and if it achieves
the other, fine? How is a team supposed to view other series its
competitors play?
</P>
<P>
   On the very three days the Mets are playing the Astros at Shea
Stadium, the Reds are playing the Braves in Atlanta. The Mets
entered Monday night's series opener half a game behind the Braves
in the East; the Reds began their series half a game behind the
Astros in the Central. The Mets were a game and a half ahead of the
Reds in the wild-card standing.
</P>
<P>
   Given that the Mets haven't played a post-season game since
1988, shouldn't they be satisfied to get in through the wild-card
door? They do, after all, have six games with the Braves in a
nine-game stretch in the last two weeks of the season, and they
know how tough the Braves can be in those circumstances, wounded or
not. (For the latest evidence, see the last three games of last
season, when the Braves won all three and dumped the Mets out of
the wild-card slot.)
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the Mets should pull for the Braves to knock off the
Reds and shove them further back in the wild-card standing, putting
the Mets in a stronger position to claim that fourth playoff spot.
That would be the conservative approach to the playoffs, maybe the
safer route.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the important thing is to get in,'' Mets catcher Mike
Piazza said Monday when asked about his rooting interest in the
series in Atlanta. ``It's not a situation where we can be choosy.''
</P>
<P>
   But would a Reds sweep or a Braves sweep be better for the Mets?
``Who knows, man?'' Piazza responded. ``I just know it's important
to continue to go out and win as many games as you can. Hopefully,
we'll get in somehow.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Franco was asked the same thing. ``That's a good
question,'' said Franco, the Mets' pinch-hitter deluxe. ``I would
take a Cincinnati sweep definitely. Nah, I don't know. I guess
whatever happens, happens. We're rooting for Cincinnati to beat
Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Mets are thinking more first place than wild card, right?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' Franco said, ``although I guess if Atlanta swept
Cincinnati, it wouldn't be terrible. I don't know. It's a good a
question. I want to win the division, so I'm rooting for Cincinnati
to beat Atlanta. But if Atlanta were to sweep Cincinnati, I guess
it wouldn't be all that terrible either.''
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Hamilton called it a ``kind of Catch 22,'' though he sort
of changed his thinking in midthought.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of the division, obviously we want the Braves to
lose,'' Hamilton, the Mets center fielder, said. ``But there's
always the backdrop for us with the wild card. I think we're going
for our division. To be honest, we want to get in there and win the
division, so we're pulling for Cincinnati for the most part.''
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Rickey Henderson began by saying, ``It doesn't
matter.'' But then he said, ``We'd rather win our division, so we'd
rather have Cincinnati win.'' And then he said: ``It's really a
tossup. If Atlanta wins and Cincinnati loses and we win, then we
still have to face each other.'' And finally he said, ``It would
help both ways.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, trying to put the simultaneous series in some
perspective, said it was more important for the Mets to win each
series they play than to pay attention to what was happening
elsewhere. The Mets have won 11 of the 12 series they have played
since the All-Star Game break. The Reds have won 10 of 12,
including the last 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we continue to win each series,'' Hamilton said, ``we'll
have a good feeling about going to the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The four contenders will repeat their ambiguity next week, the
Mets playing in Houston, the Braves in Cincinnati, each series
scheduled for Monday, Tuesday and Wednesday. Franco saw one benefit
to the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes it easier looking up on the scoreboard,'' he said.
``You only have to look one place.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
