<SLUG> BC-FBN-MARTIN-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINO TESTIFIES IN TRIAL OF TEAMMATE  

</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ There was drama Monday in the federal money laundering
trial of Miami Dolphins wide receiver Tony Martin, with a teammate,
Dan Marino, and a former teammate, Nat Moore, testifying on
Martin's behalf and Assistant U.S. Attorney Ron DeWaard delivering
his final argument to the jury. DeWaard contended that Martin could
not use ignorance as a defense for illegal acts.
</P>
<P>
   The appearance in court by Marino, Moore and another Dolphin,
O.J. McDuffie, who did not testify, came one day before the case
will go to the jury after final arguments by Martin's lead defense
attorney, Howard Srebnick.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the jurors heard DeWaard tell them that ``Tony Martin
can't stick his head in the sand. He can't close his eyes to the
obvious. With all the money involved and all the shady
transactions, he had to know something wasn't right.''
</P>
<P>
   But the jurors also heard Marino and Moore speak up for Martin,
who was signed to a four-year, $14.2 million contract in April by
the Dolphins after starting for two Super Bowl teams in the last
five seasons but who could face three to five years in prison if
convicted. Martin is accused of being a money laundering front for
Rickey Brownlee, who has twice been convicted of drug dealing and
who is currently on trial on drug-trafficking charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe Tony to be someone that would willingly commit
a crime,'' Marino said. The veteran quarterback added that Martin,
whom Marino said he has known since 1989, had been in his home and
met his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good person,'' Marino said.
</P>
<P>
   Moore, a Dolphin for 13 years, said that he helped Martin make
the transition from college quarterback to National Football League
wide receiver. Moreover, Moore has used Martin in some of his youth
clinics.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that we try not to do in the camps is bring in guys
that aren't appropriate, guys that get in trouble,'' Moore said.
``We invited Tony because we always saw him as a good person.''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors say Martin, 33, assisted Brownlee, whom he has
known since high school, in the leasing of three luxury cars and in
trying to pay a $175,000 fee to a lawyer for Brownlee. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who played in Saturday night's exhibition game against
San Diego, catching 3 passes for 32 yards, sat slumped in his chair
through much of DeWaard's description of his activities with
Brownlee.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
