u s BC-RUN-WORLD-TRACK-NYT &LR;      08-23 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-WORLD-TRACK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES MISSES THE GOLD AND THE CONTROVERSY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEVILLE, Spain _ At first glance, the story of the women's long
jump Monday night was that Marion Jones did not win it and that a
Spaniard named Niurka Montalvo did. But as can sometimes be the
case in the narrow confines of the hit-or-miss domain in which long
jumpers ply their trade, it was quite a bit more complicated than
that.
</P>
<P>
   There was an ultimately unsuccessful protest from the Italian
federation over Montalvo's winning jump on the final round; tears
of frustration from the Italian silver medalist Fiona May, who had
been in the lead throughout the competition.
</P>
<P>
   What is beyond dispute is that Jones will have to wait for next
year's Summer Olympics in Sydney, Australia, to win the 100 meters,
the 200 meters and the long jump in the same major meet. She had
wanted an unprecedented four gold medals at this world
championship, but after finishing third Monday night with a leap of
22 feet 5 inches, the planet's most prominent female track and
field athlete will now have to scale back her aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a very unexpected decision to run both relays on the
final Sunday, the most events that Jones can win in Seville is
three: the 100 meters that she won already Sunday; the 200 on
Friday and a relay of her choice next Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no excuses,'' Jones said. ``I said wanted to come here
and win every event I entered. It didn't happen. But I think I can
sleep well tonight knowing I left it all out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Jones, who rarely competed seriously in the event as
a teen-ager, jumped 23 feet-11} inches. This year, she has yet to
get past 23 and has lost her last three competitions. Monday night,
she was again unable to translate her unparalleled speed into
unparalleled length. Her landings were often awkward; her energy
often wasted in the humid Andalusian air.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can stand here all day and talk about technique,'' she
said. ``I'll be the first one to tell you I need to work on my
technique. As you all know, my specialty is running. As you all
know, that's what I'm good at. It's very difficult to teach someone
speed, and I think it can be a bit easier to teach someone
technique. I have the speed.''
</P>
<P>
   She might still have managed to win if she had not fouled by a
slim margin on her sixth and final jump. Her leap appeared to be
her longest of the evening, slightly past 23 feet, but the Spanish
official Salvio Felipe Somohano Garcia, who was tending the takeoff
board, put his red flag in the air. And after Jones smiled and blew
a kiss to the crowd, she walked back to examine the plasticene
strip that indicates whether competitors have stepped past the
line. She did not argue.
</P>
<P>
   But Garcia would soon create plenty of debate. The next jumper
was Montalvo, a 31-year-old who fled her native Cuba and became a
Spanish citizen only late last year. In 1995, at the world
championship in Goteborg, Sweden, she had won a silver medal for
Cuba, finishing second to the British-born May.
</P>
<P>
   May was leading again Monday night, but this time, there would
be a reversal of fortune. Montalvo started her approach, a roar of
local support coursing through the stadium, and as she took off and
landed past the 23-foot mark, the roar got louder. Garcia held up
the white flag, indicating a legal jump, and Montalvo was soon in
the lead with a leap of 23-2, better than May's best effort.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was that the video replay clearly showed the tip of
her toe extending over the line in front of the plasticene strip on
her takeoff. On television, it looked very much like she had
overshot by the same slight margin as Jones. But the jump stood,
and when May came high-stepping down the runway for the final time,
the roar was nearly as loud and not nearly as supportive. She flew
only 22-9\, good enough for the silver, and Montalvo was soon
taking a victory lap and shaking a lot of happy Spaniards' hands.
</P>
<P>
   Though May gave her a congratulatory kiss, the Italian
federation was soon filing a protest that the International Amateur
Athletic Federation rejected shortly before midnight. The
conclusion was that unlike Jones, Montalvo had not touched the
plasticene on takeoff.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the first time a local hero had caused a controversy
in the long jump. In the 1987 world championship in Rome, Italian
officials rigged the measuring system so Italy's Giovanni
Evangelisti would win the bronze medal, a plot that was soon
uncovered.
</P>
<P>
   The IAAF spokesman, Giorgio Reineri, said that in this case, the
protest committee had carefully examined the video and heard from
Garcia and the supervisory judge Egil Gulliksen, a Norwegian,
before rendering its decision. The relevant IAAF rule, No. 173,
does not indicate that a competitors' foot cannot extend beyond the
takeoff line; only that he may not ``touch the ground beyond the
takeoff line.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is no mark, there is no foul,'' Reineri said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too bad that Fiona cannot accept the defeat,'' said
Montalvo, who deemed her jump ``clearly valid'' and added that ``if
it had been me, I would not have protested.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot say I'm happy, and I don't want to be unsporting but
everybody saw what happened in Montalvo's last jump,'' May said
after seeing the replay.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who declined to speculate on the legality of Montalvo's
jump and complimented the Spaniard on her fine effort, has no such
plans to stop. ``As you know, I set my goals very high, and bronze
is not going to cut it for me; just not going to,'' she said, her
tone not as sharp as her words. ``It tells me I need to get back to
the drawing board for next year. It's as simple as that.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
