<HEADLINE>
YELLOW CARDS DEAL ZENGA A SUSPENSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Revolution player-coach Walter Zenga is suspended for
Wednesday's game against the MetroStars at Giants Stadium because
of an accumulation of yellow cards.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga was cautioned for the fifth time this season while
protesting to referee Ali Saheli after a penalty kick was awarded
during the Revolution's 2-1 loss at San Jose Saturday night. Ronald
Cerritos converted the penalty for the first goal of the game. Late
in the half, defender Mario Gori was ejected for a tackle from
behind on Cerritos and will also be suspended Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution have a seven-game losing streak and are in danger
of failing to qualify for the playoffs, but things could be worse,
according to assistant coach Giuseppe Galderisi.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once, we lost the first five games of the season when I was
playing for Padova,'' Galderisi said. ``There, you have a lot of
people covering the team and you get a lot of criticism. We
couldn't even go out to a bar or restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we stayed together, fought together, and ended up having a
good season. It is times like this that can bring a team together.
You have to fight for you teammates, and if you fight together, you
become stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Revolution have committed costly errors that have
subverted any galvanizing effects of team togetherness. Defender
Brian Dunseth lost possession just outside the penalty area,
leading to the deciding goal in San Jose. The Revolution had been
attempting to compensate for the loss of Gori and seemed capable of
keeping the score tied before Alejandro Sequeira's goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody on the team has to believe in each other, sacrifice,
and eliminate those errors,'' said Galderisi. ``We have to unite
and become a team. It's easy to talk, and a lot of people are doing
that now. But we have to continue to work hard, play every game
like it is the final of the Champions League, and we will arrive at
our goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when we do, we will remember this as a time which made us
stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Defender Dan Calichman, out since July 31 with a groin strain,
will return for the game . . . The Boston Bulldogs purchased
striker Elias Montes from Alianza FC in El Salvador. Montes, 25,
has scored seven goals in five games while playing on loan and will
be in the lineup against the Staten Island Vipers Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
