<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COASTAL TEXAS DODGES BULLET AS MONSTER STORM MISSES URBAN AREAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
And JOHN MORITZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FALFURRIAS, Texas _ Armando Regallado was sitting in his living
room watching the Weather Channel when Hurricane Bret paid a rude
house call, ripping the roof off the mobile home like one pulls the
lid off a can of Spam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I could see the stars,'' Regallado said. Asked if he was
scared, the 35-year-old construction worker replied: ``Tell me
about it. I saw it. I saw it. I couldn't believe it, then I ran
into another room and it struck there.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Regallado, who considers himself lucky to be intact,
was cleaning out debris like thousands of other Texans along the
southern coast and several inland counties.
</P>
<P>
   Officials throughout the region marveled how south coastal Texas
had dodged the bullet, experiencing little property damage from a
storm many had predicted would be as destructive as Hurricane
Andrew.
</P>
<P>
   In Corpus Christi, the region's largest city, qbout 65 miles
northeast of Falfurrias, residents were permitted to return to
North Padre Island, which had been under a mandatory evacuation
order. Utility crews had spread out to restore electricity and
telephone service while city workers removed debris from storm
drains that had contributed to flooding in several areas.
</P>
<P>
   Although residents of the coastal counties were cleaning up and
assessing damage on Monday, the danger was just beginning for some
parts of South Texas where the remnants of the hurricane were
dumping up to a foot of rain.
</P>
<P>
   Laredo residents braced for flooding on the Rio Grande, and
about 3,500 people on both sides of the U.S.-Mexico border left
their homes for higher ground.
</P>
<P>
   Most Laredo businesses closed at 6 p.m., Laredo International
Airport and all three bridges linking the city to Mexico were shut
down.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush said state teams ``switched from hurricane
response mode to flood response mode.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I urge all Texans in the affected areas to take the threat of
flooding seriously, to continue to pay close attention to this
storm, and to follow the advice and direction of local officials,''
Bush said in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
   Seven South Texas counties already have been declared disaster
areas by President Clinton, and more counties were being hit by
torrential rains as the storm was downgraded to a tropical storm as
it moved slowly toward Laredo and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   State and federal officials were helping local authorities
determine the extent of the damage, and could recommend that
additional counties be added to the list, said Dave Bary, a
spokesman for the state emergency operations center in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is going to be extensive flooding, and after the
floodwaters recede there will be a significant amount of debris,''
he said. ``It's possible, given the amount of rain, that additional
counties could be added to the declaration.''
</P>
<P>
   Falfurrias, about 40 miles from the coast and in the direct path
of the storm as it moved ashore midway between Corpus Christi and
Brownsville across sparsely populated Kenedy County, damage was
evident.
</P>
<P>
   In the Gardendale neighborhood, children took advantage of
closed schools and knee-deep water to bike and run their dogs
through the flooded streets. Their parents picked up fallen
branches and urged passing trucks to go slow as their wake pushed
water too close to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Many businesses had reopened by lunch time yesterday, causing
some continued discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy's dying,'' city employee Rudy Valverde said,
referring to a colleague on cleanup detail as they pulled into the
lot of a closed Whataburger. ``He needs a taco, quick.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bret's winds were below 40 mph Monday afternoon, officials
continued to worry about heavy rain. The cotton fields and pastures
from Robstown to Falfurrias are sodden or resemble little lakes,
prompting warnings of possible flash floods.
</P>
<P>
   In the smaller towns near the coast, there was measurable
consternation about media reports, both on Corpus Christi radio
stations and national television networks, that stated that Corpus
Christi had escaped the brunt of the storm and only areas with few
people were hit hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard on the Weather Channel this guy say, `It's OK, there's
no population there,''' said Brooks County Sheriff Balde Lozano.
``I live here. I was shocked.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, nobody lives here. We're not populated,'' Mary Ann
Williams said without prompting, voicing what apparently was a
common gripe on Monday in Falfurrias.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 34, said she hid in a closet during the worst of Bret,
as did Ovidio Saenz. Saenz, a 59-year-old truck driver, said he
spent nearly an hour in a closet with his girlfriend, trying but
failing to keep her calm in the pale light of a single candle.
</P>
<P>
   The storm felled scores of trees, which in turn knocked out 90
percent of the town's electrical service and much of its telephone
service. Possible contamination of the water supply led to a
citywide cutoff until laboratory tests prove the water was safe.
</P>
<P>
   Although Falfurrias was among the areas hardest hit, property
damage was slight: gas station canopies collapsed all over town and
the El Cid Motel, along with a third of its roof, lost a crucial
letter in the storm and was involuntarily renamed the El id.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Regallado's personal loss. Destruction of his
manufactured house leaves him homeless as he fights a custody
struggle with his ex-wife, said the uninsured construction worker,
cataloging his woes, both man-made and act of God.
</P>
<P>
   But Regallado said he is fortunate to have escaped unharmed,
doubly so since his girlfriend and her brother warned him to seek
safer shelter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him it's going to hit,'' said Damacio Villarreal, the
girlfriend's brother. ``So I said, `Hasta la vista, baby!' And
cleared out.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not all doom and gloom in Falfurrias, even during the
storm. Aldalberto ``Tuffy'' Cruz, 62, said he participated in a
series of all-male kamikaze hurricane parties, where beer flowed
and chests were bared as the well-potted participants ran outside
and let themselves be lashed by the storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was no fun staying inside,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
