<HEADLINE>
SOX SEND OSE DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ The Red Sox picked a strange way to prepare for
the September wild-card chase. They optioned second-year man Brian
Rose to Pawtucket and put veteran Bret Saberhagen on the disabled
list.
</P>
<P>
   Those were just two in a series of moves designed to save a
season that seems to be slipping away. As they opened a three-game
series against the Twins, the Sox had lost four in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Jimy Williams insists that the Red Sox are not in a
state of panic. Rose (6-5, 4.98 ERA) has not won in six starts
since July 20 and is clearly tired. Saberhagen was already
scheduled to miss a start because of a sore right shoulder. Two
hours before the game, he was still planning to throw on the
sidelines, but Williams effectively took any decision out of
Saberhagen's hands.
</P>
<P>
   In the grand plan, it stands to work to the Red Sox' advantage,
as players on the 15-day disabled list Sept. 1 are eligible for
postseason play.
</P>
<P>
   To fill the roster spots, the Sox promoted righthander Tomokazu
Ohka from Pawtucket and activated outfielder Damon Buford off the
DL. Buford was eligible to come off Saturday but the Sox had no
place for him. Ohka, who went 0-2 with an 14.29 ERA in his first
tour of duty with Boston in early July, will work out of the
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   The rotation right now is down to Pat Rapp, Pedro Martinez, Mark
Portugal, and Tim Wakefield, but there is an off day Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Williams let first Rose and then Saberhagen know of the moves in
closed-door meetings Monday. He had some regrets about the decision
on Rose, but given his overall state, it was a good move for the
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing that we did last year _ and this year, too _ is
to first and foremost protect our pitchers,'' said Williams. ``The
kid didn't pitch much last year. He came back and didn't miss a
start all year. Does it take its toll when you keep bringing a kid
back over a certain period of time? Yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he did when he came here was no fluke. This kid pitched.
But the ability that he showed then may not be there right now like
it was. There is a possibly that we will back off a little bit in
Pawtucket and put him on a program where we would let him miss a
start and rest his arm. It might be the right thing to do in his
case, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Missing one game might not provide enough time for Saberhagen to
return as strong as he'd like to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need this guy,'' said Williams, ``and not for just one
start. It's my decision to give him a chance to pitch 5-6 starts
and do it by resting him X number of days. I think it's best for
our team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't panic here. He knows how to pitch and knows how to
win. He has that unique ability. He's always had it since he was a
kid. If things are right physically he's going to give us a chance
to win that game. We've had to do this all year with our
pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohka is 6-0 with a 1.79 ERA at Pawtucket. He was 8-0 at Trenton
and considered one of the team's top prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tell me he's pitched very well,'' said Williams. ``That's
what I go by.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox contingent didn't arrive to their hotel here until 6
a.m. After losing, 6-0, to the Rangers in Arlington, Texas, Sunday
night, the team went to the airport only to find that their plane
had a flat tire that took four hours to repair.
</P>
</TEXT>
