<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCK MARKETS SURGE AS INTEREST-RATE FEARS EBB
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of directionless and confused stock trading,
investors swaggered back into stocks, surer than ever that the
Federal Reserve Board would raise rates for the last time this year
at Tuesday's meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The turnabout in investor mood sent the Dow Jones industrial
average to a record high of 11,299.76, up 199.15 points, or 1.79
percent, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index rose 1.77
percent, still below its high, reached on July 16. The Nasdaq
composite index rose 2.69 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bond yields hovered at their lowest levels in a month amid
optimism over interest rates. The yield on the 30-year Treasury
issue held steady at 5.98 percent.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT FLEXES DICTIONARY MUSCLE
</P>
<P>
   As Microsoft enters the fiercely competitive dictionary market,
its offering, the Encarta World English Dictionary, a
self-described ``image of English at the turn of the millennium,''
has set off a tart war of words.
</P>
<P>
   SUN MICROSYSTEMS IN INTERNET DEAL
</P>
<P>
   Sun Microsystems agreed to pay $540 million in stock for Forte
Software, a maker of programming tools for developing Internet
applications, sending Forte shares soaring. The acquisition of
Forte will help Sun extend its reach to Web sites using IBM's
System 390 mainframe computer systems and Microsoft's Windows NT
operating system.
</P>
<P>
   EXCHANGES BATTLE OVER OPTIONS
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Board Options Exchange and the American Stock
Exchange started a market brawl by listing Dell Computer options.
Such options had traded exclusively on the Philadelphia Stock
Exchange, which struck back by listing options in Johnson &AMP;
Johnson, IBM, Coca-Cola and Apple Computer, which had traded on the
other exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   SUEZ LYONNAISE PLANS U.S. PURCHASE
</P>
<P>
   Suez Lyonnaise des Eaux said it would buy United Water
Resources, a leading U.S. water-management business for $1 billion,
heightening a fight between two giant French utilities for a piece
of the fast-growing U.S. water-treatment market.
</P>
<P>
   GERMAN BANKING UNITS MAY LINK UP
</P>
<P>
   Two German financial giants, Deutsche Bank and Dresdner Bank,
said they were in talks over combining retail banking units to cut
costs. While short of a merger, linking the two retail networks
would create a unit with almost 13 million clients.
</P>
<P>
   SILICON GRAPHICS CHAIRMAN QUITS
</P>
<P>
   The chairman and chief executive of Silicon Graphics, Richard
Belluzzo, resigned unexpectedly after a 19-month effort to restore
the company, which makes computer work stations, to health. Robert
Bishop, 56, a board member and former Silicon Graphics executive,
will succeed him.
</P>
<P>
   NBC STUDIOS GETS NEW PRESIDENT
</P>
<P>
   In a move that underscores the increasing emphasis networks are
placing on producing their own programming to take advantage of
potential profits from hit entertainment shows, NBC named Ted
Harbert, the former top entertainment executive at ABC, to the post
of president at its in-house television production unit, NBC
Studios.
</P>
<P>
   VIACOM SEEN IN TALKS WITH KIRCH
</P>
<P>
   Viacom is in talks to buy a stake in the Kirch Group of Germany,
according to Prince Walid bin Talal of Saudi Arabia, who said he
had been asked to broker the transaction. Viacom confirmed that its
chairman, Sumner Redstone, had met with the prince on ``a broad
range of topics.''
</P>
<P>
   PSINET TO BUY TRANSACTION NETWORK
</P>
<P>
   Psinet, a provider of Internet access for businesses, plans to
buy Transaction Network Services, which provides high-speed data
services for credit-card and automated bank-teller transactions,
for $720 million in cash and stock.
</P>
</TEXT>
