<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7075 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CHINA-NUKE-600&AMP;ADD-NY     08-23 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-NUKE-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIAL WHO LED INQUIRY INTO CHINA'S REPUTED THEFT OF NUCLEAR
SECRETS QUITS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JAMES RISEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Notra Trulock, the Energy Department official who
led the initial inquiry into China's apparent theft of U.S. nuclear
secrets, said he resigned Monday in protest of what he described as
a long series of roadblocks from Clinton administration
policy-makers and other government officials to his pursuit of the
case.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Trulock, the Energy Department's acting deputy
chief of intelligence, complained Monday that he had been squeezed
out of the ongoing investigation of the case, code-named ``Kindred
Spirit,'' and that he was no longer allowed to participate in any
other significant work in the department's intelligence office.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have moved me out from any participation in the Kindred
Spirit case, and from any other aspect of the management of
intelligence activities within the department,'' Trulock said.
</P>
<P>
   Trulock added that he had been thinking about resigning for
months because of what he said was political interference in the
espionage investigation. But he said he finally decided to quit
after the release earlier this month of a report by the Energy
Department's inspector general concerning the department's handling
of the spy case.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general's report found no conclusive evidence to
support Trulock's assertions that he had been temporarily blocked
from briefing Congress on the spy case in 1998. ``The IG report was
the last straw,'' Trulock said.
</P>
<P>
   Trulock has become a highly controversial figure within the
government because of his central role in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Although the FBI started a criminal investigation into evidence
that China had stolen data about America's most advanced nuclear
warhead three years ago, no arrests have been made, and the
handling of the case by officials from the Energy Department, the
FBI and the Justice Department has become fodder for a series of
special inquiries by both Congress and the executive branch.
</P>
<P>
   Trulock served as the catalyst for the public furor over the
government's handling of the case in part because of his decision
to become a secret witness late last year for a congressional panel
that investigated the allegations of Chinese nuclear espionage.
</P>
<P>
   Trulock's charges that the government's investigation had been
slowed by interference from senior officials at the Energy
Department, Los Alamos National Laboratory and the White House
quickly became enmeshed in the national debate over the proper
course of U.S. policy toward China.
</P>
<P>
   But his accusations, strongly denied by the White House and
Energy Department, also prompted strong criticism of his own
handling of the case by current and former government officials. In
June, Trulock's criticism of a report issued by the president's
Foreign Intelligence Advisory Board on the spy investigation led to
a stinging response from Warren Rudman, the former senator who is
chairman of the panel.
</P>
<P>
   Rudman wrote that Trulock was guilty of having ``misread
professional disagreements as personal affronts,'' and that he had
``misconstrued your obligation to be candid as a license for
calumny.''
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, the former chief of counterintelligence at Los
Alamos, who himself has been disciplined for mishandling the
investigation, charged that Trulock and others had been responsible
for botching the case because they unfairly focused their attention
on a Chinese-American scientist from Los Alamos.
</P>
<P>
   Trulock has denied that race was a factor in the decision to
investigate Wen Ho Lee, the Chinese-American scientist who was
fired from his job at Los Alamos in March for security violations.
Lee has not been charged with any crime.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Trulock has also had a mixed relationship with Energy Secretary
Bill Richardson. In May, Richardson gave him a special $10,000
award for having raised the alarm within the government about
China's theft of nuclear secrets, and praised Trulock for
persisting in the inquiry despite bureaucratic roadblocks.
</P>
<P>
   But last year, Trulock lost his job as chief of intelligence at
the Energy Department, and was demoted to acting deputy chief.
Richardson declined to respond to Trulock's written request earlier
this year to be reinstated as intelligence chief, and Trulock was
told this summer that he would also not be named permanent deputy
intelligence chief.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Richardson said Monday that ``he is disappointed
with Trulock's decision to leave the department.'' Richardson added
that he ``believes that Trulock performed valuable work,'' but that
he ``supports the inspector general's conclusions'' that angered
Trulock.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Sanchez, the current chief of intelligence at the Energy
Department, said Monday that he had repeatedly offered to make
Trulock the permanent deputy of intelligence, but that Trulock had
declined to accept the post. And he added that Richardson declined
to make Trulock the chief of intelligence because that would have
meant firing Sanchez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been his protector, ensuring that his message was
continually being carried and ensuring that he was at every
congressional hearing on the case that he should have been at,''
Sanchez said. ``He was not actively being cut out of things. I knew
he was going to leave anyway, and we knew he was actively seeking
another job.''
</P>
<P>
   Trulock, who is taking a private sector job, said that he was
particularly angry that the Energy Department's inspector general
report stated that there was no conclusive evidence to prove that
Elizabeth Moler, then acting energy secretary, blocked Trulock from
briefing the House Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence about
the nuclear spy case.
</P>
<P>
   Trulock had charged that Ms. Moler prevented him from briefing
the panel, and told him that congressional Republicans would only
use the information to attack President Clinton's China policies.
Ms. Moler has repeatedly denied Trulock's allegations, and Trulock
later did brief a special congressional panel that investigated the
nuclear theft.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
