<DOCNO> NYT19990823.0405 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7077 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SOUP-FAD-COOLS-NYT &LR;      08-23 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUP-FAD-COOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NEW YORK, SOUP ISN'T SO HOT ANYMORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ First there was ``Seinfeld,'' which, with one famous
episode, made it hip to stand in line for a $7 container of tomato
bisque.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the sandwich was passe. Office workers were tossing
off demands for midday mulligatawny. Little vellum bags filled with
cookie crumbs, and the occasional bruised banana, littered midtown
garbage bins.
</P>
<P>
   But, as with shocking pink purses and pashmina shawls, food
trends, too, usually lose their steam. While there are still plenty
of places to buy a bowl of designer soup at noon, many who in
recent years chose soup as their business are falling on tough
times. Some have closed up entirely; others have scaled back their
growth plans. Most of the stronger players are learning that they
cannot live on soup alone, and are quickly moving to add other
items to their menus.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the classic retail foul-up _ overambition ignited
by early success _ has been their downfall. Daily Soup, for
example, one of the largest and best-known of the soup stands,
admits to opening too many stores too fast, losing control of some
of them and opening a few clunkers in bad locations.
</P>
<P>
   Gone is Soup Nutsy. Souperman closed its second location.
Souperdog just became Wrapsody, a wrap sandwich shop. Zoop Soup is
adding a deli, and Daily Soup and other stores are rethinking their
business plans.
</P>
<P>
   What soup sellers all realized is that soup is a very difficult
food to make money on. It is highly seasonal _ how much chicken
soup can a city eat in July? _ and most people are not willing to
eat it every day, even in the dead of winter. However high your
prices, you have to shovel a lot of split pea to pay the rent;
volume during the high season is essential to cover the hot months,
when the rent remains the same but sales dive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We discovered that the soup fad is fading,'' said Roger
Fields, who owns Wrapsody nee Souperdog. ``And when there is warm
weather, no one will eat it, which is very limiting.''
</P>
<P>
   Stands selling soup and soup alone as a meal _ save a piece of
fruit and a little confection _ was a New York trendlette, food
experts note. Daily Soup appeared to have mastered the concept, but
did not invent it. It all began with one Al Yeganeh, who has been
selling fancy soups for years from Soup Kitchen International, his
stand on West 55th Street. His churlish demands (customers must
move like lightning to the left after ordering or incur bitter
wrath) was parodied in a 1995 episode of ``Seinfeld,'' titled
``Soup Nazi.''
</P>
<P>
   The episode courted the ire of Yeganeh, but made his yummy soups
even more popular. And soon, copycats abounded.
</P>
<P>
   The most high-profile of soup-only stores is Daily Soup, which
started in 1995 with one store and now runs 10. At first, lines
formed out the door. People could not get enough of mushroom
barley, vegetable gumbo, Mexican cheese. The chain started to open
more stores at a breakneck speed. But problems ensued.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we expanded too quickly,'' said Robert Spiegel, a part
owner and the chief executive of Daily Soup, where he said eight of
the stores make a profit. ``We are not in the red now, but we are
undercapitalized.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside of the need to have high volume, problems associated
with overexpansion surfaced, he said. Managers did not inspect the
fruit that comes with a soup lunch, and often it was damaged.
Employees started to slice the bread too thick, cutting away at the
bottom line with every piece. The delivery area was over too many
blocks, so people across the street from the store were waiting a
half hour for orders. These problems have been addressed, Spiegel
said, and by ``going back to basics'' he expects to help the
company perform better now that the busy season is upon it.
</P>
<P>
   But many people in the food business say that soup as a
stand-alone lunch concept is perhaps ill conceived.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soup is a great idea,'' said George Naddaff, chairman of
Franchise Concepts, which runs Ranch 1 chicken stores and aborted
its plans to acquire Soup Nutsy two years ago. ``But it cannot
stand on its own. There need to be other legs on the stool.'`
</P>
<P>
   Even soup fanatics concur. ``Even with 15 varieties, I can't eat
it all the time,'' said Michele Kreolin, an interior decorator, who
often goes to Hale and Hearty Soups. ``In the summer, I can't eat
it at all.''
</P>
<P>
   As such, soup shops are finding the need to become, well,
sandwich shops. Mr. Soup, a store at One New York Plaza, sells
sandwiches and salads. Zoop Soup is opening an attached deli. And
Hale and Hearty Soups, a chain with eight locations, is quickly
adding other lunch items. ``If you don't evolve and hear what the
market is saying, you can't survive,'' said Andrew Schnipper,
president of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Daily Soup is experimenting with a tossed salad station in one
of its stores, and is also going into the wholesale business with
dreams of selling fresh soup to gourmet stores.
</P>
<P>
   But competition awaits. ``It is a pretty crowded marketplace,''
said John Gottfried, a part owner of Gourmet Garage, an upscale
market with four Manhattan locations. ``We are always being
approached'' by potential suppliers. But soup stand prices _ which
can be prohibitive _ will not hold up in retail stores, he warned.
``In the retail setting, if we start trying to charge $6 for a pint
of soup it better have truffles in it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yeganeh, reached in Europe where he is on vacation, mocked the
troubles and strategies of others. ``I will never add anything!
Nothing! Not even a drink,'' he said. ``I charge high prices and I
am the original one. I was the best 10 years ago, before that clown
Seinfeld.'' Indeed, he fetches $25 for a quart of seafood bisque.
</P>
<P>
   Daily Soup charges anywhere from $5.50 for a 12-ounce container
of gazpacho, to close to $9 for a 16-ounce bowl of Tuscan shrimp
with white bean. It has a daily blue plate special that is cheaper,
and it now plans to discount its soups heavily after 4 p.m. But
high prices reign in the soup business.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people who don't understand why we charge
$7 for soup,'' sighed Dominque Drevet, co-owner of Souperman, which
sells soups around Wall Street. ``But we use fresh ingredients, we
go to the fish market, et cetera. But when people think soup, they
think cheap.''
</P>
<P>
   Souperman has moved into sandwiches, and Drevet said that he
sells about 100 daily sandwich-soup combinations, which has helped
the business a lot. Still, Drevet, whose partner is the chef
Johannes Sanzin, said the two are already looking for their next
hot concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the end of the fashionable soup,'' he said.
``We are putting our minds to something else. Maybe breakfast.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
