<SLUG> BC-FBC-OSU-QUARTERBACK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sophomore QB to get start in OSU opener
 &HT;    By Susan Vinella
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ For weeks now, Ohio State coaches have kept
copious statistics on their top two quarterbacks, Austin Moherman
and Steve Bellisari. They've charted every pass, every decision,
every mistake.
</P>
<P>
   When they added it all up this past weekend, Moherman, a
third-year sophomore from southern California, came out on top. He
will be the starter for the Buckeyes' season opener Sunday against
12th-ranked Miami (Fla.) in the Kickoff Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was real close but Austin has graded out ahead of Steve,
particularly in the last couple of scrimmages we've had in the
stadium,'' OSU coach John Cooper said. ``We think he deserves to
start in this first ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision brings to an end _ at least temporarily _ the
guessing-game of who will immediately replace record-breaking
quarterback Joe Germaine, now in the NFL. Bellisari will get his
turn, Cooper said, but it won't be a series-to-series job share
like Germaine and Stanley Jackson had two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going into this ballgame saying, 'Austin, you're
going to play the first two series, then Steve, you're going in,'
'' Cooper said. ``But I can tell you there's probably a good chance
that somewhere during the game Steve will go in.''
</P>
<P>
   Moherman (pronounced Mock-er-man), who last started a football
game as a senior at Capistrano Valley High School in 1996, learned
he'd be the No. 1 guy during a quarterbacks meeting Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surprised would not be a word I would use,'' he said,
describing his reaction. ``But I felt happy with the decision,
obviously. I was pleased. I just have to go out there and do it on
the field now.''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterbacks coach Tim Salem said Moherman, 6-5, 215 pounds, won
the job because of his poise under pressure during practices and
scrimmages. His reads of the defense, his accurate throws, his
``poise in the pocket'' were what separated him from Bellisari,
Salem said. Everything else was close between the two.
</P>
<P>
   Moherman said he felt good after last Friday's scrimmage but
didn't know the coaches were leaning toward him. Bellisari, who
played on special teams as a true freshman last year, was surprised
the decision came this soon. He expected it later in the week, even
on game-day.
</P>
<P>
   But Salem said there was no need to wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``There weren't many major mountains this week to evaluate them
on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Salem said he'll continue to treat both players like starters,
prepping them to be ready to enter the game at any time. He said
Bellisari will likely get his chance late in the first quarter or
early in the second on Sunday. If Moherman struggles significantly
before then, it could be sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's not playing that good, then Steve deserves a chance to
play,'' Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Bellisari: ``I wanted to be the starter but I'll live. I
know I'm going to play in the game sooner or later. I just have to
be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Vinella writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
