<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-RAFTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAFTER IS CONFIDENT HE CAN WIN OPEN AGAIN, MAYBE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ROBIN FINN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The batik boy left his favorite toys _ scuba gear,
golf clubs, even the trusty tennis racquet that helped him win the
last two U.S. Opens _ back home in Bermuda Monday. Plagued at just
the wrong time by chronic tendinitis in his serving shoulder,
Patrick Rafter was forced to use his left arm for all his heavy
lifting this week.
</P>
<P>
   After jetting to Manhattan for a day trip that fulfilled a
commitment to Reebok, the sponsor that dresses him like a surfer,
and pleased a few hundred shrieking girls at a Macy's autograph
session, Rafter said he still hoped to raise his racket next week
in time to successfully defend his title.
</P>
<P>
   Aching or not, the upbeat Australian promised he'd be back at
Arthur Ashe Stadium, site of his only two Grand Slam championships,
to try to become the first man since Ivan Lendl (1985-87) to win
three straight Opens.
</P>
<P>
   Will he play? No question. Can he win again? He has his doubts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing best-of-5 sets, it's got to be pretty much 100
percent, or 90 percent anyway,'' Rafter said of his suspect
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   The shoulder also pained him at the start of the 1997 Open.
``But I didn't feel it then after the second week,'' he said. He
feels it now, even when he sleeps, but ``even if it's worse than
this, I'll be playing the Open: I mean, that's too big a priority
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with Rafter's possessiveness about this title, there's the
iron man streak of 26 consecutive Grand Slam events that he has
been compiling since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not about to miss this one,'' said Rafter, who failed to
pass the Open's third round on his first four visits to Flushing
Meadows. ``It would have been third on my list in terms of Slam
expectations. Sort of freaky to have won it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafter silenced his critics, notably John McEnroe and Pete
Sampras, by defying a one-Slam-wonder label and winning the Open a
second time last year despite entering it unconvinced of his
ability to defend his title. ``Last year, I would have said,
`Please don't put any money on me to repeat; there's no bloody
way,''' he said. ``But this year, I came in thinking I could win it
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Sampras, a four-time Open champion, and Andre Agassi, who
won his only Open in 1994, have put on a summer hardcourts clinic,
Rafter can't be counted out.
</P>
<P>
   After a sluggish start in 1999, Rafter reached the Italian Open
final on clay and went 10-1 on grass. His semifinal finish at
Wimbledon was his best ever, and he proceeded from there to a 10-2
summer hardcourts record that included Australia's dismissal of the
United States in the Davis Cup quarterfinals in Boston last month.
</P>
<P>
   But ever since Sampras burned a serve right through his racquet
strings during the first-set tie breaker of their Aug. 15 final at
Cincinnati, a 7-6 (9-7), 6-3 Sampras victory, Rafter's shoulder
hasn't stopped complaining. He tried to play in Indianapolis last
week but pulled out after the quarterfinals, then canceled this
week's title defense at the Hamlet Cup on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter said the week he spent at No. 1 at the end of July made
him hunger for more time at the top, a space Sampras has occupied
for a record 274 weeks. Rafter also said that knocking Sampras out
of last year's Open was among the most satisfying victories of his
career, but one he felt Sampras diminished by claiming a hamstring
pull.
</P>
<P>
   After sniping at each other in the news media, a feud began last
summer when Sampras disparaged Rafter's Grand Slam production after
losing to him at Cincinnati. And it escalated to the point where
headlines claimed they hated each other. Then last month, Rafter
put in a conciliatory call to Sampras. ``I don't like to be enemies
with anyone,'' he explained, adding that he was relieved when
Sampras responded in kind. ``I was sitting there sweating bullets
that he'd chew my head off.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rafter doesn't even hold a grudge against the 130 MPH. Sampras
serve that hurt his shoulder, shaking it off as an occupational
hazard _ one he'd prefer to avoid at the Open. ``Pete's probably
the No. 1 guy to beat,'' he said. ``But I'll be one of 128 guys
that says he's the one to beat. There are plenty out there to
beat.''
</P>
<P>
   And that includes the ponytailed two-time defending champion.
Rafter commuted back to Bermuda Monday with his trainer in tow but
vowed to resurface at the National Tennis Center on Friday, three
days before the hunt for his title begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``To defend it, to try to do it three times in a row, that's
exciting,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
