<HEADER>
A7093 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-OHIO-CONVICTS-COX     08-23 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-CONVICTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Packages to convicts won't get new limits for now
 &HT;    By Tom Beyerlein
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Families and friends of Ohio convicts won at
least a temporary victory Monday, as state prison officials hit a
roadblock in their proposal to put new limits on packages that
inmates can get from home.
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials agreed to go back to the drawing board after
the legislative Joint Committee on Agency Review expressed concerns
about the plan, which would reduce the allowable number of packages
from the outside world and could eventually eliminate such packages
and require inmates to order sundry items from a state-approved
vendor's catalog. The goal is to cut down on contraband smuggling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's only humane that they should be able to receive
things from home,'' said Brenda Hopfer, of Centerville, one of
several prisoner advocates who testified before the committee. She
and her husband, Kenneth, who also testified, are the parents of
Rebecca Hopfer, who is serving 15 years to life in the Ohio
Reformatory for Women in Marysville for killing her newborn baby in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   Inmates currently are allowed to receive four packages of
sundries, such as extra clothing items, and two packages of food
per year from approved visitors, such as family and friends. The
proposal would allow one to four packages a year, depending on an
inmate's security level. In-person visits and unlimited letters
would not be affected by the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Supermaximum-security'' inmates aren't allowed any packages,
and that wouldn't change.
</P>
<P>
   J. Donald Mottley, R-West Carrollton, chairman of the committee,
said the committee balked because prison officials didn't analyze
the financial impact of the change on the prisons or inmate family
members. The committee also felt the proposed rule gave prison
officials too much latitude to set policy without legislative
review.
</P>
<P>
   James Guy, staff counsel for the Ohio Department of
Rehabilitation and Correction, said he believes officials will be
able to redraft the proposal to satisfy the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials say the change is aimed at reducing the amount
of contraband such as drugs, weapons and gang-related clothing that
gets into Ohio prisons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to provide a safe and secure environment for not only
the inmates, but any visitors and for the prison staff,'' Guy said
before the committee meeting.
</P>
<P>
   They also say it would give officials the flexibility to change
the kinds of sundries allowed, or go to an all-catalog system.
Under such a system, families would send money and inmates would
order approved items from a catalog vendor specializing in prison
work. Several Ohio prisons are trying a no-packages-from-home
policy on a pilot basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying we're going to stop packages (from home) from
coming in, but it gives us the option of doing that,'' said
department spokesman Joe Andrews. He said ``we've seen people who
have ingenious ways'' of doctoring packages to smuggle contraband
past prison officials who fluoroscope, open and inspect them.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents say the proposal would unfairly punish all inmates for
the violations of a few, sever important family ties and cause
hardships on family members, who would no longer be able to shop
for bargains. They also say it would cause accounting nightmares,
and they dispute prison officials' position that no new staff would
be needed to implement the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``The broader concern is, this is part of a pattern of taking
more and more and more privileges away,'' said prisoner advocate
Jana Schroeder, of the American Friends Service Committee of
Dayton, a Quaker peace and justice group. She said the rule could
contribute to prison unrest.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Beyerlein writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
