<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Primaries Scheduled
</P>
<P>
   The three largest political parties have scheduled their first
presidential primary elections for this fall. Members of the
center-right National Action Party will pick their nominee on Sept.
12, even though only one candidate has registered for the
balloting: the Guanajuato governor, Vicente Fox. The center-left
Party of the Democratic Revolution has scheduled its vote for Oct.
10, with Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, the Mexico City mayor, the only
candidate certain to take part, although others may register.
President Ernesto Zedillo's Institutional Revolutionary Party's
primary will be on Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Students Clash
</P>
<P>
   Six people were hurt when students supporting the 4-month-old
strike at the National Autonomous University of Mexico threw
homemade shrapnel bombs filled with metal coins at marchers
protesting the strike. It was the second clash in four days between
student factions, and took place when strikers sought to block the
advance of the anti-strike demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuela: Colombian Sites Targeted
</P>
<P>
   A small bomb exploded outside the Colombian Consulate in
Caracas, and a police search turned up explosives at two more
Colombian government offices. A guerrilla group called Los
Tupamaros took responsibility for the blast, which came as tensions
between Colombia and Venezuela climbed. President Hugo Chavez of
Venezuela has said he will meet with Colombian guerrillas without
approval from the Colombian government.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina: Menem's Money
</P>
<P>
   In a sworn statement, President Carlos Saul Menem declared that
his net worth was $1.7 million, including two houses, two
apartments, three cars, a plane and a racehorse. Opposition leaders
said that Menem was lying, and that he had acquired an enormous
fortune through corrupt acts, a charge that Menem denied.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Germany: Optimism on Slave Compensation
</P>
<P>
   Otto Lambsdorff, the government's negotiator on compensation for
Nazi slave workers, said he was ``cautiously optimistic'' about
talks on a settlement. Representatives of the former slave workers,
the German and American governments and Jewish groups will meet in
Bonn on Tuesday for a new round of negotiations. They are trying to
work out a compensation deal with 16 German companies for an
estimated 1 million survivors of slave labor and forced labor
camps.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   Cambodia: U.N. Center
</P>
<P>
   The government agreed to allow the U.N. Center for Human Rights
in Phnom Penh to remain open for another year, turning down a
request for a two-year extension. The center, the first to be set
up by the United Nations in any country, was designed to teach
people haunted by the Khmer Rouge years how to monitor and
safeguard human rights, and to serve as a documentation center for
past atrocities. It has been opposed by Prime Minister Hun Sen.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   Angola: Malnutrition's Deadly Toll
</P>
<P>
   Every day at least 200 people are dying in Angola of illnesses
related to malnutrition, and 1.7 million people are homeless, U.N.
aid experts told the Security Council. Catherine Bertini, executive
director of the World Food Program, said Angola, a potentially rich
country torn for three decades by civil war, was ``living at a
level of despair that exists virtually nowhere else in the world
today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
