<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-ECOLOGY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROP BUSTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a big difference between caution and hysteria. Galloping
scientific progress demands that society exercise the first, but no
one is served by the second.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental extremists who destroy genetically altered crops,
supposedly to save the world, are not only breaking the law, as
they did last week at the University of Maine, but are stopping the
very research that can tell people about the risks of growing such
plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be that I find that farmers shouldn't be using this
crop,'' says John Jemison, water quality specialist at the
University of Maine's cooperative extension service. ``But I won't
know until I study it. The people responsible for this didn't even
want me to try.''
</P>
<P>
   Jemison's half-acre of corn, which was being tested in a weed
control project on university land in Old Town, Maine, was slashed
to the ground last week, and a group calling itself ``Seeds of
Resistance'' has claimed credit for the vandalism through a posting
on a Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The posting is full of misguided bravado, promising that the
Maine attack ``is the first in a series of actions'' and announcing
that ``there is absolutely no benefit to humanity'' in Jemison's
project.
</P>
<P>
   But Jemison was testing corn with a resistance to the herbicide
Roundup, which does not leach into ground water, soil, or plant
tissue as much as other weed killers do. The project, funded
primarily by university money _ the seeds were donated by a
subsidiary of Monsanto Corp. _ would have told farmers what sort of
yield they could expect.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the zealots, Jemison will have to start over next
spring. Such misdirected fear is prompting similar crop vandalism
in Europe, particularly in Britain, where protesters equate
genetically altered crops with mad cow disease.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing wrong with peaceful protest or with insisting
that troubling eco-questions be answered. But slashing an
experiment and attempting to stop science is the height of
ignorance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
