<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-LESLIE-SPARKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LESLIE HAS PROVIDED THE SPARKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The pressure and the expectations were there
from the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, the Los Angeles Sparks were convinced they
received the cornerstone of a successful WNBA franchise when Lisa
Leslie was assigned to them. Who better to take the team on title
runs than a former Olympian, All-American and national player of
the year?
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't happened, although it would be hard to blame Leslie.
She produced, but her team didn't: 14-14 in the innaugural season
and 12-18 last year.
</P>
<P>
   It was enough to cause the 6-foot-5 center to question her
ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very frustrating because I know that we had the
potential to do that on paper. It's just that we never played
together,'' Leslie said. ``It's different when you don't have the
talent, but we had talent and we had beaten everybody in the WNBA
both years, except last year we didn't beat Houston. It makes you
kind of question yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   After two coaching changes, the firing of a general manager and
the installation of a new defense, Leslie and the Sparks finally
are in the playoffs. They finished second in the Western Conference
and face the Sacramento Monarchs in a single-elimination game
tonight at 6 at the Forum. If they win, they will host two-time
defending champion Houston in the first of a three-game series
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   While her numbers are down by almost four points and two
rebounds a game, Leslie's effectiveness is up.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year my role has changed somewhat, but it's been a lot
happier than the last years,'' said Leslie, who's averaging 15.7
points and 7.9 rebounds, compared to 19.6 and 9.5 last season.
``It's a lot easier than feeling like I just have to score every
shot and force shots when I'm doubled and tripled in order for us
to get points.''
</P>
<P>
   Teams couldn't focus solely on Leslie because of former ABL
players DeLisha Milton (first-round draft pick) and La'Keisha Frett
(fourth round).
</P>
<P>
   ``That's very tough, because being a marquee player, a lot is
expected of you,'' Milton said. ``She's criticized and always put
under a microscope. She's scrutinized for every little thing. I
think it takes one heck of a person or individual who can withstand
something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Leslie's improved stats is 3-point shooting. This year,
she's 20 of 48 (42 percent). The past two years, she was a combined
30 percent (21 of 69).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely feeling more confident about that shot this
year, and I think not having to be the one to get all the rebounds
with DeLisha down there, I can afford to take that shot,'' Leslie
said.
</P>
<P>
   She has taken and made that shot much more since winning the
Most Valuable Player award at the inaugural WNBA All-Star Game on
July 14. The Sparks went on a six-game win streak, Leslie averaging
19.6 points during that stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd be surprised how you'd go to an All-Star Game and win
the Most Valuable Player award, what that does,'' Sparks coach
Orlando Woolridge said. ``It gives you a shot in the arm. I could
see it in her face. She came back with so much confidence after
that. Since that All-Star Game, it's like she has a new shot of
energy. There's no question about it. When she goes, so do we go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
