<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7113 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-BLASS-FASHION-ART-2TA     08-23 1456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLASS-FASHION-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLASS: AN AMERICAN ORIGINAL, SEEN ONLY IN SILHOUETTE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN:   Ind., Conn., France, Britain)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A few years ago, in his office at 550 Seventh Avenue
_ amid the book-lined shelves, the bound volumes of Vogue and
Harper's Bazaar from the 1950s, the portraits of Diana Vreeland and
Marlene Dietrich, the bibelots, the awards and the beat and hum of
the midtown traffic _ Bill Blass was at his desk scanning another
magazine article about himself.
</P>
<P>
   He looked remarkably well-preserved considering that he was then
facing 75 and had spent a lifetime standing in Park Avenue drawing
rooms with his hands in his pockets, his jacket hooked up over
them, a cigarette dangling from his bored lips. Somewhere in his
impressionable Midwestern youth, he had acquired, along with the
rich tone of a foreign-service officer (Cary Grant in
``Charade''?), the habit of calling women ``babe'' or ``kid.''
</P>
<P>
   The way he could growl ``babe'' before telling a woman to do
something with her hair _ well, it had a curious effect. It added
to his sexual appeal, for one thing. There is no telling how many
men and women, especially women, have fallen in love with him, and
even harbored vain hopes of matrimony. But that is another story.
</P>
<P>
   Up in his office, Blass _ whose friends call him Blass or Willie
B. or, as the late designer Jacques Tiffeau did, ``Bilbo'' _ was
looking over the article with faint interest. It had a couple of
paragraphs about his Indiana childhood, how he went to the movies a
lot, followed by his senatorial thoughts on style. It seemed a
press agent's dream.
</P>
<P>
   He snapped the magazine shut and sent it skidding across the
desk. The most famous American designer of them all _ the first to
market his name in a big way, the first to break out of the old
Seventh Avenue formula, the first to see that style plus money
equaled a new kind of excitement _ turned out to be no open book at
all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' he said, breaking into a boyish grin, adding that
he had been saying all that ``for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometime fairly soon, Blass expects to sell his
$700-million-a-year company with its constellation of 40 licenses.
With such a deal, he would no longer be involved in the day-to-day
operations of the company, which he has owned exclusively since
1970, when he bought out his former partners at Maurice Rentner,
the dress house that had employed him beginning in the 1950s, and
formed Bill Blass Ltd. Blass, who has spoken often of retiring _ he
turned 77 in June _ said he expected to play a consulting role,
overseeing collections and making personal appearances to promote
the brand and its perfume.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers are eager for him to. ``We have trunk shows with Bill
in New York where he breaks $1 million in sales,'' said Philip
Miller, the president of Saks Fifth Avenue. Saks said that last
week in California, following Blass' 30th-anniversary benefit show
at Lake Tahoe, where the suntanned crowd included many San
Francisco clients and one lady who arrived by seaplane, Saks sold
$700,000 of his fall and resort clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Bill elects to stay in the game, we will have a big
business with him as far as I can see,'' Miller said, hoping to
avoid what happened after Adolfo shut his doors. ``We had a
wonderful, big-time business with him, but that business just went
away, and we were not able to capture the customer.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, aside from the simple irony that it was Bill Blass who
helped put Adolfo into business with $10,000 of his own money, it
should be obvious to almost anybody that no designer has more
profoundly influenced American life. More than Ralph Lauren, more
than Calvin Klein or anyone else who came along later, he changed
the status of designers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, you've got to thank Bill Blass for making American
fashion respectable,'' said John Fairchild, the former chairman of
Women's Wear Daily. ``In the old days, the fashion designers were
chained to their back desks on Seventh Avenue. They never came out,
never were seen or heard from. They were just little characters who
did the work. And Bill made them respectable and powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   In the era Fairchild was describing, the 1940s and 50s, Seventh
Avenue was a venal place. At some firms designers weren't allowed
to ride in the same elevator with their bosses. Blass started
changing things.
</P>
<P>
   In 1946, he had come back from the war, where he had served in
Europe with the 603rd Engineer Camouflage Battalion, an outfit that
also included the artist Ellsworth Kelly and George Diestal, the
Hollywood set designer, and whose job was to obscure the movements
of other troops by using decoys like inflatable rubber tanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was still very thin and blond and in my uniform,'' Blass
said of his return to New York. ``There was a whole cafe society
that was in its full glory. You went from El Morocco to the Blue
Angel to Monte Carlo to the 1-2-3. Nothing seemed to cost much in
those days.''
</P>
<P>
   But if New York was a swinging place, the upper reaches were
hardly open-minded toward dress designers _ even a good-looking one
with perfect manners and a posh accent. He rarely told people what
he did. ``If it came up,'' Blass recalled, ``I'd say something
offhand, like I worked in advertising.'' He added: ``I was always
much more comfortable in a heterosexual world than a homosexual
one. That in itself may have set me apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, he met people like Missy Bancroft, a post-debutante
who modeled on Seventh Avenue; Chessy Rayner, then an editor at
Glamour, and Nicolas de Gunzburg, a socially-connected editor who
brought him to the attention of Mrs. Vreeland.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview before she died last year, Mrs. Rayner said:
``He really got on the bandwagon early, by getting a certain woman
to wear his clothes. I'm not saying he went after them, but if they
came to him, he opened the door. Not just a crack, but all the way.
So he really got everyone in town wearing those dresses. The effect
was that people out in the sticks were dying to wear them, too.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   By the time Mrs. Vreeland went barreling into Maurice Rentner,
demanding to be taken into the back room to meet the young
blue-eyed Englishman she had heard so much about, Bill Blass had
already crossed that threshold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, if you want to talk about Claire McCardell or Bonnie
Cashin _ fine,'' Fairchild said, citing the obvious examples of
American ingenuity. ``But they never really caught on the way Bill
did. He did create American style. Norman Norell was a copy of
Chanel or Saint Laurent, and Galanos was pure European copy. But
Bill absolutely created a look that was strictly American.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Other designers have done things that are more daring than
putting a camel's hair polo coat over a sequined dress, or a
cashmere twin set with a taffeta ball gown. A lot have made more
money. But no designer has spent his career working entirely within
an American ethos. It's as if everything Blass has done over the
last 50 years has been run through the same exquisite filter.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't confined to making clothes or useful connections with
socialites. You can see it in his homes, too, in the almost
ruthless way he has pared down his New York apartment and house in
Connecticut. Every piece is exceptional. ``But not one thing in a
room ever jumps out at you,'' his friend Nancy Kissinger said.
``It's an incredible feeling of calm.''
</P>
<P>
   One can think of any number of designers _ Ralph Lauren _ who
have influenced the field. But how many have done so purely on the
basis of their personal style? ``The important thing about Bill,''
the decorator Stephen Sills said, ``is that he is the only American
designer who has an original point of view about his interiors. He
isn't copying anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   He started designing men's wear in the mid-1960s and made a
huge, splashy success of it. But the thing that really put Bill
Blass over was that he took his clothes on the road. He got to know
the social life of cities like Denver and Phoenix. ``Bill is a cult
figure,'' Nan Kempner said. ``There is the cult of Bill Blass from
one end of this country to the other.''
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, he knew about Saturday night in America. He knew
about East Coast taste, the right plate and so forth. He knew about
the business of Seventh Avenue, the raving egos, but above all, how
much money could be made. Bill Blass wasn't at the intersection of
American fashion and society. He was the intersection.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   Yet, hardly anyone has been able to do much more than describe
the parts. ``I can tell you that Bill has suffered his whole
life,'' said Tom Fallon, who worked for him for more than 20 years.
``He's been a great social success in New York. His success in the
fashion establishment has been a more tenuous affair.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s, when Blass was up for a lifetime achievement
award from the Council of Fashion Designers of America, a group of
editors opposed him, arguing that he wasn't creative enough. But
Perry Ellis, who was then the organization's president, insisted,
Fallon recalled. Such slights were wounding, he added, but perhaps
none more so than the perception that Mrs. Vreeland, whom Blass
often escorted, had favored others over him in Vogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, Bill took everything in stride,'' Fallon said. ``He
would give you the impression that a lot of the detail didn't
matter. It all mattered to him. And he could make you crazy
because, in the beginning, you thought he didn't care about these
little things. But he recorded everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Blass is someone whose savoir-faire and good looks, combined
with a dry wit, have helped to deflect attention away from himself.
Very few of his friends know, for instance, about his childhood _
his father's suicide when he was 5 _ or how the war years seemed to
liberate everything in him. When asked if she had ever asked Blass
about his Indiana years, Marguerite Littman, a friend in London,
laughed and said: ``Childhoods bore me. We're very close without
asking personal questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all the American designers, Oscar de la Renta has had the
closest friendship with Blass, and he said: ``Bill is sort of a
silent friend. You know he is always there. In that sense, he is
one of the most solid people I know.'' But he added, ``If you want
to get something out of Bill, you have to fish very, very deeply.''
He could never learn, for instance, why Blass abruptly broke off
his friendship with Slim Keith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you Bill's personal life is practically verboten,''
Fairchild said. ``I think he's terrified of getting involved with
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Blass, sitting one afternoon in his Connecticut house, laughed
when told of something Mrs. Rayner had said about his decorating
style. She said: ``It's not the most comfortable house in the
world. I mean, we've all discussed it. He gets a few comfortable
chairs and then the dogs sit in them.'' Asked to interpret, she
replied, ``I guess it says he doesn't like having too many people
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Blass smiled. ``Absolutely true,'' he said. ``Bravo for her to
have said that.''
</P>
<P>
   He did speak of what it meant to grow up in a small town, at the
height of the Depression, when things were left unspoken. ``There
was always a sense of something hidden,'' he said. ``And I've found
that this is certainly the guide to my own adulthood, my own life.
Really my own inability to relate to people in a very, very
personal level, and rarely do I.''
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke, one got a picture of a good-looking man, just shy
of his 80th birthday, leaving all that behind and going East. He'd
probably laugh at that and say, ``It sounds like a million kids out
of Indiana, babe.'' Still, something set him apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of living is the talent to survive, and this guy is a
survivor,'' Tom Fallon said. ``You could go down the list of those
big talents _ whatever happened to ... ? And Bill Blass, Bill
Blass, Bill Blass has stayed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-99 2223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
