<DOCNO> NYT19990823.0417 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7117 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-OPTIONS-BRAWL-NYT &LR;      08-23 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPTIONS-BRAWL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OLD-FASHIONED BRAWL AMONG OPTIONS EXCHANGES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Ill.)  (mk) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Facing new challenges from electronic trading systems
and regulatory inquiries into anticompetitive practices, the
nation's leading options exchanges opted Monday for an
old-fashioned market brawl.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Board Options Exchange and the American Stock
Exchange fired the opening salvo Monday morning by listing options
of Dell Computer Corp., which for years had been traded exclusively
on the Philadelphia Stock Exchange. The two won huge market share
on the first day of trading.
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia Stock Exchange struck back by listing options
in Johnson &AMP; Johnson, IBM, Coca-Cola and Apple Computer _ stock
options that traded primarily or exclusively on the Chicago and
American exchanges. The Philex, as it is known, won back some
market share.
</P>
<P>
   In the world of options trading, the cross-listing battle
promises to shake up the nation's leading exchanges and prepare
them for competition from low-cost electronic trading systems that
some fear may steal away significant market share.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday the main exchanges said they were pleased with the
new competitive environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new era in the options business,'' said William
Brodsky, the chairman and chief executive of the Chicago Board
Options Exchange, the world's largest options exchange. ``The
competitive juices are flowing.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the Chicago exchange that made the first move last week
by announcing that it would break the Philadelphia exchange's
stranglehold on Dell, one of the most popular options listings. A
day later, the American Stock Exchange, the No. 2 player in
options, said it, too, would list options in Dell.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, on the first day of trading, officials at the Chicago
exchange said it traded more than 59,000 contracts, about 37
percent of the market; they said Philadelphia traded 68,000, or
about 43 percent of the market, and the American Stock Exchange
traded 31,000, or 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The trading in Dell was far higher than normal, officials at the
Chicago and Philadelphia exchanges said, but they attributed it in
part to increased competition and a strong earnings report from
Dell last week.
</P>
<P>
   There were rumblings, however, from traders in Philadelphia that
the Chicago traders were illegally ``painting the tape'' _ or
inflating volume by trading among themselves _ but officials at the
Chicago Exchange dismissed such notions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because there's increased volume doesn't mean they're
painting the tape,''said Lynne Howard, a spokeswoman at the Chicago
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer Frucher, the chief executive at the Philadelphia exchange,
said that despite losing market share in Dell, the exchange had
kept its volume high and proved that its trading technology was
sound.
</P>
<P>
   Frucher said that Dell options had been shifted to the American
exchange's floor, but after a planned merger between the two broke
down, the options were returned to Philadelphia. He said Chicago
officials were trying to steal market share away because some
feared technology weakness in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of folks didn't send their order flow here because they
were worried about the technology,'' he said. ``That question was
answered Monday. For us it was a very successful day.''
</P>
<P>
   Frucher also said they won small market share gains in Apple,
IBM and Coke and gained a 50 percent share of Johnson &AMP; Johnson, a
smaller Chicago listing.
</P>
<P>
   The changes were brought about, in part, because of concerns
about the International Securities Exchange, an electronic trading
system that plans to trade in the 500 most active options beginning
next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than a year ago, I rallied the troops and said, `Do you
want someone to determine your future or do you want to act?'''
Brodsky said in an interview Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year, the Justice Department has also been looking
into anticompetitive pricing on the exchanges, another factor that
seems to have pushed the exchanges into a more competitive
environment.
</P>
<P>
   Though Philadelphia has the most to lose because Dell options
make up about 30 percent of its business, Frucher said he was
confident. ``In the long run, Philadelphia will be stronger in a
multilisted trading environment,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
