<SLUG> BC-SEMTECH-TURNAROUND-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEMTECH UPBEAT ON EARNINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JASON TAKENOUCHI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Nearly a year after the Asian crisis battered
semiconductor maker Semtech Corp., the firm based in Newbury Park,
40 miles northwest of Los Angeles,is on the rebound.
</P>
<P>
   The company has said it expects to beat analysts' projections in
its earnings report for the quarter that ended Aug. 1, which will
be released after the close of markets Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus of analysts surveyed by First Call Corp. is 31
cents per share. Last year, the company reported second quarter
earnings of 24 cents a share on revenues of $24.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock has already experienced a stunning
turnaround, rising from a low of around $10.375 last year to a high
of $70.75 this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've come back quite nicely since the correction of 1998,''
said Arun Veerappan, an analyst with BancBoston Robertson Stephens.
</P>
<P>
   Veerappan said Semtech has benefited from the booming demand for
switches and regulators for under-$1,000 computers, where the firm
has a relatively high market share, and for voltage suppression
products that protect circuits from voltage surges.
</P>
<P>
   Veerappan estimated the company would announce earnings of 31
cents a share for the second quarter on revenues of $35.7 million.
For the year ending in January 2000, he estimated earnings of $1.29
a share on revenues of $149 million.
</P>
<P>
   The company announced July 28 that it would beat analysts'
forecasts for the quarter ending Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Semtech shares closed at $68 Monday, up 50 cents on
lower-than-average trading volume.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
