<HEADER>
A7122 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TEXAS-STORM-2NDLD-WRI     08-23 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-STORM-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORM PULLED ITS PUNCH, AS IT MOVED INLAND IN RURAL TEXAS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to add explanation for role of trees   in graf beginning:
Sitting behind...)   By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARITA, Texas _ If there is such a thing as a perfect spot for a
hurricane to come ashore, Kenedy County might be it. The flat,
green pastures are filled with wild oaks and mesquite instead of
shopping centers and subdivisions. There is not a store, restaurant
or gas station in this county called home by only 460 people.
</P>
<P>
   But if you are one of those 460, perfect is not the right word
at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all make jokes about it,'' J.A. Garcia, a county judge,
said inside the darkened county courthouse as a thunderstorm
crackled overhead Monday afternoon. ``There are people who are
living here.''
</P>
<P>
   On the day after Hurricane Bret slowly pushed ashore onto the
South Texas coastline, people awoke to find most buildings still
standing and lives spared; not a single fatality or serious injury
was reported. Initially compared in its potential for destruction
to Hurricane Andrew, this storm picked a path as if it were trying
to avoid people, grinding steadily through the vast ranch lands
halfway between Brownsville and Corpus Christi as it was downgraded
to a tropical storm.
</P>
<P>
   But federal officials were still cautioning Monday that flooding
was possible as the storm moved inland and stalled near Laredo,
dumping heavy amounts of rain. Federal officials closed the three
bridges over the Rio Grande as a precautionary measure, blocking
traffic on both sides of the border. Sporadic flooding was reported
in some Laredo neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   With the storm moving well inland from the South Texas coast,
city officials in Corpus Christi began allowing evacuated residents
to return home late Monday. About 30 miles to the south, more than
16,000 people remained without power, many of them in Kingsville,
as utility workers struggled to restore electricity. Yet for a
region that has not endured a major hurricane in more than 20
years, the fears that prompted thousands of people to evacuate the
coast were replaced by relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were lucky, man,'' said Sam Delarosa, the kitchen manager
of Snoopy's Cafe, located on Padre Island, the barrier island
stretching down the coast. ``Very, very lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials had warned that a tidal surge of 12 feet could cause
flooding inland as well as tremendous damage to the low-lying
barrier islands. But the tidal surge apparently never happened.
From Port Aransas as far south as Malaquite Beach on the Padre
Island National Seashore, the damage was light. ``That tide hasn't
gone up more than a foot or two, and the wind must have just blown
all that water back out into the Gulf,'' Delarosa said.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting behind his desk inside the Kenedy County Courthouse,
Sheriff Rafael M. Cuellar Jr. offered his own theory of why the
storm weakened as it came inland: trees. Kenedy County _ which has
nearly a million acres of pasture land, much of it divided between
the Kenedy Ranch and the King Ranch, the two largest ranches in
Texas _ is covered in oaks, mesquite and cactus, which, the sheriff
said, absorbed the storm's power like a sponge.
</P>
<P>
   The terrain is so desolate, and so stultifying in the summer,
that illegal immigrants walking through the pastures north toward
Houston often succumb to the elements in Kenedy County. Last month,
Cuellar said the bodies of four illegal immigrants were found in
the brush dead from the heat.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The isolation infuses every aspect of life in Kenedy County.
With the closest convenience store a 5-mile drive from Sarita, the
county seat, the sheriff said people become accustomed to living
apart from the modern world. ``Anybody who wants a Coke has to come
up here and get it from the courthouse,'' the sheriff said, nodding
toward the drink machine.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But when people learned of the approaching storm, many of them
sought shelter. Most of Sarita's 200 residents gathered in the
local Roman Catholic church or schoolhouse. In the early hours
Monday morning, the storm's worst winds tore through Sarita and
Falfurrias, about 25 miles to the west, uprooting trees and downing
power lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was bad,'' said Cuellar, although he noted everyone in the
shelters got along. ``They all knew each other,'' he said. ``More
than half of them are related. You don't have problems like in big
cities where they don't want to be close to one another.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Genho, vice president for livestock for the King Ranch,
said the 825,000-acre ranch lost about 25,000 acres of cotton and
suffered extensive damage to trees and various buildings and
windmills. He said the Norias division in the Ranch in Kenedy
County, absorbed the full brunt of the southern eye of the storm.
``We were extremely blessed,'' Genho said. ``I have been in a lot
of hurricanes having lived in Florida most of my life. When you get
a Class 4 hurricane, that's scary anywhere. There's a lot of
potential for damage.''
</P>
<P>
   At the courthouse in the afternoon, sheriff's deputies returned
after canvassing the county for damages. They had seen many downed
trees, but everyone agreed it could have been far worse.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CAN END HERE.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   All of that was good news for Cuellar.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I need most is to go to sleep because I haven't slept in
two nights,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-99 2239EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990823.0422 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7123 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f BC-DISNEY-RETIREES-LADN     08-23 0416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-RETIREES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY SETTLES BENEFITS DISPUTE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The Walt Disney Co., averting a potentially
embarrassing legal spat with 3,800 longtime employees, has agreed
to settle a dispute over medical benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal ends a five-year fight that began when the
entertainment giant decided to change its policy that gave 20-year
employees free medical coverage for life once they reached the age
of 62. In March, a federal judge in Los Angeles gave class-action
status to a lawsuit accusing Disney of illegally charging for
health benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is a very good settlement, especially
considering that many other companies are eliminating these kinds
of benefits,'' plaintiff's attorney William T. Payne said Monday.
``We had a meeting of plaintiffs in Florida this morning, and
people seemed to be very happy about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Payne said lawyers for both sides expect to file a joint
settlement motion next month in federal court. ``The judgment could
be effective in February if everything goes smoothly,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was sparked by a 1994 decision by Disney to boost the
age eligibility for free coverage to 65; in 1995, it began charging
premiums unless the employees and retirees joined a health
maintenance organization. Payne said changes in the medical plans
led to a typical couple paying $1,023 in annual premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Disney contended its contracts allowed it to impose charges when
the costs of coverage increased, but the employees insisted Disney
managers had been explicit in their pledge of free coverage for any
employee meeting three conditions _ 62 years of age, 20 years of
service and 30,000 hours of work.
</P>
<P>
   Disney and the plaintiffs reached a tentative settlement on the
suit in late 1997 but that deal collapsed amid accusations Disney
had planned to make additional changes not specified in the
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Payne said the new settlement calls for reducing the annual
premium for a typical couple to $102 and returning premiums paid
since the plans were changed. Maximum out-of-pocket expense for a
family was boosted from $1,500 to $2,100 per year.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement also covers employees who had worked for 20 years
for Disney but had not retired when the changes were made. That
group will be paid $4,500 each and have company-paid Medicare
supplemental insurance for five years.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
