u a BC-BRET24-COX     08-23 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRET24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bret dwindles to tropical storm after leaving surprisingly
little aftermath
 &HT;    By Ralph K.M. Haurwitz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Thousands of people along the Texas coastline
were forced to find shelter inland. Still more in a vast area of
South Texas lost electrical power. Laredo had to shut down three
international bridges and its airport. And runoff could spread an
outbreak of dengue fever, a tropical disease carried by mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   But overall, Hurricane Bret and its progeny, Tropical Storm
Bret, had caused surprisingly little damage to life and property by
Monday evening. Relief was palpable, from the state's emergency
operations center 40 feet underground in North Austin to the
wide-open brush country south of Corpus Christi and north of
Brownsville where the storm swept in from the Gulf of Mexico on
Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hurricane Bret kicked a field goal. It went right between
Brownsville and Kingsville where there is plenty of open space,''
said Kingsville Mayor Phil Esquivel.
</P>
<P>
   There were no reports of injuries or deaths. The storm tore off
some roofs in Falfurrias and caused minor flooding along the Nueces
River north of Corpus Christi. It threatened to cause more serious
flooding Monday evening and this morning as it drove west toward
the Rio Grande at Laredo. Up to 12 inches of rain was expected to
fall between Laredo and Eagle Pass. As much as 24 inches fell in a
24-hour period in a narrow band of ranch country along U.S. 77 in
Kenedy County.
</P>
<P>
   Bret turned out to have more feather and less whip for several
reasons. Foremost was its fortuitous landfall, at perhaps the most
lightly populated stretch of coastline anywhere in the nation, said
Tom Millwee, director of emergency management for Texas. Fewer than
500 people live in Kenedy County, where Bret drove ashore after
first touching down on Padre Island, a barrier island with little
development in that stretch.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Bret was rather compressed as hurricanes go,
meaning that its high-velocity winds did not stretch too far from
the eye. Also, Bret lost horsepower abruptly just before and after
landfall, quickly dropping to 80 miles per hour from a peak of 140
mph. And prompt warnings by the National Weather Service, coupled
with evacuations organized by local and state officials, ensured
that many people got out of harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these were factors that worked in our favor,'' said
Brad Gair, the coordinating officer assigned to Bret by the Federal
Emergency Management Agency.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, in response to a request by Gov. George W.
Bush, declared seven coastal counties eligible for limited federal
disaster assistance. Under Clinton's declaration, the federal
government will pay 75 percent of the cost of debris removal and
emergency protective services incurred by state and local officials
in Aransas, San Patricio, Nueces, Kenedy, Kleberg, Cameron and
Willacy counties.
</P>
<P>
   State officials were still hoping for an additional declaration
from the White House that would provide assistance to individuals,
including temporary housing, replacement of appliances and
out-of-pocket expenses. Federal officials said Monday that damages
were still being assessed and that no overall dollar estimate of
damages had been calculated.
</P>
<P>
   Bret, downgraded from hurricane to tropical storm at 8 a.m.
Monday, now poses primarily a flooding hazard, said Jack Colley,
the state's assistant director of emergency management. Swift-water
rescue teams, high-clearance vehicles and rescue aircraft were
being stationed in Laredo and other South Texas cities in
anticipation of floodwaters, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't stop a storm, but at least you can lessen the
impact,'' Colley said during a briefing at the emergency center at
Texas Department of Public Safety headquarters in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   It could be days before electrical power is fully restored.
Three of four major power lines serving the lower Rio Grande Valley
were knocked out of service. Central Power &AMP; Light Co. estimated
that as many as 60,000 customers lost power in scattered areas,
including Corpus Christi, Kingsville, Falfurrias, Port Aransas,
Rockport, McAllen, Mission, Edinburg and Weslaco. By 5 p.m. Monday,
the damaged main lines had been repaired and power was restored to
all but about 10,000 customers, said Jessica Mahaffey, a
spokeswoman for the utility. Crews were working house by house to
repair transformers and power lines in numerous neighborhoods, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials worried that rain and flooding could cause additional
power outages as the storm moves west toward Laredo, Eagle Pass and
Del Rio. It was in Del Rio on Aug. 23 and 24 of last year that 18
inches of rain caused deadly flooding and extensive property
damage.
</P>
<P>
   Bret's damage, at least so far, has been fairly minor.
</P>
<P>
   The King Ranch in Kenedy County reported downed trees but no
livestock losses on one of the country's largest cattle operations,
founded in 1853 by riverboat captain Richard King. Ranch President
Jack Hunt said all 300 people who live and work on 825,000 acres
tending 60,000 head of cattle were evacuated before the storm hit.
The cattle were left to fend for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``About all you can do is open the gates and make sure the
cattle can go where they need to go,'' Hunt said.
</P>
<P>
   In Port Aransas, a vacation community, Francis Stokes used a
squeegee to push about two inches of water out of the Value Bank
Texas branch Monday morning. The bank, in a strip center on Tarpon
Street, was dark and without power. Most of the 3,000 residents of
Port Aransas had evacuated Saturday night or early Sunday,
including Stokes, who stayed with friends in Corpus Christi.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not too bad. We just got some water inside,'' said
Stokes, sweating through a brown T-shirt and gray shorts.
``Everyone's breathing a sigh of relief.''
</P>
<P>
   In San Diego, the seat of Duval County, Ruben Valadez saw an
example of Bret's power. High winds scraped the tin roof off the
Plaza Alcala, the festival grounds across the road from his uncle
and aunt's house on Garcia Street. The sheet metal smashed against
the house and the one next door and hung like crumpled tinfoil onto
the eaves. The flying debris split a wooden power pole and tipped
it into the roof, poking a hole that leaked rain into the living
room of his uncle and aunt's house.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're lucky the damn thing didn't go in and knock the house
down,'' Valadez said. ``Thank God they were in the back of the
house.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph K.M. Haurwitz writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas. The Associated Press contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
