<HEADLINE>
WILY, PATIENT DEFENSE WINS FIRST GAME OF CHESS MATCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ROBERT BYRNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the first game of the International Chess Federation's world
championship match on Sunday night, Alexander Khalifman defeated
Vladimir Akopian in a slow, tense demonstration of ingenious
defense.
</P>
<P>
   When Akopian went for a breakthrough and saw it powerfully
countered, he evidently despaired of pulling out the game by normal
means and gave up a knight for two pawns to make winning difficult
for his opponent. But Khalifman painstakingly broke down his
resistance with fine technique and won after a marathon of almost
six hours.
</P>
<P>
   It takes 3{ points to decide this six-game series at Caesar's
Palace in Las Vegas, so any loss has to be taken as a serious
setback. Akopian is aware that his opponent could possibly become
champion with a skein of draws.
</P>
<P>
   In a hypermodern English Opening, Akopian staked a claim to
queenside space with 3 b4 but delayed direct contact with the
enemy.
</P>
<P>
   Unhindered, Khalifman seized central terrain with 6 ... e5 and
after 7 d3 cleared his king knight out of the way with 7 ... Nh5,
preparing to seize more kingside space with 8 ... f5. His plan was
to attack the white king as soon as it castled kingside.
</P>
<P>
   After 11 e4, it was too early for Khalifman to begin kingside
operations with 11 ... f4 because Akopian could have countered with
12 d4. Instead, he gave himself queenside space with 11 ... c5, to
anticipate his opponent's maneuvers there.
</P>
<P>
   Akopian pounced on that by opening lines with 12 bc bc, hoping
to damage the black queenside pawn structure with 13 c5, the point
being that taking the pawn with 13 ... dc? lets White get in 14 Na4
with a double attack on the c5 and e5 pawns. If 14 ... Qc7, then
comes 15 Nc5 and Akopian is sitting pretty with an advanced knight
outpost at c5 and a target in the isolated c6 pawn.
</P>
<P>
   Akopian must have underestimated Khalifman's counterthrust with
13 ... d5! 14 ed cd 15 Qb3 e4! Perhaps Akopian was hoping for 15
... Be6?, which was to be hit by 16 Ng5. Instead, he was staring at
16 de fe 17 Nd2 Ba6 18 Re1 Rb8 19 Qa3 Bd3 and feared Khalifman's
aggressive center. So, with 17 Ne4 Bb2 18 Qb2 de 19 Ng5 Bf5 20 Ne4
Rb8 21 Qc3 Nd5 22 Qa3, he chose to put up a battle with only two
pawns for a knight.
</P>
<P>
   But after 26 c6, he made a brave fight of it with his advanced
c6 pawn, which tied the black forces to defense. His bishop was
able to give the pawn long-distance support and held Khalifman's
knights at bay.
</P>
<P>
   The first step in the unwinding process was the firm blockade
with 29 ... Rc7. The second step was to exchange rooks with 35 ...
Rf6 36 Rf6 Nf6. The third step was to play 44 ... Qd6, threatening
to break into the white king position with 45 ... Qf4 and thus
forcing the exchange of queens with 45 Qa3 Qa3 46 Ra3.
</P>
<P>
   Once Khalifman's king and knights got into the battle with 52
... Nd4, Akopian could no longer offer serious resistance. When the
c6 pawn fell to 54 ... Nec6, his situation further deteriorated.
</P>
<P>
   After 57 ... Nc2, Akopian gave up in the face of 58 g5 Kf7 59
Re4 Ne3 60 Kf2 Nf1 61 Kf1 Ra3 62 Re2 Nd5 63 Rf2 Ra4, winning one
pawn after another.
</P>
<P>
   ENGLISH OPENING
</P>
<P>
   White..................... Black
</P>
<P>
   Akopian................... Khalifman
</P>
<P>
   01. Nf3................... Nf6
</P>
