<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-WATER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 SUEZ LYONNAISE TO BUY U.S. WATER-MANAGEMENT BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ A brawl between two giant French utilities for a piece
of the fast-growing U. S. water-treatment market intensified Monday
when Suez Lyonnaise des Eaux SA agreed to buy a leading American
water-management business for $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Suez's deal for United Water Resources Inc. is the latest in a
spree of American purchases by the French company and strengthened
its hand against Vivendi SA of France, Suez's main rival.
</P>
<P>
   The deal comes at a time of rapid change in the water-management
business in the United States, where towns and cities are now
contracting out what were formerly municipal water services to
private companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States is an emerging market for water, and that's
great'' for companies like Suez, said David Marcus, an asset
manager at Franklin Mutual Advisers, a large mutual fund company
that holds shares in Suez.
</P>
<P>
   The French company had owned 33 percent of United Water
Resources, and under terms of the acquisition announced Monday it
will acquire the rest for $1 billion, or about $35 a share. Suez
will also assume $800 million in United Water Resources debt.
</P>
<P>
   United Water Resources shares rose $2.4375, or 7.8 percent, to
$33.50 on the New York Stock Exchange on news of the deal. Suez
shares fell 1.8 percent to 154.1 euros, in Paris, while Vivendi
rose 1.5 percent, to 70.7 euros.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Suez acquired Nalco Chemical Co., water treatment
specialists in Naperville, Ill., for $4.1 billion. Earlier, Suez
acquired Calgon Corp., a Pittsburgh water company.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus said Suez paid a ``very full price'' for United Water
Resources but commended the purchase, saying it would make Suez's
corporate structure easier to understand by consolidating its
ownership of affiliates. Suez has been moving quickly to acquire
all the shares of companies it had partly owned, in an effort to
attract investors by simplifying its balance sheet. Earlier this
month, Suez paid almost $9 billion to acquire shares it did not
hold in Tractebel SA, Belgium's largest utility, and Sita SA,
Europe's largest waste-management group.
</P>
<P>
   Gerard Mestrallet, Suez's chief executive, said that combined
with the acquisition of Nalco and Calgon, Suez's move Monday
``further strengthens its position in the U.S. industrial and
municipal water-services market.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it would enable Suez to ``grow more efficiently and more
rapidly'' in the United States, which he described as ``the
fastest-growing market in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Suez's existing stake in United Water Resources is rooted in a
large share it had held in General Water Works, which merged in
1994 with Hackensack Water Co. to form United Water. The company,
based in Harrington Park, N.J., provides water- and waste-treatment
services to 7.5 million people in 19 states.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Correll, United Water's chief executive, said Monday's
deal would have ``no immediate impact on rates'' for water
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   United Water has enjoyed major successes over the last year or
so, signing waste-water treatment contracts with the cities of
Milwaukee and Indianapolis last year. This year it reached an
agreement with Atlanta to operate the city's entire water system,
including water treatment and distribution and waste-water
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   But most of this activity has come in the nonregulated rate
market, which is increasingly attractive to private companies.
Correll said consolidation was coming rapidly among the 58,000
water systems in the United States, but that the market was growing
``very competitive.'' The Suez deal, he said, would afford United
Water ``the financial firepower'' for further moves.
</P>
<P>
   Correll said that 85 percent of the U.S. population continued to
be served by municipal water companies, and roughly 95 percent of
waste-water treatment remained in municipal hands, and that many of
those services would be transferred to private contractors in
coming years. Last year, United Water's revenue in the nonregulated
rate market totaled $101 million, roughly double the amount the
year before, and next year, the company's revenue in this category
is expected to reach $160 million. ``We are growing far in excess
of the market,'' Correll said.
</P>
<P>
   Mestrallet has been under pressure to bring growth to Suez,
which was formed in 1997 by the merger of Compagnie de Suez and
Lyonnaise des Eaux. Back then Mestrallet pledged to build up Suez's
energy-, water- and waste-management businesses, and United Water
has become the vehicle for growth in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Mestrallet's drive has been in response to an enormous offensive
by the French market leader, Vivendi, and its chief executive,
Jean-Marie Messier. Earlier this year, Vivendi, which was formerly
known as Compagnie Generale des Eaux, made a major move into the U.
S. water market, acquiring the U.S. Filter Corp. in a deal worth
$7.9 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
