u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-REDS24-COX     08-23 0460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-REDS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Old rut for big road machine
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The wild-card contending Cincinnati Reds, who are
baring down on the Houston Astros in the NL Central with the best
road record in the majors, have stalled out at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves beat the so-called big road machine 6-2 Monday night
in the opener of a three-game series, dropping the Reds to 0-4 this
season at Turner Field and 2-11 since it opened in 1997. The Reds
will have to win the next two to take their first series in Atlanta
since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds have been a much better team since getting swept here
in late April and early May, but the Braves wouldn't let them show
it.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves stole a season-high seven bases, Brian Jordan
collected his 100th RBI, Andruw Jones extended his hitting streak
to 11 games and Chipper Jones took care of the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones put on an early offensive exhibition against the
struggling Brett Tomko, hitting his 33rd home run on an
opposite-field drive to left in the first inning, then pulling a
double past first base in the third as he drove in three of the
Braves' first four runs on the way to an early 4-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves swept three games from the Padres over the weekend
without a ball leaving the yard. Chipper Jones took care of that
34-inning homerless stretch, which matched the Braves' longest of
the season, with his two-run shot in the first inning, giving the
Braves a 2-1 lead. That brought him to the brink of his career high
in home runs, set last year.
</P>
<P>
   Bret Boone set Jones up by reaching base twice in his first two
at-bats on a hit and an error, and scored two runs against his
former team in the first three innings.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Millwood (14-7) went heavy on the fastball and had it
working well enough for his second win in his last three starts.
</P>
<P>
   He used a couple nice plays by Andruw Jones to survive a rocky
first inning in which he fell behind 1-0, and after that settled in
nicely. He allowed only an infield hit to Barry Larkin on a
grounder bobbled by Chipper Jones over the next four innings before
Michael Tucker cut the lead to 4-2 on a home run. That's five
consecutive starts in which Millwood has surrendered a home run.
</P>
<P>
   Tomko, the Reds' opening-day starter and a minor-league pitcher
a month later, is back on the big-league job barely, with Steve
Parris ready to come off the disabled list and make a claim for his
spot in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Tomko walked five and allowed six runs, giving him 19 runs
allowed in his last 23 1/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
