</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAKE-FAMILY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turkish earthquake: Surviving family members and lost kin flown
homeBy Arthur Brice
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Friends and loved ones will say good-bye Friday to the
four young victims from Marietta, Ga., who perished in last week's
Turkish earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   A memorial service for the four Kilic children _ Jeffrey, 6;
Jennifer, 5; David, 2; and Katie, 9 months _ will be held at noon
at Mount Vernon Baptist Church, where the family worships.
</P>
<P>
   Nizam Kilic, the children's grandfather, also died in the quake.
His wife, Turkan, clung to life Monday at WellStar-Kennestone
Hospital, said her son, Timur, a physician at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if she'll live,'' Timur Kilic said. ``It's just a
day-to-day thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Turkan Kilic has double pneumonia and suffered a stroke that has
left her left side paralyzed, Timur Kilic said. She is on a
ventilator in the fourth-floor intensive care unit.
</P>
<P>
   The children's mother, Jan, survived the earthquake, as did a
daughter, 3-year-old Natalie.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Kilic was in good condition at WellStar-Kennestone,
recovering from injuries to her head, neck and lower back. She is
expected to be discharged this week, Timur Kilic said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mentally, she's very with it,'' Timur Kilic said. ``She's very
positive. She knows exactly what happened, but she's very positive
because of her faith: This is God's plan and they've gone to a
better place.''
</P>
<P>
   Jan and Turkan Kilic arrived at the hospital in the early
morning hours Monday after a 13-hour trip aboard an airplane
ambulance.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies of the five victims returned to the Atlanta area
Sunday night on a Delta Air Lines jet, accompanied by the
children's father, Babur Kilic, his brothers, Timur and Cengiz, and
an older sister, Zehra. Natalie, who is staying with Timur Kilic,
also was on the flight.
</P>
<P>
   Natalie only suffered a black eye that is now barely visible and
is ``doing great,'' her uncle said Monday night. The child was
trapped for 36 hours underneath rubble from the collapsed
five-story building in which the Kilics were staying.
</P>
<P>
   ``All she knows is she was sleeping and all she remembers is
that somebody put her underneath a rock,'' Timur Kilic said.
</P>
<P>
   No funeral arrangements have been made for Nizam Kilic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to go ahead and bring some closure to this,'' said
maternal grandfather William Kemp.
</P>
<P>
   The children's father, Babur, is doing as well as can be
imagined, his older brother said Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's hanging in there,'' Timur Kilic said. ``He's getting a
lot of support from the family. He's kind of numb from the whole
thing. I'm sure he's hoping this is a nightmare he can wake up
from.''
</P>
<P>
   The tragedy started during an idyllic vacation for Jan Kilic and
her five children, who were staying with her in-laws at their
summer home in the Turkish seaside resort of Yalova. Her husband
Babur, a physician, was supposed to join them this past weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he and his two brothers caught a Lufthansa flight to
Turkey on Wednesday, hours after being told the horrible news.
</P>
<P>
   After arriving in Turkey, they checked on Jan and Turkan Kilic
and then began searching for their missing family members. They
found them at a make-shift morgue at a factory's refrigeration
unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing my nieces and nephews was pretty hard,'' Timur Kilic
said. ``But also finding my father, that was pretty tough stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerned with getting their loved ones back to Georgia as soon
as possible, the Kilic brothers tried to obtain help from U.S.
officials in Turkey. That went nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, back in Georgia, Jan's parents, other Kilic family
members and medical colleagues started to see what they could do.
Discussion with State Department officials in Washington proved
fruitless.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Delta offered to fly them home.
</P>
<P>
   About the same time, Tom Hurd, head doctor at Georgia
Anesthesiologists, the group to which the three Kilic brothers
belong, hired MedJet International Inc., an air ambulance company
out of Birmingham, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim was concerned about his mom, getting her straight back to
the United States,'' Hurd said. ``They thought one transport was
all she could really handle.''
</P>
<P>
   MedJet brought a plane up from Miami on Friday, picked up a
doctor, nurse and respiratory technician in Birmingham, Ala., and
flew on to Vienna, Austria, stopping to refuel along the way in
Canada and to switch pilot crews in Iceland, said the company's
vice president, Stan Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   After a federally mandated 18-hour stop in Vienna so the crew
could rest, the MedJet flight continued to Istanbul. The plane
arrived early Sunday afternoon, picked up the two patients and
started back.
</P>
<P>
   About 13 hours later, after another crew switch in Iceland, the
plane touched down in Atlanta about 1:30 a.m. Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The 13,211-mile round trip cost about $64,000, most of which
insurance will pay, Timur Kilic said.
</P>
<P>
   Kemp said the family was grateful to have the women home but was
still bitter over the State Department's inability to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're angry. We're still angry,'' Kemp said.
</P>
<P>
   His daughter, meanwhile, has begun the hard road to physical
recovery. She will need physical therapy, Timur Kilic said, and a
deep gash on her forehead likely will require reconstructive
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take a long time,'' said Kemp.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Brice writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Julie Bryant contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
