<HEADLINE>
SITE GIVES SPORTS FANS THE BUSINESS LOWDOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it was reported in this newspaper on how the Texas Rangers
baseball club was marketing postseason tickets, it was exactly the
type of news that Howard Bloom was waiting for.
</P>
<P>
   In case you ask ... no, Bloom is not some Rangers fan from
Pantego, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   From his vantage in Ottawa, Bloom tracks the sports business
world and posts daily updates at his site, Sportsbusinessnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Bloom's updates might range from simple attendance figures and
money leaders to commentary on escalating players' salaries or
stadium funding issues. Or, as he did with the Rangers' ticket
news, he might add some perspective on a current topic.
</P>
<P>
   On his site, Bloom observed that the Rangers are offering fans
who aren't current season-ticket or mini-season ticket holders an
opportunity to buy postseason tickets as long as they commit to
purchasing a mini-season (11-game plan) for next year.
</P>
<P>
   Bloom advocated the plan: ``It's a reward and sends a strong
message about customer loyalty to the business community and to
your fan base,'' Bloom wrote.
</P>
<P>
   It's that kind of approach that sets his site apart from the
others, Bloom said. Anyone can collect news from the multitude of
sources on the Internet; it requires effort to make sense of the
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take a very tough look at sports,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bloom, who has worked with several Canadian-based amateur sports
programs, launched the site May 24, 1998. He gave his site one year
to establish credibility before he began expanding his efforts to
turn it into a serious venture.
</P>
<P>
   His goal is for the site to evolve into a sports version of the
Drudge Report.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that I think that Matt Drudge is any kind of role model,
but that's what we want to become,'' said Bloom, a part-time
weekend host on Ottawa Sports Radio.
</P>
<P>
   To accomplish this, Bloom has assembled a staff of
correspondents who will provide in-depth commentary. He said he
also plans to create an audio version of his site for sports talk
radio or other sports sites.
</P>
<P>
   Bloom said it's important that sports fans on the Internet be
able to get everything they want from one site. It doesn't always
have to be routine news, but an understanding of the issues, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it's more important to know what's going on off the
field than on the field,'' Bloom said. ``The business of sports
really is as important as winning or losing.''
</P>
<P>
   GOT AN EXTRA MILLION? A week ago, New York Jets fans John Crotty
and Peter Lyons launched Buythejets.com with the idea to pool
enough cash, via the Internet, to come together to submit a united
bid to become majority owners of the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is to collect at least $180 million, enough to become a
majority owner. No fan will be allowed to purchase more than $5,000
worth of the partnership.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Jones wannabes should know this: According to the
frequently asked questions section, if you become a minority owner,
you will not be able to play quarterback for the team.
</P>
<P>
   TOUR DE JERSEY: The selling off of Lance Armstrong continues on
the Internet. The Tour de France winner from Austin already has
sold one of his autographed bikes for $5,500 to Larry Latham of
Austin on the Internet. Now until Sept. 10, Armstrong will make his
yellow race-leader jersey _ worn during the Tour de France _
available for auction on Active USA and SportingAuction. Proceeds
benefit the Lance Armstrong Foundation, which is dedicated to
fighting cancer through awareness, education and research.
</P>
<P>
   POINT AND SERVE: In case it's hard to keep track with pencil and
paper, the official U.S. Open site (www.usopen.org) plans to have a
detailed statistics section for this year's event, which opens
Monday in Armonk, N.Y. The Event Stats section features data on tie
breaks, first points won, server points and return games won, aces
and double faults from all main match courts. The site has
scheduled a live cybercast of the draw ceremony at 9:30 a.m.
tomorrow. When the tournament begins, fans can capture their own
view via three robotic cameras, download real-time match scores,
chat with players and purchase official merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   INDUSTRY NEWS: ESPN.com plans to launch a redesign of its site
the first week of September to coincide with the opening of the NFL
season. The redesign is expected to give users a faster access to
the site, easier navigation and quicker downloads in addition to a
look that is consistent with ESPN television graphics ... ESPN.com
is following CBS SportsLine's venture into international sports
with Buena Vista Internet Group's re-launch of Soccernet,
recognized as the world's most-popular soccer site with more than
20 million page views per month. Buena Vista Internet Group
operates ESPN.com ... ESPN.com also has enhanced its baseball
presence by partnering with Baseball America Online.
</P>
<P>
   (Tommy Cummings writes about the Internet for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 390-7397. E-mail:
dragon(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
