<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 23:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7237 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BRUT-AD-COLUMN-520&AMP;AD     08-23 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRUT-AD-COLUMN-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: BRUT CAMPAIGN IS POLITICALLY INCORRECT, ON PURPOSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By PATRICIA WINTERS LAURO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a new Brut man, and _ to borrow a phrase from the
brand's glory days of the 1970s _ he's a male chauvinist pig.
</P>
<P>
   The new $12 million campaign for the Brut toiletries brand,
introduced last week in print and some outdoor ads, features
headlines like ``You're welcome to throw your clothes on the floor,
too'' and ``Actually, yes. That outfit does make you look fat.''
Other ads go further in references to sex and other personal acts.
</P>
<P>
   The ads, from Ammirati Puris Lintas, New York, part of
Interpublic Group of Cos., are aimed at men from 18 to 34 and are
politically incorrect on purpose. They are tapping into an emerging
'90s-style men-behaving-badly ethos that is seen in the success of
things like Maxim magazine, a Playboy-like publication, and
television shows like ``The Man Show'' on Comedy Central.
</P>
<P>
   To Brut's owner, Unilever, the British-Dutch conglomerate, the
trend is a perfect fit for Brut, which was a huge success when it
was introduced some 30 years ago with macho, tongue-in-cheek TV
spots featuring the football great Joe Namath. But the brand has
been slipping in the last decade and is now ranked third in the
$521 million mass-market fragrance business behind Stetson and Old
Spice, and it badly needs a boost.
</P>
<P>
   The new campaign tries to keep Brut's manly image, popularized
by Namath and other sports celebrity ads, said Rob Feakins of
Ammirati, one of the campaign's two creative directors, but it also
aims to update the image with a bit of humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``These ads reflect the style of how these young guys feel
today,'' Feakins said. ``It accepts it and speaks in their language
that it's good to be Neanderthal again.''
</P>
<P>
   The agency's research, which included some 30 focus groups of
men and women of all ages, showed that the new Brut man is accepted
as a postfeminist guy whose crassness is apparently a joke among
many young people of both sexes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our findings were the same everywhere we went,'' said Jim
Allman, chairman of Ammirati New York. ``People are very
comfortable with themselves and the opposite sex, and can even poke
fun at what would've been once considered misogynist behavior. The
women were just as comfortable with this kind of edgy, macho
humor.''
</P>
<P>
   More important, said Roger Bentley, the other co-creative
director for the campaign, the ads reach an audience that just
doesn't believe the babes-come-running and sports-hero advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ads come off as very honest to our target audience _ we
hear all the time people are tired of being told what they should
be like,'' Bentley said.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign features bold white headlines on a background of
emerald green _ Brut's signature color _ and the tag line ``Inside
every man is a guy.'' The product is not seen in the ads, nor do
you see an actual Brut man. TV ads, now in production, will run
later in the year.
</P>
<P>
   The print campaign, which is running in men's magazines like
Maxim and in outdoor ads in seven cities, also includes posters at
construction sites. Brut will also get so-called urinal
advertising, ads positioned at eye level above urinals, mostly in
bars.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Several other companies are picking up on the postfeminist guy
thing.
</P>
<P>
   Rheingold Brewing Co. is now selling its signature beer as the
brew ``for the few real men still left.'' Wendy's International
also has a campaign aimed at young men, with lines like ``This is a
burger town, pretty boy.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Brut ads may say things that would have been
unacceptable even five years ago, the ads pale in comparison with
some recent films and television shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Candor in the media, certainly on the editorial side, is
something that seems to be manifesting itself more actively _
witness Monica,'' said Stephen Greyser, a professor of
communications and marketing at Harvard Business School, referring
to the explicit discussions of the Monica Lewinsky debacle. ``I
couldn't say they are breaking new ground. Advertising reflects
changes in society over time.''
</P>
<P>
   Unilever can risk such ``candid guy talk,'' he said, because the
advertising pinpoints a very specific audience in very specific
media outlets, which is unlikely to reach _ and potentially annoy _
the general population, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Alan Jope, a Unilever vice president for marketing,
noted that Brut's racier ads will run above urinals and in men's
publications but not in more public locations. And while the TV
spots will maintain the spirit of the print ads, Jope said, they
won't be as ``out there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We absolutely do not want to be offensive to people,'' Jope
said. ``However, we're not afraid of talking to different target
markets in a tone they find relevant.''
</P>
<P>
   Jope said the ``emerging guy phenomenon'' allows Brut to talk to
men in ways beyond the typical male hero stereotype because the
trend tells Unilever that men and women have loosened up about
politically correct roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until the 1970s, it was expected that men were male chauvinist
pigs,'' he said. ``Then came the era of new male sensitivity for 20
years. Finally young men have grown up now, and are able to have
multiple roles. They can be full equal co-workers, good fathers and
one of the guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is the latest effort by Brut to reclaim its status
as a premiere mass brand. As men's roles have changed, the brand
has tried several approaches, from the sexy actress Kelly LeBrock
talking about relationships in the early '90s to a ``men are back''
campaign that blended swagger and sensitivity. In 1997, it returned
to sports celebrities with the Dallas Cowboy quarterback Troy
Aikman as the Brut man.
</P>
<P>
   The latest campaign is a first step toward positioning Brut as a
stronger player in the $1.68 billion anti-perspirant category,
which is much larger than the fragrance market, Jope said. Brut,
with a 2 percent share, is sixth in men's anti-perspirants. The
leader, Right Guard by Gillette, has a 9.8 percent share, according
to A.C. Nielsen.
</P>
<P>
   Brut has a tough job ahead mostly because it is always tough to
revive a brand, said Allan Mottus, editor of The Informationist, a
beauty industry trade publication. Mottus said it made sense to
focus on the larger anti-perspirant market, but to succeed Brut
will have to establish a benefit for the product beyond smelling
good. To that end, Unilever will promote Brut's new dryness
ingredient _ trimax _ in its TV campaign, Jope said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the new, supermacho print campaign, Mottus said he was
not in the target audience, which may be why he just doesn't get
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like they're trying to be cute,'' he said. ``And
sweat ain't cute.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
