<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-SPARKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARKS TO FACE SHORT-HANDED MONARCHS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ What could have been a matchup of league MVP
candidates has turned into a decided advantage for the Sparks.
</P>
<P>
   They begin the WNBA playoffs today against the Sacramento
Monarchs in a single-elimination first-round game at 6 p.m. at the
Forum.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Leslie will be ready to play, having helped the Sparks
(20-12) finish second in the Western Conference with the league's
second-best record.
</P>
<P>
   The same can't be said for Sacramento's top player, 6-foot-3
center Yolanda Griffith, who suffered a season-ending knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith's absence could have a major affect on the matchup. She
averaged 21.8 points and 9.8 rebounds in the four-game,
regular-season series, which was split 2-2. Tangela Smith takes
over for Griffith.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks coach Orlando Woolridge is not counting on Sacramento
(19-13) having a big letdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know they are a very capable team, even without Yolanda
Griffith,'' Woolridge said. ``We're going to go about our
preparation as if she was there. When I look at Tangela Smith,
particularly the last two games, she's been very aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith will be matched up against Leslie, who is averaging 15.6
points and 7.8 rebounds. Leslie is a dominant post player but has
become an outside threat with her 22 3-pointers and 42-percent
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who averages 8.3 points and 3.8 boards, is more of a
small forward but is quick and runs the floor well.
</P>
<P>
   First-year coach Sonny Allen Smith has been impressed with
Tangela Smith's play of late.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's really stepped up. She had a double-double against
Houston,'' he said. ``I knew she had talent, but she really
surprised me.''
</P>
<P>
   Probably one of the most physical and aggressive matchups in the
paint will feature the Sparks' 6-1 DeLisha Milton against the
Monarchs' 5-11 LaTasha Byears. With her wide wingspan, Milton (9.9
points, 5.5 rebounds) has established herself as a defensive power.
She'll get a workout against the tireless and relentless Byears
(9.2 points, 5.3 rebounds), who has the offensive abilities,
especially with Griffith out.
</P>
<P>
   The Monarchs have a three-guard lineup with Ticha Penicheiro,
Ruthie Bolton-Holifield and Kedra Holland-Corn.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks can have La'Keisha Frett or Mwadi Mabika cover
Penicheiro and Bolton-Holifield. Frett (6.1 points, 3.0 rebounds)
has been a pleasant surprise since earning a starting spot midway
through the season. Penicheiro leads the league with assists (7.1).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-99 2320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
