<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-WORLD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES ON THIRD-BEST LONG JUMPER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KIRBY LEE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEVILLE, Spain _ Marion Jones already has proven she is the
fastest woman in the world. Yet she concedes she is far from the
world's greatest long jumper.
</P>
<P>
   That was apparent Monday after Jones finished third in the long
jump in the World Championships to end her bid for an unprecedented
four gold medals.
</P>
<P>
   Niurka Montalvo of Spain won the competition with a final leap
of 23 feet, 2 inches to upset 1995 world champion Fiona May of
Italy. May was second at 22-9{ and Jones was third at 22-5. Dawn
Burrell, who defeated Jones in the U.S. championships to hand the
Thousand Oaks High graduate her first loss to an American in two
years, was sixth at 22-1{.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can stand here all day and talk about technique,'' Jones
said. ``I'll be the first one to tell you I need to work on my
technique. My specialty is running until I have a little bit of
time to work on technique. I have a lot of speed. It is a lot
easier to work on technique than to find speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who set a 100-meter championship record of 10.70 seconds
Saturday to record the fastest time ever at sea level, will attempt
to rebound in the 200-meter preliminaries, which begin today. She
also will compete in either the 400- or 1,600-meter relay in these
World Championships, which run through Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   There also was disappointment Monday for Mark Crear of Valencia,
who was disqualified after two false starts in the 110-meter high
hurdle quarterfinals. Crear, the 1996 Olympic silver medalist in
the 110 high hurdles and the world-leader at 12.98 seconds, won his
first-round race easily in 13.30.
</P>
<P>
   Crear said he was merely trying to react to the gun and wasn't
trying to catch a flyer on his second false start, especially in a
second-round race. Crear, in lane 5, said Sweden's Robert Kronberg
in lane 1 pulled him off on the first false start.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team has lodged a protest for the Jury of Appeals to
review videotape. An analysis of reaction times indicate that in
Crear's quarterfinal, which was restarted five times, there were 13
reaction times under the allowable time. Both of Crear's marks were
coincidentally the same to a thousandth of a second, .057. Yet
Crear was the lone athlete disqualified.
</P>
<P>
   ``I trained all year ... but I never prepared myself for this,''
Crear said. ``Somehow, I'm going to have to pick up the broken
pieces and salvage the rest of the season. You win like a man, you
lose like a man. It's one of those unfortunate situations that you
don't want to go through.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a day of celebration for UCLA's Seilala Sua in the
women's discus final. Sua, at 21 the youngest competitor in the
field, finished sixth with a throw of 209-1, the highest finish
ever by an American. Franka Diestzsch of Germany won with a throw
of 223-7.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am happy about making history but I am a bit upset with my
performance,'' said Sua, the 1999 NCAA and U.S. champion, who has
thrown 212-10. ``I was the youngest ... but I am going to use it to
my advantage in my next competition. They're fading out and I'm
coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, ranked No. 1 in the world in the 100, 200 and long jump
in 1998, also hopes to bounce back after her long jump performance.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' best effort of 22-5 came in the fifth round but was far
off her personal-best 23-11}. On her sixth and final attempt, Jones
appeared to surpass the 23-foot mark, but the jump was ruled foul.
</P>
<P>
   It was the next jumper, Montalvo, who stole the spotlight. She
jumped 22-7 in the fourth round to trail May by two inches but
responded with her winning jump. Montalvo's foot was on the edge of
the board and it took several moments before the judges ruled the
jump fair to send the primarily Spanish crowd of 37,815 into a
boisterous and raucous celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew there was going to be a little doubt from many people
that thought it was a foul,'' Jones said. ``It says a lot about her
character that she can come back on her last jump and produce one
like that. I'll give it to her. She was the best jumper today.
There are no excuses for me. I think I can sleep well tonight
knowing I left it all out there.''
</P>
<P>
   On a sultry and steamy night, with temperatures in the high 80s
and 40 percent humidity, Jones was second after the first round
with a leap of 22-3{, a quarter of an inch behind Montalvo. In the
third round, May responded with her best effort of 22-9\ to bump
Jones to third.
</P>
<P>
   If Jones captures gold medals in the 200 meters and a relay, she
would join Carl Lewis (1983 and 1987) and East Germany's Marita
Koch (1983) as the only athletes to claim three gold medals in the
same World Championships.
</P>
<P>
   That would do little, however, to console Jones after her
setback in the long jump.
</P>
<P>
   `` I set my goals very high. Bronze is not going to cut it for
me,'' Jones said. ``It blows my mind that people can't understand
that people want me to say I'll settle for three golds and a
bronze. Of course, I am going to want to win every event I am in. I
put pressure on myself saying I want to win four golds but I would
not change anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
