<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-SHARPTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY GOES TO HARLEM TO SPEAK ON RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In some of his most detailed remarks about race
relations and the plight of urban America to date, Bill Bradley
told a Harlem audience Monday night that he would use the power of
the presidency to push for universal health care, end child
poverty, abolish mandatory sentencing of criminals and end racial
profiling by police.
</P>
<P>
   During a two-hour appearance before more than 500 people at the
National Action Network, a group led by the Rev. Al Sharpton,
Bradley said that the desire to improve race relations was a major
reason he first became interested in Democratic Party politics some
35 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm saying is that racial unity is not a political
position,'' he said. ``It is who I am. It's what I believe. It's
what I care most about. It's one of the main motivations for my
being in politics in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   For months, Bradley, the former U.S. senator from New Jersey,
has been telling audiences that he considers race relations a
``defining issue'' in American politics today. But in appearing
before Sharpton's group, he made it clear that he is willing to
work closely with the most liberal wing of the Democratic Party, at
least on issues concerning race and urban poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's appearance also provided a political boost for
Sharpton, who at times has been ostracized by some Democratic Party
officials, but whose standing within the party seems to have risen,
partly because of public outcry against police brutality in New
York City and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Though he declined to say whether he would endorse Bradley,
Sharpton praised the former senator for being, he said, the first
presidential candidate since Robert Kennedy in 1968 to campaign in
Harlem. And he called on the other candidates to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not continue an illicit affair where people have fun
with us in private but don't want to deal with us and our issues in
public,'' Sharpton said to much laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has described his campaign as being in a phase where he
outlines general positions without getting into policy details. For
that, he has been criticized as overly vague by supporters of Vice
President Al Gore, who is generally viewed as the front-runner for
the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday night, during a speech he gave from notes as well as
in answers to questions from the crowd afterward, Bradley did not
shy away from taking clear and strong positions on a number of
major issues. And more often than not, his remarks drew warm
applause from the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about how he would help the urban poor, Bradley said he
would institute policies intended to end discriminatory lending
practices by banks, press for tax cuts specifically aimed at
helping middle-class and low-income people, raise the minimum wage
and push for legislation that would make it easier for workers to
join labor unions.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that he would veto a $792 billion tax cut recently
approved by Congress ``in a nanosecond,'' Bradley also said he
would use the federal surplus to extend health insurance to all
Americans and to reduce childhood poverty. But he did not offer
specific proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to know that because of what we did over four or
eight years that every child in America has a chance to realize his
or her potential,'' he said. ``There are still 14 million children
today who live in poverty. There are still 45 million people in
America without health insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   As he often does in his speeches on race, Bradley, a former New
York Knick, recalled his experiences playing alongside blacks on
athletic teams. In his hometown of Crystal City, Mo., he said, the
Little League baseball team was integrated ahead of other town
institutions. And he recounted being forced to stay in ``third-rate
hotels'' and being denied service in segregated restaurants while
traveling with the Little League team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We walked out of more than one restaurant in our time,'' he
said to applause.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who received a standing ovation when he finished, also
asserted that he had made it a point to speak forcefully about race
relations on the floor of the Senate. He recounted a floor speech
he gave after the beating of Rodney King by Los Angeles police
officers in March 1991, when he pounded the lectern 56 times in two
minutes to dramatize the number of times the police hit King.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to show that a white face could talk about race
without vaporizing before your eyes,'' Bradley said. ``I'm still
here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
