<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUN-FORTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUN MICROSYSTEMS TO BUY FORTE IN $540 MILLION DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Sun Microsystems Inc. said Monday that it had
agreed to buy Forte Software Inc., which produces programming tools
for developing Internet applications, for $540 million in stock.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which is valued at $22.275 a share, represents a 31
percent premium to Forte's closing price of $17 a share on Friday.
Shares of Forte rose $4.125 Monday, to $21.125, while Sun rose
56.25 cents, to $74.8125.
</P>
<P>
   Sun's server computers and related software run many Web sites
and electronic commerce businesses. Acquiring Forte helps extend
Sun's reach to sites using IBM's System 390 mainframe computer
systems and Microsoft's Windows NT.
</P>
<P>
   Companies use Forte's software tools to better integrate
applications like sales-force automation and call-center
management, so-called front-office applications. All of these
programs used to run on companies' own computer systems, but they
are increasingly moving to servers running on the Internet or
private intranets, allowing companies, their suppliers and their
customers to handle sales, service, support and buying processes
from a Web browser.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies across the globe are dot-coming their businesses at
an incredible pace _ by extending legacy applications to run across
the Internet and by creating new applications to run across all
platforms,'' Ed Zander, Sun's president and chief operating
officer, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We welcome Forte's team, solutions and expertise to our line
of Internet development and deployment products and are looking
forward to working with Forte's customers on multiple platforms,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Forte has had growing revenue but erratic profitability. In the
quarter ended June 30, Forte reported a loss of $487,000 compared
with a loss of $2.3 million in the period a year earlier. Revenue
grew 22 percent, to $22.2 million from $18.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1991, Forte is one of a group of companies focused on
so-called middleware, which seeks to help companies integrate all
their enterprise applications, which help manage operations like
accounting, personnel and manufacturing. Because most corporations
have completed the deployment of big back-office programs, like
SAP, Oracle applications and Peoplesoft, and are now in the midst
of rolling out front-office applications from the likes of Siebel
Systems, Ariba and Remedy, there is an opening for companies that
can help link these different products.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-99 2332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
