u a BC-OBIT-GOTTSCHALK-NYT &LR;      08-23 0376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-GOTTSCHALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN GOTTSCHALK, FORMER DIRECTOR OF U.S. FISH AND WILDLIFE SERVICE,
DIES AT 86  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Ind., N.J., Wash.)   By NICK RAVO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   John S. Gottschalk, a director of the U.S. Fish and Wildlife
Service in the 1960s who oversaw developments like the first
endangered species act, the banning of the pesticide DDT and the
comeback of the whooping crane, died on Aug. 13 at his home in
Arlington, Va. He was 86.
</P>
<P>
   During his tenure, from 1964 to 1970, Gottschalk helped to start
several urban wildlife programs and add more than 500,000 acres to
the national wildlife refuge system.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in his career, when he was a regional director in the
service, Gottschalk played an important role in the Interior
Department's takeover of the Great Swamp in Morris County, N.J. In
the early 1960s, the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey had
considered using the area, now called the Great Swamp Wildlife
Preserve, for an airport.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the service, Gottschalk was assistant to the
director of the National Marine Fisheries Service and then was an
executive vice president and counsel of the International
Association of Fish and Wildlife Agencies. He retired in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   John Simison Gottschalk was born on Sept. 27, 1912, in Berne,
Ind. He graduated from Earlham College, in Richmond, Ind., and
received a master's degree from Indiana University.
</P>
<P>
   He began his career in the 1930s and early 40s as a park ranger,
park naturalist and fisheries superintendent with the Indiana
Conservation Department. He joined the Fish and Wildlife Service in
Montana, and in 1951 he became the first director of the sport
fisheries division of the agency. In 1959, he went to Boston as
director of the service's 11-state northeast region.
</P>
<P>
   He also served as president of the American Fisheries Society
and as a board member of the National Wildlife Federation and the
Audubon Naturalist Society, a conservation group for the Washington
metropolitan region.
</P>
<P>
   Gottschalk is survived by his wife of 62 years, Edith
Gottschalk, of Arlington; a son, Thomas, of Washington; a daughter,
Sara Nell Davis of Seabeck, Wash.; five grandchildren and two
great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-99 2333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
