<HEADLINE>
NBC NAMES EX-ABC EXECUTIVE TO HEAD TV PRODUCTION UNIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ NBC on Monday named Ted Harbert, the former top
entertainment executive at ABC, to be the new president of its
in-house television production unit, NBC Studios.
</P>
<P>
   The move underscores the increasing emphasis that networks are
placing on producing their own programming to take advantage of
potential profits from hit entertainment shows.
</P>
<P>
   Harbert had a 20-year career at ABC that ended in 1997, when he
stepped down as chairman of ABC Entertainment. He subsequently
joined the television division of the Dreamworks studio as a
producer and worked on comedies including ``Arsenio'' and the
current ``It's Like, You Know.''
</P>
<P>
   The appointment, a four-year deal, was made by Scott Sassa, the
president of NBC's West Coast division. Harbert will be in charge
of all of the operations under NBC Studios, including its
late-night, daytime and Saturday morning shows. He will report to
Sassa.
</P>
<P>
   The selection of such a high-profile executive as Harbert was
widely interpreted in the television industry as evidence of NBC's
commitment to upgrade its studio as a supplier of programs for its
network. Last year NBC Studios turned out the network's two most
successful new shows, ``Will and Grace'' and ``Providence.''
</P>
<P>
   Only last month, Walt Disney Co., parent of ABC, moved to
incorporate all its entertainment operations, including its studio,
under three ABC executives. Harbert said Monday that NBC would not
emulate that model.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is looking at the ABC model to see how it will
work,'' he said. He said he would act as an advocate at the network
for the shows developed by the studio but would expect Sassa and
his top entertainment executive, Garth Ancier, ``to throw me out of
the room'' when they made their final program choices. At ABC, the
executives scheduling the shows will be the same executives who are
developing the network's in-house programs.
</P>
<P>
   Harbert said NBC would still seek to acquire the best shows from
other studios, even as it tried to increase its own in-house
production. NBC Studios will also sell shows to other networks when
suitable, but Harbert said that was clearly not his first priority.
</P>
<P>
   Because NBC is not aligned with a big Hollywood studio as are
both ABC and Fox, there has been frequent speculation that the
network would eventually seek an alliance with a studio like
Columbia or Warner Brothers. Harbert said his appointment, as well
as the money NBC is committing to build its studio, are indications
that NBC, which is owned by General Electric Co., is willing to go
on its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``With GE behind it, NBC can be as big as anybody,'' Harbert
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
