<SLUG> BC-NY-BOMBING-CLEMENCY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE VICTIMS OF BOMBING FIGHT CLEMENCY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Officer Rocco Pascarella lost part of his left leg
when a bomb planted by Puerto Rican nationalists outside Police
Headquarters in Manhattan exploded on New Year's Eve in 1982. Later
that night, Detective Richard Pastorella lost five fingers and was
left blind after he tried to disarm a bomb across the street; his
partner, Detective Anthony Senft, lost an eye.
</P>
<P>
   That same night, members of a Puerto Rican nationalist group,
the Armed Forces of National Liberation, better known by its
Spanish initials, FALN, claimed responsibility for the bombings.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the three retired officers returned to 1 Police Plaza to
join Police Commissioner Howard Safir and police union officials in
calling on President Clinton to withdraw a clemency offer that he
made to 16 jailed members of the group.
</P>
<P>
   Pastorella, who now wears dark glasses, was led to a lectern in
front of reporters. ``Go ahead,'' Thomas J. Scotto, the president
of the Detectives Endowment Association, whispered as he reached
the lectern. ``The mike is right there.''
</P>
<P>
   The retired detective told the group that he thought the
president was making a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can I tell you what the psychological effect was to my
family, to my children, to my wife?'' he said. ``Certainly, it took
me fully two years to physically recover. But the emotional
injuries remain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You wake up with nightmares at night and cold sweats,'' he
said. ``It never leaves. It never goes away.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton offered conditional clemency to the 16 members of the
FALN on Aug. 11. Most of them were convicted of crimes like
seditious conspiracy or possession of an unregistered firearm, and
Clinton administration officials said none of them directly caused
any deaths or injuries. The officials added that the president felt
that their long prison terms _ one was sentenced to 90 years _ were
excessive. Under the offer, the prisoners must renounce the use of
violence and agree to comply with parole requirements.
</P>
<P>
   The president's clemency offer came after a number of
politicians, human rights advocates and church leaders, including
former President Jimmy Carter, Desmond Tutu and John Cardinal
O'Connor, lent their names to a high-profile campaign calling for
their release.
</P>
<P>
   But Safir denounced the president's offer, saying the FALN was
responsible for more than 130 bomb attacks between 1974 and 1983
that killed six people and injured more than 70. ``This type of
action will encourage terrorism worldwide,'' Safir said of the
clemency offer. ``We should never make deals with terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   Pastorella and the relatives of other bombing victims suggested
that Clinton's clemency offer was a politically inspired move
intended to drum up Puerto Rican support for Hillary Rodham Clinton
as she weighs a run in New York for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It says to me, at least, that this is really and truly
pandering to the Hispanic community, to the Latino community, for
their vote when Mrs. Clinton runs for the vacated seat of Patrick
Moynihan in New York state,'' Pastorella said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has denied the assertion that the offer is
politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
   Safir said Mayor Rudolph Giuliani _ Mrs. Clinton's likely
opponent in the Senate race _ opposes the clemency offer but did
not want to be accused of trying to use the issue for political
gain. ``The only reason the mayor is not here is because he doesn't
want to politicize this issue,'' Safir said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, who was in Rochester Monday, said he did not have
enough information to judge the merits of the decision to offer
clemency, and he repeated calls that he had made earlier this month
for the Justice Department to release its reports recommending
clemency for the 16 prisoners. But he questioned their reluctance
to sign documents renouncing the use of violence in the future, a
condition of their release.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the failure of the people involved to quickly
renounce violence gives you a sense that this was a mistake,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
