<SLUG> BC-BKL-COMMENTARY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE ALL THE GREAT PLANS, IT'S STILL THE COMETS AND EVERYBODY
ELSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just think about the announcers gushing with hyperbole ...
``Lisa Leslie passes around to DeLisha Milton who gives it to
Michael Cooper down to Orlando Woolridge who slams it in the face
of Cynthia Cooper. Orlando says not in my house Ms. Two-Time MVP
... and the Sparks trail Houston by 12 points.''
</P>
<P>
   If anyone has a chance of removing the Houston Comets from atop
the WNBA's nest, it's Woolridge and the Los Angeles Sparks.
Woolridge played for 13 seasons in the NBA. His teammate and
assistant, Michael Cooper, played for 11 seasons in the league.
</P>
<P>
   The male coaches obviously will not be allowed to play in the
1999 WNBA playoffs. With Woolridge and Cooper, someone other than
the Comets had a chance of winning the title. Without them, The
Comet Chase, Part III continues with the excitement and
anticipation of a ``Shaft/ rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I am bringing to the table is the type of playoff
mentality,'' said Woolridge, who is in his first season as L.A.'s
head coach. ``When I was with the Lakers, Bulls and Pistons I saw
the type of commitment and mentality everyone made to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   But who cares about mentality? Bring your jumper and first-step
and then talk, because babbling about mentality is for the American
Basketball League.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of which, this was supposed to be the year that the
infusion of ABL talent plus expansion meant a new WNBA champion.
That planned worked as well as New Coke. Houston posted the
league's best record for the third consecutive season and has won
79 percent of its games and is a virtual lock for a third
consecutive title.
</P>
<P>
   In a league with players and teams still trying to get know
themselves, Houston kept its core of Cooper, Sheryl Swoopes, Tina
Thompson and coach Van Chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   Until this group is broken up, any talk about a New York or Los
Angeles championship is as likely as Buffalo winning the Super Bowl
... or a Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming the league really wants parity, it would allow the
former NBA legends to suit up for their respective teams. If the
WNBA is lucky, maybe Magic Johnson will pull another Ali and
unretire for the millionth time.
</P>
<P>
   On second thought, scrap that. Let's keep the men on the
sidelines. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
