<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-WNBA-COMETS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMETS SET SIGHTS ON THIRD CONSECUTIVE TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Three years ago, Louisiana Tech women's basketball
coach Leon Barmore was asked to coach the Houston Comets of the
WNBA. He passed.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think they had enough good players,'' Barmore told
then Mississippi coach Van Chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor agreed with Barmore, but then decided to play
Mississippi Gambler and accepted the job.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter, former Texas Tech star Sheryl Swoopes was
appointed to the franchise. An unknown guard _ Cynthia Cooper _
returned from the European leagues to play for Houston at the age
of 34. And Tina Thompson was selected by the Comets in the league's
first draft.
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes, Cooper and Thompson have since combined to put the
Comets on the verge of a trilogy as dominant as ``Star Wars.'' The
Shooting Comets combine to average 48.7 points, 14.5 rebounds and
8.2 assists per game. One of the three has led the team in scoring
86 of 90 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Houston could represent the United States in the Olympics and
possibly win a gold medal,'' Detroit coach Nancy Lieberman-Cline
said. ``They have set the standards by which everyone tries to
measure themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the Olympics, but five teams will try to measure up
against the Comets as the WNBA playoffs begin in two cities Tuesday
night. Houston's postseason begins on Thursday in the Western
Conference finals against the winner of the Los Angeles-Sacramento
game.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the past two seasons when Houston won by the combined
average of 16.1 points, the Comets don't appear to be as dominant;
they won by an average of less than 10 points this season.
</P>
<P>
   But the Houston dominance is in the eye of the titleholder.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year I see nothing but a three-peat,'' Comets center Kara
Wolters said.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets have a three-year winning clip of 79 percent, have
never lost more than two consecutive games, have outscored their
opponents by an average of 13.9 points, have a playoff record of
6-1, have a two-time league MVP in Cooper and a two-time coach of
the year in Chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   However, as with any team that dominates, the seat on the throne
isn't eternal.
</P>
<P>
   With the tragic death of former teammate Kim Perrot last week,
the Comets might be more susceptible to defeat now than at any time
during their run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two things could happen,'' Los Angeles coach Orlando Woolridge
said. ``They could be a little flat and vulnerable from the
emotional stress they are under. But, the flip side to that is that
is they could be very focused. I know when I was with the (NBA's)
Pistons and Lakers they lost some of that hunger after two titles.
But when you get a team like that that has something to rally
behind, it makes them more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Perrot's death, the toughest obstacle Houston had to
overcome was the league adding four teams since 1997. That, plus
the addition of the American Basketball League players, was thought
to narrow the gap between the also-rans and the Comets this season.
</P>
<P>
   The gap did close, just not enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully we can keep it going for as long as we can but the
competition level is so much better,'' Swoopes said. ``I am sure
the league doesn't want one team to dominate and that it's not good
for the sport. I think the league would love to see someone else
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Great, but who? The Comets have a winning record against every
team in the league.
</P>
<P>
   The best candidates appear to be Los Angeles or Sacramento,
which both defeated Houston during the season. The top challenger
out of the Eastern Conference appears to be New York, the only
Eastern team to defeat Houston this season, and the East's only
team with a winning record.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte and Detroit, which both finished 15-17, were a
combined 0-4 against the Comets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if this is going to stop or not,'' Cooper said of
the Comets' title run. ``If I wasn't a Comet, yeah, it would better
for the league if in three different years there would be three
different championship teams. If that's not good for the league ...
sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   So is Barmore.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
