<SLUG> BC-FBC-BIG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI RESURGENCE NOW IN HANDS OF YOUNG PLAYERS
</HEADLINE>
 12 PREVIEW-MISSOURI-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Missouri football media guide boldly proclaims, ``It's a
great time to be a Tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   At quick glance, that slogan would appear to be one of those
things that make you go hmmmm.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri is coming off consecutive winning seasons for the first
time since 1982-83 and back-to-back bowl appearances for the first
time since 1980-81. So indeed, the past two seasons have been great
times to be a Tiger.
</P>
<P>
   But quite a few of the players who contributed mightily to the
recent good times are now part of recent history _ players such as
quarterback Corby Jones, tailback Devin West, offensive guard Craig
Heimberger, defensive lineman Justin Wyatt, cornerback Wade Perkins
and safeties Harold Piersey and Caldrinoff Easter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a big challenge coming off two winning
seasons and an (Insight.com) bowl victory,'' coach Larry Smith
said. ``We return the least amount of experience over the last
three or four years, but the most talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith still can count on proven players such as All-Big 12
senior center Rob Riti and sophomore defensive end Justin Smith, a
first-team freshman All-American who might become the featured
player on a highly regarded defense. But much of the talent that
Smith sees is young and inexperienced.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be scary when almost half of your top 44 are either
sophomores or redshirt freshmen,'' Smith conceded.''But we have a
stellar class of seniors, though not a whole lot of starters
(seven). The key is how they provide leadership to go with our good
young talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Riti knows what Smith is talking about. He's the only returning
starter on the offensive line. And now that returning fullback Rob
West is likely out for the first two games with a hairline fracture
in his left foot, Riti is one of only three senior starters on the
offensive unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of questions are being asked _ specifically on offense _
and I don't blame people for asking,'' said Riti, who has received
considerable preseason All-America mention. ``We've seen a lot of
new faces over the winter and spring. But the developing players
are very talented, and all they lack is game experience, and that's
something I feel will come together the first two games of the
season (Alabama-Birmingham, Western Michigan).
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the guys we have right now are very young. But they
were not with the program when we were losers, so to speak. And the
older guys have a real desire to be successful because of our
humble beginnings. We're used to winning now, and winning becomes
perpetual. You don't get used to it, but it becomes easier.''
</P>
<P>
   The offense is suspect. And after a week at Camp Wentworth,
where the Tigers go for two-a-days, one thing became readily
apparent. Either the offense is indeed a long way from putting it
together, or the Tigers' defense is as formidable as Smith and
others believe it will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of our marquee players are on our defense, which could
give us a chance to be outstanding,'' Smith said. ``We've got
talent, speed and maturity on defense. We feel like our defense is
going to have to carry us early to give the offense time to
mature.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost some talent on offense, but we have to move on,'' said
corner Carlos Posey, one of defensive leaders. ``I feel like our
offense is going to be really good. But until then, our defense
just has to keep on doing what it's been doing.''
</P>
<P>
   So it will still be a good time to be a Tigers defender,
provided too much isn't required of a good thing. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
