<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-MISSOURI-CAPSULE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS: WITH BIG 12 PREVIEW-MISSOURI
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coach: Larry Smith (136-111 overall in 22 seasons, 26-31-1 at
Missouri in five seasons).
</P>
<P>
   1998: 8-4 overall, 5-3, third in North Division.
</P>
<P>
   Returning starters: 5 on offense, 5 on defense.
</P>
<P>
   What has to go right: Either sophomore quarterback Jim Dougherty
or redshirt freshman Kirk Farmer must seize control of the offense,
or Smith is going to have to count on a system that utilizes the
talents of each in a manner that doesn't detract from the offensive
flow.
</P>
<P>
   What can't go wrong: Though inexperience is rampant, the Tigers
might survive wholesale losses in the offensive line _ which was a
major team strength last season _ unless injuries hit. Then, a
serious lack of depth will rear its ugly head.
</P>
<P>
   Update: The offense suffered recent unexpected losses when
sophomore offensive guard Jeff Hellerstedt, who started six games
last season, quit the team; junior wide receiver John Dausman was
lost for the season with a knee injury and West was lost for at
least the first two games with a hairline fracture in his left
foot. ... Dausman's loss leaves Mizzou with only two proven
receivers: senior Kent Layman (26 catches, 495 yards) and senior
Kareem Wise (9-143). ... Senior DeVaughn Black is listed as the No.
1 tailback to succeed Devin West (1,601 yards, 17 TDs), but
observers like the breakaway speed of sophomore backup Zain
Gilmore. ... Smith says that though neither of his two young
quarterbacks have the running ability of Corby Jones, both might
naturally be a little more adept at running a balanced passing
game.
</P>
<P>
