<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7280 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-SEARS-CAMPAIGN-KAN &LR;      08-23 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEARS-CAMPAIGN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEARS DROPS ITS TOO SUCCESSFUL `SOFTER SIDE OF SEARS' CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Call it the death of a sales pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Come September, the successful ``Softer Side of Sears'' campaign
joins other memorable ones such as ``Good to the Last Drop'' and
``Plop, Plop, Fizz, Fizz, Oh What a Relief It Is'' in the graveyard
of slogans.
</P>
<P>
   For Sears, it was a situation of the softer side campaign,
designed to put some sizzle in its name, being too successful.
Sears wasn't able to deliver on the pizazz promised by the ads.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign cleverly juxtaposed things such as hammers,
batteries and tires vs. items such as satiny robes, strappy black
dresses and sexy shoes.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was to get women between the ages of 25 and 54 into the
stores. That group controls at least 70 percent of all dollars
spent at Sears.
</P>
<P>
   In one ad a woman said, ``I came in for a DieHard _ and I left
with something drop dead,'' showing the model in a sexy black
dress.
</P>
<P>
   Sears' advertising agency was able to tweak the idea to cover
dozens of categories. Eventually, it evolved the tag line into
``Come See the Many Sides of Sears.'' The campaign had great legs.
</P>
<P>
   When it made its debut in 1993, Sears' Chairman Arthur Martinez
elaborated on the goal of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've listened carefully to the women who shop at Sears for
their families and homes and we know that they want affordable,
fashionable apparel for themselves,'' Martinez said. ``We want the
campaign to disarm the skeptics and pleasantly surprise our
customers and feature the kind of merchandise that's on our sales
floor right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone forgot to tell Sears' merchandising staff. The women
came in droves, but they didn't find the merchandise shown in the
ads. In the end, the empty promises turned off the customers Sears
was courting.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Sears has seen its sales slide. Sears finished 1998
with five consecutive months of same-store sales declines. This
year hasn't been much better.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, the company has decided to do an about-face and
focus less on image and more on price.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Mark Cohen, Sears' executive vice president of
marketing, elaborated in an Associated Press story on the
turnabout: ``Whether we like it or not, we're in a price-game war,
a value shootout with all our competition. With the Softer Side
campaign, the customer feedback has been, `We love the commercials,
imagery and models, but we don't find those goods at Sears.' ''
</P>
<P>
   So, why not deliver on the softer side promise and make sure the
goods were there?
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't that we didn't have the merchandise featured, it was
that maybe we didn't have enough,'' said Sears' spokeswoman Lee
Antonio. ``If women came in three days after they saw the ad, the
merchandise featured might already be gone.''
</P>
<P>
   David Farmer, head of creative at Barkley Evergreen &AMP; Partners
in Kansas City, Mo., is a fan of the softer side campaign but
thinks Sears was faced with a tough choice.
</P>
<P>
   The retailer could have taken the campaign off the air while it
fixed the merchandising problem. Or it could start from scratch,
which is the route Sears has chosen.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of clients that say it's more important to
roll the dice and drive traffic to the stores, like Sears did, and
hope the brand experience lives up to the promise,'' Farmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Sears' new campaign will begin next month, dubbed
``The Good Life at a Great Price. Guaranteed. Sears.''
</P>
<P>
   Antonio said it spoke for the whole house of Sears: ``This
covers everything from batteries to appliances to apparel. It's a
jungle out there, and we need to continue to be competitive on
pricing, but we've never shouted that and this campaign does
that.''
</P>
<P>
   True, but the aforementioned tag line could apply to any of a
dozen different retailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A very good measure of how well your campaign is connected to
your brand is if you put a competitor's logo at the end of it and
it works,'' Farmer said. ``If it does, then you haven't done your
job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
