<HEADER>
A7281 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-SGI-SGI_SFCHRON &LR;      08-23 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SGI-SGI </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 SGI Chief Belluzzo Resigns
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Henry Norr &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
Silicon Graphics Inc. CEO Richard Belluzzo resigned abruptly
yesterday, just 18 months after taking the job and less than two
weeks after announcing his latest plan to turn around the troubled
company.
</P>
<P>
   SGI, which made its name building high-powered graphics
workstations for engineers and for Hollywood special effects,
immediately announced the appointment of Robert Bishop to replace
Belluzzo as chairman and CEO.
</P>
<P>
   Belluzzo, 45, had been frustrated in his efforts to restore the
Mountain View company to health. ``More and more, it's become clear
that this thing wasn't headed in the right direction,'' said
analyst Kimball Brown of Dataquest. ``I think he just got tired of
trying to turn it around.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop, 56, was a high-ranking sales executive at SGI between
1986 and 1995. Although not directly involved in the company's
management since then, he's been a member of its board of directors
since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Belluzzo's decision to resign was entirely his own, company
officials said in a telephone news conference yesterday. ``This was
a surprise to the company,'' said Bill Kelly, SGI senior vice
president and board secretary. ``It was certainly not
anticipated.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said Belluzzo would take a ``non-CEO'' job at a company
that does not compete with SGI but declined to provide further
details. Belluzzo could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   In its 1999 fiscal year, which ended June 30, SGI recorded a net
loss of $115 million, excluding proceeds from the sale of part of
its interest in MIPS Technologies, a subsidiary that designs
microprocessors.
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth quarter, the company achieved a net profit of
$158 million, or $22 million excluding the MIPS sale, but Belluzzo
warned at the time that a return to sustained profitability was not
assured.
</P>
<P>
   On August 10, the company announced a massive restructuring,
including layoffs of between 1,000 and 1,500 of its 9,000
employees. Under that plan, SGI would sell off not only the Cray
supercomputer division, which it acquired in 1996, but also its
line of low-cost workstations based on Intel chips and Microsoft
Windows NT, which it introduced with great fanfare earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NT plan was a lot of what Belluzzo was betting on,''
Dataquest's Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the plan, SGI will refocus on selling Unix-based
graphics workstations and Internet servers, especially for machines
serving up digital audio and video to customers with high-speed
Internet connections.
</P>
<P>
   As a member of SGI's board, Bishop was involved in development
of the latest plan, and he said yesterday that he fully supports
it. He added, though, that the company's key challenge now is
execution, and ``that's where we have some room for involvement or
fine-tuning.''
</P>
<P>
   He also reaffirmed the previously announced goal of returning to
profitability in the December quarter. Kelly said the restructuring
is proceeding ``acceptably.''
</P>
<P>
   Explaining why the board decided not to conduct a search for a
new leader, Kelly said, ``We felt that with the amount of change
and work we have in front of us ... the company could not afford an
extended period of interim leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   SGI announced the change at the top after the close of trading
yesterday. Earlier, the stock rose 31 cents to close at $12.44.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
