<TEXT>
<P>
   ARTS AND ENTERTAINMENT EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years ago, no one had a video collection. No one
bought laserdiscs or DVDs _ these words did not exist. If someone
asked, ``What should we rent?'' he was talking about a car.
</P>
<P>
   Today 80 percent of the people who own color televisions also
own VCRs. Video has changed our entire relationship with film and
moving images onscreen _ and important aspects of our
off-the-screen lives as well.
</P>
<P>
   In a package of stories on ``25 Years of Video,'' The San
Francisco Chronicle examines the video age, assesses its influence
on our lives, looks ahead to the future of home viewing and
celebrates some of the best and worst movies available on tape. All
stories will move in the ``e'' entertainment category:
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-25YEARS (Undated) _ Twenty-five years after the first
videotapes were manufactured in this country, the medium has
permeated our lives, from how we watch movies to what we think
about celebrities to where our courtships unfold. By Mick LaSalle.
(950 words)
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-FUTURE (Undated) _ The future of home video is here right
now, and it's digital. It's just that most people are not yet
plugged in. By Bob Graham. (790 words)
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-ONLINE (Undated) _ It was inevitable, especially
considering the stay-at-home nature of video viewing, that video
sales would spread to Web sites. Here is a survey of online
marketers. By Edward Guthmann. (520 words)
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-GENERATION (San Francisco) _ The influence of video may be
greatest on people born after 1975, who can't remember a time when
video didn't exist. Now they're putting their money into the medium
that has shaped their idea of entertainment. By Ruthe Stein. (650
words)
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-TEACHING (Undated) _ From history and biography to music,
religion and poetry, specialized videos offer several college
degrees' worth of knowledge that one may glean while curled up on
the couch. By Peter Stack. (685 words)
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-GOOD (Undated) _ They aren't necessarily the best movies
ever made, but they are particularly well suited to home viewing _
they don't lose a lot in the transition from big screen to little
one. Here are 25 great movies to watch on tape. (1120 words)
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-BAD (Undated) _ The world of video is filled with guilty
pleasures. Here's one critic's sampling. By Mick LaSalle. (645
words)
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-PORN (Undated) _ Despite new competition from the Internet
and DVD, adult video remains big business. (435 words)
</P>
