<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7283 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-SUN-SUN_SFCHRON &LR;      08-23 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUN-SUN </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Sun to Pony Up $540 Million for Forte Software
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Steve Ginsberg &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Sun Microsystems Inc. said yesterday that it is buying Forte
Software Inc. of Oakland in a $540 million stock deal that will
give Sun a broader range of software for electronic commerce
applications.
</P>
<P>
   Forte makes software tools and applications that run on a wide
range of computing platforms, including Sun's Java.
</P>
<P>
   Programmers use Forte's tools to customize software for
corporate networks. Its clients include MCI WorldCom, American
Airlines and Marriott International Corp., which uses its software
in online reservations system. Telecommunications companies are
using Forte's tools and software to develop their automated call
centers.
</P>
<P>
   Sun chief executive Scott McNealy has positioned his company to
be the leader in e-commerce, and that has meant diversifying
quickly into tools and software applications that let Sun's
computer servers be used for Internet commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Sun has made other four other acquisitions since October, but
the Forte deal is a sign that Sun is willing to spend heavily to
acquire software that will run on hardware from companies such as
Hewlett-Packard and IBM, as well as Sun's Java.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest challenge for a hardware company is to become a
complete supplier of systems of hardware, software and development
tools. What Sun must do is buy the parts they don't have,'' said
John Jones Jr., technology analyst with Salomon Smith Barney. With
the market moving at Internet speed, buying rather than building is
the best strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Sun will exchange 0.3 share of its stock for every Forte share.
That values Forte at $22.43 per share, based on Sun's closing price
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Forte's shares soared $4.13 _ about 24 percent _ to $21.13
yesterday, while Sun's shares closed at $74.81, up 56 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Forte's stock traded as high as $80 two years ago, but the
company's original technology didn't change quickly enough, and
Forte, until recently, didn't have enough other products to
maintain profitability. Forte lost $1.2 million on sales of $79.5
million last year.
</P>
<P>
   Sun, by comparison, earned $1.15 billion on revenues of $11.7
billion in fiscal 1999, which ended in June.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had expected that Forte eventually would sell out but
thought that it would fetch at least $40 a share. They said Forte
wasn't far along in its turnaround to get the higher price
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Forte chief executive Marty Sprintzen defended the deal in a
teleconference, saying the chance to merge with Sun, a leader in
e-commerce, might not be available later and would add value for
shareholders over time.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is expected to close by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Forte's headquarters will remain in Oakland and will continue to
be led by Sprintzen. The company will keep its 49 offices and will
add to its 400 employees, Sprintzen said.
</P>
<P>
   Security analysts said Sun is buying Forte at six times
revenues, a reasonable price compared with some software deals that
are well over 10 times revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The pace of Sun's acquisitions could be accelerating. Cnet
reported on Friday that Sun has agreed to acquire Star Division, a
German software-maker whose lead product is comparable to Microsoft
Office. Cnet said the deal was signed August 11 and is expected to
be announced August 31.
</P>
<P>
   Zander would not comment on the report.
</P>
<P>
   If the deal is consummated, it would push Sun into direct
software competition with Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
