<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990823.0452 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7285 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-VIDEO-25YEARS-SFCHRON     08-23 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-25YEARS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
25 YEARS OF VIDEO: HOW IT CHANGED OUR LIVES AND THE WAY WE SEE  THE
WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICK LaSALLE  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Twenty-five years ago, no one had a video collection. No one
bought laserdiscs or DVDs _ these words did not exist. No one said,
``Let's watch a video,'' and if someone asked, ``What should we
rent?'' she was talking about a car.
</P>
<P>
   Today, video has permeated every aspect of our lives, not just
in the affluent United States but all over the world. Twenty-five
years after the first videotapes were manufactured in this country,
it's a good time to take a look at the changes and influences of
video on our lives.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, video was on the way for a long time before it
actually arrived. As early as 1970, Life magazine ran a big feature
on the coming revolution, ``cassette TV,'' which discussed possible
formats, none of which caught on. In one, the cassettes weren't
videos at all. They had film inside.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, the first Betamaxes became available. They cost $2,295
and few people bought them _ few even knew about them. Video didn't
really take off until 1980, when the price of a recorder in the VHS
format dropped to $800.
</P>
<P>
   For many of us at that time, our first encounter with video
remains our most profound experience of technology _ just as
television was for our parents. In December 1979, a friend took me
into his room to show me this big contraption he had gotten for
Christmas. The whole room smelled like the VCR _ that warm,
new-appliance smell. My friend pressed a button and the top sprang
open. He pulled the videotape out. It looked like an audiocassette
on steroids.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the future _ it actually seemed like that in the
moment.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, every time I saw a movie I loved, there was an
accompanying pain. I'd wait for it to be revived at a theater and
be thrilled when I'd see the listing. I'd check TV Guide every week
and do a double-take when it was finally there. I'd set my alarm
clock for 3 in the morning and watch it on the ``Late Late Late
Show.'' When it was over I'd feel sad because I never knew how long
I'd have to wait to see it again.
</P>
<P>
   Days of deprivation have a way of turning romantic when
remembered in days of plenty. Movies meant more to us before the
video revolution for the simple reason that we had no control over
when we got to see them. At the same time, I can't forget the sheer
thrill of seeing that video recorder for the first time, knowing
that from then on, things would be different.
</P>
<P>
   Few of us realized (set ital)how(end ital) different. Today 80
percent of the people who own color televisions also own VCRs, and
that's worldwide. Video has changed our entire relationship with
film and moving images onscreen _ and important aspects of our
off-the-screen lives as well. Here are a few of the ways:
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Video Changed Our Relationship to Movie Stars: &LR;  Newspapers
and magazines make a big fuss over the fact that these days movie
and television stars cross over, whereas before there was a
dividing line between the two media. But nobody has pointed out
that the reason for this is video. (set ital)All(end ital) movie
stars are also TV stars. They are shrunk to fit a TV screen and can
be easily manipulated with a remote control.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Video Changed the Way We Watch Movies: &LR;  The first time I hit
rewind and made Marlene Dietrich walk backward across a room, I
felt as if I'd violated her. Before video, viewers didn't blink
during close-ups. Today, people blink ... and then rewind. We watch
movies the way we read books. We put them down and pick them up at
will, and we skim over the boring parts.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Video Created a Two-Tiered Hierarchy: &LR;  I don't quite
understand the concept of waiting until a film comes out on video
to see it for the first time if it's considered a subpar movie. If
a movie is bad, there's no reason to see it _ ever. But the concept
of ``wait for video'' is pervasive. Thanks to video, people end up
seeing more mediocre movies than they ever would have previously.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Fans Don't Have to Chase Movies to the Suburbs: &LR;  Before
video, if you missed a movie the first time around, or loved one
and wanted to keep seeing it, you had to follow it to the
third-string theaters. Then it would disappear for a year before
appearing on network television in edited form. Today, a fan can
wait a few months and buy the video.
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &UR; Video Influences Box Office: &LR;  The last ``Austin Powers''
movie made only about $50 million at the box office, but it became
such a hit on video that everyone knew that the sequel, ``The Spy
Who Shagged Me,'' would be huge. And it was.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Video Keeps Film Historians Honest: &LR;  In the 1960s and '70s,
film historians could write anything. They relied on their memories
or the memories of others, and the result was mistake after
mistake. It's not just that they didn't have video recorders. They
knew readers didn't have them. Film historians today have to know
what they're talking about.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Video Has Changed Courtship Patterns: &LR;  In modern America, the
first sex date is often a video date. Men used to say, ``Would you
like to see my etchings?'' Now they say, ``How about if I make
dinner and we rent a movie?'' Sinatra on the phonograph has been
replaced by Harrison Ford on the TV screen.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Video Changed Our Relationship With the Present: &LR;  People
videotape their weddings and then forget the actual wedding and
remember only the video. They pay money to go on vacation to a
foreign country and see it through the lens of a camcorder. In one
of the few light moments in the horror film ``The Sixth Sense,'' a
children's play begins and an entire audience of parents begins
videotaping the performance.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Video Changed Our Relationship With the Past: &LR;  One of the
heartaches unique to the 20th century is being able to see
cherished past events and even dead loved ones come alive again
onscreen. Since video, unlike film, has a present-tense feeling,
these images can be a comfort _ but they can also do a number on
us.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; We Know What We Look Like: &LR;  It used to be that only
celebrities knew what they looked and sounded like moving around.
Nowadays, many of us have been on video. And the result is that
there are fewer bad comb-overs today than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
